<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 00:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7237 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-HNS &LR;      11-12 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
LAS VEGAS _ Custodians at the Boxing Hall of Fame probably already
have dusted and cleaned out one little corner of the building, a
sanctuary reserved for future resident Evander Holyfield.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is the only boxer besides Muhammad Ali to claim the world
heavyweight championship three times and is certain to be enshrined
five years after the day he finally decides to hang up his gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's ultimate place in history is not a subject the
part-time Houston resident dwells on.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it takes some serious urging to get him to give more
than casual heed to the theme.
</P>
<P>
   Upon persistent prodding, Holyfield, who turned 37 in October,
said Thursday, ``If you go by statistic-wise, I'm already one of
the best, if not the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can't make anybody believe you.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's track record should speak for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly the undisputed world cruiserweight champion, Holyfield
in 1988 moved up to heavyweight and gradually began carving out a
niche for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said I was going to be heavyweight champion of the
world someday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though a shot at a world title evaded him through the first
couple of years he campaigned as a heavyweight, Holyfield finally
got his big shot in the fall of 1990.
</P>
<P>
   James ``Buster'' Douglas had upset the boxing world earlier that
year, knocking out Mike Tyson in Tokyo to take away the undisputed
heavyweight championship.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas sat idle over the next seven months, then looked like a
beached whale when he lumbered in against Holyfield, who turned
Douglas' lights out with a third-round knockout.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield successfully defended the crown against former
champion George Foreman, Bert Cooper and ex-champ Larry Holmes,
then suffered the first loss of his pro career in the first of
three fights with Riddick Bowe.
</P>
<P>
   A dispute with the World Boxing Council resulted in Bowe dumping
that organization's title and belt into a trash can. But he
retained the World Boxing Association and International Boxing
Federation titles.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield took the WBA and IBF titles back in a rematch _ the
infamous ``Fan Man'' bout at Caesars Palace here.
</P>
<P>
   But in the first defense of his newly reclaimed crowns,
Holyfield looked increasingly aged as each round progressed and
lost a unanimous decision to Michael Moorer.
</P>
<P>
   An incorrect diagnosis of a heart ailment ensued, forcing
Holyfield to briefly retire.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield returned to health in 1994, and in 1995 he beat Ray
Mercer to herald his comeback.
</P>
<P>
   One year later, Holyfield gained a piece of boxing immortality.
The history-making fight was a match with Mike Tyson, a 25-1
favorite who at the time was the WBA champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew going into that fight that Tyson wasn't the baddest
fellow around, like he wanted everybody to believe,'' said
Holyfield trainer Don Turner. ``We knew he could be beaten.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield rocked Tyson over the first two rounds, then knocked
him out in the 11th.
</P>
<P>
   He was champion again. For the third time. Proof positive, says
Turner, ``that Evander is the best there is or ever was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put him at the top. You can't put him anywhere but at the
top. Look what he's done. He's beat everybody that's supposed to be
anybody, all the good fighters of his day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ain't no man, other than Ali, been heavyweight champion of the
world three times. 'Nuff said.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight months ago, a lot more was being said. On the 21st
anniversary of Ali's epic battle with Joe Frazier at Madison Square
Garden, Holyfield visited the sports mecca to face Lennox Lewis in
a heavyweight title unification bout.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis owned the WBC title; Holyfield, the WBA and IBF belts.
</P>
<P>
   Though it appeared to everyone but two of the three ringside
judges that Lewis had clearly won the bout and become England's
first undisputed world heavyweight champ in 100 years, the verdict
rendered was a draw.
</P>
<P>
   Critics were questioning how anyone could have deemed
Holyfield's performance worthy of a draw. And he has consistently
been asked if the sport hasn't passed him by.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody can say what they want to say. You can't stop people
from thinking and saying what they want,'' Holyfield responds.
``The fact of the matter is what you do in the ring. I'm 37 years
old, and the point is, `Can Evander still perform?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Won't nobody have to guess, because they will get an
opportunity to see it in the fight (Saturday night at the Thomas &AMP;
Mack Center on the campus of UNLV).
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that I was too old in (the initial fight). It was
just that I was a little under the weather. But being under the
weather, you still have to go to work or go home with no check.
These are decisions one has to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield vows his performance, the manner in which Lewis
responds and the outcome Saturday will be completely different from
last March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will redeem myself, and people will see a better Evander
than they have seen in my whole boxing career,'' he said. ``This
definitely may be one of my greatest fights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
