u k BC-EDIT-AMERICORPS-NYT &LR;      11-12 0244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AMERICORPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AMERICORPS LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Nov. 12:
</P>
<P>
   Americorps, President Clinton's national service program, has
survived the budget warfare in Washington. An appropriations
measure already signed by Clinton earmarks $438.5 million for the
valuable five-year-old program _ roughly the same amount as last
year.
</P>
<P>
   This will allow Americorps to continue supplying nonprofit
groups around the country with volunteers, who receive a $4,725
educational stipend in exchange for an intensive year performing
worthwhile tasks like tutoring at-risk children, restoring
dilapidated housing and parks, and helping communities rebuild
after natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointingly, however, Congress ignored a White House request
for additional funding that would have allowed Americorps to
significantly expand its present complement of about 40,000
members. As in previous years, Republicans bent on embarrassing the
President made sure the House version of the budget contained no
money for the program, forcing its Senate supporters to scramble
for the funds necessary to keep it going at its current level.
</P>
<P>
   Congress undervalues the accomplishments of Americorps' mostly
young volunteers and the hard-working agencies that sponsor them.
Next year's debate should focus on spreading the program's spirit
of service instead of trying to kill it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
