r s BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     11-12 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR A VERY BIG DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To put NASCAR's new TV deal into an easy to understand context,
it is tantamount to the NFL, at the urging of commissioner Pete
Rozelle, agreeing in 1962 to sell its national TV rights as a
single unit.
</P>
<P>
   It's worked wonders for the NFL, which is still giggling over
the $17.6 billion in TV contracts it signed the last time it went
to market. NASCAR's decision has the same sense of ingenuity.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the TV rights to NASCAR Winston Cup races were sold
individually by the tracks, which caused some inequities from race
to race and splintered marketing. Every network had some small
piece of the stock car season.
</P>
<P>
   But beginning late last year, NASCAR started terminating some TV
deals early so it could take its entire package to market. The
result was Thursday's announcement of two package deals, one with
NBC and Turner Sports and the other with Fox Sports, that have a
combined worth for NASCAR of $400 million-plus a year.
</P>
<P>
   Fox signed an eight-year deal calling for NASCAR events in the
first half of the year, beginning in 2001. NBC signed a six-year
deal and Turner an eight-year pact for the second half of the
package, beginning in July. More than 70 percent of all Winston Cup
events will be aired on an over-the-air network, and each
half-season package will likely include 17 events.
</P>
<P>
   It is standard at times like this for the dealmakers to say the
money wasn't the key issue, and NASCAR execs did. But the packaging
concept for the sport is truly as important as cash.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's first-half will receive a huge boost from promotion
during Fox's NFL playoff coverage each January, and its second-half
will get the same kind of boost from NBC's NBA playoff coverage.
And the series will be anchored to three well-known networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are reorganizing the packages and creating a national
franchise at the same time,'' said Brian France, NASCAR's senior
vice-president. ``That was our goal. I think we now have a
promotional platform as good as any in sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, the top execs and Fox and NBC were ecstatic
about writing checks. In a decade that has seen sports ratings
steadily decline, even for the monolithic NFL, NASCAR's numbers are
going up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sitting here with a fact sheet about NASCAR that awes
you,'' said Fox Sports President David Hill. ``It's number two
among all sports, trailing the NFL but ahead of the NBA, NHL and
baseball. It's number two in male demographics, beating the NBA by
27 percent. Their household numbers are up 70 percent while others
are eroding. And NASCAR isn't just a rural phenomenon. The numbers
are great in cities like Philadelphia and Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only sport of the '90s that has had sustained growth,
and that's been with six different (TV) partners,'' said NBC Sports
President Dick Ebersol, who will use NASCAR as programming to
counter NFL Sundays in the fall. ``It's often been difficult for
fans to know where NASCAR races are. This will make it easier for
the fan, and they'll get a chance to know these people (drivers and
teams) a whole lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   With winners, there are also losers. CBS loses four NASCAR
events after the 2000 season, including the Daytona 500, the
biggest (and first) race of every season. Beginning in 2001, Fox
and NBC will alternate Daytona each year.
</P>
<P>
   ABC/ESPN loses 18 events, five of them on ABC, including the
Brickyard 400. A ESPN spokesman said the two nets would lose about
195 hours of programming, but still has hundreds of hours of other
motor sports in hand. It will keep its RPM2Night daily show on
ESPN2 despite losing the NASCAR package.
</P>
<P>
   Big numbers
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's TV ratings keep humming along. The season to date
averages have Fox at 10.8, up seven percent over last year; CBS at
8.8, up nine percent; ABC's Monday Nighter at 13.9, up two percent;
and ESPN at 6.4, up 16 percent. One ratings point is equal to
994,000 homes.
</P>
<P>
   This comes at a time when most experts say the quality of play
has deteriorated because of retirements, injuries and a shallow
pool of quarterbacks. The only reasonable answer is that fans enjoy
seeing fresh faces on TV, like the St. Louis Rams, Tennessee Titans
and Indianapolis Colts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone had told me that the Giants and Redskins would lead
the (NFC) East, the Lions the Central and the Rams the West, I
would have gone to bank with him,'' said Fox analyst John Madden.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one saw this coming. Here we are at midseason, and no one
knows what's going to happen, not even the experts. When you don't
know what's going to happen, you've got to watch it. It's
topsy-turvy and interesting as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Of the 128 games played to date, 65 were decided by a
touchdown or less, and 43 of those 65 were decided by three points
or less. Fifty different quarterbacks have started at least one
game among 31 teams. That has a lot to do with so many surprise
endings.
</P>
<P>
   Madden fears the quarterback shortage for the league's long-term
health. ``There are not enough Peyton Mannings to go around,'' he
said. ``I read where the top four quarterbacks in the league have
all played in NFL Europe. Well, that's great for NFL Europe, but it
doesn't speak well of the quality of quarterbacking in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   And now the news
</P>
<P>
   Longtime L.A. voice Rich Marotta is picking up more work for Fox
Sports Net. He'll do live reports from the Holyfield-Lewis fight
this weekend, including post-fight interviews and commentatary.
``These two guys have a big responsibility for the entire sport.
They need to come out and fight and really make something happen.''
Marotta is picking Lewis. The fight is available on pay-per-view
via TVKO. ... ESPN airs its ``SportsCenter of the Decade, 1990s,''
today at 4 p.m. ... Irv Kaze's KIEV (870 am) show Saturday (6 p.m.)
features ex-Trojan (Vince Evans, Paul McDonald) and ex-Bruin
quarterbacks (Tom Ramsey, Matt Stevens) ... Tuesday's edition of
``Real Sports'' on HBO includes a segment on the 1966 Notre
Dame-Michigan game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 0011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
