<HEADER>
A7243 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-U.N.-DUES-CONGRESS-2N     11-12 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-DUES-CONGRESS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT OFFERS TO ABSORB CRITICISM FOR DEAL ON U.N. DUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ADDS Rubin's declining to give details in 9th graf; DELETES
``blocking in 10th graf; Adds background in 13th graf; CORRECTS
Holbrooke's title in 14th graf; Story now moves in 2 takes) 
(sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has
volunteered to be the lightning rod for criticism from abortion
rights groups if President Clinton compromises with Congress on a
deal to free nearly $1 billion the United States owes the United
Nations, senior administration officials said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As a Cabinet member who supports abortion rights, Albright has
urged the White House to cut a deal that some administration
officials fear could strike some Clinton supporters as a retreat
from the president's pledge to defend abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, the administration has refused a demand from House
conservatives, led by Rep. Christopher Smith, R-N.J., to cut off
U.S. financing to international organizations that promote abortion
rights as a condition to repaying Washington's debt to the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   White House domestic advisers, in particular, have been loath to
alienate a core Democratic constituency, women voters, by backing
away from Clinton's commitment on abortion rights abroad to resolve
an increasingly embarrassing foreign policy issue.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent months, Albright, a former ambassador to the
United Nations, has aggressively lobbied Republican lawmakers and
Clinton to resolve several issues that threaten American global
leadership: the United Nations dues, debt relief to impoverished
countries and foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   Albright recently told John Podesta, the White House chief of
staff, that if services offered by abortion rights groups overseas
are only minimally affected by any deal, the administration should
be willing to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have to move off existing law, as a woman secretary of
state who knows extremely well the instinctive concerns of women's
groups, she's prepared to take the heat,'' said a senior
administration official, who would speak on the condition of
anonymity. ``She is prepared to meet with them and explain to them
why this does not harm our fundamental position, but that getting
the U.N. dues is critical for our national security.''
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, declined to comment on
any offer Albright had made, saying, ``We're committed to paying
our fair share at the United Nations by paying our back dues, and
we're working very hard on a way to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   A State Department spokesman, James Rubin, also declined to
comment on any offer or details of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and administration officials said discussions
continued Thursday on the abortion issue, which is holding up a
deal on the U.N. payments, one of the last major sticking points in
a session-ending budget deal.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators also faced a new environmental amendment delaying a
ban on road building in national forests and a dispute over debt
relief to impoverished countries. But the abortion issue could be
the last issue left on the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a great deal of rigor on that, as regarding the
question of whether or not American tax dollars should be used by
the U.N. or any other agencies to lobby other nations on their
abortion laws,'' said Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the House majority
leader.
</P>
<P>
   While the United States has had disputes over its debts to the
United Nations for years, the issue escalated after the Republicans
took control of Congress in 1994. Dislike of the United Nations by
many lawmakers, and the linkage of dues to the abortion issue, has
effectively thwarted any effort to pay the dues in full.
</P>
<P>
   The aggressive lobbying by Albright and Richard Holbrooke, the
new chief U.S. delegate to the United Nations, to repay $926
million over the next three years has been well known.
</P>
<P>
   Making known Albright's intention to absorb the political flak
of a sensitive domestic political decision serves several purposes.
</P>
<P>
   It prepares abortion rights groups for a possible deal they may
not like, and that will probably affect the presidential campaign
of Vice President Al Gore and the possible Senate campaign of first
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It also serves to pressure wavering White House domestic
advisers. And it could be intended to steal some of the limelight
from Holbrooke, with whom Albright has had a tense relationship.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Family planning groups reacted cautiously to reports of
Albright's willingness to bear the brunt of any political fallout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that will cut family planning is hardly a compromise
on the issue of abortion,'' said Susan Cohen, assistant director of
policy development for the Alan Guttmacher Institute, a research
and advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Despite declarations that a deal may be near, only a tiny number
of people are intimately involved with the talks, mainly between
Steve Ricchetti, a White House deputy chief of staff, and Scott B.
Palmer, chief of staff for the speaker of the House, Dennis
Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   The ingredients of a possible deal include using Smith's
language but allowing presidential waivers to that provision for
international organizations that provide abortions or lobby for
abortion rights. The agreement would also include funding penalties
imposed by Congress on the amount of U.S. grants awarded to the
foreign organizations if the waivers were used.
</P>
<P>
   Administration and congressional aides said there were other
approaches under consideration that they refused to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   But all sides agree that the political climate and cast of
characters this year enhance the prospects of ending a three-year
battle.
</P>
<P>
   This year, for instance, Clinton is free from the distractions
of the Monica Lewinsky scandal, and advisers like Albright and
Holbrooke have been pushing harder to resolve the issue. That is in
part because the stakes are higher. The United States will lose its
vote in the U.N. General Assembly if it fails to meet a Dec. 31
deadline for payments
</P>
<P>
   The dispute does not threaten the U.S. vote or seat on the U.N.
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   There are also practical budget considerations for striking a
deal this year. Under the 1997 balanced budget agreement, Congress
can appropriate money for the United Nations without having to make
cuts in other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, that will not be allowed, making repayment in an
election year much more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are also feeling some pressure. Some conservatives
do not want to give Clinton ammunition to fuel his charges that
Republicans are isolationist.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who opposes abortion, has quietly
urged both sides to reconcile, and he called Hastert on Wednesday
to offer his advice. Helms wants a deal because a Senate bill that
he sponsored ties the repayment of $926 million over three years to
changes he wants at the United Nations, including reducing budgets
and the United States' share of payments.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders are also weighing in with Republicans. The
Business Roundtable and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce are pushing
for a deal to pay back the dues and carry out reforms at the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The Better World Campaign, a group financed by Ted Turner that
advocates repaying the debt, has hired Haley Barbour, former
chairman of the Republican National Committee, to lobby on its
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   It still remains unclear whether House conservatives will
support a deal. Their demand is to write into law an executive
order issued by President Ronald Reagan in 1984. Clinton reversed
the order in 1993, shortly after taking office.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has barred direct financing for abortion since
1973, but the 1984 policy, known familiarly as ``Mexico City''
since Reagan announced it during a U.N. conference there, denied
grants to international family-planning organizations for any
purpose if they promoted abortion rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
