<HEADER>
A7247 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     11-12 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG FIGHT, YEAH RIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS---Oh no, here we go again, another Big Fight involving
(a) Don King, (b) Evander Holyfield, (c) Lennox Lewis, (d) Las
Vegas and (e) the gullible, exploited, gouged, worn-out fistic
patrons who (f) will pay up to $2,000 for ringside tickets and (g)
$49.95 to watch the pay per view telecast.
</P>
<P>
   What will happen Saturday night in the long unanticipated
rematch between Holyfield and Lewis at the Thomas &AMP; Mack Center?
</P>
<P>
   Will Lennox Lewis navigate backward for 12 rounds, as Oscar De
La Hoya did recently in his ripoff snoozer against Felix Trinidad?
Will Evander Holyfield throw a late punch that results in a
no-contest decision, as Mike Tyson did recently in his latest sorry
spectacle against Orlin Norris? Will Lewis dominate the proceedings
and wind up with a distasteful draw, which is what happened in his
first engagement with Holyfield?
</P>
<P>
   The strong feeling here is that Lewis and Holyfield will
dispense a replica of their March 11 bit of non-violence at Madison
Square Garden, but that this time Lewis will be awarded with a
decision that will temporarily knock the sport's reigning Rasputin,
Don King, out of the heavyweight title picture.
</P>
<P>
   You never, of course, know for sure what will unfold in a boxing
ring in one of these high-profile events, especially in this weird
fight year in which, against all odds, the IBF's president, Bob
Lee, winds up being indicted of accepting bribes to fix boxing
ratings before the WBC's lovable Jose Sulaiman, long-time
unofficial partner of King in all sorts of shenanigans.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there are passionate Holyfield advocates who think their
37-year-old hero simply had an off evening against Lewis and that
he will rise gallantly this time to score a spectacular upset
victory as he did so memorably in the past against Tyson and
Riddick Bowe.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe he will.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe Don King will give a glowing testimonial at Bob Arum's
70th birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe Lennox Lewis, whose dull, safety-first style doesn't
exactly inspire the passions of the aficionados, will react to
Holyfield's baiting tactics and actually brawl with him.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, and Shaquille O'Neal suddenly will start shooting free
throws as though he were Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander Holyfield is a totally shot fighter,'' his former
manager, Lou Duva told me several months back. ``He shouldn't be
fighting, and Lewis will handle him easily again and probably knock
him out.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure that will happen because that would constitute
Lennox Lewis having to become aggressive and taking risks, which
he's never done in his career and which he did not do in that first
fight against Holyfield that he controlled from long range with his
superior left jab and strength.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-5 Lewis easily tied up Holyfield on those few occasions
when the 6-1 Atlanta native managed to maneuver inside. And Lewis'
84-inch reach---Holyfield's is listed at 77{---turned out to be a
decisive advantage against an aging opponent who seemed to have
lost his quickness and desire.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing figures to change.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis still possesses his size and power, while the 37-year-old
Holyfield is another 7{ months older.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't myself in that first fight against Lewis because I
had a stomach ailment,'' says Holyfield, not so convincingly. ``I
just fought poorly, and had a bad performance. It will be different
this time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to let the judges decide this fight,'' promises
Lewis. ``I'm going to knock out Holyfield.''
</P>
<P>
   And Lewis probably could if he would shed his conservative
tactics and open up against Holyfield, but that's simply not his
style.
</P>
<P>
   It won't surprise me if Holyfield-Lewis II is as yawningly
tiresome as Holyfield-Lewis I.
</P>
<P>
   Natch, Don King envisions only drama, tension and violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be the greatest fight of all time,'' he cackles.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps the worst.
</P>
<P>
   The only surefire winners in this match are the participants,
each of whom is guaranteed of earning $15 million, and King, who
will earn his usual undisclosed millions.
</P>
<P>
   The losers?
</P>
<P>
   If you go by what has happened in recent times, it will be those
cursed souls who wind up investing money on an event that would
turn out to be a stunner only if it comes close to living up to Don
King's inflated expectations. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet If Evander Holyfield seems to have lost the ferocious
fire in his heart, it's quite understandable. They tell me the guy
is worth about $60 million, and he lives in a 45,000-square foot
mansion in Atlanta. How can he work himself into a maniacal state
at his age for such a savage activity?. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet Robert Daly's first major move with the Dodgers was a
winner with the signing of Shawn Green, and another positive move
would be to bring back Steve Brener to boost the team's sagging
public image.
</P>
<P>
   There is recurring speculation that this might happen---Brener
was the best PR man the Dodgers ever had---but it's no certainty
that Brener would return.
</P>
<P>
   He owns a lucrative public relations firm in the San Fernando
Valley---the NFL, Showtime, the LPGA are just a few of his
clients---and it would take a sizable financial package to uproot
him now from his secure and cushy position to spin tales for Kevin
Malone and Gary Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   Brener this week has been at the Desert Inn hyping the LPGA's
PageNet Championship. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet After Charles Barkley's impressive takedown of Shaquille
O'Neal the other evening, it's obvious Sir Charles has quite a
future in the WWF. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet I just wish Shaquille O'Neal would become as enraged with
his pathetic deportment from the free throw line as he does with
guys dealing him hard fouls, or bouncing basketballs off his
anatomy. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet The question to me about USC's Paul Hackett is not if he
can coach, but, instead, how in tarnation did ever wind up becoming
a coach at USC in the first place after his disastrous stay at
Pittsburgh?. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet Long Beach celebrity bodyguard Mike (The Hammer) DiMarzo
recruited his brother, Tony (The Baddest Bull) DiMarzo, a federal
prison guard in Florence, Col., to work with him here tonight at
the Sammy Hagar concert at the Hard Rock Hotel. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet One of the most well-liked athletic PR operatives in
Southern California history, Bob Steiner, has retired from Jerry
Buss' organization. Steiner has been Buss' top man for the past 20
years and also is well-known in track and field as being one of the
sport's best public address announcers. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet I never realized the great former Bakersfield College and
Los Angeles State football coach, Homer Beatty, is living in Long
Beach. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet The Montreal writers tell me the new Angels general
manager, Bill Stoneman, is a bottom-line guy in financial matters,
which means the Angels don't figure to be active in the free agent
market in upcoming seasons. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet Toronto Blue Jays running coach Maury Wills tells me he
has worked closely with Shawn Green, and says the new Dodger
outfielder is a terrific person who will be become a ``huge
presence in Los Angeles for at least the next 10 years.''. . .
</P>
<P>
   bullet Honestly, it won't be startling to me if Saturday's women
volleyball showdown at the Pyramid between Long Beach State and UOP
winds up being more entertaining than the Holyfield-Lewis fight
that, deservedly, seems to have inspired wide-spread public
indifference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
