<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FIGHT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUICK FIX FOR BOXING?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Boxing could sure use a good fight Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It's been that kind of year, one that started with so much
promise but unraveled into a mess that has left everyone disgusted
with the sport.
</P>
<P>
   There were pathetic fights, maddening decisions, indictments for
selling rankings and another bizarre episode involving Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   This is why those in the boxing business are hoping _ (begin
ital)praying(end ital) _ the rematch between Lennox Lewis and
Evander Holyfield is a good one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fight is being billed as the fight of the millennium. We
just need it to be the fight of the year,'' said Mark Taffet, head
of TVKO, HBO's pay-per-view arm.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, things looked good this year after a 1998 void of
meaningful matchups.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar De La Hoya had outpointed Ike Quartey in a thrilling fight
in February and plans were made for the meeting we'd all been
waiting for: De La Hoya-Trinidad, in September.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it was announced that Holyfield and Lewis _ seen as the
two best heavyweights in the world _ would meet in March.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, boxing fans had reason to be excited. And then they
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the short list of things that went wrong:
</P>
<P>
   _Lewis seemed to have beaten Holyfield soundly, but the fight
was scored a draw, leaving fans with dropped jaws and little faith
in boxing's judging system.
</P>
<P>
   _De La Hoya outboxed Trinidad for eight-plus rounds but ran the
final three-plus rounds and lost, though most believed he had done
enough to win. The fight was both a dud (begin ital)and(end ital)
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   _Last month, popular Naseem Hamed and Cesar Soto engaged in a
televised bout that was a hybrid of wrestling and boxing. It was
joke _ a bad joke.
</P>
<P>
   _A day later, Mike Tyson punched Orlin Norris after the first
bell, Norris fell and sprained his knee and the fight was ruled no
contest.
</P>
<P>
   _And, out of the ring, IBF president Robert Lee and others were
indicted on charges of taking payments to improve fighters'
rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Could it get any worse?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true,'' said promoter Dan Goossen of American Presents.
``It looked so promising and then it was one disappointment after
another.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest was the first Holyfield-Lewis fight. It was the
first time in a generation that the two best heavyweights in the
world met to decide who was No.1 _ Holyfield, the indestructible
warrior, or Lewis, the behemoth with remarkable strength and
athletic ability.
</P>
<P>
   And then (begin ital)splat(end ital).
</P>
<P>
   The fight wasn't horrible, but it certainly wasn't special.
Lewis was overly cautious but still controlled the action while
Holyfield seemed to be either old or off.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the decision, which seems to have served as a last
straw for many disenchanted boxing fans and the powers that be in
the sport, who are now clamoring for reform.
</P>
<P>
   How disenchanted are the fans?
</P>
<P>
   The first fight had a pay-per-view audience of 1.2 million,
eighth on the all-time list. On Saturday, most agree, TVKO will be
lucky to draw 600,000.
</P>
<P>
   And the Thomas &AMP; Mack Center might not sell out. Tickets were
still available on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't normal for a fight of this magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's public weigh-in, hundreds of fans from England
were present to show Lewis loud and enthusiastic support. Had they
not been there, it would've been awfully quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the Brits,'' one knowledgeable observer said, ``no one
would care.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, millions of eyes worldwide will be on the fight and many
more will watch the replay on HBO the following weekend. And boxing
people care deeply about what they think.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fight is definitely important for the future of
pay-per-view,'' Goossen said. ``If we have another bad fight, I
really think they might say, `That's it. We're not going to take it
any more.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a good fight, even if (the fans) stayed away this
time, they might say, `OK, it was a battle' and come back the next
time.''
</P>
<P>
   All the ingredients are in place for a good fight.
</P>
<P>
   The judging, so criticized after Holyfield and Lewis fought in
New York, is as solid as it gets. Nevada, not the sanctioning
bodies, selected its best and most experienced.
</P>
<P>
   Judges Jerry Roth, Chuck Giampa and Bill Graham have worked more
than 200 championship bouts between them. Mitch Halpern, perhaps
the state's most respected referee, will work the fight.
</P>
<P>
   And both fighters seem to be extremely motivated: Lewis has
yearned his entire career for the universal respect a victory would
bring him and Holyfield must prove that he's not finished at nearly
37.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you never know what might happen in boxing,
especially when Don King, Holyfield's promoter, is involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done everything we believe is possible to make this a
good fight,'' Ratner said. ``We can't judge the fight or fight the
fight, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Bob Arum, for one, thinks it's too late. The damage has
been done.
</P>
<P>
   One fight, even a fight for the undisputed heavyweight
championship such as this one, isn't going to have a tremendous
impact on the sport whether it's good or bad or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's good, great,'' he said, but ``it's going to take a lot
of good fights to make up for what happened this past year. It's
like starting from scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   And if it's bad?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a bombed-out building, what's the difference if
you bomb it again,'' Arum said.
</P>
<P>
   Television boxing analyst Larry Merchant, who works for HBO,
also believes boxing needs a good fight. At the same time, he, like
Arum, doesn't see this as a do-or-die fight. Throughout its
history, boxing has had more than its share of disappointing
fights, corruption, controversial decisions and bizarre instances.
</P>
<P>
   And it still stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say that no matter what happens, they'll keep
coming back for more,'' Merchant said. ``Boxing is a resilient
sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always had black eyes. Maybe that's part of its appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
