<HEADER>
A7254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MEXICO-AIRLINE-NYT &LR;      11-12 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-AIRLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN AIRLINE ACCUSED OF LAPSES IN UPKEEP 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexico's third-largest airline, already facing
financial and legal pressure, is now defending itself against
assertions by a labor union that its maintenance procedures are
dangerous and deceptive.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the airline, Transportes Aereos Ejecutivos S.A.,
known as Taesa, denied the claims, which came in interviews on
Thursday with the leader of Mexico's union of flight attendants and
in a complaint filed before the U.S. Labor Department in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But the complaints drew considerable attention since they came
two days after a Taesa commuter DC9-31 crashed west of Mexico City,
killing all 18 occupants.
</P>
<P>
   Taesa's 300 flight attendants are represented by a
pro-government labor federation, but some attendants are trying to
decertify that union and affiliate with the larger, more aggressive
and politically independent Flight Attendants Union of Mexico.
Taesa is resisting the decertification drive.
</P>
<P>
   Alejandra Barrales Magdaleno, the leader of the flight
attendants union, on Thursday accused Taesa of keeping two sets of
records for the DC9-31 and for other aircraft in its fleet. She
said one set accurately reflected maintenance deficiencies, and
another set, which was turned over to federal aviation authorities
during periodic inspections, offered a false and less-troubled
assessment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrales said she had personally informed Mexico's director
of Civil Aviation of the group's suspicions but that he had taken
no action. A Civil Aviation spokesman said the director was
investigating the Taesa crash and was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for Taesa, Eduardo Cacho Silva, denied the
record-keeping accusation and said Taesa complies strictly with
government maintenance regulations. He said the ill-fated DC9-31
had been in good operating condition before its last flight, from
Uruapan, Michoacan, to Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are irresponsible accusations made to confuse the
public,'' Cacho said.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint filed with the Labor Department asserted that
Taesa engaged in unfair labor practices. The complaint was lodged
under a side accord of the North American Free Trade Agreement, in
which the member countries agreed to review each others' records on
labor rights and safety practices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 0023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7256 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     11-12 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEARIN KEEPS NORTHRIDGE SPIRITS UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It figures Jeff Kearin would keep a copy of
``14,000 Things to be Happy About'' within easy reach on his desk.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)A grass field.
</P>
<P>
   Warm sunshine in November.
</P>
<P>
   An office with a door.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Only someone who smiles at life's simple pleasures could sit in
the non-descript trailer that houses his office, look out at the
drab stadium that houses his team and see neon lights and Broadway
somewhere off in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin, 39, is directing the football program at Cal State
Northridge, which means he can't be sure how much longer the
production will run.
</P>
<P>
   The reviews this year have been mostly positive. USC and UCLA
may be the Mark Taper Forum and Schubert Theater of football
productions, but most Saturdays the Division I-AA Matadors have
been the ones putting on the best show.
</P>
<P>
   They are the only college football team in the Southland with a
winning record, the only team unbeaten at home, the only team with
a running back averaging more than 100 yards a game, the only team
with a quarterback who has thrown nearly twice as many touchdowns
as interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   And yet to be associated with CSUN football is to tap-dance
furiously on the big stage while glancing furtively at the shadows,
in anticipation of the hook.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Athletic director Dick Dull could drop the curtain at
the end of this season. Or in 2001, when all the CSUN sports teams
figure to join the realigned Big West Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin, though, is counting on Dull being a man of his word.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin, a former CSUN assistant, left a cushy job coaching tight
ends and special teams at UNLV to return to his native Southern
California in late July after gaining assurances from Dull that the
Matadors' football program wasn't going anywhere but up.
</P>
<P>
   Left in Kearin's capable hands, that doesn't seem like such a
reach. The Matadors are 5-4 overall and 4-3 in the Big Sky heading
into Saturday's nonconference game at SMU. Jaumal Bradley is
averaging 102.3 yards rushing and Marcus Brady has thrown 23
touchdowns (against 12 interceptions) despite playing the past two
weeks on a swollen, gimpy left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Following the lead of his coach, Brady has stayed upbeat (and
upright) in spite of the pain. ``Coach, you never see him really
down or frustrated,'' Brady said. ``You never see him depressed. He
never stops going. He's got a lot of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jeff has the perfect personality for that program,''
said San Diego Chargers head coach Mike Riley, who worked alongside
Kearin on John Robinson's staff at USC. ``He's great with people,
he's a hard worker and he's not an ego guy. He's not going to let
peripheral stuff get him down. His focus will be on his kids and
what he has, not the facilities and resources he doesn't have.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, you won't hear Kearin complain about CSUN's
shortcomings. He doesn't waste one second of his precious time
worrying about how the stadium and weight facilities don't compare
to those of his alma mater, Loyola High, much less Montana State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have what we need,'' Kearin said, sounding unlike any CSUN
football coach in recent memory. ``We have a field with grass in
it. We have seats in it. We don't need a new $10 million stadium.
Give us $1 million to build a press box and restrooms and hire more
people to work the concessions so my dad isn't waiting half an hour
to get a beer and a hot dog. We have to look at how we can maximize
football in a minimal way.''
</P>
<P>
   It says here Dull shouldn't waste another second signing Kearin
to a long-term contract, lest Kearin recovers his senses from
beneath the piles of paper on his desk.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin's title _ interim head coach _ doesn't begin to cover his
duties.
</P>
<P>
   Picture a playwright manning phones in the ticket office,
handing out programs and sweeping the theater after every
performance and you've got the idea.
</P>
<P>
   When we caught up with Kearin, about six hours into one of his
typical 16-hour work days, he was answering general telephone
inquiries _ ``We're back at home Nov. 20 against Northern Arizona.
You're welcome. Thank you for your interest in Matadors football''
_ and making arrangements to have a bus waiting to pick the team up
at the airport today in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin is some 25 miles from USC, where he toiled four years as
a low-level assistant under Robinson. In reality, he's worlds
apart.
</P>
<P>
   At USC, head coach Paul Hackett cracks a joke about how you know
the losses are mounting when luncheon meat replaces hot dishes in
the weekly media buffet. At CSUN, Kearin jokes that the football
department's VCR better not start eating his game tapes because he
can't afford a new one.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK,'' Kearin said, smiling. ``When you come to this
level of football, it's definitely a reality check.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearin may wear rosy-colored glasses, but he isn't blind. He
knows the football team has to reach out to the community if it
expects to be embraced. So he had his players practice one day
alongside a local Pop Warner team.
</P>
<P>
   He realizes the school is easily overlooked by top high-school
prospects. So he's lobbying hard for CSUN to bid on hosting the
participants of the game between Texas and California high school
standouts, to be played at Cerritos College in June.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin understands it's important for his players to be good
citizens. It's one of his pet sermons. So he was heartened,
recently, when he found out a student challenged a football player
at a fraternity party, only to have another teammate step in and
escort the player away before tempers could get out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   He knows accountability starts with him. So he was full of
apologies after letting the officiating become a distraction during
last week's 13-point loss at Portland State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought I dropped the ball,'' Kearin said three days
later. ``I grew up a little that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearin would like to mature along with the Matadors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could be happy here the rest of my life,'' he said. ``I know
you think I'm full of it, but it's the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   It'd be sad for CSUN if he blossoms somewhere else, just as it's
a shame USC isn't profiting from Riley's polish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are looking for those good stories,'' said
Riley, who spent a year raising expectations at Oregon State before
moving to the Chargers. ``They recognize hard jobs being done
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Memo to Dull: That's not just an observation, it's a warning. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 0025EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
