r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     11-12 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER FINE MESS FOR SHAQ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The NBA gave Shaquille O'Neal a slap on the wrist
Thursday. His coach may want to give him a slap someplace else.
</P>
<P>
   A day after being ejected for the second time in three games
after scuffling with Charles Barkley in an 89-88 victory over
Houston, O'Neal was suspended for one game without pay and fined
$10,000. Barkley also received a one-game suspension without pay
and a $5,000 fine for his part in the wrestling match. O'Neal
received the greater fine for throwing the first punch and getting
involved in a fight. Barkley was fined for throwing the basketball
and fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Although O'Neal said there is no problem, Lakers coach Phil
Jackson isn't so sure, hinting that frustration over O'Neal's poor
foul shooting and opponents' constant fouling tactics may be taking
their toll on his center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a lot of pressure in this business and there's
a lot of focus on Shaquille, but you just can't take yourself that
seriously,'' Jackson said. ``It's a game and you still have to
remember that there's a certain lightness or playfulness to it, and
that's one of the things that I keep trying to bring back to these
players, the playful aspect of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things, it happens in slow motion, you look
at it and say `Oh, Charles just threw the ball at Shaq, that's
going to put him out of the game. But what's Shaq doing?' I
couldn't imagine what he was doing, because certainly he's been in
situations (like that) before. But obviously there was a lot of
pressure there, and he reacted.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal and Barkley will sit out tonight's Lakers-Rockets game at
Staples Center. Dating back to last year, O'Neal has been tossed
from three of the Lakers' last 14 regular-season games. He was
ejected from last Saturday's loss at Portland after throwing a ball
at Jermaine O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   That's hardly the playful demeanor Jackson is seeking, although
O'Neal insisted Barkley caused the altercation by throwing a ball
at his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get frustrated,'' O'Neal said. ``If anyone is
frustrated, it's him. It's his team that's 0-5. My team is 5-1.
Besides, life is too short to be frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Kobe Bryant said people should not over-analyze
O'Neal's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think he wanted to punch (Barkley) in the mouth,'' said
Bryant, laughing. ``You don't have to read too much into it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, some of his teammates weren't smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is that we have to hold one another
accountable and responsible for their actions,'' said veteran A.C.
Green, whom the Lakers traded for during the offseason. ``I don't
know how it was (here) last year, but that's the way it's going to
be this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Lakers vice president Jerry West hopes O'Neal will learn from
the last two ejections.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only advice to any player is that part of being a
professional and a person of stature in this league is how you
handle these kinds of stressful situations,'' West said. ``They
happen so fast, that anyone can go off. He just can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   With O'Neal out, Jackson will use a combination of John Salley,
Travis Knight and Green on Hakeem Olajuwon tonight. Robert Horry
might be activated off the injured list today, depending on how his
sore left knee responds to Thursday's light workout. His return
would give Jackson other options in the frontcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll put the guy out there that's got the most nerve,''
Jackson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 0033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7261 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-PEARL-THEFTS-LADN     11-12 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEARL-THEFTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEARLS STOLEN BY JEWELRY RING, POLICE SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jason Kandel  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Police believe that a band of gun-toting Colombian jewelry
thieves hit the Los Angeles region again Thursday night, robbing a
man of $600,000 in pearl necklaces on a freeway transition road in
South Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The heist is the latest in a string of holdups around Los
Angeles and the San Fernando Valley, netting about $500 million
annually, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having a lot of these robberies,'' said Los Angeles
Detective Michael Woodings, part of a 15-member jewelry heist task
force. ``We've got some good information regarding some aspects of
who the suspects are, but all we know is we've got violent
criminals who are good at what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   The thieves tail jewelers from areas such as the Los Angeles
Jewelry Mart to the jewelers' homes. They also have been known to
disable the victim's car by slashing a tire or ripping out a
radiator hose.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest heist at 8 p.m. Thursday, a jewelry salesman had
hailed a cab downtown and was en route to Los Angeles International
Airport to catch a flight to New York. Four gunmen in a
dark-colored Chevrolet Blazer boxed in the taxi on the transition
from the southbound Harbor Freeway to the eastbound Glenn Anderson
Freeway.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen, including one wearing a dark-colored ski mask and a
hood, approached the cab, took the keys, opened the trunk and
grabbed two suitcases containing pearl necklaces valued at
$600,000. The robbers then fled.
</P>
<P>
   Police have recorded more than six such incidents in the Valley
so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   In February, gunmen carjacked a jewelry courier at his home in
Woodland Hills and stole $100,000 in goods. In March, thieves
confronted a courier at his home in Encino and stole an undisclosed
amount of goods. In April, a crook carrying a shotgun stole
$300,000 in jewelry from a courier in Chatsworth.
</P>
<P>
   That same month in Thousand Oaks, a gunman forced a courier into
his trunk and stole $500,000 worth of jewelry. On April 26, robbers
were foiled in Van Nuys when they took an empty jewelry case from a
courier who had dropped off his goods for the day. Later that
month, a gunman took $20,000 in gold and jewelry from a courier in
Reseda.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe that a network of about 200 thieves they
describe as Colombians who live in Los Angeles make their living by
selling stolen items to a single person, earning about 25 cents on
the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Because the group consists of many leaders and is egalitarian in
its operations, all participants in a robbery receive equal pay for
equal work, police said.
</P>
<P>
   They are so sophisticated, police say, that some of their
surveillance and countersurveillance capabilities make it difficult
for police to catch them.
</P>
<P>
   One theory is that the gang prefers to recruit former Colombian
police and soldiers because they typically are disciplined and
steer clear of drugs and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're working for a bigger network,'' said Moshe Pereg,
president of the Jewelry Manufacturers Guild in Los Angeles.
``Organized crime in Colombia is very developed.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 0046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7263 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r n BC-PEARL-THEFTS-LADN     11-12 0538
</HEADER>
