r f BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      11-12 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT'S BIGGEST SIN WAS SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The sad irony of government antitrust actions is that
those prosecuting and judging these cases have never met a payroll
or created a scintilla of wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, they find themselves empowered to destroy or
cripple a wealth-creating enterprise and diminish the financial
fortunes of millions of workers and investors.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Microsoft's prosecution, the judge apparently
even sees himself as more of a software expert than the real
experts. What worries Microsoft's friends and foes alike is the
judge's critical assessment of the integration of the Internet
browser and operating system.
</P>
<P>
   One of his findings of ``fact'' claimed putting the browser into
the operating system ``unjustifiably jeopardized the stability and
security of the operating system.'' This attempt by a judge to
instruct the industry in how best to engineer its products raised
more than a few eyebrows among information technology experts.
</P>
<P>
   While everyone is uncomfortable with ``the choke hold Microsoft
has,'' said the dean of the school of information management and
systems at the University of California-Berkeley, ``they are also
uncomfortable with having government get involved in software
design decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   In another somewhat puzzling twist of logic, Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson faults Microsoft for pricing its wares both too
high and too low. Thus, in the judge's eyes, Microsoft is guilty of
both charging too much and too little. This is what happens when
legal power trumps market power. The law becomes what the judge and
prosecution say it is.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is the company many love to hate. Columns taking
Microsoft's side during the company's legal troubles of recent
years evoked as much vitriolic denunciation as columns urging fair
play for the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The paradox of the substantial ill will toward Microsoft,
though, is how the company still managed to become one of the most
successful entrepreneurial undertakings of the 20th century. In the
process, it became the corporation with the highest stock market
capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   In a fledgling industry for which innovation is a life-and-death
matter, Microsoft came to rule its markets. Its sometimes ruthless
business practices made it many enemies; its contempt for political
niceties has sown the seeds of its potential destruction.
</P>
<P>
   What Microsoft really stands guilty of isn't violation of
antitrust laws, which is essentially a subjective matter. What's
it's really guilty of is ruthlessness and arrogance. In other
words, it acted as any powerful business tends to act. In the real
world, this means Microsoft's legal vulnerability has more to do
with politics than economics.
</P>
<P>
   If Microsoft falls, many may cheer, but it will be a Pyrrhic
victory for society at large. To the extent that government is
allowed to destroy the value Microsoft's employees have created, it
will diminish the financial fortunes of millions of hapless
bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's high-flying stock has become one of the most popular
among managers of pension funds and mutual funds, as well as people
creating nest eggs for college educations and retirements.
Economics, as always, is about tradeoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 0054EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7266 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-TIMBERWOLV     11-12 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-TIMBERWOLVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARNETT WINS LATE DUEL WITH CAMBY AS TIMBERWOLVES EDGE KNICKS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ For most of the game, the Knicks' Marcus Camby and
the Timberwolves' Kevin Garnett kept their distance Thursday night.
But in the crush of the moment, they were one-on-one, two young
stars so spindly and sturdy you could run a flag up their frames.
Two stars under pressure so intense one was bound to come out with
a game-turning moment.
</P>
<P>
   So with the ball in his hands on the baseline and Camby as close
as the rules allow, Garnett faked to his right and spun to his left
and into the paint. He stepped back and launched a fade-away shot
that arched over Camby's wingspan and an oncoming double team. As
Garnett hit the floor, his 6-foot shot landed in the net with 24.9
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Right then, it was decided. This would be Garnett's moment, his
turn to come up with a game-deciding shot and disappoint a Knicks
team that had the game wrapped up with a bow on top midway through
the fourth quarter, only to lose, 93-90.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets back to the Michael Jordan thing,'' Knicks coach Jeff
Van Gundy said of Garnett. ``I don't think he ever wanted it more
than anyone else. I just think he was better than anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   No one was better than Garnett Thursday night. He finished with
35 points, 14 rebounds and two blocked shots _ one against Camby
with five seconds left. And 15 points came in a fourth quarter in
which the Knicks shot just 6 for 20. The Knicks, led by Allan
Houston's 29 points, folded down the stretch after having a
12-point lead early in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing,'' said Latrell Sprewell, who was 0 for 5
in the fourth quarter and missed a potentially game-tying 3-point
attempt as time ran out. ``We had them. This is a game that was
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   A game Garnett single-handedly took away. After Houston was
forced to sit down in the fourth quarter with foul trouble, the
Knicks could not generate another offensive source. After Garnett
had been guarded by Larry Johnson and Kurt Thomas _ both fouled out
_ he started to take his toll on Camby, too.
</P>
<P>
   Garnett ended a 19-6 run by the Timberwolves with a 6-foot hook
shot with four minutes left to give his team an 85-84 lead. His
shot with 24.9 seconds left was the one from which the Knicks never
recovered as it gave Minnesota a 91-88 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was everywhere in the end,'' Camby said. ``I thought I had
him played tight, as tight as I could. It was a tough shot he made
to decide it. I think he was on the ground when he let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' defense was up against one of its great challenges
of the season in a talented team led by a superstar who plays with
the versatility of a Swiss Army knife. Garnett can hold down center
and forward and can cover guards. He dunks with a vicious flair,
hits a soft baseline jumper and can even pop a shot from 3-point
range. And he can do it at all from the vantage point of his
6-foot-11-inch frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can be listed at whatever he wants,'' said Van Gundy, who,
like most in the league, measures Garnett at 7-1. `'I'll say this,
he'll be the tallest guy on the floor tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Garnett stood out in every way, scoring around the Knicks'
musical-chair defense. They rotated Johnson until he found early
foul trouble, and then Thomas and Camby. But no on was going to
stop Garnett completely. That much the Knicks knew.
</P>
<P>
   The bold Wally Szczerbiak, the broad-shouldered rookie forward
from Cold Spring Harbor on Long Island, was more of a mystery. Few
knew how well he would play but Szczerbiak himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy is to go at him,'' Szczerbiak said before the
game ``Sprewell is a 40-minute player. He doesn't want to get into
foul trouble. He wants to rest on defense and play offense. His
game is offense. I think I pose some matchup problems for him.''
</P>
<P>
   At a muscular 6-7 and 244 pounds, Szczerbiak revealed a
deceptively quick first step to go with his shooting range. And at
times he got the best of Sprewell. The tandem of Garnett and
Szczerbiak kept the Knicks from blowing the game out of hand by
combining for 43 points through three quarters, but they could not
keep up with the Knicks, who had a 74-66 lead entering the final
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   What the Knicks did was more than match Minnesota's star power.
Houston helped put the Knicks in front, 31-19, after scoring 16
points in the first quarter around a helpless Anthony Peeler. His
scoring spree included eight points in the final 2 minutes 36
seconds of the quarter to set up the Knicks for the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   While Houston rested early in the second quarter, and did not
score another point in the first half, the Knicks slipped a bit to
finish the half ahead by 51-45 after having a double-digit lead
most of the way. Until the last eight minutes of the half, the
Knicks were clicking as well offensively as they had all season,
even without Houston's points.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, Chris Childs and Sprewell, moving the ball in sync,
helped the Knicks to a 14-point lead midway through the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Was this a product of the Timberwolves' jet lag from their trip
to Japan to open the season? Were they rusty from their four-day
layoff? Minnesota was supposed to be one of those Western
Conference teams equipped to beat the elite from the East. Whatever
excuse the Timberwolves wanted to use, the Knicks were in an
unflappable groove until the final minutes of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Szczerbiak and Garnett combined to cut into the
Knicks' lead. Szczerbiak, cutting across the lane, slipped around
the pedestrian defense of John Wallace for one dunk and then did
the same thing to Sprewell a couple of minutes later. Meanwhile,
Garnett was flaunting his versatility by knocking down a 3-pointer
with 1:30 left in the half to end an 18-8 run and allow Minnesota
to close to 49-43. After Sprewell scored four points to end the
half, the Knicks led, 51-45.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
