<HEADLINE>
DAVIS SAYS HE'LL STAY AT USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC defensive tackle Ennis Davis admitted that he
considered turning pro after the season, but said Thursday he
expects to return for his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   The preseason All-American from Reseda High has intercepted two
passes, an unusual stat for a lineman, but has never been 100
percent while recovering from knee surgery following last year's
Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm coming back. I've pretty much made my decision. I don't
see a reason to leave yet,'' Davis said. ``It probably would be a
whole different situation if I played as well as I can. It's a
disappointing season for me. I want to be healthy when I go to the
(NFL) combines.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say I could go in the first round this year, but I
could go a lot higher next year when I'm healthy. Of course, it's a
childhood dream to play in the NFL, but I want to maximize what I
can get out of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he is close to recovering from torn knee ligaments in
his left knee but probably won't regain full strength until after
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel 100 percent, but I feel good,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer throws: In a slight change from the original plan,
injured quarterback Carson Palmer threw a football 30 times at a
distance of 10 yards Thursday as part of his rehabilitation from a
broken collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The doctors) felt this would be an action they couldn't
simulate without throwing,'' coach Paul Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   The exercise does not change Palmer's status, with Sunday still
a key day for the quarterback to try to throw. Even if Palmer does
throw, there's doubts his shoulder could endure a full practice
next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is can he be ready for Tuesday?'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Pep talk: Hackett met with the team's seniors after practice to
offers some words of encouragement before USC plays at Washington
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `This is our last road trip together guys, let's make
it be a memorable one,''' Hackett said. ``I think they have done a
great job focusing on the team. I said they should get the most out
of these last three games.''
</P>
<P>
   Deja vu? Hackett's 3-6 record this season is identical to the
3-6 record his final Pitt team had in 1992. That team finished 3-9.
</P>
<P>
   Filling the roster: Defensive tackle Aaron Williams (neck) and
wide receiver Marcell Allmond (shoulder) will not make the trip but
should return next week. Defensive end Matt Childers (shoulder)
will probably not make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   USC will take Palmer and injured tailback Petros Papadakis. Even
though both players are out, they will count against the 60-man
limit the Pac-10 allows for road games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
