<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-NETWORK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT GEARS UP TO TAKE ORDERS FOR BUNDLED SERVICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Sprint Corp. will start taking orders from
consumers in Kansas City, Denver and Seattle on Monday for its
long-awaited, much-touted Integrated On-Demand Network.
</P>
<P>
   ION, as it is known, is a sort of Veg-O-Matic of phone services,
an all-in-one package delivered through a single connection to the
home, with one bill and one flat-rate price.
</P>
<P>
   The service bundles high-speed Internet access, up to four phone
lines and 2,200 minutes of local and long-distance calling for
$159.99 a month.
</P>
<P>
   With installations beginning in December, Sprint is one of the
first companies to deliver such an integrated package to
residential consumers. But the concept is one that almost every
phone company is working on, testing or getting ready to deliver in
selected markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is interesting. It's truly something consumers haven't
seen before,'' said Boyd Peterson, an analyst with the Yankee
Group. ``It's going to take some education. Consumers are going to
be forced to make a comparison, but there's no other service
provider you can compare this to.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Southwestern Bell's DSL and Time Warner's Road Runner
services, which are considerably cheaper, ION will offer consumers
unlimited, superfast Internet access that is always connected,
eliminating busy signals and other service interruptions common
with dial-up modems.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint says ION will offer download speeds ranging from 1.5 to 8
megabits a second, a fat enough pipe to grab large information and
entertainment files from the Internet in seconds, compared with
minutes or hours using a conventional modem.
</P>
<P>
   Upstream, or sending speeds, will be about 684 kilobits a
second, fast enough for fairly seamless videoconferencing or
desktop collaboration between home and office.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the phone and cable companies' services, however, ION
will allow consumers to reallocate their available bandwidth as
they choose, using a computer mouse to connect up to four separate
phone lines, all of which they can use simultaneously with their
Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   The package includes 2,200 minutes of calls a month, either
local or long-distance. Additional minutes are 10 cents a minute.
</P>
<P>
   The $160 monthly price tag doesn't include one-time charges of
$250 for an integrated access hub and installation costs of $150.
</P>
<P>
   But Sprint says it is marketing the service to users who already
spend upward of $200 for multiple phone lines, Internet service and
long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price point and the number of minutes included are based
on usage patterns that we know from our own experience with
customers and other industry research,'' said Steve Lunceford, a
Sprint spokesman. ``We think it's in line with the type of
customers we're targeting. If we find that people want more
minutes, that could certainly be adjusted.''
</P>
<P>
   To provide the service, Sprint will deploy electronics that
increase the capacity of the copper phone lines that run from the
local phone company's central offices to most homes. The
technology, known as a digital subscriber line, is the same as used
by Southwestern Bell to offer its high-speed Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   As with Bell's service, the technology has limitations. To
qualify for the service, customers must live within three miles of
one of Southwestern Bell's central offices, and their line must be
free of interference and electronics that are often used to extend
the range of standard phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint says it can reach up to 70 percent of the customers in
metropolitan Kansas City, although analysts say that may be wildly
optimistic based on past experience with similar technologies in
other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint will need to qualify each customer for the service ahead
of time. Initially, it will take up to 45 days between the time
customers sign up for the service and it is installed, although
Sprint says it will cut that time in half as it gets up to speed.
</P>
<P>
   Competition for high-end residential customers is heating up
around the country. But according to Peterson at the Yankee Group,
Sprint is setting a new standard with ION.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other companies are going to have to respond in kind with an
integrated offer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T plans to use cable television lines to deliver video, voice
and Internet services to residential services.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern Bell offers a package of local phone and high-speed
Internet service for $88.95 a month on the Missouri side of the
state line. It also plans to add multiple phone lines and
long-distance to its package as soon as regulators and technology
allows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The package we've come up with best represents the needs of
our customers,'' said Ellen Pantaenius of Fleishman Hillard,
Southwestern Bell's public relations firm. ``As soon as we're able
to offer long-distance, that will certainly be included in the ...
package.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 0101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
