<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7281 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-AVIATION-DIRECTOR-KAN     11-12 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVIATION-DIRECTOR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AVIATION DIRECTOR FACES BIG CHALLENGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE RICE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Shortly after Russell Widmar became Kansas
City's new aviation director, he singled out a staffer's
performance at a City Council committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
   That employee had successfully applied for a state grant that
will pay $640,000 to convert the department's diesel bus-fuel
system to compressed natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let people know if staff does a good job,'' said Widmar, who
came to Kansas City in August after working as executive director
of the Salt Lake City Airport Authority. ``You have to take
interest in what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Such words should be welcome in a department that has been beset
with morale problems. In the two years before Widmar arrived, 200
of the Aviation Department's 460 full-time employees left.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing stability to the department is just one of several
challenges that Widmar faces _ including a $156 million renovation
of Kansas City International Airport, maintaining the Downtown
Airport as a prime facility for corporate aviation and transforming
Richards-Gebaur Memorial Airport into an intermodal transportation
hub.
</P>
<P>
   Widmar, 53, has held executive positions with Hughes Aircraft
Co. in Fullerton, Calif.; Lockheed Air Terminal Inc. in Burbank,
Calif.; and Los Angeles' Department of Airports, where he began his
aviation career in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City is his first job in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, my impressions of Kansas City have been very
positive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And so far, city leaders like what they have seen of Widmar.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Teresa Loar, who chairs the Aviation Committee,
said she has already received memos from Widmar about the
accomplishments of some staff members.
</P>
<P>
   Widmar ``has excellent credentials and a keen understanding of
aviation issues,'' Loar said. ``And he has made it a priority to
stabilize staff, and so far he has done a good job at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City's airports, Widmar said, are filled with potential _
especially KCI, with its three circular terminals and its
drive-to-the-gate convenience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The buildings have a wonderful and unique design to them,'' he
said. ``There is no other airport in the United States like KCI.
Where else can you park this close to a gate?''
</P>
<P>
   Widmar said the renovations, which are scheduled to begin in
late 2000 and be completed in 2004, will maintain the
drive-to-the-gate system.
</P>
<P>
   And in an era when airport officials throughout the country are
crying for extra gates, Widmar thinks KCI has enough gates to get
through the next eight years. The renovations would leave six
unassigned gates, which would allow for an airline to expand.
</P>
<P>
   And KCI, he said, could install loading bridges for crews to
connect planes with terminals. That way, crews would not have to
work in inclement weather.
</P>
<P>
   Widmar said the city will continue to invest in the 72-year-old
Downtown Airport. The old control tower soon will be demolished,
and other improvements will be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``That airport is very convenient for corporate America,''
Widmar said. ``It is one of the premier general-aviation facilities
in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Flying operations at Richards-Gebaur Memorial Airport will close
at the end of the year. Voters in August approved a measure that
will turn the airport into an intermodal hub.
</P>
<P>
   The plans call for another runway to be built, although skeptics
have questioned whether the Federal Aviation Administration will be
willing to help pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council, however, has approved a master plan for the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a strong sense of what can be done there,''
Widmar said. ``But the city just approved the master plan, so I
don't want to prejudge anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Widmar also has told city leaders that voters might have to
approve an increase in the city's bonded-indebtedness capacity for
the airport. That capacity right now is near $200 million, but two
projects alone _ the KCI terminal renovations and a proposed
consolidated car-rental system _ would cost that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Other top priorities, he said, are maintaining the Trans World
Airlines overhaul base, maintaining KCI's successful cargo
operation, and land acquisitions. The city was recently embarrassed
when it failed to buy land near Interstate 29 that a private
parking company eventually bought.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his resignation earlier this year in Salt Lake City amid
staff dissension over a proposed $1.03 billion expansion of Salt
Lake City International Airport, Widmar said he remains proud of
the work he did there.
</P>
<P>
   But Widmar, who recently finished moving out of his Salt Lake
City home, said he is focused on Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am looking forward to being here,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
