<HEADLINE>
UCLA NEEDS TO IMPRESS RECRUITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's a big game for UCLA _ not just because of the
opponent (first-place Washington), but also because of the
spectators. This is one of the Bruins' biggest recruiting weekends
of the season, with four coveted national prospects visiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a bunch of recruits from out of state,'' Bruins coach
Bob Toledo said, ``and it's important to put on a good show for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   They are:
</P>
<P>
   _Stevie Lee, one of the nation's top defensive tackles. He's
from Evangel Christian Academy in Shreveport, La., and he has
Michigan, Florida State, Texas and Texas A&AMP;M on his list.
</P>
<P>
   _Phillip Geiggar, a safety from Evangel Christian who's
considering Florida State, Florida and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   _Ronnie Rodamer, a 6-foot-4 receiver from Morgantown, W.Va., who
has scholarship offers from Tennessee and Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   _Albert Hollis, a tailback from Sacramento who orally committed
to UCLA months ago but is visiting other schools.
</P>
<P>
   Valencia linebacker Ray Cassaday, who has committed to UCLA, and
tailback Manuel White, who has not, also are visiting this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Pep gathering: Thursday's practice was interrupted for 10
minutes when hundreds of UCLA athletes and athletic-department
employees trotted onto Spaulding Field to inspire the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   A local Pop Warner team dressed in UCLA jerseys also attended
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for some substitutes,'' Toledo quipped. ``They're
a little skinny, but they're hard to tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   Review of the Week: Defensive tackle Pete Holland, a history
major and six-time member of the director's honor roll, has agreed
to review a book each week for the Daily News. This week: (ital)The
Lords of Discipline, by Pat Conroy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conroy, the most poetic and contemporary storyteller of the
South, tells the tale of a young group of men struggling for
survival and striving for manhood in The Citadel, the brutal South
Carolina military institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through carefully and artfully wrought characters, Conroy
weaves a poignant tale of how ambition and prejudice challenge
everything these young men think they know about loyalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 sacks (out of four).
</P>
<P>
   Big Kick: Gastin Kutos, winner of the Daily News/KCAL 9 Kick For
Cash promotion, could score a grand prize of $100,000 if he makes a
35-yard field goal at the end of the first quarter Saturday. Kutos,
22, from Los Angeles, reached the finals by kicking the longest
field goal in the qualifying round.
</P>
<P>
   If Kutos misses, he'll receive two tickets to the Jan. 1 Rose
Bowl, plus UCLA season tickets for next season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
