<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7285 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-HOTLINE-INQUIRY-KAN &LR;      11-12 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTLINE-INQUIRY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATHS OF BROTHERS PROMPTS HOT-LINE INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONNA McGUIRE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ State Auditor Claire McCaskill expects to
spend as long as six months conducting the first statewide probe
into how Missouri workers respond to hot-line calls on child abuse
and neglect.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill pledged to conduct a performance review of the
Division of Family Services hot-line system during her campaign for
auditor more than a year ago. The deaths of 8-year-old brothers
Larry and Gary Bass last month in Kansas City prompted her to begin
the audit earlier than she had planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided I couldn't wait any longer,'' McCaskill, the former
Jackson County prosecutor, said during a press conference Thursday
at Kansas City Police Department headquarters. ``It is pretty
important that somebody answers the bell when people call (the hot
line).''
</P>
<P>
   An internal DFS investigation recently found that a hot-line
worker and other staff made errors in the Bass case after a
hot-line call was received this fall. DFS suspended at least three
employees for 20 days, expanded employee training and hired an
outside expert to study the agency's child-welfare training
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The boys' mother, Mary Bass, 31, faces child-abuse charges and
two counts of second-degree murder. Child-abuse charges also were
filed against her boyfriend, Tony Dixon, 36.
</P>
<P>
   A four- or five-member team from the state auditor's office will
spend a few weeks learning DFS hot-line guidelines and training
procedures before studying how well the agency meets its own
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Agency officials pledged to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have talked all week about the necessity to look at
ourselves and improve procedures to protect children,'' said Deb
Hendricks, a spokeswoman for the Missouri Department of Social
Services, which oversees DFS. ``This is certainly another piece of
information to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The auditor's probe will not attempt to study individual cases
or judge any DFS child-protection decisions, McCaskill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Monday-morning quarterbacking,'' she said.
``Rather, it is about the process of the hot line and whether or
not we have consistency and whether (DFS) processes are being
followed.''
</P>
<P>
   All calls to Missouri's child abuse hot line, (800) 392-3738,
are routed to Jefferson City. Reports generated by those calls are
electronically forwarded to individual DFS offices. In Jackson
County, for example, a bell rings when a report arrives on a
printer. After hours, an on-call staff member receives a page.
</P>
<P>
   Calls are coded as emergency or nonemergency. On emergency
calls, an investigator is sent as soon as possible. Nonemergency
calls are to be handled within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   After making contact, the investigator logs information about
that contact into the DFS system. A supervisor reviews that
information.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Jefferson City track response times statewide each
month.
</P>
<P>
   On average in Jackson County, DFS receives about 600 reports of
child abuse and neglect per month. Most investigations are
concluded within 30 days, and some are concluded much more quickly.
In the majority of cases _ 75 to 80 percent of the time _ the state
decides it lacks ``probable cause'' to show that abuse or neglect
occurred.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 0114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0033 </DOCNO>
