<SLUG> BC-POKEMON-BOX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL VIEWERS MAKE HIT OUT OF `POKEMON' 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Dave McNary  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pokemania has struck America's multiplexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pokemon: the First Movie'' generated a better-than-expected
$10.1 million on opening day Wednesday at 2,889 theaters as
exhibitors reported numerous sellouts. Warner Bros. predicted the
Thursday total would match that number.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pokemon'' posted the fourth-biggest Wednesday opening ever,
trailing ``Star Wars: Episode 1'' ($28.5 million), ``Independence
Day'' ($17.4 million) and ``Men In Black'' ($14 million). The
number was impressive since most tickets were sold at discounted
children's and matinee rates.
</P>
<P>
   The studio also predicted the movie will break the $45.7million
record set by ``A Bug's Life'' for best five-day opening by an
animated film.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Dergarabedian, president of Exhibitor Relations, credited
Warner Bros. with exploiting the children's fad of collecting
Pokemon cards and toys. Warner planned to give away 8 million cards
_ one for each ticket _ and reported Thursday some theaters had run
out of their allocation.
</P>
<P>
   Warner also will distribute 2 million cards at its Studio
Stores; Burger King has launched a tie-in promotion giving away 57
Pokemon toys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie has been part of a brilliant marketing scheme,''
Dergarabedian said. ``They've also released it at exactly the right
time. It's imperative to release this kind of film when it's hot
because kids can change their minds quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Dergarabedian said the film should perform well through the
holiday season even after Disney's ``Toy Story 2'' opens Nov. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Warner distribution chief Dan Fellman said the opening was far
above studio forecasts, adding, ``We've had exhibitors calling all
day to say it's a great way to launch the holiday season.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellman said the studio plans to extend the card giveaway by up
to 10 million more cards.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
