A7293 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-PEARL-THEFTS-WRITETHR     11-12 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEARL-THEFTS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEARLS STOLEN BY JEWELRY RING, POLICE SAY
</HEADLINE>
  
( Eds, corrects time element in lede sentence to Wednesday night.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jason Kandel  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Police believe that a band of gun-toting Colombian jewelry
thieves hit the Los Angeles region again Wednesday night, robbing a
man of $600,000 in pearl necklaces on a freeway transition road in
South Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The heist is the latest in a string of holdups around Los
Angeles and the San Fernando Valley, netting about $500 million
annually, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having a lot of these robberies,'' said Los Angeles
Detective Michael Woodings, part of a 15-member jewelry heist task
force. ``We've got some good information regarding some aspects of
who the suspects are, but all we know is we've got violent
criminals who are good at what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   The thieves tail jewelers from areas such as the Los Angeles
Jewelry Mart to the jewelers' homes. They also have been known to
disable the victim's car by slashing a tire or ripping out a
radiator hose.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest heist at 8 p.m. Thursday, a jewelry salesman had
hailed a cab downtown and was en route to Los Angeles International
Airport to catch a flight to New York. Four gunmen in a
dark-colored Chevrolet Blazer boxed in the taxi on the transition
from the southbound Harbor Freeway to the eastbound Glenn Anderson
Freeway.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen, including one wearing a dark-colored ski mask and a
hood, approached the cab, took the keys, opened the trunk and
grabbed two suitcases containing pearl necklaces valued at
$600,000. The robbers then fled.
</P>
<P>
   Police have recorded more than six such incidents in the Valley
so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   In February, gunmen carjacked a jewelry courier at his home in
Woodland Hills and stole $100,000 in goods. In March, thieves
confronted a courier at his home in Encino and stole an undisclosed
amount of goods. In April, a crook carrying a shotgun stole
$300,000 in jewelry from a courier in Chatsworth.
</P>
<P>
   That same month in Thousand Oaks, a gunman forced a courier into
his trunk and stole $500,000 worth of jewelry. On April 26, robbers
were foiled in Van Nuys when they took an empty jewelry case from a
courier who had dropped off his goods for the day. Later that
month, a gunman took $20,000 in gold and jewelry from a courier in
Reseda.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe that a network of about 200 thieves they
describe as Colombians who live in Los Angeles make their living by
selling stolen items to a single person, earning about 25 cents on
the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Because the group consists of many leaders and is egalitarian in
its operations, all participants in a robbery receive equal pay for
equal work, police said.
</P>
<P>
   They are so sophisticated, police say, that some of their
surveillance and countersurveillance capabilities make it difficult
for police to catch them.
</P>
<P>
   One theory is that the gang prefers to recruit former Colombian
police and soldiers because they typically are disciplined and
steer clear of drugs and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're working for a bigger network,'' said Moshe Pereg,
president of the Jewelry Manufacturers Guild in Los Angeles.
``Organized crime in Colombia is very developed.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
