<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7295 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-VETERAN-MEDAL-KAN &LR;      11-12 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETERAN-MEDAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERAN RECEIVES REPLACEMENT PURPLE HEART IN CEREMONY AT GRADE
SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT STEARNS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGHLANDVILLE, Mo. _ Like countless others, Ralph P. Francisco
Jr. served.
</P>
<P>
   For him, it was in Gen. George S. Patton's 3rd Army, as it
slogged slowly through Europe to Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco vividly remembers the day his war ended; the day a
shell fragment tore through his leg in a snowy field in February
1945. He received a Purple Heart for having been wounded in combat.
</P>
<P>
   Like countless others, Francisco went home, put his medal in a
cedar chest and got on with his life. Never thought much about it,
other than the satisfaction of knowing it was there.
</P>
<P>
   Until the day, 14 years ago, when it wasn't. When Francisco
realized someone had stolen the Purple Heart from his home in the
small southwest Missouri town of Forsyth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ralph's not much to say anything,'' said his wife, Allene
Francisco. ``It made him sick. Who would do that?''
</P>
<P>
   Veterans Days, when folks would ask about it, were especially
hard, Ralph Francisco said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, thanks to the interest of a third-grade teacher in
the Ozarks, the dogged efforts of a Pentagon employee who knew her,
and the military code of honoring those who came before, the town
of Highlandville gave Francisco, 73, a Veterans Day to remember.
</P>
<P>
   There, in a linoleum-tiled school gymnasium, underneath a set of
smudged glass basketball backboards, before several dozen rapt
students, friends and relatives, Ralph Francisco got a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   He got a new Purple Heart.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for replacing Francisco's medal came up about two weeks
ago in a conversation between Stephani Bryant, a third-grade
teacher at Highlandville Elementary School, and Jo Higgins, the
school's gym teacher and Francisco's daughter. Higgins told Bryant
of her father's loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to get him a new one,'' Higgins said. ``I
didn't know if it was possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, who had taught a special section on veterans to her
class and had invited several veterans to speak for Veterans Day,
decided to see whether she could get Francisco a replacement medal
in time for the holiday. She called Steve Doucette, a college
friend who is a civilian employee at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, they ran into a problem. The military has a backlog
of about 98,000 requests for replacement medals _ about two years'
worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paperwork at the Pentagon is a nightmare,'' Doucette said.
``Going through the official chain would have taken months.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Francisco's discharge papers would have allowed them to
bypass the lengthy procedure. But he had given them to his mother,
who had since died. Francisco, who settled down on a Forsyth farm,
raised three children, ran a service station and sold insurance,
hadn't given much thought to them. Nobody knew where the papers
were.
</P>
<P>
   But when Higgins asked her father whether he had any other
documentation, he pulled out his wallet and withdrew a tattered old
card he had been carrying around for 53 years: a portable copy of
his discharge papers. Under a category for citations, it read,
``Purple Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant and Higgins sent a copy of the card to Doucette, still
keeping the quest a secret from Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just thought my class was really into it and that's why we
were asking him all this,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to get the medal, which Doucette's co-workers
chipped in to pay for. But just getting the medal wasn't enough for
Doucette.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `We've got to do more than just send down the
medal,' '' said Doucette, a senior intelligence specialist for the
Air Force. ``What a great opportunity for this guy. It just made me
feel like we've got to do more. The military is a big family, and
it's nice to have an opportunity to thank him.''
</P>
<P>
   So Doucette, through his military contacts, arranged for an
autographed picture to Francisco from Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. He arranged for Lt. Col. Gus
Stafford, a battalion commander from Fort Leonard Wood, to present
the medal in the ceremony at the school gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 23,000 people that work here,'' Doucette said of the
Pentagon. ``Getting things through is just impossible. I think
everyone knew this little school was the catalyst.''
</P>
<P>
   And just two weeks after the initial conversation, Stafford
pinned the Purple Heart to the left breast pocket of Francisco's
green-and-white plaid shirt as sunlight poured in through the
gymnasium's open doors.
</P>
<P>
   Stafford, a strapping Ranger with a dazzling set of medals and
ribbons on his own uniform, choked up a bit as he presented the
medal to the aging veteran, who stood straight, but whose slack jaw
gave away his shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rare to give a Purple Heart in the first place,''
Stafford said afterward. ``To be able to put a Purple Heart on a
World War II veteran is just an unimaginable honor for me. I use
the movie `Saving Private Ryan' in basic training to teach the
whole idea of duty, of fulfilling your obligations. This is the
Army living up to its values.''
</P>
<P>
   And in era when the military seems fairly distant from many
people's lives, Stafford said, the ceremony also served the
military's purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really important to reach out to American society,
especially in small towns like this,'' he said. ``To make sure they
don't forget us and to show we don't forget them.''
</P>
<P>
   The message, taught by Bryant and symbolized by Francisco and
Stafford, seemed to get across to the children in the town of about
700.
</P>
<P>
   ``Veterans are important, because they keep us safe, they fight
for our freedom....That way, other countries can't steal our
freedom,'' wrote Brian Campbell, 9, in an essay he read aloud at a
classroom reception after the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Even Francisco said he learned something from the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really something,'' Francisco said. ``It means a lot more
to me now after this. It was just something I had before. I'll put
it back in a box, but I'll keep a close watch on it. I'll wear it
on Veterans Day, and maybe some days when it's not Veterans Day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
