<HEADER>
A7297 &Cx1f; tab-z
r t BC-COWTOWN-CHICAGO-INDEP     11-12 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWTOWN-CHICAGO-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `UDDER' CHARMS OF MRS. O'LEARY'S TOWN  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: CHICAGO, Midwest Editors)   (This lively 875-word ``separate buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``a''
domestic news, ``k'' commentary news and ``t'' travel news
files.)  
  
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The cows are everywhere in the Chicago Theatre,
standing around the elegant marble lobby, scattered about the
balconies and queuing up along the carpeted corridors. There are
one or two outside in the street, waiting to be brought inside, and
there are quite a few in the showroom next door.
</P>
<P>
   These are the most famous, well loved and certainly the best
behaved cows that the city of Chicago has ever known, which has a
lot to do with the fact that they are made of fiberglass.
</P>
<P>
   For months over 300 of them stood around the center of the city,
as ornaments, contemporary art and just plain fun, delighting the
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that can take my teenager downtown four times must be
good,'' says Dave Durham, a local journalist, as he prepared for
the charity auction Tuesday night that was to sell them off for
good.
</P>
<P>
   They are pure fantasy and imagination, some in pop art or
psychedelic colors, a Mondrian, Magritte and Miro, one in red
mirror tiles, and another covered entirely with bottle tops.
</P>
<P>
   There are cows done up as grandes dames with dresses and pearls,
a space cow in full NASA kit (called ``Mooooooonwalk''), Yankee
Doodle Cow, one with a shark's fin, and (my personal favorite) a
carmine red cow suspended upside down and entitled Odalisque
(Reclining Nude).
</P>
<P>
   There is one still on display in the United Airlines office,
which is a bovine member of the Coldstream Guards, complete with
bearskin and chin strap, but all the rest have been corralled here
into the theatre.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, Chicago was a little wary of being called
Cowtown. The city has long thought of itself as a sophisticated,
international metropolis, not a center for cattle auctions any
more.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that today Chicago is a sophisticated international
metropolis, utterly confident of itself, the center of the city
revived by a booming economy, a smart mayor and a lot of hard work.
It can afford to laugh at itself a little.
</P>
<P>
   It made its fortune through its vast stockyards, abbatoirs and
meat packing plants and agriculture is still very important to the
local economy: farm machinery makers John Deere and Caterpillar and
agribusiness giants like Archer Daniels Midland are locals, and
much of Illinois is still farming country.
</P>
<P>
   But the giant Chicago exchanges are more likely to be trading
financial futures than longhorns these days, and many of those
giant buildings sprouting out in the fields are distribution
centers for electronic commerce companies.
</P>
<P>
   Chicagoans still have a love affair with the cow in another
form, suitably aged, perfectly grilled and plonked on to a plate
with some of Idaho's finest potatoes and a little freshly made
English mustard.
</P>
<P>
   Only in Buenos Aires and Kobe in Japan will you find a similar
fixation on steak. At Gibsons, one of the finest steak houses in
the world, they will lovingly show you the cuts before you order,
indicating the finer points of the marbling and the texture.
</P>
<P>
   There is everything from a dainty little 22-ounce rib eye to the
life-threatening 48-ounce Porterhouse, which presumably requires
health insurance (they sell three or four a night).
</P>
<P>
   Preceded by a vase full of gin martini, accompanied by a bottle
of hefty cabernet sauvignon and followed by a cigar in the bar
afterwards, this is a truly Chicagoan meal, one that leaves you
with great respect for these tough, gritty Midwesterners and their
tough, gritty digestive systems.
</P>
<P>
   But there is rather more to Chicago food than steak these days,
just as there is more to Chicago than cows. The new restaurants
which are springing up around town are as likely to serve bean
sprouts as beef.
</P>
<P>
   Blackbird has milk-soaked and rock-salt-cured foie gras with
quince puree; Tru offers roasted sturgeon over braised oxtail and
truffle ragout. The challenge to the digestion is just as robust
and the cholesterol count remains impressive, of course; this is
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The cows _ frivolous, wild, wacky or endearing _ have helped
Chicago crystallize a sense of itself as a city on the up.
</P>
<P>
   It was a very typical gesture from Mayor Richard Daley, who is
sometimes mocked as ``Mayor of the Flowerpots'' for his obsessive
interest in the details of city management, but he also understands
intuitively what works and what makes people happy. Getting the
details right, and doing it in a spirit of fun, are critical to a
city's sense of itself.
</P>
<P>
   There was an additional perk from the cows, which is that they
helped Chicago get one up on New York.
</P>
<P>
   As they were on display in Chicago, New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani hit the headlines for trying to close down the
``Sensations'' exhibition of contemporary art in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Daley is positively upbeat, Mayor Giuliani comes across
as a mean man,'' wrote Thomas Cochran, Executive Director of the
U.S. Conference of Mayors. ``It is interesting how art affects two
cities and how two mayors use art _ one in a very positive way and
the other negative _ to convey different messages.''
</P>
<P>
   For a city with a robust sense of civic pride, it was mooooosic
to their ears. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
