<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7300 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-MEMORIAL-CEREMONY-KAN     11-12 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEMORIAL-CEREMONY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERTY MEMORIAL CEREMONY HONORS VETERANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA AND STEVE PENN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Before a hushed crowd at the Liberty Memorial
on Thursday, retired Adm. Robert Spane told tales of the Navy
bombers who won the Battle of Midway and helped change the course
of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He heralded the bombers as ``common Americans who did uncommon
things.''
</P>
<P>
   On a crisp morning, city leaders also used the Veterans Day
service as a chance to honor the unsung heroes of Kansas City:
ordinary people who helped save the Liberty Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, the city will begin a $65 million restoration of the
monument, which has been closed since 1994 because of unsafe
conditions. Leaders praised voters who last year backed a sales tax
to finance improvements.
</P>
<P>
   The monument is to reopen on Veterans Day 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I believe it is fitting that on such a beautiful day,
the cloud over the Liberty Memorial is lifting,'' said Sheila
Kemper Dietrich, co-chairwoman for the Kids for Liberty campaign.
``And many of you here are the reasons why we're here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as they looked with hope toward the monument's future,
almost 1,000 dignitaries, veterans and other people remembered the
sacrifices of the past. Spane, who is chief executive officer of
Vanguard Airlines, gave the keynote address.
</P>
<P>
   As with every Veterans Day service, this year's gathering
honored the thread that binds veterans of all generations.
</P>
<P>
   The Sons of the Revolution, dressed in uniforms of the 1700s,
recalled those who fought for America's independence.
</P>
<P>
   They marched with high school ROTC students walking lockstep on
the circular drive in front of the memorial. Drums tapped. Shoes
clacked. Veterans from the Vietnam and Korean wars clustered with
their compatriots.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial was one of the last Kansas City landmarks Robert
Chappell saw before he boarded a train at Union Station on his way
to fight in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   After being captured at the Battle of the Bulge, Chappell said,
he spent five months in a German prisoner-of-war camp. His captors
sent him on forced marches. A small chunk of bread lasted a week.
He lost 80 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to Kansas City, the 217-foot-monument high on
the hill nearly brought tears to his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like heaven to me,'' recalled Chappell, 75, as he
adjusted his hearing aid and gazed up at the deteriorating
structure again Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The restoration will fortify the structural support system under
the courtyard, replace the elevated decks and stairways, and
restore or replace the fountains, urns and sphinxes. The city also
will restore Memory Hall, the administration building, the tower
and the grounds adjacent to the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters still need more private donations for an expanded
museum at the monument's base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still need another $18 million to make sure that we have
exhibits you can see when the doors open,'' said Ollie Gates,
chairman of the Citizens to Save Liberty Memorial Campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a great job across the street,'' Gates noted,
referring to Union Station. ``But we can do even better.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Mayor Kay Barnes called the day a significant one in
the city's history. As Barnes attended the reopening of Union
Station on Wednesday, she said Liberty Memorial was in her
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``My vantage point looked up to the memorial,'' Barnes said.
``There are significant improvements under way in these two blocks.
And we have an obligation to bring this memorial back so we can
continue to be able to commemorate all veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur S. Brisbane, president and publisher of The Kansas City
Star, said it was important for children to learn from the ``wisdom
of past generations.'' The newspaper helped sponsor the Kids for
Liberty campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Some youngsters appeared to be getting the message.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Jo Baumgardner, 11, of Clear Creek Elementary School in
Shawnee, Kan., read a winning essay about the importance of
citizenship. Her school raised $1,056 for the Kids for Liberty
campaign, a citywide effort to involve schoolchildren in the fund
raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``My essay was about serving the needs of others,'' Katie Jo
said. ``And as the city gets larger, so do its needs. By learning
to serve, we will become good citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   David Valdivia, 10, roamed the grounds holding a sign with a
picture of his late grandfather, who served in World War II. Daniel
Barrera died in 1986, before David was born. The sign was meant to
honor Barrera and all other veterans.
</P>
<P>
   As a high school band played taps to end the ceremony, David ran
across the driveway for a better look.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'd love to follow his grandfather into the Army.
Although he'd never visited the Liberty Memorial, David said he
recognized the sacrifices of those who served their country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of them, because their job is important,'' David
said.
</P>
<P>
   Said his mother, Carmela Valdivia: ``He's learning a lot
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Anita Gorman, a former member of the Kansas City Board of Parks
and Recreation Commissioners, said she was proud that the city was
remembering veterans and reclaiming the memorial that honored them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that Kansas Citians don't forget,'' Gorman said.
``And promises we make, we keep.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
