<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY REACHES MLS FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ Rarely seen team president Tim Leiweke visited the
Galaxy locker room before Thursday's decisive match with Dallas. He
said he saw a bunch of focused faces and admitted his presence may
have spoiled the mood.
</P>
<P>
   A problem with preparation was one reason why Leiweke fired
coach Octavio Zambrano in March and replaced him with longtime UCLA
coach Sigi Schmid.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Leiweke's paying Schmid, he certainly got his money's
worth.
</P>
<P>
   In a near-flawless performance from start to finish, the
emotionally-charged Galaxy delivered quick blows, then kept the
Burn on its heels, not allowing the pesky group from Dallas to ever
find a rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   Once Galaxy playmaker Mauricio Cienfuegos delivered the biggest
blow in the 68th minute, L.A. knew it was on its way to the Nov. 21
MLS Cup championship in Foxboro, Mass., eliminating the Burn 3-1 in
front of 25,703 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos, Carlos Hermosillo and Greg Vanney all scored to give
the Galaxy its second Western Conference title in four years,
returning the team to the place where it suffered the toughest loss
in franchise history, a 3-2 defeat to D.C. United in the inaugural
1996 MLS championship.
</P>
<P>
   Now all L.A. has to do is await the winner of Saturday's
decisive match between Columbus and D.C. United to learn who stands
in the way.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy didn't waste any time testing Dallas' thin backline _
which was without starters Eric Dade and Brandon Pollard.
</P>
<P>
   Vanney sent a cross in the second minute for Ezra Hendrickson.
Dallas' Paul Broome was in position to head it away, but the rarely
used defender mistimed his jump, allowing the ball to roll off his
sleeve to set up a Galaxy penalty kick. Vanney finished from there,
easily beating goalkeeper Mark Dodd for his second goal of the
playoffs and 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo, who scored two goals on his wife's birthday last
week, scored on his 11-year-old son's birthday this time, giving
the Galaxy a 2-0 lead in the 20th minute.
</P>
<P>
   The play started on Roy Myers' run down the left side. He
crossed in front for Clint Mathis. Dodd came out to challenge, but
his errant clear rolled in front to Hermosillo, who finished into
an open net.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Note:!off! The Galaxy's Robin Fraser has been named a
finalist for Major League Soccer's 1999 Defender of the Year award.
D.C. United's Jeff Agoos and Chicago's Lubos Kubik are the other
finalists.
</P>
<P>
   The BIC Defender of the Year is awarded to the player judged by
MLS coaching staffs and general managers to be the best defender
during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser, 32, made his first season as team captain a solid one,
helping the Galaxy set a league record for defensive efficiency.
The team became the first in league history to allow less than one
goal per game (29 goals in 32 games for a 0.91 goals-against
average).
</P>
<P>
   With Fraser leading the way, the Galaxy recorded a league-high
11 shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser is one of four Galaxy finalists up for league awards this
season. First-year coach Sigi Schmid is up for Coach of the Year,
netminder Kevin Hartman is among the favorites for Goalkeeper of
the Year, and Simon Elliott is nominated for Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   The winners of the the league's 12 awards will be announced next
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
