<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS DEFEAT COLORADO 5-2
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Kings don't have two-thirds of their No.1
line. Nor do they have their best goalie.
</P>
<P>
   But they do have Ziggy Palffy, Vladimir Tsyplakov, Jamie Storr
and an effective penalty-killing unit. Thursday night at Staples
Center, that was enough to beat Colorado 5-2 in front of 14,323.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, a right winger, is the lone healthy member of the top
line. Luc Robitaille has a broken foot and Jozef Stumpel is
recovering from hernia surgery. Yet Palffy continued to score,
getting a goal and two assists to give him a team-best 21 points.
His goal gave the Kings a 1-0 lead, and Marko Tuomainen followed 52
seconds later with his fourth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy later assisted on Tsyplakov's power-play goal in the
second period and Len Barrie's first of the season in the third
period. Tsyplakov scored his second with 2:52 remaining on a
wraparound.
</P>
<P>
   Also, goalie Stephane Fiset is listed as day-to-day after
suffering a contusion on his right hand from being struck by a puck
during Tuesday's pregame warmup. His replacement, Storr, stopped 25
shots in improving to 3-0-1 this season.
</P>
<P>
   Storr stopped four shots in Colorado's first power play. It
appeared Storr moved the puck into the goal after the last shot got
pinned against the post, but referee Don Van Massenhoven ruled the
puck dead.
</P>
<P>
   But Colorado scored on that power play when Chris Dingman banged
a shot off Storr. It's not surprising, since the Kings entered the
game tied for 26th in the league in penalty killing at home.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Klemm added a third-period goal for Colorado, his third of
the season. Colorado played without captain Joe Sakic, who suffered
a stiff back during Monday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   Storr got help from the penalty-killing unit, which is a good
thing because the Kings have been anemic on the power play.
Although Tsyplakov scored on the power play to give the Kings a 3-1
lead, Los Angeles entered Thursday's game having scored in just one
of its last 11 power plays over three games.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche penalty-killing unit had stopped 11 of the last
12, so it didn't need any assistance. Yet twice Los Angeles right
winger Donald Audette committed penalties to kill his team's power
plays.
</P>
<P>
   As if the Kings' power play hasn't been dreadful enough lately,
now they're helping their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter Thursday. The Kings stopped four of five
Colorado power plays through the first two periods.
</P>
<P>
   In the first period, the teams decided to skate instead of fight
_ there wasn't a penalty until King Brad Chartrand was called for
holding a stick.
</P>
<P>
   Twice, Colorado left the left side open, and twice in 52 seconds
the Kings made the Avalanche pay.
</P>
<P>
   First, Palffy stood unguarded next to Colorado goalie Patrick
Roy, received Sean O'Donnell's across-the-slot pass and knocked it
in at 7:24.
</P>
<P>
   Then at 8:16, Tuomainen retrieved a loose puck and beat Roy to
the stick side. It was Tuomainen's fourth goal, all in the last
seven games.
</P>
<P>
   After Los Angeles first goal, the crowd started chanting
``Patrick! Patrick!'' After the second goal, an animated Eric
Cartman from ``South Park'' provided the chant, much to the crowd's
delight.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado outshot Los Angeles 12-10 in the first period and 18-15
through two.
</P>
<P>
   Roy stopped 18 shots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
