<HEADER>
A7306 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-CAR-NHRA-QUALIFYING-L     11-12 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-QUALIFYING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADER SCHUMACHER POSITIONS HIMSELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   POMONA _ It's not over yet.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Schumacher, who needs only to qualify for this weekend's
Auto Club NHRA Nationals to clinch his first Top Fuel championship,
failed to put himself safely into Sunday's race following the first
round of qualifying Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago native recorded a 4.712-second pass at 300.13 mph,
which is good enough for the No. 9 qualifying position, but puts
him in a precarious position if he's not able to improve in the
final three sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Amato, who won this event in 1997, is No. 1 at 4.610 with
two-time defending Top Fuel champion Gary Scelzi second at 4.613.
Other category leaders are Ron Capps in Funny Car, Warren Johnson
in Pro Stock, Whittier native Matt Hines in Pro Stock Bike and Bob
Panella in Pro Stock Truck.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not concerned'' said Schumacher, who leads Scelzi by 109
points heading into the event. ''If we can't run better then
(4.71), we don't deserve to qualify. It was on a pretty good pass,
then something broke lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Amato, who still has an outside chance at his sixth Top Fuel
championship, isn't counting on similar occurrences for Schumacher
during the rest of the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''They'll do better,'' said Amato, who would still need to win
the event and set a national record to win the title. ''They've
been the most consistent car this season, so you have to figure
they can run quicker. That (4.71) will be close.''
</P>
<P>
   Amato doesn't have that concern after recording his 4.61 at
316.90 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're excited about just getting the car down the track,''
said Amato, who has won a series-high five events this season. ''We
have the (Big Bud Shootout) coming up on Saturday, so we didn't
want to go into the shootout not qualified. We've been down that
road too many times. So we put a conservative, 4.60-second setup on
it. The track is pretty good. It went right down Broadway, and here
we are.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Capps, who achieved his second quickest pass with a 4.868
run at 309.34. Tony Pedregon, who won the season-opening
Winternationals here in February, is second at 4.957. Nine-time
Funny Car champion John Force is not qualified after smoking the
tires almost instantly, slowing to a 19.504.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't change a thing from Houston (two weeks ago),'' said
Capps, who is driving for his fourth crew chief of the season at
this race after Dale Armstrong was replaced by Ed ''Ace'' McCulloch
earlier this week. ''Ace left it alone, just compensating for the
change in air.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was just a great run. I clicked it off a tad early,
otherwise it would have been quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who is has recorded the top speed at the past 28
national events, claimed the lead in Pro Stock with a 6.908 pass at
201.07 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ''The conditions were good for us,'' Johnson said. ''It's dry
out there, which produces a lot of speed in a Pro Stock car. The
cars have a tendency to go left at this track. We thought we'd
compensate for that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 0145EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7307 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-CAR-NHRA-WOMEN-LADN     11-12 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-WOMEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN MAKE IMPACT IN NHRA COMPETITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Hot Rod Association prides itself on being the
world's fastest motorsport.
</P>
<P>
   But the Glendora-based organization can also take pride in that
it is the only motorsport where women have seemingly equal access
as drivers or mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   Long before Janet Guthrie and Lyn St. James got their first
chance to take hot laps around Indianapolis Motor Speedway in Indy
Cars, Shirley Muldowney was winning national Top Fuel titles.
</P>
<P>
   In 25 years of national event drag racing, six women have 32
victories in professional events. In the same time, not a single
woman has driven in one NASCAR race and Guthrie and St. James have
been the only women to race in a major open wheel division race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a family sport and I think there is an
acceptance of male competitors to female drivers,'' outgoing NHRA
president Dallas Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the status of women in the sport today is not as rosy
as it was last year, when Covina's Shelly Anderson, San Dimas'
Rhonda Hartman, Cristen Powell and Angelle Seeling were racing in
professional categories. Heading into this weekend's 35th annual
Automobile Club of Southern California NHRA Finals at Pomona
Raceway, only Seeling was racing; the other three were unable to
find sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, it's not surprising that the women of Top Fuel
have had trouble finding sponsors in a sport that is self-professed
macho and inspires more testosterone than any other motorsport.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to put your foot on the gas and go,'' said
Connie Kalitta, who helped Muldowney win 18 national events and Top
Fuel titles in 1977, '80 and '82. He scoffs when asked to talk
about Muldowney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all the women drivers know that we're all in the same
boat and that we all have to face the same things,'' said Powell,
who has landed a Funny Car ride for next season. ``We're not alone
in that.''
</P>
<P>
   So why have women found success?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think their reaction time might be a little better,''
Gardner said. ``I don't think there is any more pure thrill in
other motorsports than to go 100 mph in less than a second. That's
a rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction times can make or break a race that covers 440 yards in
less than 8 seconds. Step on the gas too soon and you've
red-lighted _ you're eliminated. Step on it a fraction of a second
too late and your competitor is already 100 feet in front of you.
</P>
<P>
   Step on the gas too soon in another motorsport? They line the
cars up and restart the race. Get off too slowly? There's plenty of
time and opportunities to make up ground.
</P>
<P>
   The first victory by a woman at a national event was not in the
professional division, but by Shirley Shahan in 1966, driving a
1965 Plymouth 101.23 mph to win the stock title at the
Winternationals at Pomona. Muldowney was the first woman to win a
pro event title, winning in Columbus, Ohio in 1977. Lucille Lee
('82 in Atlanta), Lori Johns (two titles), Anderson (four titles),
Powell ('77 in Morristown, N.J.) and current pro motorcycle points
leader Angelle Seeling (10 victories) are the lone female victors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not take a NASA scientist to race these cars,'' says
Muldowney, who admits to being outspoken at times. ``In NASCAR, it
takes strength and endurance. It takes a lot of strength to do what
those guys are doing. I'm not sure ladies can do what they're
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Drivers were not happy to see Muldowney join the circuit in
1963.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not have any friends,'' she recalls. ``The key was to be
a smart lady and handle going fast. I kicked their butts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, a lot of guys had a tough time swallowing what she
was doing,'' said four-time Funny Car champion and current car
owner Don Prudhomme. ``When (the NHRA) started, it was like, `Oh,
(jeez), fire and shake.' Cars would catch on fire or flip. They
were always crashing. You had to be on top of the game. The bottom
line to it all was that women were thought not to be tough enough
for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Shirley got enough credit for what she did.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, says Ercie Hill, wife of Top Fuel driver Eddie
Hill, is that it takes women longer to be accepted into the NHRA
fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would ignore me until they saw that I knew what I was
doing,'' Ercie says of her first year in drag racing.
</P>
<P>
   To Shelly Anderson, going racing was just an extension of the
family. Her father, Brad, won three Top Alcohol Funny Car national
titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted to do this,'' said Brad Anderson, who was national
champion in 1983, '84 and '89. ``She was kind of a tomboy, anyways.
But it was a matter of affording to do (this). She went out and
found the sponsors and put the deals together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the only way I could do this,'' Shelly said of finding
her first sponsor, Jolly Rancher.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said she has never encountered any resistance, perhaps
because she has worked on her own cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around this all my life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Powell has been trying to make a switch from Top Fuel to Funny
Car.
</P>
<P>
   ``As NHRA goes, no woman has ever won a national event in Funny
Car,'' she said. ``That was a big turn-on for me. I kept hearing
people say that women can't drive Funny Cars. Not only did that
make me angry, but it's an open door for me. I proved I could drive
dragsters and now I think I've proved I can drive a Funny Car.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeling leads defending champion Matt Himes of Whittier by 14
points as she aims to become the first female national winner since
Muldowney.
</P>
<P>
   Muldowney says it takes something special to win a national
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, it just clicks,'' she said. ``I know. If you do it
right, everybody's happy and winning. You can't win a title if it's
handed down to you and there is not one lady that I know of that
can talk (Top Fuel) championship.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of ladies need more experience because you can't win
without running on a consistent basis,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 0148EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
