</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-DUES-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright has volunteered to be the lightning rod for criticism from
abortion rights groups if President Clinton compromises with
Congress on a deal to free nearly $1 billion the United States owes
the United Nations, senior administration officials said on
Thursday. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-PARDONS (Washington) _ The new president of Indonesia
said here Thursday night that he had decided to pardon the nation's
former leader, President Suharto, if Suharto is convicted of crimes
as a result of an investigation into whether he and his family
stole billions of dollars from the government. Exclusive. By Philip
Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-ECON (Jena, Germany) _ There is much economic despair in
the former East Germany, but something else has happened: Parts of
the east have become magnets for entrepreneurs and high-technology
start-up companies. In Jena, a small city that is unreachable by
train or plane, the renaissance is striking. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: A graphic and a map have been sent to NYT graphics
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BIOTECH-CAMPAIGN (Chicago) _ Worried about growing
resistance to genetically modified foods, some of the world's
biggest biotechnology companies have decided to launch a huge
public campaign to counter their critics and combat what they fear
is a rising tide of anti-biotech ``hysteria.'' By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS (Washington) _ A plan to improve the
fairness of allocating organs to those needing transplants has been
agreed to following the end of a one-year congressional moratorium.
By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-BASKETBALL (Washington) _ For one of the most
recognizable sports stars of his generation, basketball was a
subject of great ambivalence to Bill Bradley. When he left the game
to enter politics he paid it no further attention. Now, in his
presidential race, basketball is the very first way many people
connect with him. ``It's his base and it's a huge asset,'' said his
friend Carl Wagner. ``They know him from the game, and in the game
he was highly respected.'' By Melinda Henneberger and Jane Gross.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEECEE-CITY-HALL _ The once seedy D.C. City Hall, which was
splendidly refurbished by the federal government and was about to
be taken over by the EPA, has been spared at the last minute. The
step is a symbol of the city's success at gaining self-respect in
its foundling relationship with the Feds. The city had handed over
the century-old building and its prime site at 13th and
Pennsylvania Ave. next to the Reagan Building, in hard times, five
years ago. But with economic turnaround, the city pleaded not to
surrender such a piece of heritage. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-PFIZER (Undated) _ Hostile takeover offers have surged
this year. An unprecedented 100 unsolicited bids valued at $364
billion have already been made worldwide. And the largest hostile
bid ever was made last week when pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc.
bid for Warner-Lambert. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   (The story is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   FED-WAGES (Washington) _ The nation's low and still declining
unemployment rate _ the lowest in almost 30 years _ has been great
news for workers in most industries all over the country. But the
shrinking pool of available labor, and the possibility that upward
pressure on wages could spur inflation, seems to be much on the
minds of Federal Reserve officials as they debate whether to raise
interest rates a third time this year.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo and graphic have been sent to NYT photo/graphics
clients.)
