<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS FIND NEW HEROES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Kings don't have Luc Robitaille or Jozef
Stumpel on the first line with Ziggy Palffy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, joining Palffy for the second straight game were
Vladimir Tsyplakov, who had no goals, and Len Barrie, recalled from
Long Beach on Monday and scoreless in an NHL game since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, that was enough to beat Colorado and goalie Patrick
Roy. In ending a three-game winless streak, the Kings used a goal
from Palffy during a two-goal-in-52-second run, two from Tsyplakov
and another from Barrie during a 5-2 win over Colorado in front of
14,323 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (10-4-2) also won without goalie Stephane Fiset,
listed as day-to-day after suffering a contusion on his right hand
from being struck by a puck during Tuesday's pregame warmup. His
replacement, Jamie Storr, stopped 25 shots Thursday in improving to
3-0-1 this season.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's lackluster 1-1 draw with Edmonton, the Kings
felt good about their offensive production from their first line,
as Palffy assisted twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Ziggy Palffy, you'd better get your stick on the ice
because you're going to get some pucks,'' Kings coach Andy Murray
said. ``I would say it's expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Tsyplakov hadn't scored since April. He finished the scoring
with 2:52 to play, awarded the goal after Roy intentionally lifted
the net forward.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie hadn't been in the NHL in four years but put in 107 goals
in the minors since his last NHL goal. When the Kings brought him
up from Long Beach, he was leading the International League with 10
goals and 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why (Kings general manager) Dave Taylor signed me: I'm
depth for the organization,'' Barrie said, ``and I know I can score
in this league because I can score everywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings even scored once on the power play, which hasn't
happened very often. In fact, Los Angeles is two for its last 16
chances.
</P>
<P>
   But the penalty-killing unit remains effective, having stopped
12 of 16.
</P>
<P>
   Storr gave up goals to Chris Dingman on the power play and Jon
Klemm.
</P>
<P>
   Marko Tuomainen also scored for the Kings, giving him four goals
in the last seven games. Colorado goalie Patrick Roy stopped 18
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a better effort and a better defensive performance
from everyone to win on the road,'' Colorado coach Bob Hartley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado was already missing Peter Forsberg after offseason
shoulder surgery and scratched center Joe Sakic before the game
because of a stiff back he suffered during Monday's practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 0216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
