<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY ADVANCES TO MLS FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ Rarely seen Galaxy president Tim Leiweke visited the
Galaxy locker room before Thursday night's decisive Game 3 match
with Dallas. He said he saw a bunch of focused faces, admitting his
presence may have spoiled the mood.
</P>
<P>
   It was partly because of preparation problems that Leiweke fired
coach Octavio Zambrano in March, replacing him with longtime UCLA
coach Sigi Schmid.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Leiweke's paying Schmid, he certainly got his money's
worth.
</P>
<P>
   In a near flawless performance from start to finish, the
emotionally charged Galaxy delivered two quick punches, then kept
the Burn on its heels, not allowing the pesky group from Dallas to
ever find a rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   Once Galaxy playmaker Mauricio Cienfuegos delivered the biggest
blow in the 68th minute, L.A. knew it was on its way to the Nov. 21
MLS Cup championship game in Foxboro, Mass., eliminating the Burn
3-1 to win the Western Conference championship in front of 25,703
at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Hermosillo and Greg Vanney scored in the first 20 minutes
and Cienfuegos added the finisher to give the Galaxy its second
Western Conference title in four years _ returning L.A. to the site
where it suffered the toughest loss in franchise history, a 3-2
defeat to D.C. United in the inaugural 1996 MLS championship.
</P>
<P>
   Now all L.A. has to do is await the winner of Saturday's
decisive match between Columbus and D.C. United to learn who stands
in the way of the elusive MLS Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully this takes the monkey off of our back because
everyone keeps telling us we lose in big games,'' said Vanney.
``You could see how much this meant to everyone. We have been close
all season, but this was the closest we have ever been tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the crowd was electric. It just seemed like everything was
in our favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid, who won three NCAA titles with the Bruins, talked about
the Galaxy's preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of made a joke and said `If you're really ready for
business, you'll come dressed for business,''' said Schmid. ``And
when they showed up, a lot of guys walked in with jackets and ties.
It's little things like that that sometimes trigger reaction and
gets you going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew this team would roll up their sleeves when they
had to and they were certainly rolled all the way up tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Up 2-0 at halftime, Schmid made sure his players wouldn't allow
Dallas to climb back the way it had in recent playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We promised ourselves we would not let them back this time,''
Schmid said. ``We knew we had to match their effort because Dallas
has shown an ability to keep fighting. They were around the goal,
but we never gave them anything goal-dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   The best work may have come from veteran Paul Caligiuri. The
35-year-old hounded Dallas striker Ariel Graziani, who had scored
three goals in the series entering Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani never got off a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took it personally because I got tired of reading and
hearing about Graziani,'' said Caligiuri. ``He scored three great
goals against us and I didn't want that to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   After a few showers of champagne, it didn't take long for the
players to start talking about '96 and a possible rematch with
United.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would take either of them (D.C. or Columbus), but D.C.
would be a good matchup because of what happened before,'' said
Vanney. ``But we're not going to complain if Columbus shows up
because we think it's about how we play and not who's on the other
side.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy didn't waste any time testing Dallas' thin backline _
playing without starters Eric Dade and Brandon Pollard.
</P>
<P>
   Vanney sent a cross in the second minute for Ezra Hendrickson.
Dallas' Paul Broome was in position to head it away, but the rarely
used defender misjudged the ball, letting it roll off his sleeve
and set up a Galaxy penalty kick. Vanney finished from there,
beating goalkeeper Mark Dodd for his second goal of the playoffs
and 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo, who scored two goals on his wife's birthday last
week, scored on his 11-year-old son's birthday this time, giving
the Galaxy a 2-0 lead in the 20th minute.
</P>
<P>
   The play started on Roy Myers' run down the left side. He
crossed in front for Clint Mathis. Dodd came out to challenge, but
his errant clear rolled in front of Hermosillo, who finished into
an open net.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
