<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 03:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7339 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-SFCHRON &LR;      11-12 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, MCCAIN IN DEAD HEAT FOR PRIMARY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI and PAMELA J. PODGER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Tearing away at Texas Governor &LR; . George W. Bush's aura of
invincibility, Arizona Sen. John McCain has pulled into a dead heat
with the GOP front-runner in New Hampshire, turning the 2000
Republican presidential nomination into a genuine contest for the
first time.
<P>
   A poll of voters in the key primary state showed that Bush's
favorability rating has dropped a full 15 percentage points since
last month. Thirty-eight percent favor Bush and 35 percent favor
McCain _ a statistical tie _ in the American Research Poll released
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's latest gains came after Bush did not appear at two
televised New Hampshire debates, prompting criticism that he was
taking the state for granted.
</P>
<P>
   And last week, the front-runner flubbed a televised quiz on
foreign policy, failing to name the leaders of four global trouble
spots. That has made Bush the butt of late-night television jokes
and raised questions about his command of important issues.
</P>
<P>
   The slip comes as Bush is slated to travel to California next
week to deliver what has been billed a ``major foreign policy
address'' at the Ronald Reagan Library in Simi Valley _ a stop
scheduled long before his current troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McClellan, spokesman for Bush, played down the results of
the latest poll, which surveyed 600 GOP voters in New Hampshire.
``Governor Bush has always said this primary would be
competitive,'' McClellan said. ``He will continue working hard to
earn the support of voters in New Hampshire, and across America.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Bush added New Hampshire trips to his calendar,
moved up his debate schedule and promised to smother voters with
personal attention, according to the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   But with 10 weeks to go before the first votes are cast in the
race _ in Iowa on January 24 _ the poll and the TV fiasco have
fueled speculation that Bush, who rocketed to the GOP front-runner
slot, faces some erosion of support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush has been arguing for several months that he's
the strongest candidate in the field. Now, in the first primary
states, it's no longer the case,'' Dan Schnur, McCain's California
communications director, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in California, which holds its primary March 7,
``we don't expect to see significant poll movement until after the
New Hampshire primary. But the candidate who wins New Hampshire is
going to attract a huge amount of media and public attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign argues that the front-runner's position is
secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush knows this campaign is about ideas, and he's
continuing to lay out his ideas, from improving schools to
strengthening the military,'' said Bush spokesman Scott McClellan.
``America wants someone with a proven ability to lead and clear
ideas where to take America.''
</P>
<P>
   But in California, the nation's most populous state _ where Bush
is still far ahead of his opponents not only in the polls but also
in campaign donations and endorsements _ some Republicans now say
they're taking a second look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was an early supporter of George W. Bush, and I am now
losing some confidence,'' said Jerry Patrick, a Republican who runs
a high-tech marketing firm in San Francisco and showed up to hear
challenger Steve Forbes this week in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I detect a weakening in Bush, in that he has peaked too soon.
I think he is a shallow enough person that there is not much left.
I think he doesn't have the equipment to forge ahead in the next
four to five months.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Corey Moore, a marketing research executive in San Jose,
``Bush sort of reminds me of a tin man. I think he comes across as
a snake-oil salesman and a little weaselly.'' Moore said he prefers
McCain to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Such tough words about Bush were hardly spoken here just a few
months ago. They suggest that the candidate's armor has been
pierced after Bush took heat over his handling of drug questions,
shunning of debates and his performance on the foreign policy quiz.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: Late-night television hosts David Letterman and
Jay Leno have opened their shows with biting monologues on Bush's
gray matter _ or lack of it. That, political insiders say, is every
campaign's nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Fear of Jokes
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to have a bad story about your candidate in the
newspaper, but when Leno and Letterman start telling nightly jokes,
you've got a much bigger problems &LR; ,'' said a leading GOP
strategist.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people get their information from the late-night shows
than even those voters who read the newspapers faithfully. Leno and
Letterman give them an indication of what to think about a subject.
(Dan) Quayle is the best example of that.''
</P>
<P>
   University of California at Berkeley anthropology professor Alan
Dundes, a renowed expert on humor, agreed that the jibes from
well-known personalities, more than pundits, ``have a lot of impact
... a devastating effect. (Politicians) can't get their spin
doctors to undo all this. ... It's communicated over the water
cooler and the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans like knocking the front-runner,'' Dundes added. ``We
love to root for the underdog. We like upsets, even in football.
It's part of the American joy in deflating pomposity. We don't like
people who put on airs. There's a little bit of this `cut 'em down
to size' thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Quiz Called Important
</P>
<P>
   Pollster Mark Baldassare said Bush's handling of the foreign
policy questions is troubling to voters because it underscores
deeper doubts about the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason that these foreign policy tests are important for
(Bush) is that ... his most formidable challenger _ John McCain _
is in the Senate and knows quite a bit about it,'' he said.
``Ultimately, the question is: How prepared is he to be president
of the United States?''
</P>
<P>
   Baldassare predicts that Bush's foreign policy speech in Simi
Valley will be closely watched and could determine how he is
covered in crucial future months in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations will be fairly high (to show) he's knowledgeable
and not reading off cue cards. He will have to show he has this
deep knowledge, not just gained personally from his circle of
advisers,'' Baldassare said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's going to convince people one time out. A
series of tests are coming, as there should be.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle wire services contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
