<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STINKING BREATH, BADGES, BAGGAGE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ Deep thoughts, cheap shots and bon mots ...
<P>
   THOSE CIGARETTE executives who swear under oath that tobacco is
good for you, I wonder what they tell their kids.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Young lady, you will not be excused from the table until you &LR; 
 &UR; finish your after-dinner cigar. Children in China are having &LR; 
 &UR; nicotine fits. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I'M TIRED of hearing people use the phrase, ``We don't need no
stinking badges.''
</P>
<P>
   In the movie ``Treasure of the Sierra Madre,'' here's the
dialogue between the Mexican bandito and Humphrey Bogart's
character:
</P>
<P>
   ``Oiga (listen), senor, we are Federales. You know, the mounted
police.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are police, where are your badges?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Badges? We ain't got no badges. We don't need no badges. I
don't have to show you any stinking badges.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheesh. Get it right.
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING OF stinking, chef Paul Bertolli and owner Bob Klein of
Oliveto in Oakland recently returned from their annual white
truffle hunt in Italy (truffle dinners through Saturday at
Oliveto).
</P>
<P>
   They bagged their limit, sacked up 10 kilos (22 pounds) of the
pungent fungus and hand-carried 'em home on their Alitalia flight.
Several days later, the captain of that flight told Paul and Bob
that the ground crew was still trying to get the truffle smell out
of the first-class cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Funny. It's an Italian crew. You'd think they'd find a way to
say arrivederci aroma.
</P>
<P>
   SURELY THERE IS a simple explanation, but I worry about
hyphenated last names. Specifically, what happens with succeeding
generations? For instance, what will be the surname of kids born to
Glenda Gluteus-Maximus and Fernando Lasorda-Cerveza?
</P>
<P>
   THE UNION SQUARE Garage has a generic ATM that sucks a $1.50
surcharge out of your account with each withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Since it's a city garage, Rich Herrera wonders if the city will
demand that its own ATM stop charging a surcharge. Could get ugly.
</P>
<P>
   MENU OPTIONS. They keep changing. Everywhere you call, it's:
``Please listen carefully, we have changed our menu options.''
</P>
<P>
   I say it's a trick to get you to pay attention instead of just
punching random buttons and causing some actual human being to put
down his or her Mad magazine and actually answer a damn phone.
</P>
<P>
   I'LL PAY the buck-fifty surcharge for using the wrong ATM, if my
bank will credit me a buck-fifty every time they put me on hold and
make me listen to music that's not my preferred genre.
</P>
<P>
   THE CAR INDUSTRY is suffering a shortage of new model names, I
hear. Jim Blake and daughter Jenny suggest naming cars after foods
or diseases. Chevy Casserole. Ford Fondue. Pontiac Paranoia. Dodge
Dyslexia. And Eric Eichorn suggests Ferrari Testosterossa.
</P>
<P>
   Or what about: Dodge Dubious, Ford Flatulent, Plymouth Pequod,
Subaru Superfluous, Ford Folderol, Honda Dogmatic, Cadillac
Skedaddle.
</P>
<P>
   LOTTA DOTZ was in Costa Rica, inserted ATM card in ATM, screen
flashed message: ``Insufficient funds _ Us, not you.''
</P>
<P>
   ENOUGH ALREADY on the cigarette taxing. We can only milk that
cow so many times before the well runs dry, to coin a phrase. If I
was a smoker, one more tax and I'd start growing my own.
</P>
<P>
   TO BE CHISELED on my tombstone: ``Can I please get a
periscope?''
</P>
<P>
   ENOUGH, ALREADY of the trend to bemoan the death of letter
writing in this age of e-mail. If you write a letter and you're not
famous, nobody gives a whit about it.
</P>
<P>
   If you are famous, they save your letters and publish 'em in a
book to embarrass the hell out of you. Who needs it?
</P>
<P>
   THIS CAST? Surfing injury. Yep, sprained my elbow reaching for
the clicker I dropped between the couch cushions.
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLE ARE very strange. Janet Shahan noticed that page 69 of
the new S.F. phone book's business pages covers listings from
DEMENTED to DEVILBOY, and has listings for ``Departures _ From the
Past,'' ``Depression Resource Center,'' ``Detox &AMP; Rehab Help Line''
and ``Democratic Party of San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   I VOTE for voices, especially in the big offices, like
president. Eight years of Clinton's pseudo-sincere twangy whine was
about seven years too many. Gore? Sounds like the preacher in ``The
Simpsons.'' I'm writing in James Earl Jones.
</P>
<P>
   SEND NOW for your copy of my new ``Breakfast Boy's Toast Cook
Book.''
</P>
<P>
   Recipes include Toast Flambe (a touch of lighter fluid), Toast
Tartare (toaster unplugged), Cajun Style Toast (crank that darkness
dial full right), Toast 'n' Turf (toast sprinkled with A-1 Steak
Sauce), Toast L'Orange Under Glass (toast doubling as coaster for
glass of orange juice), Toastquito (toast wrapped 'round a
mysterious beef substance).
</P>
<P>
   NOBODY names boys Sherlock anymore. Maybe they're afraid of what
people would say to their son when he stated an obvious fact.
</P>
<P>
   I DON'T lift weights, diet and do Jazzer-tae-bo to attract women
or impress people or feel good. I do it because I'm afraid that if
I die fat and sloppy, I won't get my security deposit back when I
turn in my body.
</P>
