<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7369 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-BUDGE     11-12 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Nov. 12, 1999  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   As a U.S. bankruptcy judge nears final decision on whether to
allow Dow Corning Corp. to close the books on thousands of breast
implant-related lawsuits, the Hearst News Service and the Midland
Daily News examine the controversy that put the company out of the
implant business and forced it to seek bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Dow Corning _ once the world's largest producer of
silicone gel breast implants _ filed for bankruptcy protection in
1995, the company had paid out $500 million in verdicts,
settlements and legal costs. The company was facing nearly 19,000
new lawsuits alleging that silicone breast implants caused serious
diseases such as lupus and scleroderma.
</P>
<P>
   Since then more than 20 scientific studies have shown no link
between silicone implants and serious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Against this background, many of the 40,000 residents of
Midland, Mich., wonder why Dow Corning's implant business came to
such a cataclysmic ending.
</P>
<P>
   The following package of stories and photos is designed to
answer that question and to explore the relationships between the
legal system, federal regulators, Dow Corning and the scientific
community. Photos are available on the Wieck database.
</P>
<P>
   The full package is for release Sunday, Nov. 21. Editors wishing
a two-day display might consider this lineup:
</P>
<P>
   DAY 1: BREAST-IMPLANTS-RDP, BREAST-IMPLANTS-LESSONS,
BREAST-IMPLANTS-FDA.
</P>
<P>
   DAY 2: BREAST-IMPLANTS-STUDY, BREAST-IMPLANTS-KESSLER,
BREAST-IMPLANTS-LAWYER.
</P>
<P>
   For questions about stories, please call Jack Telfer, editor of
the Midland Daily News, at 517-835-7171 or Chuck Lewis at the
Washington bureau of Hearst Newspapers, 202-298-6920. For questions
about photos, please call Rodney Curtis at the Midland Daily News,
517-835-7171.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-IMPLANTS-RDP (Midland, Mich.) _ With scientific research
showing no link between silicone breast implants and disease, the
residents of Midland express wonder and anger over how Dow Corning
Corp., a company they see as responsible and supportive, could be
put through a blizzard of lawsuits and public criticism. We assess
the economic and emotional impact of the implant crisis on the
community where they were produced. By DAN FREEDMAN, JENNIFER
CORBETT DOOREN and CHERYL WADE.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-IMPLANTS-FDA (Washington) _ Silicone breast implants _
virtually banned in the United States since 1992 _ may be back on
the market in the next several years if the federal Food and Drug
Administration finds that the devices are ``safe and effective,''
the agency's standard for allowing them to be marketed. Two
California manufacturers are working to get FDA approval. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-IMPLANTS-STUDY (Washington) _ A long-awaited government
study of silicone breast implant safety has stirred sharp criticism
from scientists, plastic surgeons and implant makers, even though
the results of the study aren't yet known. The study by the federal
government's premier cancer research center, the National Cancer
Institute, is being attacked for alleged bias. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-IMPLANTS-LESSONS (Midland, Mich.) _ How do Dow Corning
Corp. executives assess their performance during the implant
crisis? Company managers say that, with the benefit of hindsight,
they would have done some things differently in two categories, the
public relations aspect that exploded when the controversy first
exploded in late 1990 and early 1991, and Dow Corning's errors in
the development and marketing of implants from the 1960s through
the 1980s. DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-IMPLANTS-KESSLER (Washington) _ Dr. David Kessler, the
former Food and Drug Administration commissioner, defends his 1992
decision to ban silicone breast implants, saying it was justified
by the state of scientific knowledge at the time. ``What we know
today is that there is no significant risk of these devices causing
systemic disease,'' he said. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-IMPLANTS-LAWYER (San Francisco) _ Dan Bolton, the first
attorney to successfully sue Dow Corning Corp. over allegations
that silicone breast implants cause autoimmune disease, now says he
won't argue with the scientific evidence refuting those claims. The
nearly two dozen scientific studies released since his 1991
landmark case ``are hard to explain away,'' Bolton conceded in an
interview. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   With chronologies:
</P>
<P>
   LEGAL-CHRON, SCIENCE-CHRON, FDA-CHRON.
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 1009EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
