<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7373 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-RDP-2     11-12 1422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-RDP-2TAKES-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDLAND IS ANGRY, PERPLEXED ABOUT BREAST IMPLANT CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN, JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN and CHERYL WADE  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDLAND, Mich. _ When the breakfast regulars at Shirlene's
Cuisine restaurant talk about the breast implant controversy, the
discussion ranges from outright anger to head-scratching
bewilderment.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Corning Corp., headquartered nearby, made this placid city
ground zero in the war over allegations that implants cause
disease. The company was the world's leading manufacturer of
silicone gel implants. And the safety of breast implants was topic
No. 1 at Shirleen's in the early 1990s when the war over implants
raged.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with scientific research finding no link between implants
and disease, the Shirlene's crowd wonders why Dow Corning was
forced to pay hundreds of millions of dollars to women who filed
lawsuits, and why it had to seek federal bankruptcy protection and
get out of the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing was a tragedy,'' said Wayne Crosby, a real
estate broker and regular among the small-business owners and
executives who gather at Shirlene's. ``(American) society jumped on
us here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Miller, an insurance executive and another Shirlene's
breakfast regular, expressed puzzlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand how we got from there to here without
anyone proving anything,'' Miller said. ``There was never ever
substantial proof that (implants) were causing ill effects.''
</P>
<P>
   At its heart, the implant crisis is a tale of what happens when
science, industry and the law keep separate timetables and fail to
connect. And one of its legacies is a small American city of 40,000
trying to figure out what hit it.
</P>
<P>
   For Crosby, Miller and many others here, Midland and Dow Corning
were the victims of waves of negative publicity, money-hungry
plaintiffs' lawyers and a legal system that ran amok before the
scientific research on implants was in.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a flood of lawsuits from women claiming Dow Corning
implants had threatened their health, the company sought bankruptcy
protection in 1995. By then, Dow Corning already had paid out over
$500 million in implant-related lawsuit judgments, settlements and
legal costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Chapter 11 filing was a strategic calculation by the company
to hold back the lawsuit tide until science had time to judge
whether implants cause disease.
</P>
<P>
   The implant controversy unfolded at a time when feminism and
skepticism about large corporations were in full bloom. In 1991,
law professor Anita Hill's explosives charges of misconduct by
Supreme Court nominee Clarence Thomas put sexual harassment on the
map. That same year, author Susan Faludi published ``Backlash: The
Undeclared War Against American Women.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, health-related controversies such as the one involving
the Dalkon Shield birth control device had put many women on guard
about safety claims of medical device manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Through the news media, the nation saw a deep-pockets
corporation accused of developing and marketing an untested, unsafe
product to thousands of women seeking to improve their looks or
complete their recovery from breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But people in Midland saw a trusted friend and neighbor on the
ropes, as well as a way of life possibly going down the drain.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the company's 2,700 employees initially feared for their
jobs. For everyone else, the implications also were worrying. Dow
Corning, together with its larger and better-known parent, The Dow
Chemical Co., pays 27 percent of Midland's tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Dow-related foundations have pumped $28.8 million into town
improvements since the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This town isn't held up by a lot,'' said Miller. ``It's
basically a one-horse town.''
</P>
<P>
   As things turned out, the horse rolled over once or twice and
now is getting back up on its feet.
</P>
<P>
   Implants were never more than 1 percent of Dow Corning's sales,
so shutting down the implant assembly line at the company's plant
in nearby Hemlock was no great headache. The company continued to
make other silicone-based products for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Corning now is a $2.5 billion business. It has submitted a
$4.5 billion plan which would allow the company to emerge from
bankruptcy. The plan is under review by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge
Arthur J. Spector in Bay City, Mich., who is expected to rule
within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the plan, $3.2 billion would be used mostly to settle
lawsuits. Dow Corning made a calculation that settling is less
expensive than fighting each one in court, where the cost per trial
runs as high as $1 million ``even if we win,'' according to Barie
Carmichael, the company's chief communications officer.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining $1.3 billion could be used to pay commercial
creditors.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the bankruptcy filing, the scientific world had
not answered the central question of whether silicone breast
implants caused diseases of the body's immune system such as lupus,
scleroderma or rheumatoid arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with increasing unanimity, scientific researchers are
saying the answer is ``No.'' The final word is not in, but more
than 20 medical studies in the past five years have shown that
women with implants do not suffer higher rates of those diseases
than women without implants.
</P>
<P>
   For some scientists, the studies completely undercut the caution
that has guided federal policy on implants.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all practical purposes, (implants) are safe,'' said Dr.
Marcia Angell, editor of the New England Journal of Medicine and
author of the 1997 book ``Science on Trial,'' which questioned the
legal world's rush to judgment on implants before science had
spoken.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that seven years had elapsed since then Food &AMP; Drug
Administration Commissioner David Kessler imposed a ban on
implants, Angell said ``it's time'' to lift the ban.
</P>
<P>
   John Eesley, a coin laundry operator and another Shirlene's
regular, is puzzled why Dow Corning is being forced to remain in
bankruptcy proceedings if the scientific jury has exonerated the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Dow Corning had been guilty of something, then God knows
they ought to pay,'' said Eesley. ``They weren't and they aren't,
but they're still paying. That makes me mad.''
</P>
<P>
   In their own search for explanations, some Midland residents
zero in on the American legal system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our legal system today is a glorified transfer of wealth, with
the attorneys getting a percentage,'' said Dennis Starner, an
insurance salesman and one of the more vocal Shirlene's
participants. ``It's a cultural phenomenon fueled by greed.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Dow Corning had 137 product liability lawsuits filed
against it. By 1995 _ the year Dow Corning filed for bankruptcy law
protection _ that number had grown to 19,000.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Corning's glass-and-concrete headquarters is set amid
farmland outside town. In the modest third-floor executive suites _
little more than oversized cubicles enclosed by partition walls _
senior managers say they feel vindicated by science.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't quite gotten to the `Whoopee' stage yet,'' said
Richard Hazleton, who earlier this year stepped down as Dow
Corning's CEO after six tumultuous years at the helm. ``There's a
feeling of confidence and sense of reassurance that we weren't way
off base with this thing from the very beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Dow Corning counter that no matter what the recent
studies show, the company originally marketed a product without
knowing whether it was safe and did little to warn women once
doubts were raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is they should have studied the device in
women,'' said Dr. Diana Zuckerman, who as an aide to the late Rep.
Ted Weiss, D-N.Y., was among the first to put questions about
implants in the national spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Corning was formed in the midst of World War II in 1943 by
Dow Chemical and Corning Inc. of Corning, N.Y. Combining Dow's
knowledge of chemistry and Corning's expertise with glass, the new
company developed industrial uses for silicone, which is derived
from quartz and sand.
</P>
<P>
   Silicone combines the temperature and chemical resistance of
glass with the flexibility of plastic. The company's first product
was a grease-like compound used to seal the ignition systems of
U.S. warplanes. Today, silicone is used in adhesives, lubricants,
paints, bathtub caulk, household cleaning supplies, cosmetics and
hair-care products.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Implants began rolling off Dow Corning's assembly line in the
early 1960s, the high-water mark of America's obsession with
breasts as ``sexual ornaments _ the crown jewels of femininity,''
according to author Marilyn Yalom in her 1997 book ``A History of
the Breast.''
</P>
<P>
   The advertising industry and Playboy magazine had succeeded in
turning the breast into a commercialized icon for men. The fashion
world and women's magazines imparted the message to women that
sizable breasts were an integral part of being sexy.
</P>
<P>
   From its inception, Dow Corning was part of the Dow corporate
umbrella that dates back to the 1890s when Herbert Henry Dow came
to Midland to extract bromine and chlorine from underground brine
deposits. ``Crazy Dow,'' as he was known at the time, founded Dow
Chemical Co. in 1897. Chlorine bleach was his leading product.
</P>
<P>
   The company produced mustard gas for the U.S. army in World War
I. Dow survived controversy over its production of napalm, jellied
gasoline dropped by U.S. war planes in Vietnam, and Agent Orange, a
chemical defoliant used in Vietnam to clear thick underbrush.
</P>
<P>
   So controversy over breast implants was ``not an unusual
situation for the people of Midland,'' said Midland city manager
Karl Tomion.
</P>
<P>
   Midland was always willing to overlook accusations against Dow
in part because of the immense generosity to the community of
Dow-connected foundations. They have chipped in to build a dozen or
more public sites, giving Midland big-city facilities in a
small-town environment.
</P>
<P>
   Among them: the 1,538-seat Midland Center for the Arts, the
Grace A. Dow Memorial Library with 277,000 volumes, a
state-of-the-art tennis complex, and Dow Gardens, a 66-acre plot
that hosts 2,000 varieties of trees, shrubs and flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Midland High School's sports-teams are known as the Chemics. In
1968, Midland opened a new high school and named it _ not
surprisingly _ Herbert H. Dow High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always considered ourselves a Camelot,'' said Ashley
Bromley, a Realtor in Midland. ``I love selling Midland to people.
It's a wonderful place to live.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, the closing of a partially constructed nuclear power
plant in Midland threw more than 5,000 people out of work. ``That
was devastating,'' Bromley said, recalling how property values
bottomed out with a flooded real estate market, and unemployed
workers unable to meet payments came by to drop off their house
keys.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast the Dow Corning bankruptcy filing was hardly a blip
on the economic screen. Still, some in Midland likened it to a
family tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like when you have a friend who's accused of
something, your natural instinct is to be protective and
supportive,'' said Tracy Meister, head of the Dow College
Opportunity Program, which helps guide a select group of low-income
students through the maze of high school and prepare them for
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are found guilty, you look at the bigger picture: Is
the offense outweighed by the good the person does in the
community?''
</P>
<P>
   Meister said that prior to the bankruptcy filing, Dow Corning
contributed about $20,000 to the program, spread over five years.
Afterward, Dow Corning ``made it clear to us they wouldn't renew
it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For Dow Corning contractors, the bankruptcy filing and its
aftermath have been an object lesson in hope and persistence.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Beebe, a supplier of commercial gases to Dow Corning and
other customers, wondered how his company could inaugurate its new
$5 million gas production plant located on Dow Corning property.
With two months to go before ribbon cutting, Beebe worried that his
project was dead because of the bankruptcy petition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dow Corning was a very good customer,'' Beebe said. ``There
were not a lot of good alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   When Dow Corning assured him and the entire Midland community
that it intended to stay in business, Beebe decided to tough it
out.
</P>
<P>
   Now, four-and-a-half years after the filing, the gas plant is on
line. Beebe had to sell about $85,000 in unpaid Dow Corning bills
to an investment bank, but his business with the company now is
double what it was prior to the filing.
</P>
<P>
   Beebe's story is typical of Midland _ the economic disaster that
loomed on the horizon never really materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wood, then a 39-year-old heavy equipment operator at the
sprawling Dow Corning plant, worried about losing his job. He faced
what seemed like the insurmountable difficulty of going somewhere
else after 17 years in the plant, virtually his entire adult
working career.
</P>
<P>
   When the fear of job loss faded, Wood confronted the small
things that go with employment at a company in bankruptcy
proceedings: Paychecks stamped with ``debtor in possession,''
cancellation of company awards for downing the largest buck in
hunting season or catching the largest pike, and his son's sudden
disinterest in taking the high school science classes necessary for
work at Dow Corning.
</P>
<P>
   The psychological damage took its toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had caused these problems, you wouldn't have this
resentment,'' said Wood, a member of the bargaining committee of
United Steel Workers of America Local 12934, which represents 646
blue-collar workers at the Dow Corning plant in Midland. ``But the
scientific evidence shows no connection. So what happens to the
people worried about their paycheck and their future, the people
who went through all the stress we went through?''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in Midland is a gung-ho Dow Corning supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Roberts, a breast cancer survivor and self-described
``thorn'' on implants since she had her own ruptured set removed in
1995, said she has paid a high price for her outspokenness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was a woman against the town, against my family,
cousins, uncle who'd worked at Dow Chemical and Dow Corning,'' said
Roberts, 52, an art teacher before extreme pain and cognitive
problems forced her to quit. She blamed her ill health on implants.
</P>
<P>
   When Dow Corning was accused of putting an unsafe, untested
product on the market, some Dow Corning employees scratched their
heads in wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us had been around awhile realized these things had
been tested,'' said Gretchen Kohl, a scientific quality specialist
who was an intern in 1974 at the Dow Corning plant. ``The standards
at that plant were very high.''
</P>
<P>
   Others accepted the company's view that its scientists had
tested implants and knew they were safe. But they were frustrated
that people outside Dow Corning did not.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Gosney, a Dow Corning marketing specialist, recalled how
he mentioned his employer in a conversation with a woman sitting
next to him on a long flight from California.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a friend with implants who was sick so there was no
debate,'' he said. Gosney tried discussing scientific research
suggesting implants were not the cause.
</P>
<P>
   But his seatmate's response was ``don't confuse me with facts,
I've made up my mind,'' he recalled. ``It was a long, cold ride
from then on.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, ``we were as devastated as anybody'' said Dow Corning
senior research scientist Deb Bergstrom. ``Employees began to
wonder if something had gone wrong or if we had done something
inadvertently (wrong).''
</P>
<P>
   When employees learned of the scientific studies that failed to
link implants to disease, ``We were very relieved,'' she said.
``You're talking about a really ethical group of people ... We
would be the last kind of people that would want to be implicated
in that kind of activity.''
</P>
<P>
   But up until that point, employees felt they had been condemned
before all the evidence had been presented.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Midland, there was ``a perception that we were a
nameless, faceless thing with a lot of money,'' said Bergstrom.
``They didn't see us as employees who could get hurt by this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
