</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-STUDY-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT'S NEW SILICONE IMPLANT STUDY COMES UNDER FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A premier federal research center, the National
Cancer Institute, is under attack for its new study of whether
silicone breast implants can trigger serious diseases in women.
</P>
<P>
   Critics claim the study is biased because of the way women have
been recruited to participate. They also say the study's director,
Dr. Louise Brinton, chief of NCI's environmental epidemiology
branch, may have formed her conclusions before the study even
began.
</P>
<P>
   The quarrel is rare because it erupted even before the study
results have been published.
</P>
<P>
   The NCI, renowned for its impartiality and scientific
horsepower, has denied the charge that the long-awaited, $5 million
assessment of silicone implants is biased.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers and advocates for women with silicone implants who
believe their ailments are caused by the devices have been eagerly
looking forward to the study to prove them right.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 previous studies by institutions like the Harvard
Medical School, the Mayo Clinic, the National Academy of Science's
Institute of Medicine and Britain's Ministry of Health found no
evidence that implants cause cancer or autoimmune diseases such as
arthritis and lupus. However, several studies did find that local
complications, such as painfully hardened breasts and implant
ruptures requiring repeat surgery, can occur.
</P>
<P>
   Critics claim these earlier studies that focused on a link to
disease allegedly involved too few women over too short a period of
time or were biased because some were indirectly funded by implant
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   One critic, Dr. Sidney Wolfe, of the Washington, D.C.-based
Public Citizen Health Research Group, asserts that the NCI study
has the best chance of drawing ``accurate'' conclusions because it
is the largest study to date of women with implants. The medical
histories of 13,500 women who received breast implants before 1988
will be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Detractors of the NCI study object to its design and the
recruitment of participants. They claim it is biased to show that
implants pose a threat to a woman's long-term health.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most serious charges is that lawyers for implant
plaintiffs and advocacy groups have aided the NCI in getting women
to take part in its study.
</P>
<P>
   That criticism was made by five scientists writing in The
Lancet, a British medical journal. The scientists _ two from the
United States and one each from Mexico, Germany and Canada _
contended in a May 2, 1998, letter to The Lancet that such
recruitment could introduce ``major biases.'' They reason that more
women claiming they were harmed by implants may respond to the
study than women with implants who did not make such claims.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent salvo lobbed at the NCI came in October from Dr.
Marcia Angell, acting editor-in-chief of the New England Journal of
Medicine, a respected medical publication.
</P>
<P>
   Angell, in an interview with the Hearst Newspapers, said letters
written by NCI officials contain ``a lot of talk about the
cooperative effort with plaintiffs' attorneys in designing the
trial, and I thought that was exactly the wrong place to go to
design a study.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 Angell wrote a book, ``Science on Trial,'' which
examined how juries awarded millions of dollars to women who
believed they were injured by silicone implants _ even though
scientific studies had at that point been unable to prove a link
between implants and disease.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Angell said a letter from Brinton explaining
the study to potential participants raised questions of
impartiality.
</P>
<P>
   The letter says ``the study provides an opportunity for women
who may be suffering as a result of implants to be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Such comments, according to detractors, also appear designed to
attract women who believe their implants caused disease.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the ammunition against the study _ internal letters to
and from NCI officials _ was unearthed through the Freedom of
Information Act by lawyers for former silicone implant
manufacturers. The companies have agreed to a $4.2 billion
settlement with women who believe that implants sparked their
ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Brinton responded to the criticisms by sending a short letter to
The Lancet, denying that the recruitment of subjects for her study
involved plaintiffs' lawyers or advocacy groups. She also said some
of the five scientists' concerns ``reflect their unfamiliarity with
the study as designed ...''
</P>
<P>
   Brinton acknowledged in a separate letter that she met with
about 45 implant plaintiffs' lawyers on two separate occasions in
1995, but said the meetings were proper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked that the lawyers indicate to their clients that this
was an important study, and one in which they should participate,''
Brinton wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The NCI says it has taken several steps to ensure the study's
objectivity. It said the agency is overseeing the study with the
help of two data-collection companies and that academic scientists
not associated with the agency are providing oversight.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that women who report ailments have legitimate medical
problems, the NCI said, its investigators validate the cases
through participants' medical records.
</P>
<P>
   The NCI study uses epidemiology _ statistical methods to assess
incidents of disease _ to reach conclusions. The rate of illness
among the 13,500 women is being compared with the rate in a group
of 4,000 other women of similar age who had plastic surgery other
than a breast implant. If the rate of illness for a particular
ailment in the first group is greater than that in the comparison
group, scientists might conclude that implants are associated with
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Brinton declined to discuss the study until after its findings
are published. The NCI also declined to ask any other NCI scientist
to discuss the controversy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
