<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7379 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-LESSO     11-12 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-LESSONS-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW CORNING OFFICIALS SAY THEY LEARNED FROM THE IMPLANT FLAP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDLAND, Mich. _ By any measure, the controversy over silicone
gel breast implants in the early 1990s was a public relations
nightmare for Dow Corning Corp.
</P>
<P>
   News accounts reported that Dow Corning implants could cause
debilitating autoimmune diseases such as lupus and scleroderma. Dow
Corning, the world's largest manufacturer of silicone implants, was
portrayed as indifferent to the safety of its product. Waves of
lawsuits from implant recipients buffeted the company.
</P>
<P>
   At their headquarters here, Dow Corning executives reacted with
stunned anger. They followed their first instinct: Deny the
accusations and depict the company as a victim of an organized
attack by plaintiffs' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, four years after the company filed for bankruptcy
protection to ward off the lawsuits, Dow Corning executives say
their original stance has been vindicated by new scientific studies
showing no links between implants and autoimmune diseases.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's managers also say that, with the benefit of
hindsight, they would have done some things differently.
</P>
<P>
   The ``lessons learned'' were in two categories: How the company
handled public relations when the controversy first exploded in
late 1990 and early 1991, and Dow Corning's errors in the
development and marketing of implants from the 1960s through the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Barie Carmichael, Dow Corning's chief communications officer,
says company executives were angry and frustrated about the
accusations. When filtered through the media, she said, these
emotions reinforced what she characterized as a false image of a
company that was uncaring and aloof to suffering women.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rylee, the Dow Corning executive designated to deal with
the media, insisted in interviews at the time that the company's
implants were ``safe and effective.'' His assurances often were
contrasted to emotional anecdotal accounts of women who said their
implants had ruined their health.
</P>
<P>
   Rylee also insisted it was up to plastic surgeons to explain the
risks of implants to women patients. ``We don't know who the
patients are,'' he said in interviews at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot, according to Carmichael: ``We looked arrogant.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times on Jan. 29, 1992, compared the company's
handling of the implant controversy to the Exxon Corp.'s response
to the Exxon Valdez oil spill in 1989 off the coast of Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon was castigated for fumbling the cleanup effort,
downplaying the impact of 240,000 pounds of crude oil in Prince
William Sound, and giving the impression its top executives did not
care about the problems it had caused.
</P>
<P>
   The Times quoted Gerald Meyers, an author and crisis management
expert, as calling Dow Corning's handling of the implant
controversy ``a textbook case of crisis mismanagement.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time well before scientific research backed their claims
that the implants were safe, Dow Corning had inadvertently
increased public sympathy for the women plaintiffs. Each quote in
the media seemed to give their lawyers and anti-implant advocates
more ammo.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when asked in 1991 why Dow Corning had not made its
internal implant studies public, Rylee responded: ``We don't want
to be overeducating plaintiffs' lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyers, who is also a visiting business professor at the
University of Michigan, said in an interview with Hearst Newspapers
last month that Dow Corning was overwhelmed by events.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a small-town company that felt the onslaught and
withering fire of the mass-tort lawyers,'' he said. The company was
``decimated by the strength of the firepower they were facing.''
</P>
<P>
   Things improved somewhat with the 1992 appointment of Dow
Chemical veteran Keith McKennon as Dow Corning's new CEO, according
to Meyers.
</P>
<P>
   McKennon was an ``aw-shucks kind of fellow'' who was more open
and visible, and he pushed the company to appear more sympathetic
to women with implants, Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Under McKennon, Dow Corning set up a fund to pay $1,200 to any
woman who wanted her implants taken out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds corny but it's true, you've got to open lines of
communications,'' Meyers said. ``Just because you got sharks
swimming around you doesn't mean you have to get eaten.''
</P>
<P>
   There also were miscues in the development of silicone implants
that no amount of public relations could smooth over.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in the 1960s when Dow Corning first marketed implants,
company scientists conducted over 300 studies of silicone and the
effects of implants on animals. But there was little research done
on the impact of a slow-leaking or ruptured implant on actual
women.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dow Corning still defends its research as valid, ``in
hindsight we could have done a lot more testing,'' said Gary
Anderson, the company's current CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Corning also says it made a mistake in keeping its internal
research away from outside scientists because of fear that
competitors would obtain it and gain commercial advantage, Anderson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had great confidence in the safety of silicone implants,''
Anderson said. ``But the outside world didn't know that.''
</P>
<P>
   When the attacks came, ``we didn't have independent academics or
government folks or medical people who could stand up and defend
us, and say `Wait a minute, you got this all wrong,''' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the controversy, Dow Corning took steps to show its
concern for women fearful their implants caused disease. But these
efforts either were drowned out by overwhelming negative publicity
or they simply backfired.
</P>
<P>
   A company 800-number hotline for women with implants had to be
overhauled after the Food &AMP; Drug Administration complained that Dow
Corning operators were telling women ``there have never been health
problems with implants or silicone.'' News stories described the
flap.
</P>
<P>
   As a company led by engineers and chemists, Dow Corning had a
difficult time seeing the controversy through the eyes of the
public, particularly women with implants, according to Ian Mitroff,
a business professor at the University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard for scientific people to understand anything
outside of science,'' Mitroff said. ``One thing they do is mistake
the boxes in their organizational charts as the way the world
thinks. The world doesn't think that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The implant controversy has led to some changes in Dow Corning's
way of doing business. For one, the company has beefed up its force
of ``product stewards'' responsible for checking safety and
investigating product liability. ``It's now on everyone's radar
screen,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Before he departed as Dow Corning CEO earlier this year, board
chairman Richard Hazleton made it clear to employees that they
should use less colorful language in internal reports and
memoranda.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Corning had been stung by release of its own internal
documents.
</P>
<P>
   In one, a marketing executive reported keeping his fingers
``crossed'' while telling plastic surgeons that testing of silicone
seepage from implants was underway.
</P>
<P>
   In another, a salesman called the quality of implants
``questionable.'' The strategy for marketing them, he added, was
``right up there with the Pinto gas tank,'' a reference to the
1970s scandal involving the ill-designed Ford Pinto automobile's
gas tank that exploded on impact.
</P>
<P>
   Hazleton has let executives and scientists know they must watch
what they write. ``I want people to state opinions forcefully, but
not so it's useful (to opponents),'' Hazleton said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail, at
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
