<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7381 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r w BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-KESSL     11-12 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-KESSLER-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KESSLER DEFENDS HIS BAN OF SILICONE BREAST IMPLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dr. David Kessler, the former Food and Drug
Administration commissioner, defends his 1992 decision to ban
silicone breast implants by saying he was justified, given the
state of scientific knowledge at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agency was left with little recourse,'' said Kessler, now
dean of Yale University's medical school.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA was acting on limited scientific data because the
manufacturers of silicone breast implants hadn't proven the devices
were ``safe and effective,'' the FDA standard for allowing medical
devices or drugs on the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, without that data, I think the decision that
was made was the only decision one could reach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA was being bombarded at the time with complaints from
women who said the implants caused diseases such as arthritis and
lupus. The alleged link to disease was one of the main reasons for
the ban, along with concerns that implants could rupture and cause
other health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler concedes the disease claim now is tenuous, given the
results of more than 20 medical studies from prominent institutions
like the Mayo Clinic, Harvard Medical School and the National
Academy of Science's Institute of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Those studies generally found that while implants can cause
severe localized problems like painfully hardened breasts, there is
no evidence that they cause cancer or autoimmune diseases such as
arthritis and lupus, which occur when the body's immune system
attacks skin and connective tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we know today is that there is no significant risk of
these devices causing systemic disease,'' he said, adding that one
study says there may be a slight increase in risk.
</P>
<P>
   But the as-yet-unknown rate at which silicone implants rupture
was enough justification for the ban, Kessler said in a recent
interview. Studies have shown widely varied rupture rates, with
some models rupturing 5 percent of the time and others more than 51
percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have a hard time saying that something is safe if the
rupture rate is 50 percent. But even 5 percent, if the device kills
you, maybe that's too high,'' Kessler said. ``If the rupture rate
is 5 percent and the only problem is repeat surgery, 5 percent may
be an acceptable risk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not knowing the rupture rate, it's hard to say the product is
safe,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1988, the FDA reclassified breast implants as Class III
medical devices, a step that required manufacturers to demonstrate
that the implants were safe and effective in order to stay on the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler asserts that for too long the FDA had a hands-off policy
toward breast implants and medical devices in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not as scientifically sophisticated as we were for
evaluating drugs,'' he said. ``We weren't as rigorous from a
regulatory perspective. Some would characterize it as the agency
was rubber stamping medical devices.''
</P>
<P>
   While Kessler maintains he was performing a public health duty
by banning the devices, various medical and patient organizations _
including the American Cancer Society, the American Society of
Clinical Oncology, the Society of Surgical Oncology and the
National Alliance of Breast Cancer organizations _ accused him in
1996 of creating ``a climate of fear and confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the FDA's ban, some physicians reported that
patients were terrified that they were walking around with ticking
time bombs embedded in their chests. There were reported incidents
of distraught women attempting to remove their implants themselves
with crude surgical tools.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler conceded that the FDA could have done a better job of
calming fears and communicating to women that the ban wasn't a vote
of ``no confidence'' in silicone implants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said that the manufacturers had not demonstrated the safety
of these devices. That is not the same thing as saying they are
unsafe. There's a world of difference between those two things,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler's action had stark ramifications in the legal world
where the number of women seeking damages from implant
manufacturers dramatically climbed after the ban was publicized.
The crush of litigation led Dow Corning, then the largest of the
implant makers, to declare bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler's actions still sting Dr. Elizabeth Connell, chairman of
two FDA advisory panels on breast implants and a professor emeritus
in obstetrics at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was I happy? No. Was I infuriated? Yes,'' she said about
Kessler's ban. ``We felt that implants were basically safe. We said
to leave them on the market. They pose no health threat and they
serve a public health need.''
</P>
<P>
   Connell said the interplay of Kessler's actions and the
avalanche of lawsuits against implant manufacturers have damaged
the greater cause of women's health issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's now very, very difficult to get a company to invest money
in women's health care these days,'' Connell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen 17 companies in the contraceptive field drop to two.
The damage has been done, and I think it's irreversible,'' she
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
