r a BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-LAWYE Nov.21) &LR; -HNS   11-12 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-LAWYER-$ADV21 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
21)  -HNS  
 &HT;    
 PLAINTIFF'S LAWYER CONCEDES NEW EVIDENCE UNDERMINES HIS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, Nov. (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Dan Bolton, the first attorney to successfully
sue Dow Corning Corp. over allegations that silicone breast
implants cause autoimmune disease, now says he won't argue with the
recent scientific evidence refuting those claims.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly two dozen scientific studies released since his 1991
landmark case ``are hard to explain away,'' Bolton, 43, conceded in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
   His client, Mariann Hopkins, of Sebastopol, Calif., then
48-years old, won a $7.3-million verdict in U.S. District Court
here after she claimed that breast implants caused her autoimmune
disease. The case received widespread publicity and triggered a
flood of lawsuits against Dow Corning and other breast implant
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, there were no published scientific studies either
way on whether implants caused disease. But Bolton was able to
convince a six-person jury that Hopkins' implants, which she
received after a 1977 mastectomy, resulted in her diagnosis two
years later of mixed connective-tissue disease _ an autoimmune
disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Bolton used expert witnesses who testified that it was more
likely than not that Hopkins' implants, which had ruptured and
leaked silicone, caused her illness. He also focused on internal
Dow Corning memos and animal studies that raised questions about
whether silicone implants were safe enough to be placed in the
body.
</P>
<P>
   Those memos showed that Dow Corning's scientists urged the
company to begin a long-term testing program on silicone implants
in the mid-1970s _ a suggestion that wasn't followed up until 1988
when the U.S. Food and Drug Administration requested such
information from all breast implant manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   One expert, Dr. Frank Vasey, the head of rheumatology at the
University of South Florida College of Medicine, testified that it
was possible that Hopkins' implants weren't the primary cause of
her disease but said there was ``certainly no question her clinical
disorder became much worse after the implants.''
</P>
<P>
   He also told jurors that most of his 100 patients who had their
implants removed after being diagnosed with autoimmune diseases and
similar disorders slowly improved over time.
</P>
<P>
   Bolton still criticizes Dow Corning for not giving women more
information about the risks of implants such as the possibility
that painful scar tissue can develop around the implant. And he
points out that internal memos showed Dow Corning was aware as
early as 1975 that some breast implants could rupture and leak but
that women weren't warned of that complication until 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Lappe, now 56, and then a professor of health policy and
ethics at the University of Illinois, also testified for Hopkins,
but he now agrees that implants weren't the primary cause of such
illnesses, despite his previous suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   During Hopkins' trial, Dow Corning attorneys argued that the
company's animal studies showed that implants were safe. Subsequent
independent scientific studies of humans showed no evidence that
the implants were unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   But the lack of those independent tests hurt Dow Corning at the
time. On top of that, Lappe testified that some of Dow Corning's
animal studies showed an immune reaction to silicone. Thus, Lappe
said, it wasn't unreasonable to conclude that silicone breast
implants cause autoimmune disease in humans.
</P>
<P>
   He also told jurors that Dow Corning's tests, including ones
that showed no problems with silicone, were insufficient to prove
the long-term safety of breast implants.
</P>
<P>
   After the Hopkins verdict in December 1991, the Dow Corning
documents were obtained by the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   The following month then-FDA commissioner David Kessler cited
the documents when he ordered a moratorium on the sale of silicone
breast implants. Kessler's decision was based on what he said was
Dow Corning's failure to prove that the implants were ``safe and
effective,'' the standard that the FDA had imposed on the
manufacturers in 1988 and given them 30 months to meet that test.
</P>
<P>
   Partly as a result of the FDA action, the number of lawsuits
against Dow Corning and the other breast implant manufacturers
steadily rose throughout 1992 and 1993. It wasn't until 1994 that
the first independent study, done by the Mayo Clinic, was published
and showed no link between silicone breast implants and disease.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer volume of cases forced Dow Corning to file for
bankruptcy protection in May 1995 _ when the company was facing
nearly 19,000 lawsuits _ even though the scientific evidence was
swinging in the company's favor. The effect was to freeze all of
the pending litigation against the firm.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Arthur J. Spector in Bay City, Mich., is
expected to rule within weeks on whether to accept Dow Corning's
$3.2 billion proposal to settle those lawsuits and emerge from
bankruptcy protection. The company figures that payout is cheaper
than fighting all of the cases in court at a cost of $1 million
each.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at
jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
