<HEADER>
A7383 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-LAW-C     11-12 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-LAW-CHRON-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW CHRONOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers.  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the key events in Dow Corning Corp.'s legal battle over
silicone gel breast implants:
</P>
<P>
   _ November 1984: Maria Stern of San Francisco becomes the first
plaintiff to win a jury verdict against Dow Corning Corp. after
claiming that silicone-breast implants caused her to suffer
autoimmune diseases. Stern wins $211,000 in compensatory damages
and $1.5 million in punitive damages. The case is appealed but then
settled for an undisclosed amount. As part of the settlement
agreement, internal Dow Corning documents used in trial are sealed
by a court order. The case receives little publicity.
</P>
<P>
   _ December 1991: A California jury awards $7.3 million to
Mariann Hopkins of Sebastopol, Calif., who claimed her Dow Corning
breast implants caused an autoimmune disease. The $7.3 million
verdict is the largest ever against a breast implant manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   _ January 1992: FDA Commissioner David Kessler calls for a
moratorium on the sale of silicone breast implants, citing internal
Dow Corning documents used in the Hopkins' trial that raised
questions about the long-term safety of breast implants.
</P>
<P>
   _ June 1992: About 400 lawsuits filed in federal courts against
silicone breast implant manufacturers are transferred to U.S.
District Judge Sam Pointer in Birmingham, Ala., who will oversee
all federal litigation. At this point several hundred lawsuits are
also pending in state courts.
</P>
<P>
   _ December 1992: Pamela Johnson wins $25 million in Texas state
court against breast implant manufacturer Bristol-Myers Squibb Co.
The increasing size of the jury verdicts prompts breast implant
manufacturers to begin negotiations to settle existing lawsuits and
to limit losses from additional lawsuits. At this point about 2,000
lawsuits have been filed in federal court and state courts.
</P>
<P>
   _ September 1993: Dow Corning, Minnesota Mining &AMP; Manufacturing
Co. (3M), Bristol-Myers and Baxter Healthcare Corp. agree to a
$4.25 billion settlement of all silicone breast implant litigation,
which is rapidly approaching 10,000 suits at the federal and state
levels.
</P>
<P>
   _ March 1994: Dow Corning, the nation's largest breast implant
manufacturer, agrees to pay $2 billion of the $4.25 billion
settlement. By now, an estimated 16,000 lawsuits have been filed in
federal and state courts against the breast implant manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   _ May 1995: Dow Corning files for Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection in U.S. District Court in Bay City, Mich. This means all
pending 19,000 cases against firm are frozen and transferred to Bay
City. Dow Corning drops out of the global settlement deal because
the company says it can't afford both to pay the $2 billion and to
defend the hundreds of suits from women who are dropping out of the
settlement plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ September 1995: Judge Pointer declares the $4.25 billion
settlement dead because there isn't enough money to pay for the
overwhelming number of claims, now that Dow Corning has dropped out
of the settlement. About 440,000 women with implants registered for
the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   _ October 1995: A Nevada state jury holds Dow Chemical Co. _ one
of Dow Corning's two parents _ liable for medical problems
allegedly linked to breast implants made by Dow Corning and awards
Charlotte Mahlum of Las Vegas $14.2 million. Mahlum sued Dow
Chemical because she was unable to sue Dow Corning because it filed
for bankruptcy protection in May. Later, the Nevada Supreme Court
upholds the verdict but reduces damages to $4.2 million. Dow
Chemical settles the case for an undisclosed amount.
</P>
<P>
   _ November 1995: 3M, Baxter and Bristol-Meyers agree to a new
settlement plan without Dow Corning.
</P>
<P>
   _ December 1996: After studying a report by a panel of impartial
scientists, U.S. District Judge Robert Jones in Portland, Ore.,
rules that lawyers for women suing implant manufacturers cannot
present evidence asserting that implants cause disease because such
a claim would be false. Jones dismisses 70 claims.
</P>
<P>
   _ November 1998: Dow Corning files a plan with the bankruptcy
court to pay $3.2 billion to about 170,000 women who claim they
were injured by its silicone breast implants.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal _ which is still under review by U.S.
District Court Judge Arthur Spector of Bay City, Mich. _ a person
claiming an illness could receive up to $250,000 in compensation
plus $20,000 if the device ruptured as well as $5,000 to pay for
removal.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who hasn't reported any ill effects but who wants to
settle and waive future disease claims would receive $2,000. Women
can opt out of settlement and sue on their own _ a $400 million
legal trust would be established by Dow Corning. Any separate
lawsuits would have to be filed in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   _ December 1998: A panel of four independent scientists
appointed by Judge Pointer _ who is overseeing federal implant
lawsuits against manufacturers other than Dow Corning _ finds there
is no evidence linking silicone implants with any disease. This has
no effect on the more than 100,000 women who are apart of the
settlement because the manufacturers have already agreed to pay
damages.
</P>
<P>
   _ July 1999: Hearings on the Dow Corning bankruptcy settlement
are held. Judge Spector is expected to rule this year on the
proposed breast implant settlement.
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
