<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7385 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-SCIEN     11-12 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-SCIENCE-CHRON-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE CHRONOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When then-FDA Commissioner David Kessler banned silicone gel
implants in 1992, there was little scientific research on whether
the devices did or did not cause disease.
</P>
<P>
   The few studies that did exist, usually collections of anecdotal
reports of small groups of fewer than 100 women, cut both ways.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the FDA ban went into effect, results of larger
epidemiological studies _ studies that use statistical methods to
assess incidents of disease _ began to show no link between
implants and serious diseases such as cancer, arthritis and lupus.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some key events in the scientific research on silicone
gel breast implants:
</P>
<P>
   _ December 1993: The Journal of the American Medical Association
publishes a review of existing scientific data, showing no increase
of breast cancer among women with silicone breast implants. The
study also finds insufficient evidence to conclude that implants
are the cause of connective tissue disease.
</P>
<P>
   _ June 1994: A study by the Mayo Clinic finds no increased risk
of connective tissue disorders and other diseases in women studied
with breast implants. Published in the New England Journal of
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   _ September 1994: An Australian study of women with implants
finds no link between implants and scleroderma, a connective tissue
disorder. Published in the Australia-New Zealand Journal of
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   _ January 1995. A British government assessment of over 200
medical studies finds no link between breast implants and
connective tissue disease. Published by the Medical Devices Agency
of the British Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
   _ June 1995: The Harvard Nurses Health Study concludes there is
no increased risk of connective tissue disease in women with
silicone implants. Published in the New England Journal of
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   _ October 1995: The American College of Rheumatology issues a
statement saying that the evidence is ``compelling'' that there is
no link between implants and disease.
</P>
<P>
   _ February 1996: A Harvard Medical School study of 400,000
women, including 11,000 with implants, shows no large increase in
the risk of connective tissue disease reported by women with
implants. The study maintains, however, that there may be a small
risk. Published in the Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   _ December 1996: After studying a report by a panel of
independent scientists, U.S. District Judge Robert Jones in
Portland, Ore., rules that lawyers for women suing implant
manufacturers cannot present evidence asserting that implants cause
disease because such a claim would be false. Jones dismisses 70
claims.
</P>
<P>
   _ January 1997: The American Academy of Neurology reviews
existing silicone implant studies and concludes that ``existing
research shows no link between silicone breast implants and
neurological disorders.''
</P>
<P>
   _ September 1997: The Journal of the National Cancer Institute,
in a review of existing medical studies, concludes that implants do
not cause cancer. The article also concludes that evidence linking
implants with any other disease is ``borderline.''
</P>
<P>
   _ April 1998: Two large Scandinavian studies find ``no support
for the conjecture that breast implants cause neurologic disease.''
Published in the Neurology journal.
</P>
<P>
   _ July 1998: A review by the British Ministry of Health of
existing medical literature concludes that ``the incidence of
ill-health in women implanted with silicone gel breast implants is
no greater than in the general population.''
</P>
<P>
   _ December 1998: Four independent scientists appointed by U.S.
District Court Judge Sam Pointer of the Northern District of
Alabama _ who is overseeing federal implant lawsuits against
manufacturers other than Dow Corning _ finds there is no evidence
linking silicone implants with disease. This has no effect on the
more than 100,000 women who are part of the settlement because the
manufacturers have already agreed to pay damages.
</P>
<P>
   _ June 1999: The National Academy of Science's Institute of
Medicine releases a 400-page study prepared by 13 scientists who
conclude that implants do not cause major diseases, although they
can cause serious local complications such as painful hardening of
the breasts. The findings were based on a nearly two-year review of
existing scientific literature.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999: Scientists and breast implant manufacturers eagerly
await the findings of the largest study to date of women with
silicone implants. This study, by the National Cancer Institute, is
under attack by implant makers and some scientists as biased toward
showing a link between implants and disease. The NCI denies any
bias.
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
