<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7387 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-FDA-C     11-12 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-FDA-CHRON-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA CHRONOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1992 ban on silicone gel breast implants by the U.S. Food
and Drug Administration climaxed the gradual expansion of FDA
regulation of the devices. Following are the key events in that
evolution:
</P>
<P>
   _ 1962: Silicone breast implants were first used in
reconstructive surgery following breast surgery. Cosmetic use grows
in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   _ May 1976: Congress gives the U.S. Food and Drug Administration
responsibility for assuring that medical devices are ``safe and
effective.'' But because silicone breast implants had been on the
market for nearly 15 years, the FDA ``grandfathers'' implants,
exempting them from the ``safe and effective'' requirement.
</P>
<P>
   _ July 1976: The FDA's advisory panel on surgical devices
recommends that breast implants be classified as Class II medical
devices. Class I and II cover medical devices with well-established
safety records.
</P>
<P>
   _ January 1982: Prompted in part by anecdotal reports in medical
journals and news stories about illnesses caused by implants, the
FDA proposes that breast implants be reclassified from Class II
medical products to Class III. The new classification would require
manufacturers to demonstrate that the implants are ``safe and
effective'' in order to keep them on the market.
</P>
<P>
   _ November 1984: For the first time, a woman successfully sues
Dow Corning Corp. after claiming that her silicone implants caused
her autoimmune disease. The plaintiff, Maria Stern of San
Francisco, wins a jury verdict of $1.7 million against Dow Corning.
</P>
<P>
   _ June 1988: Six years after proposing the change, the FDA
reclassifies breast implants as Class III medical devices. The FDA
directs the manufacturers to come forward with proof by July 1991
that implants are ``safe and effective.''
</P>
<P>
   _ November 1988: The Public Citizen Health Research Group, which
is associated with Ralph Nader, charges that Dow Corning has
evidence silicone gel implants cause cancer in laboratory animals
and pose a threat to women. The group, basing its charge on
documents from Dow Corning and the FDA, calls for banning the
implants.
</P>
<P>
   _ November 1991: The FDA's plastic surgery advisory panel
examines the scientific data from breast implant manufacturers,
including Dow Corning, and concludes that the information doesn't
prove the devices are either safe or harmful. The panel asks
manufacturers to submit more data. In the interim, the panel
decides that the implants fulfill a public health need and allows
the implants to remain on the market while the companies collect
additional scientific data.
</P>
<P>
   _ February 1992: FDA's plastic surgery panel reviews new
scientific data on implants and concludes that there is no causal
link between implants and autoimmune diseases.
</P>
<P>
   _ April 1992: Facing pressure from patient groups, members of
Congress and newly uncovered Dow Corning documents showing quality
control problems, FDA commissioner David Kessler bans implants
because the manufacturers have not proven them to be ``safe and
effective.'' However, the agency allows implants to continue to be
used for reconstructive surgery if the recipients agree to
participate in medical studies.
</P>
<P>
   _ September 1996: The Y-Me National Breast Cancer Organization
asks the FDA to ease restrictions on availability of silicone
implants.
</P>
<P>
   _ February 1997: A group of women with breast implants who have
serious health problems asks the FDA to ban all implants, including
those used for reconstructive surgery.
</P>
<P>
   _ Present: Two companies _ Mentor Corp. and McGhan Medical
Corp., both of Santa Barbara, Calif. _ are manufacturing silicone
implants for use in the FDA-approved medical studies. The companies
plan to submit their scientific data to the FDA in an effort to
persuade the FDA that the devices are ``safe and effective.''
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 1029EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7412 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CARIBBEAN-ROCKET-$ADV     11-12 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARIBBEAN-ROCKET-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEXAS BANKER IN TOUGH FIGHT TO BUILD SATELLITE LAUNCH PAD ON
TINY ISLAND
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Sombrero island is about 40
miles northwest of Anguila in the Caribbean.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Nov. 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. CROIX, U.S. Virgin Islands _ Plans by a Texas entrepreneur
to assemble huge rockets here and launch commercial satellites from
a nearby island have set off fireworks on this laid-back vacation
paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas banker Andrew Beal's high-flying plans were stuck on the
ground this week in a Virgin Islands territorial court, where
opponents argued against a controversial land swap between Beal and
the Virgin Islands government.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the site Beal wants for his headquarters and
rocket assembly plant is rich in pre-Colombian ruins, and fronts an
environmentally sensitive bay and offshore coral reef.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our environment is critical to our economic future,'' said
attorney Ned Jacobs, who represents 20 islanders opposed to the
land deal that was approved last month by the islands' government.
``Beal wants to turn an area of great cultural and natural resource
value into an industrial setting, and people think that's a
horrible idea.''
</P>
<P>
   A judge has already temporarily blocked the deal, and is
expected to rule soon on a permanent injunction. Wade Gates, a
spokesman for Beal Aerospace Technologies, said the company would
appeal any adverse court rulings. He also defended the plans for
the site in question.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't destroy anything,'' he said. ``We would actually
preserve what's there, clean it up and provide improvements. After
we build our headquarters, people would still have access to the
beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Beal also faces opposition from environmentalists on Anguilla, a
British territory that owns tiny Sombrero Island, where he hopes to
build his launch pad.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, he must convince potential customers _ largely
satellite telecommunications companies _ that a start-up company
can compete in the risky, expensive launch business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people in the industry feel Beal still has a lot to
prove,'' said Craig Covault, senior editor of Aviation Week and
Space Technology. ``As a start-up, they're very impressive in their
engineering team and approach, but whether they can overcome the
technical and cost challenges remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The rocket plant would bring an economic boost to the troubled
U.S. Virgin Islands, where the tourism-dependent economy is mired
in the doldrums and the government has wracked up a $1 billion
debt. Beal says he would bring 150 permanent jobs to the island of
55,000, with a $75 million initial investment.
</P>
<P>
   On tiny Anguilla, with a population of barely 12,000, the 200
full-time jobs would also be a boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very small financial base and any type of
diversification is favorable,'' said Hubert Hughes, chief minister
of Anguilla. ``It would be stable, prolonged employment. Right now
we have only a fragile, one-crop industry called tourism.''
</P>
<P>
   Beal is already developing his rocket, designing the engines at
a facility in Frisco, which employs about 200 people north of
Dallas, and test-firing at an old military base near Waco.
</P>
<P>
   With his background in real estate and banking, Beal seems an
unlikely rocket man. But he's reportedly something of a math
genius, and has offered a $50,000 prize to anyone who can solve a
complex problem he wrote. So far, nobody has solved ``Beal's
Conjecture.''
</P>
<P>
   He began his foray into the space business four years ago,
attracted by the boom in satellite communications and a backlog in
launch schedules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to keep it as simple as possible, with few moving
parts, so that it is reliable and inexpensive,'' Gates said of the
proposed booster.
</P>
<P>
   Beal chose the Caribbean for his launch site because it is near
the equator, where rockets can reach orbit with less fuel because
the earth's rotation helps catapult them into space. He was
attracted to the U.S. Virgin Islands because of tax incentives, and
because laws governing the space business strictly limit what types
of technologies are allowed off U.S. soil.
</P>
<P>
   While Beal has approvals for the facilities from both island
governments, he must still win approvals from both the British and
U.S. governments before he can proceed. As a back up, Beal has been
negotiating with Guyana on the South American coast for the launch
facility.
</P>
<P>
   At 236 feet tall and with a payload capacity of 40,000 pounds,
Beal's rocket would be one of the biggest in an increasingly
crowded field. Since NASA scaled back commercial satellite launches
following the Challenger disaster in 1986, private launch companies
have sprung up in Europe, Russia, Japan, China and India.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention Boeing and Lockheed-Martin, the two U.S.
companies already launching commercial payloads from Cape Canaveral
in Florida and Vandenberg Air Force Base in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very big business worldwide with lots of competition,''
said Covault. ``I think Beal is very serious and is aware of the
challenges, but there are a lot of hurdles to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   In the islands, Beal has plenty of support among top government
officials and business leaders. But his opponents are determined
and vocal.
</P>
<P>
   On Anguilla, local preservationists and the Royal Society for
the Protection of Birds _ which boasts Queen Elizabeth among its
patrons _ say the launch pad would harm birds and lizards on the
tiny island. The only person living on Sombrero _ 38 miles from
Anguilla _ is a lighthouse keeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sombrero is one of the more important sites in all of the
Caribbean for nesting seabirds,'' said the Royal Society's Jim
Stevenson. ``So many other islands have been built over that it
makes an island like this all that much more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates said the company has conducted extensive environmental
studies on Sombrero, and believes the impact would be minimal. The
launch pad would use only about 10 percent of the island's 95
acres, and the company would help create nature preserves on other
nearby islands, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On St. Croix, opponents have circulated petitions and held
marches. The issue has dominated the local press, with radio talk
shows buzzing over the latest developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think part of the problem is that some people feel Beal is
arrogant and condescending,'' said talk show host Maria Heywood.
``People here are politically astute. They feel that giving away
this property for a few jobs isn't a fair trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Jacobs said his group would drop their opposition if
Beal agrees to move to an existing industrial park.
</P>
<P>
   But Gates said the company feels it would just face new
opposition if it agreed to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``These debates about progress and preservation were going on
long before Beal arrived,'' he said. ``We're offering the kinds of
jobs and investment that will allow these people's children to stay
on the islands. Unfortunately, you have a small number of people
who appear to oppose almost anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
