<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7414 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-IRAN-JEWS-$ADV14-COX     11-12 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-JEWS-$ADV14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A DWINDLING MINORITY: IRANIAN JEWS UNNERVED BY ARRESTS
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Nov. 14 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ The Jews of Iran are one step closer to leaving
their homeland of more than 2,500 years.
</P>
<P>
   They were stunned in March, when Iranian police in the southern
city of Shiraz arrested 13 Jews and seven Muslims. Police accused
them of spying for the United States and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Those jailed include a 16-year-old boy, four religious school
teachers and a lay leader who performs Jewish ritual circumcisions.
</P>
<P>
   Accustomed to cautious but prosperous lives, Iranian Jews now
wonder if the rules have changed. Many consider joining relatives
in North America, Europe or Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every Jew in Iran has a plan. They just don't know when,''
said one member of the Jewish community in Tehran recently. He
asked, as most do now, not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   But, a daughter of one of those arrested wrote a poem in August
in an Iranian Jewish magazine pleading for help from the Islamic
country's Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei. In it, she
described the dilemma for Iranian Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, who have devoted our lives to Iran, could we leave this
country, take our hearts away from it?'' wrote Sahar Puyan Rad, a
high school student. ``We've been planted here. Iran is our garden
. . . but our days are now filled with sorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Though we are two religions, still we've got one heart, one
God, one homeland then therefore one leader,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Iranian Jews regularly pray for Khamenei and other
Iranian leaders. It is one of the ways through the centuries that
they have woven Persia, now Iran, into their religion.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the country's 50 synagogues are decorated in Persian
carpets. Worshippers remove their shoes before praying _ as do
their Muslim countrymen. The city of Hamadan is home to the
5th-Century tomb of Jewish Queen Esther.
</P>
<P>
   Jews here weathered the birth of Israel, which saw the expulsion
of Jews from many Muslim countries. They survived the radicalism of
the 1979 Islamic Revolution, though more than half of them fled.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Turkey, Iran remains the only Middle
Eastern Muslim country with a sizable Jewish population _ numbering
about 30,000 in a country of about 65 million.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the Jewish community here, mindful of maintaining
good relations with Iranian officials, assert that anti-Semitism is
no worse in Iran than in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   However, one acknowledges that the Shiraz arrests in March may
push emigration this year to about 900 from some 600 in previous
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe a crisis has occurred in the Jewish community.
But it will calm down,'' says Haroun Yashayaei, leader of the
Tehran Jewish Association and a prominent Iranian film producer.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed, he acknowledges the arrests caused a ``little
panic.'' But he blames that on foreign media and diplomats he
claims want to stir up anti-Iranian feelings.
</P>
<P>
   There has been an outcry. Joined by Jewish groups throughout the
world, diplomats from the United States to Israel to Russia have
expressed concern about the arrests.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, at the request of American Jewish
leaders, has said that he may visit Iran to win the Jews' release.
</P>
<P>
   They all search for delicate ways of pressuring a country that
is anti-Israel, stridently independent and undergoing its own
struggle over calls for democratic reform.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders worry that a hard-line faction in the government had
the Jews arrested in order to generate anti-Western sentiment
within Iran.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are particularly concerned that these members of the Jewish
minority may have been singled out for persecution to make a
political point, as a gambit in what is widely described as a
struggle within Iran's leadership, rather than to serve justice,''
wrote Human Rights Watch in a letter to the head of the Iranian
judiciary in September.
</P>
<P>
   Concern peaked months ago, when a high-ranking Iranian court
official promised executions for those arrested. The judge later
lost his job _ though it is unclear why _ and reform-oriented
President Mohammad Khatami has promised fair trials.
</P>
<P>
   However, Khatami does not control the courts and is second in
power behind Iran's Supreme Leader Khamenei. It appears that the
trials may be held in secret Revolutionary Courts.
</P>
<P>
   There are differing reports as to whether the defendants have
been able to meet with lawyers. Family members say that, as
Orthodox Jews, they have refused to eat non-Kosher jail food,
limiting themselves to bread and water.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about the reason for the arrests is rampant within
Iran's Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   One story is that they found the Jews with Hebrew videotapes
about religious themes and mistook them for something sinister.
Another theory is that some members of the group may have been
caught sending e-mails or letters to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   And, some speculate that other Jews may have been trying to
settle a score in some internal dispute by alleging crimes to the
police.
</P>
<P>
   The facts are disconcertingly sketchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows about the case. Because of that, we are
worried,'' said Parves Ahobim, 52, a Jewish merchant in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
   But some of those arrested are well-known leaders within the
Jewish community. Said a Tehran Jew, asking not to be identified:
``We don't know about the case, but we know they are not spies.''
</P>
<P>
   Jews have always been quick to point out that Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, the founder of the Islamic revolution, stated that Jews
and Christians should be allowed to live peacefully in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish community publishes a booklet of Khomeini's sayings
about the Jews. When a celebration was held this summer to mark
what would have been his 100th birthday, 27 buses of Jews showed
up.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the Shiraz case prompted the huge attendance as a show
of loyalty to Iran and solidarity within the Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   Under Khomeini's dictate, Jews in Iran were given a seat in
parliament, as were a few Christian denominations.
</P>
<P>
   But, minority religions have run into problems under the Islamic
regime. The Bahai's, practitioners of an offshoot of Islam, have
been especially persecuted with arrests and hundreds have been
executed.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Associated Press, 17 Jews have been executed in
the last 20 years. But, human rights groups in most cases have been
unable to determine if the past arrests were based on religious
persecution.
</P>
<P>
   Muslims get lighter sentences for crimes against against
non-Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   But, Jews have some small liberties. They are allowed to drink
alcohol while Muslims, at least in theory, are not. Men and women
can mix at their weddings, while they are not supposed to in Muslim
weddings.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Jews trade scant information about the 13 of their faith
in jail, those allowances are overshadowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have taken away some of us and hurt our hearts by doing
this. The backs of the women have been bowed because their husbands
are gone,'' high school poet Rad writes. ``The soil of Iran is part
of our lives and we do our best for Iran.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
