NYT-11-12-99 1104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7418 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     11-12 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Friday, Nov. 12, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Saturday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILIPINO-VET (San Francisco) _ As a Filipino American in the
U.S. Army, Pfc. Gary Aranal endured the famed Bataan death march
during World War II after his surrender to Japanese forces in the
Philippines. More than 55 years later, Aranal is locked in a
different battle, trying to win the same benefits accorded other
American World War II soldiers for himself and thousands of other
Filipino American war veterans. So far, Aranal has fared better
against the Japanese. By RYAN KIM.
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYORAL (San Francisco) _ His opponents may call him a big
spender, but no one can accuse mayoral candidate Tom Ammiano of
getting rich off public office. Tax returns and other financial
documents covering the last four years, show Ammiano has struggled
to stay afloat financially during his term on the Board of
Supervisors _ a job that paid only $23,924 a year until last year.
By ERIN McCORMICK.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN-LION (San Francisco) _ Authorities say they believe
they have found the remains of a missing Walnut Creek, Calif., man
and it is almost certain he was killed by a mountain lion in the
remote desert northeast of Winnemucca, Nev. By The San Francisco
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ESHLEMAN-OBIT (San Francisco) _ Private memorial services are
being planned for John M. ``Jack'' Eshleman, a reporter who was
fired by The San Francisco Examiner and blackballed by the industry
for refusing to answer questions from the communist-hunting House
Un-American Activities Committee in the 1950s. By LARRY D.
HATFIELD.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-NOW-AND-AGAIN (Undated) _ One of television's most thrilling
shows is ``Now and Again,'' and it has nothing to do with cheap
action or riveting drama. ``Now and Again'' is a treasure, a
wonderful, inexplicable piece of work that separates itself from
the pack mostly by being so hard to pigeonhole. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NINERS (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ J.J. Stokes has an idea for
the San Francisco 49ers' passing-game problems, one that his fellow
wide receivers agree with: Keep everything simple. Nothing against
the masterful complexities of the West Coast offense, but all that
choreographed mayhem isn't helping the 49ers these days. By JEFFRI
CHADIHA.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RAIDERS (Alameda, Calif.) _ Junior Seau comes to town for
Sunday's Raiders-Chargers game at the Oakland Coliseum, and if the
Raiders want to neutralize the game's most feared linebacker, they
may just want to hold a full-length mirror in front of ole No. 55.
Because nothing makes Junior Seau drop all he's doing like the
chance for Junior Seau to admire Junior Seau. By BRIAN MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ This has to be the perfect lunch.
My wife is at Greens with a friend, enjoying marinated tofu
brochette with brown rice, and I'm sitting in a row of men at the
counter of Original Joe's eating piles of meat. And I'm the one on
a diet. It's the modified Dr. Atkins low-carbohydrate, no-hunger
caveman weight-loss plan, the diet half the men in America are on,
and quite a few women. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
