<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There is nothing worse than a politician who's found a 'crisis'
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ I missed my chances to see debates among the
Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   I would have been parked right in front of my television, but
I've always had something else to attend, the outcome of which was
far, far more important to the future of our country _ Marshall
High School football games.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks had a losing season and I was, truth to tell,
depressed about the whole matter, but not nearly as depressed as I
would have been watching Republicans savage themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, I'll probably have something more important to
do every single time C-SPAN replays the debates, about 400 times or
so I would imagine. I'll just have to miss hearing the GOP
candidates talk about what a terrible, horrible, rotten place
America is today.
</P>
<P>
   Really? Is America really so bad? Is this a crisis? Is this what
our parents faced in going through the Great Depression, or as they
struggled through the fighting of the Second World War?
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, I wonder if times are as bad as they were
during the great social upheavals of the '60s and '70s. I was
pretty young during those days, but it seemed like the United
States was going through a much rougher time then than now.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is no crisis, other than the personal one each
of these candidates face in realizing they don't have a dog's
chance against Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In politics, the worst crisis of all comes when the candidate
realizes he is probably going to lose. Then the sky can't fall fast
enough. Descriptions of all sorts of ills _ almost entirely
imaginary or overblown _ slip from the mouths of likely losers.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, when Ronald Reagan was running for re-election, a
group of Democratic candidates got together for a debate at about
this same time during the election. I didn't watch that one,
either. I think my car needed to be washed.
</P>
<P>
   You may recall, as I do, that those were mostly good days in the
United States _ not perfect, but pretty good. But to hear the
Democrats, Dante's hell would have been a more pleasant place to
be.
</P>
<P>
   One of the candidates said it was ``midnight in America.''
Really? No, of course not, but it was midnight in his campaign.
Reagan won in a walk.
</P>
<P>
   I'm no fan of Bill Clinton's, but let's be realistic for a
moment. Take Monica Lewinsky and sex out of the Oval Office
(please) and would America really be much of a different place had
Bob Dole won the last election? The honest answer is ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm tired of hearing candidates of any ilk make up crises that
don't exist. To do so tarnishes the accomplishments of the
generations of Americans who've suffered through _ and conquered _
real crises. Most of us living today and most of the candidates
(John McCain excepted) don't even know what a real crisis is.
</P>
<P>
   But we may someday all have to face something like a world war,
where it isn't immediately clear who is going to be the winner. We
may face an economic crisis where people are starving in our own
country. It is hard to believe it may happen, but our own fathers
and grandfathers experienced it. We aren't so far removed.
</P>
<P>
   If that time comes, it won't have been helpful that we pretended
our role in the United Nations was a ``crisis.'' Or
most-favored-nation trade status for China was a ``crisis.'' Or
even that sex in the White House was a ``crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Every problem and difficulty is not a crisis. When our
politicians try to tell us so, it is time to turn them off, get
outside and enjoy our nation not in crisis. You might even consider
a high school football game.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (TX) News
Messenger. His e-mail address is platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
