<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The gift is thanks to UD
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When I heard about the largest-ever gift in
University of Dayton history, the number simply staggered me.
</P>
<P>
   No, not the $10 million pledge, $2 million a year over five
years.
</P>
<P>
   It was that class of '78 number that stunned me. My class.
</P>
<P>
   John McHale is 43 years old. My age.
</P>
<P>
   I graduated from Miami University in 1978, and I still can't
figure out the high finances of my son's Cub Scout popcorn sales.
What business does McHale have, a kid like us, with so much spare
cash to donate to his alma mater?
</P>
<P>
   At times, the Internet entrepreneur can't believe it either. He
vividly remembers living in UD's Ghetto, not so long ago, and
selling his plasma once a week for $10. ``A Milano's cheesesteak
sandwich figured in that equation, and maybe a six-pack of Little
Kings,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Aren't benefactors of this magnitude supposed to be dead? Or, at
the very least, venerable? I didn't detect a fleck of silver in the
photo of McHale standing next to a beaming Brother Raymond Fitz,
UD's president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of my good fortunes,'' McHale says, ``that I can do
this while I'm younger, and live long enough to see the effects.''
His wife, Chris, told a UD interviewer, ``You don't forget who
brung you to the dance.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how many times you've told yourself that you don't
equate money with success, it's hard for those of us still playing
stagger-the-bills not to feel like a loser, a loser with a capital
L, when faced with stories like McHale's. Where is this magical
land called Adulthood, my friends and I ask ourselves, where you
don't have to fret about paying the mortgage and the car payment in
the same week?
</P>
<P>
   Talking with the modest, normal-guy McHale is an excellent
antidote to such feelings of inadequacy.
</P>
<P>
   As an undergrad, McHale shared a house in the Ghetto with five
other guys, and they had a system for dishwashing: Each roommate
was assigned a day, and if he didn't do the dishes that day, he'd
get stuck with the next day's, too. ``This one guy didn't do the
dishes for 10 days, and finally we ran out of dishes and put them
all in his bed.''
</P>
<P>
   His first year out of college, working for Texas Instruments in
Dallas, McHale became ``UD-sick,'' flying back to Dayton every few
weeks to visit friends still in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have friends in Texas who have that kind of devotion to a
team,'' he reflects, ``but don't have that broad passion for the
university.''
</P>
<P>
   The struggle, the territorial initialing of cartons of eggs and
gallons of milk, all factored into the fun of those days, McHale
says. Those struggles are long gone for the man who sold two
computer companies, NetWorth and NetSpeed, for a total of $600
million. But he has never distanced himself from UD, or from
ordinary life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how great it feels to finally have my student
loan paid off,'' he joked at the 1997 groundbreaking for what was
initially called the McHale Basketball Center. At McHale's
insistence, it was renamed to honor legendary UD coach Don Donoher.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't live in a 50,000-square-foot pleasure palace, a la
Bill Gates: ``You can only be so comfortable in life. You can
isolate yourself from your family and from society if you build
your physical wealth around you.
</P>
<P>
   Having three children under the age of 6 keeps him grounded,
McHale says: ``I know it's easy for me to say this, but making
money is such a small piece of the the life struggle. I'd call it a
5 percenter, definitely not a 100 percenter.''
</P>
<P>
   So how does he define success, if not in terms of wealth?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll point to an example,'' he says. ``Brother Ray. I would
define success as rising to the top of one's field with grace and
humility.''
</P>
<P>
   We might expand that definition to include those who give back
in the same spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
