<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7426 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MINTER-COLUMN13-COX     11-12 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `So frightful an endeavor'
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Minter writes about his visit to the D-Day invasion beaches
in France. Following is the first of two columns.
</P>
<P>
   Omaha Beach, the bloodiest of the invasion sites, and the big
American cemetery in Normandy are places the president, the Cabinet
and every member of the Congress ought to be required to see in
person before taking office. They are powerful reminders of what
Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower said when he came here years after he had
led the greatest military operation in history: Never again must
nations have to call on their young men for so frightful an
endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   To someone who has only teen-age memories of June 6, 1944, the
Normandy coast of France at the end of this century seems almost
like home. The beaches, today as tranquil as St. Simons or Sapelo
on the Georgia coast, were so dearly repurchased from Hitler's Nazi
occupants that you have a feeling of being on American soil.
</P>
<P>
   Old soldiers from this country, from Great Britain and Canada,
some wearing ancient and bemedaled tunics, are common sights as
they stroll beaches and villages where they fought half a century
ago. No great imagination is needed to hear thunder of guns and
cries of wounded, to see golden sand stained red, beaches littered
with young soldiers who would never go home again to all we have
enjoyed in these 50-plus years since that awful day.
</P>
<P>
   They bought it for us, the unlucky ones who died and the lucky
ones who lived. Nowhere is our debt more obvious than the American
cemeteries with their endless ranks of white crosses and Stars of
David spread across acres as vast as a South Georgia cotton field.
No words or pictures can describe these scenes. They must be seen
with the eye, and yet there is no way to truly understand, except
for those who were there.
</P>
<P>
   Their flags still fly over Normandy, the Stars and Stripes most
prominently. Unlike other parts of France, the people speak
English, and gladly so. Museums dedicated to liberation tell a
story that much of America has forgotten, or never really knew. In
village squares, and on bluffs overlooking the sea, you see
well-preserved jeeps, Sherman tanks and artillery pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Remains of man-made ``Mulberry'' harbors, manufactured in
England and towed across the Channel, shelter fishermen at
Arromanches. The artificial harbors, needed for unloading ships and
supplies on the beaches, were the second largest and most expensive
industrial endeavor of World War II, exceeded only by the Manhattan
Project that produced the atom bomb.
</P>
<P>
   LEADING THE WAY OFF UTAH BEACH
</P>
<P>
   Utah Beach, westernmost of the invasion points, was not so
heavily defended as Omaha, but bloody still. Men spearheading the
4th Division's assault were pinned almost in the surf by German
machine guns and cannons firing from concrete bunkers embedded on
bluffs until Brig. Gen. Theodore Roosevelt Jr., son of Teddy and
too old for combat, picked up his walking cane, stepped out front,
and headed into the hedgerows.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things you see on a visit to Utah Beach is a
copy of The Atlanta Journal, dated June 6, 1944. The yellowed front
page has the same headlines and typefaces I worked with so many
years in the sports department, describing bloodless battles
between Georgia and Georgia Tech, Alabama and Auburn. The next
thing you noticed is a baseball bat from the old Hanna factory in
Athens. An unidentified soldier from Athens had carried it across
the Atlantic, and then across the English Channel to France. For a
visitor from Georgia, D-Day comes closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   As spring edged toward summer, everyone knew it was coming. What
they didn't know was when, or where. Hitler and his generals in
their map room were about as much in the dark as my young cousins
and I chopping cotton in Fayette County. No landing of the
magnitude required had ever been attempted, and certainly not
against such massive fortifications as the Germans had built into
their ``Atlantic Wall'' along the French coastline. If a Las Vegas
bookie had been making odds, the outcome of the invasion would have
been ``too close to call.''
</P>
<P>
   AFTERNOON PAPER GOT STORY
</P>
<P>
   Looking at a copy of a newspaper that had hit the streets in
Atlanta only hours after the first waves hit the beaches, I thought
about what it must have been like that morning in the Journal
offices on Forsyth Street. I knew the afternoon Journal had enjoyed
what we used to call a ``P.M. Break'' on the biggest story of the
war.
</P>
<P>
   The Allied invasion forces, preceded by parachutists jumping
behind German lines just after midnight, hit the beaches at dawn.
Breakfast in Normandy is still midnight in Atlanta. Surely the
morning Atlanta Constitution, a rival Journal people in those days
regarded only slightly below Germany and Japan, had been shut out.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Journal's ``Weather Ear'' in the top left-hand
corner of the front page, Atlanta on June 6 expected a high of 79
and a low of 68, with cooler weather on the way. The paper
``Covered Dixie Like the Dew'' and sold for 5 cents a copy.
</P>
<P>
   The lead headline, eight columns of thick, black, capital
letters, more than an inch high and hand-set from ancient wooden
type, announced the long-awaited invasion: ALLIES STORM COAST
LINES. Wes Gallagher's Associated Press story under the headline,
filed from Supreme Headquarters of the Allied Expeditionary Force
in London, reported fighting in the inland city of Caen. German
defenses on the beaches were said to be lighter than expected.
</P>
<P>
   That turned out to be terribly optimistic. Caen did not fall to
English Gen. Bernard Montgomery until many days later, but
Gallagher, who later became chief of the Associated Press, could
report only what he was told by Army press officers. No reporter
had an eyewitness account to send home. Before the morning was out,
one would.
</P>
<P>
   Next week: Atlanta Journal editor Wright Bryan's eyewitness
report of Allied landings is arguably the ``scoop'' of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
