<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7427 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD13-COX     11-12 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reader asked for advice, but may not like the response
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``I would like your advice on which tool to buy
next,'' a reader says. ``I plan to do built-in bookshelves and
cabinets (a huge job for me and nothing like I've done before). I
have the usual hand power tools (but no orbital sander), a 10''
table saw (so-so) and a 12'' DeWalt compound mitre saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like I'll have to build up some panels from hardwood
(maple or alder) and am thinking the jointer will be the next power
tool to buy. I can spend in the $400-$500 range. I look forward to
your advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, sir, however much you may have been looking forward to it,
I'm not sure you're going to like it. The e-mail doesn't contain as
much information as I'd like, such as exactly what kind of panels
we're talking about and how big they're going to be, and what you
mean by ``build up.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't have enough money to buy a really useful jointer. You
might be able to find a decent 6-inch jointer for $500 but this
won't do you any good except for edge jointing, and you can handle
that well enough with a Record bench jointer.
</P>
<P>
   Much as I hate to say it, I would suggest you consider plywood,
at least for your bookcases. If your 10-inch bench saw is only
so-so, then invest in a good portable circular saw, put a carbide
blade on it, and get an eight-foot straightedge for cutting plywood
(they're not expensive, but be sure to use a brace in the middle if
you're cutting in the 8-foot direction) and a set of sawhorses.
This will allow you to slice up the plywood panels more safely, and
possibly more accurately, than with a lightweight table saw.
</P>
<P>
   You can use veneer tape to edge the work, or if you want to do a
really nice job, edge it in hardwood. Buy enough matching 4/4
hardwood to do the job, joint one edge with the Record plane, and
rip it on the table saw into one-inch strips for the edging, which
only needs to be glued to the plywood.
</P>
<P>
   The cabinets are another matter. I don't know what kind of
cabinets you have in mind. Plywood is always used for the carcass
of kitchen cabinets. If you have frame-and-panel doors in mind,
hardwood is most often used for the frames, and can easily be used
for the panels, too, if you wish. If you plan on flat, frameless
doors, then plywood is essential to avoid the warping likely with
that much solid wood. I'd definitely use hardwood edging in this
case. Same goes for drawers.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to use frame-and-panel doors and drawer fronts, I'd
still use the hand plane for jointing. My advice would be to save
your money until you can buy at least an eight-inch jointer and a
portable 10-inch planer, or better yet, a European combo
jointer-and-planer with a 10-inch or larger capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
