<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7438 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NO-Y2KPARTY13-COX     11-12 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NO-Y2KPARTY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cut loose on New Year's Eve? They'll pass
 &HT;    By Ricardo Gandara
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Hey, not everybody is attending Sandra Bullock's
New Year's bash. Or dining at Sullivan's. Or shooting bullets into
the night sky.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are staying home. Maybe they're on a different
calendar. Maybe they interpret our calendar differently. Maybe they
just don't care.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Dickey is hunkering down with his family. ``What better way
to break in the new year? If I'm going to be hugging and kissing
anyone on New Year's, it will be my family,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Denise, and sons, Benjamin and Samuel, 4 and almost 2,
are making cheese pizza on New Year's Eve. They'll splurge on
chocolate ice cream. They'll play indoor basketball and, when
everyone is tuckered out, watch a rented movie and eat popcorn.
``Maybe even do some arts and crafts with the kids,'' he says.
Maybe they won't fall asleep by midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Exciting, huh? ``Nothing better,'' Dickey says.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Davis, president of the Pagan Alliance of Central Texas,
doesn't observe New Year's _ at least not on Dec. 31. The Pagan New
Year, known as the feast of Samhain, is from sundown Oct. 31 to
sundown Nov. 1. ``In old Europe it was the feast of the last
harvest. Most importantly, it's the time when the veil between the
world we live in and the world of spirit is the thinnest. We
remember and celebrate our beloved dead,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   So what will he be doing on New Year's Eve when some of us are
having the time of our lives? At 7 a.m. Dec. 31, he'll be watching
TV to see if there are any Y2K glitches in Australia when it turns
midnight there. ``I want to watch very carefully what happens in
the world because it will give us a good indication what will
happen here,'' he says. ``This is just me. I'll do the normal stuff
that I usually do. Sleep and eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin Tan's New Year is some time around mid-April 2000. He's
Buddhist and follows the Burmese calendar. So this Jan. 1 ``is a
normal day,'' he says. ``We'll do the normal things like clean
house, go shopping, take the kids to the library.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin, that's a Saturday, and it's a national holiday because
there are six bowl games on the tube. ``Oh,'' he says,
recalculating, ``we'll probably just stay home.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the party poopers who keep insisting that the new
millennium doesn't start until 2001. They keep reading all that
rational stuff on the U.S. Naval Observatory's Web site: ``The end
of the second millennium and the beginning of the third will be
reached on Jan. 1, 2001. This date is based on the now globally
recognized Gregorian calendar ... Rather than starting with the
year zero, years in this calendar begin with the date Jan. 1, 1
Anno Domini (AD). Consequently, the next millennium does not begin
until Jan. 1, 2001 AD.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, yeah, yeah. So what if they're the official timekeepers?
So what if they're right? We may not be around Dec. 31, 2000. WE
WANT TO PARTY NOW!
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not Melanie Carter. This 57-year-old isn't going to
be a homebody, but she's hardly tearing up the town. On New Year's
morning she's going house to house as she does every year. She has
a list of elderly shut-ins who look forward to her home-cooked
meals on Christmas and New Year's. This year it's a rice, cheese
and broccoli casserole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is more important. I'll celebrate the following
weekend when I go visit my daughter in Fort Worth,'' she says.
``Know what? She's staying home New Year's Eve and New Year's Day
to avoid the drunks. Hey, some of us stay boring just to stay
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
