<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ MARSHALL, Texas _ Every problem and difficulty
is not a crisis. When our politicians try to tell us so, it is time
to turn them off, get outside and enjoy our nation not in crisis.
You might even consider a high school football game. (Latham,
Marshall News Messenger) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ Jim Minter writes about his visit to the D-Day
invasion beaches in France. (Jim Minter is a former editor of The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ When I heard about the
largest-ever gift in University of Dayton history, the number
simply staggered me. No, not the $10 million pledge, $2 million a
year over five years. It was that class of '78 number that stunned
me. My class. John McHale is 43 years old. My age. I graduated from
Miami University in 1978, and I still can't figure out the high
finances of my son's Cub Scout popcorn sales. What business does
McHale have, a kid like us, with so much spare cash to donate to
his alma mater? (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Not only are the Israelis trying again to make
peace with the Palestinians. Now they also must make peace with the
Christians. That's because the Israelis have been trying to be fair
to Muslims. Go figure. At issue is a vacant lot in Nazareth. (Tom
Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED
THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Poor Brownie. Our family dog was a scapegoat;
he bore the blame for others. Today, people are always looking for
a Brownie of their own. Few admit to doing anything wrong these
days. It's always someone or something else. (Howard Kleinberg is a
columnist for Cox News Service.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ Busting up Windows (as opposed to busting up
Microsoft) neither protects consumers nor elevates the economy.
Instead, we should invoke the antitrust laws to reflect the real
world by turning Windows into a regulated monopoly. (Andy Glass is
a columnist for Cox News Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED
THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
