<HEADER>
A7513 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-12 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DIET ALL MEN WILL LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This has to be the perfect lunch.
</P>
<P>
   My wife is at Greens with a friend, enjoying marinated tofu
brochette with brown rice, and I'm sitting in a row of men at the
counter of Original Joe's eating piles of meat.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm the one on a diet.
</P>
<P>
   It's the modified Dr. Atkins low-carbohydrate, no-hunger caveman
weight-loss plan, the diet half the men in America are on, and
quite a few women. Cathy of the comic strip complained that it
can't be a diet because it's not painful enough.
</P>
<P>
   Look at it this way, Cathy. It's painful to think I've become as
full of magical thinking as those who believe breaking a cookie
lets the calories leak out. Or that food speared from somebody
else's plate doesn't count.
</P>
<P>
   I've stopped using sugar in my coffee and already can tell the
difference between the stuff in the blue packets and the stuff in
the pink packets. You might even find me snacking in that
calorie-free zone: grocery store lines. But you won't find me
chomping on baguettes.
</P>
<P>
   I'll be following Dr. Atkins' advice, and eating the
protein-rich nuts and jerky that ancient hunter-gatherers used as
fuel, after I hunt and gather them on Aisle 4.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what you eat at Original Joe's if you're on a diet _
``the diet plate.'' It's a 12-ounce hamburger steak the size and
shape of a half-inflated football, served with cottage cheese and
fruit. You know, so the plate can shout ``diet.''
</P>
<P>
   It's acceptable on Dr. Atkins' diet, all but the fruit. Fructose
is murder.
</P>
<P>
   Just a year or two ago I laughed at this quaint diet plate,
which probably has been on Original Joe's menu the entire 62 years
it's been in business.
</P>
<P>
   A hamburger, hold the bun? Don't they know anything about fat,
cholesterol and the deadly capacities of red meat?
</P>
<P>
   Then I read Dr. Atkins' suggestions for a strict beginning diet.
They included bacon and eggs (no toast, hash browns or orange
juice) for breakfast and perhaps a bacon cheeseburger (no bun) for
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Life is suddenly glorious, imitating that Woody Allen movie
about a future in which scientists discover that chocolate sundaes
are good for you.
</P>
<P>
   Well, they aren't. Not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   I knew I loved Dr. Atkins when I looked at the recipes in the
back of his book, ``Dr. Atkins' New Diet Revolution.'' There was
bearnaise sauce, made with clarified butter, not tofu juice. Go
ahead, spoon it all over oily salmon filets.
</P>
<P>
   And there was guacamole, hold the starchy chips, which are just
a form of transportation anyway. Oh boy, we get to dip with our
fingers.
</P>
<P>
   What really made me a believer was the ``Swiss snack,'' cubes of
Swiss cheese wrapped in bacon, then deep-fried in hot oil.
</P>
<P>
   Mmm, mmm, good. Enough grease to clog the Lincoln Tunnel. No
wonder Dr. Atkins recommends regular check-ups and cholesterol
tests.
</P>
<P>
   I know a lot of men following some version of Dr. Atkins'
low-carbohydrate diet, usually the high-steak-intake version, and
they claim to be losing weight. Of course, the dead men aren't
talking.
</P>
<P>
   So far I've managed to stay on this diet for a week. Although I
haven't lost much weight, I haven't died either. Mostly I've eaten
sensible low-carbohydrate foods like grilled fish and broccoli, or
tofu and broccoli soup, or bits of chicken with broccoli.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, who shares these feasts, is losing weight like Gandhi
on Fen-Phen. Life isn't fair, and she doesn't have Cathy's problems
or mine.
</P>
<P>
   This diet may sound grim, but I get to add toasted almonds. And
I get to eat cans of tuna at lunch.
</P>
<P>
   That's a pleasure left over from bachelor days when there was
nothing in the fridge but mustard and mayo, and the only thing to
stir them into was a can of tuna from the cupboard.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Jesse Ventura. Dr. Atkins is the new super hero to
red-blooded, red-meat eating males. Our red blood, unfortunately,
has to be refrigerated and skimmed like fatty chicken soup.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
