<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Saturday,
Nov. 13. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   BRAD _ Bill Bradley is in Kansas City for a fund-raiser and news
conference. Photo. 18. Steve Kraske.
</P>
<P>
   HMO: Beginning next year, Medicare beneficiaries in HMOs will
face the biggest cut in benefits in this decade. Premiums also are
going up in most HMOs. The is happening nationwide because of
federal cutbacks in Medicare payments, health-care inflation and
the rising cost of prescription drugs. About 50,000 Kasas City area
seniors are enrolled in Medicare HMOs. This doesn't affect the
200,000 local folks who just get regular Medicare, which provides
fewer benefits. Graphic. Photo. Alan Bavley. 38.
</P>
<P>
   FLAG: The Chiefs, the NFL and the Local Initiative Support
Corporation are creating a flag football field at 43rd and
Cleveland with a $75,000 grant. Today, kids will play flag football
with the Chiefs to celebrate. Carl Peterson and other Chiefs
bigwigs will be at the ceremony. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   HOLD: A bill that will be offered in the next Missouri General
Assembly would extend the 20-hour hold law to 48 hours for felonies
such as murder, rape, etc. Police say its long been needed. They
complain that the 20-hour hold does not allow them to build a case
to charge a suspect and that, as result, dangerous felons are
released with charges pending. Legal advocates say extending the
hold will only mean that innocent people will be held longer in
jail. 25. Malcum Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   OSCO: Demetrius Davis, who died after an altercation Tuesday
outside a drug store in Kansas City, was a man struggling to find
his way, his parents said. Davis worked part-time, but couldn't
keep up with child-support payments and keep a job, his parents
said. Ed Fletcher and Christine Vendel. 15.
</P>
<P>
   IMPACT: Kansas City leaders wants developers who build in the
Northland to start paying an arterial street impact fee to help pay
for new road construction. The new fee would be based on the amount
of rush-hour traffic that a new development would generate.
According to the formula that the city would use, a drive-in bank
would have to pay the most while a residential development would
pay much less. Developers agree that there needs to be some kind of
funding mechanism for street construction but are concerned about
some aspects of the proposal. 30. Photo, graphic. Mike Rice.
</P>
<P>
   BLOOD. Monday is the 40th anniversary of the Clutter murders, a
crime that Truman Capote and Hollywood turned into an icon for
senseless and sudden violence visited upon unsuspecting innocents;
it's clear from visiting the scene today that the one thing
Holcomb, Kan., is remembered for is the one thing residents wish
the world would just forget. Mark Wiebe. Photos. Map
</P>
<P>
   DOYLE. Today is the first day of the rest of Francis Patrick
Doyle's life. The octogenarian, convicted in the deadly Leawood
baseball bat attack, will be sentenced to spend the rest of his
life in prison. Tony Rizzo. 20. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   KCPL _ Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co. is under mounting pressure
to consider walking away from its merger with Western Resources
Inc. as the deal's value continues to erode. By Steve Everly
</P>
<P>
   Y2K13 _ Column by David Hayes and Finn Bullers
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   NEIGHBOR. Some neighbors are ``enemies'' this weekend as K-State
and Nebraska fans back their football teams, which meet in THE Big
12 showdown of the season on Saturday. Jim Pedley. 18. Photo
</P>
<P>
   MUMHOOP. MU men's hoops opener vs Wisconsin. 6 p.m. start at
