<SLUG> BC-MOUNTAIN-LION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEVADA AUTHORITIES BELIEVE HIKER KILLED BY MOUNTAIN LION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Authorities say they believe they have found the
remains of a missing California man and it is almost certain he was
killed by a mountain lion in the remote desert of northern Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   A human skull believed to be that of Dennis Dorsey, 49, was
found Wednesday by deputies and tracking dogs in the rugged Owyhee
Desert, Elko County Sheriff Neil Harris said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said evidence at the scene indicated Dorsey had been
attacked and killed by a mountain lion, numerous in that remote
wilderness, and that what was left by the big cat probably was
devoured by coyotes and other scavengers.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsey, of Walnut Creek, Calif., was on a 10-day fishing and
hiking trip when he vanished last month. He was last heard from on
the afternoon of Oct. 10 when he phoned his family from Orvada, a
desert town north of Winnemucca, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsey's abandoned sports utility vehicle was found Monday on an
old off-road trail 11 miles west of the mining town of Midas.
Harris said Dorsey's sleeping bag was still rolled and food in the
car was spoiled, indicating that he probably was attacked and
killed a day or two after his phone call.
</P>
<P>
   Shredded clothing and other personal items were found about 300
yards from Dorsey's car, Harris said, adding that the evidence
pointed to a mountain lion attack rather than a human one.
</P>
<P>
   The skull was discovered by deputies not far away from that
spot, the sheriff said. The skull and other effects were being sent
to California for identification.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said he knew of no other incident of a human being killed
by a mountain lion in his 28 years in law enforcement in Elko
County, the fifth largest and one of the most remote counties in
the nation. He said the rugged canyon and high desert country, a
mecca for wild game hunters, is abundantly populated by mountain
lions, bears and other predators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
