<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QB DILEMMA PUTS PARCELLS AT A LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ He has searched endlessly for a quarterback
to replace Vinny Testaverde, who ruptured an Achilles' tendon on
opening day vs. the Patriots, shattering a promising season for the
Jets. Yet the search in his mind is short when coach Bill Parcells
is asked to identify the best quarterback in the league right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Performance-wise this year you'd have to put him right at the
top,'' said Parcells of Drew Bledsoe. ``I don't see anyone playing
better right now. You look at Drew and Peyton Manning, and I think
those other guys quickly come to mind for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Since that horrible 30-28 loss to New England, Parcells has been
trying to solve his quarterback riddle. He has been heavily
criticized in New York and nationally for not addressing the backup
quarterback issue after he had traded Glenn Foley to Seattle for a
draft pick. But Parcells didn't feel he could keep a $2
million-plus backup, given the Jets' salary cap woes. So he took a
chance. He brought in Scott Zolak, then cut him in camp. He decided
to risk that Tom Tupa would be an adequate backup and Ray Lucas
could emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Then he made his annual deal with Green Bay general manager Ron
Wolf, who sold him on Rick Mirer, the player Parcells almost took
ahead of Bledsoe in the '93 draft.
</P>
<P>
   When Testaverde went down, Parcells went from Tupa to Mirer, to
Lucas, back to Mirer, and now back to Lucas. Mirer went 2-4 during
his reign, but the Jets weren't scoring points. Mirer seemed
tentative, unable to get the ball to open receivers. The Mirer move
was made even though he led the team to a 12-7 win over Arizona
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the games we've been involved with have been undecided
in the very late portion of the game,'' said Parcells. ``All but
one went down to the last 3-4 minutes to determine the winner. You
always look at yourself and say `gee whiz, if we hadn't done this
or that.' But mostly we've lost because we haven't been able to
score enough points. Our turnover ratio is still on the plus side;
we don't have an inordinate imbalance in turnovers and takeaways
that you would have when you're losing. We're not highly penalized
although we've had a couple of critical penalties. We're not giving
the games away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most specifically, we haven't been able to execute well in the
passing game to create enough opportunity to win the game,''
Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   So Lucas is the man. Most Patriots were surprised Parcells named
him the starter so early in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an effort to try to maybe score more points,'' he
said. ``We've been in the same pattern since Vinny got hurt. We
averaged 26 points a game last year and now we're down 11 points a
game to 15. You just can't win. You're not doing enough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells knows he's taking a risk with Lucas, who is raw and
unproven. He figures Lucas may make more mistakes than Mirer, but
he may take more chances to win games, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to try and find that output,'' he said. ``Because on
the present course we're not scoring enough to win. so I think the
risk is worth it. If it doesn't work, I'm no worse off.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells does have a great running game. Curtis Martin has
strung together three consecutive 100-yard games when teams have
known the Jets are going to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need much better balance,'' said Parcells. ``We need a
couple of big plays in the passing game. New England is a team that
can go on and maybe something doesn't happen for a while, but they
have the ability to make big plays in the passing game. Drew is
playing well, and the receivers he has, they can generate points by
doing that. That's where we're having a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   With his predicament, Parcells understands that it has become a
quarterback-driven league, though he sites examples of teams that
emphasize other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think its happening in Miami,'' he said. ``There are a
couple of teams _ Jacksonville, really, if they were in the AFC
East, they would be more like Miami than New England. To me
offensively, they're not quite on par with other teams but their
defense is strong, and they do have a good running game. That's two
examples of teams in the AFC that kind of get away from that
quarterback high-powered offense theory, and they have the chance
to be in it at end. As does New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is a quarterback-driven league. In the end it will
prove to be true. In the end you're going to face somebody you have
to score on to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells does not call this the most frustrating team he's
coached; that honor belongs to the Giants (3-12) of 1983, the first
year he coached in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've (the Jets' players) been receptive. They're working
pretty hard. We haven't always played well. I haven't had any
discipline problems or off-the-field stuff that accompanies losing
records. I wouldn't say it's frustrating, but I had a good team
coming out of training camp. It goes to show how fragile and
humbling this game can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to comment on Ben Coates's outburst, Parcells said, ``I
don't have any reaction to it because I don't know what the deal
is. He was really a developmental guy at the time. He came along so
quickly. He's blossomed into the best tight end that's ever played.
That tight end position, the fullback position where Sam Gash
played and still plays in Buffalo, and strong safety where Lawyer's
(Milloy) playing now _ the wear and tear on those three positions
is so different than any other position in football. Very seldom
are those guys out of the game. It's a high ratio of collisions.
That's the way Lawyer plays the strong safety position.''
</P>
<P>
   He will not commit to his coaching future with the Jets. There
are many factors involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't changed my view,'' he said. ``At the end of the year
I'll (evaluate). You hate to leave losing, but if I felt it was
time, it wouldn't have anything to do with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
