<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTVILLE WEIGHS IN ON UPCOMING FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who is better than Sports Illustrated's Leigh Montville?
</P>
<P>
   His ``Viewpoint'' segment on CNN/SI is one of the best
commentaries on television.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Montville, a former Boston Globe sports columnist,
has to say about the upcoming Holyfield-Lewis fight. ``Which
officials or promoters will be indicted? Who will be sued? Whose
purse will be held up by the Nevada State Athletic Commission? Will
Jim Gray be around, making a nuisance of himself? Ah, there's
nothing like a good heavyweight championship fight these days.
Outside of maybe a good bass-fishing tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Montville's colleague at CNN/SI, Nick Charles, said that Lewis
and Holyfield must deliver in the ring in order to restore a
modicum of respectability to the sport. ``It's amazing,'' Charles
said. ``Boxing keeps trying to kill itself, yet it won't die.
People are disgusted with what has happened in past fights. I still
think people will tune in and watch, but I do think it will be a
lower number. People are reluctant.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sox rights still in limbo &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations for the Red Sox television rights are inching
along. The major problem is that none of the potential television
carriers are prepared to lose millions of dollars on an inflated
product.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are looking for at least $10.5 million in rights
fees, but the local television stations simply can't afford it,
especially considering the added $3 million in production and
talent costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd really like to make it work but we are in no position to
lose money,'' said Channel 38's Lee Kinberg, director of
programming.
</P>
<P>
   No one else is, either.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe Barry Diller. The media mogul wants to establish his
brand of local programming in Boston. He already owns Channel 66,
better known for its shopping programming than local news and
sports. Diller's strategy in Miami has been to obtain a sports
package and wrap local programming around it.
</P>
<P>
   Diller tied to acquire the Red Sox rights last year but the deal
fell through.
</P>
<P>
   In Diller's case, it might make sense to lose money in order to
gain name recognition by airing Red Sox games.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox brass like those kinds of people.
</P>
<P>
   They like them even better if they have guaranteed letters of
credit from a reputable bank.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
EPSN ratings through roof &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPN ratings are up so far this NFL season. Among the increases
is ``NFL Primetime,'' up 17 percent in viewership, from 2.853
million homes to 3.339 million, and 14 percent in ratings, from
3.80 to 4.34.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's ``Sunday Night Football'' is averaging 6,401,066 homes
and an 8.32 rating, increases of 14 percent and 11 percent,
respectively, over this point last season. Last Sunday's telecast
of the Tennessee Titans at Miami Dolphins earned a 9.0 rating,
ESPN's fourth highest of the season. And last Saturday's Notre
Dame-Tennessee game on ESPN was the highest-rated and most-watched
college telecast (4.7 rating and 3.63 million homes) in two years.
</P>
<P>
   The big news from ESPN, however, is the phenomenal growth of its
on-line service. ESPN Internet Ventures registered more than 1.3
billion page views in October, a 236 percent increase over October
1998 and the first time any Internet sports entity attracted more
than a billion page views. The ESPN sites averaged 32 million page
views per day during the week of Oct. 17-23.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ironmen compete &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NBC airs the 1999 Ironman Triathlon World Championship Nov. 14
at 4 p.m. Al Trautwig and Mark Allen call the two-hour tape-delay
broadcast. Among the contestants are Dick and Rick Hoyt. Rick, 37,
has cerebral palsy and gets assistance from his 59-year-old father.
The elder Hoyt pulls his son in a boat for the 2.4-mile swim,
attaches a cart to the front of his bike for the 112-mile ride, and
pushes him in a special chair for the 26.2-mile marathon. This year
marked the Hoyts' 19th consecutive Boston Marathon appearance.
Another athlete is Kathleen Kinz-Smith, a 37-year-old mother of
five. And Boston's Karen Smyers finished second in 9:20:40.
Contestants have 17 hours to complete the course.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
