<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN YELLOW PINE GAINS IN USE, STILL HARD TO FIND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, November 14, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am restoring the woodwork in my two-family house built in
1925. The woodwork is good looking, but some of it needs replacing,
and it has a nice dark orangey finish and color. Someone told me it
is hard pine (Southern yellow pine). Where can I find it? The big
lumber stores look at me as if I was nuts.
</P>
<P>
   FRANK CONNORS, Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Nuts you are not. Some of those stores just don't want to be
bothered. Yes, that is Southern yellow pine; it was used in the
early part of the waning century, and earlier, but lost favor when
white pine and other kinds of pine were marketed. In fact, I was
doing an interview last week at the Fisher School (circa 1845) in
Westwood, and my goodness, the floors were Southern yellow pine,
and new pieces were used to fill in.
</P>
<P>
   It is available; in fact there is a heavy revival of Southern
yellow pine, pushed by the lumbermen who are harvesting it.
</P>
<P>
   Lumber stores that carry hardwoods and exotic woods also may
carry Southern yellow pine, even though it is called hard, it is
not classed as a hardwood: Rooney, Somerville, 617-666-4030.
Leonard Lumber Co., Branford, Conn., 269-2626, 269-2775.
Henderson's Hardwoods, King St., Hanson, Mass.; Cambridge Lumber &AMP;
Supply, 617-876-4460.
</P>
<P>
   Also, you could call the Southern Pine Council to find out where
it is sold locally: Kenner, La., 504-443-4464, or Forest Park, Ga.,
404-361-1445.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I found some very old liquid in a can, although I could not
open the can that has a ``push down and twist'' cap. It is called
Ditzler alkyd enamel reducer, made for automotive finishes. What is
it, and is there any use I could put to it? Or should I recycle it?
</P>
<P>
   BARBARA CHOLAKOS, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It sounds like a fancy word for paint thinner, a thinner for
an oil-based (alkyd) enamel. Since it is for automotive enamels, it
might be lacquer thinner, which is extremely volatile and difficult
to use safely. At any rate, since we don't know for sure what it is
(``reducer'' is as vague or generalized a word as sealer or
thinner), and since it is old, I suggest you take it to the next
hazardous waste collection.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My cedar fence is three or four years old, is gray and looks
lovely. My husband feels it should be sealed. Is that really
necessary?
</P>
<P>
   C. M., Milton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Not at all. Many people, including your husband, have been
brainwashed or propagandized by manufacturers who say that outdoor
wood that is not painted should or must be sealed to make it water
resistant, so water will bead up on it instead of soaking in (to
rot the wood). Their admonitions (with the threat of decay and
other disasters) apply to any kind of wood, even pressure-treated
wood, in any application (vertical or horizontal). They don't tell
you that these sealers must be reapplied once a year. They don't
tell you that semitransparent stain will work better and will last
for three to five years. They don't tell you that it is not
necessary in many cases.
</P>
<P>
   They do have a point in some cases, such as with
pressure-treated deck floor boards; sealing them will help prevent
their warping, spalling, splitting, and splintering.
</P>
<P>
   As for your fence, it is white cedar, has already weathered to
the gray color you so admire, and will continue to weather without
ill effect or treatment of any kind. If this fence gets wet and
dries out between wettings, it will last indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   You and your husband can do more interesting things than spend
money on sealing something that does not need sealing.
</P>
<P>
   And don't let anyone tell you that sealing the cedar will help
reduce mold and algae from growing on it. It won't. The handyman's
white cedar high picket fence is many years old, untreated, and is
a nice, weathered, silver color. It does have some black (mold) and
green (algae) stains, but they can be treated with bleach and
water, when the handyman gets around to it. One thing about mold
and algae: They should be killed and removed occasionally with the
bleach and water solution because left on wood, they can cause the
wood to decay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Help! My concrete-block foundation has developed pebble-itis,
the pebbles in the blocks showing more than they should. How can I
cover the pebbles and smooth out the concrete?
</P>
<P>
   M. B., Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. To cure the pebble-itis, which is caused by water running
down the face of the blocks, try this: Apply a bonding agent to the
existing blocks and then apply a thin layer of mortar. It is called
parging, and should help a lot, but the bonding agent is essential
to prevent that thin coat of mortar from sloughing off.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative is this (it will not cover the pebbles but will
make the concrete more resistant to water and erosion): Apply a
coat of cement-based paint (no other paint will do). This is a
powder that is mixed with water and brushed onto the concrete with
a heavy brush.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
