<HEADLINE>
`MARY' WON'T OFFEND, BUT IT WON'T INSPIRE, EITHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
MARY, MOTHER OF JESUS 
Starring: Pernilla August, Christian Bale, Geraldine Chaplin 
Directed by: Kevin Connor 
On: NBC 
Time: Sunday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of the ads for ``Mary, Mother of Jesus'' use a cover
version of the Beatles' ``Let It Be'' for their soundtrack. It's
perfect: ``When I find myself in times of trouble, Mother Mary
comes to me, speaking words of wisdom . . .''
</P>
<P>
   And you can bet NBC executives were pleased that it was the
honorable Sir Paul McCartney who paid homage to the Blessed Virgin
Mother, and not John Lennon, the fiesty bloke who once said about
his band, ``We're more popular than Jesus now; I don't know which
will go first _ rock 'n' roll or Christianity.'' Because this
made-for-TV movie is in no way an attempt to rock the Old Testament
with desert-chic hair styles, or to challenge our understanding of
the story of Christ with revisionist assertions. ``Mary, Mother of
Jesus,'' which airs Sunday, is a safe, reverential portrait of the
most worshiped woman of all time, a movie created solely to
celebrate the role she played in her son's life, death, and
resurrection. ``Everything he is, you made him,'' a dying Joseph
says to Mary, articulating the not-so-subtle gist of the project.
It's cynicism-free TV, and it plays more like Sunday-morning
religious programming than most of what airs in prime time these
days.
</P>
<P>
   The smartest decision by the ``Mary'' filmmakers, including
executive producers Eunice Kennedy Shriver and her son, Bobby
Shriver, was to keep ``Mary'' from becoming a star vehicle. You
know, Cher is Mary. As their lead, they chose Swedish actress
Pernilla August, best known in the States as Anakin Skywalker's
mother in ``The Phantom Menace.'' August is terrifically stoic and
dignified throughout, glowing with pride and faith in her son even
when he briefly turns his back on her. And she is equally able to
convey profound grief during the scenes when she must watch him
die. The filmmakers also wisely opt for a plain, earthy-looking
production, without any of the slickness and special effects
overkill that are so identified with today's sweeps TV-movie
events.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Mary'' fails as drama on a number of important counts, and
I can't recommend it for those seeking anything more than a sketchy
religious primer. For one thing, the script is stilted and
overflowing with cliches, from the opening ``The Romans are coming,
the Romans are coming'' to Mary's pledge, once Herod has the baby
boys in Bethlehem murdered, that, ``As long as I have breath in my
body, God help me, this child shall live.'' Such lines are meant to
sound authentically biblical, but they are bland and stiff, and
they are awkwardly interrupted by contemporary turns of phrase like
``Why are you always so stuck-up and superior?'' The script doesn't
endow the familiar sacred story, or Jesus himself, with much
complexity or vitality.
</P>
<P>
   The pacing of ``Mary'' is also off, particularly in the latter
half, when the movie should get a speeding ticket for rushing
through Jesus's adult career and crucifixion in under an hour. To
meet its epic ambition of portraying two major figures, the movie
probably needed more than two commercial-heavy TV hours to be
anything more than superficial. They wouldn't have improved the
dialogue, but another two hours might have allowed time to pursue
the bond between Mary and Mary Magdalene, for instance, which is
repeatedly suggested but never explored.
</P>
<P>
   We can only hope the networks' religious fervor (``Noah's Ark''
and ``Joan of Arc'' were ratings hits) will provide us with a more
dynamic interpretation of the Bible next spring. CBS airs its
``Jesus'' in May, and ABC brings us ``The Miracle Maker'' in April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
