<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FINDING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FINDING NORTH' GETS LOST ALONG THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
FINDING NORTH 
Directed by: Tanya Wexler 
Written by: Kim Powers 
Starring: Wendy Makkena and John Benjamin Hickey 
Running time: 95 minutes 
Rating: Unrated 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Finding North'' opens with a forlorn young man, Travis Furlong
(John Benjamin Hickey), naked, perched on the edge of a bridge in
New York, looking longingly into the river, and Rhonda Portelli
(Wendy Makkena) stuck in traffic behind all the commotion. They
don't meet that night _ though she recovers a shoe he left behind
(hello, Cinderella) _ but rest assured, they will. It's not giving
away too much to say that Furlong does not jump, and it's probably
not going to be the biggest shocker of the day to surmise they will
have nothing in common. He's gay but despondent; his lover has just
died from AIDS, and he wants nothing more than to join him in the
endless sleep. She's straight, 30, a bank teller, living in
Brooklyn with her Jewish-Italian parents, being nagged to death for
a lack of husband and other perceived failures.
</P>
<P>
   And so, the stage is set for yet another UBM _ Unlikely Buddy
Movie. They bicker and they bond, bit by bit, and then they bicker
again and they bond a little more and then . . .
</P>
<P>
   Travis and Rhonda have two semi-humorous close encounters
post-bridge before they finally connect. He can't figure out for
the life of him what she wants to do with him, being suicidal, gay
and all. She accepts the gay part, but not the suicidal part. Her
life having bottomed out at the bank, she joins him on a trip
through rural Texas. It seems Travis's dead lover, Bobby Sullivan,
has mailed him an audio tape that arrives posthumously. Bobby says
that in lieu of the joint trip they were going to take to Bobby's
hometown, he should go it alone and discover his roots. Also, he
implies, there's a mission involved, a scavenger hunt of sorts.
This puts a crimp in Travis's suicide plans, but he figures he'll
do it later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding North'' does have a certain sweetness about it, traces
of knowing dark humor. Some of the situations bring a smile. But
Travis's journey through Bobby's boyhood moves at a snail's pace
and director Tanya Wexler's frequent cuts to Rhonda's parents on
the couch watching TV may drive you as crazy as they drive Rhonda.
This film's semi-edge dissipates as it nears the inevitable climax.
``Finding North,'' by the way, was Bobby's expression for when
things have gone so far to south, a.k.a. hell, all one can do is
try and find north. Which is fair enough, but by the end we don't
care at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
