<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASS TOURNEY KEEPS AT LEAST ONE RIVETED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I &UR;  &LR; guess maybe it's just not a New England thing.
</P>
<P>
   See, there I was last Sunday afternoon, sitting on my couch,
beverage within reach, all atwitter with expectation. In fact, I
was a bundle of nerves.
</P>
<P>
   Could the Fox network really pull it off? Televise the first
live bass fishing tournament in TV history and make it interesting?
</P>
<P>
   I had asked several of my friends if they wanted to watch it
with me, friends with whom I have watched baseball and football,
friends with whom I have sailed and fished and shot ducks.
</P>
<P>
   They were all busy.
</P>
<P>
   One said he was going fishing. One said he was going hunting.
One said he had to go to a neighborhood lawn tractor rodeo for a
Very Worthy Charity.
</P>
<P>
   Another said he had his Waylon Jennings albums all mixed up with
Jerry Jeff Walker, and he had put aside the time last Sunday to
sort them out.
</P>
<P>
   So I was going through my butterfly time leading up to the
beginning of the M1 Millennium Fishing Tournament all alone. Just
me, my beverage, and my Maine Coon cat, Pink Floyd, dozing beside
me.
</P>
<P>
   So why all the nerves? Well, when the sports beat you have
covered for decades as an outdoor writer finally breaks into the
big time, you can't avoid feeling a bit responsible for what folks
are about to see, and the impression big-time televised fishing
makes on them.
</P>
<P>
   After all, when you talk up fishing for so many years you're
preaching to the converted. But now, right there, on one of the
major networks, a live fishing tournament . . . What would happen?
</P>
<P>
   Now, on one channel Tiger Woods was making golf history, and on
another the Lions and Rams were locked up in a potboiler. Brian
Boitano and a cast of former skating greats were swirling on
another, and there was a NASCAR race on.
</P>
<P>
   So how many people would be left to watch the fishing derby
anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, everyone just surfing channels has come across those
canned fishing shows at some point on a Saturday morning. But Fox
had something far different in mind. Teaming up with Operation Bass
at Cyprus Gardens, Fla., this show required a cast of hundreds and
a production investment of half a million bucks _ about what it
costs to televise an NFL game.
</P>
<P>
   And then it was on, complete with an anchor desk high over the
Cyprus Gardens lakes _ where all the championship waterskiing is
filmed _ and a team of fishing broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, two of them were baseball broadcasters, Joe Buck and
Bob Brenley. The guest analyst was Forrest Wood, founder of Ranger
Boats, which, festooned in advertising logos, zipped around those
lakes at about 70 miles per hour. It would seem with a
250-horsepower power plant screaming across the water, any fish
within 2 miles would have figured it was the end of the world and
made a suicidal leap onto the shore.
</P>
<P>
   (Note to self: Find out why those anglers need to go so fast,
anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   Like a golf tournament, the fishing was to feature 10 anglers
who would be shown fishing live, with tapes of their earlier
catches that day woven throughout the presentation.
</P>
<P>
   In their utter determination not to let the show drag,
Intrasport, which produced the show for Fox, went a bit the other
way.
</P>
<P>
   With live shots, taped shots, one angler after another with bio
spots, and at least one angler appearing on a recurring commercial,
it became increasingly difficult to sort things out.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter, if you got a little confused in places, you'd
then see a shot of one of those high-powered Rangers flying over
the lake, and you knew what that was about _ an image aimed right
at the 12-year-old in all of us.
</P>
<P>
   The finale, which had been touted all day, got a little frantic.
After all the anglers sped to the weigh-in center, each one was
called to the podium with a shopping bag full of fish.
</P>
<P>
   (Note to self: Find out how, if the anglers were spread out over
five lakes, they all roared into the same weigh-in center and
parked their Rangers in that round dock.)
</P>
<P>
   It was like the game of blackjack when you keep one card face
down until the money's on the table, then turn it over.
</P>
<P>
   Each angler held one last fish in the bag (immersed so as not to
kill the fish), and his last act of the day was to pull the last
fish out of the bag and put it on the scale.
</P>
<P>
   Which was a spectacle in itself. The emcee would put the
flapping fish in a box on the scale, then jam a plastic top down to
keep it still. This created a remarkable flashback to the Dan
Akroyd Bassamatic skit on ``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Darrell Robertson from Jay, Okla., pulled out the
winning fish and picked up a check for $600,000, part of a $3.6
million purse, the largest in fishing history.
</P>
<P>
   Well, again, it just isn't a New England sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   Here, where fishing is about cool bubbling streams and canoes,
or about turning off the motor and drifting saltwater flies through
a rip, the pro bass scene just doesn't satisfy that thirst for
kicking back in the wilderness and watching the summer clouds drift
by.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament fishing in New England is about a place to bring one
good catch, meet with fellow anglers, drink beer, and tell lies.
The secrecy about hot spots along the surf is a matter of stealth
and stillness.
</P>
<P>
   But while New England anglers may have been a bit nonplussed by
a bass derby in Florida, when I next got to the office, all the
editors and sportswriters who regularly cover _ ah _ mainstream
sports were going wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, was that cool!'' one of them said. ``I love how they
pulled out those fish (at the weigh-in).''
</P>
<P>
   Said another: ``That guy (Robertson) was fishing in pain. He had
just passed a kidney stone the day before. Amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   And a Globe columnist was on the verge of writing an angry
commentary on the fact that if all the anglers were on five
different lakes, the playing field was inconsistent. He was
steamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``And those killer boats,'' said another, ``and those bags of
fish hiding what was coming next . . . that was way cool.''
</P>
<P>
   (Note to self: Better find out what happened during the 15
minutes you switched channels to watch that Lions drive.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain writes about the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
