<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7584 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-THOREAU-SCHOLAR-ART-B     11-12 1374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOREAU-SCHOLAR-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WILD FRUITS' COMES TO LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Mass. _ Bradley Dean was a ``beer swilling surfer''
struggling through high school when he first read a book by Henry
David Thoreau: the Cliff Notes version of ``Walden.'' He only got
serious about the famed naturalist and social critic when the Navy
threw him in the brig for refusing a haircut in 1974, and he took
solace in Thoreau's acid attacks on arbitrary authority.
</P>
<P>
   Now, this unlikely Thoreau scholar has done what once was
considered almost impossible: produced a ``new'' book by the great
Transcendentalist. By deciphering Thoreau's crimped handwriting and
reorganizing the jumbled manuscript, Dean has resurrected ``Wild
Fruits,'' the ambitious book Thoreau was working on when he died of
tuberculosis in 1862.
</P>
<P>
   The book _ a scientific yet almost religious look at the nuts
and berries in Thoreau's Concord _ puts Dean at the center of a
seismic shift in the way scholars view Thoreau, once regarded as a
man whose career declined after ``Walden'' was published in 1854.
Thoreau's real problem, says Dean, is that he died at 44 before he
could finish the project of which ``Wild Fruits'' is part.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to kind of revolutionize Thoreau studies because
it presents a guy who was not only being creative throughout his
life, but also a guy who had an almost unbelievable ambition,''
said Dean, resident scholar at the Thoreau Institute supported by
rock star Don Henley.
</P>
<P>
   The book, the second Thoreau manuscript that Dean has prepared
for publication since 1993, cements his rise from the Navy brig to
the Tudor mansion near Walden Pond where the Thoreau Institute
resides. The first book, ``Faith in a Seed,'' was widely praised by
reviewers, but the less technical ``Wild Fruits'' is expected to
reach a broader audience.
</P>
<P>
   Though Dean's doctorate is in American literature, his
contribution seems more like detective work, including a rare
ability to reconstruct the order of Thoreau's notes using
indicators as subtle as the pattern of tear marks made by Thoreau's
push pins.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a completely obsessive personality that works extremely
well in this field,'' said Ronald Hoag, a Thoreau scholar at East
Carolina University in North Carolina, where Dean formerly taught.
</P>
<P>
   Early reviewers say ``Wild Fruits'' compares with Thoreau's best
work in passages, such as his account of cranberry picking, in
which he argues that God resides in the commonplace. ``It would
imply the regeneration of mankind if they were to become elevated
enough to truly worship sticks and stones,'' he writes. ``If I
could, I would worship the parings of my nails.''
</P>
<P>
   However, in the hothouse world of analyzing an American icon
like Thoreau, Dean faces criticism, too. Leo Marx, a prominent
Thoreau scholar at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology,
argues that Dean's resurrection of Thoreau manuscripts is a veiled
attempt to advance radical environmentalism.
</P>
<P>
   In the New York Review of Books last summer, Marx writes that
``Faith in a Seed'' offers little that is new, except to organize
previously known writing into an attack on human domination of the
environment, which Marx calls ``ecocentrism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a significant work not so much for any literary merit it
may have (slight, in my opinion) as for the light it throws on the
current effort to re-evaluate Thoreau's work from an ecocentric
point of view,'' writes Marx.
</P>
<P>
   But others, such as Thoreau biographer Robert D. Richardson Jr.,
believe the new books showcase Thoreau as a great scientist, in
addition to his more recognized gifts, showing that, in the last
years of his life, Thoreau anticipated Charles Darwin's theory of
evolution as well as modern ecology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thoreau has become a much bigger subject in the history of
science'' in part because of Dean's work, said Richardson. ``Forty
years ago, scientists would sort of snicker about him as a
naturalist,'' but now they take his findings more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is the legacy of a man whose sharply observed, clever
writings have inspired people across a remarkable range of
endeavors from civil rights leaders such as Martin Luther King Jr.
to Depression Era labor activists to modern environmentalists such
as Rachel Carson.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Thoreau's reputation rested heavily on two
books, ``Walden'' and ``Civil Disobedience,'' both drawn from
experiences in the 1840s. ``Walden,'' an account of living alone at
the edge of a Concord pond for two years, set out Thoreau's rules
for good living, including healthy doses of nature as well as
moralizing. ``Civil Disobedience,'' based on Thoreau's one-night
jailing for refusing to pay a tax on voting, argues that, if a law
is unjust, ``then, I say, break the law.''
</P>
<P>
   After 1850, however, Thoreau's writing began to change, becoming
increasingly scientific and focusing on ecological processes such
as the way forests grow back over untended meadows or the minutiae
of the change of seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people dismiss the final years of Thoreau as his turn
toward science and his dropping of weighty philosophical thought,
whereas Brad (Dean) and other people argue there's a lot more
there,'' said David Foster, author of ``Thoreau's Country,'' which
relies heavily on the later writings to describe the mid-19th
century landscape.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the last 25 years have been preparing Dean to make
his case for Thoreau. Dean's reading of Thoreau while in the Navy _
both in and out of the brig _ transformed him from an indifferent
student and sometime troublemaker to a Thoreau disciple, including
a 900-page masters thesis on ``Life Without Principle,'' a Thoreau
essay he had quoted at his court-martial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owed Thoreau a big one,'' said Dean, 45, and still something
of a rebel with his ponytail and Harley-Davidson motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   Dean believes Thoreau, if anything, improved as a thinker after
``Walden,'' undertaking a massive course of science reading and
field observations in Concord. After exalting nature as an ideal,
Thoreau was trying to understand how nature worked at a level of
detail few had even imagined, Dean said.
</P>
<P>
   But a key part of Dean's proof, the ``Wild Fruits'' manuscript,
was in such bad shape that other scholars had given up on it.
</P>
<P>
   Though the dying Thoreau had neatly bundled up the 600-page
manuscript, over the generations, the pages were shuffled
completely out of order, winding up in the Berg Collection of the
New York Public Library in the 1940s. There it sat, known to
scholars but hardly mentioned in biographies such as Richardson's
``Henry Thoreau: A Life of the Mind'' in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, Dean _ so obsessive that he still has the Cliff
Notes of Walden he read as a teenager _ was the right candidate for
the restoration. Immersing himself in Thoreau's writing, reading
the books Thoreau read, wandering the places Thoreau went, living
at the institute, Dean slowly put the manuscript back to the way
the dying Thoreau left it.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a single-volume fragment of what Dean believes was
intended as perhaps a four or five volume set. Some of the 181
different fruits described receive little more than a sentence, and
perhaps half the material had been published in other forms before
by other editors, but the book's organization casts even published
material as part of a larger scheme.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to scientific observations, Dean sees a less dour,
less judgmental Thoreau, more eager to celebrate nature in ``Wild
Fruits'' than in earlier works. ``If you read ``Walden,'' you come
across this austere, somewhat intimidating guy that preaches at
you. You don't like him a lot,'' said Dean. ``In a sense, it is a
more humble man you encounter here.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dean's view, Thoreau had found his way at the end, not lost
it, as critics once believed. As Thoreau wrote in a letter just six
weeks before he died: ``If I were to live, I should have much to
report on Natural History generally.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
