<HEADLINE>
BCS POLL PROCESS NEEDS OVERHAUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The numbers were released on Monday afternoon. No. 1 in the Bowl
Championship Series rankings? Florida State. No surprise there. The
Seminoles were unbeaten, untied, and had not played a game the
previous week.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2? Tennessee. No. 3? Virginia Tech. Excuse me. Tech had not
lost a game, Tennessee had. Tech had won on Saturday, albeit a
last-second win over lightly regarded West Virginia. Tennessee had
won at home, rolling over Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   So the numbers came up and leapfrogged the Volunteers over the
Hokies. Explanation? Strength of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's was tougher, much tougher, said the computers.
</P>
<P>
   So what do we have? A controversy. An embarrassment? A bad
system?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is D. None of the above.
</P>
<P>
   There is no controversy because right now the numbers are for
entertainment purposes only. No one has been hurt, no one has been
shut out of playing in the BCS title game in the Sugar Bowl in New
Orleans Jan. 4. It's clearly a no-harm, no-foul situation _ right
now.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassment? Sorry. In a weekly poll situation, Florida State
and Tennessee are probably the two best teams in the country right
now.
</P>
<P>
   A bad system? Not really. It's better than it was, but not as
good as it should be.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something that needs to be corrected, sooner rather
than later.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are gathered by the Southeastern Conference office,
which compiles the data and releases the weekly poll.
</P>
<P>
   The people in the BCS say this is no big deal. SEC commissioner
and BCS chairman Roy Kramer and his staff are merely dispensers of
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a problem with it,'' said Big Ten commissioner
Jim Delany, whose league is part of the BCS arrangement. ``And I
don't think anyone else involved with this does, either. It's just
numbers. There's nothing subjective about it.''
</P>
<P>
   And we're not going to question the integrity of Mr. Kramer, who
jokingly has said he has been blamed for everything from El Nino to
the rise and fall of the Dow Jones average in the past year the SEC
office has been handling the poll.
</P>
<P>
   But what is wrong with this picture?
</P>
<P>
   There is more than a good possibility that the BCS title game
could be a rematch of Tennessee-Florida.
</P>
<P>
   For that to happen, Tennessee must win its final three
regular-season games, Florida must beat Florida State at home and
win the SEC title game, Miami or BC must beat Virginia Tech at
home, and Nebraska must beat Kansas State at home.
</P>
<P>
   None of those _ maybe BC beating Tech _ is a totally
off-the-wall possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems obvious that the commissioner of the SEC can't be
announcing numbers that could put two of his teams _ for a payout
of approximately $18 million _ into the championship game.
</P>
<P>
   How difficult would it be to have some accounting firm in a
place like New York, where they don't really care about college
football, handle the administration of the BCS poll each week?
</P>
<P>
   Delany and Kramer argue that there is no problem because it is
strictly a bookkeeping arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   But those numbers come from somewhere. They come from computers,
which are programmed by people who tell the computers what numbers
are important and what numbers aren't.
</P>
<P>
   They come from formulas created by people who tell the computers
that Tennessee beating Notre Dame by 24 points is better than
Tennessee beating Notre Dame by 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   And what isn't being said very much by anyone is that contrary
to the public stance (that No. 1 should meet No. 2), they are all
better served when that does not happen.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this. A championship game between unbeaten Kansas State
and unbeaten Virginia Tech, or a championship game between
once-beaten Florida and once-beaten Tennessee in the Sugar Bowl, a
match between once-beaten Florida State and unbeaten Virginia Tech
in the Orange Bowl, and unbeaten Kansas State and twice-beaten
Wisconsin in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Which would create more controversy?
</P>
<P>
   Instead of interest in one game, you would create interest in
three BCS games. If Kansas State and Tech each won their games, you
would have controversy because both unbeaten teams would claim a
right to the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, which has all the BCS games, would love it. Ratings would
increase and everyone would make money.
</P>
<P>
   But that's another issue, for another time. Right now, we're in
the preliminary stages of what could be a huge mess.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are this all will work itself out with the next few
weeks of games.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing seems apparent. If the BCS rankings _ which now
have supplanted the AP and USA Today coaches poll in importance and
relevance _ are going to remain, they need to be distributed by
someone who does not have something to gain by them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Filling the bowls
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston College fans need to be pulling for Pittsburgh to pull
off an upset of Notre Dame in Saturday's game at Pitt Stadium,
which will also be the last game played in that historic venue.
Here's why. Right now, the Big East has four guaranteed bowl slots:
BCS Bowl, Gator Bowl, Insight.Com Bowl, and Music City Bowl. It has
four teams which either are or should be bowl eligible: Virginia
Tech, Miami, Syracuse, and Boston College. In a perfect world, each
of those teams would be guaranteed a bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Big East made a deal in which Notre Dame could fill any
of the non-BCS Bowl slots in any given season, with some
restrictions. The deal was made because two years ago the Big East
was coming off an 0-4 bowl season and was not in a position of
strength in its negotiations to get commitments from bowls. Adding
Notre Dame enabled the Big East to secure the bowl tie-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame, however, must win two of its final three games to
become eligible. The Irish play Pitt Saturday, BC next week, and
finish with a road game at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating the Irish from bowl consideration would then
guarantee BC a slot even if it loses its remaining three games.
</P>
<P>
   BC, however, can take care of its own destiny with a win over
West Virginia. If the Eagles win that game, they should, at worst,
get one of the slots in the Music City Bowl _ against probably the
winner of the Kentucky-Vanderbilt game. A win in the final two
games of the season _ against Virginia Tech or Notre Dame _ could
send the Eagles to Jacksonville and the Gator Bowl, or Tucson and
the Insight.Com Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a remote possibility that if the Eagles were to
run the table and finish 9-2, they could wind up in the Fiesta
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, however, is that a win over the Mountaineers
will clinch a bowl bid for the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Davis NFL-bound?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if Miami coach Butch Davis becomes the
hottest candidate among college coaches for any NFL openings that
develop. Davis has done a nice job in rebuilding Miami's program
and reputation. But Davis also is in the Tom Coughlin mind-set of a
few years ago. He is frustrated by the restrictions college coaches
face in recruiting, practicing, and everything else and he also
would like to see Miami improve its facilities. With background on
Jimmy Johnson's staff when he was with the Cowboys, Davis has an
NFL pedigree. It would not be outrageous to see the new Houston NFL
franchise make a run at Davis . . . Here's the latest oddity from
the Pac-10. Both Stanford and Arizona, regarded as the
front-runners for the league title at the start of the season,
might not garner enough wins to even qualify for a bowl game, much
less win the title. The Huskies must beat UCLA and Washington State
to get to the Rose Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 1355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7588 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-DIGITAL-LIGHT-ART-BOS     11-12 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-LIGHT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BULBS MERGE TECHNOLOGY, SCIENCE -- ATTRACT INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a world of digital cameras, digital telephones, and
even digital rice cookers, now comes the digital light bulb.
</P>
<P>
   What makes it digital is a tiny chip embedded in the bulb that
lets users generate one of 16.7 million hues at the touch of a
switch.
</P>
<P>
   The bulb is produced by Color Kinetics Inc., a Boston company
founded by two twentysomething entrepreneurs in the spare bedroom
of an apartment in the North End.
</P>
<P>
   Their tinkering seems to have paid off. The bulbs are displayed
in Disney theme parks, Boston Symphony Hall, and numerous retail
stores including Brookstone, Saks Fifth Avenue, and Nine West.
</P>
<P>
   Like moths to light, venture capitalists and other investors
have also been drawn to the company, pouring $12.5 million into the
two-year-old firm thus far.
</P>
<P>
   To them, Color Kinetics represents a new breed of technology
companies that marry old-fashioned technology with the kind of
science normally associated with hip Internet companies that have
lots of hype but little in the way of tangible products, said
George G. Mueller, the company's president and co-founder.
</P>
<P>
   ``What investors like about us is that we're a high-tech company
that has revenues, products, and patents. We're not an Internet
company that sells a hope and a prayer but has no revenues and
little long-term sustainability,'' said Mueller, a 29-year-old
graduate of Carnegie Mellon University who, ironically, founded a
thriving Internet company with his brother Gary in the mid-1990s.
That company, Internet Securities Inc. _ an economics research firm
the brothers sold 80 percent of in January for $43 million _ was
the subject of a Harvard Business School case study that has become
required reading for legions of budding entrepreneurs in business
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller and his Color Kinetics co-founder, Ihor Lys, are
engineers who met at Carnegie Mellon while working together on a
robotics project. They came up with the idea of a digital light
bulb in 1993, said Lys, who is now 30. The project was put on hold
when Mueller dropped out of graduate school to found Internet
Securities with his brother in Boston. Mueller returned to the
light bulb idea in 1997, and the two entrepreneurs shipped their
first order of lights in September 1998. Though not yet profitable,
the company is expected to record sales of up to $7 million this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The company's offices have since moved out of Mueller's
apartment to new digs in Post Office Square, where the long-haired
entrepreneur gets the occassional odd look when he skateboards to
work. Mueller tries to infuse his company with the kind of
freewheeling culture normally associated with Internet companies.
The dress code is decidedly casual, and the reception area is
furnished with brightly colored bean bag chairs and is decorated
with a cardboard cutout of movie icon Austin Powers. To brainstorm,
Mueller often kicks a soccer ball around the office.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the trendy packaging, the science behind Color Kinetics'
digital lights is actually decades old. Each bulb is made up of
dozens of light emitting diodes, or LEDs, that have long been used
in clocks or as indicator lights on stereos and computers. But up
until the early 1990s, only green and red LEDs were available.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, blue LEDs were discovered, enabling a mixture of red,
green, and blue lights to produce a full spectrum of colors _ about
16.7 million hues, according to Lys, now Color Kinetics' chief
technical officer. Color Kinetics' LED bulbs, manufactured in
Hudson and Mansfield, can last 100,000 hours, as opposed to
traditional incandescent bulbs, which last about 1,000 hours.
Theoretically, an LED bulb can burn continually for 11.4 years.
</P>
<P>
   What Mueller and Lys added to this existing technology was the
ability to manipulate the light. They embedded a microchip in each
bulb and wrote software that allows users to change the color at
whim or program the bulbs to gradually change color over a set time
frame.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the ability to control colored lights is big
business for retailers who are continually searching for ways to
draw shoppers into their stores and keep them there long enough to
buy merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes back to the emotional value of how consumers react to
light,'' said Scott Swaebe, director of visual merchandising of
Brookstone Co. in Nashua. The national retailer is experimenting
with Color Kinetics lights in four prototype stores and is planning
to install the lights in all of its 198 Brookstone stores next
year. ``What's exciting about it is that you have the intrigue of
seeing that sign change color. Those that get it, you leave them
with something they'll remember. It also draws people into the
stores because the lights give them a warmer, more inviting feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Retail lighting is just the beginning, according to a June
report by Jesup &AMP; Lamont Securities Corp. in New York. LED lighting
is poised to take over the $10 billion commercial and residential
lighting market now dominated by halogen and incandescent lights.
</P>
<P>
   Before that happens, however, LED technology has to improve,
wrote Sean Chaitman, author of the Jesup &AMP; Lamont report. ``The
ability for LEDs to replace conventional white lighting will take
time. There are technological limitations, including brightness and
size,'' he wrote. ``Cost is also an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Lys acknowledges those downsides, noting that one of their
bulbs, a two-inch lamp called the iColor, produces just 2.5 watts
and costs $159 a bulb, not including the equipment required to
control the bulb. Lys says, however, he believes the future is
bright for LED technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brightness will get better, and they'll only get more
efficient, which will help bring the prices down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brookstone's Swaebe said while prices are steep for Color
Kinetics' products, it hasn't deterred Brookstone from paying the
premium to distinguish its stores from others around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the mall the other day in one of our stores, and I
saw that no one else had any energy with their signs in terms of
moving color,'' he said. ``We're the first retailer that's going to
have this cool sign that's constantly changing color.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
