<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY FIRING PUTNAM'S CYLINDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Technology can make most things perform better. We'd say that
includes the stock mutual funds at Putnam Investments lately.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Putnam's equity funds, which went through a period of
dull performance after their mid-1990s roar, are making noise again
in a stock market that has rewarded technology companies far above
all others.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam has a few blockbuster performance numbers to crow about
this year, including the 66 percent year-to-date gain in its $5
billion OTC Emerging Growth fund and the 40 percent advance of its
aggressive $2 billion Voyager II fund.
</P>
<P>
   But lots of fund companies have a few ultra-hot funds among
their offerings this year (Fidelity's Aggressive Growth had earned
over 62 percent for 1999 as of mid-week, when stablemate New
Millennium was up 54 percent).
</P>
<P>
   A better measure of Putnam's broad rebound can be found in its
overall performance compared with the nation's other top mutual
fund companies over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam's 29.9 percent asset-weighted return for the year-long
period ended Sept. 30 ranked third among the big 10, according to
Kanon Bloch Carre, a mutual fund consulting firm in Boston.
Putnam's performance ranked eighth among the same group a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Putnam's few dazzling performers there is a cast of solid
funds as well. Two that prefer mid-sized companies have been strong
in 1999 so far: Voyager, which is up more than 26 percent, and
Vista, ahead by 22 percent. Growth Opportunities, which manages a
concentrated portfolio of large stocks, is up by 26 percent so far
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind has been in our sails,'' said John Morgan Jr., a
managing director at Putnam and chief investment officer for its
global core and growth equities. ``But we've used the same
discipline we've always used.''
</P>
<P>
   Others agree Putnam's fund performance has more to do with a
market smiling on its investing strengths in technology and
mid-sized stocks than strategy shifts by its managers. Exhibit A:
the Nasdaq stock index's year-to-date gain of 45.8 percent through
Thursday, more than triple the performance of the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their product is geared toward where the success in the market
has been coming in at least the last year, but mainly the last few
months,'' said William Dougherty, president of Kanon Bloch Carre.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is no doubt Putnam funds have been building more
technology-focused portfolios in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Technology made up 22.2 percent of all Putnam's combined
domestic stock holdings on June 30, according to the Carson Group,
a New York firm that tracks institutional stock holdings. But that
figure soared to 28.9 percent by Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam's tech portfolio had grown by $8.4 billion during the
quarter to a total of $56.7 billion. Financial stocks, the
second-largest investment group in the combined stock portfolios of
Putnam's mutual funds, amounted to $23.8 billion, according to
Carson.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan says part of the tech buildup is due to the appreciation
of stocks Putnam managers already owned and the migration of new
investor money into funds tilted toward technology.
</P>
<P>
   But we found little evidence of new money flooding Putnam's
hottest funds.
</P>
<P>
   The big and less aggressive Putnam Investors fund was the
company's 1999 best seller as of Sept. 30 with net sales of $3.6
billion through the nine months, according to Financial Research
Corp., a Boston investment data firm. Putnam Growth Opportunities
was second with net sales of about $2 billion, according to FRC.
</P>
<P>
   Though Putnam Investors ranks as one of the company's most
conservative growth funds, one third of its portfolio was made up
of technology investments on Sept. 30 (go-go OTC Emerging Growth
counts 59.9 percent of its portfolio as tech).
</P>
<P>
   In a stock market that seems to shower its affection on tech
investors at the expense of everyone else, Putnam certainly has
some funds that didn't make it to the party.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam's giant Growth and Income fund is up about 3.7 percent so
far this year, treading water at roughly the same rate as Putnam
Capital Appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam managers insist a range of performance numbers is part of
the package in their system that assigns different but strict
investment criteria for every fund and then makes managers stay in
their lanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we've done pretty well almost all across the board,''
said Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Good jobs at good wages: The total direct compensation for the
average chief executive of a publicly traded Internet company is a
mere $1.74 million a year, according to a new survey conducted by
PricewaterhouseCoopers. And that's the bad news for the aspiring
dot-com CEOs. That same average Internet company chief owns 12.1
percent of the company, a holding worth $468.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
