<HEADLINE>
SENIOR WORKER MAY WANT TO BUMP UP FIXED-INCOME HOLDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, November 14, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 62 and have recently been downsized. I am beginning to
face the reality that I won't be able to obtain decent employment.
I have decided to try to develop an income stream through
multilevel marketing, but I realize this will take time. I don't
want to apply for Social Security until age 65. My assets consist
of a $430,000 self-directed IRA, a $289,000 taxable trading
account, a $5,000 IRA in Janus Olympic, and $15,000 in cash. The
larger IRA has returned an average 18.3 percent over the past 10
years, and the trading account has averaged 24.09 percent. Both are
dominated by large-cap blue chip common stocks. My expenses are
approximately $40,000 a year after taxes. What changes in this
portfolio do you recommend to maintain the status quo until I reach
age 65?
</P>
<P>
   R.J., Wellesley, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I calculate a total of 26.7 percent of your total portfolio
on the fixed-income side, a figure that counts your preferred
stocks. Another calculation, based on a presumption of 6.5 percent
average returns from the fixed-income side and 2 percent from your
equity accounts, showed a total portfolio yield of $24,025, which
is probably about half of what you would need after paying your
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   You could make monthly withdrawals of $4,000 and stand still for
the next three years if you achieved total portfolio returns of 6.7
percent. In view of the good returns you have managed over the past
decade, that at first seems to be a pretty reasonable target. But
because so much of that growth was the result of capital
appreciation of your stocks, it's not the kind of thing I advise
planning on. I suggest you move about $200,000 from the stock
accounts within your IRA (or perhaps some from the taxable stock
holdings, if there are positions you could liquidate without
unpleasant tax consequences) to fixed-income holdings. This move
would boost your fixed-income position to about 53 percent of the
total portfolio, and increase the portfolio yield to $33,025.
</P>
<P>
   That would still leave you about $15,000 a year short of your
likely requirements. Given the uncertainties of your situation _
primarily that you might or might not realize a significant income
stream from your venture into self-employment _ I think I would
simply leave the balance of the portfolio as it is, withdrawing
money as needed from the tax-deferred stock accounts, calculating
that when your earned income begins coming in, and when Social
Security checks begin arriving, you can restore that element of the
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 26 and have yet to invest for my future. I have zero
debt and about $2,500 in my company's 410(k) plan. That is all I
have as far as investments go, but my employer just went public and
I now have $40,000 in cash from the sale of stock I had been given.
I would like to put that $40,000 somewhere and forget about it for
the next 30 years; I would like to be able to retire at age 56.
What do you suggest I do with the money?
</P>
<P>
   J.O., Jamaica Plain Mass.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion would be that you make your investments by buying
variable annuity accounts, which will allow that 30-year
accumulation to occur on a tax-deferred basis. To do this within
the tax regulations, variable annuity accounts must include a very
small amount of insurance, which takes a tiny bite out of the
investment performance, but this is usually in the range of 1/2 of
1 percent a year, which in my view is a small price to pay for the
tax deferral.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest you put most of the money in a portfolio of Vanguard's
variable annuity accounts, with 60 percent in the Equity Index
account, which tracks the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, and 20 percent
each in Vanguards Mid-Cap Index and Small Company variable
annuities.
</P>
<P>
   Why did I say put most of the money in variable annuity
accounts? Because there's an even more attractive investment
vehicle open to you, which is the Roth IRA. So I would hold $4,000
of the money aside, putting $2,000 of it in a Roth IRA for the tax
year 1999, and, after the start of the year, sending the remaining
$2,000 in as a Roth contribution for the year 2000. In both cases,
I'd just put it in the Vanguard Index 500. With the Roth IRA, the
money, and all of your investment returns, will be tax-free upon
withdrawal after age 59 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   If you achieved average annual returns of 10 percent from these
accounts over 30 years, the accumulation would be $697,976. This
represents a very nice start on a retirement nest egg, but its only
a start _ if inflation runs at an average 3.5 percent for 30 years,
that pool would have the buying power of a little less than
$250,000 in today's money. So its important that you keep plugging
away at the 401(k).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Through an inheritance, I will be receiving approximately
$125,000. My goal is to maximize my returns for retirement. I am 47
and earn $27,000 a year. I don't expect this to increase greatly in
the near future. My only savings is $8,000 in a brokerage account
invested in common stocks. On the advice of friends, I was planning
on opening an IRA, and possibly a Roth IRA. Should I focus on
mutual funds, CDs, or stocks?
</P>
<P>
   A.S., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   A. While you could open either a Roth or a traditional IRA, the
most you can contribute is $2,000 a year, so no more than $4,000 of
the money could go into IRA accounts within the next couple of
months _ $2,000 for the tax year 1999 and a further $2,000 for tax
year 2000. Since you will in all likelihood be in a lower tax
bracket in retirement than you are now, I would favor the
traditional IRA with its short-term tax break.
</P>
<P>
   The best vehicle for the remainder of the money is a variable
annuity, which will protect the accumulation from taxation until it
is withdrawn in retirement. And at that point, you would owe taxes
only on the percentage of the withdrawals that represent the
internal growth within the account, but not on the percentage that
represents your initial investment.
</P>
<P>
   As for the investment vehicle, I'd suggest a portfolio leaning
heavily on funds that track stock market indexes. I would stay away
from individual stocks because of the higher risks entailed in a
portfolio built on a few selected securities, and I would stay away
from CDs because they don't have enough risk _ and therefore don't
provide enough potential for the kind of growth you'll need to
build a satisfactory retirement pool.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
