<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON HOLDS KEY TO SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Celtics seemed to be pointed in the right direction
before the final quarter of Wednesday's game against Detroit. Now,
Kenny Anderson wants to re-establish the team's sense of propriety
and purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who suffered a hip pointer after a collision with
Grant Hill, practiced only briefly Thursday but expects to start
against New York Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   After Anderson departed in the second quarter against the
Pistons, the Celtics struggled. They were outscored, 36-18, in the
fourth quarter of a 110-92 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a matter of turnovers,'' coach Rick Pitino said.
``There were six 4-point swings, where turnovers led to easy
layups. That's 12 points in the first half alone. It was a close
game (in the second half) and we had two great shots in the lane,
we missed, and they got the ball and scored. We didn't run the fast
break well. We ran the fast break for jump shots rather than
layups. Whether Kenny was a factor in that . . . you've got to run
the break for layups.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson helped set the tone for the Celtics' fast start with a
purposeful attitude in the exhibition season. Anderson is
attempting to play a more substantive role in the direction of the
team. The Celtics won their first three games, and Anderson was a
key.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I fell like that I broke my wrist, in 1993,''
Anderson said about the collision Wednesday. ``It happens quick.
You look at it in slow motion and it looks harder than it really
is. But nothing is broken. It's a matter of how much pain I can
take and if I can be myself out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to win the game and be out there for the team.
I couldn't be myself, I couldn't be aggressive and penetrate, be
speedy, and take advantage of the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be injured and sit out two games. It's not
only what I can do offensively. I want to be able to move and not
be a liability for my teammates defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Dana Barros and Doug Overton filled the point guard role, but
Anderson's injury highlighted a Celtic vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   ``If their teams lost Grant Hill or Allen Iverson, they would
fall apart, too,'' Pitino said. ``Kenny is one of the premier
guards in the league. He is efficient in running the offense and
running the fast break. He gets where you have to go with the
basketball. He is a terrific offensive point guard and the aspects
of his game that were liabilities, conditioning and defense, are no
longer liabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics will be seeking to regain some momentum after two
successive defeats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit was 0-4 when they came here and they were starving,''
Anderson said. ``They had not had a meal in days and they saw that
fat ham sitting there. That was the worst game we have played, but
we still competed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a bad game. We didn't have that same spark. But you
have to stay upbeat, always stay above water. I don't want to
slide, lose three or four games in a row, because every game is so
tough and you never know when your next win is going to come. I
wanted to have a winning record in November, and it will be tough,
but we can still do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks, who visited Minnesota Thursday, should be a
difficult test.
</P>
<P>
   ``Along with Miami and San Antonio, they are the best defensive
teams in the league,'' Pitino said. ``They shoot 46 percent and
make you shoot 38 percent. Fundamentally, they are the soundest
defensive team in the league. If you play their half-court game,
you lose. You have to create a style of play that takes them out of
their game, or else you will not win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics also were vulnerable against the Pistons' inside
quickness. Jerome Williams had 16 rebounds as the Pistons
outrebounded the Celtics, 46-40. The Knicks' Marcus Camby has the
potential to present similar difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Camby is a factor on defense and on the offensive glass,''
Pitino said. ``We will have to do a good job on him. We did not do
a good job of keeping Jerome Williams off the offensive glass.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
