u i BC-RUSSIA-ARMY-BOS &LR;      11-12 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ARMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN MILITARY FALLS IN BEHIND PUTIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV AND BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOZDOK, Russia _ In a large tent on Russia's main air base in
the Caucasus about three weeks ago, Prime Minister Vladimir Putin
raised his glass of vodka to the senior commanders of Moscow's
offensive in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed a toast to the success of the Russian campaign
against separatist Chechen militants, and to lasting peace in the
strife-torn Caucasus region. But just as the 15 assembled generals
and colonels were about to drink, the premier slammed down his
glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys, I'll drink when this is over and there are no more
bandits in this land,'' Putin declared, according to several who
were present. The officers put their glasses down, too.
</P>
<P>
   That was when the generals knew that Putin was their man.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's six-week-old offensive in Chechnya belongs to Putin as
much as it belongs to the generals. The former KGB spy has linked
his political aspirations and future to the success of that
campaign, and has vowed to defeat the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Now the military is returning the favor.
</P>
<P>
   As civilian casualties mount in Chechnya and the West pressures
the Kremlin to begin talks to end the war, speculation has grown in
Moscow that Putin, the war's architect, will soon be fired by
President Boris Yeltsin _ who has sacked four prime ministers since
March 1998 when they threatened to eclipse him.
</P>
<P>
   That is something that leading military commanders, who last
week threatened to quit if the Kremlin stops their offensive, are
determined to prevent.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by their failure in Russia's 1994-96 war in Chechnya,
a conflict they say politicians prevented them from winning, the
generals now say they can defeat the separatists if Moscow does not
interfere.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Putin's tough stance in the army tent in Mozdok, the
generals believed he meant what he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearing that from Putin, we knew he was with us,'' said one
officer who was there. ``It was a real vote of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   General Vladimir Shamanov, who commands Russia's forces in the
Caucasus, said: ``I would say that Vladimir Vladimirovich (Putin)
is today a symbol behind which many people march. I am in the first
rank, without a doubt. All Russians are sick of the fact that
Russia is humiliated, insulted, and asking for handouts.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Shamanov told Russian State Television that he will
resign if ordered to halt his troops' advance in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tear off my stripes and go and do something in
civilian life. I would no longer serve in such an army,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anatoly Kvashnin, the Armed Forces general staff chief, has also
threatened to resign, along with several other officers, if a
cease-fire is ordered in the breakaway region.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Zhilin, a retired army colonel and Moscow-based
military analyst, said the generals were really sending a
not-so-subtle message to the Kremlin: don't mess with our Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past week, Russia's leading newspapers and television
stations have been reporting that Yeltsin is about to sack his
prime minister, whose popularity has soared as the war has
progressed.
</P>
<P>
   The generals' threats were interpreted by many here as a
challenge to Russia's civilian government. But in a country where
the past three prime ministers _ Putin, Sergei Stepashin and
Yevgeny Primakov _ all came out of Russia's highly militarized
security services, it is difficult to speak of a civilian
government in the Western sense.
</P>
<P>
   The real message the generals were trying to send, analysts
said, is that they are happy with the current government and prime
minister, and they do not want it changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The generals were sending the Kremlin a warning not only not
to interfere in military affairs but also not to interfere with
Putin's government,'' Zhilin said. ``Putin and the generals have
found a common language.''
</P>
<P>
   And it appears that, for now at least, the Kremlin has gotten
the message. Yeltsin has reportedly assured military leaders that
the war will not be stopped. He also awarded Hero of Russia medals
to Kvashnin and other leading generals.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Kremlin spokesman Igor Shabdurasulov said this week in
a radio interview that there ``can be no talk'' about ousting
Putin, who was a political unknown when Yeltsin named him prime
minister in August. At the time, Yeltsin also said he wanted his
new premier to succeed him as president.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the dour and steely Putin has become the leading
candidate in the presidential elections scheduled for next year.
Polls show that more than 60 percent of Russia's electorate approve
of his performance as prime minister and about 30 percent would
vote for him in the elections.
</P>
<P>
   But just as importantly, Putin appears also to have gone from
being Yeltsin's boy to being his own man, with his own political
base in Russia's powerful military and security services.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large part of the military establishment sees Putin as a
guarantee that the war in Chechnya will continue, that the military
budget will increase and that Russia will take a more assertive
stand abroad,'' Alexander Pikayev, a military analyst at the Moscow
Carnegie Center, said. ``For a long time the military has been
dissatisfied with what it sees as Yeltsin's weak foreign policy.
Putin's style and behavior contrasts with this sharply.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin has already increased military spending by $387 million
for this year and his 2000 budget calls for another increase of $1
billion. Next year, Russia's proposed military budget will be $5.57
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin is limited in his political base and doesn't have the
complete support of the Yeltsin administration. He has turned to
the military and security services for support,'' Pikayev said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin may be itching once again to fire his popular prime
minister. But with the military solidly behind Putin, the mercurial
Yeltsin could be stuck with him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Filipov reported from Mozdok. Whitmore reported from Moscow.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
