<HEADLINE>
RUDOLPH THE HARD-NOSED REINDEER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well in advance of the holiday season, our shopping force is
already scouring the stores, looking for items of interest such as
this:
</P>
<P>
   A devoted reader went to Pottery Barn the other day to buy
Christmas place settings for his family. Jumping the gun, you might
think, but no; the place settings in question, emblazoned with a
not unattractive reindeer motif, sold out before Thanksgiving last
year. He had previously bought a few plates, and was returning for
the plat de resistance: the centerpiece platter featuring Rudolph
the Red-Nosed Reindeer.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, no Rudolph. As it was explained by staffers on the scene,
Pottery Barn had made a mistake relatively common in modern
America. They assumed (dangerous to assume!) that Rudolph _ like
his companions Donner, Blitzen, &AMP; Co. _ is a public-domain
character. But he is not. So this year's companion platter features
Vixen and Dasher.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph is the creation of the late Robert May, who wrote the
original children's poem as a Christmas promotion for his employer,
Montgomery Ward. By the end of World War II, Monkey Ward had
distributed more than 3 million free copies of the poem, making
Rudolph _ who was almost named Reginald, or Rollo _ a national
celebrity. In 1947, Ward gave the rights to Rudolph back to May.
Two years later, May's brother-in-law, Johnny Marks, wrote the
famous song that Gene Autry, Alvin and the Chipmunks, and dozens of
other recording artists have engraved in our memories, for better
or worse.
</P>
<P>
   So who owns Rudolph? May's daughter, Virgina Herz, who lives in
California, and she's locked up the copyright through 2014.
(Dartmouth College also has a significant Rudolph archive,
including cookie jars, neckties, and the original Monkey Ward
manuscript, donated by loyal alumnus May.) Herz wasn't available
for comment, and a spokeswoman for San Francisco-based Pottery Barn
professed ignorance of the whole affair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arguably (equals) Not
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Arguably Watch continues with this contribution from Tom
Scocca, late of The Boston Phoenix and now writing for Baltimore's
City Paper: ``The Knicks have arguably two of the top 10 players in
the NBA in Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell,'' quoth the
CNN-Sports Illustrated Web site. Says Scocca: ``Off the top of my
head, I count 28 players who are _ inarguably _ better than Houston
or Sprewell.''
</P>
<P>
   I encountered the a-word in Rupert Murdoch's utterly mediocre
London Times: ``The brilliant Michael Winner, arguably the most
significant film director of the postwar era,'' blah blah blah.
Winner is a technically proficient journeyman director who has
directed many movies, including ``Death Wish'' and its two sequels,
``DWI'' and ``DWII.'' He also happens to be a columnist for another
Murdoch-owned newspaper, the Sunday Times.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   'Twasn't
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An alert reader noticed the following squib in the Portland
Press Herald's feature ``Biblio Files,'' in which prominent Maine
citizens natter on about their favorite books and authors: Robert
Gardiner, president of Maine Public Broadcasting, praised Tom
Wolfe, Aldo Leopold, and Mark Twain, dissed Tom Clancy, and then
was asked, ``Who is your favorite author, and why?'' Gardiner
replied, ``Evelyn Waugh, because her books are so witty and
unpredictable. I have read many of her books and have loved every
one. I can't say that about many other authors.''
</P>
<P>
   Ain't she great! The newspaper says the gender mishap came in an
e-mail from MPR, where some underling is blamed for gelding Mr.
Waugh. In a subsequent correction, the newspaper fell on its sword
and admitted that ``Waugh was a man'' . . . Perhaps my editors
could hire some underlings for me to blame for my occasional slips,
like calling Ireland the land of author Frank McCourt's birth in a
recent column. In fact, McCourt was born in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
