<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LETTER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BAND THAT ROCKS THE CRADLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The scene at the Atlantic Fish Company on a recent
afternoon is like a chapter from a parenting manual. Call it
Oysters and Diapers: Adventures in Dining With Your Newborn. Kay
Hanley and Michael Eisenstein _ leaders of the Boston rock band
Letters To Cleo, and parents of 4-month-old Zoe _ have just
discovered a nappy-related problem. Hanley (she of scathing
punk-pop vocals) is berating herself for not bringing a change of
clothes for the baby. Eisenstein (renowned for raucous power
chords) suggests a quick run to Baby Gap. But the model modern dad
instead spirits Zoe off to the men's room, returning 20 minutes
later with a clean, if scantily-clad, baby.
</P>
<P>
   Life has changed for this pair who once pursued rock 'n' roll
excesses with the gleeful enthusiasm they now reserve for cooing
over their child. Letters To Cleo _ a band that was the break-out
darling of the Boston rock scene in the mid-'90s _ hasn't performed
together in more than a year. The quintet has been without a record
contract since mid-1998, and hasn't had a hit single since 1994,
when the song ``Here and Now,'' from the band's debut CD, ``Aurora
Gory Alice,'' was featured on TV's ``Melrose Place.'' (Two
subsequent albums, 1995's ``Wholesale Meats and Fish'' and 1997's
``Go!'' were commercial disappointments.)
</P>
<P>
   In an unforgiving industry that's only grown more ruthless in
the aftermath of record label mega-mergers and artist-roster
slashings, and faced with a music culture where trends come and go
as fast as a three-minute pop song, Letters To Cleo is wading back
in _ fortified with healthy doses of both circumspection and
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there is this feeling of . . . are we really relevant? In
the big, horrible, ugly world of radio, are we even going to
matter? Do we want to go out and pursue a deal again? And how much
more of my life do I want to invest in this, really?'' Hanley is
her usual candid and forthright self, though she swears, after
three mangled attempts at articulating the word relevant, that
infantitis has claimed her verbal skills. ``On the other hand,''
she says, ``I've been in this band since I was 18. You know, my
entire identity is informed by this experience. And the band brings
me a lot of happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenstein concurs. Like his wife, he takes a philosophical
approach to riding the industry roller-coaster. ``We had to get
off, because they were going nowhere with or without us,'' says
Eisenstein of the band's departure last year from Revolution
Records, a subsidiary of Warner Bros. ``They were yanking our chain
every time,'' adds Hanley, a stickler for accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of chaos,'' Eisenstein concedes. ``They
couldn't pick a single. They hemmed and hawed on a video budget.
They didn't know what they wanted and they didn't know what they
wanted us to be. But it wasn't like we were coming off a platinum
record and now we were free agents. The security blanket was pulled
out. We were happy and sad and worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Letters To Cleo found themselves more in demand as
an unsigned band _ which makes the notion of this being a comeback
seem a bit exaggerated. They may have been label-less, but the band
continued to work. Soundtrack offers started pouring in almost
immediately, resulting in LTC songs in the recent films
``Jawbreaker'' and ``Ten Things I Hate About You.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out there were people who wanted to work with us for
a long time but who didn't want to deal with our old label,'' says
Eisenstein. ``Didn't want to deal with Irving,'' Hanley clarifies,
referring to Irving Azoff, the veteran industry bigwig who ran
their label.
</P>
<P>
   Most serendipitous of all was a query from Sony Wonder, which
was looking for a female-fronted band to supply songs for ``Molly
O,'' an animated children's series being developed about an
8-year-old rock star. Hanley faxed them some ideas, but didn't hear
back for many months. ``Then in June they called, they're like
`alright, we need a song by Thursday,' '' Hanley recalls. ``It was
a Saturday. I'm 8 1/2 months pregnant. We wrote it on Sunday and
Monday, went into the studio and recorded it on Tuesday. I couldn't
breathe. You know, I really thought my uterus might explode. We
mixed it on Wednesday, put it in the mail that night, and got it to
them on Thursday. It was a burst of activity that I did not know we
had in us.''
</P>
<P>
   That burst of activity jump-started more than just a foray into
television, although ``Molly O'' _ which will premiere next fall on
one of several networks currently bidding for it _ comes at an
auspicious time. It will supply both the luxury of working at home
and a steady paycheck while Letters To Cleo puts the wheels in
motion once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was time,'' Hanley announces emphatically, ``to write our
own music. For my own satisfaction, my own sense of well-being . .
. I really need to be doing this.'' Hanley dreamed up the idea of a
four-week October residency at the Kendall Cafe in Cambridge, just
she and Michael, voice and guitar, working up new material and
dusting off the old. ``I needed to have a deadline, especially
right now with the baby. It forced us to get the songs down.''
</P>
<P>
   And it lit a fire in Hanley that she frankly didn't anticipate.
``A month and a half ago, I was nowheresville in my feelings toward
the band. I would have been happy hanging out with Zoe and writing
songs for the cartoon. But there was the residency, and then all of
sudden there's the new batch of songs, and we're rehearsing, and
we've got a big rock show!'' she laughs. ``The thing is, once
things start rolling with us, generally they go at warp speed.''
</P>
<P>
   The band has booked time at Q Division studios next month, where
Letters To Cleo will record demo tapes to shop for a new deal.
Hanley is confident, she says, in the band's ability to take the
world by storm. All they need to do is make the album that turns
people's attention away from ``Here and Now,'' which was featured a
few weeks ago on MTV's ``Ultrasound'' special about one-hit wonders
of the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absurd,'' says Hanley. ``I could be bitter about it, but
I see it for what it is. My band is identified with that song, and
I'm identified as the girl who sings the fast part. You could see
it as a terrible albatross around our necks. But it was also a
tremendous blessing. That song gave us a certain amount of
insurance that we would be able to make albums in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, everything that's happened to us has kind of
happened by fate,'' admits Hanley, who always thought she'd wind up
a novelist. ``That we were never real precious about doing it in
the first place has saved us from a lot of heartache and a lot of
bruised egos. We've just never been as bummed out as people told us
we should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenstein, however, makes no bones about the fact that he would
very much like to sell millions and millions of records. He doesn't
wonder for a second if they can write great songs. He fully
believes it's not even possible for Letters To Cleo to make an
album that doesn't have a couple of potential hit singles. All they
need is a chance to step up to the plate. ``Inside 128, we're
huge!'' Eisenstein proclaims. ``It's not that far-fetched.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, everything's changed. Hanley's usual method of writing a
song, playing it through once, taking it to the band and letting
the guys go to town on it has been upended. At the Kendall, Hanley
says, ``we played these new songs so quiet, so stripped-down. I'm
getting so used to hearing them this way that I'm starting to
think, well, maybe it's time to do something mature, you know, our
`Car Wheels on a Gravel Road,' '' she says, referring to Lucinda
Williams's bare-bones gem from last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sort of feeling like an Earth mother, in the core of my
soul.'' Hanley gazes at Zoe, sleeping peacefully in her stroller
next to the table. Then she glances sideways, and rolls her eyes.
``But then I think, `uugh, I don't know.' There's something that
happens when we're all together. I'm not stuck on any one thing.''
</P>
<P>
   So everything's changed, and everything is, in a way, still the
same. The band is intact, invigorated, pumped to play, ready to
record. Hanley and Eisenstein are writing. Ideas are flowing like
wine. Letters To Cleo is ready to jump back into the game. But
there's this little girl _ she's awake now, kicking her tiny legs
and smiling up at her parents _ who makes it all feel very, very
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making an album, it used to be like putting everything you
have into that creation. You'd put it out there, and it was like
fresh meat to the wolves. I've never gotten used to it, being torn
to shreds for what I do. On some level, having her, it's put
everything in perspective. It's like, I've done this in my life,''
says Hanley, turning toward Zoe. ``I think from now on it's going
to be much easier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
