<SLUG> BC-TV-AFTERSHOCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STUNNINGLY STABLE `AFTERSHOCK' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
AFTERSHOCK: EARTHQUAKE IN NEW YORK 
Starring: Sharon Lawrence, Cicely Tyson, Jennifer Garner, Frederick
Weller, Lisa Nicole Carson, Charles Dutton, Tom Skerritt 
Directed by: Mikael Salomon 
On: CBS 
Time: Sunday and Tuesday nights at 9 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its intense 15 minutes of brownstone-facade-crumbling, Lady
Liberty-cracking, flailing-body-flying, fire-and-smoke-spewing,
car-alarm-wailing, dust-and-cement-raining horror, ``Aftershock:
Earthquake in New York'' powerfully imagines what a 7.0 shake would
look like in the Big Apple. The two-part TV movie, a CBS sweeps
event airing Sunday and Tuesday nights at 9), offers up a
stunningly vivid fantasy of the undoing of Manhattan in the middle
of an ordinary urban afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But the earthquake, which occurs midway through Part 1, is the
only convincing thing in this overlong, paint-by-numbers disaster
movie. How strange it is to watch such a catastrophe and think,
yawn, ``Been there, done that.'' Every single one of the characters
is a familiar TV type, and the plot lines include nary a surprise.
It's a prime example of how lazy TV and movie scripts can turn
viewers into fortunetellers, as we learn to read the fates of
characters after only a few scenes. Right off the bat, you'll know
(or at least I knew; read no further if you don't want the obvious
spelled out) that the daddy's-girl ballerina will find love with
her immigrant cabbie, that the guilty mother will rescue her
disabled son, that the feuding mayor and fire chief will learn to
forget their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the lead players are from other TV shows. Sharon
Lawrence, currently on ``Ladies Man,'' plays the overprotective
mother. She has the movie's most ridiculous subplot, which
ultimately finds her being hoisted into a collapsed school to
collect her son, all dolled up like a renegade with a handkerchief
around her forehead, dirt smudged on her cheeks, and lots of
emergency spandex. Jennifer Garner, one of the Manhattanites on
``Time of Your Life,'' is the spoiled dancer, and Lisa Nicole
Carson from ``Ally McBeal'' plays a lawyer who gets a murder
suspect off the hook, then gets trapped in the subway system with
him. We're supposed to wonder if he really committed the murder,
but one look at his cool eyes and you'll know. Charles Dutton and
Tom Skerritt are on hand as public officials, a pair of actors who
are better than their roles here. Also deserving of richer material
is Cicely Tyson, who has a small part as a wise grandmother who _
gag _ helps a thug find honor during the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   One of the oddities about these disaster movies is their
penchant for turning the worst events in human history into grand
opportunities _ for romance, for heroism, for peace. Love among the
ruins, as it were. ``Aftershock'' takes this courage business much
too far, wallowing in its own earnestness as the city joins hands
and hearts to save itself. Oh sure, there are three looters
who make their way through the mess, walking into shattered
storefronts, but you just know these bad sports are going to see
the light before the tragedy ends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
