<HEADER>
A7622 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-ANYWHERE-BOS &LR;      11-12 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ANYWHERE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTMAN, SARANDON, GO `ANYWHERE' WITH STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ANYWHERE BUT HERE 
Directed by: Wayne Wang 
Screenplay by: Alvin Sargent (novel: Mona Simpson) 
Starring: Susan Sarandon, Natalie Portman, Eileen Ryan, Ray Baker,
John Diehl, Shawn Hatosy, Bonnie Bedelia, Caroline Aaron, Hart
Bochner 
Running time: 114 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (sex-related material) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Breathing new life into old formulas, ``Anywhere But Here'' aims
its big, bold mother-daughter conflicts straight at the heart by
way of the tear ducts, and connects. There always was a certain
big-screen quality to Mona Simpson's 1986 novel, and Susan Sarandon
and Natalie Portman convince us they're just the ones to bring it
off. They plunge confidently into the story of a discontented
single mom who uproots her resentful teenage daughter from their
life in Wisconsin and drives to Beverly Hills in a used Mercedes
she can't afford. Sarandon's Adele clearly has a spirit too big to
be contained by the confines of a town she sees as a backwater, but
one that her daughter, Ann, regards as a safe cocoon.
</P>
<P>
   Still, pretty soon after they arrive, it's obvious that a role
reversal has taken place, with Portman's serious and intense young
Ann mostly slipping into the adult role her mom isn't quite
prepared to assume. When her romantic mom thinks she's found true
love, it's the astute Ann who sees a one-night stand for what it
is. One of the film's high-impact scenes comes when Ann auditions
for an acting job, not realizing her mother is watching, and
uncorks an improv, a mercilessly accurate and unflattering
impersonation of her mother. Adele, seeing herself thus reflected
in her daughter's eyes, interiorizes her pain, but interiorizes it
intensely.
</P>
<P>
   Ann has more than a few shots at teary emotions too, one coming
when she accuses her mom of keeping her from contacting her
estranged father. She defiantly phones him in Las Vegas, and is
hurt to find that he greets her not with outpourings of the love
she had envisoned, but with a pinched suspicion that she's calling
to get money from him. The back-and-forth is intense, including the
intermittent interactions with family, especially in Portman's
scenes with a beloved cousin (Shawn Hatosy). One reason the film
works as well as it does is that the fast-rising Portman is a
dramatic match for Sarandon's big screen presence. Because
Portman's Ann is strong, and realizes it, she's open, too, to
admiring some things about her mother. Goose that she sometimes is,
Adele shows Ann how to live life without pettiness or meanness, and
even with a sense of flair and style.
</P>
<P>
   Mother and daughter have their troubles, but they enlarge and
deepen each other, and face life courageously. It's easy to like
these women, easy to tie into their ups and downs for the better
part of two hours, despite the transparency of the film's
manipulations. Wayne Wang, who has been this route in ``The Joy
Luck Club,'' knows how to direct light-handedly enough to keep them
palatable. ``Anywhere But Here'' is much closer to ``Stella
Dallas'' than to ``Mildred Pierce.'' Portman's Ann matures
satisfyingly and Sarandon's Adele easily makes the jump from
airhead to earth mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere But Here,'' while more conventional than Sarandon's
last excursion into movie motherhood (``Stepmom''), is also more
likable and better able to connect us to its emotions. Portman and
Sarandon give us more than bravura bonding. Their star turns in the
classic Hollywood mold are permeated by crowd-pleasing warmth and
emotional generosity. Nobody is going to call ``Anywhere But Here''
modernist, but it's simpatico enough to make the
less-than-cutting-edge nature of its delivery system unimportant.
It probably works better for being slightly old-fashioned. With
``Tumbleweeds'' due to arrive from the festival circuit, and now
``Anywhere But Here,'' we're richly supplied with women who buck
the odds, are willing to be called irresponsible, and write
themselves into that most American of activities _ hitting the road
to a better life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
