<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GUEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GUEST' RECOUNTS MEETING OF TWO REMARKABLE MINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE GUEST FROM THE FUTURE 
Anna Akhmatova and Isaiah Berlin 
By Gyorgy Dalos. With the collaboration of Andrea Dunai;
translated, from the German, by Antony Wood. Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux. 250 pp. Illustrated. $25. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In September 1945, Isaiah Berlin arrived at the British Embassy
in Moscow. Five years earlier, he had left Oxford, already on his
way to becoming a figure of academic legend, to join the war
effort. Most of his service had been at the Washington embassy.
Indicating the quality of his work there is the fact both Churchill
and King George regularly read his dispatches.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a diplomatic posting to the Soviet Union made even more
sense. Born in Riga, in what is now Latvia, in 1909, Berlin had
moved with his parents to England when he was 12. He retained a
profound affinity for Russian culture and spoke the language with
no accent.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as soon as he arrived, Berlin started planning a trip to
Leningrad (now St. Petersburg). He had lived there for three years
as a boy and, still the good Oxford don, he had heard that books
were more readily available in the former imperial capital than in
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Leningrad boasted another attraction, though Berlin did not as
yet realize it. Anna Akhmatova lived there.
</P>
<P>
   One of the supreme figures of 20th-century Russian poetry,
Akhmatova ``brought to the Russian lyric the wealth of the
nineteenth-century Russian novel,'' or so thought her literary
contemporary Osip Mandelstam. Like Mandelstam, Akhmatova ran afoul
of Stalinism (unlike him, she survived). Both her son and husband
were imprisoned during the purges, and her poetic cycle ``Requiem''
is a monument to the barely conceivable suffering endured by the
Soviet people.
</P>
<P>
   Literally millions of people had disappeared into the maelstrom
of Stalinism, the great as well as the unknown. So far as the
outside world knew, Akhmatova was one of them _ as likely to be
dead or in a labor camp as living in obscurity. Thus Berlin was
amazed to discover the latter was the case when her name came up
during a casual conversation in a Leningrad bookshop. He was even
more amazed to learn she lived only a few blocks away. ``It was as
if I had suddenly been invited to meet Miss Christina Rossetti,''
he later wrote. ``I could hardly speak: I mumbled that I should
indeed like to meet her.''
</P>
<P>
   What ensued was one of the century's more extraordinary literary
encounters: a meeting of East and West, imagination and intellect,
past and future. Indeed, ``The guest from the future'' is what
Akhmatova called Berlin in her epic sequence, ``Poem Without a
Hero.'' It's also the title the Hungarian novelist and essayist
Gyorgy Dalos has given his ruminative account of the meeting
between them, how it came to be, and what followed from it.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin and Akhmatova spent all of 12 hours together, but that
brief time more than sufficed. Their encounter produced the sort of
spiritual communion commonly found in the pages of Russian
literature but rarely anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Even 35 years later, when Berlin came to write an account of
their conversation (part of his celebrated essay ``Meetings with
Russian Writers in 1945 and 1956''), the emotional intensity of the
encounter remained palpable.
</P>
<P>
   As for Akhmatova, she came to see the meeting has having had
nothing less than global significance. Twenty years later, when
Oxford gave her an honorary degree, she told Berlin that their
meeting had so angered Stalin it helped usher in the Cold War. Such
exaggeration is understandable, perhaps, in light of the dire
personal consequences Akhmatova suffered for having met with a
foreign diplomat. Expelled from the Writers' Union, she was
denounced by a leading Communist Party official as ``half nun, half
whore,'' and her poetry became unpublishable. Also, both her son
and ex-husband were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Dalos adds much detail and a larger context to Berlin's essay,
but his book cannot be said to supplant it. The greatest value of
``The Guest from the Future'' lies in the view it affords of Soviet
culture. Precisely because it was at once so monstrous and absurd,
that world hardly seems credible now to an American. Precisely
because of that monstrousness and absurdity, the fact of its
existence must never be forgotten. ``You come from a society of
human beings,'' Akhmatova remarked to Berlin, ``whereas here we are
divided into human beings and _'' She did not finish the thought.
There was no need for her to do so then. Thanks to Dalos, there is
no need for her to do so now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
