<HEADLINE>
`MESSENGER' LACKS SPIRITUALITY, PASSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE MESSENGER: THE STORY OF JOAN OF ARC 
Directed by: Luc Besson 
Screenplay by: Andrew Birkin, Besson 
Starring: Milla Jovovich, John Malkovich, Faye Dunaway, Dustin
Hoffman, Pascal Greggory, Vincent Cassel, Tcheky Karyo, Richard
Ridings, Desmond Harrington, Timothy West 
Running time: 141 minutes 
Rated: R (strong graphic battles, a rape and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No small part of the history of movies consists of men giving
the movie-star treatment to women they're close to. Sometimes it
works brilliantly. Think of Stiller and Garbo. Think of von
Sternberg and Dietrich. Sometimes it doesn't work at all. When
French director Luc Besson cast Milla Jovovich in the title role of
``The Messenger: The Story of Joan of Arc,'' it may have done
wonders for their relationship, but it doesn't do much for the
film. Jovovich, a former model, can slink with the best of them.
She looks great in armor. She even can ride a horse. But she can't
act.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad, because Besson goes at this retelling with epic size,
epic sweep, and epic amounts of bloody battlefield carnage under
leaden gray skies that press panoramically down upon the world as
if to remind even those looking heavenward of the crushing weight
of medieval life. It begins with a brutal scene of Joan as a girl
in hiding, watching British invaders rape and murder her mother.
But the film begins to smack of compromise when Joan bypasses the
usual hacking off of her long tresses with a dagger and instead has
her hair cut stylishly by a barber at the dauphin's court, a barber
who, incidentally, has mastered the medieval hairdresser's art of
blond highlighting.
</P>
<P>
   Her first meeting with John Malkovich's dauphin, a sly weakling
she means to crown king of a divided, demoralized France, is right
out of ``The Exorcist.'' It's a pattern to which we get accustomed,
as Besson does a lot of cross-cutting to Joan's legendary visions
with MTV moves and computerized effects. The film takes the
contemporary view of Joan as a pioneer feminist who was burned at
the stake for political reasons after being sold out by the king
she championed. It wasn't until this century, 500 years after the
burning, that the church admitted it was perhaps too hasty in
torching her, and whitewashed itself by posthumously declaring her
a saint.
</P>
<P>
   But Joan's trial, presented with such brilliant irony by Shaw in
``Saint Joan,'' is thrown away. Besson does a lot of quick cutting,
almost turning the film into the cinematic equivalent of a shell
game to cover, one supposes, the fact that Jovovich can't speak
lines with any sustained passion, or any inner anything. Because
physicality comes so naturally to her, she's at her best in the
battle scenes where her modus operandi is to shout, ``Follow me.''
She shames the French soldiers into charging with her into battle
and infuriates the English. Grimacing mightily, they just hate it
when they're routed by a 19-year-old peasant girl. They attribute
it to witchcraft, reasoning that no woman on her own could defeat
them.
</P>
<P>
   So there you have it _ a lot of striking pictures in this
would-be feminist ``Braveheart,'' but a film that's pretty flat and
earthbound because of the limitations of the figure at its center.
Besson has surrounded Jovovich with hands experienced at fighting
genre cliche, ranging from John Malkovich's wimpy survivalist
dauphin to Faye Dunaway's manipulative power behind the throne to
Dustin Hoffman, almost unrecognizable as a mysterious hooded figure
who appears to Joan in her dungeon at the end and may be a figment
of her imagination. There's more than a hint that Joan is
hallucinating. What's never there is any hint that there's any
spiritual component in what we're seeing.
</P>
<P>
   The film aims at being a rationalist Joan of Arc, which I think
misses the point. But then Joan lived in an age of religious belief
and we live in an age of scientific data. And in any case, Joan has
always been a challenge for actresses, has always been a tough role
to nail. The best they can hope to do is convince us they're aflame
from within, an achievement totally out of this film's reach, which
in its big, hectic, and thoroughly mundane way can do better than a
Joan aflame from without. Ingrid Bergman wasn't a bad Joan. Poor
Jean Seberg wasn't as bad a Joan as critics said she was. But the
best Joan remains one of the first, Maria Falconetti in Carl
Dreyer's potently expressionistic silent ``The Passion of Joan of
Arc'' (1928). It remains the standard. ``The Messenger: The Story
of Joan of Arc'' isn't even in the running.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
