<HEADLINE>
`NEW YORK': A LONG, LOVING LOOK AT THE BIG APPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
NEW YORK: A DOCUMENTARY FILM 
Directed by Ric Burns. 
Produced by: Ric Burns and Lisa Ades. 
Written by: Ric Burns and James Sanders. 
When: Sunday through Thursday, 9-11 p.m. 
On: PBS 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ric Burns's PBS documentary on the history of New
York is a city-lover's dream _ a pastiche of photos, film clips,
music, lit-readings, and talking-head musings that unveils the
grandeur and terror of metropolitan life with the sweep of an epic
poem.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee-haters may tire of the narrator's endless exaltation of
Manhattan as center of the universe. (One is often reminded of
Updike's description of the ``true New Yorker,'' who holds the
``secret belief that people living elsewhere had to be, in some
sense, kidding.'')
</P>
<P>
   But Burns's five-part, 10-hour sprawl _ plainly titled ``New
York: A Documentary Film'' _ is as much about the making of modern
America as about any one city.
</P>
<P>
   After all, as one historian puts it, New York was the first city
to test ``all the great experiments of American society'' _
immigration, unionization, industrialization, social-welfare
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Dutch arrived in 1624, it has been the place
where people from every part of the world have gathered, mingled,
and struggled for a piece of the action, a spot in the sun, or
simply a buck to get by.
</P>
<P>
   These are the threads that run through what could have been an
unwieldy narrative: New York as the densely packed melting pot,
where the strengths and foibles of democracy are played out as a
daily street drama; and, as backdrop to this drama, New York as the
cauldron of capitalism, where human dreams and desires are most
wildly satisfied or brutally crushed.
</P>
<P>
   The remarkable thing is that Burns _ who also produced
documentaries on Coney Island, the Donner Party, and (with his
brother, Ken) the Civil War _ takes in this panorama whole. His
view of New York is romantic, unabashedly so, but not sentimental.
</P>
<P>
   Much is made, for instance, of Walt Whitman's celebrations of
the city's lush mosaic (``What hurrying human tides, of day or
night! What passions, winning, losses, ardors, swim thy waters!''
the poet swooned, in ``Leaves of Grass'').
</P>
<P>
   But no less is made of the Draft Riots of 1863, in which the
passions of these human tides _ in this case, 15,000 Irish
immigrants enraged at rich natives and poor blacks _ erupted in a
weeklong melee that resulted in 119 deaths and might have brought
down the city but for intervention by the Union Army.
</P>
<P>
   We are led to admire the Fifth Avenue palaces of ``Vanderbilt,
Morgan and the other tycoons'' who built wealth in the early 20th
century _ but also to cringe at the ghastly tenements captured by
Jacob Riis's ``How the Other Half Lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The contrasts are drawn clearly but not crassly. Whitman isn't
made to seem naive or stupid for focusing on the rosy side of life.
(The passages from his ``Crossing Brooklyn Ferry,'' as read
off-camera by Spalding Gray, will bring tears to all but the steely
eyed.) Nor is Morgan painted as evil for hoarding money when so
many had none.
</P>
<P>
   All these characters, properties, views, traits _ they're all a
part of the swirl of the city, and Burns views them on their own
terms and for how each contributed to the velocity of the gust.
</P>
<P>
   Part 5 ends in 1931, with the ambivalent triumph of the Empire
State Building, soaring splendidly into the sky, but with
half-vacant offices, at the start of the Great Depression. F. Scott
Fitzgerald stares out from its towers and _ as he writes in his
essay ``My Lost City'' _ sees ``with dismay what he had never
suspected, that the city was not the endless succession of canyons
that he had supposed but that it had limits. . . . And with the
awful realization that New York was a city after all and not a
universe, the whole shining edifice that he had reared in his
imagination came crashing to the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a weird finale. It might make some wonder how much the
concept of New York that they've been imbibing in the previous 10
hours _ an all-enveloping land of magic and mayhem that does seem a
universe all its own _ has been an edifice reared in Ric Burns's
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   This tangle might be resolved in the sequel _ yes, a Part 6,
subtitled ``New York and the World,'' spanning the years 1931-2000
(all in two hours!), to be broadcast in the spring. For now,
though, the first five parts, which air Sunday through Thursday
from 9 to 11 p.m. on Channel 2, provide more genuine human drama
than anyone had any business to expect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
