<HEADLINE>
EARNEST `DOGMA' A FILM TO BELIEVE IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
DOGMA 
Written and directed by: Kevin Smith 
Starring: Ben Affleck, George Carlin, Matt Damon, Linda Fiorentino,
Janeane Garofalo, Salma Hayek, Jason Lee, Jason Mewes, Alan
Rickman, Chris Rock, Smith 
Running time: 125 minutes 
Rated: R (strong language including sex-related dialogue, violence,
crude humor and some drug content) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because it tweaks conventional holy images, ``Dogma''
predictably has been attacked as blasphemous. But it's a film that
only a sincere believer could make. Or would want to. Kevin Smith,
who wrote and directed it and plays an off-the-wall prophet, thus
weighs in alongside such serious grapplings with faith and belief
as ``Hail, Mary,'' ``The Last Temptation of Christ,'' and
``Priest.'' The difference is that while Smith struggles just as
earnestly as the makers of those films to renew his belief in
Christianity, ``Dogma'' is a lot more scatologically funny.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing, that. Its outrageous humor saves it from its own
earnestness. It's a sweet, clunky film that's so eager to air its
theological ponderings that it isn't afraid to seem a bit of a
bore. It's a low-budget film that looks like a low-budget film
except for the snazzy wings on the renegade angels played by Ben
Affleck and Matt Damon _ two pairs of the very best avian
appendages in angel movie history. Affleck and Damon interrupted
the shooting of ``Dogma'' in Pittsburgh to fly to Hollywood for
their ``Good Will Hunting'' Academy Awards. So ``Dogma'' is a cusp
film for them. It finds them still at work in the filmmaking
trenches, pre-A list.
</P>
<P>
   They launch ``Dogma'' in bracingly cheeky fashion as fallen
angels, Affleck's Bartleby filled with rage, Damon's Loki with
mischief, playing off each other with loosey-goosey chemistry,
garbed in K-Mart chic and hooded sweatshirts. Having been exiled to
Wisconsin for centuries, they're aching to go back to heaven and
think they've found a loophole in divine law that will permit it.
There's one little catch: If they do get back, it will mean that
God is not infallible, which in turn will mean the end of humanity.
This is something the angels can live with. In fact, they get a
jump on the impending wipeout by pulling the trigger themselves on
certain selected sinners.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a counterforce is assembled to keep them from entering a
heavenly portal in New Jersey. Centering it, although she'd rather
not, is a descendant of Jesus, an abortion clinic worker played by
smoky-voiced Linda Fiorentino, at home in her character's survivor
mode, although in a refreshingly confused and consequently humble
fashion that has nothing at all in common with the dogmatic.
Prodded into activism by Alan Rickman's droll seraph, she's
assigned a couple of prophets to serve as gofers and bodyguards _
the couple seen in every Smith movie, Jason Mewes' horny,
garbage-mouthed Jay and Smith's stalwart stoner known as Silent
Bob. Among the friends and enemies they meet en route: Selma
Hayek's blocked muse, an excrement monster, Jason Lee's snazzy
demon, and Chris Rock's 13th apostle, still annoyed because Christ
owes him money.
</P>
<P>
   Except for instances when Smith veers into some theological
explication, they keep things at a lively boil while somehow
managing to make us feel the author's pain at humankind's
too-frequent moral shortfall into depressing pettiness. Even more
surprisingly, we also feel the angels' pain, especially Bartleby's,
at being estranged from God. ``Dogma'' doesn't always cover its
self-assigned territory gracefully or sparklingly, although it ends
on a note of creative uprush as Affleck's dark angel confronts
Alanis Morissette's God in all Her quirky grandeur. Still, it's a
small miracle that it covers the ground at all, amusing us with its
transformations into the vernacular and the vulgate, winning us
over simply by virtue of how much it really cares. Raunchy
'tudefest apart, ``Dogma'' has that rarest of qualities in movies
that think of themselves as religious. I'm talking about the vision
thing. And the ability to make morality entertaining.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
