<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TRAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRAIN OF LIFE' IS WORTH THE TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TRAIN OF LIFE 
Written and directed by: Radu Mihaileanu 
Starring: Lionel Abelanski, Rufuscq, Clement Harari, Michael
Muller, Agathe de la Fontaine and Bruno Abraham-Kremer 
Running time: 143 minutes 
Rated: R (Brief nudity, sexual situations) 
In French, with subtitles 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not all that long after ``Life Is Beautiful'' won audiences'
hearts and Hollywood awards, ``Train of Life,'' another
phantasmagorical tale of life among the Nazis, is upon us. This one
works much better. Writer/director Radu Mihaileanu shuffles humor
and harsh reality, and comes up with an illuminating film with
layers of conflict. Tension lingers constantly, and yet there is
joy to be found. (There is some bitterness on Mihaileanu's part
vis-a-vis ``Life Is Beautiful'' director-star Roberto Benigni;
Mihaileanu says he let Benigni read his script in 1996 and offered
him a lead role. Benigni considered it, but turned it down.)
</P>
<P>
   The premise: It's 1941 and Jewish villagers in an Eastern
European town have heard rumors about Jews being deported by train
to concentration camps. Fearing this, the village idiot (or
visionary) Shlomo (Lionel Abelanski) comes up with a plan. They
procure their own train, costume some of the potential deportees in
Nazi uniforms and put them in charge, pretend they're being
shepherded to a camp, but instead bolt toward Palestine (by way of
Russia) and freedom. Oh, with an ``engineer'' who's never driven a
train. Sounds plausible, eh?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. Mihaileanu, a Romanian refugee, asks you to
accept a number of preposterous suppositions _ from the main theme
to the ``Fiddler on the Roof'' kind of joie de vivre to the idea
that Shlomo can stand on top of a train car as it whizzes through
the countryside _ but stick with him. There are some wonderful
moments _ some tense, some fanciful _ along the way and a
gut-wrenching payoff that makes sense of it all. (Think ``The Sixth
Sense.'') ``Train of Life'' won the Audience Award at this year's
Sundance Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   So, who are the lucky folks who get to play Nazis? The village
elders, led by the rabbi (Clement Harari), look for volunteers. ``I
couldn't,'' says the respected woodworker Mordechai (Rufus), citing
poor health, ``but thanks for asking.'' He is appointed Nazi
commander. A man is brought in to teach German to the Jews. The
Yiddish-speaking Jews try to get their tongues around the guttural
language. The difference? German is ``rigid and sad,'' explains the
teacher. ``Yiddish makes fun of German.'' The fake Germans try to
perfect their calls of ``Sieg Heil!,'' to comic effect. Down the
road a piece, Mordechai seems to have taken a little too
wholeheartedly to the Nazi persona _ the fake Nazis ride in
comfort, the Jews do not _ suggesting horrible things about power.
</P>
<P>
   Along the journey, this ghost train faces the threat of being
blown up by Resistance fighters, who think the train is the real
deal, and of being stopped by Nazis, who suspect everything is not
on the up-and-up. There is a rewarding interlude when persecuted
Gypsies engage the Jews, and partake in a festive dinner and dance,
sharing music and cultures. The only real misfire is a tiresome
subplot about a rejected suitor, Yossi (Michael Muller), who turns
into an irritable communist and ferments revolt. This does,
however, lead to a sharply funny confrontation between the rabbi
and the atheist Yossi, as they argue about God. ``God exists! God
doesn't exist! Who cares!'' exclaims Shlomo, again playing the wise
fool. They've got a mission here, and that is to live. The foes
hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``Train of Life'' is a long movie, and there are some
kitschy-cutesy stretches, but whatever you do, don't leave when you
think it's over. Hang on. There's a kicker that reverberates
deeply, and will make you reevaluate what you've just seen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
