<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANIC WON'T GET JAMMED UP BY A GENRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jam bands.
</P>
<P>
   The term won't go away, so why fight it?
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't have their whole lifetime to describe something,
but it's no big deal. We can live with the term,'' says John (J.B.)
Bell, singer/guitarist/songwriter with Widespread Panic, an Athens,
Ga. group which is near the top of the jam list with Phish and the
Allman Brothers Band.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basis is improvisation, in the sense of playing off of
each other,'' says Bell. ``There's more freedom to it. Then again,
you've got some folks really going after the music in an
exploratory form _ and others who hear `jam band' and say, `Oh,
we'll become that.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So there are some acts out there that are Flock-of-Seagulling
us,'' he adds, referring to a trendy new wave band from 20 years
ago that flamed out quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread Panic is, despite its name, a low-key jam band
(``We're not trying to glamorize ourselves in some big rock 'n'
roll identity''). But it's also a band very much into taking
chances _ an impressive achievement after being together for 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   The new Panic disc, `` `Til the Medicine Takes,'' is rooted in
lively, Southern-spiced rock and funk, but also makes room for some
turntable scratching, some bluegrassy banjo, some gospel (aided by
singer Dottie Peoples), and some ragtime, with New Orleans guests
the Dirty Dozen Brass Band.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time we said, `Let's not just be a band playing songs,
but let's make believe that we're taking a further step in Never
Never Land,'' Bell says, offering a Peter Pan reference.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we felt we approached these things in credible fashion. We
felt, `Let's bring in these elements, but no go overboard.' . . .
We felt we shouldn't be constrained. Personally, I like a little
variety when I see a band.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been trying to keep things fresh from the very first
days we played together,'' Bell adds. ``But if we were running
around struggling to recapture the sound we first had, we'd go
nuts. You see a lot of bands doing that. They repeat something
until it gets old. We always knew the deal was to have fun now,
because it might not be there later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
