<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-OTTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SWEDISH SONGBIRD GOES POP FOR THE HOLIDAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``It was not my choice to train my voice for classical
singing,'' says Anne-Sophie von Otter, one of the ranking singers
of today. ``But when I started to take singing lessons, my voice
broadened, and I had to face what the possibilities of my voice
were. If I had another life to live, I might choose another way of
pursuing a singing career.''
</P>
<P>
   The Swedish mezzo-soprano is one of the most versatile singers
before the public today, excelling in early music, opera, oratorio,
and the recital literature; her new Christmas album for Deutsche
Grammophon suggests, as she herself does, that she might have made
her name as a pop star.
</P>
<P>
   Von Otter is familiar to music lovers because of her CDs and
operatic videos _ her song records (Grieg, Korngold, Schubert,
Schumann, Sibelius, Late Romantic, and Swedish songs) in particular
have captured the imagination of the public, and of the committees
that bestow international recording prizes. But von Otter has been
in Boston only once before, when she sang Mahler's ``Das Lied von
der Erde'' with the Boston Symphony Orchestra under James Levine in
1994. Her fans must be eager to hear her, because her appearance
with Reinhard Goebel and Musica Antiqua Koeln Sunday in Jordan Hall
is ``sold out to the rafters'' according to the sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from Stockholm, where her children, 8 and 11, were
clamoring for her attention at bedtime recently, von Otter said
early music has been with her all throughout her career.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first moved to Stockholm and started working properly
on my voice, I sang very actively as a chorus singer, and my
favorite choir was the Bach Choir, which is still very good and
very active. Also I was part of a quartet that sang Renaissance and
Baroque music. My first work as a soloist was in baroque music, the
Bach Passions, and things like that, and my first opera was a
baroque opera. It was the music I loved listening to most of all,
especially to those discs by Nikolaus Harnoncourt, and this kind of
music is still one of my great loves.''
</P>
<P>
   With Goebel and Musica Antiqua Koeln, von Otter has recorded two
discs, a Handel album and a collection of ``Lamenti'' that remains
a local bestseller at Tower Records two years after its release.
``I've worked together quite a lot with Musica Antiqua Koeln. We
did a Handel pastiche at the Drottningholm Court Theater with
Barbara Bonney and my husband, Benny Fredrickson, directed it. We
did a `Lamenti' concert before the recording and the Handel record,
and some concerts _ not that many. I do find Reinhard Goebel a
wonderfully dynamic and very musical person and I am looking
forward to this tour very much. It's a short tour, only three
concerts, because I do not want to be away from my family for too
long again _ I've just been in Paris for four months of Gluck's
`Alceste.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Von Otter matches the diversity of her repertory with an
extraordinary palette of vocal colors and timbres, which she is
careful not to mix up. ``Obviously you do not rush from singing
Octavian in `Der Rosenkavalier' to Monteverdi's `L'Incoronazione di
Poppea.' I do not find it difficult to go back to early music; it
just takes a few days to adjust the voice up and down, to go
wherever you're going. I enjoy changing my repertory.''
</P>
<P>
   Von Otter's fans may not even recognize her voice on her new
Christmas album, ``Home for Christmas'' _ she sounds like Judy
Collins; also Duke Ellington's Swedish muse, the extraordinary
soprano Alice Babs, comes to mind occasionally. Von Otter takes
this as a compliment. ``Alice Babs made a record of Bach's `Anna
Magdalena Notebook,' and when I was young, I used to love that _
and played it over and over again. She must be 75 or something by
now, but she did a couple of concerts last year and came out with a
new CD sounding fresh as a daisy; she still has the same girlish,
fresh voice. My favorite singer when I was growing up was Julie
Andrews, and I still love that kind of clear fresh voice. People
like Joni Mitchell and Judy Collins I enjoyed as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Von Otter says she didn't want to make another conventionally
operatic Christmas album. ``So many Christmas albums by classical
singers make the songs and carols sound like film-score music; the
singers belt it out, and I don't feel the records sound as if they
were made with a lot of love. I didn't want to churn out a
Christmas album. The music is too beautiful, the message too
lovely, not to do something personal, something with some thought
behind it, a sense of humor, and a twinkle in the eye.'' Von Otter
manages to sound intimate even in Adam's ``Cantique de Noel'' (``O
Holy Night''). The mezzo responds to this comment with laughter.
``It's almost impossible to sing that intimately. The arranger
wanted to avoid doing anything big, but neither of us was happy
with our first attempt _ in the key we tried at first, I had to
sing it a little bit too big. But then we took it down a tone or
so, and I was able to sing it differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Von Otter sings a number of American Christmas songs, like
``White Christmas,'' and she does it with a convincing accent.
``Well, they'd sound pretty strange in the queen's English,
wouldn't they?'' she says. ``I believe strongly in adding the
flavor that suits the song in question.''
</P>
<P>
   The Paris ``Alceste'' was a Robert Wilson production conducted
by John Eliot Cardiner that was also recorded. ``Alceste is a
fantastic part, very much on the heavy side for me, because it is
associated with a higher and more dramatic voice than mine. We did
it in a version that Sir Charles Mackerras arranged for Janet
Baker. I did not feel that Robert Wilson made me stand still all
the time _ I enjoyed it very much, and it was quite good for my
singing to be so concentrated on not throwing myself around. This
role is so difficult that it helped me to have the enormous
concentration on my body that Robert Wilson required. I don't think
it was quite the same concept as his earlier productions with
Jessye Norman; Jessye Norman and I are slightly different!''
</P>
<P>
   Von Otter also recently sang a run of Monteverdi's
``L'Incoronazione di Poppea'' in Aix-en-Provence. She particularly
enjoyed working with Lorraine Hunt. ``It isn't often that two
mezzos get to sing in the same opera; I was Nero and she was
Ottavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Her next venture is a Handel album, and she plans a return to
the Metropolitan Opera in 2002, where she will reprise one of her
famous trouser roles, Idamante in Mozart's ``Idomeneo.'' ``James
Levine has put together a very good cast, and it is one of his
favorite pieces, and he wants it back again.'' The grapevine is
already buzzing about her decision to add ``Carmen'' to her
repertory two years from now. ``Alceste was a big adventure, and my
next big adventure will be Carmen. Nobody knows what the outcome
will be, but I'm looking forward to the production at Glyndebourne,
which will be directed by a young man named David McVicker; they
say that everything he touches turns to gold, and I hope it's true.
Carmen is not an obvious role for me. My height is always an issue
if I'm not playing a man! Another issue is how people imagine my
personality. I do look very fair and Scandinavian, and nothing
about me looks Spanish or Gypsy, so I am going to need a very good
wig, costume, and makeup!''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday afternoon von Otter will sing a Vivaldi cantata,
``Cessate, ormai, cessate.'' ``It's about an unhappy man with
severe love problems, so I'm a man in it again. And then I'm going
to sing a short cantata by Bertali that Reinhard found in a chest
of drawers someplace, maybe in Uppsala, here in Sweden; it's about
a queen lamenting the death of her king. There's a gorgeous piece
by Monteverdi to open the whole thing, and I hope I'll get to sing
some encores _ I'm bringing some Handel with me! I have wanted to
come back to Boston to sing again, that's for sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
