<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL VOICE SPEAKS IN TONGUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Recently I purchased ViaVoice so that I could
dictate my sermons. No matter what I do or say, how slowly or
softly or loudly I try, I keep getting a message that says ViaVoice
cannot understand all of my words.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mumbles
</P>
<P>
   DEAR MUMBLES: I hate to contradict all those nifty TV
commercials that make it seem like everybody can carry on
meaningful conversations with their computers, but it just isn't so
yet. You might as well be talking to your toaster.
</P>
<P>
   Voice-recognition systems _ at least those that normal consumers
can afford _ are novelties that produce accurate results only when
you follow instructions to the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the last time you saw a movie where everybody was
speaking with British accents? You didn't have any idea what
anybody was saying until halfway through the film, but you
eventually got used to the goofy voices. The software has to get
used to your voice, too.
</P>
<P>
   All voice programs have some sort of training module, where you
recite pre-defined phrases. The better ones continue to learn
heuristically as you use them or repeat the training sessions. But
even if you've spent days training your program, it's not going to
know what you're saying if you start mumbling or putting emphasis
on the wrong syllables. You must learn to speak in a strong, clear,
bland monotone with no hint of emotion in your voice. Of course,
then you might be mistaken for Al Gore or Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   If that still doesn't work, make sure your hardware is up to
snuff. You generally need more memory and a faster chip than most
packages say you do, but you also need a decent microphone, and you
have to have it positioned the same distance from your mouth every
time you use it.
</P>
<P>
   Your software probably has some sort of utility to fine-tune
microphone settings, but double-check your sound card's recording
capability. You should be able to record a short phrase or two
using Windows' built-in Sound Recorder (it's in Accessories). If
the playback sounds like you're gargling with razor blades, you've
located the problem.
</P>
<P>
   I'd tend to rely on voice software to make notes rather than to
create a finished document. It certainly couldn't be any worse than
my handwriting. If you want to use it to jot down your sermons,
don't be surprised if some Sunday your congregation may think
you're speaking in tongues, but that seems to have worked out
rather well for some of those TV preachers.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I used to be able to type NUMOFF in the
Autoexec.bat file to keep the Num Lock from activating when
booting. This doesn't work with Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   _ Numb Lock
</P>
<P>
   DEAR NUMB: All I want to know is which bonehead thought
everybody in the world wants that stupid numeric keypad on by
default. You can change that in the computer's setup program (oh,
go read the manual) or get a freeware utility to do it each time
you boot. Try a package called JW-Utils at www.zdnet.com/swlib if
you can't find Numoff.com somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   (We think Dr. Emilio Bombay really does use voice-recognition
software. That would explain why nothing he writes makes any sense.
Voice your opinion by writing to drbombay(at)star-telegram.com.
Snail-mail: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101). Fax: (817) 390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is editorial
systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
