<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SATIRDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, Nov. 13:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-TRADE (Beijing) _ Developments at the WTO talks
between the U.S. and China. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-ATTACK (Islamabad) _ Six rockets were launched in a
coordinated attack on U.S. and U.N. offices in Pakistan's capital.
There were no deaths; six or fewer wounded. The attack comes two
days before U.N. sanctions _ pushed by U.S. _ are to go into effect
on neighboring Afghanistan if the ruling Taliban does not turn over
Osama bin Laden, the suspected terrorist. By Steve LeVine.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TALKS (Belfast) _ Saying that the peace talks have
reached their ``final and most critical stage,'' George Mitchell,
the U.S. mediator, adjourns them until Monday to have leaders
``reflect'' over weekend. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   BRITIAN-PEERS (London) _ Folo on Tony Blair's success in ending
the role of all but 92 hereditary peers in the House of Lords. By
Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-MASSACRE (Washington) _ South Korean massacre survivors
meet Army officials at Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-APARTMENT (Rome) _ Death toll up to 30 in building
collapse. Nearly 30 still missing. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   (See also PM-ITALY-APARTMENT, updating Thursday's story, which
has moved.)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-U.S. (Washington) _ Indonesia's new president meets
President Clinton. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ Business and environmental
amendments to the Interior Department spending bill are the last
great stumbling block to passing the budget. The members gone, but
staffers are at work, and numbers flow back and forth from the Hill
to the White House. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ In compromise after compromise,
Republicans have been giving in to President Clinton in the final
weeks of this budget fight. Yet unlike past years, there has been
no rebellion, so far, from conservatives. The reason is that the
GOP began the year so weak and so fractured, their only goal is
survival. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EDUC (Undated) _ Folo on Clinton's proposal to provide
money for 100,000 new teachers. Will this money just replace local
spending? Do schools even have classrooms for these new teachers?
By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   NIXON-PARDON (Pittsburgh) _ Doings at a conference on the Nixon
pardon. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-DEATH-PENALTY (Miami) _ The Supreme Court decision to
consider whether the electric chair is an inhumane punishment has
reignited the debate over its use in Florida and put the governor
on the defensive. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   SC-CONFEDERATE-FLAG (Charleston, S.C.) _ As Charleston has a
ceremony to bury confederate soldiers whose bodies were found in a
construction site, the state still wrestles with ghosts of another
kind. Although Gov. Jim Hodges has offered a compromise that is the
closest two sides have gotten in years, there is still a standoff
about the confederate flag flying over the capitol and there is
still a tourism boycott by the NAACP. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Denver) _ At a sentencing hearing for the
man who sold guns to the two students who staged the high school
attack, a transcript is read from a video that the two boys made
before they started shooting. It is reportedly their own obituary.
By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   COUNCIL-OF-CHURCHES (Cleveland) _ On paper, it's one of
America's grandest religious alliances, representing 35
denominations with 50 million members and styling itself as ``the
primary national expression of the movement for Christian unity.''
But as it celebrates its 50th anniversary and names Andrew Young as
its head, the National Council of Churches is in trouble
financially and internal squabbling over mainline churches and
newer versions has left its mission unclear. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CABS-BIAS (New York) _ New York City police begin their
campaign to nab taxicabs that fail to pick up blacks. By Somini
Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By Peter
Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-DUTIES (Washington) _ A look at how Vice President Gore
mixes official duties and campaign goals. By Katharine Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   FORBES-POLICY (Yorba Linda, Claif.) _ Steve Forbes outlines his
foreign policy ideas at the Nixon Library. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   TV-DEBATE (Undated) _ ABC pulls out of Dec. 2 GOP debate.
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-MIDEAST (Petra, Jordan) _ A day after the flap over a
meeting with Mrs. Arafat, Hillary Rodham Clinton tours sites in
Petra. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-GIULIANI (New York) _ New York's mayor, Rudy
Giuliani, sharply criticizes Mrs. Clinton, his potential rival in
the Senate race, for her embrace of Mrs. Arafat. By Elisabeth
Bumiller.
</P>
