<P>
   POKEMON-FAD (Undated) _ ``Pokemon'' the recently opened movie,
is part of a carefully orchestrated effort to prolong the life of a
fad indefinitely. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   For other culture and entertainment, including Saturday's Ideas
Page stories, see the separate entertainment budget.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Growth in productivity surged in the
third quarter, while a rise in labor costs moderated. Productivity,
defined as the amount of output for each hour of work, rose at a
4.2 percent annual rate _ the biggest gain in 18 months.The gain
helped slow the growth of unit labor costs to 0.6 percent, the
lowest rate since the fourth quarter of 1998. The numbers suggest
that productivity gains remain more than sufficient to offset
rising wages amid the tightest United States labor market in three
decades. In a separate report, retail sales were unchanged in
October, but excluding cars and trucks, sales rose a more robust
0.5 percent. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-U.S.-INVEST (Winnipeg, Manitoba) _ Taking advantage of a
neighboring economy newly open to foreign investment and a Canadian
dollar trading near historic lows, Americans are snapping up
Canadian companies at a record pace. At the same time, oddly
enough, Canadians are funneling their money across the border in
volumes evocative of capital flight from Latin America. By James
Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-INTERNET (Hong Kong) _ Entrepreneurs and investors in the
Internet have been nervously watching the state of talks between
the United States and China on China's entry into the World Trade
Organization. China's Internet industry has been in state of
suspension since September, when the nation's top communications
official suddenly reaffirmed a longstanding ban on foreign
investment in Chinese Internet service providers. While a trade
agreement is not expected to deal specifically with the Internet,
analysts said it could clarify Beijing's stance toward its bubbling
online industry. By Mark Landler.
</P>
