<HEADLINE>
A FILMOGRAPHY OF THE BOND SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: Not for use before Sunday, Nov. 14.) 
 
  
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   __ Sean Connery's reign &QL; 
``Dr. No'' (1962) &QL; 
Villain: Dr. No (Joseph Wiseman). &QL; 
Of note: The least pretentious, but some say best Bond movie, with
the classic Bond girl in Ursula Andress (as Honey Rider). John
Barry's famous James Bond theme music is introduced. &QL; 
Song: ``The James Bond Theme'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
From Russia With Love (1963) &QL; 
Villain: Switchblade shoes helped keep assassin Rosa Klebb (Lotte
Lenya) on her toes. &QL; 
Of note: A terrific battle to the death between Bond and Red Grant
(Robert Shaw) aboard the Orient Express. Daniela Bianchi (as
Tatiana Romonova) was the Bond girl. &QL; 
Songs: ``James Bond With Bongos'' and ``From Russia With Love'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Goldfinger (1964) &QL; 
Villains: Oddjob (Harold Sakata), the man with the razor-sharp hat
brim, and Goldfinger (Gert Frobe). &QL; 
Of note: Ingenious gadgets and vicious villains lead you into a
hair-raising climax inside Fort Knox. Bond girls _ Honor Blackman
(as Pussy Galore), Shirly Eaton (as Jill Masterson, who is gilded
to death) and Tania Mallet (as Tilly Masterson). &QL; 
Song: Shirley Bassey's title track &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Thunderball (1965) &QL; 
Villain: Evil SPECTRE agent Emilio Largo (Adolfo Celi) &QL; 
Of note: Oscar-winning special effects and the elusive Bond zipping
out of trouble with a personal jetpack. Claudine Auger (as Domino)
was the girl. &QL; 
Song: Tom Jones belts out the title track. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
You Only Live Twice (1967) &QL; 
Villain: First look at arch-nemesis Ernst Stavro Blofeld (Donald
Pleasence). &QL; 
Of note: Bond fakes his own death in hopes of giving himself some
breathing room before exploring the volcano that houses Blofeld's
secret spacecraft. Bond girls _ Akiko Wakabayashi (as Aki), Karin
Dor (as Helga Brandt) and Mie Hama (as Kissy Suzuki). &QL; 
Song: Nancy Sinatra sings the title track. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Diamonds Are Forever: (1971) &QL; 
Villain: Blofeld and Bond meet again. &QL; 
Of note: A colorful comic-book adventure that brings bond to the
U.S. Well, Las Vegas anyway. Bond girl _ Jill St. John (as Tiffany
Case). &QL; 
Song: ``Diamonds Are Forever'' sung by Shirley Bassey. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
__ George Lazenby's one-shot &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
On Her Majesty's Secret Service: (1969) &QL; 
Villains: Blofeld (this time played by Telly Savalas), Marc Ange
Draco (Gabriele Ferzetti), while some Bond fans may choose
Lazenby. &QL; 
Of note: Diana Rigg (Mrs. Emma Peel of ``The Avengers'') plays
Draco's daughter and Bond's love interest. Incredible action
sequences take precedence over Lazenby's only role as Bond. &QL; 
Song: Louis Armstrong sings ``We Have All the Time in the World.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
__ The Roger Moore years &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Live and Let Die: (1973) &QL; 
Villain: Drug dealer Kananga (Yaphet Kotto). &QL; 
Of note: The Moore era starts off by being less _ with a messy plot
that seems to act as an excuse to film wild powerboat chase
sequences. Jane Seymour (as Solitaire) played the girl. &QL; 
Song: Paul McCartney and Wings do the title track ``Live and Let
Die.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Man With the Golden Gun: (1974) &QL; 
Villain: Evil Christopher Lee as assassin Scaramanga. &QL; 
Of note: Car chases taken to a whole new level in worldwide
locales. Britt Ekland (as Miss Bonnenuit) and Maude Adams (as
Andrea Anders) provide the female scenery. &QL; 
Song: Lulu sings the title track. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Spy Who Loved Me: (1977) &QL; 
Villain: The metal-mouthed Jaws (Richard Kiel) dispatched by Capt.
Nemo-esque Karl Stromberg (Curt Jurgens). &QL; 
Of note: A lavishly produced adventure with a ski jump into
oblivion that took 10 days to shoot. Barbara Bach (as Major Anya
Amasova) and Caroline Munro (as Naomi) are the girls. &QL; 
Song: Carly Simon's international smash, ``Nobody Does it
Better.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Moonraker: (1979) &QL; 
Villain: Jaws is brought back for an encore, but Bond's real
opposition is Deax (Michael Lonsdale). &QL; 
Of note: An eye-popping free-fall opening ... and Bond in space. A
big-budget entry that cost as much as the first eight Bond films
put together. Lois Child (as Dr. Holly Goodhead) and Corinne Clery
(as Corinne Dufour) are the girls. &QL; 
Song: Shirley Bassey sings the title song. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
For Your Eyes Only: (1981) &QL; 
Villain: Soviet agents plague Bond as he tries to recover computer
secrets. &QL; 
Of note: Spectacular chases, stunt work and a no-gimmicks,
down-and-dirty Bond. Carol Bouquet (as Melina) is the girl. &QL; 
Song: Sheena Easton sings the title track. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Octopussy: (1983) &QL; 
Villain: Maud Adams in the title role. &QL; 
Of note: A fistfight on top of an airplane makes for a very
entertaining show. Kristina Wayborn (as Magda) is the girl. &QL; 
Song: ``All Time High'' by Rita Coolidge. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A View to a Kill: (1985) &QL; 
Villains: Christopher Walken and Grace Jones. &QL; 
Of note: A battle atop the Golden Gate Bridge and a farewell to
Moore. Tanya Roberts (as Stacey Sutton) is the Bond girl. &QL; 
Song: Duran Duran sings the title track. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
__ The Timothy Dalton 2 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Living Daylights: (1987) &QL; 
Villain: Necros, played by Joe Don Baker. &QL; 
Of note: Exotic locales and great stunts make this an impressive
debut for Dalton. Maryam d' Abo (as Kara Malovy) plays the cello _
and with Bond. &QL; 
Songs: Title track by a-ha; ``Where Has Everybody Gone'' by the
Pretenders. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
License to Kill: (1989) &QL; 
Villain: Franz Sanchez (Robert Davi). &QL; 
Of note: Dazzling stunts, high adventure and a sexy companion for
Bond makes this one of the best. Carey Lowell (as Pam Bouvier) and
Talisa Soto (as Lupe Lamora) are the girls. &QL; 
Song: ``License to Kill'' sung by Gladys Knight. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
__ The Pierce Brosnan era &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
GoldenEye: (1995) &QL; 
Villain: Alec Trevelyan (Sean Bean), a former colleague turned
traitor. &QL; 
Of note: A bungee jump off the world's biggest dam. The role of M
is taken over by Judi Dench. Izabella Scorupco (as Natalya
Simonova) and Famke Janssen (as Xenia Onatopp) are the girls. &QL; 
Song: ``GoldenEye'' sung by Tina Turner. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tomorrow Never Dies: (1997) &QL; 
Villain: Jonathan Pryce as an evil media mogul. &QL; 
Of note: Bond's new and nifty gadget, the remote-controlled BMW,
isn't too shabby. Teri Hatcher (as Paris Carver) and Hong Kong
martial-arts star Michelle Yeoh (as Wai Lin) are the girls. &QL; 
Song: ``Tomorrow Never Dies'' by Sheryl Crow. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The World Is Not Enough: (1999) &QL; 
Villain: Robert Carlyle plays a terrorist. &QL; 
Of note: John Cleese joins the crew, and R. Sophie Marceau (as
Electra King) and Denise Richards (as Christmas Jones) are the
girls. &QL; 
Song: Garbage sings the title track. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
__ Outside the realm &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Casino Royale: (1967) &QL; 
Villain: Would you believe Woody Allen? &QL; 
Of note: This Bond film originated as a one-hour TV show in 1954
and was not part of author Ian Fleming's main body of work. The
movie's a '60s trip with five directors, including John Huston.
Everybody yuks it up throughout the film, which stars Peter
Sellers, David Niven and whoever else happened to be around when
they were shooting. Ursula Andress plays Mata Bond.  &QL; 
Song: Burt Bacharach and Hal David wrote the title song. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Never Say Never Again: (1999) &QL; 
Villain: Klaus Maria Brandauer plays Largo. &QL; 
Of note: Connery returns after a 12-year absence in this remake of
``Thunderball'' (which also fell outside the MGM rights). There are
enough jokes about an aging Bond, but Connery does look a bit long
in the tooth. Barbara Carrera (as Fatima Blush) and Kim Basinger
(as Domino) are the lovely ladies. &QL; 
Song: Lani Hall sings the title track, written by Alan and Marilyn
Bergman. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
