<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD EXCURSION IS BIG, ROOMY AND UNWIELDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Driving all kinds of different vehicles can cause
unexpected problems. Such as confronting a vast parking lot, when I
have to stop and ask myself not only where did I park but what did
I park.
</P>
<P>
   Not a problem with the new Ford Excursion. The moment I scanned
the lot, I could see it looming, like the Queen Mary docked among a
sea of dinghies or a woolly mammoth trying to appear inconspicuous
among a herd of gazelles.
</P>
<P>
   A true behemoth, the Excursion is the world's biggest
sport-utility vehicle, somewhat dwarfing the erstwhile holder of
the claim, Chevrolet Suburban, and making Ford's former big dog,
the Expedition, look like a shrinking violet.
</P>
<P>
   Excursion stands 7 inches longer, 4 inches wider and 6 inches
taller than a Suburban, and weighs about 2,000 pounds more. It's
built from Ford's construction-site tough guy, the F-250 Super Duty
pickup truck, and comes in either two- or four-wheel drive with
engines ranging from a 5.4-liter V-8 to a powerful 6.8-liter V-10
and a monster 7.3-liter diesel V-8.
</P>
<P>
   The Excursion is the sport-ute that environmentalists love to
hate, seen as a flash point for all that is wasteful and
over-the-top in our consumer society. It's viewed by some as an
oversize, gas-guzzling air polluter, a land-yacht for
status-seekers and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, see the Excursion as a successful blending of a
powerful, heavy-duty truck with a passenger vehicle, one that can
contain eight passengers and plenty of gear in spacious
surroundings, and tow 10,000 pounds (with the V-10 or diesel). It's
a truck for the great out of doors, although undoubtedly it will be
used most often for schlepping kids and groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Ford disputes the gross-polluter charge, claiming that the
technology used in the Excursion has reduced its emissions to an
acceptable level. Maybe, pound for pound.
</P>
<P>
   The gas-mileage issue is a bit harder to counter; there's no
official tally by the EPA because Excursion's gross weight is over
the limit to require a federal fuel-mileage designation. I poured
plenty of gas into the V-10 test truck, and the Excursion's
on-board computer showed that it was averaging just 10 miles per
gallon in a mix of urban and city driving. It has a 44-gallon gas
tank for good reason.
</P>
<P>
   The V-10 is one heck of an engine, however, pulling the 3{-ton
Tessie up to highway speed with a smooth rush of power. If I were a
hot-rodder, I'd be looking at this slick mill for a roadster
project.
</P>
<P>
   Other than being impressed by the engine and the excellent
automatic transmission, I was not terribly excited about the
Excursion's driveability. I had read previously some positive press
about the handling of the two-wheel-drive Excursion, but I found
the four-wheel-drive truck to be cumbersome at best.
</P>
<P>
   The ride was surprisingly rough, with the front suspension
turning every bump into a jarring hop while third-seat passengers
bounced heavily above the rear axle.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the wheel, you never lose the sense of maneuvering a big,
heavy truck, and you must alter your driving habits accordingly.
The steering is rather slow to react, despite being overboosted
with power assist, and the 4-wheel-disc brakes seemed to be taxed
to the limit in curbing the massive load of forward momentum.
</P>
<P>
   One thing's for certain, the Excursion doesn't have nearly the
handling or stopping power of the smaller Expedition, nor does it
have nearly as comfortable a ride. Expedition set a benchmark for
driveability in this class of vehicle, although I'm looking forward
to the new, improved Suburban, Tahoe and GMC Yukon that are coming
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Outward vision is great, because you're riding up there with the
semi drivers, but the Excursion's bulk allows smaller vehicles to
hide out in the blind spots. Little people, too.
</P>
<P>
   As well as supplying a good level of safety features for the
occupants, Ford has made the effort to protect other people sharing
the highway. There's a ``blocker beam'' under the front bumper to
keep the Excursion from overrunning a smaller vehicle in a rear-end
crash and a similar setup in the rear to keep a smaller vehicle
from submarining under the back bumper.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-lock brakes are standard, but side air bags are not.
Another thing I expected to see on the Excursion were gas and brake
pedals that were adjustable for shorter drivers, like they have in
the Expedition and, coming soon, in the Mercury Sable.
</P>
<P>
   The tailgate is a Dutch-door design, with the upper glass
folding up and the lower door splitting to either side, an
excellent design for rear vision and ease of loading.
</P>
<P>
   Excursion certainly has the space for hauling, especially after
removing the center seat, which comes out on rollers, creating a
cavernous cargo area. If cavernous is not big enough, the center
seats fold forward, leaving a cargo area large enough for sheets of
plywood or small bulldozers.
</P>
<P>
   The leather-bound interior of the test truck was handsome,
comfortable and workable, with a galaxy of cup holders. Leg, head
and hip room are generous in all positions.
</P>
<P>
   The Excursion is obviously not for everyone, mainly because of
its huge size (it fills a parking space completely from white line
to white line while hanging over either end). But there are plenty
of people who want them, with Ford taking more orders for the 2000
models than it originally had planned to build.
</P>
<P>
   The target markets are the wide-open spaces in Texas, Wyoming
and the like, but expect to see plenty of them coming to a shopping
center near you. You can't miss 'em. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vehicle type: Eight-passenger, four-door sport-utility vehicle,
rear/four-wheel drive. &QL; 
Base price: $40,205. &QL; 
Price as tested: $40,955. &QL; 
Engine: 6.8-liter V-10, 310 hp at 4,250 rpm, 425 lb-ft of torque at
3,250 rpm. &QL; 
Transmission: &QL; 
4-speed automatic. &QL; 
Curb weight: 7,190 pounds. &QL; 
Wheelbase: 137 inches. &QL; 
EPA mileage: &QL; 
N.A. On-board computer showed 10 mpg in highway/city mix. &QL; 
Highs: &QL; 
_Spacious interior. &QL; 
_Powerful engine. &QL; 
_Quality feel. &QL; 
Lows: &QL; 
_Cumbersome handling. &QL; 
_Rough ride. &QL; 
_Poor gas mileage. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bob Golfen can be reached at (602) 444-8106 or by e-mail at
bob.golfen(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
