<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOY-ROPER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRICK ROPER J.W. STOKER LASSOS A SPOT IN THE COWBOY HALL OF FAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF PRINCE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEATHERFORD, Texas _ For years, cats have chased rats out of
J.W. Stoker's barn, and for that he is grateful. But rarely did he
pet the cats or talk to them.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   Three kittens adopted him after their mother was killed by a
coyote several weeks ago. Stoker fed the kittens, one drop of
formula at a time, and now they follow him everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   He enjoys their presence. ``They've been sleeping in the
house,'' he said. ``They won't make very good barn cats.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoker is also sleeping in his house more these days.
</P>
<P>
   For much of his life, the 72-year-old trick roper has been on
the road, hauling a horse and trailer. He has twirled ropes for
presidents, singers, movie stars and a queen, and he once got a
glimpse of a goddess.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's alongside Roy Rogers, Gene Autry, Hopalong Cassidy and
other cowboy entertainers in the National Cowboy Hall of Fame in
Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel it's the highest honor you can have,'' said Stoker, who
was inducted Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Still, don't expect a cartwheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about it that much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stoker doesn't spend much time reflecting about small matters.
The sun comes up and goes down, and he does what needs to be done
in between, usually while chewing on a toothpick.
</P>
<P>
   His manager and assistant, Demetra Risenhoover, recently told a
visitor about Stoker's 1971 trip to perform for ``the queen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Queen Elizabeth?'' the visitor asked, looking at Stoker.
</P>
<P>
   The cowboy paused, perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't know her name,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Risenhoover laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it was Queen Elizabeth,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stoker's aw-shucks personality is endearing, but it might have
delayed his selection to the hallowed Hall. Lobbying for a
nomination is common, said Mitzi Riley, 71, a former trick rider
from Aledo and a member of the Hall who serves on the nominating
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people campaign and write letters and call around,''
Riley said. ``J.W. didn't do any of that. He's cowboy modest.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoker's reserve fades, however, when he performs.
</P>
<P>
   He wears flashy cowboy outfits with colorful scarves. He tucks
his pants inside handmade boots. He stands on his horse's back and
swings a rope above his head, making it dance and whoosh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's physical, but it's stuff I've done so long it's second
nature,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After his Hall of Fame induction, Stoker headed to New York for
a rodeo. But he is more likely these days to drive to Dallas and
perform at a business conference or at a child's birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   Many rodeos are cutting costs and no longer hiring entertainers
like Stoker. That's OK, he said. He is enjoying time at home after
so many years on the road.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, Stoker bought 25 acres of ranch land near Bankhead
Highway in Weatherford. He built a large barn for his horses with a
tiny room for himself. A bed and a window-unit air conditioner kept
him happy for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, he built a three-bedroom brick house. His only
extravagance is a full-sized fiberglass horse rearing up on his
hind legs in a rock garden next to his driveway.
</P>
<P>
   The surrounding area was once little more than prickly, rocky
land, but now grand houses have popped up, including a
multimillion-dollar house across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Makes my place look like an outhouse,'' he said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Stoker spends his time training horses, repairing fences, mowing
and talking to cats. He's not rich, but he's comfortable, and he's
proud that he made a life with a rope and a horse.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures and mementos from 60 years of rodeo performances are
stuffed haphazardly in a few boot boxes stacked in a closet. Only
with prodding does Stoker recount his past.
</P>
<P>
   He was born Sept. 30, 1927, on a Kansas farm. Several years
later, his dad gave him a Shetland pony named Peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   Infatuated with cowboys, Stoker joined the Santa Fe Trail Riders
and learned fancy riding and roping. He practiced before school,
during recess and after school and eventually became a world
champion juvenile roper. That's when a General Mills employee saw
him in 1939 at the Minnesota State Fair. The company put Stoker's
face on Wheaties boxes.
</P>
<P>
   During the Korean War, he was an entertainment specialist along
with singer Eddie Fisher, then a 21-year-old newcomer.
</P>
<P>
   The 1950s and 1960s were glorious. Singing cowboys ruled the
radios and movie theaters, and westerns such as Gunsmoke and
Bonanza dominated prime-time television.
</P>
<P>
   Rodeos were big, and almost all of them featured trick riders
and fancy ropers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, Stoker worked as an extra doing rope tricks in Marilyn
Monroe's ``Bus Stop,'' with rodeo scenes shot in Phoenix. One
morning, he was exercising his horse and noticed a pale, slight
woman sitting on the fence, watching him. They nodded, but did not
speak.
</P>
<P>
   Only later did it dawn on him that it was Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was so much smaller and so white and so thin, I just rode
by her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He performed for presidents Harry Truman and Ronald Reagan. He
remembers Steve McQueen as ``an oddball'' and Tex Ritter as
``down-to-earth.''
</P>
<P>
   He says Clint Eastwood hired him in 1979 to do rope tricks in
the movie ``Bronco Billy.''
</P>
<P>
   The stories wind down and the sun sinks. Stoker settles into a
leather chair, tired of talking about himself. He'll watch TV
awhile, say goodnight to his horses and go to bed.
</P>
<P>
   He never married, but has no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always happy doing what I was doing and being my own
boss,'' he said. ``I was never lonely. Everywhere I went was a
celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
