<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS LOOKING FOR MORE PRODUCTION FROM WIDEOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ J.J. Stokes has an idea for the San
Francisco 49ers' passing-game problems, one that his fellow wide
receivers agree with: Keep everything simple.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing against the masterful complexities of the West Coast
offense, but all that choreographed mayhem isn't helping the 49ers
these days. Stokes, Jerry Rice and Terrell Owens have only one
desire _ to have the football in their hands and be in a position
to do something with it.
</P>
<P>
   However that happens, they will gladly accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not talking about anything we haven't done in the past,''
Stokes said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking about a simple out, a smoke, a hitch, whatever. If
we run a simple rout, maybe we'll have a chance to make a big play
off of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Excuse the 49ers wide receivers for their frustrations. They
have so many reasons to be frazzled aside from the team's 3-5
record. They represent a major chunk of change for the 49ers. As a
trio, Stokes, Rice and Owens represent roughly a quarter of the
team's payroll, meaning they should feel most slighted when the
offense drones to a halt, as it has throughout this season.
</P>
<P>
   For a group of receivers that spent last season grappling with
the idea that 60 receptions wasn't a sufficient amount, this year
has been pure hell. Rice, Stokes and Owens would surely rejoice
over the days when a four-catch game would leaving them fuming.
Stokes, for one, has gone three games without amassing that many
receptions.
</P>
<P>
   Their numbers are staggering. Both Lawrence Phillips and Charlie
Garner are averaging more yards per reception than Rice, who is
gaining 9.3 yards every time he touches the ball. Owens has 25
receptions and missed two games with a high ankle sprain prior to
the bye week on Oct. 31. Stokes has 16 receptions and no
touchdowns. In 1998, this same group combined for 223 receptions.
Currently, they're on pace for 146.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get our receivers the ball,'' 49ers coach Steve
Mariucci said. ``We have some good receivers and they would like to
get involved. There was a stretch last year where we threw for 300
yards in six straight games. But that was last year's team, too.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the overwhelming problem for the 49ers. So much of last
year's magic has vanished with injuries to quarterback Steve Young
and running back Garrison Hearst and the early season shuffling of
the offensive line. The only area of the team that hasn't suffered
a major loss this season is wide receiver. Rice, Stokes and Owens
have paid the price for that.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of the year, they haven't been able to find
a rhythm with whoever is throwing the football. First Young
succumbed to heavily blitzing, finally being knocked unconscious
and out of the lineup in Week 3. Then his successor, Jeff Garcia,
fared no better. He played well in his debut against the Tennessee
Titans but declined over the next four weeks before eventually
losing his job to Steve Stenstrom on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to put a finger on that problem,'' Garcia said.
``Over the last four weeks, we just haven't given those guys many
chances to do anything. Against Pittsburgh (a 27-6 loss Sunday), it
was really difficult. The bad weather really affected my accuracy
and I felt like I got out of synch.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't just a feeling; it was reality. In that contest,
caught three passes, Rice two for a career-low two yards and Stokes
one for 11. Often, they trudged back to the huddle in the aftermath
of overthrown balls or drops that wouldn't have led to more than a
handful of yards anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Like their teammates, they were confused by the ineptitude of an
offensive system known for producing results regardless of
personnel or circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know what's going on,'' Owens said. ``I never
thought we would be 3-5 with everything unraveling like it is.
We're trying to make the best of our opportunities, but last year,
you knew you would have at least one chance a game to make a play.
Now you don't even know if you're going to touch the ball at all.''
</P>
<P>
   To a man, no wide receiver blames Garcia for this predicament.
They acknowledge it as a team dilemma, one that has resulted from
inconsistent pass protection, inexperience at quarterback and an
inability to run the ball on a weekly basis.
</P>
<P>
   But the offensive line has improved, the running game churned
for more than 200 yards last week and a new quarterback is under
center. Maybe all those factors will help the receivers. At this
point, they're praying something will.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to get our attitude back,'' Owens said. ``We have
to feel like we can beat the guys across from us, no matter what
position we're talking about. As receivers, we feel like we can
beat any defensive back. We all just have to get back on the same
page again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
