<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7705 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-INTERNET-REGULATION-B     11-12 1344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-REGULATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON GROPES FOR LAWS TO CONTROL THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w, a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's not a store, but it moves merchandise. It's
not a TV network, but it broadcasts to millions of people. It's not
a magazine, but it publishes plenty of material _ some of it
libelous, and plenty of it pornographic.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has become a massive economic and social force
almost entirely without regulation from Congress or federal
agencies. But increasingly, Washington is being forced to decide if
the laws concerning books, broadcast, and brick-and-mortar stores
are adequate to reckon with the wired world.
</P>
<P>
   In just the past week, the House passed a bill to give
electronic signatures the same validity as the handwritten version.
And the leader of a congressional commission called for banning all
sales taxes on purchases made over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Federal Trade Commission held a public
discussion on limits to ``on-line profiling,'' the practice of
tracking people as they click across the Web in order to advertise
products based on their habits. And last Friday, a federal judge
issued a stinging assessment of Microsoft Corp.'s business
practices that lays the groundwork for broad antitrust penalties.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the ultimate law or outcome is undecided, with
many people arguing that the old-world concepts of taxation,
antitrust, and other types of regulation have little place in
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our antitrust laws were enacted at a time of slow-moving
trains, not high-speed computers,'' said Senator Pete Domenici,
Republican of New Mexico, after the Microsoft ruling. ``I wonder
whether Congress should reconsider our antiquated antitrust laws
and look for a way to make them more responsive to today's global
high-technology economy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take much candlepower to see that this isn't going
to be an easy thing to do,'' Jerry Berman, executive director of
the Center for Democracy and Technology, said of Internet
regulation. ``The Internet is changing rapidly, and new (computer)
operating systems could be developed tomorrow, and gambling is
moving offshore,'' possibly beyond the reach of US laws. ``The idea
that everything can be worked out using traditional law is proving
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 79 bills were filed in Congress this year to regulate
access to the Internet and the material that travels across it,
according to a tally by Congressional Quarterly, which covers
Capitol Hill. Moreover, a range of federal departments, from health
agencies to stock-market regulators, are grappling with what the
move on line means for their area of the law.
</P>
<P>
   But on some of the largest issues, lawmakers are asking for a
pause before they act. They want time to better understand the new
world of networked computers, and time for industries to try their
hand at self-regulation. Moreover, speedy action resulted in the
Supreme Court rejecting one of their first efforts, a law aimed at
regulating on-line pornography and other material deemed harmful to
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first mantra of the Internet is that before the government
regulates, go slow, that this is a new medium, a young medium, and
it's feeling its way,'' Berman said.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Edward Markey, Democrat of Malden, said that
there are many established legal principles that should be extended
quickly to the Internet. For example, he said, Congress has barred
companies from tracking which cable television shows a person
watches and selling the data to marketers. Phone calling patterns
and video rental records are also private.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only question is whether this new commercial phenomenon
(of on-line shopping) should be held to the same standards as other
commerce,'' Markey said. Privacy and consumer protection laws
should protect people on line as much as in other activities, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The most active issues include:
</P>
<P>
   --Sales taxes. While on-line retail sales could grow to $80
billion next year, up from $9 billion in 1998, Congress last year
imposed a three-year moratorium on Internet taxes and appointed a
study commission.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which will report in April, must balance the
argument that taxes might choke Internet growth with the budgetary
needs of cities and states, which depend on sales tax revenues.
This week, the panel's chief proposed banning Internet sales taxes
and using federal money to cover the revenue that cities and states
would lose.
</P>
<P>
   --Stock trading. With on-line stock accounts expected to
quadruple in four years, to 20 million, regulators are just
beginning to grapple with how consumer-protection laws should apply
on line, where a rumor in a chat room can move stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Arthur Levitt, chairman of the Securities and Exchange
Commission, has warned that the established stock markets must use
the rise of on-line trading to give small traders the highest price
when they sell stock and the lowest price when they buy. Currently,
some critics say that individual investors do not get the best
prices because brokerage firms fill orders for large customers
first.
</P>
<P>
   --Privacy. While the number of households on line will jump to
43 percent this year, up from 6 percent in 1994, Congress has yet
to address many aspects of on-line privacy. At the lawmakers'
direction, the Federal Trade Commission last month issued rules to
protect the privacy of children but little has been done about
adult Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, lawmakers failed to meet their own deadline for
passing laws on medical records privacy, an issue made more
pressing because records are often stored electronically and
accessed over computer networks. Independently of Congress, the
Department of Health and Human Services recently issued a set of
privacy protections for electronic health records.
</P>
<P>
   --Gambling. The Justice Department has prosecuted several
on-line gambling operators and won several guilty pleas, using a
nearly 40-year-old law that bans wagers on phone lines or other
wires without state approval. But it is unclear whether these laws
apply to the Internet, and Congress has not yet spoken.
</P>
<P>
   --Antitrust. As soon as the Justice Department filed charges
against Microsoft, alleging that it used its Windows monopoly to
hurt competitors and consumers, critics said that the software
world moves too fast for antitrust regulation to be effective. What
looks like a monopoly today could be gone with a quick technology
shift tomorrow, they said.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the way Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson saw it. In his
200-page preliminary findings of fact last week, which agreed with
many of the government's claims, the federal district judge devoted
about 30 pages to discussing the durability of Microsoft's market
power.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson acknowledged that plenty of new computing products are
on the horizon, such as hand-held computers, ``smart'' cell phones,
and TV set-top boxes, which will make televisions more like
computers. He wrote that people may soon use these devices instead
of Microsoft software to send e-mail and browse the Web. He noted
the rise of Linux, a rival operating system to Microsoft's Windows.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that dampens the fact that Microsoft holds a
monopoly today, the judge wrote, and that its market power will
continue in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Others have disagreed, saying that the computer world moves too
quickly for prosecutors to respond. Their most signficant evidence:
After the trial began last year, one company that the government
says was injured by Microsoft's business practices _ Netscape
Communications Corp. _ was acquired by America Online, giving it
new resources for a fight with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this case ever makes it to the Supreme Court, Microsoft and
the Justice Department will be arguing about events in a
long-forgotten world,'' wrote David S. Evans of National Economic
Research Associates Inc. in Cambridge, Mass. in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
