<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SENSE ON EXECUTIONS FROM COURTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to believe, but it's true: The American justice system
produced two sensible rulings this week on issues involving capital
punishment. The rulings came down on the same day, in fact, and
both paved the way for condemned killers to finally face their fate
after years of successfully dodging the executioner.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the cases, a state district judge ruled that Texas
Death Row inmate Larry Keith Robison is sufficiently competent to
receive the lethal injection that should have been administered
nearly three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Robison was scheduled to be executed Aug. 17, but his trip to
the death chamber was delayed by the Texas Court of Criminal
Appeals after his lawyer claimed that Robison wasn't capable of
understanding the punishment. Judge Everett Young rejected the
claim Monday at a hearing in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Robison was convicted and sentenced to death for one of five
murders he committed near Lake Worth in August 1982 _ then
convicted and sentenced to death again after the original
conviction was thrown out on a technicality. His victims' loved
ones and the taxpayers of Texas wait patiently for Robison to
undergo the punishment he so richly deserves.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court, meanwhile, ventured into the realm of
common sense by rejecting the appeals of two condemned killers who
claimed that their lengthy stays on Death Row _ one for 19 years in
Nebraska, the other for 24 years in Florida _ added up to cruel and
unusual punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Can you believe it? Convicted killers and their lawyers employ
every trick in the law books to delay executions _ two-decade stays
on Death Row are commonplace _ and now we have the instigators of
the delays claiming that the delays are unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Supreme Court saw through this preposterous and
ironic argument.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Justice Clarence Thomas said, as quoted by The
Associated Press:
</P>
<P>
   ``Consistency would seem to demand that those who accept our
death penalty jurisprudence as a given also accept the lengthy
delay between sentencing and execution as a necessary
consequence.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if these vile excuses for human beings who
populate the nation's Death Rows want to postpone the inevitable by
filing appeal after appeal after appeal, they should be prepared to
wait in prison limbo for however long it takes for the legal system
to work its magic.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine that a legal argument could be any more
disingenuous than a condemned killer's claim that it takes too long
to put him out of his misery when in fact the only reason it takes
so long is because the killer keeps putting it off with redundant
appeals. If these creeps are so eager to face their personal
doomsdays, why don't they just shut up and face them?
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to Larry Keith Robison, who testified the
other day that the delay of his execution was not his doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready to accept my execution in August,'' Robison said.
``I was ready to go peacefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Good for him. It's high time that the state of Texas put this
guy to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   So why are the do-gooders and bleeding hearts working so hard to
prevent the fate that Robison is so perfectly willing to accept?
</P>
<P>
   That's an easy one. It's what do-gooders and bleeding hearts do.
It's what they live for. You'd think that these nitwits could keep
themselves plenty busy just trying to save all the homicidal
maniacs who don't want to be executed without gumming up the works
trying to prevent the long-overdue death of a man who knows that
it's long overdue and just wants to get it over with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm willing to accept the ruling of the court on this
matter,'' Robison said.
</P>
<P>
   This is a man who understands exactly what he's saying and doing
_ just as he understood what he was doing back in 1982 when he
slaughtered five people whose surviving loved ones deserve, at long
last, to see justice done.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, delaying an execution for 20 years really
is cruel and unusual punishment _ not for the killer, but for
society.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
