<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAIDERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN DIEGO LINEBACKER IS THE BEST. JUST ASK HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRIAN MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALAMEDA, Calif. _ If the Oakland Raiders want to neutralize San
Diego Chargers linebacker Junior Seau, they may just want to hold a
full-length mirror in front of No. 55.
</P>
<P>
   Because nothing makes Junior Seau drop all he's doing like the
chance for Junior Seau to admire Junior Seau.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Seau's self-confidence is to be admired. While most NFL
players shy away from any topic other than the proverbial ``one
game at a time,'' Seau isn't afraid to talk about Seau. And Seau's
talent. And Seau's impact on the game. And Seau's future
enshrinement in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a guy who, asked to describe his play, said he liked to
think he has the athletic ability of Lawrence Taylor, the
intelligence of Mike Singletary and the durability of Clay
Matthews. What, Dick Butkus slipped his mind? Here's a guy who, in
a telephone interview with sports writers this week, was asked if
he is at a point in his career where his body and mind have peaked
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say I am,'' Seau, 30, said. ``And it's a comfortable
feeling to go out on the field and know that, no matter what type
of personnel you put out there, I can take a glance at what you
give me and 85 percent of the time I know what you're going to do
and when you're going to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys think they know football, but they really
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a guy who was asked about his tendencies to study film,
and managed to turn the answer into a boast of how every NFL team
fears him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't sit there every day of the week and wonder if my
opponents are thinking of me,'' Seau said. ``I know they are. And I
know they have my picture up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Seau was also asked if he thinks about his place among the
all-time greats. While nearly every NFL player gives the standard
answer of: ``Guys, that's for you to decide,`` or ``Guys, I worry
about this week's game plan,'' Seau instead tasted the topic like a
fine wine, enjoying every implication.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are bringing that up,'' Seau said. ``In order
to be special in this league, you've got to put years together.
I've been able to withstand a lot of injuries and be blessed with
the health that I have ... the only reason I haven't slowed down is
due to the knowledge of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   For a guy raised in American Samoa who didn't speak English
until the age of 7, the University of Southern California product
sure has mastered the use of the first-person in his second
language.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the catch: Seau backs it all up. All of it.
</P>
<P>
   Because yes, the Raiders acknowledge, they have spent all week
thinking of Seau and yes, the Raiders believe he is one of the
NFL's truly special players and yes, they buy all of it.
</P>
<P>
   Priority number one when the Raiders try to move the ball
against the NFL's No. 6-ranked defense on Sunday: They will have to
do it despite the play of San Diego's leading tackler, sacker and
eight-time Pro Bowler.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a Hall of Famer,'' Raiders coach Jon Gruden said. ``How
he keeps his energy level up is beyond me. I'd like to know what
he's eating, how much he's sleeping, what program he's on, because
I want to get on that. Since I've been in the league, he's probably
the one guy that I admire the most. He's amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every young football player, they ought to make Football
101 and they ought to watch him play. If anything, he's gotten
quicker, stronger and more irritating for an opposing coach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 1652EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
