<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7850 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     11-12 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARRY KEITH ROBISON: JUSTICE DELAYED, BUT PERHAPS NOT DENIED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Slowly, one tortured legal step after another, the relatives of
Bruce Gardner are inching toward justice.
</P>
<P>
   A ruling this week by state district Judge Everett Young that
Larry Keith Robison is mentally competent to be executed for
killing the Fort Worth man in 1982 brings the final curtain of a
17-year tragedy one act closer.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, relatives of five victims are waiting for the end of
this passion play. Although Robison was only tried for the shooting
death of 33-year-old Gardner, he savagely killed Rickey Lee Bryant,
Gloria Ann Reed and her son, Scott, and Earline Barker the same
bloody August day.
</P>
<P>
   Robison was just hours away from lethal injection on Aug. 17
when the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals issued a temporary stay,
ordering a competency hearing to determine whether Robison
understood that he was to be put to death for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   Robison's mother, his attorneys and anti-death-penalty advocates
have long professed that mental illness should exempt Larry from
his jury-imposed sentence with the needle. Make that twice
jury-imposed sentence. Two different juries seated before two
different judges determined that Robison was sane when he committed
the crimes, sane when he was convicted and sane when he was
sentenced.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony this week by five mental health experts, including
three hired on Robison's behalf, along with Robison's own apologies
to the victims' families led Young to the right decision: Larry
Keith Robison clearly understands the consequence that awaits him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the judge's ruling this week is not the end of the story.
Attorneys for Robison _ or more accurately, for his mother, who has
fought doggedly to keep her son's death penalty from being carried
out _ say they plan to appeal Young's competency ruling, saying
that more tests are needed and that Larry only said what he said
because he doesn't want the world to think he's mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable that a mother would want to do everything
possible to save the life of her son, but another round of appeals
is nothing more than a stall tactic. Drag it out long enough, and
one could expect Robison's lawyers to attempt to argue that
delaying the execution is in itself cruel and unusual punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the U.S. Supreme Court shut down that avenue this
week when it refused to consider whether the execution of prisoners
nearly two decades after taking up residence on Death Row is
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Appeals from Florida and Nebraska Death Row inmates who claimed
that delayed executions _ one for 20 years, the other for almost 25
_ violated their Eighth Amendment rights were rejected. Justice
Clarence Thomas wrote one of the most common-sense concurrences to
ever come out of the high court: ``I am unaware of any support in
the American constitutional tradition or in this court's precedent
that a defendant can avail himself of the panoply of (Rappeals) and
then complain when his execution is delayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Death-penalty opponents have been working overtime on Robison's
case, citing how ``barbaric and capricious'' the act of capital
punishment is. In truth, the death penalty is the least arbitrary
and capricious punishment meted out in the American criminal
justice system.
</P>
<P>
   The law is relentless to the point of obsessiveness in finding
grounds to set aside a death sentence. If it weren't, this country
wouldn't have killers sitting on Death Row decade after decade.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 25 years, less than 500 Death Row felons have seen
their sentences carried out. More than 2,000 have had their
sentences vacated. A Death Row prisoner is more likely to have the
sentence overturned, commuted, a new trial ordered or a pardon
granted than he is to be executed.
</P>
<P>
   So don't talk to the families of Bruce Gardner, Rickey Lee
Bryant, Earline Barker, and Gloria Ann and Scott Reed about how
``capricious'' capital punishment is in this country.
``Capricious'' may be used to describe whatever evil and
inexplicable urge drove Larry Keith Robison to slaughter five
people on Aug. 10, 1982 _ but please don't insult the memories of
the victims by using it to describe justice, no matter how long it
might be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or at (817) 390-7599. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
