<SLUG> BC-STYLE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 Attn: Style and Leisure Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, Nov. 14, and thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   BODY-MIND-WORKOUTS (New York) _ Though Tae-Bo's 15 minutes of
martial-arts workout seem to be up, it has produced spinoffs that
fuse American fitness with ethnic cultural traditions, promising
not only to strengthen the body but also to integrate it with the
mind. Now the art of capoiera from Brazil and krav maga from Israel
claim to achieve this connection. By Alex Witchel. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   BIRTHDAY-BASHES (New York) _ Writers about raising children may
preach modesty in birthday parties or advise inviting one guest for
each year celebrated; but all over New York, parents are ignoring
them. ``We have never been busier,'' said Chuck Santoro, aka
Professor Winkle, who with his partner, Liz Nagengast, aka Ms.
Teazlebee, runs In Tandem Productions, which puts on elaborate
children's parties. Besides playing host to FAO Schwarz parties,
they offer Madeline brunches for girls and Batman brunches for boys
at the Four Seasons Hotel for about $4,000. The American Museum of
Natural History lets members have birthday parties among its
exhibits for $1,500 and up. ``People are spending more money than
they ever have for kids that are younger and younger,'' said
Katherine Wyse Goldman, author of ``New York's 50 Best Places to
Have a Kids Party'' (City &AMP; Company, $12). By Monique P. Yazigi.
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   BUTLER-BOOK (Undated) _ According to a new book by Paul Burrell,
``In the Royal Manner: Expert Advice on Etiquette and Entertaining
From the Former Butler to Diana, Princess of Wales'' (Warner, $28),
is that, let me quote here, ``style is not the exclusive preserve
of the rich and the famous.'' ``Style,'' the book says, ``can be
achieved by anyone.'' Burrell, a cheery fellow of 41, looks a lot
like Tom Hanks but who, unlike Tom, is presently without a
full-time job. By Joyce Wadler. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-DOGMA (New York) _ This is about as exciting as my life
gets on a Saturday night, going to Mass,'' said Kevin Smith, who
wrote, directed and acted in the new film ``Dogma.'' Going to Mass
has lately become exciting for Smith, thanks to the prospect of
confrontation arising from ``Dogma.'' The Catholic League picketed
its premiere at the New York Film Festival in October, citing the
film's implication that Mary and Joseph had sex and a second child,
that one of Jesus's collateral descendants works in an abortion
clinic and so on. By Linda Lee. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   SKIN-DOCTORS (Undated) _ Welcome to the age of the new
dermatology, the once humble medical specialty that is elbowing
aside plastic surgery as a glamour profession. Gone are the days
when acne sufferers shamefully scurried to a skin doctor to have
pimples popped in drab green examining rooms. Today's skin doctors,
repackaged as beauty gurus, are marketing their own cosmetics,
promising to reverse the effects of aging and _ the latest trend _
opening their own day spas, complete with facials, seaweed wraps
and a nice soak in a Jacuzzi. By Elizabeth Hayt. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Despite all the gloomy predictions
that the summer's drought would drain the woods of color this fall,
I've seen some pretty fiery sweet gums, maples and scarlet oaks.
But I also watched the leaves of birches and dogwoods, both
shallow-rooted trees, droop and turn brown by mid-July. Some trees,
especially those on dry hills, simply toppled over. By Anne Raver.
</P>
