<HEADER>
A7855 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     11-12 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYOTA ROLLS OUT STUNNING NEW CELICA FOR 2000
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The seventh-generation Toyota Celica sport hatchback began
rolling into dealer showrooms last month as a 2000 model,
completely redesigned from the roof to the road.
</P>
<P>
   This subcompact sports-car wannabe is designed for people who
like the looks of a sporty vehicle, but can't afford a real sports
car. The new design, a product of Toyota's California studio, is
worthy of a vehicle a lot more expensive than the Celica's
mid-teens to low $20,000 base prices.
</P>
<P>
   Two models are offered: the base GT, which lists for $16,695,
and the uplevel GT-S, which we tested. The GT-S, which lists for
$21,165 before extras are tacked on, gets a bit more power than the
GT model.
</P>
<P>
   Both vehicles carry the same basic 1.8-liter four-cylinder
engine, but a special variable valve timing and lift system in the
GT-S engine gives it 180 horsepower, 40 more than that of the GT.
</P>
<P>
   That extra power takes some effort to get to, however, since the
GT-S engine doesn't reach peak performance until 7,600 rpm _ just
200 rpm under redline. The 133 foot-pounds of torque don't develop
fully until 6,800 rpm, so this vehicle is a bit slow getting
started.
</P>
<P>
   But don't forget: it's not really a sports car. If it were, it
would have at least a six-cylinder engine, and it would cost a lot
more. It would have rear-wheel drive, too; instead, it has
front-wheel drive, which takes a good bit away from what its
roadhandling characteristics could be.
</P>
<P>
   Just like a Ford Mustang with a four- or six-cylinder engine,
the Celica is meant more for show than go, which matches its
projected buyer demographics. The car is aimed primarily at young
women, most of whom probably won't care that there isn't a lot of
macho power under the hood.
</P>
<P>
   Climbing into the Celica, my head touched the ceiling and I'm
just barely 5-foot-10.
</P>
<P>
   To make it more comfortable for me, I would have to forgo the
optional $880 moon roof, which takes up about two inches of head
room. Forget putting anyone larger than a small child in the back
seat; it's there mostly for insurance purposes (to keep the car out
of the higher-cost sports-car class). The rear seat does fold down
to increase cargo area, however.
</P>
<P>
   The exterior is absolutely beautiful, with a cab-forward design
that Toyota describes as ``a high-fashion look with Indy-car
elements.'' The projector-beam halogen headlights are decidedly
high-tech and futuristic, and the sharp-edged side panels and hood
air scoop add considerable excitement to the overall look.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently gone, at least for now, is the convertible version of
the Celica. No mention is made of it in Toyota product literature
for 2000. The Celica comes only in the hatchback body style,
although it really doesn't look like a hatchback _ it looks like a
coupe.
</P>
<P>
   GT models come with a five-speed manual transmission or an
optional four-speed automatic. With the GT-S, a six-speed manual
gearbox is standard, and this is the best choice to wring the most
power out of the engine. A four-speed automatic with
steering-wheel-mounted sport-shift buttons is optional. This
arrangement, like that found on a Formula One race car, allows for
clutchless manual shifting of gears to improve performance.
</P>
<P>
   The Celica has MacPherson struts up front and a double-wishbone
suspension in the rear, which work together to hold the car to the
road fairly well. Again, it's no sports car, but it does hug the
road in tight curves much better than the average family sedan.
</P>
<P>
   The brakes on the GT-S have great stopping power, thanks to
11.5-inch ventilated front discs and solid, 10-inch rear disks. The
GT model has 10-inch ventilated front discs and eight-inch rear
drum brakes, which aren't quite as effective. Antilock brakes are
optional, and were not included on our test car. That is a safety
feature that should be standard.
</P>
<P>
   Front air bags are standard, but Toyota offers side air bags
($250) for the driver and front passenger as an option.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen-inch steel wheels are standard on the GT, while 15-inch
alloy wheels are standard on the GT-S. Ours came with optional
16-inch alloy wheels ($60).
</P>
<P>
   Standard equipment on GT models includes air-conditioning, a
six-speaker AM/FM/cassette/compact-disc in-dash stereo, power
steering and power mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   With the GT-S, Toyota adds power windows and door locks, cruise
control, fog lights, aluminum sport pedals, and a premium
AM/FM/cassette/CD system with eight speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Factory options on our test vehicle included the moon roof,
16-inch wheels, side air bags, leather-faced front seats ($620),
and rear deck-lid spoiler ($435).
</P>
<P>
   Distributor-installed options included a vehicle exterior
``protection package'' for $199 (what, Toyota doesn't protect the
finish at the factory?), and the ``extra-mile option package''
($775), which added permanent etching of the vehicle identification
number on the windows, custom pin striping, a cargo net, floor
mats, and a rearview mirror with built-in digital compass and
outside thermometer.
</P>
<P>
   Total price of our test car was $24,669, including $455
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings for the 180-horsepower engine with
six-speed manual transmission are 23 miles per gallon in the city
and 32 mpg on the highway. The tank holds 14.5 gallons of gasoline,
and unleaded super is recommended for the GT-S. The GT model runs
on regular unleaded and gets up to 28 mpg in the city and 34 mpg on
the highway.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE: 2000 TOYOTA CELICA GT-S SPORT HATCHBACK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE PACKAGE: Subcompact, two-door, four-cylinder,
sport-hatchback. Highlights: With an all-new California-born design
for 2000, the Celica looks a lot more expensive than it is. It
comes in two trim levels, GT and GT-S, with a 180-horsepower
1.8-liter engine in the GT-S model. The car handles well, and shows
great attention to detail _ a Toyota trademark.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVES: Could use more power via a six-cylinder engine; head
room is limited, cramping even marginally tall people.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR COMPETITORS: Ford Mustang, Chevrolet Camaro, Honda
Prelude, Mitsubishi Eclipse, Pontiac Firebird.
</P>
<P>
   EPA FUEL ECONOMY: 23 miles per gallon city/32 highway.
</P>
<P>
   BASE PRICE: $21,165 plus $485 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE AS TESTED: $24,669, including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD RATING: B.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III is transportation writer and
automotive columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Contact him
at 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford, TX 76022; telephone
(817) 685-3810; e-mail chambers(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
