<HEADER>
A7858 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-E-COMMERCE13-COX     11-12 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HIGH TECH INDUSTRY TO WORLD TRADE BODY: HANDS OFF E-COMMERCE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. high-tech industry Friday called on
foreign governments to keep their hands off the booming
international digital
</P>
<P>
   marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   With the full White House backing, industry leaders will press
for unimpeded e-commerce trade rules at the coming World Trade
Organization (WTO) meeting. Two key groups have joined in drafting
a position paper that says:
</P>
<P>
   ``The WTO ministers should make a commitment to keep electronic
commerce barrier-free. Such a commitment would set the tone and
direction for ongoing liberalization, (and) foster a transparent,
predictable and technology neutral environment that will help spur
global economic growth throughout the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement was released by Robert Holleyman, president and
chief executive officer of the Business Software Alliance, which
represents such leading software developers as Microsoft Corp., and
Rhett Dawson, president of Information Technology Industry Council,
the trade association of information technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   At a briefing for reporters, Holleyman noted that 54 percent of
software revenues of domestic firms are currently being generated
beyond U.S. borders. ``The benefits of liberalized e-commerce trade
are enormous,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts predict that by 2003, the amount of e-commerce
conducted over the Internet will top $1 trillion, while the number
of Internet users worldwide will rise from 196 million to 500
million, with the biggest percentage jump occurring outside the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a recent survey of 50 big U.S. online retailers,
conducted by Jupiter Communications, found that 28 percent of these
companies have mounted Internet pages targeted at foreign buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The e-commerce issue will rank high on the agenda when the 134
members of the World Trade Organization gather Nov. 30 to Dec. 3 in
Seattle. Both the Clinton administration and the Republican-led
Congress have signaled their strong support for continuing on an
indefinite basis the duty-free e-commerce policy begun last year.
</P>
<P>
   WTO members have already reached a preliminary accord not to
levy import duties on e-commerce until at least 2001. But a major
battle looms in Seattle between the United States and the 15-member
European Union and over how to classify the burgeoning business for
trade purposes
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans will argue that every item traded over the
Internet should be treated as a service. Washington, however, wants
e-commerce to remain more nebulous, to be treated as ``virtual
goods'' or left unclassified.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction is vital because if such downloaded items as
music, videos and books are viewed as services, then current trade
rules provide for much more restricted market access than the kind
of across-the-board access enjoyed by most goods.
</P>
<P>
   India and several other third-world nations are also expected to
balk when the ministers seek to fit e-commerce into the tangle of
laws that discipline world trade.
</P>
<P>
   Indian officials appear ready to use e-commerce liberalization
as a bargaining chip to gain concessions in other trade areas, such
as agriculture. A U.S. trade delegation has been sent to New Delhi
in a bid to convince that government_ which heavily subsidizes the
training of computer programmers _ that it is in India's
self-interest not to block world e-commerce expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need a whole new set of rules for e-commerce,''
Susan Esserman, the deputy U.S. trade representative, told Congress
last month. ``The existing regulations can apply.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
