<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7861 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-PLANE-1113-COX     11-12 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PLANE-1113-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOLDIERS SEARCH FOR WRECKAGE OF MISSING FOOD PLANE IN KOSOVO; 24
POSSIBLY DEAD
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Soldiers from the international
peacekeeping force in Kosovo searched the hills near the Serbian
border Friday night for a humanitarian aid airplane that vanished
from radar earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   There were conflicting reports late Friday as to whether the 21
passengers and three crew members on the World Food Program (WFP)
chartered flight were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was on approach to the militarily controlled airport
here in Pristina when it disappeared, said Bernard Kouchner, the
head of the United Nations Mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Aboard the aircraft included staff from the WFP, the U.N.
Mission in Kosovo (UNMIK), U.N. volunteers, non-governmental
organizations and a Canadian official. Their names were not
released.
</P>
<P>
   While officials in Kosovo said they could not confirm that the
plane had crashed, a WFP executive in Rome told reporters that the
aircraft had gone down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just learned that the flight has unfortunately crashed,''
said Catherine Bertini, the Rome-based agency's executive director
told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters reported that an unidentified U.N. official said search
teams had found the wreckage near a village 25 miles north of
Pristina, Kosovo's provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials in Pristina denied that any wreckage had been
found by early evening.
</P>
<P>
   Kouchner said there was no immediate way to know what happened.
The U.N. assumed administrative control over Kosovo in June after
Serbian-led Yugoslav forces were forced to leave following a 78-day
bombing campaign by NATO. The international community intervened to
stop the Serbs from ethnically cleansing the province of its
Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot of the twin-engine turbo-prop passenger plane had been
in radio contact with controllers in Pristina minutes before the
aircraft disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was on a routine flight between Rome and Pristina for
WFP, a U.N.-affiliated organization. It disappeared from radar at
about 11:20 a.m. local time. The French-made ATR 42 chartered from
the Balmoral Co. in South Africa, left Rome's Ciampino Airport at
9:05 a.m. (3:05 a.m. EST), the WFP said.
</P>
<P>
   The military force in Kosovo, known as KFOR, immediately
deployed helicopters to search the hills north of Pristina where
radar last indicated the aircraft's location, said Kouchner during
a briefing with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Squads of troops also were deployed in the area, which has been
identified as containing minefields, said U.S. Brigadier Gen. Jack
Schmitt, the head of KFOR ground operations.
</P>
<P>
   The ground search was called off at sunset, Schmitt said. ``It's
a mountainous area, very rugged with numerous known minefields so
it is very, very dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   After nightfall, as family members gathered outside the U.N.
headquarters here in Pristina awaiting news, KFOR continued
searching for the aircraft with helicopters equipped with special
night vision and thermal detection equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
