<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MARY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MARY, MOTHER OF JESUS': IT DOES BETTER WHEN IT STICKS TO
SCRIPTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review. Time,
channel are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By ANITA GATES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the end of the NBC film ``Mary, Mother of Jesus,'' Pernilla
August as the title character is asked by her son's disciples what
they should do now that Jesus is gone. That's simple, she says,
with an attempt at a beatific smile, they should ``try to teach as
he taught, live as he lived and love as he loved.''
</P>
<P>
   Any script that sums up the meaning of the life of Jesus (which
is what this does, despite the title) with greeting card sentiment
is in deep trouble. And this one, by Albert Ross and directed by
Kevin Connor, whose previous work includes television movies on
Mother Teresa and Diana, Princess of Wales, is sadly simple-minded.
When John the Baptist's headless corpse is thrown to the crowd
waiting for him _ this is the New Testament influenced by Tarantino
_ someone cries out, ``They've murdered him!'' You think?
</P>
<P>
   Connor does better when he sticks to Scripture. For instance,
when the aforementioned John, while baptizing new converts in the
River Jordan, looks up and sees Jesus in the flesh for the first
time, he announces convincingly, ``Behold the Lamb of God, who
takes away the sins of the world.'' But there isn't nearly enough
of that in this very disappointing two-hour movie, a project of
Bobby Shriver and his mother, Eunice Kennedy Shriver, who served as
executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   The only real reason to watch ``Mary, Mother of Jesus'' is to
see Christian Bale play Jesus as a confident, purposeful, sexy
young revolutionary. After all the soft-spoken, sad-eyed Jesuses in
movies past, Bale's interpretation is, pardon the choice of words,
a revelation. When he gently but firmly tells Mary that he has to
go on the road and leave her behind, and later _ shortly before the
Last Supper _ when he tells her, ``Now it's nearly over,'' he could
be Bobby Sands, the Irish Republican Army martyr, explaining to his
mother why he has to go on a hunger strike. Or just about any young
man with intense political convictions that go against the
Establishment of the time. Bale has said that Che Guevara was one
of his inspirations for the role.
</P>
<P>
   Bale was born with a mixed blessing, at least for actors:
striking good looks. This is often mentioned in reviews of his
films, which include ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' (Demetrius),
``Velvet Goldmine'' (the journalist) and even ``Empire of the Sun''
(the boy), Steven Spielberg's 1987 film, when Bale was 14. In
``Mary, Mother of Jesus,'' this adds a welcome credibility to
Jesus' remarkable popularity during the three short years he
preached.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with biblical movies is that scholars don't know a
lot about the main characters beyond what the Bible tells us.
Sometimes screenwriters decide to invent personal lives for the
historical figures, and that leads to lines like Nina Foch's to
Charlton Heston in ``The Ten Commandments'': ``Moses, you beautiful
fool!'' At other times screenwriters stick to the biblical facts,
which don't do much emotional delving, and end up with scenes that
look like dramatized re-creations on ``America's Most Wanted.''
This happens a lot in ``Mary, Mother of Jesus,'' from the
water-into-wine miracle at the wedding in Cana to Jesus' entering
Jerusalem on a donkey while believers wave palm fronds.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. August as Mary is lost in all this re-created detail. Even
she has compared this role to the one she played in ``Star Wars:
Episode One _ The Phantom Menace'': the mother of Anakin Skywalker,
who will grow up to be Darth Vader. In ``Star Wars'' mythology,
that is as close as you can get to having given birth to the Devil.
Anakin's birth, too, was a matter of immaculate conception. But in
the ``Star Wars'' role Ms. August, who is best known for working in
Ingmar Bergman films, exhibits a complicated, noble maternal love,
a fierce resignation to her son's inevitable departure and to his
future, which cannot include her. As Mary, Ms. August seems to be
straining to convey some of that intensity _ or at least an
emotional radiance _ but neither ever surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   It would be interesting, from a feminist perspective, to see the
story of Mary's entire life, before the Annunciation and after the
Resurrection. This film is about the 33 years of her son's life,
with cruel Roman soldiers, stonings and unconvincingly unruly mobs
thrown in for action fans.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MARY, MOTHER OF JESUS'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Sunday on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Eunice Kennedy Shriver and Bobby Shriver, executive producers;
Howard Ellis, producer; Kevin Connor, director. Written by Albert
Ross, based on material by John Goldsmith. Produced by the Shriver
Family Film Company.
</P>
<P>
   With: Pernilla August (Mary), Christian Bale (Jesus), David
Threlfall (Joseph), Geraldine Chaplin (Elizabeth), Melinda Kinnaman
(Young Mary), Toby Bailiff (Young Jesus), Hywel Bennett (Herod),
Christopher Lawford (Rueben), Simone Bendix (Mary Magdalene),
Christopher Routh (John the Baptist), Crispian Belfrage (James),
Robert Addie (Pontius Pilate), Michael Mears (John).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 1716EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7892 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-FILIPINO-VET-HNS &LR;      11-12 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILIPINO-VET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILIPINOS STRUGGLE TO GET U.S. VETERANS BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRIAN MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As a Filipino in the U.S. Army during World War
II, Pfc. Gary Aranal endured the Bataan death march after his unit
surrendered to Japanese forces in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   More than 55 years later, Aranal is involved in a different
battle. He is fighting to get the same veterans benefits that other
American soldiers receive.
</P>
<P>
   Aranal, commander of the Veterans Federation of Filipino
Americans in Daly City, said the United States has ``forgotten
about its own citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Aranal, 73, was one of 400 Filipino war veterans who turned out
Thursday at the grand opening of the Veterans Equity Center, a
small advocacy and assistance office in San Francisco. The opening,
timed with Veterans Day, was used by many of the veterans to plead
for more help as time runs out on the aging generation's cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``America hasn't come to our aid,'' said Federico Rivas, 80, a
retired lieutenant who lives in San Francisco. ``We want to get the
benefits promised to us by General (Douglas) MacArthur,'' who
commanded American and Philippine forces in the Philippines at the
time of the surrender of the islands in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   The situation creates a special tension for the veterans, who
remain loyal to the United States despite their struggles.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the veterans saluted the U.S. flag in commemoration of
Veterans Day while some acted out a short skit chronicling the
Japanese invasion of the Philippines and MacArthur's eventual
victory in what was then an American commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   But the events and speeches belied a sense of betrayal felt by
many of the veterans, who equate their compensation with
recognition of their service in the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still profess loyalty to the U.S. in spite of all that's
happened against us,'' Aranal said. ``We really feel bad about this
but there's nothing we can do except keep fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, about 200,000 Filipinos fought alongside
American troops under MacArthur, who had recaptured the islands by
July 1945. Though U.S. leaders promised the veterans they would
receive U.S. citizenship and veterans benefits after the war,
Congress withdrew that offer in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   It would be 44 years before President George Bush signed a
citizenship bill, allowing the veterans to emigrate to the United
States. The law, however, did not address benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands took advantage of the offer in hopes they could
eventually win their veterans benefits while bringing their
families to the States. But after almost a decade, many are now
stranded here, receiving meager Social Security checks that won't
pay the cost of bringing their wives and other family here. And
most won't return to the Philippines because they will lose their
Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   It has become a lonely and frustrating existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad to be here, separated from our families,'' said Mario
Enrique-Lim, 87, a retired major in the medical corps. ``We're used
to having close-knit families in the Philippines.''
</P>
<P>
   Founders of the Veterans Equity Center hope they can ease the
situation for the veterans. The center offers health, legal and
immigration advice to veterans who may not know where to go to
receive it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the veterans feel secluded and isolated and are
hesitant to avail themselves to the resources out there for them,''
said Lourdes Tancinco, a San Francisco lawyer and president of the
center's board of directors. ``Because of the language and cultural
problems, they fear they won't be understood.''
</P>
<P>
   While the center provides limited help for the veterans, the
real aid would come with the long-awaited military benefits. The
benefits would include monthly payments of up to $700 for veterans
and medical attention at any Department of Veterans Affairs
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   After four consecutive tries in Congress, a benefits bill was
not introduced in the most recent session. Filipino leaders are
first trying to get a pending humanitarian bill passed that will
allow the veterans to return to the Philippines while still
receiving 75 percent of their Social Security benefits, said Abe
Angeles, secretary general of the Sons and Daughters of Filipino
War Veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Angeles said perhaps as many as 500 veterans in San Francisco
would return to the Philippines if the humanitarian bill passes.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's not the ultimate goal, it would provide many
veterans the means to return home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better dying in their motherland than dying here alone,''
Angeles said.
</P>
<P>
   Time is running short for the veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much time left and we're dying every day,'' Aranal
said. ``That's why this is so disgusting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 1717EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7899 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-BODY-MIND-WORKOUTS-$A     11-12 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BODY-MIND-WORKOUTS-$ADV14-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A HUFF AND A PUFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Nov. 14)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When someone has been Mr. America, it's tough to
ignore him when he talks physiques. Rich Barretta, a personal
trainer who charges $150 an hour to inspire Manhattan's
office-bound bodies, recently opened Duomo at 11 E. 26th St.
``Stepping is pretty much dead,'' he proclaimed, touting instead
the latest trend in workouts: aerobic versions of battle, namely
capoiera (pronounced ca-PWHERE-ah), which is Brazilian martial
arts, and krav maga (pronounced krav ma-GAH), which is Israeli
hand-to-hand combat.
</P>
<P>
   Who said New Yorkers are getting nicer?
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always looking for something new and different,''
Barretta said. ``I thought we should go find art forms from around
the world that have been getting people in shape for hundreds of
years.'' These also include belly dancing and kick boxing. ``I want
martial-arts instructors, not Tae-Bo instructors,'' he said,
referring to last year's rage, which combined boxing, aerobics and
tae kwon do.
</P>
<P>
   Though Tae-Bo's 15 minutes seem to be up, it has produced these
spinoffs that fuse American fitness with ethnic cultural
traditions, promising not only to strengthen the body but also to
integrate it with the mind. Both capoiera and krav maga claim to
achieve this connection, but Barretta prefers that his instructors
teach aerobicized versions of the original disciplines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional capoiera class is too dangerous,'' he said.
``And it takes a long time to get good.''
</P>
<P>
   Nanette Pattee Francini, a founder of the Sports Club company,
which owns the Reebok Sports Club/New York and two branches of the
Sports Club/L.A., scheduled to open in New York next year, said:
``The future direction of fitness is definitely body-mind. Baby
boomers want a kinder, gentler workout now. Many have been injured
by high-impact aerobics, and they've gotten more educated about
their internal health as well as their external beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Come January, gyms across the country will also start teaching
Jo Sand, ``a new concept in total fitness,'' as the press release
says, developed by Johnny G (ne Goldberg), the daddy of Spinning.
Students will design their own stick ``which becomes a metaphor for
your life.'' There's more: Moving your body in sync with the stick,
``you discover your power and become aware of your inner strength.
Jo Sand takes the emphasis away from raw physical strength and
places it in the strongest muscle of all: the mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Suitably lulled by all this talk about the mind, I took my place
in the capoiera class taught by Edna Lima. Capoiera was developed
hundreds of years ago by Africans enslaved in Brazil, she
explained. ``It was martial arts disguised as a dance. They would
pretend they were dancing while they developed the skills and
techniques to run away and get their freedom back.''
</P>
<P>
   Really? I couldn't see how anyone could even think of running
while trying to execute these deep lunges and squats. Ms. Lima's
lower body seemed elastic as she assumed the crouching stance and
moved like a panther, her behind slinking along right above the
floor. Mine stuck up into the air, refusing to slink. ``Drop it,''
she yelled to me and to another woman in an identical pose. Once I
did, she had gone on to a set of O-shaped kicks that I attempted
once the room quit tilting. The bend-over-grab-your-ankle steps had
left me red-faced and dizzy.
</P>
<P>
   I finally grasped the mind connection when mine insisted I stop,
though the class was only at its halfway mark. If her legs were
elastic, mine were jelly. I'm not in terrible shape, either, or at
least I didn't think I was. Since I didn't know stepping was dead,
I still do it at home with tapes. As I crumpled onto the floor, I
couldn't help noticing that I was a good 10 to 15 years older than
most of the other students.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the hour I watched as people turned cartwheels
in formation and used some moves that looked straight out of ``West
Side Story.'' Many of them also study the authentic capoiera with
Ms. Lima at Revolution Studios at 104 W. 14th St. ``It is not
repetitive like Tae-Bo,'' she said. It brings body and mind
together. It is an art to exercise you and condition you to think.
It's about concentration and focus, each movement built onto the
next.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
