<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 230 or 227.
PLEASE NOTE: THERE IS NO ATTENDANCE CHART WASHINGTON, Nov. 12 --
The following chart shows how senators and representatives voted on
key bills and amendments within the last week. A ``Y'' means the
member voted for the measure; an ``N'' means the member voted
against the measure; a ``?'' means the member did not vote; and a
``P'' means the member voted ``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: MINWAGE
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday approved, 53 to 44, an amendment to raise
the minimum wage and cut taxes. The measure, attached to a
bankruptcy reform bill, would raise the hourly wage by $1 to $6.15
over 28 months, and cut taxes by $18.4 billion over five years for
small businesses. Supporters said the bill would make the minimum
wage reflect the reality of the marketplace and give tax relief to
small businesses. Opponents, including President Clinton who said
he would veto the measure, said the bill was a ``cynical tool'' to
give tax breaks to special interests. A ``yes'' vote favors the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: MINWAGE2
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday failed to pass an amendment to raise the
minimum wage by $1 over 13 months and cut taxes by $1.5 billion
over five years. Voting 50 to 47, the Senate tabled, or set aside,
the Democratic-sponsored measure. Supporters said the amendment,
attached to a bankruptcy reform bill, would bring a much-needed pay
raise. Opponents said the measure did not provide sufficient tax
relief for employers that would have to support the pay hike. A
``yes'' vote tables the measure.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: COCAINE
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Wednesday approved, 50 to 48, an amendment to
strengthen penalties for selling powder cocaine and for selling all
illegal drugs to minors. The provision, attached to a bankruptcy
reform bill, would make the punishment for selling powder cocaine
comparable to the punishment for dealing crack, which is currently
more severe. Supporters said the bill provides a more appropriate
penalty for powder cocaine violations. Opponents said they would
rather scale back the penalty for selling crack. A ``yes'' vote
favors the measure.
</P>
<P>
   4) BILL NUMBER: MOSELEY
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Wednesday approved, 95 to 2, the nomination of
former Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun, D-Ill., as ambassador to New
Zealand. Supporters said she was fit for the position. Opponents
questioned her ethics in handling campaign and personal finances. A
``yes'' vote favors the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3 4
</P>
<P>
   --- --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: FOREIGN
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Nov. 5, the House approved, 316 to 100, a compromise
$15.3 billion foreign aid bill. The bill includes $2.6 billion more
for the Wye River Middle East peace accord, international debt
relief and economic assistance than the original bill. Supporters
said the bill sufficiently funds foreign aid initiatives. Opponents
said the bill offsets funding from programs they consider more
important. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: E-COMM
</P>
<P>
   The House on Tuesday approved, 356 to 66, a bill to give
electronic documents and contracts the same legal standing as those
written on paper. Supporters said the bill was crucial to the
development of electronic commerce. Opponents said it would relax
consumer protections. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: FATHERS
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 328 to 93, a bill to support
fathers in lower income families. The measure would grant $150
million over six years to nonprofit groups that provide job
training for young parents. Supporters said the bill helps men meet
their responsibilities as fathers. Opponents said it violates the
separation of church and state by giving federal funds to churches.
A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
<P>
   --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The attendance record is not part of the
current vote chart because the company that supplied us with the
information is no longer in service. We are looking for a new
source.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
