<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7901 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-BODY-MIND-WORKOUTS-$A     11-12 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BODY-MIND-WORKOUTS-$ADV14-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the next.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next morning, I took my sorry lower body back to Duomo,
completely unprepared for Nathalie Levy-Koffler, who was an
instructor in krav maga during her stint in the Israeli Army, from
1986 to 1988. She was first in her class of 30 _ the other 29 being
men. I was genuinely impressed. Having grown up in New York, I am
an expert at mouth-to-mouth combat, but that's about it.
</P>
<P>
   Krav maga is street fighting, Ms. Levy-Koffler explained. Its
literal translation is ``contact combat,'' which means a series of
chops and blows that if delivered correctly can break someone's
eardrums or blind him. I had no idea I had signed up for Camp
Entebbe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intifada was a Cold War, so we had to go harder with
self-defense,'' Ms. Levy-Koffler said. ``We started to use the gun
to injure them, not to kill them.'' She picked up a 9-pound body
bar. ``This is like the gun a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever made her think of translating this kind of thing into
an aerobic exercise? She smiled. ``People are thirsty for new
information,'' she said. ``You know how New Yorkers get bored with
what they have.''
</P>
<P>
   This class was smaller than capoiera, and most students were
newcomers, though one woman, an aerobics instructor in Israel, was
studying Ms. Levy-Koffler's version to teach there. And Henry Levy,
Ms. Levy-Koffler's brother, will also teach her techniques in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   As the Arabic music pounded through the speakers, Ms.
Levy-Koffler instructed: ``You have two enemies next to you. One in
front, one on the side.'' She demonstrated arm blocks and punches,
calling out, ``Protect your face,'' and I quickly found my upper
body was as weak as my lower body was sore.
</P>
<P>
   Then she went on to show us the hammer move. ``It goes to the
base of the skull, and it can paralyze or kill someone,'' she said.
Everyone repeated the chopping movement until they were sweating.
One woman rubbed her arm, and another woman, red-faced, had to sit
down. I was right behind her.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Levy-Koffler brought a male student to the front to
demonstrate the finer points of kneeing someone in the groin,
cautioning not to go too high. ``That's the pubic bone, not the
groin,'' she called. She showed how to kick from the hip at the
imaginary enemy. ``After the hammer, he's crashing, so help him to
go down faster.'' Her kick from the side was a perfect straight
line.
</P>
<P>
   The students were panting by now, and she sent them out for
water. ``This is a class for beginners, man,'' she muttered.
</P>
<P>
   When they came back, she had them take partners and work with
the body bars. ``Pivot in _ that's it, use your hip. Push, kick,
groin, then go for the knee.'' She turned to the man who was her
partner and said, ``No, here's my groin. Here.'' The Israeli army,
it seems, teaches equal opportunity kicking.
</P>
<P>
   After the class, Evelyn Daitchman, an elated first-time student,
said: ``This makes you so present. You're alert, and in a certain
way you feel relaxed when you're alert. You're very present and
powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Levy-Koffler, who is also a personal trainer, teaches the
authentic krav maga privately.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you feel more secure in yourself,'' she said. ``I
have women who have had problems with rapes, or battered women, who
took my classes. You don't have to be flexible or fit. You don't
have to be the champion of the world. High kicks are nice, but low
kicks are effective.'' She grinned. ``My master in Israel was 300
pounds and short, but he would kick low and break a leg.''
</P>
<P>
   Lovely. Whatever happened to ``Hava Nagila''?
</P>
</TEXT>
