<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Nov. 13, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   The contiguous states will be virtually bereft of precipitation
Saturday as a two-pronged high pressure system resides over much of
the southern two-thirds of the nation. The easternmost high,
centered over the lower Mississippi Valley, will also prevent
moisture over the Gulf of Mexico from streaming northward.
</P>
<P>
   In northeast New England, however, a few pockets of chilly rain
or snow will affect Maine as a weak area of low pressure with
limited access to Atlantic moisture drifts east across the Gulf of
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, isolated showers will form near Florida's east
coast, but most places will stay dry. Areas of low clouds may
affect parts of northeast Florida early in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, record to near-record warmth will build in the Great
Plains under the auspices of an expansive ridge of warm high
pressure. Temperatures could approach 80 degrees as far north as
Nebraska. The warm spell will break by Sunday across the central
and southern Plains as a cool front surges southward. On Saturday,
the cool front will advance into the northern Plains and northern
Great Lakes, accompanied by gusty winds from the north. Very little
rain will attend the front, owing to a lack of moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, spotty, generally light rains will occur from
northern Washington to the Bitterroot Mountains as a streak of fast
winds at altitudes near 30,000 feet promote rising currents of air.
</P>
<P>
   Record to near-record warmth is possible across interior
California in response to a second center of high pressure over the
Great Basin.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Fire Danger
</P>
<P>
   With hunters poised to venture into the woods in northern lower
Michigan, there is growing concern about wildfires. Persistently
dry and warm conditions across the upper Middle West have allowed
grasses, leaves and brush to turn tinder dry, creating ample ground
fuel for wildfires. Though a cold front will arrive this weekend,
it will pass without much rain, owing to a dearth of moisture. With
moisture from the Gulf of Mexico prevented from streaming northward
by a high pressure system over the lower Mississippi River,
substantial rains in Michigan are unlikely through next Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
