<SLUG> BC-MARLOWE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHERE'S MARLOWE:' FILMMAKERS TURN INVESTIGATORS AND PLOTS TWIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at end of review.) 
(dw) 
 By ANITA GATES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two young filmmakers who bombed out with their first
documentary (``Watering the Apple,'' a three-hour-plus salute to
New York's drinking water) decide to do their second on a Los
Angeles private eye. Things get complicated, though, when the
cheating wife they're shadowing for a client turns out to be
sleeping with the private eye's partner. Soon the partner, who
flees to Mexico with $40,000, turns up dead.
</P>
<P>
   Since the private eye is grieving, the filmmakers take over the
case. The woman they're all following turns out to be not the
client's wife but his secretary and paramour, who was indeed
cheating on him. They learn this when the real wife turns up. She's
beautiful, blond and rich and likes the looks of one of the young
filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The private eye has an inspiration, heads for a beach hotel in
Ensenada, figures it all out and arrests the culprit. The
filmmakers have enjoyed all this so much that it looks as if
they'll be taking up investigating full time.
</P>
<P>
   If the film ``Where's Marlowe?'' sounds like the pilot of a
one-hour detective series, that's exactly what it was meant to be.
It might have been acceptable prime-time entertainment, if the
regulars grew on you.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Ferrer does a nice job as the private eye. John
Livingston and Mos Def (who is also a hip-hop performer) are both
attractive and likable as the filmmakers. But ``Where's Marlowe?''
has little energy and nothing much to say beyond the message that
hunting down murderers can be fun.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of the film is a funny sequence at the end about a
gun, an elderly woman who faints, two neighbors and a misbehaving
dog.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `WHERE'S MARLOWE?'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Daniel Pyne; written by Pyne and John Mankiewicz;
director of photography, Greg Gardiner; edited by Les Butler; music
by Michael Covertino; produced by Pyne, Mankiewicz, Aaron Lipstadt
and Clayton Townsend; released by Paramount Classics. Running time:
97 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   With: Miguel Ferrer (Joe Boone), John Livingston (A.J. Edison),
Mos Def (Wilt Crawley), John Slattery (Murphy) and Allison Dean
(Angela).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 1735EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
