<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7941 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     11-12 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV15-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DEFENSE OF GEORGE W. BUSH
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Monday, Nov. 15)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is concern in some circles that front-running Republican
presidential candidate George W. Bush may be _ how can I put this
delicately? _ an idiot.
</P>
<P>
   This concern was heightened recently when Bush failed to name
the leaders of Chechnya, India and Pakistan, three of the leading
grain-producing states in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   I, personally, think these concerns are overblown. Even though I
am a highly trained professional journalist who prides himself on
his accuracy, I know that it's impossible for anyone to know
everything, especially if, like Bush, you grew up in a rundown
Florida trailer park and dropped out of school in the third grade.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush is such a dumb-bunny, then why did the good people of
Minnesota elect him governor? Because they see things in George W.
Bush that the rest of us don't, that's why.
</P>
<P>
   While it's true that Bush doesn't have the fancy Ivy League
education of some of the other candidates, he has a graduate degree
from the ``school of hard knocks,'' which is more than you can say
about Elizabeth Dole and Dan Quayle, two Republicans whose
campaigns continue to gain strength.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was a popular professional wrestler back in the '80s who
went by the name ``Dubya the Destroyer.'' He is probably best
remembered for punching out the lights of comedian Andy Kaufman on
the David Letterman show, April 3, 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was also a member of the elite Navy Seals and once rode
atop the back of Shamu at Sea World.
</P>
<P>
   I doubt seriously if the voters care that Bush can't tell the
difference between Aslan Maskhadov and Pervaiz Musharraf, two of
the better, modestly priced cabernet sauvignons from Chile that
recently received favorable reviews in The Wine Spectator.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do voters care if Bush is a little light on the subject of
foreign affairs. There are a lot (27) of countries in the world and
many of them are located far away and have hard-to-pronounce names.
I believe, and many (27) other Americans believe, that if these
foreign countries want to be better remembered, they should stop
calling themselves things like Herzegovina or Uzbekistan and change
their name to something more familiar and easily remembered like,
say, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It would also help if the press asked Bush questions about
something he is more familiar with, like baseball. As everyone in
his home state of Minnesota knows, George Bush is part-owner of the
Minnesota Twins, the team that won the 1999 World Series by beating
the Atlanta Braves four games to zip. If you asked Bush a question
about the Twins' star third-baseman, Cal Ripken, I'm sure he'd be
more likely to answer correctly than if you asked him some arcane
foreign-policy question, like who won World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, George W. Bush has been harshly and unfairly judged as
an intellectual lightweight simply because he's a little spotty on
world leaders and geography. What's the worst that could happen? He
confuses Canada with Cuba and reduces Winnipeg to radioactive slag?
Hey, even presidents make mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, even if he's not the sharpest knife in the drawer, Bush
has enough sense to surround himself with knowledgeable advisers,
which is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some people have suggested I hire some myself, though I
can't imagine why.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
