<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Nov. 14, will move Saturday in the early afternoon,
Eastern time.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-DEBATE-REVIEW (Washington) _ Hardly a day has gone by
recently when drug policy and the pharmaceutical industry have not
been at the top of the news in stories that reflect the tension
between the scientific and financial accomplishments of the
pharmaceutical manufacturers and the unmet needs of a society that
increasingly depends on the industry. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   (Moving in the `a' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-LITERATURE-REVIEW (Johannesburg) _ For many whites, the
new South Africa is a place they no longer understand, a country in
which they grope for a sense of belonging. This new sense of
uprooted victimhood is finding expression in a new literature of
South Africa's whites that vents and explores the fears even as it
helps focus them into a new outlook on the post-apartheid nation.
By Rachel Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   (Moving in the `i' category.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNMENT-BIZ-REVIEW (Washington) _ A look at the
transformation going on in markets and how the government regulates
them. The new law removing barriers between banking, insurance and
securities does little more than allow Washington to catch up with
the sweeping changes that have reshaped the financial services
industry over the past few decades. Other major impending changes
involve health care, the burgeoning online industry and the
Microsoft antitrust case. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   PRESCHOOL-EMOTIONS-REVIEW (Undated) _ When educators gather this
week in New Orleans for a national conference on teaching young
children, the focus will be on anger management: aggression
prevention, self-regulation and emotion control. The themes may
seem more suited for adults in mid-life crisis than 3-year-olds,
but they are part of an evolving movement to develop and offer
formal lessons in the ABCs of feelings to children under 5. By
Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   OCEAN-RECOVERY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Lost at sea once meant exactly
that: irretrievably vanished beneath the waves. But in recent years
there has been a remarkable shift in the public imagination. People
have come to expect the sea to reveal its graves. And in some
cases, they have expected investigators to tease insights from
sunken ships and plane wreckage as easily as if the doomed craft
were resting in a cornfield. By C.J. Chivers.
</P>
<P>
   MAIL-CHANGES-REVIEW (Undated) _ The surge of interest in UPS
stock appears to be a vote of confidence in snail mail, as well as
a debunking of the myth of a paperless society and a harbinger of
good things for the U.S. Postal Service. The telephone and the fax
didn't reduce the amount of mail people send. Now, the theory goes,
the Internet will not, either. The underlying message, however, is
more complicated. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   JUDY-MICROSOFT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Hypothetical courtroom scene
of TV hyperjurist Judge Judy handling the Microsoft antitrust case.
By Jeff MacGregor.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-LORDS-REVIEW (London) _ Last week, all but 92 of
Britain's hereditary peers shuffled out of the House of Lords for
the last time, finally made redundant by Prime Minister Tony
Blair's modernizing juggernaut. As they left, many Britons paused
to indulge in a bit of nostalgia for the old days, when the landed
aristocracy ran the country and to be a hereditary peer really
meant something. By Sarah Lyall,
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN-U.S.-REVIEW (Undated) _ Most Americans don't care about
Sudan, but the few who do have made it a rarity in U.S. foreign
policy: an African nation with an American constituency.
Schoolchildren raise money to buy back slaves. Fundamentalists in
Congress, troubled by Sudan's war on its Christians, are finding
common ground with black legislators concerned about slavery.
Recently a group of well-connected aid agency officials met with
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to plead for a new course. By
Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-VIOLENCE-REVIEW (Bogota) _ What makes Colombia so
brutal a society? To the toll of those killed by paramilitary
groups and guerrillas in the region's longest-running civil
conflict must be added those murdered by drug cartels and criminal
gangs, as well as the 140 young boys kidnapped, tortured, raped and
butchered by a serial murderer who recently confessed his five-year
killing spree. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PROVERBS-REVIEW (Shanghai) _ Chinese is a difficult
language for any Westerner. But the real killer is often learning
the proverbs with which the Chinese pepper their conversation.
Generally four to eight characters long, a proverb is invariably
incomprehensible at first hearing, and, once learned, often easily
forgettable. By Seth Faison.
</P>
