<HEADLINE>
NOMINATIONS FROM CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   BOXER FORCES VOTE ON TWO JUDICIAL (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The longest wait in the history of federal judicial
nominations will come to an end by early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly four years after President Clinton nominated Richard Paez
to the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals, which covers California and
eight other western states, the Senate vote will finally vote on
his nomination by March 15.
</P>
<P>
   The end to Paez's Cal Ripkin-like streak came after Sen. Barbara
Boxer, D-Calif., held up a Senate vote on the nomination of a
friend of Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. Her move was a
retaliation against conservative Republicans for blocking votes on
Paez and another California nominee to the Ninth Circuit, Marsha L.
Berzon. Her nomination has been pending for nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Republican senators objected to Berzon, a federal
appeals attorney from San Francisco who is also a member of the
board of the American Civil Liberties Union, and Paez, a U.S.
district court judge in Los Angeles, on the basis that they were
too liberal.
</P>
<P>
   However, Democrats pointed out that both Berzon and Paez have
gained the support of several prominent Republicans, including Rep.
James Rogan, R-Calif., a floor manager during the impeachment
hearings against Clinton, and Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of
the Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch went so far as to call Berzon one of the most qualified
nominees he has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, Democrats had showcased the stalled
nominations of Berzon and Paez to make their argument that Senate
Republicans were slow in dealing with judicial nominees who were
female or members of minority groups. The Republicans denied the
accusation.
</P>
<P>
   To gain leverage against the Republican majority, Boxer last
month took a political hostage of her own, holding up a Senate vote
on the nomination of Glenn McCullough, the mayor of Tupelo, Miss.,
to the board of the Tennessee Valley Authority. McCullough had been
nominated by Clinton as a favor to Lott.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer invoked a Senate rule allowing an individual senator to
put a ``hold'' on a bill, effectively blocking floor action on the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. Boxer decided that after waiting nearly four years for a
vote, she needed to push along the process'' said David Sandretti,
a spokesman for Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday night, Lott and Minority Leader Thomas A.
Daschle, D-S.D., broke the logjam. Lott agreed to let the Senate
vote on the two Californians' nominations by March 15, and Boxer
agreed to let the Senate vote on McCullough. Later that evening,
the Senate confirmed McCullough's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been frustrating waiting for this reasonable request to
be granted, but I am gratified that this day has come and that
Richard Paez and Marsha Berzon will get their vote,'' Boxer said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Latino leaders applauded the agreement to push the nominations
to a floor vote and praised Boxer for her efforts on the nominee's
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited that the Republican leadership finally has
made the commitment to give these two qualified individuals the
chance they deserve,'' said Marisa Demeo, regional counsel for the
Mexican American Legal Defense and Education Fund, a
Washington-based advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad that Sen. Boxer needed to do what she did, but we
thank her for doing it and believe she did the right thing,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Currently, seven of the 28 positions on the U.S. Ninth Circuit
Court of Appeals are vacant. Court officials have said that 800
appeals due for action will not be considered this year because of
the judge shortage.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Chief Justice William Rehnquist, while not commenting
directly on the Ninth Circuit's judge shortage, has said that, in
general, unfilled vacancies are the most serious problem facing the
federal courts, and that after nominees' credentials are reviewed,
the Senate should vote.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
