<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE FOOTBALL REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SATURDAY'S KEY GAMES
</P>
<P>
   No. 5 Kansas State 9-0
</P>
<P>
   No. 8 at Nebraska 8-1
</P>
<P>
   The winner has a clear path to the Big 12 North title. Nebraska
decimated Texas A&AMP;M last Saturday with eight sacks and two blocked
field-goal attempts and allowed only 2 yards rushing. Kansas State
stopped Colorado's passing game until it gave up two long touchdown
passes and barely hung on.
</P>
<P>
   No. 16 Mississippi State 8-0
</P>
<P>
   No. 6 at Alabama 7-2
</P>
<P>
   These are the best teams in the Southeastern Conference's West
Division. Mississippi State has the nation's stingiest total
defense (198.5 yards a game) and rushing defense (54 yards a game).
Alabama lost four defensive starters to injuries last week.
</P>
<P>
   No. 12 Michigan 7-2
</P>
<P>
   No. 9 at Penn State 9-1
</P>
<P>
   Penn State, chancy on offense all season, lost to Minnesota on a
last-second field goal, and life gets no easier. The Nittany Lions
close against Michigan and Michigan State. Michigan ends with Penn
State and Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   No. 13 Miami 5-3
</P>
<P>
   No. 4 at Virginia Tech 8-0
</P>
<P>
   The winner is headed for the Big East title and Virginia Tech
has designs on the national title. Eleven times since 1983, Miami
has knocked teams out of the battle for No. 1, but that is a tall
order here.
</P>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame (5-4)
</P>
<P>
   at Pittsburgh (4-5)
</P>
<P>
   John Turman replaces the injured David Priestley as Pitt's
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia (3-6)
</P>
<P>
   at Boston College (6-2)
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia has lost its quarterback, Marc Bulger, to an
injured thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Yale (7-1)
</P>
<P>
   at Princeton (3-5)
</P>
<P>
   Yale's passing game should get it through this matchup fairly
comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH
</P>
