<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KHRUSHCHEV-POET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COLD WAR TURNING POINT ON TAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LYNDA RICHARDSON  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until now, there have been only memories of Nikita S.
Khrushchev's furious tongue-lashing of the famous Russian poet
Andrei Voznesensky during a Kremlin meeting on March 7, 1963. But
in a newly uncovered audio tape, the scornful voice of the Soviet
leader _ the man who first launched the great thaw ending the
Stalin era and then tried to crush it _ can be heard in a landmark
confrontation that signaled a clampdown on artistic and
intellectual freedom.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Voznesensky, now 63, obtained the tape, which was
unearthed by a Moscow television journalist in a closed government
archive in the provincial Russian town of Penza.
</P>
<P>
   Khrushchev's explosive outburst that March day was seen as a
calculated attempt to silence artists and writers like Voznesensky,
whose poetry recitals were packing stadiums. Then 29, Voznesensky
was among the literary and intellectual elite summoned to a two-day
meeting of the political leadership. Others included Aleksandr
Solzhenitsyn, playwright Vasily Aktsonov and sculptor Ernst
Neizvestny.
</P>
<P>
   Khrushchev's rant, translated off the tape by Audrey Beeber
David, began shortly after Voznesensky rose to say that like the
great Russian poet of the 1920s, Vladimir Mayakovsky, he was not a
Communist Party member. In a mocking voice, Khrushchev interrupted
Voznesensky's every sentence, as the audience applauded:
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to challenge us? We'll grind you to dust. And we will
turn to dust anyone who is an obstacle to the Communist Party . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there will be no thaw, no melting, but instead a frost
will descend. For people like you we will make a rock-solid
frost.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparing Voznesensky with his disaffected mentor, Boris
Pasternak, Khrushchev told Voznesensky he should leave the country:
``Would you like to receive your passport tomorrow? You can even
get it today, if you like. And then get the hell out of here, you
Devil.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
