<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVIATION13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIRPORTS, TRAVELERS COULD SUFFER FROM CONGRESSIONAL IMPASSE
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Airports will be squeezed and passengers will soon
feel the pinch, aviation experts said Friday about the collapse of
congressional efforts to pass a major funding bill for the nation's
overburdened air transportation system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real big disappointment,'' said Darryl Jenkins,
director of the Aviation Institute at George Washington University.
House and Senate negotiators deadlocked earlier this week in the
latest failed attempt to pass a long-range improvement plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our system is antiquated. It was never meant to deal with the
traffic we have,'' Jenkins said. ``And now we're at gridlock and
we're at a point that's going to become a safety problem. That is
not that far away.''
</P>
<P>
   His dire warning, echoed by others, came as airports braced for
delays and cutbacks in construction projects.
</P>
<P>
   Especially hard hit would be small and medium-sized air fields,
said Todd Hauptli, a lobbyist for the American Association of
Airport Executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The larger airports will have other funding sources'' such as
local bond issues, he said, adding that the rest are more reliant
on federal funding that is now stuck in limbo on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Austin-Bergstrom International Airport, for example, will have
to pay extra for financing its recently built facility if a
promised $10 million grant is delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Gates, director of finance and administration, said the
airport would also have to scale back a planned $15 million
noise-abatement program to buy out some homeowners and build
buffers to reduce the impact on others. Federal grants are supposed
to pay 75 percent of the cost.
</P>
<P>
   At Atlanta's Hartsfield International Airport, officials on
Friday were still studying possible effects of an impasse in
Congress, said airport development official Art Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's Palm Beach International Airport would probably not
have to change its development plans, spokeswoman Lisa Waters said.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional deadlock is the latest glitch after years of
attempts to provide long-range planning and reliable funding for
increasingly strained airports. Much of the air traffic control
system is still operating with 20-year-old equipment, coping with
increasing congestion in the skies.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. General Accounting Office, the bipartisan research and
investigative arm of Congress, has concluded that airport
improvement spending is $3 billion a year short of what's required
to keep up with the growing numbers of travelers, now at 600
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   House negotiators want to spend all of the $10 billion collected
each year from airline ticket fees for airport improvements and add
a higher contribution from the U.S. Treasury. Senate negotiators
have balked at the plan, drawing a heated response from House
Transportation chairman Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worshipping at the altar of fiscal short-sightedness will
carry a high price when our aviation system becomes hopelessly
congested,'' Shuster said. ``If we do not make the investments that
are necessary we risk the destruction of one of the economic
engines that keeps our economy roaring.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona, chairman of the Commerce Committee
that oversees air travel issues, also expressed disappointment at
the failure to compromise. McCain, a Republican presidential
hopeful, has been wary of a House plan to allow airports to
increase airport passenger fees from $3 to a maximum of $6, a move
that smacks of a tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   Hauptli said he has not given up on the legislation for this
year. ``There's still time on the clock,'' he said, before Congress
ends the last session of the century, probably by the middle of
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater has weighed in by making
phone calls to the players on Capitol Hill. But those pushing for
action say that all of the efforts are too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys waited to the last minute to try to work out a
compromise,'' Jenkins said. ``We're at a crunch point. There's no
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   If the current effort fails, Congress is expected to try again
next year.
</P>
<P>
   However, last Wednesday the air traffic system sent up another
symbolic warning flare. A computer breakdown in Memphis grounded
traffic for nearly two hours in cities around the South from Miami
to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's unfortunate is that we're all beginning to become
accustomed to these things,'' Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
