<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7949 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-SKIN-DOCTORS-$ADV14-A     11-12 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIN-DOCTORS-$ADV14-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VANITY GOES TO THE DOCTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Nov. 14.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By ELIZABETH HAYT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dr. Seth Matarasso's patients often book an entire
morning or afternoon for treatments. ``We'll start from the bottom
with the leg veins and work our way to the top, with the liver
spots on the hands and back,'' said Dr. Matarasso, a dermatologist
in San Francisco. ``Then, we do their Botox, collagen and
Derma-Peel. We may even do a micro-liposuction underneath the neck
and around the knees.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, Dr. Frederic Brandt sees patients in an office that
looks like a cosmetics boutique, with limestone floors, milk-glass
fixtures and a display case filled with his own brand of skin
creams, soon to be sold at Bergdorf Goodman. Brandt, 50, is a
walking advertisement for the Botox injections he relies on to
remain wrinkle-free. He forsakes a white lab coat in favor of
head-to-toe Prada Sport. ``Some of my patients call me Dr. Prada,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the age of the new dermatology, the once humble medical
specialty that is elbowing aside plastic surgery as a glamour
profession. Gone are the days when acne sufferers shamefully
scurried to a skin doctor to have pimples popped in drab green
examining rooms. Today's skin doctors, repackaged as beauty gurus,
are marketing their own cosmetics, promising to reverse the effects
of aging and _ the latest trend _ opening their own day spas,
complete with facials, seaweed wraps and a nice soak in a Jacuzzi.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, around the corner from Balthazar, a 36-foot
waterfall cascades into a pond at the SoHo Integrative Health
Center. The treatments include massage, acupuncture and ayurvedic
medicine. ``We're Zen with a medical edge,'' said Dr. Laurie Polis,
a board-certified dermatologist, who is the director. ``We're
open-minded and New Age without being full of baloney.''
</P>
<P>
   She has plenty of competition among dermatologists jumping on
the day-spa bandwagon. The number of day spas in New York City has
doubled in the last two years, to more than 50. The example of the
celebrity-friendly Bliss _ opened in SoHo in 1996 and sold for a
reported $30 million to LVMH Moet Hennessy-Louis Vuitton last year
_ is a beacon to all with a professional interest in blackhead-free
pores. In the same Broadway building as Bliss, Dr. Bradford
Katchen, a dermatologist, plans to open a 4,000-square-foot
skin-care center, the SkinCareLab, in January, which will provide
hair removal, manicures and pedicures. The unique selling
proposition that separates him from spas operated by nonphysicians,
Katchen said, is his ``almost 20 years studying skin care and its
physiology.''
</P>
<P>
   Contemplating the rise of medically supervised day spas, Dr.
Steven Mandy, a dermatologist in Aspen, Colo., put it bluntly:
``Beauty is where the money is. We have a baby boomer population in
their late 40s that is very concerned about their appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, ``doctors have had their income severely
restricted by managed health care,'' he said, adding, ``Cosmetic
procedures are outside the realm of managed care.''
</P>
<P>
   But as cosmetic dermatology becomes higher profile, there is
concern that general dermatology, or the treatment of skin
diseases, will suffer. Although no figures exist for the percentage
of cosmetic dermatologists among the United States' 8,000
dermatologists, Dr. Mark Lebwohl, the chairman of the department of
dermatology at Mount Sinai Medical School, said: ``I am concerned
that serious, medical dermatology not be neglected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not enough dermatologists to serve the medical needs
in places like Wisconsin, Georgia and upstate New York,'' he said.
``There are patients walking around with psoriasis that goes
untreated and skin cancer where the diagnosis is made late.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the shortage stemmed from a number of factors, including
the greater incentive for young dermatologists to specialize in
cosmetics because insurance companies reimburse medical
dermatologists poorly.
</P>
<P>
   The change in dermatology has been evolving over two decades. In
the 1980s, Retin-A creams to treat fine facial lines, and collagen,
a wrinkle-filler and lip-plumper, first became popular, and both
continue to be in high demand today.
</P>
<P>
   But the beauty boom really picked up over the last few years
with the explosion of medical quick fixes for the aging face. Botox
injections can now smooth facial lines, Softform and Gore-Tex
implants can permanently augment the lips, and the proliferation of
lasers can resurface sun-damaged skin, remove unwanted hair and
eradicate leg veins.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-90s, a new class of skin-care products has emerged
known as cosmeceuticals, which are available at doctors' offices
and are classified somewhere between over-the-counter and
prescription medications. Consumers are stocking up on these
creams, cleansers and lotions, which are enriched with vitamins,
fruit acids and antioxidants, believing they are more effective for
skin care than old-fashioned formulations like Ponds cold cream.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about the mid-'80s when women were no longer going to
the dermatologist to have a mole removed but for minor cases of
vanity,'' said Linda Wells, the editor of Allure magazine. ``More
recently, women started going to the dermatologist for mild
chemical peels and injections. This has been a big shift. Women
started treating their dermatologist as a graduated form of the
facialist.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Upper East Side, Dr. Michael Albom, a dermatologist, and
Dr. Mauro Romita, a plastic surgeon, opened Ajune in August, a
sybaritic spa for post-operative cosmetic-surgery patients. All the
treatment tables face the doors, in accordance with the principles
of feng shui. The spa sells Shu Uemura camouflage makeup; offers
endermologie, a treatment to supposedly reduce cellulite, and
teaches qi gong, a Chinese breathing therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Kilgor, the founder of Bliss, thinks doctors are in for a
surprise when they slip off their scrubs for spa uniforms. ``If I
was a dermatologist, the last thing I'd do is run a spa,'' she
sighed. ``The amount you can get per day for collagen is so much
higher in profit margin than dealing with facials and 150 staff
members.''
</P>
<P>
   Most dermatologists who offer spa treatments insist their
motivation is to improve the quality of these cosmetic services,
not to line their pockets. ``It's a natural extension of
dermatology,'' said Dr. Eileen Lambroza, a dermatologist on the
Upper East Side, who does not have a spa but has trained one of her
assistants to do facials and laser hair removal at her office.
``The facialist can be supervised; sterilization for the manicures
and pedicures can be monitored. The best products can be
customized, and if there is a reaction to the products or to the
treatment, the physician is there for decision-making.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
