<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BARR _ WASHINGTON _ Rep. Bob Barr is confident that he will be
re-elected, but he is taking no chances, telling the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution that he intends to raise $2 million for his
campaign. (Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO _ PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The wreckage of a United Nations
</P>
<P>
   plane carrying 21 passengers and three crew Friday en route to
Pristina in Kosovo has been found, a World Food Program official
said. Catherine Bertini, WFP executive director, confirmed to
reporters in Rome that the plane had gone down. (Roughton, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIANS _ PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The problem of ethnic
violence in Kosovo province that United Nations thought we be
abated by now, is far from it. The Kosovar Albanians that NATO
warplanes bombed Yugoslavia to rescue are apparently doing to the
Serbians, what was being done to them. This is making things very
complicated, and increasing the tension between the UN, Kosovar
Albanians, Russians and just about everybody else. It also makes
things tough for the people trying to raise money from private
donors, who may have their desire to help Kosovo chilled by the
sense that the Albanians are no better than the Serbs. For the
long-term, the ethnic tensions threaten any chance of Kosovo's
remaining a part of Serbia, while making it difficult to schedule
an election for Kosovo that would be considered reflective of both
ethnic populations. (Roughton, Cox News Service). 30. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EUROPE _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton leaves Sunday,
Nov. 14, for a 10-day swing through southeastern Europe,
intersection of U.S. interests in the Balkans, the Caucuses, the
Mediterranean and the Mideast. Journeying first to Greece, then
Turkey, Italy and Bulgaria, Clinton will touch on a range of issues
seen vital to U.S. economic and security interests, from
peacekeeping and oil to terrorism, exports and the future of nearby
Russia. Sets up Clinton's first visit to Turkey. (Deans, Cox News
Service). 20
</P>
<P>
   CARIBBEAN-ROCKET _ ST. CROIX, Virgin Islands _ A Texas aerospace
company with a lease to launch commercial satellites from a tiny
rocky island in the eastern Caribbean has drawn the ire of
environmentalists, who say the operation could wipe out the
unpopulated island's wildlife. Beal Aerospace Technologies of
Frisco, Texas wants to assemble its rockets on St. Croix and launch
them from Sombrero Island, a 95-acre slab of rock that belongs to
Anguilla, a British territory. Cash-strapped local governments
support the project for the jobs and investment it would bring. But
the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds in London is opposed,
as are some local groups, saying pollution, noise and the threat of
accidents could cause more harm than good. (Williams, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTOS. Also, with information for locator map.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thurs., Nov. 11.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-TRADE _ WASHINGTON _ Software industry leaders
expressed concern Friday that their growing business in electronic
commerce could be curtailed by agreements at the upcoming World
Trade Organization meeting in Seattle. (Glass, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   AVIATION _ WASHINGTON _ With aviation experts issuing dire
warnings about coming gridlock for air travelers, legislation to
expand air facilities is delayed indefinitely in Congress. What
this means for the traveling public. (Malone, Cox News Service).
20.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SLAVES-GRAVES _ CHEROKEE COUNTY, Ga. _ of Rivestone Plaza plan
to relocate the 127-year-old cemetery of Hickory Log Missionary
Baptist Church, one of area's first black churches. No written
records show the number of bodies buried at Hickory Log, but
developers say archaeologists have found at least 400 many
unmarked. Burials began around the church's founding in 1872 and
continued for more than 120 years. (Bennett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PRAY-WORK _ ATLANTA _ Group of 33 Somalis working on an assembly
line at a high-tech firm say they were forced to quit after their
boss wouldn't allow them to take a 5-minute break to pray. As
devout Muslims, they consider it their duty to pray at least 5
times a day, one of those times while they are at work. Apparently
their old boss let them pray, but a new boss said no. Group is
considering filing EEOC complaint on grounds of religious
discrimination. National Islamic group in Washginton is helping
them file complaint. (Kurlyo, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WATERWAR _ ATLANTA _ President Clinton's appointee to the
committee trying to negotiate a settlement in the water war between
Georgia and Alabama and Florida warned Friday that the talks appear
to be headed for failure. Lindsay Thomas, a former Georgia
congressman and head of the state Chamber of Commerce, said that
the complexities of the water dispute and unyielding demands from
various groups for more water may doom the negotiations that have
been taking place for nearly two years to divide up the waters of
the Chattahoochee and other rivers. ``This dispute could very well
be settled by a federal judge or the Supreme Court who never have
laid eyes on these rivers,'' he said. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS _ PENSACOLA, Fla. _ Still mourning the death of two
pilots, Pensacola hosts the final performance of the Blue Angels
this year. It's a town that closely identifies with the precision
flying team: the mayor is a former Blue Angels team leader. After
the South Georgia crash, the town bought 20,000 blue ribbons to
distribute to commemorate the dead fliers. They were gone in a
snap, and the city had to order more. (Osinski, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 45.
</P>
<P>
   MUSLIM-PRAYER _ ATLANTA _ Group of 33 Somalis working on an
assembly line at a high-tech firm in suburban Atlanta say they were
forced to quit after their boss wouldn't allow them to take a
five-minute break to pray. As devout Muslims, they consider it
their duty to pray at least five times a day, one of those times
while they are at work. Apparently their old boss let them pray,
but a new boss said no. Group tried to negotiate for two weeks with
new boss, but to no avail. Group is considering filing EEOC
complaint on grounds of religious discrimination. National Islamic
group in Washginton is helping them file complaint. (Kurylo,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CONFEDERATE-BURIAL _ CHARLESTON, S.C. _ The Confederate Heritage
Trust holds the largest reinterment of Confederate soldiers who
died in the Civil War July 1871. Horse-drawn artillery limbers will
carry 23 caskets from St. Johannes Luthern Church to Magnolia
Cemetery with more than 500 Civil War re-enactors in uniform
accompanying them. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-EXHIBIT _ ATLANTA _ New Native American exhibit opens at
the Atlanta History Center. Will be up for more than a year before
traveling to several Indian reservations. For the opening on
Saturday, there will be a special family-oriented program,
including storytelling. (JMiller, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   LIBERAL-CHURCH _ DECATUR, Ga. _ The 86-year-old Oakhurst Baptist
Church in Decatur lost more than half its members when it decided
to integrate in the 1960s. It drew national criticism from fellow
Southern Baptist in the 1970s when it ordained women. And now, it's
being kicked out of the Georgia Baptist Convention for accepting
gays and lesbians. We do a profile of the church to run before the
Convention vote. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40. WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   JEWISH-ASSEMBLY _ Final plans are being made for this year's
United Jewish Communities General Assembly, Nov. 17-20, in Atlanta.
The conference is considered the ``coming out party'' for the new
national organization, formed by the recent merger of United Jewish
Appeal, Council of Jewish Federations and United Israel Appeal.
President Clinton is expected to speak at the four-day meeting that
will also feature Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and former U.S.
Secretary of State George Shultz. (Blake, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 17.
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-BIBLE _ WACO, Texas _ What is it about the issue of
homosexuality that Christians find so devisive? Story evaluates why
church has such difficulty accepting this issue. (Waco,
Tribune-Herald) WITH ILLUSTRATION
</P>
