<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7955 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-SKIN-DOCTORS-$ADV14-A     11-12 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIN-DOCTORS-$ADV14-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: decision-making.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Many of the treatments at a spa are designed to relax you and
have no medical benefits,'' said Dr. Darrell S. Rigel, the
president of the American Academy of Dermatology and a clinical
professor of dermatology at New York University Medical Center.
``They should delineate between what is a medically proven
treatment versus something that just feels good. The public makes
the assumption that just because there is a dermatologist
affiliated with the spa, all the treatments could have medical
benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Although day-spa devotees hardly seem to be suffering at the
hands of medically unsupervised aestheticians, some prefer the
atmosphere of a medical clinic. ``I'm a spa-aholic,'' confessed
Kimberly Jane Daiber, a New York designer of clothing and home
furnishings. ``I think Bliss is all right, but I don't like it not
being very scientific. I've also gone to Elizabeth Arden, the
Golden Door and the Peninsula.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel more comfortable in a doctor's environment,''
she added. ``The facials are more effective. My face feels
cleaner.''
</P>
<P>
   Services a physician can offer, with a medical license, that an
ordinary spa cannot, include: collagen and Botox injections,
various laser procedures, medium- to high-strength chemical peels
and the treatment of blood vessels, age spots, skin lesions and leg
veins.
</P>
<P>
   To create the impression that a dermatologist-run day spa
provides more effective treatments than the nonmedical variety,
some doctors are touting their own products for their therapeutic
benefits. Last April, the Juva Skin and Laser Center opened in
Midtown Manhattan, a self-described medi-spa designed by the
architects who created Frederic Fekkai's hair salon. Images of the
Grand Canyon float across flat-screen television monitors in the
waiting room, and the dermatologist who is the director, Dr. Bruce
Katz, maintains, ``We have actually incorporated medication that
has anti-aging effects into our body treatments and facials.'' He
was referring to his custom skin-care products laced with
alpha-hydroxy acids, which he said can reverse sun damage with four
to six treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Like all cosmeceuticals, his products have not been approved by
the Food and Drug Administration, and no hard claims can be made
for their effectiveness, only general promises that they enhance
beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for alpha-hydroxy acids,'' said Rigel of the dermatology
academy, ``the FDA has looked into tighter regulation of them, but
their effects are so mild that it was felt they could be
administered by a nonphysician. It used to be a black-and-white
area; now it's gray.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the American Academy of Dermatology advised
dermatologists who sell products from their offices to do so ``in a
manner with the best interest of their patient as their highest
priority.'' But some skin doctors argue that the practice should be
banned outright. ``Patients need to trust that their doctor's
primary interest is in their health, not increasing the doctor's
bottom line,'' said Dr. Eileen Ringel, a dermatologist in
Waterville, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors are given certain privileges and respect in our
society, because their primary motivation is patient well-being,
and if you misuse those privileges to increase profits, it's
unethical,'' she said. ``Patients don't always understand the
difference between cosmetic recommendations and therapeutic
recommendations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I don't do any of the new dermatological
procedures,'' she said. ``I don't treat the aging face, as if
that's some sort of a disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Countering such criticism, Dr. Arnold Klein, a celebrity
dermatologist in Los Angeles, said: ``Although I think of my
practice as being a medical practice and not a beauty parlor, the
argument that dermatology is being diminished by focusing on
aesthetics goes back to the Judeo-Christian ethic that vanity is a
vice. Vanity is OK. If it wasn't, we'd all walk around in paper
bags and never bathe.''
</P>
<P>
   Cosmetic dermatology has turned out to be so profitable that
even doctors from other fields are crossing over to practice it.
The Institute Beaute on East 78th Street advertises laser hair
removal, facial peels and vein therapy, traditionally the realm of
dermatology. But the person who performs the treatments is Dr.
Everett Lautin, a radiologist, who along with a podiatrist, Dr.
Suzanne Levine, opened the beauty center a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the advertisement, neither doctor identifies a specialty. ``I
don't even understand how radiologists let leg veins get away from
them,'' said Lautin, when asked if he was going beyond his turf.
``People assume only a dermatologist can treat leg veins.''
</P>
<P>
   Under state laws, any licensed physician can practice any form
of medicine, from dermatology to brain surgery, said Dr. David J.
Goldberg, a laser surgeon and a professor of health care law at
Fordham University. But the regulations on laser hair removal vary
by state, he added. In New York, it can be done by a technician
under a physician's supervision; in New Jersey and Connecticut, for
example, the rules are stricter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, as dermatologists, see problems where people have gone to
nondermatologists,'' Rigel said. ``The issue of nondermatologists
and physicians in specialties that have nothing to do with their
training is an issue that will be bigger in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Polis of the SoHo Integrative Health Center has her own
perspective on this. She has long been teased by her brother, a
surgeon, over her specialty, but now he is jealous. ``When I first
went into dermatology in 1983,'' Dr. Polis said, ``my brother said,
`Congratulations! You're a dermatologist. If it's wet, dry it. If
it's dry, wet it.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, he calls me on the phone after an eight-hour operation on
a kidney,'' she continued, ``for which his local managed-care plan
has slashed their price for the sixth time and pays him $500, 85
percent of which is eaten up by office costs and malpractice
insurance. And he says to me, `Do I wish I was a cosmetic
dermatologist now!'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
