<HEADER>
A7969 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-12 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDING A CAREER IN CONSTRUCTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Deciding on a career is part research and part
happenstance. It's always a good idea to do what interests you, but
it's also important to investigate the long-term demand for an
occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Though most jobs for young men and women entering the work force
in Houston can be considered safe bets for the long term, the
construction trades _ in light of some recent bad news _ might be a
cause of concern for the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   A University of Houston economist predicted earlier this week
that the local apartment market is reaching the point of oversupply
that will force rents down.
</P>
<P>
   That, coupled with a falloff in new commercial and office
building as well as higher interest rates nationwide, which are
beginning to choke housing starts, led Barton Smith, director of
UH's Institute for Regional Forecasting, to predict Houston will
lose between 2,000 and 3,000 construction jobs next year.
</P>
<P>
   Though that sounds like a lot, the predicted loss in jobs comes
on top of a rip-roaring year in which Houston contractors added
7,700 construction jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, is construction really a good career with a lot of
long-term potential?
</P>
<P>
   Educators, construction companies and union leaders contend
construction is still a good choice in part because of demographic
changes, growth in the industrial sector and the unusual
construction-related opportunities that have popped up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RESUPPLYING THE WORK FORCE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Demand for construction workers is strong because the current
crop is getting older, said Richard Shaw, secretary-treasurer of
the Harris County AFL-CIO in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw estimates the average craft worker is 50.
</P>
<P>
   Even with fewer jobs available, there still aren't enough people
to replace the ones who are leaving, said Larry Williams, director
of human resources for Marek Family of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   Construction workers tend to become supervisors as they get
older or join Home Depot as instructors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see many 60-year-old concrete finishers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That aging population will continue to open up a lot of jobs at
a time when the construction industry has been especially
short-staffed.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, young men went into construction because that's
what their fathers did. But that pattern changed in the 1980s when
the industry went through a severe slump and thousands of workers
who had planned on a steady job for life ended up on the
unemployment line.
</P>
<P>
   Fathers told their kids not to go into construction, Shaw said,
so a whole generation of workers wasn't trained.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the cyclical nature of the business still concerns
students, who ask if the boom will last.
</P>
<P>
   But signs are on the horizon that industrial demand is on the
upswing, said Dickie Jones, manager of craft development and
training for Fluor Signature Services in nearby La Porte.
</P>
<P>
   With the deregulation of electric power, several companies are
building power plants in Texas and around the United States, Jones
said.
</P>
<P>
   And the efforts to improve air quality in Texas will also employ
a lot of welders, pipe fitters and electricians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have jobs now that we can't fill,'' said Jones, who added
that he would continue to recommend construction as a well-paying,
solid profession.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LOW ON CAREER STATUS LADDER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The news about fewer construction jobs comes at a time when the
industry is facing an image problem. Young folks are more
interested in computer-related careers than slinging hammers in hot
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Williams likes to quote a study of high school students who
rated the desirability of 250 careers. Construction came in 248th,
just before migrant farm workers and commercial fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   There's so much demand for construction workers that many
construction companies have been lowering their standards.
</P>
<P>
   Williams speculated that if a survey was taken of good-size
contractors, all of them would love to replace 25 percent of their
employees. But there is so much work that contractors will hire
folks with erratic work histories or those lacking in job skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We joke that if you can fog up a mirror, you have a job,''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he welcomes a tighter construction market next year.
That way, construction companies won't have to hire the workers who
don't show up regularly or have problems at the work site.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
