<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7980 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-CLASSICALMUSIC1STTAKE     11-12 1736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSICALMUSIC1STTAKE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crossover creates a world of potential
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Nov. 14.
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   All through its history, classical music has gone through one
crisis after another. For an art created to give pleasure and
restore the spirit, it has been interrupted time and again by
discord.
</P>
<P>
   From organum, the
</P>
<P>
   choral style in the Middle Ages, to minimalism in the 1980s, as
each form has become the accepted norm, it has found opposition
ready and waiting. When Bach wrote his late masterpieces, baroque
music was almost passe; his sons, Johann Christian and Carl Philipp
Emanuel, helped popularize the new rococo style that flowered in
the works of Haydn and Mozart. Brahms fought the ghost of Beethoven
all his life and achieved a self-sufficient artistic maturity in
his 50s _ by which time the followers of Richard Wagner were
writing polemics against what they viewed as his stuffy
conservative symphonies. Sometimes it seems as though the monks had
no sooner written down the chants approved by Pope Gregory I than
some other monks charged out of a nearby monastery to save music
from the reactionaries.
</P>
<P>
   In the 20th century, where everything moves much faster than in
the past, classical music has been through a decade-by-decade
series of movements and reactions against those movements.
</P>
<P>
   As the 19th century came to a close, composers _ much like
visual artists in their discipline _ loudly wondered if the art
form had not run itself into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   When Wagner proclaimed that his was ``the music of the future,''
he threw down the gauntlet not only to Brahms but to the entire
musical establishment, challenging them to prove that the standard
symphony and opera were not all played out. At the same time, the
anti-Wagnerians believed Wagner and his acolytes were sending
classical music and serious opera straight to hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twentieth-century music throughout the world suffered enormous
shocks,'' says former New York Times music critic John Rockwell in
a pivotal book called ``All American Music'' (1983). ``Traditions
(were) disrupted and deflected, assumptions confounded, crises
proclaimed.''
</P>
<P>
   So, just as the visual arts began to explore how the eye saw and
came up with cubism and abstraction, composers began to experiment
with how the ear heard. They were not so much interested in pretty
sound, passively accepted, as in getting the audience to listen
actively and intelligently. And what they got, all too often, was
rejection.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Pleasants, like Rockwell one of a small number of music
critics to consider classical and popular music on equal terms,
says that avant-garde composers' ``excessive complexity and
dissonance and their resultant loss of audience have condemned them
to irrelevance. The true music of our time, one that expresses its
spirit and sensibility, is popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Go back to the supersaturated romantic harmonies of Wagner. In
the new century, post-Wagnerian composers pushed harmony to the
edge, so it no longer led the ear to the home key, in the way of
the clean harmonic patterns of a Mozart symphony. This was called
``atonality,'' a term that frightens today's audiences. But, as
practiced by Arnold Schoenberg and his circle, as well as by Igor
Stravinsky in ``The Rite of Spring,'' atonality does not mean
strident dissonance; it means harmonies that do not resolve in
standard or predictable ways _ indeed, often do not resolve at all.
</P>
<P>
   As with most religions proclaimed by zealots, atonality did not
last long in its pure form. It was superseded by the 12-tone
system, also called serialism, which was based on the equality of
the dozen notes of the chromatic scale (the black and white keys in
any octave of the piano), so that no note could be said to be the
magnetic center of harmony. And within a few short years, serialism
gave way to neoclassicism, in which composers wrote in classic
forms for small, stripped-down ensembles. Stravinsky's chamber
cantata ``L'Histoire du Soldat'' and Prokofiev's ``Classical
Symphony'' spoke to the precarious economics of postwar Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction _ positive and negative _ also occurred in opera.
Romantic operas gave way to naturalistic operas, influenced by
Freud's theories of sexual identity (``Jenufa'' and ``Der
Rosenkavalier,'' despite their great differences, were shaped by
Freudian thought) and new sociological ideas, born during the
Industrial Revolution, of man's place in an indifferent world
(Alban Berg's ``Wozzeck'').
</P>
<P>
   In the Jazz Age, naturalistic opera was elbowed aside by cabaret
opera: works such as Brecht and Weill's ``The Threepenny Opera,''
which poured vinegar on the political and social sores of the day.
After World War II, naturalistic opera came back in works such as
``Peter Grimes'' (1945). By the end of the century, no style
predominated. The late century has seen everything from fantasy
opera (``The Ghosts of Versailles'') to docu-opera (``Nixon in
China''). One of the last works of the '90s, ``The Dangerous
Liaisons,'' took audiences straight back to the land of ``Don
Giovanni'' _ as seen through a bleak postmodern scrim.
</P>
<P>
   Atonality or serialism, naturalism or surrealism, no movement
lasted long enough to produce more than a couple of textbook works
before giving way to the next. Twentieth-century music obeys
Newton's third law of motion: Every action has an equal and
opposite reaction.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not a fair statement. What really has happened is
that composers have assimilated whatever is useful to them _
atonality or metric modulation or ``musique concrete'' or
indeterminism or minimalism or any of the other -isms _ in order to
re-create them in their own image. The average audience member who
won't come near Schoenberg's 12-tone ``Kammersymphonie'' might be
surprised to learn that Leonard Bernstein used a 12-tone row as the
melodic line in the ``Quiet!'' trio of the musical ``Candide.'' On
Broadway, the tone-row sounded neither academic nor fearsome _
perhaps because the composer didn't call attention to it with a
neon sign that shrieked: ``This is modern music.'' But it is.
</P>
<P>
   More important than the profusion of -isms that flowered and
wilted overnight throughout the century is the mutual cannibalism
of popular and classical music that has been called different
things at different times but is today called ``crossover.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No culture in the world has a richer confluence of these
cross-currents than the United States, where the old battles about
what is European and what is American, what is popular and what is
`serious,' are being fought with a new fierceness _ and resolved
with a new confidence,'' says Rockwell.
</P>
<P>
   Composers have always borrowed material, from the dozens of
medieval Masses based on the French popular song ``L'homme arme''
(``The armed man'' or ``The soldier'') to Bach's organ chorales
based on Lutheran hymns to the Russian folk songs that Beethoven
incorporated into his string quartets for the music-loving Russian
ambassador to the Viennese court, Count Razumovsky.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 20th century, in addition to hymns and folk tunes,
composers fell in love with jazz and with world music. Stravinsky
heard a piano rag in Paris and wrote a ragtime dance into
``L'Histoire du Soldat''; the violin in a sonata by Maurice Ravel
slithers and slides through a blues tune. Philip Glass' minimalism
_ the use of repeated chords and melodic patterns to create a
musical tapestry _ in the score to the 1983 film ``Koyaanis-
</P>
<P>
   qatsi'' comes directly from his studies with Indian sitarist
Ravi Shankar. Indian raga is based on the same principle of small
elements repeated and endlessly varied.
</P>
<P>
   There's a difference, however, of attitude. Composers of
previous eras tended to quote ``low culture'' materials to show how
cleverly they could dress them up in ``high culture'' clothes.
</P>
<P>
   In the 20th century, there is much more respect for the
nonclassical material and a sense that its freshness _ rhythmic,
melodic or harmonic _ enriches everyone's musical experience.
Gershwin's ``Rhapsody in Blue'' is filled with the syncopated
rhythms and slinky sonorities of jazz, not because the composer was
desperate for a new idea but because he heard that the mix of jazz
and classical sound was greater than the sum of its parts. His
``Porgy and Bess'' doesn't patronize African-American work songs
(``It Take a Long Pull to Get There'') or vaudeville routines (``It
Ain't Necessarily So'') or the blues (``My Man's Gone Now''). It
glories in offering up their undiscovered beauties to a new
audience.
</P>
<P>
   For another approach, consider Charles Ives, the independent
American composer who was the son of a Civil War bandmaster. You
can hear the patriotic tunes his father's band played in many of
his works. But Ives does more than quote. He alters and adapts and
fragments the familiar until the listener learns to find it in all
its infinite variety. Or he uses it to illustrate a really complex
idea: the spatial sound effect of a band marching through town _
the crescendo of its approach, the full voice of its stop in front
of the reviewing stand, the decrescendo of its departure.
</P>
<P>
   Many a politically correct academic, soul-searching the moral
question of one culture co-opting another, will downgrade the
merger by calling it ``appropriation.'' What the professor means is
that the absorption of jazz elements or world music instruments or
folk songs is exploitation, pure and simple.
</P>
<P>
   But the composers who use this material couldn't be more
respectful, whether it's Bela Bartok integrating the off-kilter
tunes and rhythms of Carpathian Mountain villagers in his piano
method, ``Mikrokosmos''; or hammered dulcimer player Malcolm
Dalglish writing songs for children that imitate the shimmering
sounds of Bulgarian women's choirs; or Hughes de Courson fusing the
music of Bach with African choral colors and rhythmic underpinnings
in ``Lambarena.''
</P>
<P>
   What crossover has done, in the simplest possible terms, is
reopen the possibilities of classical music, which less than a
hundred years ago was considered moribund and done for. The
expressive possibilities of what was once considered peripheral
music have been like a transfusion of fresh blood into an anemic
patient.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
