<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7981 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-1113-C     11-12 1316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-1113-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SE EUROPE TOUR TO HIGHLIGHT STRATEGIC IMPORTANCE OF
TROUBLED REGION
 &HT;    (800&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    EDs: With vital stats on Greece, Turkey, Italy and Bulgaria
attached to end of story.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With scheduled stops in Istanbul, Athens and
Florence, the 10-day swing through southeastern Europe that
President Bill Clinton begins on Sunday might well be dismissed as
a rugs, ruins and renaissance tour.
</P>
<P>
   There will be sightseeing and shop ops built in, to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   There's a serious purpose, though, behind a journey that takes
Clinton first to Turkey, for a two-day state visit in Ankara,
followed by a summit in Istanbul with his counterparts from 53
other countries that belong to the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   From there Clinton continues on to Greece, Italy, Bulgaria and
Kosovo, where he'll have a pre-Thanksgiving dinner with U.S. troops
making up part of the NATO force working to hold together one of
Clinton's most ambitious foreign policy gambits: a fractious
Balkans peace.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the issue is combatting terrorism or promoting
democracy, preventing the spread of Balkans-like conflict or
expanding trade opportunities, extending NATO's reach into the
Caucuses or securing access to the riches of Caspian oil, Europe's
soft Aegean underbelly has become the inescapable intersection of a
widening range of U.S. interests.
</P>
<P>
   Much is riding on how it all turns out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southeastern Europe remains the Achilles heel of Europe,''
explained Charles Kupchan, director of Europe studies with the
Council on Foreign Relations. ``If you want to eventually think
about a Europe that is self-confident, one that is enlarging, then
you really need to crack the problems of Southeastern Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The troubles range from ethnic conflict in the Balkans and the
Caucasus region of the former Soviet Union to the enduring
animosity between Greece and Turkey, symbolized by their 30-year
stand-off over the island nation of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after the fall of the Berlin Wall, much of
southeastern Europe has been left behind in the continent's broader
race toward market-opening and democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the region is impoverished _ Bulgaria's 8.2 million
people scrape by on the annual equivalent of just US$1,500 per
person _ and, technologically, several generations behind its
neighbors to the north and west.
</P>
<P>
   And, a decade after the end of the Cold War, the people of
southeastern Europe reside still in the shadow of uncertainty cast
by the economic and social collapse in Russia, in a disturbing
counterpoint to the gains made across most of central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The part of Europe where wars do not happen, where democracy
is secure, where markets are open and where nations share
responsibilities, is now larger than at any point in history,''
White House National Security Adviser Samuel Berger told reporters
Friday. ``Dealing with this unfinished business and strengthening
our ties with key allies will be the president's top priorities
next week, and is a large part of America's agenda in the coming
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Healing regional divisions that are, in some cases, rooted in
antiquity isn't the sort of thing that happens just because Air
Force One drops into a region for a week or so.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is aiming, though, for some tangible results.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to get Greece and Turkey to agree to enter into formal
talks, under the auspices of the United Nations, over the future of
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a problem that can be solved,'' Clinton said Monday in
a speech at Georgetown University. ``Eventually, it will be solved.
And I intend to see that the United States does everything we
possibly can to be of help.''
</P>
<P>
   He also expects to lend his blessing to a broader regional
agreement to support a commercial pipeline that would link Turkey's
southern riverport of Ceyhan to the vast Caspian Sea oilfields
1,100 miles to the east.
</P>
<P>
   He'll visit the epicenter of last summer's earthquakes in
Turkey, this week rocked again by killer tremors, highlighting the
U.S. military and humanitarian aid he ordered in response.
</P>
<P>
   And he'll do what he can to try to win Greece back to the full
fold of NATO in the wake of the 11-week alliance air campaign
against Serb-dominated Yugoslavia last spring, an attack that more
than nine Greeks out of 10 opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was forced to delay his visit to Greece, originally
scheduled for Nov. 13-15, after anti-American demonstrations rocked
Athens and raised security concerns. Aides expect protests when he
visits Nov. 19-20, but Clinton hopes to hold out any demonstrations
as an example of tolerance of the sort of freedom of expression he
would like to see take hold elsewhere across the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to speak about the vital role Greece is playing and
can play in Europe,'' Clinton said. ``The world's oldest democracy
is a model to the younger democracies of the Balkans, a gateway to
their markets, a force for stability in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional add.)
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of Clinton's trip, though, is Turkey, the
ancient crossroads of Europe, the Mideast, Central Asia and Islam,
and the modern nexis where American allies brush up against U.S.
foes.
</P>
<P>
   A primarily Islamic country self-described as a secular
democratic republic, Turkey has borders touching Russia, the former
Soviet states of Georgia and Armenia, as well as Syria, Iraq and
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   That makes Turkey, a NATO member that has been the staging
ground for nearly a decade of U.S. combat air missions directed
against Iraq, a unique Western ally on the front lines of global
efforts to combat an explosive mix of terrorism and Islamic
fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the coming century will be shaped in good measure by
the way in which Turkey itself defines its future and its role
today and tomorrow,'' Clinton said in his Georgetown University
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future can be shaped for the better if Turkey can become
fully a part of Europe, as a stable, democratic, secular, Islamic
nation,'' said Clinton, ``and if there is a real vision on the part
of our European allies, who must be willing to reach out and to
believe that it is at Turkey where Europe and the Muslim world can
meet in peace and harmony.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has spent much of his administration goading his
European counterparts to invite Turkey into the continent's formal
economic and political club: the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Largely at his urging, the EU is expected to give Turkey a road
map next month pointing the way toward membership sometime over the
coming decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It now has a ticket to Europe,'' said Kupchan. ``It represents
a softening of what was really nothing short of a racial prejudice
which said that Europe is Christian and Turkey is Moslem and
therefore Turkey is not Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   A BREAKDOWN OF THE COUNTRIES PRESIDENT CLINTON WILL VISIT:
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY
</P>
<P>
   Size: Slightly larger than Texas
</P>
<P>
   Population: 65.5 million
</P>
<P>
   Annual per capita income: $3,200
</P>
<P>
   GDP: $200 billion
</P>
<P>
   Estimated 1999 economic growth (contraction) rate: -2 percent
</P>
<P>
   GREECE
</P>
<P>
   Size: Roughly the size of Alabama
</P>
<P>
   Population: 11.5 million
</P>
<P>
   Annual per capita income: $11,305
</P>
<P>
   GDP: $120 billion
</P>
<P>
   Estimated economic growth rate (1998): 3.5 percent
</P>
<P>
   ITALY
</P>
<P>
   Size: About the size of Georgia and Florida combined
</P>
<P>
   Population: 60 million
</P>
<P>
   Annual per capita income: $20,800
</P>
<P>
   GDP: $1.2 trillion
</P>
<P>
   Estimated economic growth rate (1999): 1 percent
</P>
<P>
   BULGARIA
</P>
<P>
   Size: Slightly larger than Tennessee
</P>
<P>
   Population: 8.2 million
</P>
<P>
   Annual per capita income: $1,500
</P>
<P>
   GDP: $12.3 billion
</P>
<P>
   Estimated economic growth rate (1998): 3.5 percent
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
