</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7983 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-CLASSICAL-FUTURE12-CO     11-12 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSICAL-FUTURE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Technological innovations may grow audiences whatever format art
takes
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time, there were live recordings. If Vladimir
Horowitz made a mistake, he could play the whole piece over or
leave the dropped notes there on the floor. There were no other
choices.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon another time, record producers and tape editors went
into a soundproof booth with a razor blade, sharpened to
microsurgical accuracy, and cut out musical errors, patching them
with the right notes played by the musician _ or some other
musician _ on another occasion.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to Allgood Productions, a busy Atlanta recording studio,
is an eye _ as well as an ear _ opener. William Allgood, the owner
and producer, can show you the amazing fixes he can make with a
bank of computerized sound equipment. Matching the sound of a piano
trio or a brass band with equal ease, he can replace sour notes
without any live musician anywhere in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the CD-buying public gets used to perfect
performances and then, says the conventional wisdom, can't forgive
mistakes in a live recital or concert. So CDs are among the many
reasons concert promoters worry about the demise of live music.
</P>
<P>
   Bulletins about the death of classical music have been issued
with great regularity since the start of the 20th century, and
technology is often blamed. The gramophone was going to kill it. So
was radio. So were long-playing records. Instead, these helped grow
new audiences.
</P>
<P>
   But the technology alarmists still persist. So do the
youth-culture finger shakers. Years ago, the first national arts
demographic studies caused orchestra administrators to reach for
the migraine medicine with the news that the average concertgoer
was 55. ``The graying of the audience,'' they wailed. But, as
National Public Radio music commentator Miles Hoffman notes,
symphony audiences today are still, on average, 55. It's clear that
new audiences push from underneath to join the symphony crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Opera, thought a decade ago to be on its deathbed, is the hot
ticket of the '90s, thanks to supertitles that finally admit the
audience to previously untranslated jokes and threats, curses and
foreplay. Chamber music, once an elite medium, is intimate enough
to be inexpensive, which attracts younger listeners. Today,
inexpensive CD technology brings us a riotous profusion of world
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a canon of accepted great pieces anymore,'' says
composer and radio host Peter Schickele, who preaches the value of
eclectic listening on his show ``Schickele Mix.'' ``There's a lot
of music today that you can't tell whether (the composer) grew up
in classical or pop music. Name a warhorse from the second half of
this century. There aren't any, except maybe the `Adagio for
Strings.'''
</P>
<P>
   The feistiness of late 20th-century music, which draws from many
influences and vocabularies, is its strength, Schickele says. Its
weakness is the same as that of any other pop culture genre. ``For
something to be making enough money to do fine is not good enough
if it could be making more. This leads away from diversity and
toward sameness.'' Classical music goes on, despite the dire
predictions of critics and the pandering to popularity of arts
marketers. Earlier this season, the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra
thought about placing oversize video screens in Symphony Hall to
give the audience close-ups of the players. As with the super-
</P>
<P>
   titles, there would be those who love the idea and those who
hate it. But, as with the supertitles, no one has to look, and the
video innovation may attract new audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Classical music in the next century may not be recorded or
presented in a format that's familiar and comfortable. This is as
it should be. It's a living art.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 1811EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7984 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-CLASSICAL-LIST14-COX     11-12 2072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSICAL-LIST14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Classical timeline
 &HT;    Eds: Emabargoed for Sunday, Nov. 14.
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1900
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia Orchestra founded. To celebrate its centennial in
1999-2000, the orchestra announces repertory exclusively from its
century of existence.
</P>
<P>
   1904
</P>
<P>
   Alban Berg and Anton Webern, with their teacher, Arnold
Schoenberg, form the Second Viennese School (the unofficial First
Viennese School having been Haydn, Mozart and Beethoven).
</P>
<P>
   1905
</P>
<P>
   ``Salome'' by Richard Strauss becomes a cause celebre because of
the sexually explicit ``Dance of the Seven Veils.'' But it pales in
comparison to Leos Janacek's ``Jenufa'' (1903) for a truthful
depiction of passion.
</P>
<P>
   Hungarian composers Bela
</P>
<P>
   Bartok and Zoltan Kodaly head into the countryside to gather the
folk music of Central Europe's ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   1908
</P>
<P>
   Bitonality: ``The Unanswered Question'' by Charles Ives pits
</P>
<P>
   a trumpet in one key against a shimmer of strings in another.
</P>
<P>
   1909
</P>
<P>
   German music theorist R.H. Stein writes about the notes between
the cracks of the piano keys: quarter tones.
</P>
<P>
   1911
</P>
<P>
   ``Der Rosenkavalier'' (Strauss) looks back in nostalgia at
Mozart and his lyrical Viennese operas.
</P>
<P>
   1912
</P>
<P>
   ``Pierrot Lunaire'' (Schoenberg), a cantata for speaking voice
and chamber ensemble, becomes one of the most influential pieces of
the century.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Cowell, a great
</P>
<P>
   American experimenter, invents tone clusters _ literally,
fistfuls of notes.
</P>
<P>
   1913
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rite of Spring'' by Igor Stravinsky causes a riot at its
Paris premiere.
</P>
<P>
   1915
</P>
<P>
   Ives' ``Concord Sonata'' finds
</P>
<P>
   its own way to tone clusters
</P>
<P>
   and atonal freedom, with an
</P>
<P>
   American theme (the literary renaissance of New England in the
1840s).
</P>
<P>
   1916
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence: Ives' Symphony No. 4, which requires two orchestras
and two conductors, is the polar opposite of Prokofiev's
``Classical Sym-
</P>
<P>
   phony,'' a 20th-century spin on an 18th-century form.
</P>
<P>
   1918
</P>
<P>
   Stravinsky's ``L'Histoire du
</P>
<P>
   Soldat'' introduces ragtime to the classical ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ameriques,'' by the idiosyncratic French-American
</P>
<P>
   composer Edgard Varese, is the first of his ``organized sound''
compositions, which demonstrate ``a sense of discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   1920
</P>
<P>
   Student/disciples of Erik Satie, the king of ironic detachment,
form a loose association called Les Six. These enfants terribles
</P>
<P>
   of French music are Francis
</P>
<P>
   Poulenc, Louis Durey, Arthur Honegger, Darius Milhaud,
</P>
<P>
   Germaine Tailleferre and Georges Auric.
</P>
<P>
   1921
</P>
<P>
   ``Katya Kabanova'' (Janacek), the first great naturalistic
opera,
</P>
<P>
   premieres. ``Wozzeck'' (Berg) follows four years later.
</P>
<P>
   1923
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on the thoughts of Austrian composer Josef Matthias
Hauer, Schoenberg formalizes the techniques of 12-tone
</P>
<P>
   composition, in which all the notes of the chromatic scale have
equal harmonic value, destroying the sense of key.
</P>
<P>
   1924
</P>
<P>
   With ``Rhapsody in Blue,''
</P>
<P>
   George Gershwin brings jazz to the concert hall.
</P>
<P>
   Serge Koussevitzky becomes the Boston Symphony Orchestra's
conductor. His commitment to the music of his time results in a
25-year flowering of work for the orchestra by virtually every
</P>
<P>
   composer of importance.
</P>
<P>
   1925
</P>
<P>
   Dmitri Shostakovich's Symphony No. 1 pays homage to the music he
played to accompany silent films in a Moscow theater.
</P>
<P>
   1927
</P>
<P>
   ``Jonny Spielt Auf,'' a German cabaret opera by Ernst Krenek,
paves the way for topical satires such as Bertolt Brecht and Kurt
Weill's ``The Threepenny Opera'' (1928).
</P>
<P>
   1933
</P>
<P>
   The Nazis come to power in Germany, leading to an exodus of
artists and intellectuals. Some, such as Erich Wolfgang Korngold
and Bernard Herrmann, come to Hollywood and write scores of
unprecedented depth for American movies. For Alfred Hitchcock,
Herrmann uses advanced techniques and instruments.
</P>
<P>
   1934
</P>
<P>
   ``Lady Macbeth of the Mtsensk District'' (``Katerina
Ismailovna''), Shostakovich's opera of adultery and murder, arouses
the wrath of Stalin and straitjackets a generation of Russian
composers into the service of ``socialist realism,'' art for the
benefit of the masses.
</P>
<P>
   1935
</P>
<P>
   Gershwin's ``Porgy and Bess,'' an ``American folk opera,''
brings African-American life, music and singers to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   1936
</P>
<P>
   ``Music for Strings, Percussion and Celesta,'' a symphonic work
by Bartok, introduces ``night music'': the mysterious, ethereal
sound of darkness.
</P>
<P>
   In the Symphony No. 5, his
</P>
<P>
   first major work after ``Lady Macbeth,'' Shostakovich eats crow
before the Union of Soviet Composers by prefacing this beautiful
work with the words: ``An artist's response to just criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   1937
</P>
<P>
   Gershwin dies in Hollywood
</P>
<P>
   at age 38 of a brain tumor,
</P>
<P>
   diagnosed too late for treatment. His death is an inestimable
loss to American music.
</P>
<P>
   1939
</P>
<P>
   John Cage writes his first pieces for prepared piano, in which
objects (screws, coins, paper)
</P>
<P>
   are inserted between the strings to create percussive and
otherworldly sound effects.
</P>
<P>
   1940
</P>
<P>
   French composer Olivier
</P>
<P>
   Messiaen writes ``Quatuor pour la fin du temps'' (``Quartet for
the end of time'') for four musician-inmates in a German prisoner-
</P>
<P>
   of-war camp.
</P>
<P>
   1942
</P>
<P>
   Symphony No. 7 (Shostakovich), written during the siege of
Leningrad, is smuggled out of Russia and used as a propaganda tool
to raise money for America's Soviet allies. Bartok, in the
hospital, heard its ``Nazi bolero'' theme, the long crescendo that
symbolizes the German march into Russia, and makes fun of it in
``Concerto for Orchestra'' (1943).
</P>
<P>
   1945
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence: Bartok dies of
</P>
<P>
   leukemia in the United States. Webern, smoking a cigarette after
curfew in Austria, is fatally shot by an American sentry.
</P>
<P>
   Stravinsky writes the ``Ebony Concerto'' for jazz clarinetist
Woody Herman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter Grimes,'' the first major opera by Benjamin Britten,
</P>
<P>
   signals an important new voice in this field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Appalachian Spring,'' Aaron Copland's ballet for Martha
</P>
<P>
   Graham, gives American song new status in the concert hall.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Sopkin founds the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   1946
</P>
<P>
   In the Piano Sonata and later the String Quartet No. 1 (1951),
American composer Elliott Carter invents a complex compositional
technique called metric modulation, in which the performers
separately inflect the rhythmic value of their notes to achieve
tempo changes.
</P>
<P>
   1947
</P>
<P>
   ``A Survivor From Warsaw'' (Schoenberg) is the first of the
post-Holocaust works. Others to come include the Piano Trio
</P>
<P>
   and Symphony No. 13 (``Babi Yar'') by Shostakovich, and
</P>
<P>
   ``Il Prigioniero,'' an opera by Luigi Dallapiccola.
</P>
<P>
   1948
</P>
<P>
   Columbia introduces the long-playing (33 1/3 rpm) record, which
permits more material to be included on each side of a vinyl disc.
This makes possible the recording of complete sym-
</P>
<P>
   phonies and other extended words without multiple changes of
records. More convenient than the old 78 rpm format, the LP causes
a commercial explosion in the recording industry.
</P>
<P>
   French composer Pierre
</P>
<P>
   Schaeffer inserts bits of natural sound on tape into his
collage-compositions, a technique called ``musique concrete.''
</P>
<P>
   1950
</P>
<P>
   The first electronic music studio is founded in Cologne,
Germany. Its composers in residence include Pierre Boulez and
Karlheinz Stockhausen. Comparable American institutes:
Columbia-Princeton Electronic Music
</P>
<P>
   Center, founded in 1958 by
</P>
<P>
   composers Otto Luening, Vladimir Ussachevsky and Milton Babbitt,
and the electronic
</P>
<P>
   studios at the California Institute of the Arts in Valencia, an
arts college supported by Walt and Roy Disney.
</P>
<P>
   1951
</P>
<P>
   ``Amahl and the Night Visitors'' (Gian Carlo Menotti) is the
first opera written for television. It is broadcast every year
until 1964 on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   1952
</P>
<P>
   ``4'33,'''' a piece by John Cage, features a pianist who comes
onstage, sits at the piano for four minutes and 33 seconds, then
exits without having played a note. The music is provided
</P>
<P>
   by ambient sound from the
</P>
<P>
   audience, the ventilating system and anything else audible. It's
partly a spoof, partly the ultimate manifestation of Cage's
fascination with natural sound.
</P>
<P>
   1953
</P>
<P>
   At Black Mountain College in North Carolina, Cage and
</P>
<P>
   choreographer Merce Cunningham begin a lifelong association. A
mutual interest in Zen Buddhism leads to Cage's ``aleatoric'' or
``indeterminate'' music, in which the arrangement of elements
(notes, rhythms, themes, instruments) are determined by the I Ching
_ ancient Chinese book of changes _ dice or coins.
</P>
<P>
   1956
</P>
<P>
   Messiaen composes ``Oiseaux exotiques'' (``Exotic Birds'').
</P>
<P>
   A devout Roman Catholic,
</P>
<P>
   Messiaen was also a collector of tropical bird songs, whose
sounds glitter and sparkle in his mystical liturgical works.
</P>
<P>
   1957
</P>
<P>
   An Illiac computer composes a suite for string quartet.
</P>
<P>
   1958
</P>
<P>
   Stereophonic sound goes commercial, and stereo phonographs
become a standard component of the home high-fidelity system.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Bernstein's ``Young
</P>
<P>
   People's Concerts'' with the New York Philharmonic, broadcast on
national television through 1970, create a
</P>
<P>
   generation of music lovers.
</P>
<P>
   1959
</P>
<P>
   Joan Sutherland makes her debut as Lucia di Lammermoor at
</P>
<P>
   London's Covent Garden, bringing back bel canto operatic works
that had fallen out of favor.
</P>
<P>
   1961
</P>
<P>
   Leontyne Price, who had been singing at great opera houses since
1952, makes her
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Opera debut.
</P>
<P>
   1962
</P>
<P>
   Pacifist Britten's ``War Requiem,'' premiering the same year as
the Cuban missile crisis, helps raise world consciousness about the
dangers of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   1964
</P>
<P>
   Robert Moog and Donald
</P>
<P>
   Buchla introduce competing
</P>
<P>
   synthesizers.
</P>
<P>
   1965
</P>
<P>
   The National Endowment for the Arts is established. Its mission,
to democratize American culture, results in major initiatives to
bring chamber music, opera and orchestras to places outside New
York. Parallel funding by the Ford Foundation helps orchestras
build endowment funds to stabilize their finances.
</P>
<P>
   1966
</P>
<P>
   American composer Samuel
</P>
<P>
   Barber's ``Antony and Cleopatra,'' starring Price, opens the new
Metropolitan Opera House at Lincoln Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   1967
</P>
<P>
   The well-known choral director Robert Shaw becomes music
director of the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   1968
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Memorial Arts
</P>
<P>
   Center, later renamed the Woodruff Arts Center, opens.
</P>
<P>
   1972
</P>
<P>
   New York City Ballet's two-week Stravinsky festival presents 21
ballets to his music, ranging from ``The Firebird'' to ``Requiem
Canticles'' (a political statement about the 1968 assassination of
the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.). It's an unprecedented outpouring
of creative affection.
</P>
<P>
   1976
</P>
<P>
   ``Einstein on the Beach,'' an epic multidisciplinary opera by
Philip Glass, introduces ``minimalism.'' Inspired by the classical
music of India, it uses repeated chords and melodic patterns to
create a sound tapestry rather than a musical structure.
</P>
<P>
   1978
</P>
<P>
   Daniel John Cook, on a San Antonio newscast, comes up with the
immortal words:
</P>
<P>
   ``The opera ain't over till the fat lady sings.''
</P>
<P>
   1982
</P>
<P>
   Philips Electronics and Sony Corp. co-invent the compact disc.
By 1985, it is in common use, quickly supplanting the LP.
</P>
<P>
   1983
</P>
<P>
   Supertitles, translations of
</P>
<P>
   opera text for the audience, are introduced by the Canadian
Opera of Toronto. Within two seasons, they are ubiquitous in
American opera houses.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Taaffe Zwilich is the first woman to win a Pulitzer Prize
in music.
</P>
<P>
   1985
</P>
<P>
   A mere half-century late, the Metropolitan Opera finally
</P>
<P>
   produces ``Porgy and Bess.''
</P>
<P>
   1987
</P>
<P>
   ``Nixon in China,'' a John Adams opera, brings politics to the
opera stage. Others: ``The Death of Klinghoffer'' (Adams, 1991) and
``Harvey Milk''
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Wallace, 1995).
</P>
<P>
   Yoel Levi becomes Atlanta Symphony Orchestra music director.
</P>
<P>
   1997
</P>
<P>
   Wynton Marsalis, jazz trumpeter and composer, wins a Pulitzer
Prize for his jazz oratorio about slavery, ``Blood on the Fields.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman LeBrecht, British gadfly music critic, publishes ``Who
Killed Classical Music?'' _ the latest of many screeds proclaiming
the death of the art form. But, as Mark Twain said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Reports of my death are greatly exaggerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
