<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGOFHILL13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shabby treatment unworthy of a `King'
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's happened to ``King of the Hill'' is not a pretty sight.
Fox has jerked it around like a bad dog on a short chain, and it's
a miracle anybody is still watching.
</P>
<P>
   Two seasons ago, when it was on after ``The Simpsons,'' ``King''
ruled the ratings. Then Fox moved it to Tuesday nights, where its
Nielsens fell off a cliff. Fox moved the bloodied but still proud
cartoon back to Sundays, only before ``The Simpsons'' at 7:30, so
now it regularly gets bumped by Fox football. And if it somehow
survives all that, it's still a fairly subtle little show that most
kids don't appreciate but is on when a lot of adults aren't
watching.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder its ratings have fallen about 50 percent. Still, it
works and people watch, which at Fox these days is cause for
celebration, so disastrous has been its fall season.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night is typical ``Hill,'' if any show that has guest
stars Meryl Streep and the Dixie Chicks can be considered typical
in any way. Hank wins a trip to New Orleans to toss a football at
halftime of a football game and (maybe, yeah right) win $1 million.
He takes along his beer-guzzling buddies, and they stop off at
Bill's old ancestral home on the bayou, ruled by Cajun-fried Aunt
Esme (Streep) and home to three lubricious, hard-drawlin'
cousins-in-law (the Chicks).
</P>
<P>
   ``There are strings on our hearts that need to be strummed,''
says Esme to the rather overwhelmed visiting males, and the whole
thing plays like Tennessee Williams parodying himself. (The episode
is titled ``A Beer Can Named Desire.'')
</P>
<P>
   It's clever and may make you chuckle with appreciation, but
doesn't really feel like what folks are going to want to watch at
7:30 on Fox. The Chicks don't even sing or parody their own image _
again, probably not a crowd-pleasing idea.
</P>
<P>
   There's still plenty of spark left in Hank Hill and the gang,
but given their home these days, they need more of a major
jump-start.
</P>
<P>
   ``King of the Hill''
</P>
<P>
   7:30 p.m. Sunday on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
