<HEADER>
A7987 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-COVEN-DANCE-$ADV14-NY     11-12 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVEN-DANCE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STAGE WHERE WORKS IN PROGRESS CAN PROGRESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 14) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas)   (af)  
 William Harris writes frequently about avant-garde art, dance and
theater.  
 By WILLIAM HARRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The carefree, pluralistic spirit of the 1960s didn't
die; it possessed the body of Ellie Covan. As executive director of
Dixon Place, a performance space she founded in 1986, Ms. Covan
provides a venue where choreographers, actors, writers, performance
artists and musicians can present works in progress. Critics are
not invited.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Dixon Place presented some 400 performances, more
than half of them by nonwhites. ``Diversity is important to me,''
said Ms. Covan, who is 42. ``It's not that I have a quota, but New
York is not a white city.'' Every Sunday and Monday in November,
for instance, Dixon Place is presenting ``Notes of a Negro
Neurotic,'' written and performed by Nancy Giles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The original Dixon Place was situated in Ms. Covan's storefront
apartment in Manhattan. For the last seven years, it has been
housed in the living room of Ms. Covan's loft on the Bowery. In
September, she finally moved the operations into a legitimate
70-seat theater, the former Vineyard Theater in Manhattan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With its new home have come amenities. For the first time, Ms.
Covan, who wears her hair in ringlets and looks like the comic
Sandra Bernhard's kid sister, doesn't have to share her bathroom
with the performers. There's also a computerized lighting board to
replace the old homemade lighting system built by her father with
rheostat dimmers.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But costs have also increased. Ms. Covan has had to hire a
part-time technical director, for instance. She expects her budget
to grow from $180,000 to $240,000. To help raise money, she has put
together an executive committee to act as ambassadors for Dixon
Place.
</P>
<P>
   Included on it are the choreographer Ann Carlson, the actress
Kathleen Chalfant, the playwright Craig Lucas, and Jim Nicola,
David White and Mark Russell, the executive directors,
respectively, of New York Theater Workshop, Dance Theater Workshop
and Performance Space 122. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `'We're not trying to establish ourselves and compete for the
same money these other venues are,'' said Ms. Covan, referring to
her colleagues Nicola, White and Russell. ``We've proven that we
have viability and longevity and serve an important purpose.
Unfortunately, you can't get institutional support unless you own
your own building or have a very long lease.'' Ms. Covan's lease is
for one year.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What hasn't changed is Dixon Place's funky aesthetic. It remains
a playground for starry-eyed wannabes and a refuge for the already
established. Dixon Place alumni like the monologist John Leguizamo,
the lesbian comic Reno and the performance artists David Cale and
Karen Finley return there regularly to try out new material.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences sit on a mixture of traditional chairs and discarded
sofas. Tickets prices range from nothing to $12, depending on the
event, and all performers are paid a modest fee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Covan, a native of Corpus Christi, Texas, came to New York
to pursue a stage career after receiving a BFA in acting from the
University of Texas. Disillusioned, she fled to Paris, where she
stayed in the apartment of an American businessman named Daniel
Dixon. By accident, people started showing up Tuesday evenings for
informal readings of their work. The concept of Dixon Place was
born. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Evenings devoted to young writers remain an important component
in the programming mix. Ms. Covan does most of the selecting, but
not all. Eight curators are responsible for one evening each month.
</P>
<P>
   The choreographer Yoshiko Chuma, for instance, has put together
a series of dance evenings for midcareer choreographers who have
been asked to create works using the space limitations of Dixon
Place. Another dance series, ``Under Exposed,'' organized by
Christine Doempke, is devoted to untested choreographers. One night
each month is an open-mike event, where the first 10 people who
sign up can perform for 10 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Covan won't single out a favorite artist. ``I'm always
looking for something different or unusual,'' she said. ``Something
I haven't seen a thousand times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 1812EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
