<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7989 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-CEO-BOARDS-$ADV14     11-12 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-CEO-BOARDS-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETIMES, AN OUTSIDE DIRECTOR IS COMFORTABLE IN THE CHIEF'S
CHAIR  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 14)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Pa., Calif., N.Y.)  (af) 
 By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The board of Thermo Electron Corp., the scientific, medical and
industrial instrument maker based in Waltham, Mass., did not look
far when it hired a new president and chief executive last spring.
He was one of its own: Richard F. Syron, a Thermo Electron director
since 1997 and the president of the American Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   A company's board might seem a natural pool of talent from which
to draw a leader. After setting aside a couple of seats for
insiders, most companies fill out their boards with experienced
executives from other industries who can offer valuable advice and
look out for the interests of shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   After a few years on the board, good directors become intimately
familiar with the company's affairs and know its strengths,
weaknesses and competitive challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Yet such selections are rare. ``Hiring an executive from the
board is not a practice that is embraced by every company,'' said
Dennis Carey, vice chairman of Spencer Stuart Executive Search
Consultants in Philadelphia, who has studied executive succession
at large companies for a book to be published next year.
</P>
<P>
   While companies often turn to outside directors as useful,
temporary fill-ins, experts say, they are deterred from considering
them to fill top executive posts like chief executive, president or
chief financial officer for the long term. Difficulties like timing
and availability, potential conflicts of interest and corporate
cultures tilt strongly in favor of internal succession or of
searching for someone truly on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Notable exceptions include Randall L. Tobias, who became chief
executive of Eli Lilly, the pharmaceutical company, in 1993 after
serving as a Lilly director while he was chief executive of the
international division of AT&AMP;T. And in 1987, Alcoa chose one of its
directors, Paul H. O'Neill, who was then the president of
International Paper, as its chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their success, and what Carey described as a generally
favorable track record for other companies who hired from their
boards, few large companies turn to anyone beyond their own
executive ranks, let alone an outside director. Almost 9 out of 10
chief executives of Fortune 100 companies were promoted to the job
from within the company, Carey said.
</P>
<P>
   In most those cases, the successor had been specifically groomed
for the job _ an approach that almost always rules out directors,
to avoid creating an awkward situation for the current chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want a CEO anxious about who on the board wants to
take his job,'' said James Kristie, editor of Directors and Boards,
a quarterly journal that covers corporate boards.
</P>
<P>
   A director designated ahead of time as a future executive is
also put in an awkward position, one that might give shareholders
misgivings: when the interests of management and shareholders
differ, on which side is an outside director who will soon be
inside?
</P>
<P>
   Because of these difficulties, when directors are considered at
all, it is generally when the company has allowed itself to be
taken by surprise and , has no successor who is ready for the job.
Roger Raber, president and chief executive of the National
Association of Corporate Directors, said that in his mind, a
company that hires one of its directors as an executive has
probably planned poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When organizations dip into the board, I scratch my head,''
Raber said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a company finds the notion of hiring a director
attractive, its board may not include anyone who would be
available. Outside directors at large companies are typically
people who are well along in their careers, with senior jobs at
other companies, or may be semiretired.
</P>
<P>
   The picture is often different at smaller companies, where the
boardroom-to-executive-suite path is not as rare, corporate
governance experts say. A small company's directors do not
necessarily have senior positions elsewhere, and may be more ready
to make a career change. These companies are also a bit less likely
to have an heir apparent in place, and may not be deep with
management talent.
</P>
<P>
   All of those factors played a role at Camdata, a small computer
software company in Fountain Valley, Calif. David Frosh, a regional
vice president at Automatic Data Processing with previous
experience as a software marketing executive, joined its board in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   When the board discussed problems that Camdata's service
department was having trying to ensure prompt responses to calls
from clients, Frosh volunteered to oversee a reorganization of the
department. The results so pleased his colleagues that the company
chose him as its president in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one inside was ready yet to be president,'' Frosh recalled
in an interview. ``If we had gotten a total outsider, he would not
have been up to speed for maybe a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Camdata was fortunate to have on its board someone like Frosh,
an outsider with direct experience in its industry _ and who is not
retired. Active executives of competing companies are never
considered for board seats, so outside directors generally must
come from outside the industry, not just outside the company.
</P>
<P>
   Roger M. Kenny, managing director of Boardroom Consultants,
based in New York, said that hiring such directors as executives
can mean some compromises. ``You have to ask if their experience is
translatable to your company,'' Kenny said. ``But if you pick your
board right, you have some great athletes who could probably run
most any company.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many uncertainties attend the more common tactic of
hiring outside executives who are not on the company's board.
Newcomers are usually unfamiliar with a company's culture, and it
is difficult to predict how they will get along with the board.
Such risks are sharply reduced when a new executive is chosen from
among the company's directors, corporate governance experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, directors are most likely to be chosen when a company is
in crisis, as when a top executive is dismissed for poor
performance and the board, seeking a change in direction, decides
to pass over a designated successor.
</P>
<P>
   In such a case, looking to the board can be the safer solution,
said Gary Liebl of Los Angeles, a retired technology executive who
over the last 16 years has served on the boards of 25 companies:
``Is it going to be riskier to bring in someone from the outside,
or select a member of the board who knows the lay of the land?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
