<HEADER>
A7992 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-EGYPT-EXHIBIT13-COX     11-12 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-EXHIBIT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta's Fernbank Egyptian exhibit a treat
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Our fascination with ancient Egypt stems largely from
its way of death. But artifacts of this culture give us more than
mummies. As Fernbank's ``Life and Death Under the Pharaohs''
reminds us so well, the power of Egyptian art is as enduring as,
well, the pyramids.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, our first major Egyptian art exhibition has mummies.
Humans. A very skinny cat. A baby crocodile, too. Yes, it has
coffins, gorgeous ones, bearing the faces and mane of hair we know
so well, decorated with intricate images and hieroglyphs. It alsso
features a narrow sarcophagus for an eel. The show even includes a
replica of a painted tomb you can enter, where archaeologist once
found a whole family of mummies.
</P>
<P>
   But the exhibition is not limited to the eternal afterlife. Its
300 objects are so arranged to give you a sense of how the
Egyptians lived in this life, too. Nothing like a pair of palm-leaf
sandals and a make-up jar, not to mention a letter inked on papyrus
chiding the recipient for not writing, to remind us that Egyptians
were humans not unlike us.
</P>
<P>
   Through statues and reliefs of the gods and leaders, we learn
how they worshipped and were governed as well.
</P>
<P>
   Fernbank sees to it that learning is a dramatic experience. For
pure atmosphere, it's hard to beat walking through the portal of a
``temple'' to the accompaniment of mysterious music and into a
darkened chamber to face a striking gilt and bronze sculpture of
Osiris, god of the dead.
</P>
<P>
   An art museum might not have used the reproduction temple facade
and the forest of hulking columns amid which the cases are set
because they are inauthentic. They do, however, make a heck of a
stage set.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the figurines and stone tablets relating to the
Egyptian pantheon and the propitiatory rituals need much help. The
images of the gods, often with animal heads on idealized human
bodies, are as curious as they are well-made.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these artifacts are, in a word, beautiful. Drawn from
the exceptional collection of the National Museum of Antiquities in
Leiden, The Netherlands, the exhibition showcases the skill of
ancient artisans _ be they potters, sculptors, bookmakers or
jewelers. They applied themselves to the decoration of a spoon with
as much imagination and care as an incarnation of a god. Amonnakht,
an artisan who worked on the tombs in the Valley of the Kings
around 1250 B.C., is immortalized in a graceful wood statue, decked
out in his best skirt and holding a ram-head staff.
</P>
<P>
   The section about government and political history includes some
of the most impressive, larger-scale stone and wood sculptures.
These depict the pharaohs _ ancient Egypt's religious and political
leaders _ and the members of their families and court with great
dignity and monumentality. The limestone statue of chief physician
Juty, dating to 1300 B.C., is a great example of this regal
bearing. It also exemplifies Egyptian craftsmanship and style, from
the slightly blocky pose softened by such details as the careful
delineation of the pleats of his skirt to the soft curve of his
bald head.
</P>
<P>
   The relief carving is just as fine. Sculptors knew just how to
coax out the curve a of a cheek or the bulge of a muscle even if
they barely dented the surface of the stone. In some you can also
see the original color. As exemplified by the 19th century drawings
Fernbank has added to the show, Egyptian environments were awash
with vivid hues and dense patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors reach the climactic gallery of mummies and sarcophagi
through a narrow midnight blue hallway. It is lined with sheets
from the Book of the Dead, which contained incantations the dead
would need to ensure a successful afterlife. Wall texts explain the
reasons behind the elaborate burial rituals. This is where to find
the reproduction of an actual tomb, decorated floor to ceiling with
painted images of the family in the afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the artifacts shown elsewhere were discovered in the
precinct of this very tomb; It would have been exciting to see them
together. I also wish some of the cases were taller so that you
were not looking so far down to get a close look at the objects.
</P>
<P>
   But those are quibbles. ``Life and Death Under the Pharoahs'' is
truly a rare opportunity to see Egyptian objects of the highest
quality in Atlanta. Their installation_ designed to help us better
understand how ancient Egyptians lived, and died, and lived again_
turns a rare opportunity into a special experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life and Death Under the Pharaohs: Egyptian Art from the
National Museum of Antiquities in Leiden, The Netherlands.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernbank Museum of Natural History. 767 Clifton Rd., N.E. Nov.
14-Sept. 4. 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays; noon-5 p.m. Sundays.
Timed tickets available 10 a.m.-4 p.m. $9.95-11.95; with Imax
film,``Mysteries of Egypt,'' $12.95-16.95. 404-378-0127, plus .75
charge per ticket on phone orders.
</P>
<P>
   The Verdict: A treat.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
