<HEADER>
A7994 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS     11-12 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL OLD CD-ROM DRIVES BE CAPABLE OF READING CD-R, CD-RW DISKS? 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I enjoyed your reviews of CD-ROM ``burners'' a few weeks ago,
but I am confused about something. You referred to both writable
and rewritable CDs and drives, and implied that the drives you
mentioned can do both. But how interchangeable are they? Can I use
either kind of disks in any old CD-ROM drive, even if it's not a
CD-RW? When do you want to use a writable disk, and when would you
use a rewritable disc?
</P>
<P>
   (Note: The CD-ROM ``burners'' review can be accessed at
www.chron.com/cs/CDA/story.hts/tech/364618)
</P>
<P>
   A: First, some definitions. A writable compact disc can be
written to just once, while a rewritable disc can be written to,
erased and written to again many times over.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, a finished writable disc _ called CD-R _ can
be read in just about any CD-ROM drive. A rewritable disc, or
CD-RW, can only be read in a CD-RW drive, unless it's been closed
so that no more data can be written to it. Then, it can be read in
a standard CD-ROM drive. But some newer, nonwritable CD-ROM drives
now have the ability to read CD-RWs that are still open.
</P>
<P>
   In general, you want to use CD-Rs for making backup copies of
programs and music CDs. They're also great for storing and
preserving graphics and other multimedia files. And because they
are fairly inexpensive _ between $1.50 and $2 each _ they can also
be used as throwaway backup media. When the backup becomes out of
date, just toss it.
</P>
<P>
   CD-RW is best for backups when you want to overwrite older data
with new. Prices for the disks range from $2.50 to $5, down
dramatically from just a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Q: No wonder the record industry is upset about the MP3 craze!
My son just showed me how easy it is to find and download music
from so-called pirate sites. Do the record companies know about
these? Is anything being done to shut them down?
</P>
<P>
   A: The recording industry is well aware of these sites, and has
been aggressive about trying to shutter them when found.
</P>
<P>
   Pirate MP3 sites usually offer copyright music by posting it
through an FTP server _ software that lets users connect and
download files. These servers allow what is known as anonymous
downloads _ you don't have use your real name to connect. Many
pirate music sites use MP3 as both the login and password, so there
is no record of who visited and grabbed potentially illegal files.
</P>
<P>
   The pirate sites usually connect via an IP address, and you can
find them at any of several MP3 search engines. But those IP
addresses can change every time the pirate connects to his or her
provider. So if a record industry lawyer serves notice on a site,
it may disappear and then pop up somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The industry recently announced it was launching a campaign to
stamp out pirate sites by going after the Internet providers who
host the pirates. This will be on a global basis, making it tough
for some pirate sites to move overseas to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I like to take pictures I find on the Web and turn them into
Windows wallpaper. I do this by right-clicking on the image in
Internet Explorer and then choosing Set As Wallpaper. But every
time I do this, I lose the previous image completely. Is there any
way to save the image so it doesn't go away when I do this again?
</P>
<P>
   A: Your browser always saves wallpaper generated this way under
the same name _ Internet Explorer Wallpaper.bmp in the Windows
folder. Use My Computer to go into that folder, find the file and
right-click on it. Choose Rename, and then change the name to
better describe the image, and make sure it still ends with a .BMP.
</P>
<P>
   The file with its new name should appear in your list of
available wallpaper selections.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
