<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7995 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CALIF-BANK-ART-700(3T     11-12 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BANK-ART-700(3TAKES)-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT BANK: GRAND IDEA THAT WENT AWRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Nov. 14) 
(ART ADV: Photo (NYT26) is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD  
 &HT;     
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a way, Ernest Garcia and George Akers are flip
sides of the same badly tarnished policy coin, the battle against
raging unemployment in the inner cities. Both have operated small
businesses and received loans from the Los Angeles Community
Development Bank, an unusually ambitious, federally financed effort
to bring a measure of prosperity to depressed areas of this city.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, after his metal-plating business burned to
the ground, Garcia ran out of capital and hope. He had been
rejected by every commercial bank he approached, and finally turned
to the Community Development Bank for a $500,000 loan to rebuild in
his old neighborhood, East Los Angeles. The bank came through and
today his thriving company, West Coast Metal Finishing, has
increased its payroll from 7 workers to 42, and hums with the
sounds of heavy machinery and a salsa beat.
</P>
<P>
   The bank now celebrates his success with words it once reserved
for Akers' company, Trinity Knitworks, a garment maker. Akers and a
partner received the Community Development Bank's very first loan,
for $700,000 in 1996, when they sought to save Trinity and its
roughly 150 jobs. But Akers now says acidly that the loan was so
badly botched by the bank that he was effectively in default from
its first day. The company, overwhelmed by debt, has been shuttered
and Akers is mired in litigation with the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia says the bank saved his life; Akers says it just about
ruined his. In fact, the bank has produced a mix of such personal
tales, despite the confident assertions of backers like Vice
President Al Gore, who has endorsed the enterprise during visits
here and once proclaimed, ``This is an example of how an economic
empowerment program should work.''
</P>
<P>
   But the harsh reality is that, over all, this grand, $435
million government experiment has had negligible impact on
depressed areas of Los Angeles, even during an economic boom, and
the bank has been a crushing disappointment to many.
</P>
<P>
   Its loan default rate is a towering 32 percent, largely because
of one huge failure, and it has created a tiny fraction of the jobs
it promised. The Department of Housing and Urban Development, which
financed the bank, says the fault lies at least partly with lax
oversight by the city, while the city complains that the federal
money came with too many strings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past year at the bank has not been enjoyable,'' said Peter
Taylor, an investment banker at Lehman Brothers and a member of the
development bank's board. ``It's time to catch our breath and
narrow our mission and make the implementation of the idea work
properly.'' Both the city and the federal government want to keep
trying.
</P>
<P>
   To salvage the idea, the troubled development bank is being
reorganized. It is searching for a new chief executive, adding
staff and loosening some operating methods as it struggles to learn
from its mistakes and land on the right formula for stimulating
growth in areas that have been left further and further behind in
the current expansion. The bank has written a new business plan
that the City Council is scheduled to debate soon.
</P>
<P>
   Many people here remain deeply wary, but hopeful. So far, the
lending ``has not made a meaningful difference in my district,''
said Rita Walters, who represents South-Central Los Angeles, a
focus of the bank's lending, on the City Council. ``This is a whole
different world in here, and we cannot give up on it. The execution
needs to be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Marva Smith Battle-Bey, executive director of the
Vermont-Slauson Economic Development Corp., a nonprofit group that
invests in poor areas, added: ``That was a hard-fought battle to
get that bank and get it located in that neighborhood. It would
negatively affect investment there if this went south now. I feel
strongly that we need to make it a more viable instrument.''
</P>
<P>
   The interim chief executive of the bank, Linda Griego,
acknowledges the problems and argues that the Community Development
Bank can become more viable. ``A lot rides on this experiment,''
she said. ``A lot of people went out on the line for this. Some of
what's happened is just unbelievable, but it can be fixed in my
view.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the giddily prosperous era of the so-called new economy,
talking about high unemployment in depressed urban neighborhoods
may seem an anachronism, like discussing rust-prevention methods at
an Internet company. But even as the rates of teen-age pregnancy
and crime are dropping, joblessness in many cities remains
disturbingly intractable.
</P>
<P>
   Watts, for instance, which was convulsed by civil disturbances
twice in the last 31 years, has shifted from a mostly black to a
mostly Hispanic neighborhood, and it has been the target of many
government job programs. But the unemployment rate still hovers
near 20 percent, compared with 4.1 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Community Development Bank represents one of the
most expensive efforts to try a new philosophy in job creation.
These efforts are often described as partnerships, since the view
is that the government can merely help foster the growth of
businesses that must be able to survive on their own. The theory
was summed up in 1995 in an article in The Harvard Business Review
by Michael E. Porter, a professor at Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   In it, Porter said job creation would come only ``through
private, for-profit initiatives and investment based on economic
self-interest and genuine competitive advantage _ not through
artificial inducements, charity or government mandates.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
