<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7999 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CALIF-BANK-ART-2NDTAK     11-12 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BANK-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: government mandates.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo agrees: ``government is the
facilitator for the private sector. You have to promote
private-sector growth in there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Community Development Bank was set up by the
Clinton administration in the aftermath of the 1992 riots here. Los
Angeles had failed to qualify for designation as an Empowerment
Zone, a status that gives businesses an array of incentives to
operate in depressed neighborhoods and employ local people.
Furious, the city argued that it deserved some assistance, and the
administration eventually offered the development bank as a sort of
consolation prize. (Parts of the city have since received the
Empowerment Zone designation.)
</P>
<P>
   The bank was supposed to use public financing merely to water
the seeds of the private sector _ to help entrepreneurs help
themselves and then to get out of their way. In return, the
entrepreneurs were obliged to locate in the depressed areas _ a
patchwork of sites totaling 19 square miles, mostly to the south
and the east of downtown _ and hire at least half their new
employees from the neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   There are several other community development banks around the
country, in cities like Cleveland and Washington, but none are as
large, as political in their origins or as dependent on federal
funds as the Los Angeles bank. By the end of 2004, it is supposed
to have lent out all $435 million _ and then see that it is all
paid back.
</P>
<P>
   But that is becoming problematic at best. Of the $97 million in
loans it had extended as of Sept. 30, nearly a third have gone bad.
The bank's largest loan, $24.1 million to a dairy operation called
Copeland Beverage Group, exceeded the bank's own loan limit of $20
million to a single borrower, and it has been written off. The
company has been shut down. An additional $7.2 million of loans are
now listed as very high risk if not actual losses.
</P>
<P>
   The bank says it has fostered the creation or retention of 1,258
jobs, only 41 percent of the 3,039 required under the terms of the
loans it has made. (Companies are obliged to create at least one
job for every $35,000 borrowed.) And just 249 of those jobs went to
people living in the Empowerment Zone, fewer than a third of the
number required. The bank points out that since the companies have
two years to meet the standards, there is still time for some of
them to hire more people.
</P>
<P>
   But the figures are actually worse than they look. The bank's
employment statistics include nonexistent jobs _ positions created
or retained by companies that later failed, like Copeland and
Trinity. (The bank counts jobs created by its borrowers as well as
jobs retained by companies that would have closed without the
loans.) About 276 such jobs have vanished.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's proponents say that, at least in part, some of the
difficulties are built into its charter. It can now lend only to
companies
</P>
<P>
   that have been rejected by commercial banks, yet it places a
heavy burden on these companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's look at the reality,'' said Caron Caines, a member of
the Empowerment Zone Oversight Committee, a watchdog group
appointed by the City Council. ``You're going to lend money to
businesses that no one wants to lend money to, and then you're
going to saddle them with the responsibility of creating all these
jobs. I don't get it. What this policy does is to transfer the very
important policy goal of creating jobs to some of the weakest
members of the business community. These businesses have a hard
enough time just surviving.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Caines added: ``It's a grand experiment. But with that you
have to constantly monitor and evaluate and adjust the program to
make it work. None of that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Griego, a former deputy mayor, was brought in this summer
after the first chief executive, C. Robert Kemp, resigned because
of illness. She is leading the reorganization and helping to find a
permanent chief executive _ with luck, by the end of the year. She
said that every candidate who was approached initially had turned
the job down cold, but that some people were now interested. Even
the bank's sponsors _ HUD and the city _ have distanced themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would beg you not to use the bank as a platform to talk
about the bigger issues here,'' said Rockard Delgadillo, Los
Angeles' deputy mayor for economic development. ``It is one element
of what I would say is a large number for attacking this issue.
It's not a silver bullet. In fact, we've had more success with
other products.''
</P>
<P>
   The city has a new program, Genesis L.A., focusing on
encouraging businesses to locate in 15 old industrial sites. The
Community Development Bank is a bit player in the plan, well down
the list of incentives that include discounts on utility rates and
accelerated city permits.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo said in an interview that the bank's problems were the
city's, not the federal government's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can count on one hand the number of conversations I've had
with them,'' said Cuomo, emphasizing that Washington had not
meddled. ``The prevailing winds are devolution. The new ideas are
coming from the new breed of mayor. We do not come in and
micromanage.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I don't know that there's necessarily a lesson'' in
the bank's well-publicized problems.
</P>
<P>
   But many experts do see lessons, if not in the politics then in
a better understanding of what small businesses here really need.
Even some critics of the development bank, and there are many, say
it has shed some light on a more fruitful path.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's new business plan, put together during Ms. Griego's
tenure, includes some shifts in direction that are meant to take
advantage of the experiences so far.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
