<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8000 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-VATECH-MIAMI-BOS &LR;      11-12 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VATECH-MIAMI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP-PRIORITY GAME FOR VIRGINIA TECH AGAINST MIAMI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACKSBURG, Va. _ The task is as evident as it is difficult. Win
Saturday night's game against the University of Miami, and there is
a better than even chance that the Virginia Tech Hokies will be
back in the No. 2 slot of the controversial and important Bowl
Championship Series rankings.
</P>
<P>
   A loss Saturday night would have even more definitive
consequences. Bye-bye, so-long, see you in September, which will be
the next time we talk about the Hokies as a national championship
contender.
</P>
<P>
   The game Saturday night at Lane Stadium is arguably the most
important in Tech history.
</P>
<P>
   If you listen to Hokies coach Frank Beamer and Miami coach Butch
Davis, the primary concern is that it is a Big East game whose
winner will have a leg up on the league title.
</P>
<P>
   Left unsaid, for the time being, is the national significance of
the game, a rarity in recent years for any Big East matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Tech is clearly the team with the target on its back now. Under
Beamer, the Hokies have built themselves into more than a regional
power. They are unbeaten (8-0) this late in the year for the first
time in their history. And they are the flashpoint of the whole BCS
process, which weighs not only wins and losses but strength of
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Which is a sore point for Hokie fans, who have to defend the
scheduling of such ``powers'' as 1-AA James Madison and fledgling
1-A program Alabama-Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line is that Tech is very much a good _ perhaps
great _ team, no matter what its schedule suggests.
</P>
<P>
   And the key to that greatness may very well be a redshirt
freshman quarterback named Michael Vick.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Vick guy has given them a new dimension on offense,''
said West Virginia coach Don Nehlen, who saw that extra dimension
when Vick led the Hokies on a 58-yard scoring drive in the last
minute of what turned into a 22-20 Tech win, a victory which made
Saturday night's game so important.
</P>
<P>
   The Hokies come into their game against the Hurricanes as the
new beast of the Big East, a team that can beat you with Vick at QB
and a defense as nasty as it is good. The Hokies beat opponents up,
as evidenced by the 62-0 pounding they gave Syracuse earlier this
season in what was labeled the first ``game of the year''.
</P>
<P>
   Miami, which has rebounded from its mini-slump earlier in the
year when it lost to Florida State (expected) and East Carolina
(unexpected), is the type of team that can provide trouble for the
Hokies, especially with quarterback Kenny Kelly, by far the most
talented QB the Hokies will face during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone recognizes how talented Virginia Tech is,'' said
Davis. ``It's the one team in the country that puts as much
pressure on you to prepare in all three phases of the game. They
have a great reputation defensively _ an eight-man front concept _
they blitz and bring a lot of pressure. Offensviely, they have a
tremendous amount of speed at quarterback and great athleticism
with Michael Vick.And their big notoriety (is) special teams.''
</P>
<P>
   All of that makes the Hokies a solid favorite, although the
Hokies' narrow escapes in wins over Pittsburgh two weeks ago and
last week against West Virginia have created a sense of
vulnerbility.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that proves to be true will also determine whether the
Big East, maligned in recent years, has a genuine contender for the
national title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 1820EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8001 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CALIF-BANK-ART-3RDTAK     11-12 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BANK-ART-3RDTAKE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: so far.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the changes is a switch toward finding commercial banks to
go in as co-lenders, to ensure that market discipline and
professional underwriters are focused on the companies. In
addition, the bank intends to do more indirect lending, in which it
will provide funds to other, more experienced nonprofit
organizations in poor neighborhoods and then allow those groups to
make the actual loans to needy companies. That is intended to
correct what Ms. Griego said had been a major problem: that the
development bank was trying to create a lending and underwriting
department from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been reinventing the wheel,'' Ms. Griego said. ``It's
expensive, and it doesn't work to have our own people doing all
that. We're not going to compete in this market. We're putting
people with less experience than commercial bankers out there in
this market. It does not make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that in working jointly with commercial banks, the aim
was to find more resilient and experienced borrowers, not just
companies that had been rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like being a doctor and all of your patients have
serious cancer,'' said J. Eugene Grigsby III, director of the
Advanced Policy Institute at the University of California at Los
Angeles and a member of the bank's board. ``The rules we started
with say in effect that we deal only with the financial
untouchables. We ought to have more flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the rules on job creation and the need for the
businesses to be in the Empowerment Zone should be loosened. ``The
last thing a lot of start-up companies need is a requirement that
they should create a lot of jobs quickly,'' Grigsby said. ``They
have to keep costs down for a while and minimize their payroll to
survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Going forward, the bank plans to look for ways to provide not
only standard bank loans, known as senior debt, but also equity and
subordinated debt to borrowers, since that capital is more
``patient.'' It is longer term and can be used to help attract
capital from usual commercial sources, thus getting the borrowers
into the private markets more quickly. The bank already has a small
venture-capital fund but is looking to expand the ways it invests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming up with another debt program does not really help this
community,'' said Roberto Barragan, interim president of the Valley
Economic Development Center, a nonprofit organization that has done
lending deals with the Community Development Bank. Bank officials
built their strategy, he said, ``on the model of big companies,
which can service a lot of debt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a philosophy that's been pretty much trashed for these
small businesses,'' he added. ``They decided on a debt solution
before anyone had asked about the real needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Akers of Trinity Knitworks had much the same view. ``I didn't
need debt,'' he said. ``I needed working capital.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed changes in the bank's business plan have been long
in coming. Other institutions have used some of these new ideas
with great success.
</P>
<P>
   It is illuminating, for example, to compare the experience of
the Los Angeles Community Development Bank with a private-sector
organization called the California Economic Development Lending
Initiative. It is a consortium of 45 banks that has a lending
capacity of about $65 million, specifically for companies in
depressed areas.
</P>
<P>
   The Community Development Bank, which began with $435 million in
capital, took two months to start running and 14 months to make its
first loan. It was under great political pressure to put money into
the community quickly. Almost no one on the staff had extensive
commercial banking experience.
</P>
<P>
   The private consortium, by contrast, solicited two grants and
used them for a two-year study on how it should operate before it
took its first organizational step. Its staff is made up almost
entirely of experienced lending officers. Today, the private
consortium has made about $29 million in loans, with only 2 percent
of the total in default.
</P>
<P>
   George Williamson, the consortium's chief executive, insists
that his organization work with commercial banks to make sure that
the borrowers stay close to the private markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a close relationship with banks is an important part of
our strategy,'' he said. ``I would see dealing with companies no
bank would lend to as a silly way to proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some experts who say that the Community Development
Bank has legitimate functions, but that it should get out of direct
lending, because it requires too many skills. Instead, they say
that it should be only a co-lender with commercial banks, or that
it should lend indirectly through other nonprofit groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point I think they need to look at the possibility of
closing down the direct lending altogether, just close it,''
Barragan said. ``They should give management of the portfolio to
somebody else who has the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Caines of the Empowerment Zone Oversight Committee
said that her group had surveyed the bank's borrowers and that she
was slightly surprised by the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all said the paperwork was overwhelming them,'' she said.
``And it was clear the bank was really weak on technical assistance
to these companies. But, truthfully, I expected it to be more
negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert Gold, the chairman of Gold Graphics in Pacoima, a town at
the northern end of the San Fernando Valley that lies in the
Empowerment Zone, said his business was thriving until the
Northridge earthquake in 1994. The roof of the plant collapsed, and
Gold said he was woefully underinsured. He had a strong track
record and was able to secure a loan from the Community Development
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, the earthquake was the best thing that could
have happened to us because it caused us to undertake an
involuntary upgrade of all our facilities,'' he said. ``The
technology we put in was the technology the market was looking
for.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had gone from about 90 employees to about 180. But
one big drawback, he said, was the full year it took to have his
loan approved and financed _ a frequent complaint about the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from his modern printing plant is a store called Double
D Western Wear, another loan recipient. Abel Diaz, the owner, is
bitter about his experience. Diaz said the bank forced him to incur
$18,000 in costs, mostly for accounting work and an expensive
appraisal of his property, just to get the $420,000 loan, . And in
the year it took him to get the financing, his business had
declined so much that he actually needed more capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us here ran into the same situation,'' said Diaz, who
has run the store for more than 30 years. ``We came to them because
we were in trouble and needed the money. What were we supposed to
do in that year?''
</P>
<P>
   The bank said Diaz was in trouble from the start and that it had
offered enormous assistance to help him keep afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia of West Coast Metal Finishing said his experiences speak
to the bank's possibilities. On his office walls are photos of
himself with President Clinton, Gore and Los Angeles Mayor Richard
Riordan _ all elements in the dream he says he has experienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``You grow up in East L.A., and you don't have anything in this
life, and there I was at the White House,'' Garcia said, recalling
his visit there. ``They gave me an opportunity. Who else is going
to do that around here?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
