<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8002 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-BC-WVA-BOS &LR;      11-12 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BC-WVA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TABLES ARE TURNED FOR BC, WEST VIRGINIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A year ago, the Boston College football team limped
into Morgantown, W.Va., for its season finale with nothing left to
salvage except pride. The West Virginia Mountaineers, meanwhile,
were looking to score their seventh victory of the season in the
hopes of improving their chances for a bowl bid.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia defeated the Eagles, 35-10, and picked up another
victory over Pittsburgh, 52-14, in the season finale to land a
berth in the Insight.com Bowl in Tucson, Ariz. The Eagles retreated
to Chestnut Hill and pondered all that went awry after a 3-0 start
ended with six losses in their last seven games and a 4-7 record.
</P>
<P>
   Now the roles have been reversed.
</P>
<P>
   When BC (6-3 overall, 3-2 conference) hosts the Mountaineers
(3-6, 2-3) in Saturday's Big East home finale at Alumni Stadium,
the Eagles _ who this week vaulted from the obscurity of the
``others receiving votes'' to the No. 25 spot in the USA Today/ESPN
coaches' poll _ will be playing for their seventh victory of the
season and a chance to improve their posture for a postseason bid
to either the Insight.com Bowl, the Music City Bowl in Nashville,
or the Gator Bowl in Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   Favored by 3 1/2 points, the Eagles will enter the game rested
and refreshed from a week off after scoring a stirring 24-23
victory at Syracuse Oct. 30.
</P>
<P>
   And the Mountaineers? They will limp into the game after
absorbing a crushing 22-20 loss last week against third-ranked
Virginia Tech. It was a stinging setback for West Virginia in which
starting quarterback Marc Bulger, hampered by a fractured right
index finger that sidelined him for three weeks, was knocked out of
the game because of a chipped bone in his right (throwing) thumb.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question Marc came in as the guy who was going to keep us
going,'' said West Virginia coach Don Nehlen. ``He got hurt in our
opener and was very, very average, and he was about 90 percent when
we went to Syracuse and got hurt there. He was out for three more
weeks, and he's probably played with that hand at about 85 percent,
and now he's got a thumb to go with the finger on the same hand, so
he's out again. It's just been a disaster for poor Marc.''
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, the heroic effort of backup quarterback
Brad Lewis, who threw a pair of touchdowns that put the
Mountaineers ahead, 20-19, with 1:15 to play, was nullified when
Hokies kicker Shayne Graham hit a winning 44-yard field goal as
time expired.
</P>
<P>
   Also lost in the rubble of that devastating setback was the
impressive 133-yard rushing performance of freshman Avon Cobourne
against the Hokies' stingy defense, ranked first in the league and
No. 3 in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go along with the theory that a wounded animal is the
most dangerous animal, then they'd probably fit that classification
right now,'' BC coach Tom O'Brien said of the Mountaineers.
``They're a talented football team and they lost seven NFL players
from a year ago, but they still have about 18 seniors and 10
juniors on their roster, so they have a lot of good football
players in that program. I'm sure they have a lot of pride, and I'm
sure they want to come up here and play well.''
</P>
<P>
   BC's seniors are focused on matching the intensity.
</P>
<P>
   It will be Senior Day at The Heights, and for the first time in
their careers, BC's seniors will be playing a November game of
great importance _ all of which will only add to the emotionally
charged atmosphere. In fact, the last time the Eagles played such a
meaningful game at Alumni Stadium was Nov. 26, 1993, when BC,
coming off a momentous 41-39 upset of top-ranked Notre Dame,
returned from South Bend, Ind., to host West Virginia for the Big
East championship and ceded the league title and a trip to the
Sugar Bowl with a 17-14 loss.
</P>
<P>
   The following Nov. 19, the Mountaineers again posed an obstacle
to BC's bowl plans when the 6-2-1 Eagles went to Morgantown in need
of a seventh victory to seal an invite from the Fiesta Bowl
representatives in attendance. BC lost the game, 21-20, on a failed
fourth-and-1 attempt in West Virginia territory, wound up dropping
the season finale at Miami, 23-7, and went on to accept a bid to
the 1994 Aloha Bowl, which marked the last time BC earned a bowl
berth.
</P>
<P>
   Time for some payback?
</P>
<P>
   ``When we ended our season last year, this was one of the teams
that we couldn't wait to play again,'' said senior free safety
Pedro Cirino. ``They tried to rub it in our faces last year. At the
end of the game, they were throwing passes, deep balls, against us
with less than a minute left, and they were trying to run it up on
us. Hey, that's the way some programs do their thing. If we get our
chance, I just hope Coach O'Brien does the same thing to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Said junior quarterback Tim Hasselbeck, ``Anytime you go down
there to play, it's hard. Their fans are brutal, and if they get
the opportunity, they'll beat you 80 to nothing, so I really don't
think there's any love lost between the two of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, at the same time, I don't think that's the issue. I think
the issue is that we have a chance to win another game and maybe
get ourselves into a bowl game. It's also the last time that our
seniors will play in this stadium, which should be incentive
enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
