<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8004 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-BUTLER-BOOK-$ADV14-AR     11-12 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTLER-BOOK-$ADV14-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROYAL BUTLER ON A BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Nov. 14) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By JOYCE WADLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Confidentially, I did have a little problem with
Barbara Walters,'' the butler is saying on the phone from England.
``20/20. They said they needed something new _ would I be willing
to discuss A, B and C? _ and of course I could not. A relationship
between two people is a very special thing, it cannot be bought.
I've been offered a million pounds to tell my story, and I can't do
that. If I gave it away, who would I be? I wouldn't be the person
she called `My rock,' would I?''
</P>
<P>
   Poor Paul Burrell, who was butler to the late Diana, Princess of
Wales: Everybody wants to to exploit him and learn his secrets
about life with Di.
</P>
<P>
   I wish only to exploit him as a butler, to have for one magic
night a British butler in what, after only two long-distance
conversations with Burrell, I have come to think of as my Greenwich
Village ``flat.'' It is somewhat less grand than the last apartment
of the princess, a five-bedroom in Kensington Palace. I am just
guessing here, but I do not believe the princess kept her bicycle
next to her bed, or had dinner parties at which her guests sat on
the floor around the coffee table because the dining room table was
too small to seat more than four and the dining room did not exist.
This, however, is not the point.
</P>
<P>
   The point, according to a new book by Burrell, ``In the Royal
Manner: Expert Advice on Etiquette and Entertaining From the Former
Butler to Diana, Princess of Wales'' (Warner, $28), is that, let me
quote here, ``Style is not the exclusive preserve of the rich and
the famous. Style can be achieved by anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   That anyone is going to be me, assisted by Burrell, and now we
are setting up plans. I have in mind something I have been
desperate to do: a sit-down dinner for the 200 or so people with
dining rooms whom I owe. Burrell, a cheery fellow of 41, who, as he
will point out to me when we meet, looks very much like Tom Hanks
but who, unlike Tom, is presently without a full-time gig, puts the
kibosh on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dinner party will be difficult without a dining room,''
Burrell says, with exquisite butlerish manners. ``I think you
should make it as simple as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   This is my notion of what it will be like to have my own butler:
he will allow me to entertain as if I were an ex-wife of Ronald
Perelman. We will take a relaxed stroll, perhaps, to select the
wine and flowers, and then I will go off and nap. It will be the
most relaxed dinner party of my life.
</P>
<P>
   Only this is not the way it turns out.
</P>
<P>
   First there is the question of the food. ``In The Royal Manner''
has recipes, and as Burrell's contention is that anyone can
entertain in style, I had figured that Burrell and I (i.e.,
Burrell, as I cook nothing more ambitious than popcorn) would
prepare the food together. Burrell, however, has made it perfectly
clear, in the nicest possible way, that this might be ``an awful
lot'' to do, and we should get someone ``to knock it together'' in
the kitchen. In other words, before even arriving in New York, the
butler is demanding a cook. My friend Steve Jones, one of the
owners of the Knickerbocker Bar and Grill on University Place,
agrees to lend me his chef, Aaron Bashy.
</P>
<P>
   The larger problem is, I am exhausted cleaning up for the
butler. I polish the silver. I clear out the refrigerator, where a
container of milk and a wedge of blue cheese died in late summer.
The butler has said I need highball glasses, so I rush to Bed, Bath
&AMP; Beyond after work to get highball glasses. I stand in Gristede's
in front of the doilies, paralyzed with anxiety: doilies, don't
butlers live for doilies? Or are they considered tacky? If I do
need doilies, should they be square or round? From what Burrell has
told me, the butler's job is directing the staff, only in this
case, I am the staff. A butler, I see, is worse than company _ he
can go poking around everywhere. I scrutinize everything in the
apartment: that little Di and Charles china box from the wedding I
keep on the bedside stand _ should I put it away? He does still
seem pretty upset over her loss.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the flat? Can it possibly live up to the butler's
standards? He has told me he will be greeting my guests, then
bringing them in to me. I haven't had the heart to explain that
once he opens the door, they're in.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the day of the event, the butler arrives in a suit with
a knee-length jacket, with a nice big grin you can see down the
hall _ the building's hall, not my hall. Even at 50 feet, I can see
he's not a stiff British butler. The young woman with him is the
one who seems serious. She has the look of a no-nonsense book-tour
escort, there to make sure the fun-loving author makes the plane,
but this is not the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Louise Cosgrove, my PA,'' Burrell says, and, just as I'm
figuring out that my butler has a personal assistant, adds, ``I'll
let you in on a secret: she's my niece.''
</P>
<P>
   My apartment doesn't throw him. He compliments me on one of the
nicest things about it, the view of the Empire State Building. He
insists, under questioning, that he is not daunted by the size of
my 4-foot-wide kitchen _ a professional can entertain in any
surroundings, Burrell says. He was once involved in a banquet on
Tuvalu in the South Pacific where there was no electricity,
although local residents did most of the preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Doilies turn out not to be his thing. ``Honestly?'' he says when
he sees the package, in the tone your girlfriend uses when you try
on flowered pants.
</P>
<P>
   There is one surprising thing about him: Despite his refusals to
discuss his relationship with the princess, he can't stop referring
to her. ``I'm just looking to see if you have the princess'
favorite film,'' he says, examining my bookshelves.
</P>
<P>
   Which would be?
</P>
<P>
   ``Brief Encounter.''
</P>
<P>
   And, taking stock of the refrigerator: ``Veuve Clicquot _ did
you know that was the princess' favorite Champagne?''
</P>
<P>
   This is the menu the butler and I (i.e., the butler) have
decided on for the big night, which is to be a cocktail party with
finger food, on account of the lack of a dining-room table: Pimm's
cocktails (I think of them as a summer drink, but the butler says
they will be helpful as ``a talking point''), pasties, miniature
beef Wellington, leeks and mushrooms en croute and salad. (How is
that going to be finger food?) For dessert, we will serve a trifle,
which seems odd at a cocktail party, but the butler says it's is a
must. (``There's always a pudding in royal circles. The queen
always asks for a pudding, never a sweet or dessert.'')
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The recipes have been causing a small problem: Aaron the chef,
testing them in the Knickerbocker kitchen, is finding them bland
and has been spicing them up.
</P>
<P>
   There is no such problem with the butler, who sets out on our
shopping trip, full of enthusiasm and good cheer, despite having
arisen at 5:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   He loves New York; it's his favorite city; he and the princess
said many times that one day they would love to live in America.
For the right opportunity _ not butlering, because having worked
for ``the best,'' he has ended his butlering days _ he'd move here
with his wife and two sons in a minute, he says. Something having
to do with entertaining would be nice. He's writing a weekly advice
column on that in The Daily Mail and would love a TV show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like a bite of Martha Stewart's apple,'' is how he puts
it.
</P>
<P>
   He praises the selection in the markets, though he does not
throw money around. At the Crossroads Liquor store on 14th Street,
he turns down the $35 bottles of California wine he's offered for
bottles under $10: a '97 Pepperwood Grove cabernet sauvignon for
$6.99, a '97 Louis M. Martini cabernet sauvignon for $9.99. (Sound
bite: ``Entertaining is also about a budget. There is no point
serving expensive wines at a reception.'')
</P>
<P>
   He is also very taken with the tequila with the worms in the
bottle. He wants to get it for his friend Nigel back home, and when
sensible Louise tells him Nigel is too fastidious, would never
touch it, he buys a bottle of Vampire wine from Transylvania for
himself.
</P>
<P>
   He cannot, throughout the day, stop recalling Diana.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the name of that rose?'' the butler asks the owner of
the Ariston florist shop on 14th Street, where he chooses the
flowers for a pink and white display. ``It's exactly the rose I
used to bring for the princess _ 4:30 every Monday morning, I'd be
at Covent Garden, picking the flowers. ''
</P>
<P>
   I'm developing a theory about this title-dropping. I'm thinking
it's done not so much to remind people of the position Paul Burrell
once held with the most photographed woman in the world, but rather
as a widower might, or a jilted lover, who is not yet able to
accept his loss and leave the happiest part of his life behind.
</P>
<P>
   Because, from what he tells me over lunch, working in Buckingham
Palace was his dream. He grew up in a mining village in
Chesterfield, in north England, where his father drove a coal
truck. His home, which Burrell describes as very happy, had no
indoor bathroom. Burrell saw Buckingham Palace as a child of 8,
announced that someday he would work there. His mother worked in a
factory to put him through hotel school. At 18 he was off to the
palace, and within a year he was a footman for the queen. He
married a woman who was Diana's dresser, and they, like the
princess, had two sons. When the prince and princess divorced, the
princess asked that Paul Burrell go with her. Because, as Burrell
tells it, he was not only the butler; he was a soul mate,
protector, confidant _ a butler, as he explains it, of ``the new
school.''
</P>
<P>
   What is the difference between the old school and the new?
</P>
<P>
   ``One is traditional; the other is conventional,'' he says.
``One follows the rules to the letter. The other adapts his own
personality to the working environment. The princess would ask my
advice on how to dress. Remember that dress she wore to the
Serpentine gallery opening, black chiffon with long chiffon scarf?
I suggested that. If I'd been the butler in `The Remains of the
Day,' his master would never have asked advice on how to dress. The
princess often asked what I thought. I'd ask, `Do you want an
honest opinion?' She always did, and I'd give it to her. A lot
wouldn't. She knew I'd take care of her.''
</P>
<P>
   He speaks of visitors just getting to know the princess,
surprised at first at his presence in the room as they shared
stories. ``They didn't know who I was, thought I was a servant,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   There is a sad moment as we discuss the death of Diana. Burrell
remembers the queen's private secretary calling him at 3 a.m.,
asking him if he is standing or seated and then telling him to sit
down: The princess is dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I was needed in Paris more than I was needed at
home, so I packed a small bag for myself and a bag for Diana,''
Burrell says, his eyes growing moist. ``Don't ask me what was in
it. It's as far as I've ever revealed or would ever reveal.''
</P>
<P>
   An article in People magazine reported, after the funeral, that
Burrell took to the hospital a dress for his princess, fixed her
hair and held her hand until her sisters arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Burrell speaks only of the weather that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember it was very windy at the Paris airport,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But let us segue to matters not so sad, the preparations at my
flat. Mel Brooks had it right: ``It's good to be the king.'' Or to
put it another way, ``It's good to have a butler.'' I leave my
apartment, in my role as staff, to return a trolley on which we
have schlepped supplies, and when I return 10 minutes later, my
apartment looks fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   The butler has put an antique wrinkled linen runner on the table
in the dining room, surrounded it with scalloped and starched white
linen place settings I have never used, found and laid out my
prettiest, if mismatched, Limoges and Bavarian pink and white
flowered plates. Now he's in my tiny kitchen, slicing English
cucumber and oranges and lemons and strawberries for the Pimm's
cocktails, garnishing the tall glasses with a slice of orange, a
slice of lemon, crushing a mint leaf in his fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pimm's makes me thinks of Ascot,'' he says. ``The 2:30 race
about to start, or Agassi on center court. There were people who
said I made the best Pimm's. In royal circles, it's done with
Champagne, but that's too extravagant. I served drinks at the royal
box, and little sandwiches and cakes and tea. We'd have tea between
the third and fourth races. There was a kitchen behind the royal
box.''
</P>
<P>
   Was the kitchen at the track smaller than mine?
</P>
<P>
   ``Bigger,'' Burrell says, grinning.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tell me more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd arrive in a parade of carriages. I'd be riding on the
back of the queen's carriage. I'd jump off, open the door, follow
her into the royal box. All the ladies wore hats; the men wore
morning dress and top hats. I wore a stiff white frock shirt, white
tie, scarlet coat. I was sometimes able to invite my mum, and she
was so proud to see me riding along the route.''
</P>
<P>
   Happiest memory of royal service?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably looking after the queen and the royal party on
the princess' wedding day.''
</P>
<P>
   You went to the wedding?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I stayed back at the palace and walked the corgis.''
</P>
<P>
   The princess' wedding day, and he is walking the dogs?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, but I got to look after the bride and groom when they got
back. I served the top table, the bride's table. Just immediate
family. No more than 80 persons.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell what he saw at the wedding breakfast? Of course he won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``What goes on behind those walls stays behind those walls,'' he
says. Taking a swipe at the former cavalry officer who wrote a
memoir about his affair with the princess, he says, ``James Hewitt
did, and that's the difference _ a very significant difference''
between James Hewitt and himself.
</P>
<P>
   They were well acquainted?
</P>
<P>
   A stiff evasion. ``I knew him, and he was neither an officer nor
a gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   The time of the party is almost upon us. Aaron the chef, a
high-energy guy with a downtown shaved head, who, unlike the
butler, feels no compunction about complaining about anyone,
arrives, telling the butler and his personal assistant about an
idiot woman who gave him and the Cornish pasties a hard time about
being in the passenger elevator. I, as I've seen in the movies,
leave the staff to do its work and retire to the bedroom to dress.
Given the size of the palace and the boom of Aaron's voice, it is
impossible not to hear some of the talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy Hewitt who wrote the book about Diana _ he was kind
of a jerk, wasn't he?'' Aaron asks.
</P>
<P>
   I dive for my notebook.
</P>
<P>
   The butler's reply is too courteously quiet to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   The magic of that evening with my butler? Where to begin? I have
told my 10 guests I am doing a story on entertaining ``with help''
_ it is journalistic ethics to state one's purpose, and anyway they
would start wondering what was up when they saw the photographer _
but not all my guests know who the help is. I must say, with
downtown pride, they deal well with the presence of a butler. Lew
tells the butler he wishes to be announced as the Duke of
Wellington, and the butler cheerfully accommodate him.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the butler greets the guests, takes their coats (I
have explained that it is an ancient New York custom to throw them
onto the bed), makes friendly and amusing conversation, much of
which includes pointed references to Buckingham Palace and his
book. He asks the guests what they would like to drink and brings
each drink on a folded cloth napkin atop a plate, one hand behind
his back. His method of announcing dinner is different from that of
the New York hostess who address the guests as a group and invites
_ then exhorts, then entreats _ them to get something to eat. He
approaches the guests one or two at a time, asks if they would care
to have something to eat, takes them to the buffet and serves.
</P>
<P>
   There is one awkward moment when the butler greets my friend
Vicki, a strawberry blonde who once worked at People magazine, and
tells her that she looks just like Sarah Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think so?'' Vicki asks. ``You know, I like her much better
than Di.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cole Porter is playing, the Pimm's cocktails are loaded with
gin, the food _ although Aaron considers the beef Wellington
overcooked and the butler calls it undercooked _ is wonderful, so
the awkward moment quickly fades. The party grows loud, the old
friends gossip, the time in the evening for the Champagne arrives.
</P>
<P>
   I have told the butler I am going to toast a forthcoming
marriage, but this is a lie. As soon as he has passed the glasses I
make a toast, in a room full of writers, to a fellow writer _ a
wonderful fellow and a great sport _ who has just published a book.
My friend Victor, who has hidden the butler's book under his
jacket, now holds it aloft, and we all drink to Paul Burrell, who
joins the party, along with Louise the Personal Assistant and Aaron
the cook. The rest of the night I get the drinks. I would tell you
what we talked about, but as my butler has already explained, the
things that go on beyond closed doors are private.
</P>
</TEXT>
