<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8008 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT     11-12 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POTENTIAL GUSHER FOR SOUTHERN COASTAL STATES  
 KEEPING AN EYE ON UTILITIES  
 REBUILDING FISH STOCKS  
 OIL PATCH PROTESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: The South, Calif., Alaska)  (mk) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Southern coastal states would be swimming in money
for conservation projects under a measure likely to surface in
Congress next year now that it has been endorsed by a key House
panel.
</P>
<P>
   The Conservation and Reinvestment Act would radically
redistribute money collected from offshore oil drilling royalties,
setting aside $3 billion annually for environmental preservation,
land purchases and coastline protection. Advocates say it would
provide the largest-ever infusion of federal dollars into
conservation efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Since the measure would distribute money based on miles of
shoreline and proximity to oil drilling, coastal states stand to
strike it rich, particularly those close to oil and gas rigs in the
Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana would receive $313 million, second only to
California's $327 million. Alabama would receive an estimated $53
million; Florida, $141 million; Georgia, $40 million; Mississippi,
$76 million; North Carolina, $44 million; South Carolina, $28
million, and Texas, $237 million.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the measure in the last days of the congressional
session by the usually divided Resources Committee was a milestone
and came after months of negotiations ended with a measure that
drew bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, head of the panel, hopes to move the
measure by next summer. But obstacles remain, including objections
from Western lawmakers who fear the money could finance a federal
land grab.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups are not satisfied either, saying the bill
could promote offshore drilling. Yet they embrace much of the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would not recommend the president sign it as now written,
but a handful of responsible changes can turn it into legacy
conservation legislation everyone in Congress can be proud of,''
said Rodger Schlickeisen, president of Defenders of Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   POWER STRUGGLE
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists are keeping a close eye on spending measures
as Congress moves toward adjournment, worried that Southern and
Midwestern utilities being sued by the Environmental Protection
Agency may insert last-minute language intended to ease financial
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The power companies, including Southern Co. and Tampa Electric,
are accused by the EPA of illegally modifying their coal-fired
plants to extend their life span without adding the necessary
pollution controls. The utilities deny the charge.
</P>
<P>
   Watchdog groups say a proposed amendment being circulated on
Capitol Hill is intended to allow the companies to escape the stiff
daily fines they face if the EPA charges are proved.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Ferrulo of Florida Public Interest Research Group said the
firms are seeking ``a safe haven from the fees and penalties that
may be imposed as a result of 20 years of complete disregard for
the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The utilities contend the proposal would simply give them the
ability to perform necessary maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   NO FISHING
</P>
<P>
   A new congressional proposal would prohibit commercial tuna,
shark and billfish fishing in parts of the South Atlantic and Gulf
of Mexico in an effort to rebuild stocks of the depleted but
popular game fish.
</P>
<P>
   Under legislation introduced by Sen. John Breaux, D-La.,
commercial longline harvesting of the migratory species would be
banned year-round from the border of North and South Carolina to
Key West, Fla., with seasonal closures in much of the Gulf of
Mexico. Commercial fishermen would be ``bought out'' under a $25
million program, with the costs shared by the federal government,
recreational fishermen and remaining commercial operators.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux said his proposal represents an agreement among key
groups that ``all want to protect small swordfish and other rapidly
declining fishing resources. A true solution will require
international cooperation, but we are taking a bold step to address
the problems in our own coastal waters.''
</P>
<P>
   VICE PRESIDENTIAL MATERIAL
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore's declaration that if elected president
he would ban oil and gas drilling in areas already leased to oil
companies off Florida and California continues to generate howls of
protest from the oil patch _ mainly from fellow Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux of Louisiana immediately lashed out at Gore's plan,
calling it ill advised. Now Rep. Chris John, D-La., is weighing in
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, too, want to ensure that our marine and coastal environment
remains healthy and sustainable, but the policies you have outlined
jeopardize our domestic energy security, threaten the economies of
many communities dependent on the oil and gas industry and provide
little measurable environmental benefit,'' John wrote to Gore a few
days ago. So much for party unity.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
