<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMOVABLE STORAGE ZIPS WITH THE TIMES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Zip drive revolutionized removable disk storage in the
early 1990s, it did so with a 100-megabyte disk in a portable drive
that connected either to a SCSI or a parallel port.
</P>
<P>
   In the PC world, most folks used the parallel port model;
Macintosh users went with SCSI. The Mac fans had it all over the PC
users here, because SCSI is much faster than a parallel port.
(Installing a SCSI port on a PC in those early days could result in
serious torment.) Often, the parallel port drives conflicted with
printers or scanners that were also connected.
</P>
<P>
   Today, those issues have vanished with the arrival of the
Universal Serial Bus port. Makers of removable drives finally have
a way to make using them virtually painless _ and fast.
</P>
<P>
   (That is, if you're using the right operating system. The
original Windows 95 doesn't support USB; the update that appeared
in early 1997, OSR2, does support it, but not well. Windows 98 is
the first serious implementation of it, and Windows 98 Second
Edition smooths out a lot of USB bugs.)
</P>
<P>
   Last week, I looked at a slew of USB devices. I'll finish up
this week with a look at two external, ``superfloppy'' drives that
now are available in USB versions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Zip 250 USB, $180, Iomega Corp.:  &UR;  &LR; When Iomega first
introduced its 250-megabyte Zip drive earlier this year, I was
disappointed to learn that it was only available in a poky parallel
or a SCSI model, just like the original Zip drive. USB already had
come into its own, but Iomega was holding out on us.
</P>
<P>
   The USB version of this higher-capacity drive is finally here,
and it was worth the wait. The new version is sleeker, easier to
use and more versatile. It works on both PCs and Macs. An optional
PC-card adapter is available so you can use this on a notebook
computer that may not have USB ports.
</P>
<P>
   This new drive is less than half the size of the original. It's
got a sculpted, semi-translucent blue shell. It easily could fit
into the thinnest briefcase, and with its light weight you wouldn't
even know it was there.
</P>
<P>
   The 250-MB disks come in six-packs at about $100. The 100-MB Zip
disks, which this drive also will read, can be found for about $10
each.
</P>
<P>
   Installation was a breeze. You install the Iomega software
first, shut down your system and plug in the drive. When your
system next boots up, it recognizes the drive, and it appears in
your My Computer folder. Easy-to-use software lets you reassign the
drive letter to your liking.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, this is a fast little drive, with a transfer
rate of up to 950 kilobytes a second. Copying a folder with 37 MB
of files onto a 250-MB disk took just 12 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   On its Web site, Iomega warns that there may be problems writing
to 100-MB data disks, though I had no problem doing so. I also
didn't notice any slowdown, though the site warned about that, too.
Your mileage, of course, may vary.
</P>
<P>
   _ SuperDisk Drive USB, $150, Imation: The SuperDisk drive _ also
known as an LS-120 drive _ is a great idea in theory. It gives you
a high-capacity removable-disk drive and lets you read standard
1.44-MB floppies.
</P>
<P>
   But the original technology had a major drawback _ it was slow.
In fact, it was agonizingly so in some cases. Waiting on a
parallel-port-based LS-120 drive to do its thing could put years on
you, or it felt like it, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Imation has revamped the system, improved the drivers and now
offers a USB version that is much more pleasant to use. It's not as
fast as the Zip, mind you, but it's a lot better than past models.
</P>
<P>
   The model I tried was about the size of the original Zip drive
and twice as heavy. It's really meant as a desktop drive; I suspect
its size has something to do with the mechanics necessary for
reading standard floppy disks.
</P>
<P>
   The LS-120 uses 120-MB disks that are slightly thinner than
floppies. A three-pack costs about $45, so they're a bit more
expensive than Zip disks.
</P>
<P>
   Installation also was simple, but it's the reverse of the Zip.
You plug in the drive first, and when Windows asks for drivers, you
insert a CD-ROM disc and install from there. Like the Zip, this
drive also will work on a Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   The SuperDisk has a transfer rate of about 667 KB a second, and
it copied the 73-MB folder in about 20 seconds, noticeably longer
than it took for the Zip drive. It was also much noisier _ it
really chugs along, much like a traditional floppy.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect any speed improvements reading or writing to a
standard floppy, though. Floppies are just sluggish by nature.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
