<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8010 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FLA-FORENSIC-CENTER-N     11-12 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-FORENSIC-CENTER-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY OF FLORIDA IS CREATING A FORENSIC MEDICINE CENTER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CINDY SWIRKO   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Maggots can't communicate with humans. But
Bruce Goldberger can uncover secrets with maggots _ maybe even
unravel the mystery of a murder.
</P>
<P>
   The teeth from a corpse can't speak of whose mouth they once
filled, but Anthony Falsetti can make those teeth sing.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberger and Falsetti are key figures in the creation of a new
forensic medicine center at the University of Florida that they say
will be the first of its kind in the United States. Goldberger is a
professor in toxicology and Falsetti in anthropology.
</P>
<P>
   For years their interests have intersected in forensics, the use
of science in law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our two labs acted independently for several years'' Falsetti
said. ``We decided to bring together all the forensic sciences on
campus.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Goldberger, ``It's going to include forensic anthropology,
forensic toxicology and other specialities, including psychiatry,
dentistry, engineering, nursing, law, pathology.''
</P>
<P>
   Say a skeleton is found in a forest, which is not uncommon, and
police want to learn the story behind the bones. Who are they going
to call? A forensic expert, who tries to figure out who the person
was and how he died.
</P>
<P>
   Falsetti works with bones, but Goldberger works with the soft
stuff _ fluids and tissue _ to detect fatal toxins or poisons.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Goldberger doesn't even need human samples. Maggots
will do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just finished a case with maggots, which was very
interesting,'' Goldberger said. ``There was no tissue remaining _
just a small amount of muscle, and maggots. We tested both and
found drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberger and Falsetti developed the proposal to create a
center named after William R. Maples, the late UF forensic
anthropologist noted nationwide for his work. The center has been
approved by the state Board of Regents and should begin next year.
</P>
<P>
   Formal programs in forensic medicine will be drawn from
anthropology, pathology, nursing, dentistry and others. Eventually,
a master's program will be created.
</P>
<P>
   Research will look at the length of time illegal drugs remain in
bone, ways to detect drugs, the effect wildlife has on destroying
or scattering remains, the effectiveness of ground-penetrating
radar in locating remains and three-dimensional imaging for facial
reproductions.
</P>
<P>
   Courses, seminars and other programs for forensic specialists,
medical examiners and police will also be available. Center
employees will be available to police departments, communities and
other groups who need forensic expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Other universities offer courses and degrees in forensic
sciences that deal with the collection and examination of evidence,
such as bullets or explosive devices. Some also offer courses in
forensic medicine, but the UF master's degree may be the first in
the country in forensic medicine. The degree could lead to a job in
a wide range of fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could be an anthropologist or toxicologist. They could
also be a death investigator. They could be the manager of a
medical examiner's office. They could assist in autopsies, they
could work in crime labs, police departments _ it could go on and
on,'' Goldberger said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Kiser is director of certification and member services
for the American College of Forensic Examiners, an association of
forensic professionals with 15,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   Kiser said full-fledged degree programs in forensics are rare.
She added that growth in potential jobs for graduates is high.
</P>
<P>
   ``The field is always growing, but there are not many
universities that teach forensics,'' Kiser said. ``Forensics
crosses all the fields. People are fascinated with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Falsetti and Goldberger said some of that fascination is spurred
by movies and television.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberger has a picture of Dana Scully, one of two FBI agents
who work creepy cases in ``The X-Files,'' a television series.
Goldberger said Scully has inspired potential students, but a job
like her's is as rare as the alien remains autopsied on the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get silly calls from people asking how they can be a
medical doctor, a special agent, work for the FBI and investigate X
files,'' Goldberger said. ``It has drawn a lot of interest, but the
characters are total fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville Sun in Gainesville, Fla., is a member of the
New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
