<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET CAN HELP WITH TURKEY
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Thanksgiving a week from Thursday, it's not too early to
begin looking for recipes and other holiday traditions.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine remembers one tradition well. ``The definition
of eternity,'' he reminds me each year about this time, ``is two
people and a turkey.''
</P>
<P>
   Better Homes and Gardens magazine, for the fourth year now, is
featuring its Thanksgiving Survival Guide on its Web site
(www.bhg.com). To go directly to the Thanksgiving pages:
www.bhg.com/food/holiday. America Online members can type AOL
Keyword: BHG, then click on the Thanksgiving link.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more useful features is the roasting guide that
allows users to select the time they want to have dinner ready and
then see what time they'll need to start the turkey, beef or pork
roasting.
</P>
<P>
   Users will also learn that eternity is about the amount of time
needed to defrost a frozen turkey. BHG recommends four days in the
refrigerator for even a modest one of 10 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The roasting guide has been expanded this year to include beef,
pork, lamb and veal. There are new recipes, too, including ones for
crockery cooking. Cooking classes for cookies and candy making not
only include recipes, but step-by-step instructions, photos and
videos as well. In addition, the site offers ideas for dressing up
store-bought cookies. There are also recipes for old-time fudge,
peanut brittle and peanut butter balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thanksgiving Survival Guide, improved again this year, is
one of our most widely-used features, and helps our readers prepare
delicious, yet simple, holiday meals,'' said Jean LemMon, the
magazine's editor. ``With this kind of planning help and creative
holiday ideas, you can count on spending more of your time relaxing
and enjoying the holiday with family and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   If you need help beyond timing the turkey, BHG offers a menu
planner to let users select their favorite appetizers, breads,
vegetables, salads, main dishes and desserts.
</P>
<P>
   Lazier than that? There are preplanned meals (with two diabetic
selections) and menus for six, 12 or 20 people.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes not only can be printed, but the site will create a
shopping list of ingredients needed, organized by grocery sections.
A calendar shows make-ahead steps that can be done in preparation
to take some of the pressure off Thanksgiving day.
</P>
<P>
   Message boards on ``holiday traditions'' and ``holiday cooking''
let cooks exchange ideas on those subjects. Other message groups
include ones on healthy cooking, quick meal ideas and baking.
</P>
<P>
   The site features new articles each weekday and offers special
holiday and seasonal sections. It is designed to offer BHG
magazine's 35 million readers additional information on articles,
as well as augment material featured on the BHG television program.
</P>
<P>
   Cruising
</P>
<P>
   For those planning a holiday cruise, a visit to icruise.com
(www.icruise.com) will prove helpful. The site, said a company
spokesman, is ``the most complete cruise ship database ever
assembled online,'' offering exclusive cruise packages and a
``best-price'' search engine that helps pick out the lowest travel
fares available.
</P>
<P>
   The company was originally established in 1998 to provide cruise
information to travel agents on a subscription basis. But in
September, the company began offering information and travel
packages directly to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The site has listings for nearly 150 cruise ships leaving from
more than 50 ports to nearly 2,000 worldwide destinations. Users
can designate their preferences for activities, facilities,
services and dining options while searching for cruises. The
best-price search allows users to select ships, sailing dates and
cabin categories.
</P>
<P>
   A review section offers independent reviews and ratings from
CruiseReports on dining, staff profiles, service, port reviews and
feedback from cruise passengers.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
