<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8018 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TRANSPLANTS13-COX     11-12 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSPLANTS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRANSPLANT CENTERS SET FOR REGULATORY 'TRIAGE'
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Transplant centers that have resisted government
attempts to regulate traffic in human organs weighed their options
Friday after an agreement that appeared to lift much of Congress's
opposition to the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to move on,'' said Robert Spieldenner, a spokesman for
the United Network for Organ Sharing, a nonprofit organization made
up of representatives from hospitals that perform transplants,
tissue typing laboratories and donor and recipient networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to prepare, because if it does go into effect in such
a short time frame, we have to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 68,000 Americans are on waiting lists for heart, lung,
kidney and liver transplants. The new rule would dramatically
change the way the limited number of available organs are
allocated.
</P>
<P>
   The regulation is an outgrowth of more that a year of
negotiations involving the Clinton administration, transplant
centers with often opposing interests, and members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement between Health and Human Services Secretary Donna
Shalala and House Appropriations Committee Chairman C.W. Bill
Young, R-Fla., Thursday cleared much, but not all, of the
opposition to increased government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   It would force broader sharing of transplant organs, primarily
livers, and give Shalala's department final authority over
allocation policies. It would go into effect within six weeks after
Congress approves a federal budget for the department.
</P>
<P>
   The organ sharing network has resisted the new allocation
system. In general, the rule would make organs available in wider
areas and increase the priority afforded to patients in greatest
need.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the agreement, opposition remained in some congressional
offices.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., a week ago introduced a bill that
would prevent what Sessions called ``an unprecedented takeover of
our nation's transplant system by HHS.'' Sessions said he had 26
co-sponsors in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   A companion bill has been introduced in the House.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of concern about organ transplant equity is the
human liver, Spieldenner said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, around 4,500 human livers were available for
transplant. More than 12,000 patients waited to receive liver
transplants.
</P>
<P>
   However, since a liver must be put into a recipient's body
within 12 hours or the chances of the operation succeeding drop
dramatically, transplant networks have had a tendency to approve
recipients who wait in a hospital relatively near the one where the
donor died, he said.
</P>
<P>
   This has caused the national shortage to be felt most acutely in
those hospitals that perform large numbers of transplants _ such as
those at medical schools at the University of Pittsburgh, the
University of Miami, the University of Nebraska and the University
of California, Los Angeles, all of which perform from 100 to 300
transplants a year.
</P>
<P>
   These centers have been agitating for wider distribution
networks that would to some degree relieve their shortages. And a
report by the Institute of Medicine four months ago said the system
often results in persons who are less ill receiving organs sooner
than more severely ill patients served by different networks.
</P>
<P>
   The same shortages cause less contentious problems for opposite
reasons with respect to hearts, lungs and kidneys, Spieldenner
said. Kidneys can be preserved for up to 48 or even 72 hours, and
therefore shipped farther. Hearts and lungs can be kept only about
six hours, so there is little hope of sending them to patients
farther away.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute of Medicine also said transplant centers that
serve larger numbers of recipients have greater success than
smaller centers.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Hudgins, director of regulatory studies at the
Libertarian-leaning Cato Institute, which opposes virtually all
government regulation, said allocation of organs should be left to
private decision makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, when something is commercialized, it becomes more
accessible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that with advances in the science of
``xenotransplantation,'' in which animal organs may someday be
placed in human bodies, the shortage problem could disappear in a
few years ``and the government will be in place to regulate that
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Only about 50 animal organs have ever been transplanted into
humans, and all the recipients died.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
