<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8023 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ANY-GIVEN-SUNDAY-FILM     11-12 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANY-GIVEN-SUNDAY-FILM-$ADV14-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVER STONE'S NEW WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Nov. 14) 
(bl) 
 By BRUCE NEWMAN  
 &HT;     
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. _ Before the 1972 Super Bowl, President
Richard M. Nixon drew up a pass play for the Miami Dolphins and
gave it to the team's coach, Don Shula. Nixon had lately been
directing the retreat of U.S. forces from Vietnam, but was sure he
had a winner this time. The Dolphins waited only eight plays to run
the pattern against the Dallas Cowboys, resulting in an incomplete
pass and contributing to a humiliating 24-3 loss. Two and a half
years later, Nixon resigned from office in disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   Like Nixon, Oliver Stone could hardly wait to send a play into
the big game. He began collecting pro football cards when he was
10, living all alone on the fourth floor of an enormous home on New
York's East 64th Street that he shared with his father, a
stockbroker, and his French-born mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was an only child, a lonely child,'' Stone says. ``I used to
play in my little room. I called it the green room, because the
floor was green and the wallpaper was green. I had a bunk bed, and
I liked to sleep on the bottom of the bunk bed. I don't know why.''
</P>
<P>
   There he was _ an only child, a lonely child _ on his upper
floor, the empty bunk looming over him at night like a dark cloud.
And in his solitude, he would fan out the football cards from his
collection in intricate formations, and transform his garret into a
clamorous stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would play a game, a very concentrated game on this green
field _ my rug _ with the football cards _ 11 on 11,'' Stone
recalls. ``I devised an entire system of football, with books. I
had every team written down. And I kept logs, as only an obsessed
child might. Page after page.''
</P>
<P>
   As Nixon and the boy who would one day become his rebarbative
five o'clock shadow both understood, football is simply war by
other means. To illustrate this potent 1970s metaphor, now comes
``Any Given Sunday,'' Stone's film about pro football, which opens
Dec. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the movie's concussive force, it will be difficult to
improve on the assault that Nixon unleashed on North Vietnam as his
aerial follow-up to the Super Bowl debacle, a 40,000-ton rain of
bombs tellingly called ``Linebacker Two.'' Nixon knew his target
audience. The question is, does Stone know his?
</P>
<P>
   Three of his last four pictures _ ``Heaven and Earth,''
``Nixon'' and ``U-Turn''_ failed at the box office, and even his
two incendiary triumphs, ``JFK''and ``Natural Born Killers,'' left
Stone with a constituency so limited _ Doom-playing, drug-bingeing,
anomie-addled assassination theorists and 12-step conspiracists _
that it was uncertain whether he could draw a crowd anywhere
outside second-gunman chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   He was making documentaries from his own fevered dreams, making
history, and making it up as he went along, too. When he ran into
difficulty finding studio backing for ``Memphis,'' his
reinterpretation of the events leading up to the assassination of
Martin Luther King Jr., he decided to give up challenging
historical orthodoxies.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Stone came very close to making ``Mission: Impossible
2,'' before he came to his senses and dropped out to play his
football card.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever else ``Any Given Sunday'' may be, it is not least
Stone's attempt to plant his flag in the commercial mainstream.
Bomb-throwing is a young man's game. ``It doesn't excite my passion
to unveil corruption anymore,'' he says. ``It's apparent everywhere
around us, it's just part of life. I realize I can't do anything
about it. It's there, it's always going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending his films _ defending himself _ through the storms of
controversy he has sailed into has left Stone with scars that he
wears like ribbons. ``I died more than once on `JFK,''' he says.
``It became a question of, `Are you anti-conspiracy? Are you
pro-conspiracy?' Unfortunately, we tend to polarize issues rather
than debate them. Where has the middle gone?''
</P>
<P>
   This question seems especially poignant, coming from Oliver
Stone. He is 53 now, and his own middle is more evident, a
softening fleshiness having settled in everywhere but the brittle
almond eyes. During an interview at his office, he holds out his
hands to show the scars from an attack by a knife-wielding robber,
who cut Stone while he was living in the East Village, studying at
New York University's film school after coming home from Army duty
in Vietnam. And there are the scars he got taking out a Vietcong
gun nest (for which he won the Purple Heart and a Bronze Star) _
would you like to see those?
</P>
<P>
   There is something disorienting about this: that these wounds
opened three decades ago remain so raw. He had hurried to enlist in
1967, knowing the war would not last forever; he could not wait to
get to Vietnam, to prove to his father that he was ``a man, not a
boy.'' Thirty years later, he still seems reluctant to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Stone doesn't mind playing the part of the Brilliant Weirdo. He
is so exquisitely aware of his own myth that he always seems to be
standing slightly outside of it, watching to see how the customers
react. When a reporter arrived from The Washington Post several
years ago to discuss his film ``Nixon,'' Stone asked: ``Why do they
hate me so much? Do you think it's me they hate _ or my work?''
</P>
<P>
   Much of this anguish is heartfelt, as if Stone were constantly
abraded by unseen furies. He lashes out at ``liars'' in the media
who want to ``destroy'' him. One of these specimens has printed an
incorrect release date for ``Any Given Sunday.'' ``He knows the
truth, and yet still he lies,'' Stone says of this transgression.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way that Stone sees politics as inherently
Shakespearean, he views football as operatic. (He has already
boasted in an interview that ``Any Given Sunday'' will be to
football what ``The Godfather'' was to gangsters: an epic aria.)
``I think it has all the American elements,'' the director says.
``Violence, guts, blue-collar linemen, the green earth, the worms,
the Indian drums, the moccasins. The grunting and the groaning and
the fighting. It is a war, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Like the portentous quotations that open many of his films,
``Any Given Sunday'' picks at the question of what it is to be a
man, Stone's central preoccupation. His films are friezes of
hot-blooded, hyper-masculine men and chilly women who exist mostly
as chalk outlines.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of testosterone-fueled masculinism is not unknown
among violent auteurs like Sam Peckinpah, who dispatched men and
women with equal fury. ``Even with Peckinpah there was more sex,
more attraction between men and women, than there is with Oliver
Stone,'' says Molly Haskell, a critic who has written extensively
about women in film. ``I think he's unusual in that respect, in
having really virtually no women's roles. Try to imagine him
adapting Jane Austen or Edith Wharton. It's inconceivable.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Hollywood's great directors have shared Stone's macho
predilections, but because the studios kept as many women as men
under contract, movies in the 1930s and '40s treated women as part
of the human equation.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Hawks so adored women that he paid them the highest
compliment he could imagine: he hired actresses to play men. In
``His Girl Friday,'' Hawks' 1940 remake of ``The Front Page,''
Rosalind Russell was actually playing a role originated by Pat
O'Brien. But women like Jean Arthur in ``Only Angels Have Wings,''
Joanne Dru in ``Red River'' and Barbara Stanwyck in ``Ball of
Fire'' _ women who were more lip than lipstick _ were a rarity in
their time.
</P>
<P>
   Stone takes a page from the Hawks playbook in ``Any Given
Sunday'' by making Christina Pagniacci, the owner of the Miami
Sharks (played by Cameron Diaz), one of the most brutish characters
in the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about sports that brings men together and
their passions are excited,'' Stone says. ``It's a thing I know
because I do have hair on my body, and I have masculine qualities.
But that doesn't mean I'm all masculine, that through
reincarnations, dreams, fantasies, you can't be a woman too.'' In
Christina, he has found his altered ego, freshly depilated.
</P>
<P>
   The more vulnerable, self-pitying figure in ``Any Given Sunday''
is Coach Tony D'Amato, who is Stone's stalking horse this time out.
``I have sweated blood for these men,'' says the coach, played by
Al Pacino. ``Given up my wife, my children for these men. I've
given up everything I have for these men. Games are all that
matters to me, because that is pure, it's sane. Life isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone's own life hasn't always been pure either. In August, he
was sentenced to three years' probation and ordered into counseling
after being arrested with hashish in his possession for the second
time.
</P>
<P>
   His wars may be over, but Stone soldiers on. Actors who worked
on ``Any Given Sunday'' talk of having had their ``manhood
challenged,'' as one put it, and of being surrounded on the set by
beautiful women spectators, who were constantly coming and going.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Foxx, the young actor who plays the Sharks' quarterback,
Willie Beamen, said, being a football player under Stone was like
being led into battle. ``It was a nice Vietnam,'' he said. ``Only
we were in Miami, so the enemy was the women.''
</P>
<P>
   This is just as it has been since Stone's breakthrough film,
``Salvador,'' in which a photographer played by James Woods tells
his friend (James Belushi) that American women are not to be
trusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latin women, now, they're totally different,'' he explains.
``They're kind, they're understanding. . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   But Belushi's character cuts him off. ``Best thing about Latin
women,'' he says, ``is they don't speak English.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wildly autobiographical novel he published two years ago,
``A Child's Night Dream,'' Stone writes of his hero _ who is named
Oliver Stone _ dreaming of sexual ecstasies with his mother, who is
French. ``And it was my mother's face staring down at me,'' he
writes in one passage, ``as she was doing this to me and me to her,
both of us entwined like snakes of desire.'' Then comes the
transforming moment of consummation: ``O how thrilling! How
exciting! Against all rules! All flags!''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the author of this weren't also the director of ``JFK,''
it would be difficult to know how to take the dream. But something
happened to shape Stone's view of women, and of himself. ``It was
very bizarre, as a boy, to be introduced to women through my
mother,'' he says now. ``And these women were predatorily sexy.
What could I do? I didn't know what to do, didn't have the first
clue. I was a ghost. That's why I went to Vietnam. I couldn't have
an identity, I didn't know who I was. I was the invisible man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't able to do anything about it,'' he adds. ``I wasn't
experienced. I was scared of women, I was very scared. To some
degree, I guess we all still are, because they can be pretty
scary.''
</P>
<P>
   He tries to laugh at this, but instead he trills something
strained and high-pitched _ a giggle _ and suddenly he is 10 again,
thinking dreamily about the green room, the football cards, the
safety of his bottom bunk. ``Especially American women,'' he says
finally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
