<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-EXHIBIT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Native Lands' presents Ga. before Europeans
 &HT;    By Jill Young Miller
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta History Center charts new territory today
with its first major exhibition devoted to Native Americans who
once thrived in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in Atlanta, and I found ... there seemed to be very
little consciousness of the role Native Americans have played,''
said Sarah Hill, guest curator of ``Native Lands: Indians and
Georgia.'' The exhibition explores Mississippian, Creek and
Cherokee cultures in an ambitious effort to, as Hill said,
``restore this broken history.''
</P>
<P>
   A panel of Creek and Cherokee Indians, whose ancestors were
evicted from Georgia, served as advisers on the project. They will
gather today for the exhibition's opening, where they'll tell
stories, demonstrate basketry, bead working, mask carving and
perform traditional songs and dances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to educate people more about the Muscogee way of
life,'' said storyteller Joyce Bear, a Creek cultural preservation
officer with the Muscogee Nation of Oklahoma. ``Most people think
that once we were driven out of Georgia, we ceased to exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Before European settlers came to what is now Georgia, Native
Americans lived across the land. The Mississippians, who flourished
from about 900 to 1500, built ceremonial mounds and surrounded them
with their towns, some with populations in the thousands. Whole
towns died of disease contracted from Europeans in the 16th
century.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1700s, many of the Mississippians' surviving
descendants had joined a group called the Creek Confederacy and
lived throughout most of what is now Georgia. Another group of
Native Americans, the Cherokees, lived in the southern
Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Native Lands'' explores the cultures _ and what happened to
them _ in a circular exhibit with videos and significant pieces
collected from around the country. One of the finest items is a
Cherokee deerskin coat trimmed with red trade cloth and red
buttons, from about 1800, on loan from the Smithsonian
Institution's National Museum of the American Indian. At the time,
Cherokee men wore coats cut like European shirts.
</P>
<P>
   The original treaties that signed away Indian land in Georgia
also are on display; they're on loan from the National Archives. In
a case nearby is the knife that was used to kill a man who betrayed
the Cherokees by signing.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia and the federal government forced the Creeks and
Cherokees to leave their native lands and move west. By 1825, the
Creek Nation had been evicted. The discovery of gold in 1929 on
Cherokee land provided whites with another reason to drive out the
Indians. In 1838, U.S. troops rounded up the Cherokees and forced
them west. Many of them died on the infamous Trail of Tears. By
1840, almost no Creek or Cherokee people remained in Georgia. Today
their descendants live in Alabama, North Carolina and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition is sponsored in part by the National Endowment
for the Humanities and runs through Jan. 1, 2001. A smaller version
then will travel to Indian reservations around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
