</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAXIM-EARNINGS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maxim Group loses money on carpet outlet turnarounds
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ High operating costs at Maxim Group caused the floor
covering retailer to lose money in the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Delayed by its restatement of fiscal 1999 earnings, Maxim
released its results for the first and second quarters on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The second-quarter loss fell to $2.7 million, or 14 cents a
share, from a loss of $21.6 million, or $1.32 a share, in the
year-earlier period. Revenue rose to $202.5 million from $95.6
million.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, Maxim's loss after charges was $800,000,
or 4 cents a share, compared with net income of $1.3 million, or 8
cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $192.6 million from
$96.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The retailer continues to struggle to turn around
underperforming stores it acquired from Shaw Industries. Maxim
operates 1,000 carpet outlets, including 323 owned by the company,
under several nameplates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first half of this year was consumed with the problems we
have with operational efficiency,'' said Tom Leahey, executive vice
president of finance.
</P>
<P>
   Cost reductions this year have ``stabilized'' the company as it
regroups from expenses associated with the restatement of fiscal
1999 earnings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The restatement spurred a lengthy forensic audit that cost the
company $4 million. The second quarter included a related charge
for $2.7 million. The remainder will be expensed in the third
quarter, Leahey said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Maxim faces $2.7 million in settlement costs in a
tentative agreement with bondholders to waive a technical default.
Last year, the company repurchased more of its own shares than was
allowed by terms of the 9.25 percent bonds, issued in October 1997
and maturing in 2007. The default led auditors to question the
company's ``ability to continue as a going concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxim has offered to purchase at least $40 million of the bonds
at 102 percent of face value. About $95 million of the bonds remain
outstanding. Holders of the outstanding bonds would receive a
``consent fee'' of $50 for every $1,000 of principal they hold. The
interest rate on the bonds would increase to 12.75 percent from
9.25 percent. The consent fee would cure the default, Leahey said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
