<HEADLINE>
TEACHER ASSAULTED AFTER CONFISCATING POKEMAN CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ANA VALLE-GREENE    
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ A seventh-grader was charged with a felony and
may be expelled from school after he attacked a teacher who
confiscated the boy's Pokemon trading cards.
</P>
<P>
   The Polk County School Board on Tuesday will consider whether to
expel Gabriel Cruz Sosa for the remainder of this school year and
for all of 2000-2001, said Greg Bondurant, director of discipline
and security for the Polk County School District.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year-old student at Sleepy Hill Middle School was charged
with battery on a school board employee, a third-degree felony,
according to a Lakeland Police Department report.
</P>
<P>
   The student violated the school's ban on the popular
Japanese-character game. He became upset when teacher Brian
Bridges, 29, took the cards, the police report says.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel ``charged the teacher, pushed him and choked him ... and
tried to run out,'' according to a report filed by Principal Ann
Tankson. He was suspended after the Nov. 2 incident pending School
Board action, Bondurant said.
</P>
<P>
   Bondurant said the recommendation is to expel the boy for more
than a year because he intentionally assaulted a teacher. Usually
when a student hits a school employee, it happens when the adult is
trying to break up a fight among students.
</P>
<P>
   Sleepy Hill is not the only school to ban the cards, which are
part of a franchise of TV shows, games, videos, books and a movie
that opened Wednesday and has taken the under-12 set by storm.
Tankson wrote parents at the beginning of the school year
explaining that the cards would be confiscated and given back only
to parents at the end of the semester.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
