<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8035 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WATERWAR13-COX     11-12 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATERWAR13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Official: Water war truce talks sinking
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ President Clinton's appointee to the committee
negotiating a settlement in the water war among Georgia and Alabama
and Florida warned the states Friday that the talks appear to be
headed for failure.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay Thomas, a former Georgia congressman and head of the
state Chamber of Commerce, said that the complexities of the water
dispute and unyielding demands from various groups for more water
may doom the negotiations. Negotiators have been trying for nearly
two years to craft a regional water-management plan to divide up
the waters of the Chattahoochee and other rivers shared by the
three states.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this late date (in the negotiations), a failure to reach an
agreement is a very real possibility,'' Thomas said at a
negotiation session in Atlanta on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, he said, the states may be headed for ``long,
costly and arbitrary litigation'' in federal court, and they would
forfeit ``a great opportunity'' to determine their own destinies
over water. ``This dispute could be settled by a federal judge who
has never seen these river basins and who does not know of the very
important roles these basins play in these states,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who represents nine federal agencies at the negotiating
table, is a nonvoting member of the committee deliberating over a
water war agreement. However, he has the power to veto any
settlement the negotiators may reach if the decision adversely
affects the agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, Alabama and Florida are squabbling over the
Apalachicola-Chattahoochee-Flint river basin, and Georgia and
Alabama are squaring off over the Alabama-Coosa-Tallapoosa river
basin. The headwaters of both basins are in Georgia. The states are
trying to come up with water sharing formulas for each basin by
Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia wants enough water to sustain metro Atlanta's projected
growth over the next 30 to 50 years. Alabama wants adequate water
supplies to fuel its own growth, and Florida wants to be assured of
enough water coming down the Apalachicola (formed by the
conjunction of the Chattahoochee and Flint) to nourish its Gulf
Coast oyster industry.
</P>
<P>
   In between, several groups are demanding enough water to meet
their own specific needs. They include farmers in southwest Georgia
who are worried that metro Atlanta's growing reliance on the Flint
River will rob them of water for irrigation; commercial barge
operators on the lower Chattahoochee who are concerned there won't
be enough water to float their vessels; and environmental groups
who say that more water for people and industries will leave less
water for fish and other aquatic creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said that if the groups are not willing to relent on some
of their demands, a water war settlement may be doomed. The various
groups ``will not go quietly into the night,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Kerr, Georgia's chief negotiator, said that Georgia is
``willing to share the pain.'' He said Thomas's remarks brought
``wisdom, insight and perhaps some proper chastisement.''
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's negotiation session, which dealt only with the ACF,
Georgia and Florida made little headway on agreeing how much water
should flow from Georgia into Florida during droughts. A
negotiation meeting for the ACT is scheduled for Monday in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
