<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8036 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LATINO-SCHOLAR-2TAKES     11-12 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINO-SCHOLAR-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMBITIOUS INTERLOPER OR WELCOME PRESENCE? A LATINO SCHOLAR ANSWERS
CRITICS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Texas, N.C.)   By LYNDA RICHARDSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, MASS. _ Ilan Stavchansky Slomianski has come a long way
from the secluded, middle-class Jewish enclave of Mexico City where
he grew up. There Ilan, the son of a popular Mexican soap opera
star, attended Yiddish day school and celebrated the high holidays
in synagogue. Other kids called him El Guerito (Little Blondie).
</P>
<P>
   Now El Guerito is known as Ilan Stavans (his father's stage
name) and is a widely published writer and editor and one of the
most influential figures in Latino literature in the United States.
When W.W. Norton, the foremost publisher of literary canons, wanted
someone to produce a major anthology on Latino writing two years
ago, it selected the 38-year-old Stavans, a professor of Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   To some Latino experts, Stavans is a welcome presence who is
creating excitement about a long overlooked field of writing. To
others, he is an ambitious interloper who is stealing attention
from more deserving and seasoned scholars.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's becoming the czar of Latino literature and culture,''
said Juan Flores, a professor of black and Puerto Rican studies at
Hunter College. ``This guy comes in, and he's the one who is the
spokesman, the canon-former who is making the ultimate decisions
about what is worthy of readership on the part of the American
audience. It's astounding the quick move to that kind of
prominence.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Stavans says, he is what he is. ``I don't have any
apologies,'' he said in an interview in his office at Amherst
College, the only faculty office in the health center. Amid the
volumes by American essayist Edmund Wilson, the Peruvian poet
Octavio Paz and the Argentine writer Jorge Luis Borges sits a
photograph of his father dressed as a woman in a black wig, with
pursed lips, for a play like ``Cabaret.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people attack me because I wasn't born in the barrio,''
he said. ``I've been attacked for not being dark skinned and for
being young. If you paid attention to all this, you would be naked,
walking in the street, without a name and a telephone number.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he left Mexico in 1985, he has published more than a dozen
books on Hispanic culture in Latin America and the United States.
He proposed the Latino literary anthology right after Norton
published its anthology on African-American literature, which
became the fastest-selling anthology in the book publisher's
history. Norton took his suggestion, and the Latino anthology is
due out in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Stavans has several more works on the way, including
a memoir on language coming out next year, a dictionary on
Spanglish, the hodgepodge of Spanish and English, and a cartoon
history of Latinos in the United States. He is the editor of a book
series on Latin American Jewish literature and the editor in chief
of Hopscotch, a stylish new English-language magazine on Hispanic
culture and politics.
</P>
<P>
   He is ``more ambitious than 10 men and a mule,'' said Reynolds
Smith, the executive editor at Duke University Press, which
publishes Hopscotch.
</P>
<P>
   This prodigious output prompted The Chronicle of Higher
Education to label Stavans the emerging ``Skip Gates of Latino
studies,'' referring to Henry Louis Gates Jr., the ubiquitous
Harvard professor and chairman of the Afro-American studies
department who is co-editor of the Norton Anthology of
African-American Literature.
</P>
<P>
   It is a comparison that Stavans happily embraces. ``He manages
to combine academia with the public sphere in a way that I find
wonderful,'' said Stavans, fairly gushing. Stavans modeled
Hopscotch on Transition, a cheeky journal on black culture and
politics that was founded in Uganda in 1961 and resurrected by
Gates. Now, Gates is on Hopscotch's advisory board.
</P>
<P>
   Stavans' rapid rise to prominence, however, has chafed some
writers and scholars who regard him as a well-connected
opportunist; an arriviste with only a superficial knowledge of the
cultures on which he ruminates. His critics say that the Eastern
Establishment has anointed Stavans as a leading spokesman for
Latinos, whose complicated experiences he has not scrutinized
deeply.
</P>
<P>
   True, Stavans was writing Mexican detective novels and dabbling
in experimental film and theater in the 1970s and 1980s when many
Latino students and scholars in the United States were waging war
with college administrators to create Chicano and ethnic studies
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The controversy has been that he has come onto the Hispanic
literary picture fairly recently,'' said Francisco Lomeli, a
professor of Spanish and Portuguese and chairman of the Chicano
studies department at the University of California at Santa
Barbara. (He is also a consultant on the Norton anthology.)
Explaining the criticism, he said, ``People have worked so hard
against the grain, and to have somebody come in almost like a
character out of theater, deus ex machina, there's a little bit of
resentment.''
</P>
<P>
   Stavans admits that the complications of identity did not occur
to him when he was a fair-haired boy watching ``Star Trek'' on
television in Mexico City. It was not until he went to college
there that he realized how little he knew about his country. Then
he rejected his Jewish roots and went backpacking across Mexico and
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to have the least to do with Jews as possible,'' said
Stavans, a gentle-mannered man with wire-rimmed glasses. ``I wanted
to integrate and become Mexican.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stavans found that the more that he tried to become like
everyone else, the more he felt different. He dropped out of
college after two years to embark on a Hemingwayesque life as a
writer in Spain, England and Israel. He eventually returned to
Mexico City to complete his undergraduate studies in psychology,
appeasing parents who wanted him to have a backup if writing did
not succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Stavans was writing under his father's stage name when he moved
to New York in 1985. He enrolled at the Jewish Theological
Seminary, where he met his wife, Alison Sparks Stavchansky, who is
a speech pathologist. They have two young boys.
</P>
<P>
   He studied for his doctorate in Latin American literature at
Columbia University. There he wondered why so little attention was
paid to Latino writers in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   His approach to the question of Hispanic identity, however, has
not won admiration from some Latino scholars. Stavans said he
stresses the similarities among Hispanic groups rather than their
differences. That contrasts with a more confrontational approach
that emphasizes Latino ambivalence and even resistance to American
culture and history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Latinos are a separate nation in the U.S.,'' he
said. ``We are entering, belonging and sharing that melting pot
with many other minority groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Stavans' most widely taught book, ``The Hispanic Condition:
Reflections on Culture and Identity in America'' (HarperCollins,
1995), is his most controversial. While some reviewers called it a
useful primer on Latino culture, others like Flores said the book
made cosmic generalizations about Latinos and lacked rigorous
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Stavans said his views on Spain also put him at theoretical odds
with many old guard academics in Latin American studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been for many years resentment of Spain as the
conqueror, but a lot of things about modern Spain have changed,''
he said. ``We should talk about the Hispanic world as a much more
dynamic body made up of Spain, Latin America, the Spanish-speaking
Caribbean and Latinos in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   His withering assessment of some of the field's best-known
writers, like the novelist Sandra Cisneros, author of the acclaimed
book of related stories, ``The House on Mango Street,'' has also
irritated some of his colleagues. In Academic Questions, the
journal of the National Association of Scholars, three years ago,
Stavans asked why Ms. Cisneros had become ``the most sought-after
Latina writer of her generation and a guest impossible to ignore in
any multicultural fiesta.''
</P>
<P>
   Tey Diana Rebolledo, a professor of Spanish at the University of
New Mexico at Albuquerque who published an anthology of literature
of Mexican-American women, said Stavans panned Ms. Cisneros ``in
kind of nasty ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even those with mixed feelings about Stavans see his
presence as beneficial. ``He's opening doors to publishing houses
and institutions where U.S. Hispanic literature has not entered
before,'' said Nicolas Kanellos, the director of Arte Publico Press
in Houston, the largest publisher of Hispanic literature in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Kanellos said Norton never answered his letter in the early
1990s when he approached them about a 10-year project that he is
coordinating with scholars nationwide to recover, index and publish
lost Latino writings in a series of books. (The Norton anthology
will be a single volume of about 2,200 pages.)
</P>
<P>
   Rolando Hinojosa-Smith, a professor of English at the University
of Texas at Austin, insists Stavans deserves the attention that he
is getting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people complain, then they should sit down and produce,''
said Hinojosa-Smith, who will edit the contemporary
Mexican-American section of the upcoming Norton book.
</P>
<P>
   Still, to some scholars like Ms. Rebolledo, Stavans remains a
bit of a curiosity. ``He doesn't come from within the culture,''
she said. ``He's not Chicano. He's a Mexican. He hasn't been in the
movement ever since it started, so he's a little bit of an
outsider.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't bother Stavans, who considers his status as an
outsider a advantage. Stavans said his own upbringing in a Jewish
ghetto in Mexico gives him a sense of what it is like to feel
marginalized. The theme flows through much of his writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mexico, I was a Jew. In the U.S., I became a Mexican, but
all these dichotomies helped me to see that you can be an outsider
and an insider simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``You become a member of another minority, but not fully. Here
I'm a Mexican in the U.S. I'm a Latino. I'm a Jew. I'm an
American.''
</P>
<P>
   So when Stavans' authority is again questioned, this time in a
review for his skill as editor of ``The Oxford Book of Jewish
Stories,'' he brushes it off. A review in The Times Literary
Supplement in London said, ``Why Oxford University Press, which
used to pride itself on publishing reliable anthologies, should
have sponsored this particular collection, edited by a
nonspecialist, must be left open to question.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can know enough,'' he said firmly. ``Because you
live in two or three worlds doesn't mean you don't live in any of
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
