<SLUG> BC-INVEST-CONSTRUCTION-ART-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSTRUCTION STOCKS POISED FOR RESURGENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass.)  (ART ADV: Graphic of Standard &AMP; Poor's supercap engineering and
construction index is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 14) 
(af) 
 By MICHELLE LEDER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wall Street is never wrong, according to the common wisdom, just
early in making its investment recommendations. Analysts were
wildly ahead of themselves in 1998, when Congress passed a giant
transportation spending bill; many decided to recommend the shares
of engineering and heavy-construction companies.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with shares down 35 percent, on average, from their 1998
peaks, it may just be time to take the analysts up on their picks.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, the Transportation Equity Act for the 21st Century,
earmarked $217 billion for federal spending on highways, a 44
percent increase over the bill it replaced. In the first quarter of
1998, the Standard &AMP; Poor's SuperCap Engineering and Construction
Index rose 21 percent, partly in anticipation of the bill's
signing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ran it up because they saw huge amounts of funding,''
said Charles D. Brady, an analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston,
referring to the construction sector.
</P>
<P>
   But the government's future largess would be overshadowed by
more immediate concerns. Shares of construction and engineering
stocks eased as petrochemical-related projects were canceled
because of declining oil prices. The stocks' retreat became a rout
amid fears of a global recession.
</P>
<P>
   As appropriations failed to materialize, disappointing earnings
reports hurt the industry further. ``Over the past year, just about
every one of these companies has blown up,'' Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, two construction companies have failed to meet
third-quarter earnings forecasts, leading to selloffs. On Nov. 3,
Granite Construction of Watsonville, Calif., reported profits of 77
cents a share, versus analysts' estimates of 83 cents as reported
by First Call/Thomson Financial. The stock fell 6 percent over two
days, and is now at $20.375.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 27, Stone &AMP; Webster of Boston announced that it was in
violation of its credit agreements and posted a loss of 52 cents a
share instead of the profit of 65 cents a share that analysts had
expected. The stock fell 40 percent in a day; it is now at $15.625.
</P>
<P>
   But 18 months after the transportation legislation was passed,
money is beginning to trickle into the coffers of construction and
engineering concerns. Between $25 billion and $28 billion of
government funds are guaranteed next year, so analysts say the
stocks should begin to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Granite Construction, which despite its
weaker-than-expected quarterly results said it would meet 1999
earnings estimates, analysts' favorites include Jacobs Engineering
Group of Pasadena, Calif.; Morrison Knudsen of Boise, Idaho; and
URS Corp. of San Francisco, an engineering company. All are trading
sharply below their 52-week highs, most near their 52-week lows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first quarter of next year is when you're going to see the
benefit in a major way,'' said David N. Allen, director of research
for the Granite Financial Group, a San Diego brokerage firm not
affiliated with Granite Construction. Allen has buys on Granite,
Morrison Knudsen and URS.
</P>
<P>
   Already, about a quarter of the $2 billion order backlog at URS
is related to the transportation law. URS is now at $21.5625, 27
percent below its 52-week high. Allen, who rates URS a buy, has a
52-week price target of $26. He also has a buy on Granite, with a
target of $25.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks are trading for under 12 times analysts' consensus
estimates for this year's earnings. One of Brady's picks is Jacobs,
now trading at $32.50; his 52-week price target is $45. (Brady also
likes Morrison Knudsen, trading at $8.9375, on which he has a
12-month price target of $14.)
</P>
<P>
   Mark Dyer, an analyst at Strong Capital Management, says the
industry is attractive at current prices. The Strong Common Stock
fund recently increased its position in Jacobs, bringing it up to
1.2 percent of the fund's assets. Separate accounts managed by
Richard T. Weiss, manager of the fund, hold a 1.2 percent stake in
Morrison Knudsen.
</P>
</TEXT>
