<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-QUAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST 17 KILLED BY QUAKE IN NORTHWESTERN TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ At least 17 people were reported killed
Friday night by an earthquake in northwestern Turkey, and hundreds
more were injured. Many buildings collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are facing a new disaster,'' said President Suleyman
Demirel. ``This is a destructive earthquake. I hope we will not
face a great loss.''
</P>
<P>
   The earthquake struck days before a summit meeting in Istanbul
that President Clinton and the heads of more than 50 other
governments are expected to attend. No serious damage was reported
in Istanbul, but buildings shook and residents of some
neighborhoods fled from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   It was centered near the town of Duzce, in a hilly region
between Istanbul and Ankara.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately we have a heavy toll in Duzce,'' Prime Minister
Bulent Ecevit told reporters. ``The death toll is 17 so far.''
</P>
<P>
   The region around Duzce was hit by a much more severe earthquake
in August that killed more than 17,000 people. Hundreds of
thousands of survivors are still living in tents. The failure of
the government and army to respond quickly to that disaster led to
widespread outrage, and Ecevit moved quickly Friday night to assure
citizens that these failings would not be repeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rescue crews and relief aid have been sent to the region,'' he
said. ``The armed forces sent assistance to the region
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Direct communication with Duzce was cut. News reports said that
the main road leading to the town was impassable and that relief
efforts were curtailed because the local fire station had
collapsed, trapping a number of firefighters. Television footage
showed people there huddling on the street and pouring water on
flames.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is utter helplessness here at the moment,'' reported a
correspondent from one television station. ``Hundreds of buildings
have collapsed, but there is no one who can help.''
</P>
<P>
   The director of an observatory in Istanbul, Ahmet Mete Isikara,
said the quake registered a magnitude of 7.2 on a standard seismic
scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have collapsed buildings,'' the regional governor, Nusret
Miroglu, told one interviewer. ``We need rescue crews and
ambulances.''
</P>
<P>
   The president and Hillary Rodham Clinton are due in Turkey next
week, with their daughter, Chelsea. Clinton is to join other
leaders at a meeting convened by the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
