<HEADLINE>
MITCHELL RECESSES TALKS, HOPING FOR LAST-MINUTE ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ With Protestant unionists split over whether to accept
IRA promises to disarm, former US Senator George Mitchell sent both
sides home Friday for the weekend to ``reflect on the magnitude of
the decisions they have to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who has spent the last two months trying to save the
Good Friday political settlement he brokered in April 1998, had
hoped to wrap up his task Friday. Instead, he will reconvene the
talks on Monday, hoping for a last-minute compromise between
Catholic and Protestant leaders on going ahead with a plan that
would give the IRA's political ally Sinn Fein a share of power in a
new government for Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   While Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble appears willing to
form a power-sharing government in exchange for commitments from
Sinn Fein and the Irish Republican Army that disarmement would
begin quickly, his aides said he has yet to build a consensus in
his party.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble's top deputy, John Taylor, broke ranks Friday, saying he
had voted against accepting assurances from the IRA and Sinn Fein
at a much-disputed meeting of the 27 Ulster Unionists who would
become assembly members if a government is formed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm against the proposals because there's nothing new in
them,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Unionist sources insisted that a majority of the party's
assembly members had not voted against the package of assurances
put forward by the IRA and Sinn Fein, but said Trimble was worried
that he lacked the backing of some key party members, including
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Kelly, an assembly member for Sinn Fein, said the
unionists had taken only 20 minutes to consider and reject the
written and verbal assurances from the IRA and Sinn Fein that the
process of disarming would begin as soon as the power-sharing
government was formed.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most influential members of Trimble's party are
insisting that the IRA turn in weapons first, or that the IRA make
a formal declaration that the war to force a British withdrawal
from Northern Ireland is over.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble stuck to his refusal to be drawn into what he said were
speculations about the behind-the-scenes negotiations, and some
observers said that the political posturing by some unionists is a
smokescreen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal's been done,'' said Billy Hutchinson, a leader of the
Progressive Unionist Party, the political wing of the Ulster
Volunteer Force, a loyalist paramilitary group.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson said the only remaining question is whether Trimble
can sell the compromise to the Ulster Unionist council, the party's
ruling body. Trimble could put the question to the council on Nov.
20 or Nov. 27, said party chairman Lord Rogan.
</P>
<P>
   But if Trimble is on board, as Hutchinson and other participants
in the talks suggest, it remains unclear whether he can bring his
party with him.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said his 10-week review of the peace process ``has
reached the final and most critical phase.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have asked the parties to pause over the weekend and reflect
on the magnitude of the decisions they have to make,'' Mitchell
said in a statement, sticking to his strategy of low-key diplomacy.
``I recognize that this process has gone on much longer than
originally intended. However, given the gravity of what is at
stake, it is appropriate to take the time necessary to thoroughly
and carefully consider these important matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Adams, the Sinn Fein leader, could barely contain his
frustration Friday as he left the drab office complex at Castle
Buildings, where Mitchell has been holding court.
</P>
<P>
   ``This review should have been completed by now,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   He said those in the republican movement ``have stretched
ourselves to the limit,'' suggesting that neither Sinn Fein nor the
IRA would make further concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Adams had planned to visit Boston, Philadelphia and New York for
a series of public appearances and fund-raisers next week. He was
forced to cancel those visits last month because Mitchell's review,
initially expected to last a few weeks, has dragged on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
