<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILENES-PLAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILENE'S TO CUT WORK FORCE BY 900 JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Filene's Basement Corp. said Friday it plans to shrink
its work force by about 900 more jobs and close an additional 18
stores as the bargain-basement chain seeks to return to the retail
formula that made it famous.
</P>
<P>
   The cutbacks would be on top of a September announcement to
close 17 stores, which could result in as many as 400 lost jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Cash-flow problems forced the Wellesley-based company to file
for bankruptcy protection in August, and US Bankruptcy Court
approval is required for a proposal to convert what had been a
55-store chain with $588.5 million in annual sales into a 22-store
chain with projected annual sales of $350 million.
</P>
<P>
   Three Massachusetts stores, in Burlington, Framingham, and
Worcester, are designated for closing, and plans also call for New
England stores to be closed in Portland, Maine; Manchester and
Nashua, N.H.; and in Warwick, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   If the plan is approved, 14 stores would operate under the
Filene's Basement nameplate, eight of them Massachusetts and the
rest in big urban markets such as Chicago and New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan will allow us, when we emerge from bankruptcy, to be
a smaller yet stronger operation,'' said Filene's Basement chairman
and chief executive Sam Gerson. ``This is the beginning of our real
strategy'' to return to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   When it entered Chapter 11, the company employed about 4,300
people. The leaner-and-meaner chain now envisioned would employ
about 3,000 workers. Most of the layoffs announced Friday will
occur at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never happy when we lay people off,'' said Gerson, who
noted that employees who lose their jobs will receive a severance
package based on seniority.
</P>
<P>
   But downsizing is crucial if Filene's Basement is to stay in
business and the remaining 3,000 jobs are to be saved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's new strategy was drawn up in consultation with its
creditors and lenders, which makes court approval likely.
</P>
<P>
   Gerson said he could not provide a timetable for when Filene's
Basement might emerge from Chapter 11. And while he expressed the
hope that no more big cuts would be necessary, he said he could not
rule them out.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers typically use the haven of bankruptcy protection to
close unprofitable stores. During its nearly four years in Chapter
11, Bradlees Inc. of Braintree closed about a quarter of its
discount department stores and shed about 6,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But since emerging from Chapter 11 in February, Bradlees has
posted a series of solid monthly sales gains.
</P>
<P>
   Caldor Corp. wasn't so lucky. Unable to reorganize in Chapter
11, it was forced to go out of business earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   By retrenching in Massachusetts and big cities, Filene's
Basement thinks it can avoid Caldor's fate and return to health.
</P>
<P>
   Its remaining stores will not only provide Filene's Basement
with a profitable base but will also allow it to return to the
merchandising approach that made it successful, Gerson said.
</P>
<P>
   The retail formula that made Filene's Basement famous was to buy
last year's designer merchandise from department stores, then sell
those brand names at a big discount.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last decade, many department stores have concluded
that it was more profitable for them to sell last year's goods
through their own newly opened outlet stores rather than to a
regional off-price chain such as Filene's Basement.
</P>
<P>
   That shift in strategy by department stores made it harder for
smaller off-price chains such as Filene's Basement and Loehmann's
Inc., which also recently filed for bankruptcy protection, to find
high quality merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   In simple terms, what seems to have happened to Filene's
Basement was that it couldn't get enough designer merchandise to
stock 55 stores. Instead of famous brand names, disappointed
shoppers were often finding no-name private-label goods.
</P>
<P>
   With a much smaller store base, the Basement hopes it can again
fill its stores with mostly designer brand names.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be buying directly from the best European and American
designers,'' Gerson said. ``The Filene's Basement that customers
know and love is back.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's actions were the company's second big announcement
since filing for Chapter 11.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the company announced plans to close 17
underperforming stores, most of them in suburban locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to stop the bleeding,'' Gerson said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two weeks, top management and consultants looked
for a plan that would preserve the core of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Stores that were part of Friday's announced round of closings
would be liquidated to provide money for buying more merchandise
for the remaining stores and for paying down debt.
</P>
<P>
   Going forward, plans call for Filene's Basement stores to
specialize in selling designer goods to customers in urban
locations while Aisle 3, the company's new eight-store weekend-only
warehouse chain, targets a suburban customer with more moderately
priced goods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
