u i BC-BRITAIN-PEERS-(TRIMS)     11-12 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-PEERS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST HEREDITARY PEERS MAKE EPOCHAL EXIT FROM HOUSE OF LORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By SARAH LYALL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ For more than a century, reform-minded British
politicians tried to remove the country's hereditary peers from the
House of Lords, an effort so tortuous and ineffectual that, in
1963, Lord Samuel said he felt as if he had spent the previous 50
years watching ``a slow-motion film of a prima ballerina, marked by
an exhibition of almost languid deliberation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Prime Minister Tony Blair is neither languid nor
particularly deliberate, and Thursday he achieved what had long
seemed unachievable: forcing all but 92 of the ``hereditaries,'' as
they are called, to leave the House of Lords for the last time,
never to sit and vote there again.
</P>
<P>
   It was of a piece with Blair's broad program of constitutional
change, a program that has set out to do nothing less than to
reinvent the role of government in British life.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, reform of the House of Lords has been seen as a
left-wing, socialist Labor idea, which generated opposition,'' said
Alan Beattie, a senior lecturer in political science at the London
School of Economics. ``But this change was not represented as
left-wing and socialist, but as modernization, as part of a package
of constitutional reform, and was thus much more difficult to
oppose.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes to the House of Lords ended some 800 years of
Parliamentary history in one fell swoop. But since coming to power
with an overwhelming majority two-and-a-half years ago, Blair's
Labor government has also laid the groundwork for the formation of
new legislative bodies in Scotland and Wales and for a mayor in
London; enacted legislation incorporating the European Convention
on Human Rights into British law; and promised to enact Britain's
first freedom of information law.
</P>
<P>
   By removing the hereditary peers _ who inherit their titles and
are, for the most part, descended from the landed aristocracy that
ran England centuries ago _ Blair was dispensing with one of the
most extreme symbols of old-world, class-ridden Britain. Most
Britons felt that having hereditaries in the House of Lords was an
anachronism, if not an embarrassment, said Dr. Rodney Barker, a
constitutional expert at the London School of Economics, but no one
really knew what to do about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody talked about it much or took it very seriously,''
Barker said. ``But once you have a government that is seriously
committed to constitutional reform, once you start looking at the
second chamber and saying, `The majority of these people are here
because of their great-great-great grandfathers, and this is
absurd,' then everyone sees that the emperor has no clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   That has been the view that Baroness Jay of Paddington, leader
of the Lords, has always taken. But last week, Lady Jay _ who is a
life peer, meaning that her title cannot be passed on to the next
generation _ tried to strike a more conciliatory note toward the
666 hereditaries swept into mandatory retirement by the forces of
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this house, hereditary peers have served honorably, and
held the highest office,'' she said. But, she added, ``What may
have been appropriate 800 or even 200 years ago may not be
appropriate now. I do sincerely believe most have the grace and
realism to accept this change is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For all the swiftness of the change, the removal of the peers
has left Blair with a brand-new problem: what to replace them with.
For now, the House of Lords is to be made up of the 92 hereditary
peers elected to stay on by their colleagues, as well as some 500
life peers appointed over the years by various governments. In
December, a royal commission is to recommend a new configuration
for the Lords, but it is unclear what its proposals will be or how
easy it will be to put them in place.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This has been difficult for many of the outgoing hereditaries to
take. ``While I have no objection to the government removing the
rights of hereditary peers,'' complained Lord Stanley of Alderley,
in the last remark he would ever make in the chamber, ``they did
not get a mandate to get rid of us without saying very clearly who
is to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Lord Strathclyde, the Lords' Tory leader, said, `` `Trust
Tony' cannot be made into a constitutional document.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of this century, the House of Lords has held little
real political power, except as a delaying, modifying and tempering
influence on the House of Commons _ a fact that Lord Elton was only
too pleased to point out as the Parliamentary session wound down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This House has historically restrained some of the greater
enthusiasms of prime ministers of many colors, as my noble friend
Baroness Thatcher will confirm,'' he said to former Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher, dressed in funereal black and sitting
stony-faced as the bill to strip the hereditaries of their rights
in the chamber was passed.
</P>
<P>
   The hereditaries did manage to leave with a certain degree of
dignity, cheered by the sometimes stern words of the Lord
Strathclyde. ``This House has inflicted no evil in its history and
much good has been done,'' he said. ``Many people _ the weak, the
unheard, the politically unfashionable _ have come to this place.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Lord Strathclyde delivered a warning of sorts to Blair, saying
that because the hereditary peers who remain were elected to their
seats _ unlike the life peers _ they would probably find a ``new
authority and confidence'' in their role.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the hereditary peers are Conservatives, and removing
them has someone reduced the Conservative majority in the Lords.
But Labor is still in a substantial minority, with only about 180
out of 640 seats, and the Conservatives, Liberal Democrats and
Cross-Benchers, who owe allegiance to no party, are still in a
position to make things awkward for the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are already some very substantive powers in the Lords,''
Lord Strathclyde said. ``I think what the government is going to
discover is that we will be dusting them down, wiping them clean
and starting to use them with a ruthlessness they haven't seen
before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
