<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 1933EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8082 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-N     11-12 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN TROOPS OCCUPY GUDERMES AND CLOSE IN ON GROZNY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By MICHAEL WINES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian officials said Friday that they had largely
driven Islamic rebels from Gudermes, the second-largest city in
Chechnya, and in an unmistakable sign of their intention to retake
complete control of the separatist republic, proposed to move the
capital there from Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   The International Committee of the Red Cross underscored the
deteriorating military situation by announcing that it is pulling
its workers out of Chechnya to focus on helping refugees in
Ingushetia, the republic to the west.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister Nikolai Koshman, Russia's official
representative on Chechen issues, said those residents who had not
already fled the almost constant Russian bombardment of Grozny
should get out. Any part of the city that was rebuilt after the
last devastating war there, in 1996, ``has recently been destroyed
and blown up,'' Koshman said. ``The city cannot be restored.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian press services reported Friday that oil refineries and
other strategic sites on Grozny's outskirts were under the heaviest
aerial attack of the war.
</P>
<P>
   The occupation of Gudermes, on Chechnya's eastern border,
further tightened the ring of troops and armor that Russia has been
deploying around Grozny since a counterattack against the rebels
began in earnest two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Russian spokesmen at a temporary news center in Dagestan, the
republic to the east of Chechnya, said troops had discovered a
high-explosive bomb and the bodies of 57 rebels during an intensive
sweep through Gudermes. Some rebels were reportedly hiding out in
the city, but Russian military officials expressed confidence that
the town would come completely under their control by next week.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military already controls hilltops north of the
capital and is attacking west of Grozny through Barmut. Chechen
military officials have long promised a counterattack, but it has
failed so far to materialize.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo said Friday that
seizing Grozny was not on the agenda of the Russian military for
now, although there are plans to take a number of other villages in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   The Interfax news service quoted Valery Manilov, deputy chief of
the general staff, as saying the war could be all but wrapped up by
the end of the year _ an optimistic statement by Russian standards,
and one that would have been unthinkable even a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   With President Boris Yeltsin due in Istanbul next week for a
crucial meeting on European security, the Kremlin seemed to be
working overtime to depict its much-criticized operations in
Chechnya as a military fait accompli.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, of the leaders of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, is expected to highlight Western concerns
about potential human-rights violations in Russia's prosecution of
the war.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow has come under increasing criticism since Russian rockets
slammed into a Grozny open-air market nearly three weeks ago,
killing almost 150 Chechens and stampeding senior Russian officials
into a series of conflicting explanations of their actions.
</P>
<P>
   The Istanbul meeting is notable in part because Russia's
deployment of tens of thousands of troops in Chechnya is a
technical violation of one of the underpinnings of a post-Cold War
security accord, the treaty on conventional forces in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has asked European leaders to overlook the violation as
a temporary and necessary response to an internal uprising.
</P>
<P>
   He also is expected to press for agreements that members of the
security organization not intervene in national conflicts unless
asked to do so by those fighting, and that national sovereignty be
deemed a guiding principle in enforcing human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Assenting to either proposal would bolster Russia's defenses
against international criticism of its handling of the Chechnya
conflict. But while officials are clearly nettled by Western
criticism, there is little indication that it is hindering their
conduct of the war.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, the hard-line approach to the Chechen conflict
continues to draw almost unanimous support in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The patriarch of the Russian Orthodox Church, Aleksy II, issued
a remarkable statement Friday endorsing Russian attacks in
Chechnya, saying the government cannot tolerate sin and lawlessness
and is obliged to deal with the bombings, kidnappings and killings
that have flourished in Chechnya's anarchy. But the patriarch also
urged the government to pay special heed to civilians and refugees.
</P>
<P>
   While the Yeltsin administration has responded to Western
objections by suggesting that a political solution to the war is a
priority, there is scant indication that any such search is under
way.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Rushailo ruled out talks with the only political
authority in Chechnya, its president, Aslan Maskhadov, saying he is
too closely allied to the Islamic military leaders who control much
of the countryside and whom the Russians have branded terrorists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
