<HEADER>
A8083 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-TRIP-HNS &LR;      11-12 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TRIP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN TENSIONS, POST-COLD WAR ASSESSMENT FOCUS OF CLINTON TRIP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton launches a 10-day trip to Europe
on Sunday that will take him to Turkey where earthquakes still
shatter nerves, to Greece where threats prompted changes in his
schedule and to Kosovo where violence still impedes peace.
</P>
<P>
   The president at midweek will join other Western leaders in
Istanbul at a meeting of the 54-member Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe to reassess the organization's mission a
decade after the end of the Cold War. On tap: Russia's bombing of
Chechnya and aid to the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger, the national security adviser, said the
president's itinerary and the OSCE agenda intend to highlight those
difficult issues and regions still troubling Europe as a new
century approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can eliminate that zone of instability if we meet the
remaining challenges: By promoting stability in the Balkans,
democracy in Serbia, reconciliation in the Aegean, a settlement on
Cyprus, peace in the Caucasus and integration of Russia into the
global community,'' Berger told reporters Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dealing with this unfinished business and strengthening our
ties with key allies will be the president's top priorities next
week and as a large part of America's agenda in the coming year,''
he said. But outside developments also have raised concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Another large earthquake, measured at 7.2 magnitude, struck the
town of Duzce on Friday, shaking buildings more than 160 miles away
in Ankara and Istanbul ``as though they were made of rubber,''
according to The Associated Press. Clinton plans to stay in both
cities as well as visit Izmit, where a 7.4 quake killed 17,000
people in August.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said the tremor was unlikely to affect the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton begins his official visit Monday in Ankara at sessions
with President Suleyman Demirel and Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit.
He also will address the Turkish National Assembly and encourage
the Islamic nation to maintain its secular course and to reduce its
tensions with its historic rival, Greece.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the president will meet with earthquake survivors in
Izmit and tour the damaged region. On Wednesday, he flies to
Istanbul for a separate session with Greek Orthodox, Jewish and
Armenian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day OSCE summit begins Thursday where Clinton and other
world leaders will sign a statement of principles on human rights,
democracy and security to reflect the new alignments from the
demise of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   ``This document recognizes the threats to our security are as
likely to come from conflicts within states as between them, and it
will (give) new tools and a new mandate to prevent and manage
internal conflict, a role it's begun to play from the Balkans to
the Caucasus,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   At issue also will be Russia's military bombardment of one of
its own provinces, Chechnya. The OSCE session will allow Clinton
and Russia President Boris Yeltsin to meet face-to-face where the
president again will urge a negotiated settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said the United States also will use the OSCE session to
push for an oil pipeline to transport Caspian Sea crude from
Azerbaijan to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will diversify the international community's sources of
energy, help the newly independent states of the region stand on
their own feet, power Turkey's growth and provide a profoundly
important corridor that is not only of economic importance but of
strategic importance for these countries to the West,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president will spend Nov. 20 in Greece, which initially was
to be the first stop on his tour. However, there have been mass
anti-U.S. protests in Greece leading up to the traditional Nov. 17
date when the 1973 Junta put down protests by students. A terrorist
group that also goes by the name of November 17 remains at large. A
series of explosions has rocked Athens for days.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit to Athens was delayed and shortened at the
recommendation of the Greek government. Greece opposed the U.S.-led
NATO bombing campaign against the Serbs, who are Orthodox
Christians like the Greeks. Greeks also blame the United States for
Turkey's invasion of Cyprus. Large demonstrations are expected
during Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any country is a model for young democracies in the Balkans
and expression of dissent, it is the birthplace of democracy in
Greece, and I suspect we will see some of that while we're there,''
Berger said, downplaying any security concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The president will spend next weekend in Florence, Italy, for a
conference on governing in the 21st century. He begins his second
week in Bulgaria, once a Communist stronghold and now an emerging
model for democracy and open markets.
</P>
<P>
   The president will end his trip with a stop in Macedonia and
Kosovo. The president intends to have a pre-Thanksgiving meal with
U.S. troops stationed in Kosovo. He also hopes to quell the revenge
killings by Kosovars against their Serb neighbors and to renew his
message for Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic to step aside.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton on Friday signed a directive denying visa entry into the
United States by Milosevic's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president will reaffirm our determination to finish that
job and ... our commitment to help build a more tolerant and
democratic Kosovo that redeems the cause for which the United
States and NATO fought for 78 days earlier this year,'' Berger
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
