<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8090 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-GAYS-BIBLE13-COX     11-12 1948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-BIBLE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Many churches continue to grapple with homosexuality
 &HT;    By Stephanie Allmon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ When the Rev. Jerry Falwell met with gay activist
minister Mel White at an antiviolence summit earlier this month,
they didn't hesitate to pick up the stones they normally cast at
each other.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of taking aim and counting casualties, the seemingly
natural-born enemies put down their weapons and agreed to look for
common ground as a way to stop violence, particularly against gay
people.
</P>
<P>
   The same proverbial stones these two groups have thrown over the
years have also shattered denominational and, in some cases,
congregational unity, wounding people on every side.
</P>
<P>
   Christians have faced many moral and cultural issues in recent
memory, from racism, divorce, to women's roles in the church, yet
homosexuality seems to top a hierarchy of moral dilemmas. Why?
</P>
<P>
   To find the answer, some clergy and theologians say, one must
evaluate today's culture along with the culture in which the Bible
was written.
</P>
<P>
   The critical question for Christians is whether homosexuality is
a sin.
</P>
<P>
   Christians who look to the Bible for guidance on the issue may
find surprisingly little said about homosexuality. Biblical
scholars and clergy members recognize six scripture passages that
they say are at the heart of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Disagreement about how to interpret those passages stems from
differences in opinion about how authoritative the Bible is and how
relevant it is in today's culture, said Victor Paul Furnish,
university distinguished professor of New Testament at Southern
Methodist University's Perkins School of Theology.
</P>
<P>
   At one end of the spectrum are fundamentalists who understand
the Bible to be the inerrant word of God and who take its teachings
literally. At the other extreme are those who regard the Bible as
``more or less a curious artifact of history,'' Furnish said. But
the vast majority of churchgoers are in the middle, he said.
</P>
<P>
   To further complicate the issue, the word ``homosexual'' is not
found in original texts of the Bible, said Michael L. White,
professor of classics and Christian origins and director of the
religious studies program at the University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The term 'homosexual' does not exist in the Bible,'' he said.
``You can't find it. It's just not there.''
</P>
<P>
   Over time, he said, certain words have been translated to equate
homosexual behavior with immorality.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most controversial Biblical reference, Romans
1:26-27, says, ``Because of this, God gave them over to shameful
lusts. Even their women exchanged natural relations for unnatural
ones. In the same way, the men also abandoned natural relations
with women and were inflamed with lust for one another. Men
committed indecent acts with other men, and received in themselves
the due penalty for their perversion.'' (NIV)
</P>
<P>
   Furnish said those who interpret these passages as literal
expressions of God's will, without regard to cultural changes,
would say that same-sex relations violate a natural order of
creation in which heterosexuality is the norm.
</P>
<P>
   But Christians who take the Bible as an expression of human
opinion, to be understood in the context in the day which it's
written, may say that Paul, the author of Romans, personally
believes that same-sex relations are sinful and uses the example to
illustrate what goes wrong with the world if people don't worship
God, Furnish said.
</P>
<P>
   Same-sex relations were not necessarily considered sinful in
biblical times, White said. In fact, in ancient Greek culture,
homosexuality was viewed as a higher plane of spiritual
relationships, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But A.J. Conyers, professor of theology at Baylor University's
George W. Truett Seminary, said the Bible illustrates that
homosexuality is a social disorder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting the way in which (homosexuality) is brought
up,'' he said. ``It's always illustrative of the outer edge of
cultural disintegration. The intention of the Bible is not to say
this is the worst sin in the world, but to say here very clearly
how sin turns the human being against nature.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bible more clearly spells out other types of sexual sins,
such as premarital sex, adultery and even lust, but scholars offer
different reasons as to why homosexuality is such a hot-button
issue within Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   White said the belief that homosexuality is a sin is one of the
last vestiges of an older version of Christian morality that has
undergone many changes. That morality once included positions on
other social issues, such as racism, that have changed as people's
world views have changed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many people believe homosexuality is a sin because it violates
an assumed, ordained social order that includes marriage and
heterosexual sex, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Conyers said homosexuality has become a public issue for
Christians in recent years as gay rights advocates have grown more
vocal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not such a big issue 20 years ago because no one was
trying to make the case that homosexuality was a normal way of
life,'' he said. ``The reason the Christian community gets involved
is since that time, there's been an aggressive case made by
militant homosexuals to the effect that they should be given
privileges equivalent to other minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dean Riley, deacon of Central Texas Metropolitan Community
Church from the Heart, suggests that some clergy have used the
issue of homosexuality to rally troops for their own causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very easy to draw a congregation together if you have a
common rallying point,'' he said. ``Homosexuality, being so
personal and intimate, makes a great rallying cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two decades, nearly every Christian denomination,
and many individual churches, have been forced to evaluate such
issues as the ordination and marriage of gays.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most recent public denominational struggles has been
within the United Methodist Church after several pastors performed
same-sex marriages and were subsequently suspended from the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Sharon Robertson of Waco's First United Methodist
Church said that although homosexuality is incompatible and
inconsistent with the teachings of the United Methodist Church,
``the church says that ... homosexuals are no less people of worth
than heterosexuals, and all people need the ministry and guidance
of the church.''
</P>
<P>
   While many churches take a similar ``love the sinner, hate the
sin'' position, others actively seek to ``reform'' homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   In a September Waco Tribune-Herald religion page column that
received a barrage of responses, the Rev. Larry Courtney, pastor of
St. Mary's Missionary Baptist Church in Waco, stated that a rise in
homosexuality is a sign of society's decay. He called on Christians
to ``preach, teach, and pray to stamp out Satan in his lustful
attempt to deceive and consume our brothers and sisters,'' even if
it means being called hypocrites, gay bashers or homophobic bigots.
</P>
<P>
   But some churches are realizing the need to transform attitudes
to stop any hatred or harassment coming from within the
congregation.
</P>
<P>
   The Lutheran Church-Missouri Synod's ``Plan for Ministry to
Homosexuals and their Families'' offers responses to friends and
family members who struggle with a loved one's homosexuality and
ways to assure homosexuals the church won't reject them.
</P>
<P>
   Rejection often causes Christian homosexuals to leave the
church, Riley said. The MCC denomination was established as a
refuge for people seeking a congregation that welcomed gay and
lesbian Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases, (MCC church members) are people who have been
wounded by their faith traditions,'' Riley said. ``Perhaps they
have been in a church setting where they have been told
homosexuality is an abomination and they won't be welcomed into
heaven. If you are a spiritual person, that hurts. That hurts very
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Waco resident Randy Culp left his Southern Baptist faith behind
at age 30 when he revealed to his wife, his children and his father
_ a Southern Baptist pastor _ that he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to leave that tradition from which I grew up and go
elsewhere for my connection to God or a higher order of the
universe,'' he said. ``Then, as a direct result of my church now
(Unitarian Universalist), I came full circle and re-embraced
Christianity with a broader world view and greater options for
appreciating the value of Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   FACING THE ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said pastors are not shying away from facing
homosexual issues within their churches. She said she regularly
ministers to homosexuals, and she welcomes the opportunity to guide
their spiritual lives without trying to ``fix'' their sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thankfully, it's not left up to me to say who goes to heaven
and who doesn't,'' she said. ``My ministry is to help lead people
to their own understanding of who God is in their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley said instead of trying to figure out whether homosexuality
is a sin, Christians should concentrate on the commands God gave to
love him and to love others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a very personal issue that's between the
individual and God; however, as a church community, we are called
to encourage people to enter into a right relationship with God,''
he said. ``God has given us a commandment to love, and if that
means that we have to acknowledge that we have been created
homosexuals, that's OK, because God loves us and created us this
way, so we have a duty to thank God for that.''
</P>
<P>
   But is all the internal arguing over homosexual issues hurting
evangelism efforts by the church at large?
</P>
<P>
   Conyers said he doesn't think so. In fact, he said, if a church
takes a strong position against homosexuality, an unwillingness to
waiver actually strengthens its integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that the church doesn't compromise on basic
convictions about moral life, they have a stronger witness; people
take them more seriously,'' he said. ``When they compromise and
relativize, the church becomes unreliable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Conyers acknowledged that many churches and congregations
will continue to grapple with the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may well be something that will test the church,'' he said.
``And I think it is right now.''
</P>
<P>
   In his booklet ``Homosexuality and The Christian Faith:
Questions of Conscious for the Churches,'' Walter Wink, a theology
lecturer who leads nonviolence seminars around the world, suggests
Christians may have to agree to disagree about homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in the church need to get our priorities straight,'' he
said. ``We have not reached a consensus about who is right on the
issue of homosexuality. But what is clear _ utterly clear _ is that
we are commanded to love one another. We don't have to tear whole
denominations to shreds in order to air our differences on this
point.''
</P>
<P>
   With more public discussions like Falwell and White's, bridges
can be built across gaps that have been carved out between
churches, denominations and communities, Furnish said, suggesting
that Christians work together to solve more pressing social and
environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope, my reasonable expectation, is that through the
process of charitable dialogue, persons who differ on this
particular issue will come finally to see that there are more
important things that bind them together as believers than one
particular point that separates them,'' he said. ``In addition,
there are far weightier moral issues that need to be addressed and
can be addressed by Christians.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
