<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-AID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR BOMB BRINGS CALL FOR MORE US AID TO COLOMBIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the threat of renewed narco-terrorism in
Colombia, some members of Congress will attempt before the current
session ends to free up several million dollars as a signal to the
embattled nation that help is on the way.
</P>
<P>
   A car bomb that exploded Thursday in Bogota, killing seven and
injuring more than 50 people, has raised fears that drug lords
would once again carry out a terror campaign against civilians in
order to block extradition of suspected drug kingpins to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going back to the beginning of the 1990s in Colombia,
a time when these drug cartels destroyed the government,'' said
Luis Alberto Moreno, Colombia's ambassador to the United States.
``If President (Andres) Pastrana didn't have enough problems, this
is a new difficulty.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreno talked with several senior US officials Friday about the
possibility of pushing ahead with the three-year, $1 billion-plus
Colombian aid program, even though White House spokesmen said
earlier this week that it would have to be delayed until January.
</P>
<P>
   US Senator Paul Coverdell, a Georgia Republican who sponsored a
$1.5 billion aid plan for Colombia, said he believed it was
possible to release some ``symbolic'' funds now as a message to
Bogota that the United States was committed to the drug fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do something, even if it's several million dollars,
and tell them that we will get it done completely next year,''
Coverdell said. ``The bombing is just an increased expression of
what we've deemed to be an emergency for months.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bogota, the bombing investigation continued Friday with
suspicion still squarely on narco-traffickers reacting to a Supreme
Court decision to extradite two accused traffickers. Two hours
after the bombing, Pastrana signed papers carrying out the
country's first three extraditions in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hammer, spokesman for the US National Security Council,
said he knew of no plans for additional funding for Colombia next
week, but added, ``If Congress is prepared to move more quickly,
we're prepared as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though there is strong bipartisan support for the Colombian
package, which would make the South American nation the third
largest recipient of US foreign aid, the proposal was stalled in
end-of-the-session funding negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In Colombia, the delay has been a political blow to Pastrana,
analysts said. One front page headline this week in El Tiempo
pointedly said US assistance would have to wait ``until the next
century.''
</P>
<P>
   As Coverdell and others argue for some action now, US
Representative William Delahunt of Massachusetts believes that
delaying the larger package is best.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shouldn't be perceived as an unwillingness of the United
States to be engaged,'' Delahunt said. ``It should be seen as a
period of time to craft something that is thoughtful as well as
effective.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colombian package has come under intense debate within the
Clinton administration, with some favoring a plan weighted more
toward military hardware to fight guerrillas and narco-traffickers,
while others push for more economic and social incentives that they
believe would hasten a peace agreement with guerillas in Columbia's
30-year civil war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
