<HEADLINE>
INS EXPULSIONS OF IMMIGRANTS IN HOUSTON ABOVE NATIONAL RATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The number of illegal immigrants expelled by the
Immigration and Naturalization Service in Houston rose 29 percent
in the past year, far outstripping the rate nationally, INS
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston office expelled 6,792 illegal immigrants from the
country, compared to 5,280 in 1998. Nationally, INS expelled a
record 176,990 illegal immigrants in its 1999 fiscal year, compared
to 171,154 in 1998, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Houston was the only major Texas municipality that experienced a
rise in illegal-immigrant removals, a distinction state INS offices
attributed to the 60 consular offices and large state prison near
the city.
</P>
<P>
   The proximity of consular facilities enables Houston INS agents
to get travel documents for illegal immigrants quickly and thereby
speed the deportation process, said Kristi Barrows, spokesperson
for the Houston office.
</P>
<P>
   Also helping to increase Houston's expulsion figure is INS's
program for identifying, charging and initiating deportation
proceedings against illegal immigrants who are in state prisons for
committing crimes. The state prison in Huntsville, with a large
number of foreign-born inmates, provides a ready population of
illegal immigrants to be deported upon the completion of their
sentences, said Mariela Melero, spokesperson for INS's Dallas-based
Central region.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Houston, the agency's Dallas office had a 34
percent decline in the number of illegal immigrants it expelled.
San Antonio saw a drop of 14 percent, from 10,778 in 1998 to 9,264
this past year.
</P>
<P>
   El Paso and Harlingen each experienced drops of 6 percent. The
number of illegal immigrants expelled fell from 17,773 in 1999 to
16,769 last year in El Paso. In Harlingen, the drop was from 8,886
to 8,323, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   INS's data account for illegal immigrants removed at the order
of an immigration judge or officer during fiscal year 1999, which
ended Sept. 30. The figures include neither the 1.5 million illegal
immigrants apprehended at U.S. borders who voluntarily returned to
their home country nor the 72,000 immigrants in INS custody who
were allowed to leave the United States voluntarily after being
charged with violating immigration law.
</P>
<P>
   INS said the number of illegal immigrants deported in 1999 would
have been higher if not for the devastation of Hurricane Mitch,
which led the U.S. government to delay the deportation of Central
Americans to their ravaged homelands.
</P>
<P>
   Of the immigrants expelled nationwide in 1999, 62,359 _ or about
1,200 per week _ were removed after committing a crime in the
United States, INS said. Nearly half of those criminals, 47
percent, had committed drug offenses; 13 percent had simply
violated immigration laws; 6 percent had been convicted of assault;
and 5 percent had committed burglary.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, 89,035 illegal immigrants were deported when they
sought entry at U.S. ports with fraudulent, improper or no entry
documents, an increase of about 16 percent from 1998, INS said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the criminal immigrants removed, 19,592 were expelled upon
the completion of their prison sentences under INS's Institutional
Removal Program, which is targeted at seven states that account for
75 percent to 80 percent of foreign-born state inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The states are Texas, Arizona, California, Florida, Illinois,
New Jersey and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased that the exceptional efforts of INS field
personnel, combined with excellent cooperation from our federal
partners as well as state and local officials, have allowed us to
remove criminal aliens who have completed their sentences with
greater efficiency and effectiveness,'' INS Commissioner Doris
Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican nationals accounted for the overwhelming majority, 83
percent, of people deported last year, INS reported.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
