A8103 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-UNITEDHEALTH13-COX     11-12 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNITEDHEALTH13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Insurer criticized for mental health policy
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Consumer advocates expressed anger Friday over
UnitedHealth Group's exclusion of mental health services from its
new policy to let doctors have the final say on treatment
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous that they would set up a double standard,''
said Cynthia Wainscott, executive director of the National Mental
Health Association of Georgia. ``What they're saying is, they don't
trust doctors in mental health, but they trust them on heart or
kidney disease.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of a UnitedHealth subsidiary said Thursday
that costs would escalate if the company stopped its reviews of
mental health treatment decisions. ``Mental health holds a lot more
intangibles than medical care in determining what treatment someone
needs,'' said Saul Feldman, chief executive of United Behavioral
Health.
</P>
<P>
   But UnitedHealth late Friday appeared to leave the door open for
eventually treating mental health equally.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a model in evolution,'' UnitedHealth said in a
statement, citing mental health as an area in transition.
UnitedHealth added it was committed to ``continuing this
evolution'' over all UnitedHealth segments in the next 12 to 18
months.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, UnitedHealth won widespread praise from
consumer and physician groups for giving doctors the power to
decide what's best for patients. The company explained Monday that
it costs the company more to review doctors' decisions
administratively than it would to cover the treatments in question.
</P>
<P>
   UnitedHealth said it spends $100 million a year to review
doctors' decisions, of which 99 percent are upheld. Doctors'
decisions still would be monitored under the new policy, but after
the treatment or service is performed.
</P>
<P>
   But Wainscott said that for mental health, studies have shown
that early and effective mental health treatment can reduce overall
medical costs. The pre-certification process required by insurers
can prevent suicidal people from receiving needed hospitalization
or consumers from getting sufficient visits to a psychotherapist,
Wainscott said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Bob Carolla, spokesman of the National Alliance for the
Mentally Ill: ``There should be no discrimination between physical
and mental care. It's an issue of science, fundamental fairness and
moral responsibility.'' He said the UnitedHealth policy could
violate mental health parity laws in 28 states.
</P>
<P>
   UnitedHealth also has drawn complaints in Georgia for not
providing benefits to some members who seek mental health services
from non-UnitedHealth providers. But the company denies it's
skirting a state law on ``point-of-service'' plans.
</P>
<P>
   The law states employees who have only an HMO option must also
be given a POS alternative, which allows some benefits for
treatments from out-of-network providers.
</P>
<P>
   UnitedHealth lets POS members go outside its network for general
physical care but not for mental health services, says the Georgia
Psychological Association. UnitedHealth says it complies with the
law by letting employers decide whether to cover care outside of
its network.
</P>
<P>
   The state insurance commissioner's office is looking into the
complaints, as is Cathey Steinberg, state insurance consumer
advocate.
</P>
<P>
   The ``point-of-service'' law applies to employers that don't
self-insure their benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota-based UnitedHealth has 14.5 million members.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
