<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8105 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-WINONA-RYDER-FILMS-$A     11-12 1335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINONA-RYDER-FILMS-$ADV14-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINDING HER MEMORIES TO PLAY A TROUBLED SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Nov. 14) 
(jt) 
 By JENNET CONANT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the pantheon of film actresses, Winona Ryder is becoming
almost as well known for her eyes as Bette Davis. Ms. Ryder's, of
course, are brown, not blue. On screen, they appear black, enormous
and extraordinarily expressive, bearing a striking similarity to
those of the cartoon character Princess Mononoke in the
Japanimation feature of the same name. Off screen, they look large,
but less unreal.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, they are fixed on the poster for her new film,
``Girl, Interrupted,'' which is based on Susanna Kaysen's
best-selling memoir of a two-year stay as a teenager at McLean
Hospital, the private psychiatric clinic outside Boston. The
poster, propped against the wall of Ms. Ryder's Manhattan hotel
room, is a stark photograph of the left side of the actress' face,
dominated by one huge, dark eye. As both the star and an executive
producer of ``Girl, Interrupted,'' Ms. Ryder, who scarcely looks of
legal age in a rumpled button-down shirt and khaki cargo pants, her
bare feet thrust into Air Nikes, has a say over everything from
casting and script changes to the movie's trailer and promotional
billboards. The studio, Columbia Pictures, is waiting for her
feedback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, what do you think?'' she asks. Her anxious gaze
scours every cluttered surface of the room, searching for a
cigarette. Because she woke up only minutes before a 4 p.m.
interview (she is shooting night scenes for her next movie,
``Autumn in New York'') and is nursing a cold, she settles for a
sip of Orange Zinger tea and two antihistamine pills. She smiles
wanly and, curling up on the sofa, explains why ``Girl,
Interrupted,'' six years in the making, has her feeling so jittery.
She has invested more of herself in this role, she says, than in
any other in her career because of the raw, painful nature of the
material and its very personal connection to her own life _ an
early bout of depression that she is talking about publicly for the
first time. For much of the movie, she is talking directly to a
Panavision camera only six inches from her nose. ``This is risky
for me,'' she says, nodding at the poster. ``I mean, if you don't
like me, you're not going to like this movie.''
</P>
<P>
   After a two-year absence from the screen, Ms. Ryder, 28, is
ready for another close-up. Beneath the fragile, waiflike exterior
is a surprisingly canny veteran. She has 24 films to her credit,
including Janusz Kaminski's ``Lost Souls,'' opening Jan. 14, and
two Academy Award nominations, for best actress in ``Little Women''
and best supporting actress in ``The Age of Innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   She has been working since the day she was discovered eating
gazpacho at a San Francisco restaurant when she was 12, and she
says she remains every bit as much in love with the movie business
today as she was then. While she has had her share of growing pains
(including an infamous case of the flu that forced her to back out
of Francis Ford Coppola's ``Godfather 3'') and tabloid romances (a
highly publicized liaison with the actor Johnny Depp, who had
``Winona Forever'' tattooed on his arm), she has weathered it all
with grace and humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going through adolescence on screen,'' she says, rolling
her eyes. ``I mean, most kids can have a bad day and miss school,
but I couldn't miss a day of work because that would be a $300,000
insurance day, blah, blah, blah.'' Ms. Ryder, who is known as Noni
to her friends, speaks of her awkward younger self without
embarrassment and giggles with delight while recounting some
humiliating anecdotes from her teens, suggesting that she has
emerged from her Hollywood childhood with few permanent scars. She
does not hide the fact that she is happily in love with the actor
Matt Damon and flushes like a schoolgirl when a waiter asks about
him.
</P>
<P>
   She launches into an account of her own episode of depression
with an enthusiasm quaintly at odds with her topic. She cheerfully
concedes that the pressure and exhaustion of making too many movies
in a row probably aggravated a fairly typical case of
postadolescent angst, as all the therapists she consulted
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Add a natural flair for drama and particularly bad typecasting
at an impressionable age. In her first three films, she was cast
successively as a geek (in ``Lucas''), the girl with glasses
(``Square Dance'') and a freaky witch (``Beetlejuice.'') It was not
until she took a leading part in ``Heathers'' in 1989, against her
agent's advice, that she finally played someone who was not
described in the script as ugly. ``I had been called that for so
long, I had just come to accept it as fact,'' says Ms. Ryder, who
resigned herself to a career playing oddballs and character roles.
</P>
<P>
   When the pale little string bean with the cropped black hair
blossomed into a delicate beauty, the ensuing identity crisis sent
her into a tailspin. ``Imagine my surprise,'' she says dryly,
``when I got breasts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Girl, Interrupted'' represents Ms. Ryder's return to the
screen in yet another coming-of-age story _ by now her stock in
trade _ only this time in a much grittier, more demanding role. As
the 18-year-old Susanna, who tried to cure a headache by washing
down 50 aspirin tablets with a pint of vodka, Ms. Ryder gives an
effectively understated performance as a young woman struggling to
find some shred of sanity in a world that is certifiable, both
inside and outside the hospital walls. Looking like a wounded
sparrow, her big, urgent eyes observing her parents' suburban
misery (vintage 1967) without comprehending it, she is too numb to
know or care where she is going when a doctor packs her off for a
long rest.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ryder did not have to research her role. Her brief stay in a
psychiatric ward when she was 20 is still a vivid memory. ``I was
overworked and overtired _ too tired to sleep,'' she recalls. ``I
was in a really bad state.'' The insomnia and anxiety attacks she
had been suffering on and off for years had become paralyzing. At
the tail end of a long, difficult parting with her first serious
boyfriend (she had left home to move in with Depp when she was 17),
she ``hit bottom,'' she says, and checked herself into a hospital.
She signed herself out a week later, feeling she had not been
helped.
</P>
<P>
   But she was never self-destructive, she says. Her parents, who
permitted her to work only during summer vacations while she was in
high school, told her that they, too, had suffered from depression
at her age. ``I didn't do drugs; I didn't get loaded,'' Ms. Ryder
says. ``But the depression. The worst part of it was not being able
to describe it _ the overwhelming horror of the anxiety attacks _
even to my own family, to the people closest to me.'' She had all
the classic symptoms: ``My breathing would get labored; everything
would start speeding up, and I'd get very scared. The closest I
ever came to describing it was that feeling when you almost get in
a car wreck and you swerve, and for a second there are needles in
your head and needles in your body. It's that moment, but stretched
out.''
</P>
<P>
   She makes it very clear that she blames no one, especially Depp,
for something she was doing to herself. She finally made a
breakthrough while she was in Portugal on a particularly grueling
shoot on ``The House of the Spirits,'' in which she played a
character who is tortured. ``I remember I came home one night and
looked at myself in the mirror and saw myself looking so battered,
and I thought, `Wow, this is what I am doing to myself inside,'''
she recalls. She is forever indebted, she says, to ``a really
excellent shrink,'' who was treating her long distance by
telephone, for helping her realize that she could portray pain on
the screen without having to put herself through it continually.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
