<HEADLINE>
NASCAR DEAL BAD FOR THE NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a bigger story behind Friday's story about NASCAR
entering billion-dollar contracts with NBC, Fox, and Turner Sports.
While sports fans were looking at the $$$$$$$$$, a more important
story was the number of years involved in the deals.
</P>
<P>
   NBC and NASCAR have partnered until 2006 to air races every
Sunday in the fall. What does this mean to the NFL? Plenty. The
NFL's contracts with ABC, CBS, and Fox run through 2005. By taking
NASCAR on its network through 2006, NBC has taken itself out of the
pro football mix for the forseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL will not have NBC to use as ``leverage'' in the bidding
wars for television rights. This is going to hurt the NFL. Since
Fox became a major player, the NFL has had four networks bidding
for three packages: ``Monday Night Football,'' the AFC, and the
NFC. With NBC out of the mix, there is no one on the horizon for
the NFL to use as leverage to make the other three networks
competitively bid for these packages.
</P>
<P>
   Also, if NBC is airing NASCAR on Sunday afternoons in the fall
for the next six years, that should end any more talk of starting
another pro football league. Supposedly, NBC and Turner were
together going to coordinate a new league to play in the fall, but
that isn't likely to happen now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Things are not so happy in our local version of Happy Valley,
according to Fearless Fred Edelstein, the intrepid NFL insider who
has been putting out his weekly reports on pro football longer than
anyone in the business. Here is what Fearless Fred had to say in
one of his latest reports:
</P>
<P>
   Headline: ``Patriot Players Fear Winning Will Backfire And Bail
Out Carroll.''
</P>
<P>
   Text: ``The Patriots are off to a fine start, but our player
sources on the team say the club has hardly rallied around Pete
Carroll. If anything, the player sources we've talked to say the
downside of the winning in their minds is that they may be bailing
out Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``These sources say there's a strong undercurrent of a lack of
respect inside the locker room for Carroll. One story widely known
among players had to do with a veteran who wasn't able to make
Carroll's long-distance run in training camp when a doctor ordered
him to skip it because of an injury. Initially, Carroll refused to
allow the player to miss the run. Then, as the story goes, Carroll
asked the player to meet him on the practice field early the next
morning. When the player arrived, Carroll had a big bottle of water
with him. We're told Carroll threw the water on the player, which
gave the impression of sweat, and said: `Tell everybody you ran.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Offered one player source: `How do you respect a coach like
that? If he'll do that with one player, what are we supposed to
think about what he is doing with somebody else?' ''
</P>
<P>
   A top Patriot official denies the water-bottle episode ever
happened. Fearless Fred, in a phone conversation with this humble
reporter Friday, said he knew for a fact that it did happen.
</P>
<P>
   Fred II:
</P>
<P>
   In his latest report this week, Fearless Fred has another
unhappy nugget involving Ben Coates. The story begins late last
season when Coates went home to Carolina for the death of a
relative days before the St. Louis game, Dec. 13, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, owner Bob Kraft dispatched a private plane to take
Coates from the site of the service to St. Louis the morning of the
game. Instead, Coates used the plane to return to the Boston area.
At the start of this season, when Coates received his first major
paycheck, there was a large sum of money missing. When he inquired
about it, Coates was told a deduction was made for taking the
private plane back to Boston instead of St. Louis. Big Ben was not
pleased.
</P>
<P>
   Management later said it was a mistake, and Coates was
reimbursed the money, but not before his teammates took up a
collection to bail him out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There will be no new parquet floor for the FleetCenter. The
Celtics and the FleetCenter will continue to keep polishing, so to
speak, the legendary playing surface that has been in place since
the start of the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (Fleet) have come to an understanding with the Celtics that
both of us own the floor,'' says FleetCenter CEO Rich Kreswick.
``And both of us want to retain as much of it as we possibly can
for the future. For years we have been replacing certain parts of
the floor as they have worn out. Now we are looking at a complete
overhaul of the floor, rather than doing it a piece at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every part of the floor that is still in good shape will be
kept. We are going to preserve as much of the leprechaun as we
possibly can. Our goal is to eliminate the parts of the floor that
could be dangerous to players _ places that are worn down or
uneven.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't remember what year it was _ probably 1968 or 1969 because
Bill Russell was coaching the team. The Celtics went to Providence
to play a home game against the Cincinnati Royals. They did this
from time to time in those days because Lou Pieri, who owned the
old Providence Arena, was part of the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   When the teams arrived, the arena manager was telling them how
great it was going to be to play on the new floor just installed
for this contest. However, there turned out to be a slight problem.
No one removed the preserving wax from the floor when it was put
together. As a result, when the teams came out to warm up, they
looked as if they were trying to play basketball on skates. They
were slipping and sliding all over the place. The players on both
sides (can you imagine this happening today?) got towels, got down
on all fours, and stripped the wax off the floors as best they
could.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the dangerous situation, the teams agreed not to go
hard to the basket and, in particular, not to knock down anyone
going to the basket for fear of serious injury. The game was played
at three-quarter speed. The Celtics won and then, to end the day,
walked out of the building into a blizzard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's an interesting spin on the NHL's Alexei Yashin case from
Paul Weiler, a professor at the Harvard Law School. Weiler is
perhaps the top sports law expert in the country. He has put out a
book each year this decade and has another, just finished this
week, coming out in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the players' union in hockey should do something right
now to help prevent another player doing what Yashin has done in
Ottawa,'' said Weiler, who is consulted by just about every
players' union in the business. Yashin, a top center with a
long-term, guaranteed contract, refused to report to the Senators
unless they gave him a new deal. This week, Ottawa suspended him
for the rest of the season for not living up to his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Yashin has done can only hurt the rest of the players
down the line. Before the fact, an owner is the one who pays the
price. He has to take an educated guess at how good that player is
going to be over a certain period of time. The owner puts up the
money, and if the player does not perform up to expectations, the
owner still has to pay the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owner never knows for sure what he is going to get. The
player, on the other hand, once he signs, knows he is guaranteed to
get all of the money. Then some players, as it is in the Yashin
case, and I guess with Barry Sanders in football, decide not to
live up to the contract. The owner gets injured, and he has done
nothing wrong. This is a terrible message for everyone. Down the
road, if situations like this continue to come up, owners will not
want to be taking those kind of risks, and this will come back to
hurt other players in the future. The owners will pay the players
less. The union should step up and take the posture that once a
player signs that binding contract, he has an obligation to fulfill
that commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nice touch at Boston College this  &UR; afternoon &LR; . Before kickoff,
John J. Burns Jr., Class of '53, will endow a fund, in the name of
Mike Holovak, which will pay for another graduate assistant
football coach at Boston College. Burns played for Holovak when
Mike was the Eagles' coach from 1951-59 . . . Pat Burns called it
playing ``soft'' when the Bruins got whacked, 6-2, in Buffalo
Wednesday. But the greater embarrassment was the way his teammates
stood around and did nothing when goalie Rob Tallas was upended
with a cheap shot by Miroslav Satan, who should have had his butt
handed to him. But not one of Tallas's teammates did a thing. So
you know when the going gets tough this season, this Bruins team is
going to be ducking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox will visit the Dominican Republic in the spring, but
they've played in the Caribbean before. In 1967, the Sox and
Yankees played two exhibition games in the Virgin Islands, but the
excursion was a fiasco. When the teams arrived, they discovered
there were no baseball fields, so they had to play on a converted
cricket field. When Yankees manager Ralph Houk and Sox skipper Dick
Williams saw what they had on their hands, the teams met at home
plate and agreed there would be no sliding. With no mound, pitchers
were told to throw fastballs and not risk arm injury. The hitters
were told to hit the first pitch that looked good, whenever
possible. The right-field wall could not have been more than 250
feet away. There was a hospital across the street behind the wall.
Some of the Yankees' lefthanded batters had fun in batting
practice, hitting rockets over the wall, across the street, and off
the hospital wall. The Yanks won the first game, 3-1, and the Sox
took the second, 13-4. Those of us who covered the games were
punchy when they were over after listening to a band, stationed 20
feet away from what was supposed to be a press box, play nonstop
throughout the game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State basketball coach Jim O'Brien is a gamer. Obie was
supposed to fly to Boston to speak to the Boston University
basketball team as a favor to old friend Dennis Wolff, but he
injured his back and couldn't fly. In fact, he couldn't coach his
team in a game Wednesday night. So O'Brien, propped up so he could
stand, made a videotaped speech that was flown overnight to Boston
and played for the team and the alumni at the basketball tip-off
dinner . . . Ted Johnson expects to be back in the Patriots' lineup
the second week in December, which could be big for the team as it
conceivably heads into the playoffs. Johnson still doesn't have
full strength back in his injured left biceps and wants to get
banged around a little in practice before he tries to play in a
game . . . The alleged dominance of the NFC is over. The AFC has a
24-12 edge thus far in interconference games, and if the pace
continues, the AFC will have the biggest edge ever in the rivalry .
. . One of the most important games of the Patriots' season takes
place Sunday, and New England is not involved. The Bills-Dolphins
game in Buffalo will have a major impact on the AFC East race.
Miami has beaten the Patriots in New England and the Colts in
Indianapolis, and if they beat the Bills on the road, they would
appear to be a lock to win the division.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
