<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8107 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-WINONA-RYDER-2NDTAKE-     11-12 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINONA-RYDER-2NDTAKE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: it continually.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Working with Meryl Streep, one of her co-stars in ``The House of
the Spirits,'' was also a revelation. ``She would come to work
every day and do these really heart-wrenching scenes, and then go
home to her four children and husband and a wonderful life,'' Ms.
Ryder says. ``And I was thinking I had to stay in this heightened
state of fear and depression to emote.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Ryder was 21, she was given Ms. Kaysen's book in galley
form by her father, Michael Horowitz, a rare-book dealer and an
archivist of counterculture literature. (Ryder is her professional
name.) She immediately identified with the author's poignant
account of her own fraught passage into womanhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just coming out of my very serious depression, and I
didn't know what to label it, just as Susanna doesn't know what to
label hers,'' she says. She was determined to play Susanna and
tried to option the film rights. When she learned that a producer
at Columbia Pictures had beaten her to it, she says, she used her
clout to take over the project, persuading the studio to let her
star and take an active role in the production.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kaysen's darkly comic, impressionistic book, which has
virtually no plot, did not easily translate to film. Ms. Ryder
persevered through several directors and innumerable rewrites
before entrusting the project to James Mangold, who was then
completing his second film, the macho police drama ``Cop Land.''
But Ms. Ryder had been impressed by his directorial debut,
``Heavy,'' an independent film about an obese chef's obsessive love
for a woman he could never have. Deeply moved by the film, she was
convinced that Mangold could pull off a tough but tender
investigation of a confusing time in a young woman's life that
would remain true to the spirit of Ms. Kaysen's book.
</P>
<P>
   Mangold says he hated the adaptation she sent him but was
captivated by Ms. Ryder herself: ``It turned out we both loved
silent films _ all the things that aren't said on screen. Noni is a
genuine silent movie actress. She can reveal things, with just her
eyes, with a delicacy that is indescribable. I also saw that she
wanted to reach further, and as a director, I wanted to take her
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Because she was already an avid student of depression _ she can
quote freely from a heavily underlined copy of William Styron's
memoir, ``Darkness Visible'' _ Mangold discouraged her from
becoming too caught up in the diagnostic literature. ``She never
got lost in the material,'' he says. ``Because she was operating
from experiences she had had, instead of from intellectual
parallels, she spent a lot of time just remembering what it was
like to be very deep inside herself. She gives a wonderful
performance because she understood that the point of the book is
that crazy isn't all that different than normal, just a slightly
amplified or skewed way of viewing things.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kaysen, who visited the set, was struck by Ms. Ryder's
commitment to getting every detail just right. ``She's a
perfectionist, and she drives herself very hard,'' the author
observes.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Ryder admits she worried at times that making the
movie might push her over the edge _ particularly in the three
cold, gray months of filming in an empty wing of a state hospital
in Harrisburg, Pa. _ her colleagues credit her with keeping them
sane. (The supporting cast includes Angelina Jolie as her psychotic
pal, Whoopi Goldberg as the no-nonsense ward nurse, and Vanessa
Redgrave as the chief psychiatrist.) ``She has a completely
paradoxical personality,'' says Jack Green, the director of
photography. ``In certain ways, she has this incredible innocence,
and yet she is so strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Denise Di Novi, who first worked with Ms. Ryder when the actress
was 14 and has produced three of her movies (``Heathers,'' ``Edward
Scissorhands'' and ``Little Women''), says Ms. Ryder was unlike any
teenager she had ever met. ``She started out with more strength of
character and centeredness about her own instincts and beliefs than
most adults ever have,'' Ms. Di Novi says. ``She was always very
comfortable with not being average.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ryder concedes that before puberty, she was supremely
self-confident. She attributes that confidence to her parents, whom
she describes as 1960s intellectual beatniks. ``I don't know how to
say this without sounding weird, but they kind of worshiped me,''
she says with a fond giggle.
</P>
<P>
   The third of four children (she has an older half-sister and
half-brother, and a younger brother, Uri, an actor, who shares her
house in Los Angeles), Ms. Ryder spent her early childhood in San
Francisco, where her father took her on his rounds of protests,
poetry readings and regular visits to the poet Allen Ginsberg's
apartment. Her mother, Cindy, a writer and editor, often kept her
precocious daughter home to watch classic black-and-white movies.
Schooled on gangster pictures and film noir, Ms. Ryder chose as her
movie idol James Cagney.
</P>
<P>
   After spending four years in a northern California commune, the
Horowitzes moved to Petaluma, Calif., and enrolled their children
in public school. On the first day, Ms. Ryder, who was entering the
seventh grade, knew it was going to be a disaster. She had worn her
beloved Cagney attire, complete with crew cut, thrift-shop suit,
white shirt and tie. It did not go over well. On the third day of
school, she says, she was beaten up by a group of students, who
slammed her head against a locker and called her ``a faggot.'' She
was bandaged in the nurse's office and sent home. ``They kicked me
out and asked me not to come back,'' she says. ``They said I was a
distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   She was put on home study, and to occupy her afternoons, her
parents suggested she apply to the drama school affiliated with San
Francisco's American Conservatory Theater. At her audition, she
performed a monologue from J.D. Salinger's novel ``Franny and
Zooey.'' By the end of her first year, the 12-year-old misfit had
her own agent. ``So I have those kids to thank for where I am
today,'' she says, arching her elegant brows.
</P>
<P>
   Today, her sense of social obligation has spurred her to produce
a documentary on Leonard Peltier, an American Indian who has spent
the last 25 years in prison for his part in a shooting incident
during which two FBI agents were killed. The project is based in
part on Peter Mathiesson's book ``The Spirit of Crazy Horse.'' But
she is not averse to a big, glamorous Hollywood role. In the
romantic comedy ``Autumn in New York,'' she plays a beautiful young
woman who has only a year to live and chooses to have her last
fling with Richard Gere as a jaded playboy. ``The age difference is
actually an issue in the movie,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Though she is the iconoclastic offspring of anti-establishment
parents, Ms. Ryder is not a rebel. She fully enjoys the bourgeois
fruits of stardom, including a house in Beverly Hills, a
beautifully furnished New York apartment (on loan to a friend) and
a closet full of designer clothes. She is also not above throwing
her name around to get what she wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to business, she is not that delicate
creature,'' says the screenwriter Jay Cocks, who wrote the
adaptation of ``The Age of Innocence.'' He recalls a dinner during
which a famous director tried in vain to persuade her to take the
lead in a remake, something she objects to on principle. ``He kept
telling her to take the money, but he couldn't convince her,''
Cocks says, noting that Ms. Ryder has also turned down countless
offers to reprise Audrey Hepburn roles (including, reportedly, the
famously unsuccessful 1995 remake of ``Sabrina,'' which starred
Julia Ormond.) ``She has fantastic confidence in her own judgment,
which she should have, because she has very good taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she knows ``Girl, Interrupted'' may be a difficult
sell, she is hoping her star power will help it find an audience.
``This movie will be an example,'' Ms. Ryder says. ``If it does
well, the studios may be inclined to make more personal movies and
take more chances. Those are the movies that always end up being
classics.'' And she has always wanted to be in a classic.
</P>
</TEXT>
