<SLUG> BC-INVEST-EMERGE-MARKETS-$ADV14-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THE STOCK RALLY BROADENS, THE ROLE OF THE FED BANK GROWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release, Sunday, Nov.14)  (DW) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's some good news ahead of the meeting of Federal Reserve
policy makers on Tuesday: The stock market rally is broadening.
More stocks are doing better _ or at least not as poorly as they
once were _ compared with the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists are generally more comfortable with a broader
market; a market with narrow leadership is often headed for a fall.
</P>
<P>
   According to one measure, the Laggards indicator produced by
Jeffrey M. Warantz, equity strategist at Salomon Smith Barney, 58.8
percent of 7,598 common stocks are trailing the performance of the
S&AMP;P 500 by 15 percentage points or more over the last 12 months.
But that is down from a record 77.1 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   More evidence of the broadening is seen in the Russell 2000
index, which measures smaller-company stocks and is up 17.3 percent
from its low for the year in March. On a wider scale, Warantz said
companies with market capitalizations of $10 billion or less were
up 15.6 percent, on average, in the second and third quarters of
this year. This performance of midcap to small-cap stocks compares
with an average decline of 4 percent for companies with
capitalizations of more than $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That broadening has occurred while the Federal Reserve has been
raising its short-term interest rate target, to 5.75 percent from
5.25 percent. Another increase is possible on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   While the Fed was raising its target three full percentage
points between February 1994 and February 1995, this index jumped
to 44.4 percent from 28.6 percent, meaning that the leadership of
the market narrowed significantly as investors chose to switch into
the most liquid, big-company stocks that have good, long-term
earnings records.
</P>
<P>
   What does all this mean?
</P>
<P>
   One interpretation is that even though the market has broadened,
the improvement has been only from the narrowest market since the
indicator was created in 1971. Now at 58.8 percent, the indicator
is still well above the average of 34.9 percent and at the
fourth-highest point since 1971. By this interpretation, the
performance since May is not as positive as it looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market was excruciatingly narrow at its worst and it is
still narrow at its best,'' said Byron R. Wien, U.S. investment
strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   Another interpretation is that this is just another market
indicator that worked in the past but isn't working now. That is
the story for many of the guides that equity strategists and Fed
policy makers have been using to help them understand the
performance of the stock market and the economy in the last half of
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, 1987 and 1990, this indicator peaked and the stock
market had a big fall. This time, that hasn't happened yet.
</P>
<P>
   Or the index is proving that investors in general are still
confident about the outlook for stocks _ and probably more
confident than they were several months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The economy is growing strongly, while inflation still appears
in check. Third-quarter operating earnings for the S&AMP;P 500 have
risen 22 percent, according to the First Call Corp., and the
forecast for growth in the fourth quarter is 18 percent. Further,
the outlook for avoiding Year 2000 computer problems is improving.
</P>
<P>
   That optimism could change if the Fed raises interest rates
again. The October increase of 0.3 percent in the Producer Price
Index for finished goods, excluding food and energy, was bigger
than expected and revived worries about a Fed rate increase. But
strong productivity numbers and moderate retail sales data,
reported on Friday, seemed to calm investors.
</P>
<P>
   With a third quarter-point rate increase, the Fed would erase
the three quarter-point cuts made in the fall of 1998 to counter
the impact of Russia's bond default, the near collapse of a major
hedge fund and the deepening global financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   That would set the stage for new concern. Investors may find a
third rate increase tolerable because they were just taking back
the largess of 1998. But if the economy does not slow down, the
speculation will turn to where the Fed goes from here. That means
the real test for stocks and bonds won't come until after this
third rate increase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
