<HEADLINE>
SCRUTINY OF RESEARCH GRANTS STEPPED UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At academic centers around the country, including Harvard
Medical School this week, charges of misuse of federal research and
training funds are increasingly leading to internal scrutiny and
stepped-up efforts to monitor compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Within the coming days, for instance, the dean of the Harvard
Medical School plans to announce the creation of a compliance
committee to the faculty, on the heels of the resignation this week
of a nationally known aging specialist from a top administrative
post, after the application of one of her grants was questioned.
</P>
<P>
   And the association representing the nation's medical colleges
and teaching hospitals has recently created a new group to focus on
research compliance, to ensure that people who participate in
studies are protected and that federal funds are properly used.
</P>
<P>
   These efforts come after a US crackdown that has resulted in
millions of dollars nationwide being returned by institutions
alleged to have misused funds, and individual researchers being
charged.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, for instance, Beth Israel Deaconess Medical
Center in Boston returned $920,000 to the US government to settle a
suit and stepped up its research compliance program, after denying
allegations that research funds were being misused. And last month,
a New York scientist was charged with using drug abuse research
funds for personal purposes, like buying CDs and hiring people to
work on a book manuscript.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to address research compliance ``in a really
integrated and cohesive way is fairly new, and perhaps precipitated
by these problems,'' acknowledged Allan Shipp, assistant vice
president for biomedical and health sciences research for the
Association of American Medical Colleges, which represents medical
schools and teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the need for such an effort is the increasing
regulatory complexity and financial pressures on academic medical
centers, perhaps leading some institutions to use funds for
purposes other than those specified in a grant, Shipp said. In the
September issue of the association's journal, ``Academic
Medicine,'' a special article highlighted some of the common abuses
of federal research grants, and ways to avoid them through research
compliance programs.
</P>
<P>
   A prominent patient and consumer advocate, Dr. Sidney Wolfe,
director of Public Citizen's Health Research Group, agreed that
``there's been a huge change in culture in medical schools and
teaching hospitals'' in terms of how research funding is viewed
because of these other pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money that's supposed to be spent on one thing is spent for
something else,'' Wolfe said. But he added, ``This is not to say
that that legitimizes it and exonerates anyone from blame.''
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard Medical School, a five-year training grant in the
amount of $416,000 in fiscal 1999 came into question after some of
the money was apparently not used according to the grant's terms,
and diverted to other research purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeanne Y. Wei, 50, principal investigator on the grant,
resigned this week as head of the school's division of aging and as
head of Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center's division of
gerontology, days after Harvard University reported concerns about
the grant to federal officials, The Boston Globe reported Friday.
Wei, who could not be reached for comment, retains her position as
associate professor at the medical school and her research and
medical appointments at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Don L. Gibbons, associate dean for the school's office of public
affairs, said Harvard Medical School Dean Joseph B. Martin has
``over the past few weeks. . .been planning a compliance committee
that he'll be announcing to the faculty in the coming days.''
</P>
<P>
   But when asked if that was in response to an investigation into
Wei's grant, Gibbons said, ``This conversation is not about Dr.
Wei, it's about compliance.'' He declined to comment on why Wei
resigned, or whether there has been any investigation into Wei's
grants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have for a while been looking at our compliance issues to
make sure they're as good as they can be,'' Gibbons said. ``We've
always taken compliance very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center also say they
have always taken compliance seriously, even before the $920,000
repayment to the US government in April, to settle a case alleging
misuse of research funds. But Leon Goldman, director of the
hospital's office for business conduct, acknowledged that they have
stepped up implementing a comprehensive research compliance program
as part of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Goldman said, such settlements with the US government
by academic medical centers around the country prompt ``all health
care providers, academic, for-profit or not-for-profit, to be
diligent in what they do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
