<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-LAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD LAW GRADUATE   GIVES $5 MILLION FOR FELLOWSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Trying to reverse a steep decline in the number of
promising students who go into public service, an alumnus has given
$5 million to endow fellowships at the Harvard Law School that will
pay the student loans of graduates who commit to work in
government.
</P>
<P>
   As tuition has gone up, so have student debt loads. But as
salaries have gone up in the private sector, salaries in government
have remained relatively flat. Combined with a distaste for
government service, school officials say, fewer and fewer students
want to work in the public sector.
</P>
<P>
   With the new Heyman fellowships, Harvard is trying to make
service to the federal government not only more financially viable,
but also more prestigious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debt is so high these days, that it's kind of hard for
people who don't live with that kind of debt to understand how hard
it is,'' said Margo Schlanger, a 1993 Yale Law graduate who worked
in the Justice Department before returning to Harvard as an
assistant professor. ``This will at least get people thinking about
ways to work in public service. It eases the debt burden, it
encourages them to think hard about it in a way that makes it feel
prestigious. It endorses what is a good opportunity as a good
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The fellowships, endowed by Samuel J. Heyman, a former
government lawyer who went on to be a billionaire chief executive
of GAF Corp., will select 20 fellows a year, who will receive
honoraria and help paying off student loans. The program will also
set up conferences for fellows to share their experience, and also
with senior government officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gift will reinvigorate the School's rich tradition of
public service by graduates at the Federal level,'' said Dean
Robert Clark. ``Perhaps this program will produce the next
Elizabeth Dole or Archibald Cox.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest in public service jobs hit a peak in 1975 just after
the Watergate scandal, when 49 Harvard Law School graduates went to
Washington to take jobs with the federal government. Last spring,
that number was down to 7, the low point of a steady decline. The
percentage dropped nationwide, too, from about 20 percent to about
13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The decline began not least with the increasing burden of
student loans, and the increase in salaries in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, students who went to work for the federal government
and those who went to work for a Boston law firm earned about the
same amount, $60,000, after taxes and student loans, their first
year. At a New York law firm, a graduate would earn about $91,000
after taxes and loans, according to Harvard career office data.
</P>
<P>
   But the gap between public and private sector salaries has
increased enormously. Now, a student who goes to work for the
government earns about $51,000 after taxes and loans, while one who
works in a Boston law firm earns $103,000, and in a New York firm,
$146,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students often get out with $80,000, $100,000 in debt,''
Schlanger said. ``That's $12,000-$16,000 in loan payments every
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard already offers loan forgiveness for those who go into
low paying jobs, but those who earn more than $50,000 are not
eligible for it. People who enter government service are paid just
slightly more, but not enough to make the job seem attractive, or
even affordable.
</P>
<P>
   The program is to be administered by Philip Heymann, a Harvard
Law graduate who worked in several positions in the Justice
Department for the Clinton Administration before returning to
Harvard as a professor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 2000EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
