<HEADER>
A8135 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-B     11-12 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S BOXING'S TIME TO PROVE IT'S A PUNCH ABOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Don King was maybe two minutes into his riff,
seemingly without taking a breath as words and then hundreds of
words poured from his mouth, the promoter telling one and all that
he, more than anyone, wants boxing cleaned up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I steadfastly and manifestly proclaim that the evil should be
removed from this great sport,'' the promoter boomed. ``Let the
evil wrongdoers be exposed to the shining light of day, as the
Bible says they should, let the prosecutors come in and do their
manifest duty. This is America! No one in America is above the law,
the president is not above the law, so let the wrongdoers be thrown
out as they most deservedly should be thrown out, and let the
guilty ones be punished.''
</P>
<P>
   So boxing has come to this.
</P>
<P>
   Don King calling for reform, to which Lennox Lewis says,
``Anything Don King is involved in, you've got to be suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   A circus.
</P>
<P>
   Only one ring, though.
</P>
<P>
   Akin to Wrasslin'.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, much more quietly a while later, King disclosed that a
goodly chunk of tickets for Saturday's Evander Holyfield-Lewis
heavyweight title fight at UNLV's Thomas &AMP; Mack Center had come
back on the market (from Las Vegas casinos that had reserved them
for the high-rollers who didn't come). Even more, the pay-per-view
folk are not guessing, as they usually do, how many millions will
watch the fight on TV; the educated guess is that some 500,000 or
so fewer will tune in than tuned in for their controversial first
fight in March at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   King, still with a straight face, has dubbed the fight:
``Unfinished Business; The Search for the Truth.'' Truth, of
course, seldom has been able to find a sparring partner in the
boxing ring.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of the two _ boxing's ugly unshaven face finally
repelling those who buy the tickets _ has brought an aura to the
fight seldom seen; that the clean-up-the-sport crowd must finally
be heeded. On the surface, at least.
</P>
<P>
   First off, it has been trumpeted that the three judges for the
bout are both competent and honest, and definitely have not been
bought off. The judges are Jerry Roth, who has judged about 100
title fights in 17 years, Chuck Giampa who has scored about 75
championship bouts in eight years, and Bill Graham, who has judged
about 50 title fights in six years. It is heralded that all three
are from Nevada, now interestingly regarded as the most honest spot
in America to hold a boxing match.
</P>
<P>
   But in Las Vegas, where illusion is all, the truest test is
whether anyone comes to see the show. The end of the first
Lewis-Holyfield fight was controversial enough, when judge Eugenia
Williams (picked by King crony and International Boxing Federation
head Bob Lee) scored the bout as few with open eyes saw it, for
Holyfield, amid suspicions she was financially tied to King. And
King, no prisoner of political correctness, now puts it, ``Even Ray
Charles could see'' that something was amiss in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Even more, before the controversial draw when most had given the
fight to Lewis, the fight was more a cautious half-yawn than a true
heavyweigt battle.
</P>
<P>
   So, with interest in the fight tepid, the prebout consensus is
that boxing is at a crossroads. But the consensus, as with any
consensus, just may be wrong. That's because some 6,000 English
have come over to see Lewis, who was born in England, finally earn
a victory in the United States, where the English so seldom do well
(Lewis is a 2-1 favorite). His supporters will be loud and rowdy.
</P>
<P>
   And the fight just may be good. Holyfield (36-3-1), for one, has
been perfect in his rematches, going 5-0 in his second chances,
most notably against Michael Moorer and Riddick Bowe, who both had
beaten Holyfield the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get two fighters with the same skill, the one with the
most will is going to win,'' said Don Turner, Holyfield's trainer.
``In other words, the one who wants it the most. And Evander has
won the rematches because he wants to prove he's better than they
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, for his part, said he has studied the tape of the
first bout with Lewis and saw ``that I made too many mistakes. If I
just minimize the mistakes, I can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has been speaking to respected referee Mitch Halpern
through the media. (Head-butting is a longtime Holyfield ploy,
Lewis said, ``and he uses his head as if it were a battering
ram.'') Lewis's trainer, Emanuel Steward, said that his boxer is so
fit and strong now that ``I don't know of any heavyweight in the
world who can go over six rounds with him (Saturday night).''
</P>
<P>
   Steward seems to be trying to get his message through to his own
boxer, because Lewis so often has been cautious in his bouts.
Steward's message is that his fighter, with a huge weight
advantage, is too strong for his smaller foe and can put him away
early. If he dares to.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Holyfield) is the one who was supposed to come in and knock
me out,'' said Lewis of Holyfield's prediction that he was going to
knock out Lewis by the third round in the first fight. ``I've been
in there with the man and I know what I can do. I know what I
should have done and could have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield certainly has the stronger will of the two, and it is
still unknown if Lewis can dare to be great. All of which should
lead to a most interesting fight, and Don King just might be saying
late Saturday that he ``steadfastly and manifestly'' always knew in
his bones that boxing is ready for the next millennium if only
there can be more bouts like this.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 2004EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
