<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8139 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CANADA-U.S.-INVEST-10     11-12 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-U.S.-INVEST-1075-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITAL CROSSOVER: AMERICA INVESTS HEAVILY IN CANADA (AND VICE
VERSA) 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JAMES BROOKE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Twenty years ago, when an outside company tried to buy
MacMillan Bloedel, British Columbia's largest timber company, the
provincial premier reacted angrily, saying: ``B.C. is not for
sale.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Nov. 1, MacMillan, an 80-year-old Canadian company,
disappeared into the corporate maw of Weyerhaeuser in a deal worth
$2.4 billion. Approval of the takeover came this summer from
provincial Forestry Minister David Zirnhelt, who said, ``Icons
don't make jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of a neighboring economy newly open to foreign
investment and a Canadian dollar trading near historic lows,
Americans are vacuuming up Canadian companies at a record pace. In
the first nine months of this year, American companies bought 181
companies for $24 billion, double the amount spent during the
corresponding period last year, according to a survey by KPMG
Corporate Finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada has a `for sale' sign on the lawn, courtesy of a very
cheap exchange rate,'' said David Rosenberg, a senior economist at
Nesbitt Burns, a major securities firm in Toronto. Although the
Canadian dollar has strengthened slightly this year to 68 U.S.
cents, Canadian companies still seem cheap to American executives
who remember the days in the 1960s when North America's two dollars
were equal in value.
</P>
<P>
   Today, American investors are also plunging into Canadian
stocks. In the first seven months of this year, Americans increased
their Canadian stock holdings by $6.5 billion, a sevenfold increase
over the corresponding period two years ago. More American
investment is on the way, according to 23 American portfolio
managers surveyed in October about the Canadian markets by
Broadgate Consultants, a capital markets communications firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the investors surveyed said they would increase or
maintain their Canadian positions over the next 12 months,'' John
Silver, a Broadgate managing director, said from New York. ``What
caught my eye was the incredible amount of good will that American
portfolio managers had toward Canadian companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, while Americans are investing heavily in Canadian stocks
and companies, Canadians are funneling their money across the
border in volumes evocative of capital flight from Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   As of August, Canadians had, for the first time on record, more
money invested in foreign stock markets than in Canadian markets,
according to data compiled by Statistics Canada, a government
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Investing largely in American shares, Canadians now own at least
$57 billion of foreign stocks _ almost $2,000 for each Canadian
citizen. This drain has taken place despite tax credits for owning
local stocks and a government-mandated 20 percent cap on foreign
investments for registered retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   And while Canada's economy is only 7 percent the size of its
southern neighbor, Canada has become the fourth-largest direct
foreign investor in the United States. Last year, Canada, with 30
million inhabitants, had $87 billion invested in real assets in the
United States. The United States, with nine times Canada's
population, had $99.3 billion invested directly in Canada. During
much of the 1990s, Canadian investment abroad increased at twice
the rate as foreign investment here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to call it capital flight,'' Rosenberg said. ``The
irony is that while Canadians have become net sellers of
Canadian-based mutual funds, foreigners have been dramatically
lifting their investments in Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, with oil and gasoline prices rising sharply this year
and an Asian recovery fueling demand for minerals and wood
products, those bets are starting to pay off as prospects improve
for Canada's economy, which is heavily dependent on natural
resources. Compared with last year, when the Toronto Stock Exchange
300, the market's main index, dropped 3 percent, it has
outperformed the equivalent in the United States, the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500, so far this year, rising 16.04 percent, compared with
13.57 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is looking for undiscovered stocks,'' Silver said of
American interest in Canadian companies.
</P>
<P>
   Yet after watching the Canadian dollar shrink by a third in
value, Canadians are leery of investing in their own country.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians tend to dwell on their economic negatives, especially
the $50 billion a year in taxes that goes every year to service
federal and provincial debts. Largely because of these interest
payments, Canada's tax revenue equals 37 percent of its gross
domestic product, compared with 32 percent for federal, state and
local taxes in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because of this higher tax burden, Canada's unemployment
rate is 7.2 percent, well above the 4.1 percent rate in the United
States. And Canada, in contrast with the United States, has not
registered growth in real personal income during the 1990s. As the
``brain drain'' becomes a national conversation topic, half of
1,850 senior Canadian executives agreed in a recent survey with the
statement: ``Talented people are leaving the country due to high
income taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   But, after budget cutting, the federal government here recorded
a $2 billion surplus last year, which is expected to rise to nearly
$4 billion this year. After lagging behind the United States during
much of the 1990s, Canada is expected to equal the forecast U.S.
growth rate of 4 percent this year. With budget surpluses expected
to grow in coming years, business people are lobbying heavily to
use them to cut taxes and to pay down the $392 billion national
debt.
</P>
<P>
   Although Canada increased its total take in personal and
corporate income taxes by 39 percent over the last five years,
Finance Minister Paul Martin vowed in a policy speech earlier this
month to cut taxes in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, to American investors, a growing economy, an
undervalued market, and a currency that appears to have stabilized
are signals to buy.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and Ameritech this year bought up to the 20 percent limit
on foreign ownership of Canadian telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more and more U.S. investment,'' said Bruce
McWilliam, a lawyer here specializing in foreign investment in such
companies. Referring to the 20 percent limits on foreign investment
in banking, telecommunications and transport, he said, ``They
always want to try to come up to the limits of what is allowed
under foreign investment rules.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the finance sector, the CIT Group, a Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank
unit based in Livingston, N.J., agreed in late October to pay $2.7
billion for the Newcourt Credit Group, a growing commercial finance
company based in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   In western Canada's oil patch, two Houston companies are making
big purchases. Burlington Resources is paying $1.9 billion for Poco
Petroleums of Calgary, and Apache is paying $531 million for most
of Shell Canada Ltd.'s oil producing properties. Shell is a unit of
Royal Dutch/Shell.
</P>
<P>
   As some see it, in the oil and gas business _ and many other
industries as well _ the border between the United States and
Canada is being erased.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 49th parallel is gone _ just look at the deals,'' said
Rick Roberge, a petroleum analyst with PricewaterhouseCoopers.
Roberge, an Albertan who now works in mergers and acquisitions in
Houston, also noted that Canadian energy companies had made
purchases of American companies.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling the activity, he said, was a 50 percent jump in natural
gas prices since spring and the expected opening next year of a gas
pipeline from western Canada to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in Canada has extended to the aviation industry. AMR,
the parent of American Airlines, and UAL, parent of United
Airlines, marshaled rival bids of about half a billion dollars each
in an effort help Canadian allies wrest control of Canada's two
major airlines. United and its partner, Air Canada, emerged as the
winners this month after an American-backed bid was disbanded.
</P>
<P>
   All these American investments in Canada, like those Canadians
are making in the United States, reflect North America's rapid
economic integration.
</P>
<P>
   In the biggest deal on the part of Canadians in the United
States, Canadian National Railway paid $2.4 billion this summer for
Illinois Central. Building on an explosion in north-south trade
after a free trade pact was signed a decade ago, the expanded
railroad will carry freight from Canada to Chicago and on to New
Orleans. In another major deal, Toronto's Nortel Networks, a unit
of Northern Telecom and Canada's largest supplier of telephone
equipment, agreed in mid-October to pay $2.1 billion for Clarify, a
San Jose, Calif., e-commerce software company.
</P>
<P>
   And in a deal that makes Quebecor Printing the world's largest
commercial printer, the Montreal-based company paid $1.4 billion
for a major American rival, World Color Press, of Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this evidence of a two-way street, many people here
focus on what they call the threatened loss of their sports icons _
professional hockey, basketball and baseball teams coveted by
wealthy American investors. Bill Laurie, a St. Louis billionaire,
for example, has been negotiating to buy the Vancouver Grizzlies
basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Some commentators fear that Canadian National Hockey League
teams are next.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ottawa Senators will be first,'' Jeffrey Simpson, a Globe
and Mail columnist, predicted recently. ``Within a year or two, or
perhaps even sooner, the Calgary Flames, Edmonton Oilers and
Vancouver Canucks will follow, leaving Canada with only the Toronto
Maple Leafs and Montreal Canadiens.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the percentage of Canada's economy controlled by
foreign companies is actually lower today than during the
nationalist days of the 1970s, Canadian newspapers carry laments
about some of the high-profile purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great sucking sound from the south is creating a storm of
troubles,'' Eric Reguly, a columnist, warned in a recent Globe and
Mail article titled ``The devouring of Corporate Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend is depressingly familiar,'' he wrote. ``A Canadian
company grows, often with the tender loving care of the provincial
and federal governments, gets big enough to attract attention on
the international stage and _ zap! _ vanishes like a bug into a
frog's mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that Canada is losing corporate headquarters, he noted
that Alcan Aluminum was merging with two rivals and setting up a
head office in New York. The big American buyout was the topic of a
speech delivered in September by Canadian Pacific Ltd. president
David O'Brien before the Canadian Chamber of Commerce, the nation's
largest business association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canadian icons are falling like 10 pins,'' said O'Brien, who
is also chairman of the Business Council on National Issues, a
private policy group. ``The great Canadian fire sale is underway.
Because of the low Canadian dollar, Corporate Canada is easy
pickings for countries with stronger currencies.''
</P>
<P>
   But few people predict a return to the restrictive investment
policies of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't necessarily like each and every one of those
transactions, but this is part and parcel of the integration of
North America,'' said Raymond Chretien, Canada's ambassador to the
United States, in an interview. ``It worries some people,'' the
ambassador, a nephew of Prime Minister Jean Chretien, said, ``but
again if you look at the experience of the last 10 years, it
usually balances out. We Canadians buy a lot in the U.S.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 2009EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8141 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GRAVES-RELOCATE13-COX     11-12 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAVES-RELOCATE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Developer's plan to relocate cemetery stirs opposition
 &HT;    By D.L. Bennett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Ga. _ The graves of dozens of former slaves and
generations of their descendents may be dug up and moved to make
way for a Canton shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   Developers of Riverstone Plaza plan to move the 127-year-old
cemetery of Hickory Log Missionary Baptist Church, one of Cherokee
County's first black churches.
</P>
<P>
   There are no written records of how many were buried at Hickory
Log, but church members and developers say there are 400 to 500.
Burials began about the time of the church's founding in 1872 and
continued for more than 120 years.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives and church members are vehemently against unearthing
the dead to make way for a shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the dead should be left alone,'' said the Rev. Robert
Holmes, pastor of the 480-member church. ``I don't believe in
moving the dead. They shouldn't be disturbed.''
</P>
<P>
   Developer Mike Sasser contends the small cemetery is on property
owned by Bright-Sasser Co. of Atlanta and needs to make way for a
proposed expansion of the shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Riverstone Plaza is a 600,000-square-foot ``power
center'' anchored by J.C. Penney and Belks department stores off
Interstate 575 in Canton. The 650-acre site will eventually include
Cherokee's first regional shopping mall. The cemetery is on its
western edge.
</P>
<P>
   Sasser said leaving a cemetery inside a massive, regional
shopping complex just doesn't make sense. He plans to apply to the
city soon for a permit to move the graves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is relocated, then families will have the chance to be
buried together,'' Sasser said. ``There will be perpetual care. I'm
not here to judge what's good and bad, but we'd like to relocate
the cemetery.''
</P>
<P>
   With at least 400 graves, Sasser's proposed relocation might be
the biggest such project ever attempted in Georgia. He expects to
spend at least six months doing the legal work and archeological
research needed to move the bodies, he said. The work of finding
and moving the graves would likely take another year. He has no
estimate yet on how much it would cost.
</P>
<P>
   Hickory Log Church is in the small North Canton community that
has long housed much of the city's black population.
</P>
<P>
   The church was founded just seven years after the end of the
Civil War on a hill overlooking the small city. It and the
graveyard were located on 2 acres of land donated by Phillip Keith,
who was buried there in 1889.
</P>
<P>
   Church members originally met in a log cabin near the cemetery.
They relocated worship services to a brick building on nearby in
1957. Holmes said on an average Sunday about 200 attend service.
</P>
<P>
   Time hasn't been kind to the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Hidden deep in heavy woods, the cemetery is overgrown and
unkempt. Dozens of knee-high scrub pines grow from sunken graves
with broken and fallen headstones. Unmowed grass grows wildly in
some portions of the cemetery while only dirt covers many of the
more recent burials _ at least one as recent as 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Battered silk flowers decorate several graves. Trash and empty
beer cans are scattered about.
</P>
<P>
   Orange survey tape and tiny orange flags mark the cemetery's
boundaries and some of the grave sites. Newly posted signs warn off
trespassers and ban any new burials.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes said the church has no organized maintenance plan.
Members simply go by when they feel like it, he said. Still, they
don't want it dug up and moved.
</P>
<P>
   Church members contend they own the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Ferguson, whose wife, mother and father are buried
there, said no deed exists because the land was a gift so long ago.
He said members want a fence erected around the cemetery and no
graves disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   Reinterment would be difficult, Ferguson said, because so many
of the graves are marked only by fieldstones.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would you do with them, dump them all in a big hole?''
Ferguson said. ``We are going to do whatever we have to do to stop
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Sasser concedes that more than half the graves are unmarked. He
said an archeologist found about 400 graves in a survey earlier
this year, but only 150 could be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Sasser wants to rebury the bodies from Hickory Log at Cherokee
Memorial Park at in Canton, where the church has already bought 100
plots for future burials.
</P>
<P>
   Those who can be identified will be given proper markers. The
remainder will be given a group headstone explaining the history of
the area they came from, Sasser said.
</P>
<P>
   Family members say whatever Sasser could do wouldn't be enough
to convince them to support relocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me that they would do this,'' said Gable Holmes, a
church member whose mother, father, brother and other relatives are
buried at Hickory Log. ``They will never be able to dig all of them
up. They can't find half of the graves now. I'd rather them put a
fence around it.''
</P>
<P>
   The dead regularly stand in the way of progress in metro
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Auto dealer C.V. Nalley III spent five years trying to arrange
removal and reburial of 52 graves for a dealership near Town Center
mall.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the cemetery looked like a barren outcropping after
grading crews cut away all the land surrounding the Edwards-Attaway
cemetery for parking. Eventually, lawsuits were settled and the
graves moved.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, developers of Avondale Mall agreed to build a
granite mausoleum around the gravesites of some of DeKalb's
earliest settlers. In north DeKalb County near I-285, five small
family graveyards are surrounded by Northlake Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
