<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 ENCOUNTERS INSPIRE THOUGHTS OF BINDING TIES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the surface, the three events were completely different _ and
even more so the three individuals at the center of them. A small
lunch, a private interview, a public lecture.
</P>
<P>
   An Italian Roman Catholic cardinal steeped in years of Vatican
diplomacy; a Jordanian prince claiming direct descent, over 42
generations, from the prophet Muhammad; a Canadian philosopher
known for his explorations of liberalism, ethics and the nature of
modernity.
</P>
<P>
   But jammed up one after another a few days back, the three
encounters left the sense that beyond all the differences, some
common thread wove them into a larger pattern.
</P>
<P>
   The lunch was with Cardinal Achille Silvestrini. For many years
he was papal under secretary of state, the Vatican's equivalent of
foreign minister. Now he heads the Vatican's office for Eastern
churches _ that is, for the churches originating in the Middle East
and Eastern Europe that recognize the pope's authority but follow
ancient, non-Western rites and practices.
</P>
<P>
   Silvestrini has just edited a collection of excerpts from talks
that John Paul II has given in the course of 85 journeys around the
world. So strictly speaking, it was a publisher's lunch, a small
gathering of journalists and churchmen to greet ``A Pilgrim Pope''
(K.S. Giniger/Andrews McMeel Universal).
</P>
<P>
   But Silvestrini was not in the United States to publicize a
book. He was here to meet with the bishops from the Western
Hemisphere who oversee non-Latin-rite Catholic churches founded by
immigrants from Ukraine, Hungary, Lebanon, Syria, Iraq and other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   One lunchtime topic, therefore, became the strained relations
between the Catholic Church and Eastern Orthodox Christianity,
strains that leave many of these Eastern-rite Catholics caught in
the middle. Are they part of the solution, a bridge between divided
parts of Christianity? Or are they part of the problem, a papal
bridgehead that threatens Eastern Orthodoxy?
</P>
<P>
   The other topic was the plight of Arab Christians, whose
presence in the Middle East has fallen victim to the region's
religious rivalries and economic disruption.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the conversation was, of course, the cardinal
himself, always a diplomat in the best sense. His evenhanded
assessments of the fears, fault lines and failures of different
religious groups radiated sympathy and not blame. One could
understand why a few years ago he was often listed among possible
successors to John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   By now, his age, 76, might tell against him as a papal
candidate. But one could imagine him still a ``great elector,'' a
man so respected by other cardinals that his support for a
candidate would be extremely persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   From his eminence to his royal highness was a jolt. Prince El
Hassan bin Talal of Jordan, the younger brother of the late King
Hussein, is a compact, thickset man who bristles with energy,
physical and intellectual. He is a veteran of international
commissions and a serious patron of interfaith dialogue, but it is
not surprising to learn he is also a black belt in martial arts.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he had come from a meeting at the Council on Foreign
Relations to the offices of the World Conference on Religion and
Peace near the United Nations. In two weeks, he will preside as
chairman of the conference's Seventh World Assembly, which will
bring more than 600 senior religious leaders together in Amman,
Jordan, to discuss ways of resolving violent conflicts and building
peaceful institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Tossed a standard query about religion and violence, Hassan was
off and running. He quoted Pascal and Kierkegaard, Yehudi Menuhin,
Vaclav Havel and the archbishop of Canterbury. He mentioned
personal encounters in Bosnia, Prague, Ulster, Albania, Geneva, at
the Wiesenthal Museum of Tolerance in Los Angeles. No words
recurred more than ``universal,'' ``pluralism,'' ``code of
ethics.'' World leaders and institutions had to pursue a
``spiritual agenda'' alongside the political and economic ones;
humankind needed a universal morality developed on the basis of a
genuine pluralism.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Taylor was yet another contrast. On Monday evening, this
Canadian scholar of Hegel and exacting analyst of modern identity
in the magisterial work ``Sources of the Self'' (Harvard University
Press, 1989), was lecturing on ``Democracy and Exclusion'' to a
crowded auditorium at the New School for Social Research.
</P>
<P>
   Where Hassan had spilled his ideas out in a cascade, Taylor
unwrapped his carefully, step by step. Why, he asked, had the last
two centuries of expanding democracy also been an era of
unprecedented ethnic cleansing?
</P>
<P>
   He cautioned against the complacent assumption that such conduct
was merely atavistic ``tribalism,'' destined to disappear with the
progress of modernity. Exclusion, in one form or another, is also
the child of popular sovereignty, he said: democracy, no less than
authoritarian regimes, poses the question, Who is this ``we'' of
``we the people,'' and modern conditions make it increasingly
unlikely that minorities will even allow themselves to be
assimilated into the ``we'' of the majority. The problem, he said,
is not going away but has somehow to be accommodated.
</P>
<P>
   Were these three events anything more than fascinating but
unconnected moments in an overheated New York schedule?
</P>
<P>
   Was it fanciful to think that they had suddenly lit up a window
into the global web of people and projects, thinking, talking,
organizing, that keep a deeply divided humanity from tearing itself
apart, that might even, someday, stitch by stitch, bind it
together?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
