s f BC-BIZ-MEGA-YACHTS-$ADV1     11-12 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-MEGA-YACHTS-$ADV14-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GROWING MARKET FOR MANSIONS OF THE SEA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Fla.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 14) 
(af) 
 By JULIE FLAHERTY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   She prepared for the Fort Lauderdale International Boat Show two
weeks ago, where a half-billion dollars would change hands over the
next four days, Mike Kelsey Sr., a 40-year veteran of the
boat-building industry, repeated his prayer of gratitude: ``Thank
God there are rich people who love the water and will pay us to do
what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelsey's company, Palmer Johnson of Sturgeon Bay, Wis., builds
very big yachts for very wealthy people _ but not the types of
heirs and oil tycoons he might have catered to 20 years ago.
Instead, he is blessed with a new clientele of self-made Americans
who are as competitive with their toys as they are with their
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   They are people like Lawrence J. Ellison, the chief executive of
the Oracle Corp., whose flotilla includes the 240-foot-long Katana.
Or Craig O. McCaw, the cellular telephone pioneer who owns the
193-foot Calixe and is scheduled to take delivery of a
300-plus-foot yacht by the end of the year. (People in the industry
disagree over just how long it will be.) But that might still put
him behind Leslie H. Wexner, founder of the Limited. His yacht, the
Limitless, delivered in 1997, is the largest American-owned
pleasure vessel afloat, at 315 feet, according to Boat
International USA magazine.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the Forbes family's Highlander turned heads when
it was completed in 1986 at a mere 150 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the latest boats depends not only on size but also
on furnishings, engines, electronics and special features. Kelsey
said his company had just built a 195-foot boat for $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, the number of superyachts _ vaguely
defined as 80 feet or longer _ has doubled worldwide, to more than
5,000 from about 2,700, Kelsey said. And in an industry once
dominated by European craftsmen and Middle Eastern buyers, the
number of Americans building and buying these boats has grown.
</P>
<P>
   Kay Pierson, producer of the boat show and a former president of
the Superyacht Society, based in Fort Lauderdale, estimates that
American shipbuilders now supply more than 45 percent of
superyachts, up from less than 10 percent a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, most buyers were from other countries, said Diane M.
Byrne, editor of Power and Motoryacht magazine, but now ``the
majority of people buying superyachts are Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's shoppers _ they are almost always men _ are eager.
``Today there is a thought process of, `I worked hard, I made the
money and I'm going to enjoy it,''' Pierson said.
</P>
<P>
   But the buyers do want to keep close watch on how their money is
being spent. While many still turn to the Europeans for their
ships, one person in the clothing industry chose an American firm,
Broward Marine in Fort Lauderdale, so he could keep his nose in the
blueprints.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a moment's notice we could have hands-on control of the
construction process,'' the owner said in a telephone interview
from Maui, his current port of call. ``That actually was 50 percent
of the fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The owner asked to be identified only by the name of his $8
million ship, the Varsity Jacket, in keeping with the traditional
coyness of this industry and its customers.
</P>
<P>
   Yachting publications, like Boat International USA, refer to
owners in genteel, indirect ways: ``Meduse is owned by the former
partner of the world's richest man'' or ``Princess Marla's new
owners are the founders of the Home Shopping Network.''
</P>
<P>
   Meduse has its own Web site that boasts about the boat's
200-foot length, its recording studio and its helicopter that can
seat eight (www.meduse.com). The Microsoft Internet Explorer
advertisement at the bottom of the boat's home page hints at the
common industry knowledge that the owner is Paul G. Allen,
co-founder of Microsoft. (For that matter, www.mylimitless.com
carries neither clothing advertisements nor a mention of Wexner,
but it does include figures like 22,000, the boat's horsepower.)
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, the propriety of the yachting world is giving
way. ``Now, it's sort of a contest,'' said Jill Bobrow, editor of
Boat International USA. ``How much marble can they dazzle with?''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she said, ``they have to keep things high
tech.'' The latest boats are adorned with so many Jet Skis,
helicopters and submersible vehicles that they are called the sport
utility vehicles of yachts.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, ``The New New Thing'' (W.W. Norton, 2000), about
James H. Clark, the Netscape Communications chairman, Michael Lewis
built his story around Hyperion, Clark's high-technology sloop that
is so wired that it could be sailed remotely.
</P>
<P>
   Clark openly sought to have the world's tallest yacht mast, with
the caveat that it fit under the Golden Gate Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Barb Tierney, vice president of the Florida Yacht Brokers
Association, said half of the world's superyachts are bought and
sold in Fort Lauderdale, making it a bustling center for the trade.
There are companies that find and hire crews, repair and renovate
boats and supply all the extras, like lapis lazuli bathtubs. Ms.
Tierney has arranged the sale of boats that range in price from
$500,000 to $42 million.
</P>
<P>
   Because the new yachts are too big for some marinas, having a
tender _ a helicopter or a smaller boat _ on board can be essential
for reaching shore. Zodiac of North America Inc., which makes most
of the rigid inflatable boats used by the United States military,
was initially reluctant to latch on to the superyacht business.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I said, `How many of these boats can there be?'''
said J.J. Marie, Zodiac's president. But superyacht tenders costing
$25,000 to $250,000 apiece _ some come with inflatable toilets _
now make up 30 percent of the company's sales volume.
</P>
<P>
   Financing the yachts has become easier. At least one bank offers
loans with annual payments _ a plan that appeals to executives who
receive yearly bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   But the sales price is far from the entire cost of owning a
yacht. The upkeep on a $10 million yacht runs about $1 million a
year.
</P>
<P>
   The superyachts are cutting such a wide, deep swath that they
are beginning to alter the seascape. Some popular marinas, like the
site of next year's America's Cup Race in Auckland, New Zealand,
are accommodating them by dredging and installing new equipment, to
become what are known in the trade as superports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8154 &Cx1f; tta-z
u e BC-POKEMON-FAD-ART-2TAKE     11-12 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POKEMON-FAD-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POKEMON CRAZE: A LITTLE LUCK, A LOT OF MARKETING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 18 and 19 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Anthony Ruiz was celebrating his 8th birthday at the
Cineplex Beverly Center, joining the hundreds of children and
parents taking in ``Pokemon: The First Movie'' on four screens at
the center, one of 3,000 theaters that presented the animated film
on Wednesday and haven't had a quiet moment since.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute feature earned $10.l million on its opening day, a
school day, the largest Wednesday opening of any animated film
ever, and the biggest Wednesday opening for any film in Warner
Bros. history. On Thursday, it made another $9 million. By the end
of the weekend, its earnings are expected to exceed $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby toyshops sported prominent Pokemon displays; kids
clutched their precious Pokemon figurines, some wore Pokemon
T-shirts. No doubt, some had Pokemon videogames in their knapsacks.
Ruiz struggled to explain what all the fuss was about. ``It has
these characters,'' he said. ``They come from a different world.
People collect them and they have these different battles.''
Finally, he gave up. ``It's just cool,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pokemon craze can seem impenetrable to those _ adults, for
instance _ who are not conversant with its intricate fantasy world.
Even those who are promoting the phenomenon, and reaping the
astonishing rewards, are a little stunned by how deftly it has
attached itself to the hearts of millions of American children,
especially boys between the ages of 5 and 12.
</P>
<P>
   But while luck certainly played a role, Pokemon is also the
result of a very calculated series of creative and marketing
decisions aimed at learning the lessons of previous toy crazes like
Beanie Babies, Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles and Power Rangers, and
using those lessons to build something that will not only resonate
with children but survive longer than the 18 months to three years
that these crazes normally last.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a considerable amount of attention into that,'' said
Gail Tilden, vice president for product-acquisition development at
Nintendo and the queen of all things Pokemon, and responsible for
shepherding the Pokemon brand through its many American
manifestations.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tilden is responsible for making sure that all the Pokemon
products adhere to the basic story line behind the series, that
none of the products are marketed to preschoolers or toddlers
(because if babies play with it, older children will want nothing
to do with it), and that Pokemon characters are attached to
compatible toys (a water-related Pokemon on a water toy, for
instance). She also monitors the rolling out of new Pokemon
characters, which is done in a way intended to stimulate the
collecting side of the craze _ not so few characters that they are
too easily collected, nor so many that collecting them all, the
goal of all true Pokemoners, seems unrealizable. ``We are trying to
mirror the property very well, not just put the Pokemon theme on
anything,'' Ms. Tilden said.
</P>
<P>
   For those unacquainted with Pokemon, it is a series of products
that revolve around a fantasy world created by Japanese animators
and game creators in which there are two kinds of creatures, humans
and Pokemon. The latter are more than 150 animal-like creatures
(three new ones are introduced in the new film, bringing the total
to 154), each with its own personality and powers and the ability
to transform into yet other creatures. The hero of the story, Ash,
yearns to be a master Pokemon trainer, and to do so he vows to
capture all 150-plus Pokemons (''Gotta Catch `Em All'' is the
Pokemon tag line and the anthem of all Pokemon enthusiasts).
</P>
<P>
   Children can imitate Ash and try to capture Pokemon, as well,
either in the videogame or by buying their plastic figures or
trading cards. And there are dozens of related consumer items from
clothes to toothbrushes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult for any franchise to come into prominence
in the kid world, to be forefront in their minds,'' said Gene Del
Vecchio, the author of ``Creating Ever Cool: A Marketer's Guide to
the Kid's Heart'' and the head of CoolWorks, a consulting company
that helps companies invent and build brands for children. ``There
are thousands and thousands of competitors for that honored slot.
Even more difficult is trying to keep within a kid consciousness
for more than the 18 months or three years these things normally
last. How do you create a mechanism whereby you can reinvent
yourself?''
</P>
<P>
   Many children's marketing experts said that the shrewd design of
the Pokemon empire _ its perfectly pitched emotional story line,
the way it stimulates social interaction, the sense of power and
belonging it gives children _ give it a good chance to avoid
craze-burnout. Others were not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really something amazing that has occurred,'' said
Steveanne Auerbach, who goes by the name Dr. Toy and reviews toys
and children's products from her Internet site, www.drtoy.com.
``But I expect Pokemon will have the normal life span of these
sorts of things. It's here until the next wave comes along.''
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon _ which began life in the United States in September
1998 as a Nintendo videogame and quickly expanded into bean-bag
toys, action figures, comic books, T-shirts and a cartoon show _
looked as if it had reached fever pitch last spring with the
release of Pokemon collectible cards that became the currency of
choice on thousands of American playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that was just a warm-up.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of a new fall season of Pokemon cartoons on the
WB Network, which runs the program 11 times a week; the
staggeringly successful release of the Pokemon movie, and a
concurrent marketing tie-in at 8,000 Burger King restaurants has
succeeded in catapulting the Japanese-born phenomenon to new
heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got home from taking five kids to the Pokemon movie and
to Burger King,'' said Lynn Rosenblum, president of Toy Power
Consulting. ``When you look at it from a marketing and a branding
perspective, it's brilliant. It covers television, it covers video,
it covers things on your computer, there's the cards, there's the
toys, there are art contests. It's really one of the products that
has done the best job of covering all those bases.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When Pokemon was initially rolled out in Japan, beginning with
the introduction of the videogame in 1996, it was a much slower
process. The first Pokemon movie did not open in Japan until the
summer of 1998, two years after the videogame debuted and the
second film (yes, there is already a second, and it is to open in
the United States next summer) opened in Japan just three months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we were ready to import Pokemon into the United
States, all of these products were available to us,'' Ms. Tilden
said. Marketers thus could capitalize more quickly on hot moments
in the craze.
</P>
<P>
   What often happens, in cases of toy lines like Ninja Turtles,
for instance, is that by the time it becomes clear that the concept
has clicked with children, it is too late to get a movie in
production and into theaters before the craze has begun to cool.
Movies are expensive and take a long time to make, and crazes
sometimes disappear in a blink. With Pokemon, everything was ready
and could be launched whenever marketers deemed the time was right.
</P>
<P>
   So while it may look like luck that Warner Bros. has a Pokemon
movie coming out at just the moment when the fever is at its
height, it is anything but, said Brad Ball, president of domestic
theatrical marketing for Warner Bros. Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We counseled very closely with our partners, using their
insights on how they saw the new season television episodes
impacting, and we decided that the new episodes would further raise
demand for Pokemon. So ... we decided to release the movie
following the launch of the new television season but still ahead
of the competition in a very competitive environment,'' Ball said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The toughest competition appears to be Disney's ``Toy Story 2,''
which is set for release on Nov. 24, giving Pokemon two weeks in
theaters before Buzz Lightyear returns. ``Then, we can turn the
corner into the new year and have our video division ready for a
spring release,'' Ball said.
</P>
<P>
   After that, probably in the fall of next year, there will be an
entirely new Pokemon series. The current story line, known for the
red-and-blue game cartridges, will be followed by a gold-and-silver
story line, Ms. Tilden said. It, too, will star Ash, but he will
embark on an entirely new adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the former Pokemon creatures will return, others will
have mutated and there will be new ones, too (Ms. Tilden won't say
how many, beyond ``dozens''). In the first story, the Pokemon
seemed to be of indeterminate gender. In the new one, the issue of
gender will be addressed, with some creatures having definite male
and female characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are doing is extending the fantasy,'' Ms. Tilden said.
``It's the same world, but a new story. You will be able to find
out if the one you have is a boy or a girl.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two things that a children's brand needs, Del Vecchio
said: It has to ``touch timeless emotional needs within the
child,'' and it needs a ``mechanism that would allow it to stay
fresh'' and not go the way of the Power Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Barbie did was nail the whole notion of achievement for
little girls,'' Del Vecchio said. ``Pokemon was constructed to
touch several timeless emotional needs. Part of its power comes
from the story line of good vanquishing evil, where the child
becomes part of the story and is empowered to capture his own
monsters, train them and have them fight for him. It also
stimulates the desire to collect them all, but it's competitive in
a way that helps inspire social interaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon has its own story line (as did Power Rangers and Ninja
Turtles), but it also taps into the notion of collecting that
sustained the Beanie Babies craze. While Power Rangers had the
story line without the collecting and Beanie Babies had the
collecting without the story line, Pokemon has both. All of this
augurs well for the future, Del Vecchio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principles they are applying indicate it will last longer
than the average kid franchise,'' he said. ``Whether it will last
30 years will depend on other factors, like how good they are going
to be as marketers and what other franchises may be introduced that
will do an even better job. You know, kids are fickle. They will
get tired of these kinds of properties and dash off to the next
one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
