<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCAS BACK ON FAMILIAR GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Pete Carroll let Ray Lucas get away once. It cost
him a versatile fringe player. If he allows the same thing to
happen Monday, it will cost him something even more dear: a
division game.
</P>
<P>
   When Lucas arrives at Foxboro Stadium as the starting
quarterback for the New York Jets for this prime-time meeting with
the Patriots, he won't need directions.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, was his address for a year _ the Patriots'
Super Bowl season of 1996, when he was Bill Parcells's pet project.
A prolific quarterback at Rutgers, Lucas spent 15 weeks on the New
England practice squad, then was activated for the final two games
and the playoffs. Parcells made no secret that he wanted him around
_ someplace. Because of his superior athleticism, the
6-foot-3-inch, 214-pound Lucas did a little of this and a little of
that. Scout team quarterback. Spare wide receiver. Special teams
commando. And in a pinch, he could have been utilized at defensive
back. Parcells tried him at just about everything, it seemed,
except redecorating the coach's office.
</P>
<P>
   And he probably wasn't given that job only because Parcells
vacated it almost as soon as the Super Bowl loss to the Green Bay
Packers was history, heading to the New York Jets with the de facto
title of Master of All He Surveys.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement, Carroll, wasn't as enamored of Lucas, who wound
up rejoining Parcells after being cut in training camp in 1997.
Carroll had nothing personal against Lucas, even if he had been a
Parcells favorite, and the new coach eventually heard enough of his
sainted predecessor's name to wake up screaming it in horror in the
middle of the night. No, this was simply an honest miscalculation,
Carroll recalled Friday with regretful hindsight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made an error, a big mistake,'' said Carroll, who
essentially limited Lucas to wide receiver and special teams work.
``I didn't take into account that he could be starting quarterback
material. We missed that one.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no need for excessive self-flagellation. Lucas is the
Jets' starter basically by default. Vinny Testaverde, Parcells's
1998 Pro Bowl reclamation project, had his Achilles' tendon and the
Jets' playoff hopes shredded by the Meadowlands macadam in a
season-opening 30-28 loss to the Patriots. And the only other
alternative is the thoroughly uninspiring Rick Mirer. So Lucas _
who has started one game, a 16-13 loss to the Indianapolis Colts
Oct. 17 in which he completed 16 of 29 passes for 137 yards and a
touchdown before throwing a killing interception and spraining his
ankle _ is getting another chance because . . . well, why not? It's
not as if the Jets, now a gaudy 2-6, have much to risk.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the Patriots, who boast a 6-2 record after having
been off for the last year and a half _ actually, it only seems
that way to Carroll and the players; their bye week hiatus will end
at 14 days Monday _ have much at stake against their AFC East
rivals. And Carroll remembers enough about Lucas to realize he can
wreak havoc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely have to take into account the option,'' said the
coach. ``We're taking time on the practice field to prepare for
other things they can do. If Ray wasn't in there, they probably
wouldn't be running the option. When we blitz, we have to get him.
We have to keep him crowded. If we miss and he finds the seam in
the D-line, he's got a lot of open space.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, this message has been tattooed on the Patriot
defenders' psyches, and they are duly wary. Some even can see
conspiracy theories in Parcells's game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's something fishy about this,'' said defensive
tackle Chad Eaton. ``I think they'll pull something out of the hat
_ going for it on fourth down or faking a punt with (Tom) Tupa
(another ex-Patriot who doubles as a quarterback). And their punter
is also their holder on field goals . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Those with less suspicious minds are taking Lucas at face value
_ as a double migraine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know you have to cover your receiver a lot longer,'' said
cornerback Ty Law. ``You have to be ready to play street ball. When
he starts scrambling, fundamentals go out the window.''
</P>
<P>
   The secret is not to let Lucas get out of touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a quarterback that can run the ball,'' said defensive
tackle Henry Thomas, ``you have to be ready for his speed. There's
a lot of different things he does.''
</P>
<P>
   While his former colleagues are leery of Lucas, they also
applaud him for sticking with his dream. ``He was always a
quarterback at heart,'' said Law. ``He enjoyed that more than
anything. He played wide receiver because he had to, and he did a
good job at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tedy Bruschi particularly admires Lucas's resolve; Bruschi
arrived in New England the same year in a similar situation _
having played one position in college (down lineman at Arizona) and
being converted to another (linebacker).
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on the same path here,'' said Bruschi. ``Now we're
doing what we were groomed to do and playing against each other.
It's very exciting, if you ask me. It's nice to see him get a
chance like this.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as he doesn't make too much of it at Carroll's expense
again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five-time Pro Bowl linebacker Andre Tippett will be inducted
into the Patriots Hall of Fame during pregame ceremonies. Tippett
will be honored in conjunction with alumni weekend. At halftime,
other Patriots of yore will be saluted as part of the team's 40th
anniversary . . . Wide receiver Troy Brown is expected to suit up
after missing three games with a sprained ankle, but Carroll hasn't
determined whether he will resume his regular punt return duties .
. . Quarterback Michael Bishop has attracted a great deal of
interest from NFL Europe. ``Teams are calling all the time,'' said
Carroll. But it's uncertain whether Bishop will be asked to go or
will agree to go. ``We'll see how things are at the end of the
season,'' said Carroll. ``We can't make him get on the plane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
