<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS WRAP UP CASE AGAINST JASPER SUSPECT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
and RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The Jasper County Courthouse clock chimed 3
o'clock Friday, breaking the eerie quiet inside as prosecutors
wrapped up their capital murder case against Shawn Berry with a
silent video retracing the trail of James Byrd Jr.'s gruesome
dragging death.
</P>
<P>
   But the drama of Berry's trial so far hardly compares with those
of his two co-defendants, white supremacists Bill King and Russell
Brewer, who were convicted earlier this year and sentenced to death
by injection.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they have here is a murder looking for a motive as far as
Shawn Berry is concerned,'' said defense attorney Joseph C. ``Lum''
Hawthorn. ``He's not a racist. He's not a hateful person. They're
searching around trying to figure out, how are they going to
explain to this jury that he's guilty of this?
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury is gonna want to know,'' he added, ``why in the world
would somebody do something like this, something as horrific as
this, without a motive?``
</P>
<P>
   But Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray said he's
confident that the jury paid attention and will be able to follow
the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his truck. He's there. I believe there's substantial
evidence he was driving the truck,'' Gray said. ``And he's got
blood on him.``
</P>
<P>
   Berry, a 24-year-old local movie theater manager, is expected to
testify sometime next week, and Hawthorn said he plans to bring in
a blood expert to explain how several small spots of Byrd's blood
ended up on Berry's jeans, shirt and boots if he didn't help the
other two kill Byrd early on June 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But if Berry takes the stand, prosecutors will force him to try
to reconcile seven sometimes conflicting statements he gave to
police, as well as statements he made during a television interview
with CBS anchor Dan Rather, aired on ``60 Minutes II'' in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that even if Berry changes his mind and chooses
not to testify, they have already shown not just that Berry was
present at the crime scene, which he admits, but also that he
participated as Byrd was beaten, stripped and chained by the ankles
to Berry's pickup.
</P>
<P>
   They also insist that footprint evidence on a rural road east of
Jasper indicates Berry drove the truck that dragged Byrd for more
than two miles as he fought to keep his head off the pavement,
grinding his elbows and knees to the bone in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's misery ended when his head slammed into a concrete
culvert, decapitating him. The next morning, a local man discovered
his mangled corpse in the middle of Huff Creek Road, outside a
black cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   The hideous nature of the racist crime shocked the nation and
prompted armed black activists and the Ku Klux Klan to march on the
East Texas town of 8,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the first trial last February, every day brought new,
incredible information about defendant Bill King. Jurors were shown
color blowups of the ex-con and Klansman's racist tattoos,
including one depicting a black man hanging from a tree. They read
numerous letters and other documents written by the 25-year-old
King, whom prosecutors portrayed as a violent racist who spent his
time in prison dreaming of returning home to Jasper to start his
own hate group.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Berry, they were told, may have been his first recruit,
and Byrd's killing, his initiation rite. Yet in Berry's trial, the
all-white jury has been told nothing of that theory.
</P>
<P>
   In King's trial, as well as in Brewer's earlier this fall,
prosecutors made a point of pulling the murder weapon, a 24-foot
logging chain, across the courtroom and allowing it to fall loudly
onto the floor. They carefully choreographed their witnesses to
build to a climax, the silent 11-minute video showing the dragging
marks.
</P>
<P>
   In Berry's trial, Hawthorn stole that thunder before noon on the
first day, jumping in early on cross-examination to introduce the
chain and videotape himself.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses also seemed more mechanical in their testimony this
week, as if they were tired of repeating the same evidence for the
third time.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have said all along that Berry's case would be
harder to prove than the other two because he did not have a
reputation as a racist and did not have the criminal background of
King or the 32-year-old Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is much more like a soap opera,'' Gray said. ``It's
more about who do you believe.``
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors insist jurors will see through Berry's story, which
witnesses have testified changed every time he was confronted with
new evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think that anyone could do to any human being that kind of
thing is just unbelievable,'' said Byrd's sister, Betty Boatner,
who left the courtroom along with another sister, Stella Brumley,
as the pathologist took the witness stand to testify about Byrd's
autopsy. ``And to sit there, like there is no shame in his game, I
just don't understand.``
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse later, another of Byrd's sisters, Mylinda
Washington, said the family was pleased with the case prosecutors
made against Berry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel strongly in the prosecution's case and we have
confidence in the judicial system,'' she said. ``Hopefully we'll be
pleased with the outcome.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
