<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FAT-LABELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA PLANS TO REQUIRE FOOD LABELS TO PROVIDE INFORMATION ON TRANS
FATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Faced with mounting evidence that a type of fat
often found in margarine and baked goods raises the risk of heart
disease, the Food and Drug Administration announced plans Friday to
require food manufacturers to include specific information about
these fats on nutrition labels.
</P>
<P>
   The regulation covering the fats, called trans fatty acids or
just trans fats, would be the first significant change in food
labels since the FDA began requiring them in 1993. Nutrition
experts say it is important because trans fats, which are liquid
fats that have been turned into solids, are even more unhealthy
than saturated fats. Yet consumers have no way of knowing which
products contain them.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in time there is unanimity that trans fats are a
problem,'' said Dr. Walter Willett, chairman of the nutrition
department at the Harvard School of Public Health. ``We sometimes
refer to them as a stealth fat because you eat them and they are
not on the label.''
</P>
<P>
   The label changes will not take effect right away. The FDA
intends to publish the proposal in the Federal Register next
Wednesday, and the public will have 90 days after that to comment
on it. It could be as long as a year from now before a final rule
is published, and two years after that before consumers see any
changes, said Joseph A. Levitt, director of the agency's Center for
Food Safety and Applied Nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   Food industry representatives said they would not fight the
rule. But they are likely to raise objections to its details,
particularly a provision that would set limits on the health claims
manufacturers can make about products containing trans fatty acids.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rhona Appelbaum, chief scientist for the National Food
Processors Association, a trade group, called the rule premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have liked to see the science evolve further.'' she
said, adding, ``We are still looking at this proposed rule very
closely, making sure that it is truthful, useful and above all,
understandable for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Trans fats are produced artificially, through a process called
partial hydrogenation that is used to convert liquid vegetable oils
into solid fats that are often used to make margarine, shortening,
baked goods and fast-food french fries. Trans fats are chemically
different from saturated fats, which also raise the risk of heart
disease, and have not been included in saturated fat content on the
nutrition label.
</P>
<P>
   But once in the body, trans fats behave like artery-clogging
saturated fats, increasing LDL, or ``bad'' cholesterol. In
addition, Willett said, trans fats lower HDL, or ''good''
cholesterol. He said the evidence against trans fat had been
building for a decade and had become particularly strong in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement announcing the proposed rule, Dr. Jane E. Henney,
commissioner of food and drugs, called nutrition labels ``a
powerful tool for consumers,'' and added, ``By requiring this
information about trans fatty acids, this proposal should assist
individuals in their efforts to reduct their risk of coronary heart
disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed rule, products containing trans fats would
carry an asterisk or some other mark on the line for saturated
fats, directing consumers to a footnote about trans fats. The
footnote would be optional on foods that contain less than half a
gram of trans fat per serving.
</P>
<P>
   With respect to health claims, for instance, the rule would
require that foods advertised as low in saturated fat be virtually
free of saturated fat, containing no more than a half gram per
serving. Claims about low cholesterol would be permitted only on
food containing less than two grams or less of trans fat and
saturated fat combined.
</P>
<P>
   And there would be a new ``trans fat free'' claim, for foods
containing less than half a gram of trans fat and a half gram of
saturated fat per serving.
</P>
<P>
   Defining these health claims is just as important as providing
information on the nutrition labels, said Dr. Margo Wootan, a
senior scientist for the Center for Science in the Public Interest,
a consumer advocacy group in Washington. In 1994, the center
petitioned the food and drug agency to require disclosure of trans
fat content; Friday's announcement came in response to that
petition.
</P>
<P>
   ``A label of stick margarine boasts that it contains 70 percent
less saturated fat than butter,'' said Dr. Wootan. ``But the
additional three grams of trans fat hidden in each serving means it
doesn't do 70 percent less damage to your arteries.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Dr. Wootan and Willett, of Harvard, said they hoped the
proposal would spur food manufacturers to shy away from using trans
fats in their products. Margarine manufacturers have already begun
to make those changes, using new processing methods that eliminate
the fats, according to Richard Cristol, president of the National
Association of Margarine Manufacturers, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Cristol said manufacturers were anxious to post margarine's
trans fat content on nutrition labels, because they think consumers
will be surprised. He said 30 percent of margarines on the market
are made without trans fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of feel we deserve a little bit of a pat on the
back,'' he said. ``We have made tremendous progress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
