<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8162 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-PRAY-WORK13-COX     11-12 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAY-WORK13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Somalis consider suit against company that barred prayer breaks
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Kurylo
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Anab Aden is a devout Muslim from Somalia who prays
five times a day, a religious obligation she never misses.
</P>
<P>
   So when her boss told her she couldn't pray at work, she was
stunned. When the boss suggested that she pray in the bathroom, she
was so offended she quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came and suggested to us, `How about praying in the
bathroom?' The next day, we walked out,'' Aden said in Somali
through an interpreter. ``That's religious discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Aden is one of 33 Somalis from Clarkston who quit their jobs at
Solectron in Suwanee, where they worked in assembly-line jobs
making cellular phones. They had worked at Solectron from one to
six months, and in the beginning they were allowed to take two
5-minute prayer breaks each day.
</P>
<P>
   Muslims pray at certain times of the day. One of the times
coincides with sunset, when the Somalis were at work. When they
pray, Muslims have to find a clean area, remove their shoes and
face Mecca. Some Muslims put prayer rugs on the floor. At various
points during the prayer, Muslims bow, kneel and put their face on
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The prayers, which are said in Arabic, last about three minutes.
But at work, it takes about five minutes counting the time it takes
to get to a prayer area and wash their hands if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslim workers would leave the assembly line individually
and cover for each other so the work got done. But when a new boss
started, ``everything changed,'' Aden said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came to watch us work and she didn't understand why some
of us would leave for a few minutes,'' said Aden, 25, who has lived
in Atlanta five months. Shortly after the boss found out they were
going to a conference room to pray, the Somalis were told that it
had to stop. Eventually, they said, the conference room was locked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told that we could not leave the line unless we had to
go to the bathroom,'' Aden said. The assembly line workers got one
10-minute break and a 30-minute lunch break, but at times that
didn't coincide with prayer times.
</P>
<P>
   For three weeks, the Somalis tried to negotiate a settlement
that would allow them to pray during work. They offered to subtract
the prayer time, about 10 minutes, from their 30-minute lunch
break. They told the company that it could deduct the prayer time
from their paychecks. The company rejected both proposals, Aden
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Somalis said management never complained about their work.
``Each line has to make 500 phones every day and we made more than
that, not less,'' said Deqa Mohamed, 21. ``They said our work was
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Mohamed also said the Muslims were angered and offended when
management told them they could pray in the bathroom. ``We left
when they said if you want to pray in the bathroom, go ahead,''
said Mohamed, who has lived in Atlanta six years and speaks
English.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement from corporate headquarters in Milpitas, Ca.,
Solectron acknowledges it was asked to address ``unique religious
needs of one particular group of associates.'' The company denied
it told the Somalis to pray in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it ``took their concerns and requirements very
seriously and actively addressed them to look for ways to
accommodate them while maintaining all commitments to all our
constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   Solectron said the prayer break is an issue only for some
Somalis on the second shift, from 3 p.m. to 11 p.m., because one of
the prayer times occurs at sunset.
</P>
<P>
   ``We offered a change in hours to a different shift as an
alternative,'' Solectron said, adding that it provided areas for
prayer and offered to adjust the break periods to accommodate its
Muslim workers. Solectron acknowledged that ``flexibility was
offered'' for ``a brief period of time'' and that ``when normal
production resumed ... scheduled break times were necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Aden and Mohamed said the group was offered third-shift jobs,
during which no prayer breaks would be necessary. At least three
accepted the offer because they support large families and need the
money.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the head of Solectron in California, S. Eric
Shakir, civil rights coordinator for the Council of
American-Islamic Relations in Washington, said the Somalis are
prepared to file a charge of religious discrimination with the
Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Shakir said CAIR handled 600 work place discrimination
complaints last year, 100 of which had to do with prayer breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's generally a misunderstanding or ignorance'' when it
happens, he said. ``In one case in Minnesota, we had Muslims who
were being told to go outside to pray in the cold. When we wrote a
letter to them, the CEO immediately provided a space for them to
pray inside.''
</P>
<P>
   About 5,000 Somalis live in metro Atlanta, according to the
Somali Refugee Family Foundation, a nonprofit agency in Clarkston
that helps Somalis find jobs. Islam is a fast-growing religion in
the United States, which is home to about 5 million Muslims. With
at least 12 mosques, Atlanta's Muslim population is booming as
well. An estimated 50,000 Muslims practice their faith in
communities from Fayetteville to Lawrenceville.
</P>
<P>
   Mohamed, who lives in Norcross, got a new job in the jewelry
department at a Kmart in Buford and says she can take prayer breaks
whenever she needs to. ``I get two 15-minute breaks a day and I can
take my break whenever I want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali Liban Sanyare, 36, found a new job at Hertz car rentals in
Clarkston and said his new boss has gone out of his way to
accommodate his need to pray. ``He gave me a special place where I
can pray.''
</P>
<P>
   But Aden and most of the other Somalis have not yet found new
jobs. And they worry about how to meet their financial obligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to do anything we have to, to pray,'' Aden said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
