<HEADER>
A8163 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-FIGHT-COMMENT-BOS     11-12 1369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FIGHT-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CAUTIOUS VETERAN VS. A GALLANT WARRIOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Evander Holyfield may be facing his last fight while
Lennox Lewis may be facing his last chance.
</P>
<P>
   For the 37-year-old Holyfield, Saturday night's heavyweight
unification fight is a last grasp at greatness, a final attempt to
convince boxing skeptics that he is what he has so often shown
himself to be _ the finest heavyweight of his time.
</P>
<P>
   To defeat Lewis and add the World Boxing Council title belt to
the International Boxing Federation and World Boxing Association
ones he will wear into the ring would mean Holyfield had beaten
every great or near-great heavyweight and cruiserweight of his era.
Mike Tyson, Riddick Bowe, Michael Moorer, Dwight Muhammad Qawi,
Buster Douglas, Lewis, and a wide assortment of lesser lights all
would have fallen to him. Not one of Holyfield's peers can even
claim to have fought such competition, let alone triumphed over
each one.
</P>
<P>
   But if he loses, as many are predicting, what will it mean? Will
it tarnish all he has accomplished in becoming a three-time
heavyweight champion? Will it cause some to rewrite his history?
</P>
<P>
   If it does, it would be the final indignity Holyfield is forced
to suffer in a long and decorated career in which he has heard
repeatedly that he was too small, too old, or, as some say is the
case, too small and too old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who else has done what he's done?'' asked Don Turner,
Holyfield's trainer and a boxing man dating back to the days when
he watched Ezzard Charles train in Cincinnati before anyone knew
how great Charles was. ``Who else has fought every one? What more
does he have to do?''
</P>
<P>
   For some, beat Lewis. But if Holyfield doesn't, it will be the
unyielding calender that has beaten him, not the towering Brit.
Holyfield is a veteran of 40 wars that have left him 36-3-1 and
with less bounce in his legs than he once had.
</P>
<P>
   A 37-year-old fighter is a senior citizen, only two of whom have
ever won the heavyweight title at such an advanced age. If
Holyfield can become the third, he will have added one last
accomplishment to a remarkable collection of unexpected
achievements and cemented his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   But what of Lewis? What does the strapping Brit have at stake?
</P>
<P>
   Only everything. Only his legacy. Only his past and his future.
</P>
<P>
   If the 34-year-old Lewis cannot find a way to destroy Holyfield,
he will be forever dismissed as a figment of England's imagination.
Twice he has won the WBC title, but neither time was there a
champion available for him to beat to do it. His biggest wins have
come over the likes of Razor Ruddock, Frank Bruno, and Ray Mercer,
legitimate heavyweights but second-class citizens when measured
against Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, when Lewis appeared to have his moment come last March in
New York, he chose not to seize it, opting instead to try and coast
to a safe victory rather than gamble on greatness. What resulted
was a draw that denied him both the unified title and the glory he
sought, an approach Holyfield found quite telling.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is not what you'd call a convenient-type job,''
Holyfield said. ``I have to do what is necessary. The price you
have to pay for that is to take yourself out of the comfort zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people don't want to be uncomfortable. I truly believe
Lennox had the opportunity of a lifetime to be the undisputed
champion. But he didn't take that chance because he said, `I may
get caught.' In life, we all may get caught, but we all have to
take chances to be a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a winner but some people don't have the fortitude. Some
people don't have what's necessary to take chances to be the very
best they can be. Boxing is a replica of what people are. At least
I know the man for what he is.''
</P>
<P>
   What Lewis has appeared to be throughout his career is a
cautious combat veteran, not a warrior. While Holyfield has time
and again rushed into the breech and fired back against long odds
with his fists and his heart, Lewis has shown a willingness to
attack only under the safest of conditions.
</P>
<P>
   This week a European fight guy of long experience who did not
want to be named pointed out that his countryman's most
overpowering victories have all come against non-Americans. He
destroyed the stiff-standing Foul Pole, Andrew Golota, in one
round. He did the same to the Canadian heavyweight Ruddock, rushing
in to blast him out without fear eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But against top Americans such as Holyfield, Mercer, and even
young Shannon Briggs for a time, Lewis has been often tentative and
always unwilling to risk all in exchange for dominance. That
approach has won him two world titles and millions of dollars, but
it has failed to bring him the mantle of greatness he says he
wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like he gets in with the European or British fighters and
says, `I know who you are, I've been where you've been,' and
destroys them but the Americans who come from the historically
proper spawning grounds for great fighters create doubt in his
mind,'' the old British fight guy said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Lewis now concedes he was not bold enough in the first
fight, saying ``I could have done more. I played it safe. I was a
bit too cautious, but Evander can do a lot of damage if you let
him. I didn't want to take any chances and leave myself open.''
</P>
<P>
   All week he has vacillated between boldness and blandness. One
minute he talked of scientific boxing and the aim of hitting but
not being hit. The next he was promising ``fireworks'' in the first
round and a resolve to ``stay in his face.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the best way for Lewis to win is to follow his nature and
avoid Holyfield's baiting. He should use his six-inch reach
advantage (84-78) to jab an old man silly, as he did in the first
fight. With Holyfield's legs no longer the pistons they once were,
Lewis can probably control the night with his jab and a thunderous
right hand behind it, followed by much clinching and pressing down
on the back of Holyfield's head if he manages to get inside on him,
a pattern Lewis followed in the first match.
</P>
<P>
   But although victory and the unified title might well come from
that, glory will not. To achieve more than mere victory, boldness
is required. He who dares, does, and Lewis has never shown an ounce
of that in his 36-fight career except for those few minutes with
Golota and Ruddock, and he has paid dearly for it. Will he choose
to risk all he has in the search for greater glory, or will he seek
the safe route through sport's most dangerous place?
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of public perception, Lennox has paid a big price for
being too laid back,'' concedes Emanuel Steward, his trainer. ``He
doesn't need to change his style to win. He just needs to fight
with more fire.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what Holyfield hopes because while that puts him at the
most risk, it also gives him his one chance at victory. Holyfield
understands that when a fighter goes for broke he has the greatest
chance of being broken himself _ a fact Lewis seems to keep
uppermost in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield has made a proud career of that and it seems likely he
will try it again this one last time. To win he must get inside and
then punch hard and often. He cannot be too bold, but he knows he
must risk all for victory and he is willing to do it. If he can
create a moment of crisis for Lewis, he believes, he can finish him
because it is in such moments that Lewis has looked his worst.
</P>
<P>
   But to do it at his age, there is a need for Lewis to cooperate.
He must come forward himself for Holyfield to find the opening he
needs. Lewis has never done that before, but this week he has at
least talked about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize Evander doesn't have any answers for me,'' Lewis
said. ``I'm going to be right in his face. I think it will be a
good, quick fight. The first round will have a lot of fireworks.
I'm going to go after him and see what he's got.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does, Lennox Lewis will be defying his nature. That may
bring him a great victory or it could bring him what he fears most.
On the road to glory, he may find out an old warrior has some fight
left in him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
