<HEADER>
A8166 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      11-12 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG-SPENDING SOX TO COOL IT DURING FREE-AGENT MART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Red Sox, who finished last season with a payroll in
excess of $72 million, are already committed to nearly $155 million
in guaranteed contracts for the next five years, a total eclipsed
by only three teams: the Diamondbacks, Mets, and Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   So while Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette said recently that
the club will always have the means to consider the top 1 or 2
percent of the players available, citing last year's pursuit of
free agent outfielder Bernie Williams, it is not hard to understand
why CEO John Harrington has indicated the team is unlikely to be
engaged in top-dollar pursuits in this winter's free agent mart.
</P>
<P>
   However, the fact that the Sox probably will not have No. 2
starter Bret Saberhagen until at least midseason, and the rest of
the starting rotation is a list of maybes behind the Martinez
brothers, Pedro and Ramon, makes it highly likely that the Sox will
be looking for veteran pitching help entering spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen's close friend, David Cone, filed for free agency on
Thursday, and the 36-year-old righthander who pitched a perfect
game last summer for the Yankees is an intriguing name to consider,
though his $9.5 million salary in '99 suggests he would be too rich
for the Sox tastes.
</P>
<P>
   A's righthander Omar Olivares and Angels lefthander Chuck Finley
are other top names that figure to draw significant interest, while
the pitcher who ranks as perhaps the top attraction on the list,
Rangers righthander Aaron Sele, isn't entertaining any thoughts of
returning to Boston. The Rangers cleared out big bucks by trading
slugger Juan Gonzalez, and are expected to make a big bid to retain
Sele.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who would also like another productive bat, could take
another run at outfielder Greg Vaughn, whom they talked about
acquiring in a trade from the Padres last season before he was
dealt to the Reds. But again, the Sox are likelier to consider
cheaper alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   A possibility at first base could be David Segui, who opted for
free agency in Toronto and has always been high on Duquette's list,
after playing for the Sox GM in Montreal. Segui would represent a
significant upgrade in defense around the bag, though he would not
be the slugger the Sox ideally would like to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette was still in the Dominican Republic Friday, according
to a club spokesman, but that didn't keep the Sox from making a
minor deal, swapping outfielder Jon Nunnally to the Mets for
outfielder Jermaine Allensworth.
</P>
<P>
   Allensworth, 27, spent most of last season in the minors at
Triple A Norfolk, where he hit. 264 with 5 home runs and 10 stolen
bases in 81 games. He played 40 games as a reserve for the Mets,
batting .209, but came up as a center fielder in 1997 with the
Pirates, which suggests that Duquette could be considering moving
Damon Buford and wants Allensworth as a backup for Darren Lewis.
Like Buford, Allensworth is a righthanded hitter.
</P>
<P>
   In another development, DeMarlo Hale, Baseball America's choice
as Minor League Manager of the Year who threw out a first ball
before a Sox playoff game, reportedly has informed the club that he
plans to look elsewhere for a job after the Sox did not offer him a
promotion from Double A Trenton. The Thunder had the best record in
minor league ball last season, and Hale was offered his job back
for next season. He could still accept, but said he intends to
explore other opportunities in the interim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
