<HEADLINE>
MITCHELL ADJOURNS ULSTER TALKS, URGES PARTIES TO WEIGH CONSEQUENCES
OF FAILURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WARREN HOGE    
 c .1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ With his mission to salvage the
Northern Ireland peace settlement at a crisis point, George J.
Mitchell abruptly adjourned talks Friday morning and urged
negotiators to spend the weekend focusing on ``the gravity of what
is at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort by Mitchell, the American mediator, was shaken
Thursday night by word that the Ulster Unionist leader David
Trimble was unable to gain the support of his party legislators in
a secret ballot on the compromise thrashed out with the rival Sinn
Fein party over the last 10 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Talks, which Mitchell said were at their ``final and most
critical phase,'' are to resume on Monday. Their purpose has been
to end a deadlock over the Ulster Unionists' refusal to admit Sinn
Fein to the Northern Ireland g established by the April 1998 peace
accord before the Irish Republican Army starts disarming. The IRA
views disarmament as surrender, and Sinn Fein, its political
representative, argues that no such condition to take part in
government is in the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The complex formula that Trimble is using to try to break the
impasse involves a series of incremental reciprocal steps by Sinn
Fein and the Ulster Unionists rather than a single dramatic move.
Elements include an IRA statement condemning violence and pledging
not to return to its war against British rule, and the appointment
of a senior IRA official as a go-between to the international
disarmament panel headed by a retired Canadian general, John de
Chastelain.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan does not promise the actual turnover of weapons, an
insistent demand of the increasingly tough-minded Unionists, and
the absence of any such pledge cost it the required support
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   A Unionist spokesman, eager to free the party from the onus of
appearing to be a deal wrecker, said that no final decision had
been made. He explained that the Thursday night vote had merely
been a ``straw poll'' to help Trimble decide whether to put the
matter before the 900-member party council.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitchell review, conducted under a news blackout and on
occasion away from Belfast, has produced a comfort level among
lifelong enemies, establishing heretofore missing elements of trust
and mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
   But Trimble's willingness to deal directly with Sinn Fein has
not pleased many in his party, and whatever effort he makes this
weekend to push for acceptance of the rejected compromise could put
his leadership at risk.
</P>
<P>
   A call for his ouster came not unexpectedly from the Rev. Ian
Paisley, head of the hard-line Democratic Unionists and a fierce
opponent of the peace settlement. He said Trimble was promoting the
admission of ``gangsters and terrorists'' into government.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Adams, president of Sinn Fein, challenged Trimble to gain
his party's backing. ``Success in this process requires that those
in political leadership fulfill their responsibilities and give
leadership,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, in a statement Friday morning, said that ``the past
few days have been very intense and accordingly I have asked the
parties to pause over the weekend and reflect on the magnitude of
the decisions they have to make.'' He acknowledged that his mission
had gone on far longer than he had planned, but that ``given the
gravity of what is at stake, it is appropriate to take the time
necessary to thoroughly and completely consider these important
matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain, in South Africa for a
Commonwealth meeting, said the parties could not afford to let the
opportunity pass with agreement so near. ``We have never come this
far before,'' he said; ``we have never been this close. It is there
within our grasp.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
