<HEADER>
A8174 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ANGELS13-COX     11-12 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGELS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Team salutes fallen Angels
 &HT;    By Bill Osinski
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENSACOLA, Fla. _ For the men who seize the sky, a homecoming
air show was the best way to let go of a tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Angels _ the Navy's ``maximum-speed,
minimum-separation'' flying team _ performed season-ending shows
for what Navy officials projected could be near-record crowds at
Pensacola Naval Air Station, the team's home. More than 40,000
attended Friday, and perhaps double that number are expected today.
</P>
<P>
   The entire performance was a tribute to Lt. Cmdr. Kieron
O'Connor and Lt. Kevin Colling, the team members killed two weeks
ago when their F/A-18 Hornet crashed during a practice flight at
Moody Air Force Base near Valdosta, Ga. The cause of the crash is
under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have given up; we were close enough to the end of the
season to call it quits,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Doug Verissimo, a Blue
Angels pilot. ``But this way, it lets everybody know that we're
back in business.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, people closest to the Blue Angels program strongly
believe the fallen flyers would have wanted it this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go on,'' said Sandy Miller, wife of the Blue
Angels' maintenance crew chief, Lt. Neal Austin. ``The team goes
on; the Navy goes on; the country goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller added, ``This is a sad day in some ways, but it is also a
celebration of Kieron's and Kevin's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first day of the two-day air show, the celebration was a
display of the type of Blue Angels' aerial magic that most people
accept as routine _ until something happens to remind everyone how
dangerous it really is.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels do things in the air that eagles would never dare. At
speeds up to 1,000 mph, they shriek and spin through their drill,
sometimes in incredibly tight formations, sometimes seemingly
flying right at each other, sometimes upside down.
</P>
<P>
   The names of the maneuvers suggest their intricacy: the
Barrel-roll Break, the Tuck-away Cross, the Split-S Reversal, the
Vertical Roll, the Fleur-de-lis. The streaking aircraft move
through formations that suggest starbursts, or corkscrews, or
flower petals.
</P>
<P>
   But they are not stunts. As much as they push the envelope of
what men and flying machines can do, they are also related to
textbook military flying. Also, Blue Angel pilots all come from and
will return to assignments with the Navy Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   While Friday was a difficult day to fly, there are no friendlier
skies for the Blue Angels than the those over Pensacola.
</P>
<P>
   The city's special relationship with the U.S. Navy goes back to
1825, and its status as home base for the Blue Angels goes back to
1950, said Pensacola Mayor John Fogg, a former Marine aviator who
was a Blue Angels pilot in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost as if the people of this community are part of the
extended Navy family,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the recent crash, local officials ordered 20,000
blue-ribbon pins for people to wear as a show of support for the
Blue Angels. They were passed out literally in minutes, he said, as
were a second order.
</P>
<P>
   In Navy circles, Pensacola is affectionately referred to as
``the mother-in-law of Naval Aviation'' because so many young male
Navy flyers find their brides while they're stationed in there, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   These kinds of relationships have flourished to the point where
active and retired federal employees account for about one-third of
the region's economy, Fogg said.
</P>
<P>
   But many Pensacolans especially identify with the Blue Angels,
partly because the Angels are such a unique group of men and women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team's goal is perfection, to fly the most difficult
maneuvers closer and closer,'' Fogg said. ``And when you fly with a
group of people whose lives depend of everybody doing their jobs
right a thousand times out of a thousand, it brings you very close
as people.''
</P>
<P>
   The hundreds of air show spectators wearing Blue Angel support
pins Friday seemed to testify to that bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not military or anything, but we just feel a special
affection for the Blue Angels,'' said Dianne Jones of Pensacola.
``They're such an important part of the community here, and they're
the epitome of Navy aviation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Apke, from Florence, Kent., said the recent accident made
him aware of the thin margin of error that is part of every Angels'
flight. ``They understand that every time they leave the ground,
they might not get back. When I make a mistake at my job, I say,
`I'm sorry,' but these guys ... '' Apke said.
</P>
<P>
   James Ferguson, head of the ROTC program at metro Atlanta's
Southwest DeKalb High School, was one of the leaders of a group of
about 40 student cadets who came to Pensacola for the air show and
to participate in Veterans Day festivities.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hoped that the students take a lesson from the way
the Blue Angels performed in spite of the tragedy: ``You've got to
be able to get back up, after you've been knocked down.''
</P>
<P>
   Fawn Ind, the wife of Angels' pilot Lt. Cmdr. Scott Ind, said
she's been touched by the depth of community support.
</P>
<P>
   On the fence near O'Connor's parking space at the Blue Angels'
headquarters offices, other people have left flowers and poems.
``It's really heart-wrenching to see that the people out in the
community are in almost as much pain as the families of the crew,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
