<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIGEST, WITH FUNDS WATCH AND MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of Microsoft stocks is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 14)  
 (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After-Hours Trading: Managers Aren't Thrilled &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After-hours trading is upon us. But who will be doing the buying
and selling when the NASDAQ market and New York Stock Exchange
start staying open past their current closing time of 4 p.m.?
NASDAQ is in the midst of the transition, and the Big Board will
make the change next year.
</P>
<P>
   A survey conducted by Midwood Securities, a brokerage firm in
New York, suggests that the traders will not be mutual funds,
pension funds or insurance companies. In October, the firm surveyed
700 institutional money managers with assets of $500 million to
$500 billion; 60 percent of those responding said they would
probably not participate in extended trading hours, and, of the
remainder, almost all said they thought that it would not play an
essential role in their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``If institutions had their way, we wouldn't be extending the
hours,'' said Terry L. March, chief executive of Midwood.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about potential benefits of extended hours, 51
percent said they did not expect any. About one-quarter felt that
it would be useful in reacting to company and industry news,
economic or political developments and earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
   The managers were also asked about their concerns over
after-hours trading. Some 65 percent of the respondents said they
were worried about a possible lack of liquidity and 63 percent
cited the prospects of increased volatility.
</P>
<P>
   So who are the likely beneficiaries of extended trading? No
surprise there _ 68 percent of the managers cited the computerized
trading systems known as electronic communication networks, or
ECNs, many of which already offer after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   __Richard Teitelbaum &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who Depends Most On Microsoft Stock? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hottest stock of a generation turned into a hot potato last
week for the mutual funds that own it. After a federal judge
declared that it acts like a monopoly, Microsoft shares fell 2.6
percent last week, to close at $89.1875 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   So, what funds had the largest portions of their portfolios
invested in the company? It is difficult to tell, because funds are
required to disclose their holdings only when they file their
annual or semiannual reports.
</P>
<P>
   One candidate is Ameritor Security Trust, with just $5.2 million
in assets as of June 30. The fund's most recent annual report, also
as of that date, showed that the fund had 22.7 percent of its
portfolio invested in Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   If Ameritor does not sound familiar, that is because the fund's
name has changed twice in the last two years. It is the old
Steadman Associated Trust, one of a family of Steadman funds that
gained notoriety in the past decade by furnishing subpar, often
disastrous, performance.
</P>
<P>
   The fund is under new management. Its portfolio manager, Max
Katcher, said last week that he saw no reason to trim his stake.
Small wonder: Ameritor has returned 17.8 percent in the first three
quarters of the year, handily beating the 5.4 percent return of the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 and other indexes, despite an outsized
expense ratio of nearly 10 percent. The fund was helped, of course,
by its outsized position in Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Other big holders of Microsoft stock, based on their most recent
reports, included an assortment of technology-sector and
over-the-counter index funds.
</P>
<P>
   But several actively managed, diversified funds had large
stakes, too. The L. Roy Papp Stock fund had 11.9 percent of its
portfolio in Microsoft as of Sept. 30; Berkshire Focus, 11.7
percent as of June 30; Wells Fargo Large Company Growth, 9.7
percent as of Aug. 31; Fidelity OTC Portfolio, 8.8 percent as of
July 31; and CitiFunds Large Cap Growth, 8.1 percent as of April
30.
</P>
<P>
   __Richard Teitelbaum &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
