<HEADER>
A8180 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-REPUBS-CONGRESS-(TRIM     11-12 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-CONGRESS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REPUBLICAN AIM IN THIS YEAR'S BUDGET BATTLE IS SURVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As this year's budget fight sputters to a close,
Republicans are quietly ceding ground to President Clinton in their
determination to avoid even a hint of the kind of ideological
conflagration that led to the government shutdown four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Compromise by compromise, they have added more than $5 billion
to their spending bills in the last few weeks alone and given
Clinton a victory on a politically significant education program.
</P>
<P>
   A similar series of concessions last fall caused conservatives
to become so rebellious that Newt Gingrich, then the speaker of the
House, lashed out at them as ``the perfectionist caucus.'' But this
year _ at least so far _ the rank and file is showing few signs of
resistance.
</P>
<P>
   The mood underscores the Republican view that this first session
of the 106th Congress was about little more than survival under
dire circumstances. They opened the year with a razor-thin House
majority, an untested new speaker, poll ratings driven down by the
impeachment of the president and divisions between conservatives
and moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with only a handful of issues left to negotiate with
Clinton, they want to go home, satisfied that they maintained a
semblance of unity within their ranks this session, even if they
cannot point to many legislative accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Adjournment would also stop the Democrats, who have been newly
buoyed by an array of polls, from highlighting all the things that
have been left undone, like gun control, campaign finance reform
and regulation of managed health care.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the budget, Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., said,
``Everybody wants it done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a titanic battle,'' he said. ``These issues don't
reshape government for 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Anne Northup, R-Ky., referred to her party's razor-thin
majority in the House, and said, ``Considering the narrow margin, I
think we have adhered to our principles as best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   From the start of the year, mindful of their weaknesses, the
Republicans set only modest goals for themselves. They wanted an
orderly budget process to show the public that they can govern
responsibly. They pledged to adhere to the strict spending limits
set by the bipartisan balanced budget law of 1997. And they wanted
to showcase a handful of issues: social security, education, tax
cutting and national defense.
</P>
<P>
   While they failed to stay within the spending limits and their
tax cut was vetoed by the president, Republicans say that this
year's spending fight has allowed them to claim some success.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster their stand on national security, they gave the
Pentagon more money than Clinton asked for and provided a raise for
military personnel that was larger than what he requested.
</P>
<P>
   On education, they can share credit with Clinton for financing
his program for 100,000 new teachers over seven years. And because
the administration, in a nod to Republicans, agreed that 25 percent
of the money could go to teacher training instead of hiring, they
can say they at least made headway in their push for more
flexibility in the use of federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   And they believe they scored a tactical victory with their
approach to Social Security. It was Clinton who in 1998 first
talked about protecting the Social Security reserves as a way of
deflecting Republicans from tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But this year the Republicans turned the tables and took up the
cry with even more enthusiasm as a way of deterring government
spending during a time of surplus. They even ran commercials saying
that it was the Democrats who were trying to raid Social Security
for government spending.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that the public does not see Republicans as the
protectors of Social Security, and Democrats charge that the
Republicans can make that claim only by using a host of accounting
tricks and gimmicks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Republicans argue that they have created a potent
political fire wall against government spending that should last
for a long time since neither party will want to be accused of
being the one to dip into the Social Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Republicans _ and I am one _ feel we tempered the drive
of the White House and some Democrats to spend more money,'' said
Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn.
</P>
<P>
   This stand explains why one of the last remaining issues in the
budget talks is the Republicans' insistence that the White House
produce a list of spending cuts to offset the billions that have
been added into Clinton's preferred programs. Otherwise, Congress
will not make good on its pledge to avoid touching the Social
Security reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to close this budget without dipping into Social
Security,'' House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, insisted
this week.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' biggest failure was their inability to meet the
spending limits in the 1997 balanced budget law. But unlike 1998,
when the final budget deal resulted in $20 billion more in spending
than envisioned by the balanced budget act, this year the dollars
have added up slowly bill by bill. There was never a moment of
sticker shock.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even before the last few weeks of negotiations, the
nonpartisan Congressional Budget Office found that the majority's
spending bills had acceded the caps in the budget law by more than
$30 billion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Conservatives could still rebel next week and vote against the
final spending deal when they see the last compromises or if they
are unhappy with the outcome of another remaining issue _ U.N.
dues.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration wants to pay the nearly $1 billion
the United States owes the United Nations in back dues. The money
has been tied up over conservatives' insistence that the United
States bar financing to international organizations that promote
abortion rights overseas. Clinton said Friday that he was looking
for a compromise and that ``I hope we can work it out.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of Democrats may also vote against a budget deal. That
would allow them to thwart any Republican attempts to paint them as
big spenders who want to raid Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, Democrats were even looking for a way to tar
Republicans as the ones raiding Social Security. House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., said the Democrats would insist that
the Congressional Budget Office certify any budget deal. In the
past, the Congressional Budget Office has indicated when accounting
tricks have been used to hide raiding of the Social Security fund.
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats have already moved on from the budget debate to
focus on the set of issues that they believe will give them an edge
in their drive to take back the House and make gains in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   They treat each new dawn in Congress these days as an
opportunity to talk about the issues that have gone into
legislative limbo: gun control or regulation of health maintenance
organizations or an increase in the minimum wage or a Medicare
prescription drug program for the elderly. This week they even
unveiled a campaign commercial featuring grainy black-and-white
pictures of tombstones marked with the names of dead issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the issues that Democrats have helped push onto the
national agenda with no help from Republicans,'' Gephardt said
Friday, making it clear that next year these issues will form the
Democratic election platform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
