<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In New Jersey Politics, No Goldman Rematch &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So much for Goldman versus Goldman. Lewis M. Eisenberg, chairman
of the Port Authority, announced last week that he would not seek a
Senate seat from New Jersey, forgoing a rerun of an old Wall Street
grudge match. Eisenberg, 57, would have been fighting for the
Republican nomination and a possible match against Jon S. Corzine,
52, a leading contender on the Democratic side.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are natives of Illinois who earned considerable
fortunes at Goldman Sachs Group. Both became players in New Jersey
politics after their Goldman careers were cut short.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenberg resigned his partnership at Goldman, where he headed
the firm's equity sales division, under pressure after he violated
a policy against having a sexual relationship with a subordinate in
1989. Corzine scaled the firm's hierarchy to become senior partner,
the top boss, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   One former colleague of both said that Eisenberg long had his
eyes on the job Corzine eventually landed.
</P>
<P>
   A rematch was made possible when Corzine fell victim to a palace
coup at Goldman early this year. He resigned and quickly set his
sights on the Senate. ``Deep down I think Lew was looking for
revenge,'' said one retired partner who knew both men. ``We all
thought it's crazy. Given the history, it looks like he thought
better of it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   __Joseph Kann &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Return of the Munchkins &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can accuse Brian Brille, an investment banker, of
forgetting the little people. He invited some of them to his annual
Halloween party _ as part of his costume.
</P>
<P>
   At his house on eastern Long Island, Brille was dolled up as
Glinda the Good Witch from ``The Wizard of Oz'' and flanked by
three dwarfs he had hired for the evening to be his munchkins.
Brille, who specializes in the health-care industry at the
investment banking unit of Bank of America, spent about $3,000 on
his get-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people were taken aback'' by Brille's human accessories,
said one partygoer, but others were amused by another sign of good
times on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Brille's sidekicks were not the only little people there. When
Scott Brakebill, one of Brille's colleagues, showed up on a
chartered bus full of guests from Manhattan, he was dressed as Dr.
Evil, a character from the ``Austin Powers'' movies. At his side
was Scott Seidman, in an identical _ albeit much smaller _ outfit
as Dr. Evil's alter ego, Mini-Me.
</P>
<P>
   Seidman, who is 4 feet tall, proved that there were at least
three deal makers at the party. After agreeing to be one of
Brille's munchkins, he backed out of the deal when a talent agency
offered him the splashier, more lucrative role of Mini-Me. ``I
didn't have a contract,'' Seidman said. ``So I canceled the other
job.''
</P>
<P>
   His earnings for the party, which lasted into the wee hours,
were $650 plus a generous tip, he said: ``It was great. We tore the
place up.''
</P>
<P>
   __Patrick McGeehan &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Top Hat' for a `Bad Boy'? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As early as this week, a federal judge will decide how much more
United Way of America must pay to its former president, William V.
Aramony, who has been in federal prison since 1995 for
embezzlement. At issue, in pension language, is whether being a bad
boy should keep him from wearing a top hat.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, United Way directors approved for Aramony a ``top hat''
pension plan _ worth $4.2 million on top of his standard pension.
Even then, a judge has found, Aramony was already stealing from the
charity for himself, his teenage girlfriend and a second executive.
</P>
<P>
   The draft of the top-hat plan shown to the board included a
``bad boy'' clause that denied Aramony benefits if he committed a
felony. That language never made its way into the final agreement
drafted by Mutual of America, a pension plan administrator, and
signed for the board by Aramony's confederate.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Shira A. Scheindlin of federal district court in
Manhattan, ruled that because no evidence of collusion between
Aramony and Mutual of America was presented, he should get the
money, less about $2 million in forfeited salary and investigative
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Now the judge must interpret a tax law to decide whether Aramony
gets the $2.2 million difference or just $550,000. Then United Way
of America will decide whether to sue Mutual of America, which says
it has acted properly, for whatever Aramony collects because of the
missing clause.
</P>
<P>
   __David Cay Johnston &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
