<HEADLINE>
MURPHY TO PLAY SATURDAY, BUT IN BRUINS UNIFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It appeared that free agent right wing Joe Murphy was
about to sign a contract with the New York Rangers, who he had been
practicing with for about a week.
</P>
<P>
   Word out of New York is that he was supposed to meet Friday
morning with Rangers general manager Neil Smith, perhaps to
finalize a deal, but when he didn't show up, the Rangers were
baffled.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the 32-year-old Murphy was agreeing to terms on a
one-year deal with the Bruins that reportedly will pay him a $1
million base salary, plus scoring incentives that could yield
another $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   In an odd twist, Murphy will suit up for the Bruins Saturday
night against the Rangers at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   But the story gets more curious. Murphy said Friday that Smith
was so upset the winger had signed with Boston that the Rangers GM
threw one of Murphy's skates into Long Island Sound and cut his
sticks in half.
</P>
<P>
   Reports out of New York were that Murphy and Rangers assistant
coach Charlie Huddy engaged in an argument at Rye Playland, where
the Rangers practice, because of Murphy's decision and because
Murphy was upset about his missing and destroyed equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Neil on a number of occasions and he kept telling
me he was going to meet me and see me at the game,'' said Murphy.
``He would say hi and he was nice and stuff, but lip service only
goes so far. I'm out laying it on the line in practice. If they
turn me back, I go home and I have no contract, and every other
team in the league is going to look at me and say the Rangers
didn't want me either. I go down to practice and my skate is thrown
in the river. I can't play right now. I have no hockey skates.
They're going to have to order some skates for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supposedly, Neil threw my skate in the river he's so mad. He
had me under his nose and he decided he had other priorities.
Obviously, I wasn't a priority. Now they're mad they don't have me.
Obviously they're mad or they wouldn't be throwing my stuff out.
That sounds like something from grade school.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said he thought it vital that he hammer out a contract
with somebody. The Bruins offered one first.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life is hockey,'' he said. ``I love to play this game and I
didn't have a contract. I phoned (Rangers coach) John Muckler and I
totally respect John Muckler. I am thankful for him letting me come
in there, but I had the total risk at this thing. If it doesn't
work out in the New York, I'm finished. I still pressed the issue
to get something done but I wasn't a priority. But now all of a
sudden, they obviously wanted me if they're going to be throwing my
skate in the river and cutting my sticks in half.''
</P>
<P>
   When told about Murphy's recounting of the events, Smith denied
fooling around with anyone's equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had thought that one up,'' said Smith. ``I think he's
giving me more credit than I deserve. The last time I checked, I'm
not the equipment manager. It's craziness to think I'd be getting
involved like that. I wouldn't even know which sticks are his.
Nothing surprises me in the career of Joe Murphy. That's bizarre,
the whole thing is ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he was planning to meet with Murphy to talk to him
about a contract that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was prepared to sit down with him and give him something and
say, `This is what I expect you to sign for,' and I was expecting
him to sit there and give me some feedback,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   It never happened. Instead, the Bruins are hoping Murphy can
come close to the production he had last season with the San Jose
Sharks, when he potted 25 goals in the last year of a deal that
paid him $3.8 million. It was a contract originally given to him by
former St. Louis GM Mike Keenan.
</P>
<P>
   As a veteran defenseman with the Red Wings, Bruins assistant GM
Mike O'Connell roomed with Murphy back when Murphy was a rookie and
was the No. 1 pick overall by Detroit in 1986. O'Connell said he is
hoping Murphy can add some offensive punch to the Bruins' lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been looking for a forward for at least the last two
weeks,'' said O'Connell. ``We were looking at a centerman,
preferably, but the way Anson Carter has played center, it looks
like he could handle that.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy is likely to receive a hostile reaction when he faces the
players he thought would soon be his teammates. Murphy said the
Rangers just dragged their feet too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I tried to track Neil down every day to try to get
something done and I was risking my career by being out there,''
said Murphy. ``If I got hurt, I'm not going to get a contract. My
objective was to get a contract and get back to the league. I've
been sitting out for awhile. No team had offered me a contract
until the Bruins did and that's what I was looking for. I'm very
grateful and I'm very excited. Boston was my favorite team growing
up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Left wing Ken Belanger remains out of the lineup because of
postconcussion syndrome. Belanger was struck by Buffalo defenseman
Rhett Warrener Wednesday night and became ill later that night.
It's unknown how long he'll be sidelined . . . Right wing Rob
DiMaio missed his second straight game because of a badly bruised
left foot . . . Forward Peter Ferraro was sent back to Providence .
. . Goalie Byron Dafoe will get his fourth straight start Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
