<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8188 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CONFEDERATE-BURIAL13-     11-12 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFEDERATE-BURIAL13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thousands gather at parade for Rebel
 &HT;    reburials
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ The furor over the Confederate flag swept
into this city where the Civil War began, stirring the rancorous
debate with the clashing symbols of heritage and hatred.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands watched Friday as a solemn funeral procession through
Charleston transferred the flag-draped coffins of 22 Confederate
war dead to Magnolia Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Under a sky as gray as the uniforms of more than 300 Civil War
re-enactors, the crowd sang ``Dixie'' and prayed over the bones,
packed in dirt and plastic inside small coffins. After the simple
wooden boxes were lowered into a long grave, rifles and cannons
boomed in salute, followed by the mournful trumpeting of taps over
the Cooper River.
</P>
<P>
   On behalf of the ancestors of Franklin Medaris, a Georgia
infantryman who died in Charleston in 1863, Brian Medaris accepted
the Confederate flag from atop his third great-uncle's coffin.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like you know them,'' said Medaris, 39, a DeKalb
County paramedic who attended the funeral with 13 relatives. They
received red roses from women dressed in black funeral dresses and
veils.
</P>
<P>
   It was a formal, dignified reinterment of 22 soldiers and
sailors and a single child whose remains had been exhumed last
summer. Diggers recovered them from a long-abandoned mariners'
cemetery underneath The Citadel's football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``These 23 souls have been brought home to rest,'' said the Rev.
C. Lynn Bailey, presiding over a ceremony in which the Confederate
flag represented an honorable ending.
</P>
<P>
   But among South Carolinians embroiled in the controversy of the
Rebel battle flag flying atop the state Capitol in Columbia, the
mood is turning surly, despite the governor's plea for compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jim Hodges told a business audience Friday in Charleston
that leaders of civil rights organizations and Confederate heritage
groups need to issue ``statements of mutual respect'' for each
other's views on the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Hodges said, the flag controversy threatens ``to tear
this state apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in the last state to fly the flag atop its Capitol (though
Georgia and Mississippi still incorporate it in their state flags'
designs), civil rights groups label the banner as a racist reminder
of slavery; heritage groups view it as a symbol of their ancestors'
sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting has intensified since the NAACP called for a
tourism boycott of South Carolina until the Legislature votes to
remove the flag from the Capitol. Concerned by the boycott, a
growing number of organizations, including the state Chamber of
Commerce, are endorsing the idea of moving the flag to ``a place of
honor'' on the Capitol grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges, a first-term Democrat, is caught in the crossfire. He
tried Friday to mute blistering criticism of the solution he
offered two days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   If the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People agrees to suspend its tourism boycott, Hodges said, he would
muscle legislators to honor the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. with a
state holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP could always re-enact the boycott, the governor said,
if legislators balk on the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``One good-faith gesture deserves another,'' said Hodges,
explaining that a suspension of the boycott and the creation of a
King holiday would set the stage for resolving the flag dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Caught off guard by the proposal, civil rights leaders said they
were insulted Hodges would urge them to deal on an issue as
offensive to them as the flag.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Darrell Jackson of Columbia said Hodges blundered
badly by ensnaring the King holiday with the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said lawmakers working on passage of the holiday were
close to getting the votes in the Republican-controlled House. He
blamed Hodges for jeopardizing the effort and had harsh words for
flag supporters in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the House votes down the King holiday, they can consider
that the Civil War within the borders of South Carolina has
begun,'' Jackson said. ``I predict as they lost before, they are
going to lose again.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Glenn McConnell, a Charleston Republican and
re-enactor who attended Friday's burial, said flag supporters would
support a King holiday along with a state holiday honoring
Confederate Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``One is not going to ride without the other,'' said McConnell,
labeling the boycott part of the NAACP's ``hate campaign against
ground,'' McConnell said.``The flag is not coming down from the
dome until the hate campaign stops.''
</P>
<P>
   In more conciliatory terms, Hodges said the boycott stands in
the way of a flag compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boycott has focused attention on the issue,'' he said,
``but now it is creating an obstacle to a resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodges also cautioned against the escalating war of words. ``The
more strident the rhetoric on both sides, the more shrill the
headlines in our news media, the less likely we are to make
progress,'' he said. ``We seem to be dividing into separate
camps.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's funeral procession drew a curious but respectful crowd.
It stretched along East Bay Street, from the stately homes near the
Battery waterfront to the low-income apartments underneath the
Cooper River bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred, including a group of black day care children,
filed in behind the re-enactors, a few of whom were on horseback,
but most marching in cadence with rifles.
</P>
<P>
   A raccoon tail hung from a bayonet. Soldiers tucked feathers in
their floppy hats. Children dressed in costume, little boys in gray
outfits, little girls in black hoop skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Few black people watched the procession or attended the burial.
``I wonder why they need a parade,'' said William Robinson, 41, a
black carpenter visiting his mother who lives in a government
housing facility. ``It seems they are exploiting the flag. They
want a big show of it.''
</P>
<P>
   At Magnolia Cemetery, re-enactor Bill Jackson of Eastman, Ga.,
said he was showing respect for the dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not here to sing `Dixie' and swing a flag,'' said
Jackson, owner of one of the 14 cannons which saluted the deceased.
</P>
<P>
   As city sanitation workers followed the procession, scooping up
horse droppings, the street returned to normal, crowded by tourists
and office workers.
</P>
<P>
   Retired schoolteacher Henry Simmons lingered afterwards at East
Bay and Queen streets. A 62-year-old black man, Simmons said he was
heartened that no protests or hate groups had tried to mar what he
thought was a respectful procession.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people need to do _ and it's more true of Charlestonians
_ is to put this issue of race behind them, and move on with their
lives,'' Simmons said. ``The year 2000 is almost upon us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
