<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-SEARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLIGHT 990 PROBERS PUZZLED BY ENGINE CUTOFF DURING DIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ As it roared toward the ocean at nearly the
speed of sound, federal investigators said Friday, EgyptAir Flight
990's engines were abruptly cut off as cockpit warning alarms
wailed and passengers were rendered weightless by the force of the
dive.
</P>
<P>
   At a briefing here Friday, James E. Hall, chairman of the
National Transportation Safety Board, described what appeared to be
a deliberate, puzzling action, taken just after the ``controlled
descent'' that dropped the plane from 33,000 feet to about 19,000
feet within seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both left and right (engines) changed from `run' to `cut off,'
'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators still don't know why it happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, these data raise many questions in your minds,''
Hall said. ``I assure you, they raise questions in our minds, too.
We cannot at this time explain the circumstances that were
occurring on Flight 990 that resulted in the profile I just
described.''
</P>
<P>
   A commercial airline pilot who spoke on condition of anonymity
said it's not easy to shut the engines down. ``The last thing I
could imagine doing is that, even in an extremist situation,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot also speculated that, because of the lack of a
distress call from a member of the flight crew, the action taken
likely was deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   Still unsure whether the plane was doomed by man or machine,
crews off Nantucket resumed their search Friday for the jetliner's
cockpit voice recorder _ now deemed critical to understanding the
aircraft's fatal, final moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airplane was flying along with the nose perfectly level
and basically it then dove off a cliff,'' said John Hansman,
professor of aeronautics at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't seen any obvious mechanical cause for that initial
dive,'' he said. ``It may be that it hasn't shown up yet. But we're
beginning to be able to discount the initial mechanical causes that
were suspected. As we have fewer and fewer mechanical causes, the
probability of human causes begins to rise.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, a top FBI official said the 200 agents assigned
to the crash are running down leads, but, so far, none has yielded
critical clues about what went wrong with the jetliner.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Valiquette, an FBI agent who serves as the bureau's
spokesman in New York, said federal investigators are examining
every aspect of each leg of the Boeing 767-300ER's flights between
Cairo, New York and Los Angeles in the days before the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you that nothing has arisen to which we're
attaching much significance with regard to the crew,'' Valiquette
said.
</P>
<P>
   EgyptAir Flight 990 crashed early Halloween morning some 60
miles south of Nantucket, about a half-hour after the Cairo-bound
jet took off from John F. Kennedy International Airport in New
York. All 217 passengers and crew were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The flight data recorder _ one of two ``black boxes'' _ was
retrieved from wreckage on the ocean floor and flown to Washington
for analysis earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary analysis of the data shows that eight seconds
after the autopilot disengaged amid an uneventful flight, the jet
pitched into a smooth, controlled dive that ultimately became steep
enough to parallel conditions of an astronaut training for
weightlessness.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said technicians have now retrieved all but five seconds of
data from the recorder, indicating that the device stopped working
during what radar data has shown happened next: That, after the
deep dive, the plane climbed again to about 24,000 feet before
beginning one last dive and breaking apart at about 16,700 feet
above the water.
</P>
<P>
   At about halfway through that descent, ``the speed of the
aircraft reaches .86 Mach and the captain's and the first officer's
master warning activate,'' Hall said. At sea level, Mach 1 is the
speed of sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``A master warning is one that indicates a potentially major
problem with the airplane that the flight crew must attend to
immediately,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Those warnings would activate when the plane reaches excessive
speed, cabin pressure drops, sensors detect a fire aboard, or the
plane's takeoff and landing configurations are incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   ``During this descent, the airplane reached a maximum nose-down
pitch angle of about 40 degrees,'' said Hall. An airplane on a
normal glide path toward landing has a nose-down pitch of 3 to 4
degrees. ``Then, the nose-down pitch angle started to lessen and
the (gravity) forces on the aircraft increased from about zero to
about 2.5,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, the data indicates, both of the aircraft's
engines were shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Experts have said the passengers would have felt extremely
disoriented as the plane plunged in the dark of night. Anyone not
wearing safety belts would likely have flown from their seats, then
slammed to the floor seconds later when the dive bottomed out.
</P>
<P>
   Hall would not speculate about why the crew may have taken that
action, or about any of the factors that downed the plane,
confining his comments to the dry data culled from the recorder.
</P>
<P>
   But because the device indicates that the jet was in a
controlled descent _ meaning the flight crew was controlling the
plane _ investigators are more acutely concerned that a terrorist
or a criminal, and not a mechanical malfunction, was responsible
for the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, even the NTSB was surprised at that finding,''
Valiquette said of the flight recorder's readings. ``And so were
we. It does raise the specter a little bit more intensely that
maybe there was a criminal act or a terrorist act involved here.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're still a long way from making a determination that
this was a criminal act,'' he said. ``A controlled descent took
everyone by surprise. And it raises more questions than we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Crawley, the head of MIT's aeronautics and astronautics
department, said while passengers would feel weightless during a
plunge like that, they would not have lost consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we learned is that this was an intentional maneuver,''
Crawley said. ``It's all consistent with the pilot doing this. This
isn't the direct result of the flight control system. These are all
things that a pilot would sit there and do. The missing piece is:
Why would he do this?''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI's Lewis Schiliro told ABC News that officials have
received several phone calls claiming responsibility for downing
the airplane. Each is being investigated, he said, but noted that
``at this point, none of (them), we're determining to be
credible.''
</P>
<P>
   As investigators continue to pore over electronic data in
Washington, the search resumed Friday for the cockpit voice
recorder as Navy vessels and a private ship sent submersible robots
to help locate it. They were hoping to work through the weekend
before weather conditions worsen Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intentions are to put in maxiumum effort,'' said Navy Rear
Admiral William G. Sutton. ``(The USS) Grapple is anchored over the
pingers and we'll keep (conducting robot) operations there to look
for the cockpit voice recorder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
