<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8193 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-MRSCLINTON-POLITICS-N     11-12 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: NEW CONCERNS ABOUT FIRST LADY'S CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
   (See also MRSCLINTON-MIDEAST) 
(rk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Among many Democrats Friday , the question was not
why Hillary Rodham Clinton had sat silently in Ramallah as the wife
of Yasser Arafat seemingly accused Israelis of poisoning
Palestinian women and children. The question was why Mrs. Clinton
had agreed to go to the West Bank in the first place _ and than why
it took her 12 hours to offer even a tentative response to Suha
Arafat's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, when Mrs. Clinton approved television advertisements
to promote her expected Senate campaign earlier this week, the
question was not over the wisdom of such an early expenditure of
campaign funds. It was instead over the fact that it was financed
with the same kind of unregulated, backdoor campaign contributions
that had clouded President Clinton's campaign in 1996, inviting
attacks by her likely opponent, New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, and critical comment by newspaper editorials.
</P>
<P>
   These two seemingly unrelated incidents might have been
separated by three days and 5,000 miles. But taken together, they
have stirred a new round of concern among many Democrats about the
state of Mrs. Clinton's exploratory campaign and the skills of this
first-time candidate. The two events have dispirited some of her
closest associates and emboldened Giuliani in what his advisers
describe as a deliberate attempt to establish an early dominance in
the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way this developed is troubling, and this needs to be
resolved,'' said one of Mrs. Clinton's advisers, who, like most of
her associates, did not want to be identified in discussing what
one described as the low point of her fledgling campaign.
``Everything she does will be viewed through the Senate lens.
There's no escaping it.''
</P>
<P>
   The events this week on the West Bank crystallized what a
growing number of Democrats has suspected: Mrs. Clinton's
underlying problem is her continuing effort to serve both as the
nation's first lady and as the likely Democratic candidate for U.S.
Senate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   She went to the Middle East at the invitation of Leah Rabin to
discuss the peace process at the center in Tel Aviv named after the
slain prime minister, Yitzak Rabin. In accepting the invitation,
Mrs. Clinton put aside the concerns of some advisers aware of the
perils that inevitably rise when New York and Israeli politics
meet.
</P>
<P>
   The day she left, Mrs. Clinton pointedly described this as an
official trip, and said she did not want it viewed in the context
of a Senate race. She instructed her political staff to remain at
home, traveling instead with a contingent from the White House and
State Department.
</P>
<P>
   But the difficulty in drawing such distinctions became extremely
clear this week, as television and news wires brought home her
Mideast events and her dismayed political aides closely followed
the unfolding trouble. ``If you were planning a campaign trip, this
is not the kind of campaign trip you would have planned,'' said
Howard Wolfson, the campaign press secretary, speaking from Mrs.
Clinton's headquarters in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's aides said that had he found himself in a similar
position, the mayor might have stormed off, or denounced Mrs.
Arafat on the spot for making a statement that was sure to give
rise to protest among American Jews. Considering the fact that
Giuliani evicted Arafat from Lincoln Center in 1995, there seems
little reason to doubt that claim.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton and her aides offered a number of reasons for why
she, by contrast, said nothing about the remarks until she arrived
in Amman 12 hours later. She was, first off, concerned about taking
any step that might jeopardize the peace talks. The on-the-spot
translation she received was imprecise, said Marsha Berry, Mrs.
Clinton's White house press secretary, and she wanted to wait until
she got a formal written transcript before she actually offered a
response.
</P>
<P>
   And even the response exposed the dual, and dueling, roles that
she and her staffs are playing. Its delayed timing reflected the
cautious White House staff, which is often at odds with her more
aggressive, if clearly frustrated, campaign organization.
</P>
<P>
   And the sluggishness stirred concern among Democrats following
Mrs. Clinton's travels. ``If something like this happens, the first
thing you learn is fix it in the same news cycle,'' said one New
York Democratic strategist not associated with Mrs. Clinton's
campaign. ``Now you can't catch up. It's impossible to catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   A growing worry of some Democrats goes beyond her conflicting
roles to what they see as deficiencies in both her exploratory
campaign and her political skills. She has yet to hire anything
beyond a skeletal campaign staff, and what she has is scattered
between New York and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Ickes, her senior political adviser, serves as Mrs.
Clinton de facto campaign manager. But while Ickes is a native New
Yorker and well versed in city and state politics, he is based in
Washington, where he works as a private lobbyist. Until Mrs.
Clinton hires a campaign manager, there is no single force guarding
against missteps like this week's commercials and wayward trip.
</P>
<P>
   Her advisers insist that the campaign will gel once she formally
announces, and forges a separate political identity from the White
House. ``When she becomes a full candidate instead of being the
concept of the candidate, she's really going to be able to drive
her issues and her message in a way that she can't now,'' said the
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   But that quick palliative may not occur anytime soon. Before
Mrs. Clinton left for the Middle East, she and her advisers, after
some discussion, decided to push off her official announcement, yet
again, this time from January to February. Mrs. Clinton was said to
believe that January is still too early to begin officially
presenting herself as a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   From Amman Friday night, Ms. Berry, the first lady's White House
press secretary, said that Mrs. Clinton and her contingent had
monitored the tumble of events with an air of resignation. ``This
is a new process, really,'' Ms. Berry said. ``We're still working
out how to work together. We've done a pretty good job and we'll
continue to improve at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
