<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WITH-GRENDER-ART-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH GORDON GRENDER: GAMERICA CAPITAL FUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic of
GAmerica Capital Fund is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 14)  
 (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a fund manager, Gordon Grender doesn't seem to mind doing
things that might be regarded as a little odd. For example, he runs
a United States stock fund, the $58.5 million GAMerica Capital
fund, from an office overlooking Westminster Cathedral in London.
</P>
<P>
   The geography gives him an edge, he said. ``I can read The Wall
Street Journal and The New York Times on the Web and check
Bloomberg before anybody in New York gets up,'' he said in an
English accent.
</P>
<P>
   Grender, who has been managing American money from across the
Atlantic since 1974, has built an enviable record. GAMerica Capital
returned 27.2 percent a year, on average, for the three years
through Nov. 5, compared with 10.1 percent for its peer group of
small blend funds, according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago
financial publisher, and 33.8 percent for the Russell 2000 index of
small-capitalization stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Grender, 55, searches the markets for value among American
companies of all sizes, although the fund is now heavily weighted
in small-capitalization stocks _ the category where he is finding
the best bargains. He looks for businesses with annual earnings
growth of 15 percent or more and is adamant about not overpaying;
he aims to pay less than the market's price-to-earnings multiple,
currently 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't bring myself to buy glamour stocks with
capitalizations in the billions but revenues in the millions,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if a stock performs strongly ``I tend to run with it,''
he said, holding on as it rises in price. The turnover rate for his
fund, which holds just 40 to 50 stocks, averages 29 percent, versus
96 percent for a typical fund. But its class A shares carry a 5
percent front-end load and an expense ratio of 2.46 percent, versus
1.49 percent for its average peer.
</P>
<P>
   Grender reads many American business publications and gathers
valuable information on the road, he said, attending investment
conferences and visiting companies. He tours the United States at
least four times a year; each trip lasts at least two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many other managers, he ignores quarterly earnings
forecasts, which he calls a ``futile exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Analysts tend to report what management tells them,'' he said.
``They don't do their own independent work.''
</P>
<P>
   In looking at a company, Grender wants to see sales growth of at
least 5 percent a year above inflation, and relatively substantial
free cash flow, although the amount depends on the type of
business.
</P>
<P>
   He is particularly drawn to companies with very depressed stock
prices _ those that are down 25 percent to 50 percent from their
most recent highs. Here, he shows his contrarian streak: ``I don't
worry about companies whose share prices take big falls when they
report disappointing earnings if I think the fundamental story is
sound.''
</P>
<P>
   Another plus, he said, is inside ownership. ``I want top
management to own shares in the company, not just stock options,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He is not afraid to carry cash _ the fund's cash position grew
to 50 percent by October, as new money flowed in. In the last few
weeks, he has reduced it to about 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been nervous about the level of the stock market,'' he
said. ``But I've been buying lately because so many stocks have
been taking such big falls.''
</P>
<P>
   Grender owns stock in Power-One, a company in Camarilla, Calif.,
that makes power supply equipment for commercial electronic devices
like CAT scanners. He bought more shares after a conference call in
October in which company management expressed caution about meeting
fourth-quarter earnings estimates, driving down the price from over
$30 a share to $15. He paid $20. The company, he said, is ``a
lower-risk way to play the growth in electronics.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund initially bought Power-One stock in October 1998 at $6
a share. Earnings have grown about 25 percent a year since the
company went public in 1997, helped by acquisitions. Insiders own
about 15 percent of the shares, which closed on Friday at $19.625,
or 29.5 times consensus earnings estimates of 66.5 cents a share
for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Another choice is Policy Management Systems of Blythewood, S.C.,
which makes software used by insurers. Grender bought shares in
October for $21, down from $55 in February, after the company said
it would miss its third-quarter earnings forecasts because of
delays caused by Year 2000 computer issues and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``But because customers tend to rely on them heavily,'' Grender
said, ``the fact that their earnings are poor and their stock price
is down doesn't mean that their business will go away.''
</P>
<P>
   He estimates three-year earnings growth of 15 percent to 20
percent a year, on average. And he thinks sales should grow above
10 percent a year over that time. Management owns just under 1
percent of shares, but that is enough for Grender because of the
company's large market capitalization. The stock now trades at
$20.875, or 13.9 times 1999 consensus earnings estimates of $1.51 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   In September, he paid $47 a share for Sprint, shortly before the
company announced its merger deal with MCI WorldCom. The stock
price had fallen to the mid-$40s, from $55 in June, because of
worries about increased competition from other long-distance
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   He jumped in, he said, ``because I thought the company was a
likely acquisition target as the industry consolidated.'' Moreover,
he said, it was ``reasonably priced'' relative to other companies
in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Grender is bullish on the merger, and thinks the combined
company will grow 30 percent a year, on average, over three years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 2054EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
