u a BC-AIRCRASH-RDP-500&AMP;ADD-     11-12 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-RDP-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYGPTAIR FLIGHT DATA RAISES MORE QUESTIONS THAN IT ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS with MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT NAVAL STATION, R.I. _ The EgyptAir flight that crashed
on Oct. 31 went into an extreme dive, making the passengers
weightless and pitching the nose down at a 40-degree angle, before
the nose pulled back up and subjected the plane and its passengers
to two and a half times the normal force of gravity, the chairman
of the National Transportation Safety Board said Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said many of the details released Friday might reflect
an airplane that was in an emergency, but still under control. But
the chairman, James E. Hall, said that the information from the
flight data recorder also showed that both engines had been
switched off from the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots experienced with the Boeing 767, the type of plane that
crashed, said they could not understand why the engines had been
turned off, with the information now in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Hall also said that the elevators, the adjustable surfaces on
the horizontal tail that are used to raise or lower the nose, moved
to uneven positions. It is not possible for the crew to command
such a movement on the 767, according to pilots, and the fact that
the elevators moved out of unison indicates a major malfunction.
But it was not clear from the information released so far whether
this was a cause of the accident or a malfunction along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The crash, about 60 miles from Nantucket, Mass., killed all 217
people on board. Other than a small quantity of debris and human
remains, searchers have not recovered anything except one of the
two ``black boxes,'' the flight data recorder, which they are still
analyzing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, these data raise many questions,'' Hall said. ``I
can assure you they have raised questions in the minds of the NTSB
and the investigators. We cannot at this time explain the
circumstances that were occurring on Flight 990 that resulted in
the flight profile I have just described, and we will not attempt
to speculate about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, the second ``black box,'' the cockpit voice
recorder, might explain the circumstances. The Navy believes it has
located that device on the sea floor, within a pile of wreckage
from the plane, but a robot submarine was still trying to retrieve
it Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For law enforcement authorities, Friday's information raised
questions that deepened the mystery of EgyptAir even as it yielded
few clues to guide the inquiry into whether anyone might
intentionally have interfered with the flight or tried to bring
down the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that in the course of their investigation
they had examined the recent activities, background, medical
history and emotional stability of the crew members and passengers.
But so far, the officials said, those inquiries had not provided
useful information.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the officials said that while the FBI inquiry was far
from over, investigators were faced with dwindling leads and,
increasingly frustrated over their inability to help explain the
crash, were anxiously awaiting recovery of the cockpit voice
recorder.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 2057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8198 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-AIRCRASH-RDP-2NDTAKE-     11-12 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-RDP-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEWPORT NAVAL STATION, R.I.: voice recorder.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the plunge on Oct. 31, conditions on the plane, which was
about half an hour out of Kennedy International Airport on a flight
to Cairo, Egypt, would have been far different from a normal
flight.
</P>
<P>
   In everyday operations, the 767 angles up no more than 20
degrees and down no more than about 5; U.S. airlines define a
nose-down altitude of more than 10 degrees as an ``upset.''
</P>
<P>
   And in ordinary flight, passengers seldom feel the force of
gravity at less than .9 G or more than 1.1 G. One G is the force of
gravity for a person standing on the ground; anything higher is the
extra weight a person feels going up in a fast elevator, and
anything lower is what someone feels in an elevator going down.
</P>
<P>
   At 2.5 G's, ``you would feel the weight of your face,'' said one
long-time 767 pilot.
</P>
<P>
   The 767 is certified to operate at up to 2.5 G's of positive
force and 1 G of negative force, so it could survive the transition
from a steep dive to a climb without damage if the force did not
exceed 2.5 G's. In fact, damage, in the form of rivets popping and
the metal skeleton bending, is not supposed to set in at fewer than
3.75 G's, according to Boeing documents.
</P>
<P>
   But those limits assume that the plane is not exceeding its
speed limit, and Hall hinted Friday that Flight 990 may have been
exceeding that limit, 86 percent of the speed of sound, during its
descent.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe that the plane approached the speed of
sound, which varies according to the density of air but is about
700 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said that the flight data recorder had noted that a master
alarm went off, which could have been triggered by several factors,
including flying too fast. Another is cabin depressurization.
</P>
<P>
   The alarm ``indicates a potentially major problem with the
airplane that the flight crew must attend to immediately,'' he
said. The information in hand does not make clear when the crew
lost control of the airplane.
</P>
<P>
   In an emergency descent, which might be needed because of cabin
depressurization or other causes, one standard technique is to turn
off the autopilot and slow down the engines, push the nose down and
hold the speed at the ``red line.'' If the plane is flying faster,
the pilot would pull the nose up; when it goes slower, he would
push it down again.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of this flight appear to follow that pattern. The flight
data recorder indicates that the autopilot disconnected, but not
whether it turned itself off or was turned off by the crew. The
nose was lowered. And the engines were slowed down.
</P>
<P>
   But turning off the engines does not fit in, except perhaps as a
desperate way to slow down, pilots said. ``There are reasons why
you would shut down an engine, but you wouldn't shut down both
engines,'' said one pilot. The reasons include an engine fire, an
engine that had to be re-started because the flame inside went out
or a runaway engine that could not be slowed down.
</P>
<P>
   The flight data recorder is supposed to note if there were
engine fires, and there was no mention of such a finding at the
briefing Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Weather and technical problems have bedeviled salvagers for two
weeks, frustrating the Navy's search for the cockpit voice recorder
through the plane's fragments in 240 to 270 feet of water.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say the picture would be a lot clearer if only
they had the cockpit voice recorder. On Friday the weather was
cooperative; seas were light and winds gentle. But Magnum, a robot
deployed from the submarine support vessel Carolyn Chouest needed
repairs and spent much of the day on deck.
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, however, the salvage ship Grapple was anchored
over one of the audio beacons that is believed to be attached to
the missing recorder, and Deep Drone, another robot, was on the
bottom searching for it. Magnum had been repaired and was surveying
waters nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Rear Adm. William G. Sutton, who commands the salvage effort,
said the ships and their crews would take advantage of the fair
seas and work through the weekend. ``We are projected to have this
good weather to Sunday afternoon,'' Sutton said. By Sunday evening,
the weather is supposed to turn foul again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
