<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-ATTACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKET ATTACK ON U.S. AND U.N. OFFICES IN PAKISTAN FAILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By STEVE LeVINE     
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ Several rockets were fired at American
diplomatic and U.N. buildings here Friday in an apparently
coordinated attack, but they missed their targets. One person was
reported injured.
</P>
<P>
   The attack came two days before U.N. economic sanctions are to
take effect against neighboring Afghanistan if its governing
Taliban movement does not turn over Osama bin Laden, the Saudi whom
the United States accuses of masterminding the bombings of the
American Embassies in Tanzania and Kenya in 1998. Those blasts
killed 224 people.
</P>
<P>
   No one claimed responsibility for Friday's rocket launchings,
but military and political officials here suspected a link to the
sanctions. The Taliban denied that it was to blame. The Islamabad
police said no arrests were made by evening.
</P>
<P>
   The attackers fixed double-barreled rocket launchers to three
parked vehicles, fled and then set the weapons off almost
simultaneously using a timed or remote mechanism, Pakistani
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The rockets were aimed at buildings in the heart of Islamabad:
the American Embassy, a U.S.-run library and cultural office called
the American Center and a 17-story office tower housing several
U.N. agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The injured person was a Pakistani guard at the American Center.
The only reported damage apart from the attackers' own charred
vehicles was broken glass at the American Center and a few burned
trees and shrubs.
</P>
<P>
   Security was heightened around the embassy here and at the U.S.
Consulate in Peshawar, a city close to the Afghanistan border and
the home of about a million Afghan refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan's military seized power in a popular, bloodless coup, a
month ago, a period in which this turbulent country of 130 million
had been unusually peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   Large crowds milled around the blast sites, but otherwise there
was no apparent unease on the streets of the sedate capital. Friday
prayers went on as usual just an hour and a half after the
explosions.
</P>
<P>
   But tension was palpable outside the consulate in Peshawar,
where guards questioned or searched some passers-by, including a
few riding bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   The attackers seemed to have had little trouble penetrating
Islamabad's center, where most government buildings and foreign
embassies are situated.
</P>
<P>
   The attackers had bolted the rocket launchers to the floors of
the three vehicles. The launchers, tubes about four feet long and
five inches in diameter, appeared to have been crudely rigged. They
fired mortar-type projectiles.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicles were a white jeep parked beside the capital's main
parkway about 200 yards from the office tower, which houses U.N.
drug enforcement and other agencies; a Honda Civic in a parking lot
next to the American Center, which is also on the wide parkway; and
another jeep, bearing a U.N. license plate, left in a large dirt
field behind the American Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The police said they found four of the mortar shells, all far
from their intended targets. One was outside the American Center
compound, a second had struck a U.N. vehicle, a third had struck a
Pakistan government building near the American Embassy, and the
fourth was in the nearby hills. All were taken to a police lab for
inspection.
</P>
<P>
   The blasts set the vehicles ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the attackers did not appear expert. The
vehicles that were supposed to anchor the launchers were thrown
several feet by the force of the launchings, said a supervisor with
the city's anti-terrorism squad.
</P>
<P>
   Security officials immediately considered a link to the
sanctions that are to be imposed against the Taliban on Sunday if
bin Laden and one of his chief aides are not apprehended. Under the
resolution approved last month by the Security Council, the
Taliban's economic assets abroad are to be frozen, and
international flights by the national airline, Ariana, curtailed.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban has strongly urged the United Nations not to enact
the sanctions but has repeatedly refused to hand over bin Laden. He
has reportedly told the Taliban that he is willing to leave as long
as no one discloses his destination, but the movement's leaders are
said to have refused his offer.
</P>
<P>
   The list of possible culprits is not short. Apart from the
Taliban itself, Pakistan is home to several well-armed paramilitary
groups sympathetic to the Taliban and hostile to the United States,
in addition to thousands of Pakistani religious militants who over
the years have trained side by side with Taliban members in Islamic
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban leader, Mullah Muhammad Omar, issued a statement
condemning the attacks, saying they had been aimed at straining the
Taliban's relations with Pakistan, the United States and the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   In an appeal for Washington and the United Nations to refrain
from quick judgment, Omar said he had investigated and then
absolved the United States of involvement in a truck bomb explosion
on Aug. 24 outside his home in the southern Afghan city of Kandahar
that killed 10 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Islam such acts are abhorred,'' he said, ``since these are
not to the benefit of anyone but create instability in the region,
which leads to the killing of innocent people. The Islamic Emirate
of Afghanistan has always condemned terrorism and continues to do
so.''
</P>
<P>
   The threatened sanctions have already provoked protests in
Afghanistan, where the economy has been devastated by two decades
of war.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, thousands of Afghan protesters threw stones at a
U.N. building in Kandahar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
