<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8201 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-LOCKHEED-STOCK13-COX     11-12 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-STOCK13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lockheed stock price outlook poor
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lockheed Martin shareholders may be facing a cruel
dilemma: whether to cut their already considerable losses by
selling, or hang on in hopes that an expected upturn in defense
spending will rescue the troubled company.
</P>
<P>
   On one side are analysts who say the rumored sale of certain
assets would be the best news shareholders could expect from the
nation's biggest defense contractor, which has suffered from
problems all year.
</P>
<P>
   The company shocked the market on Oct. 29 by slashing its
earnings projection for 2000 in half and announcing the resignation
of its president, Peter Teets. The company's shares fell almost 13
percent.
</P>
<P>
   This offers little hope that investors can expect much of a
rally in share prices any time soon, some analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think the company's shares will do much either way
until their earnings are growing again, but they have been
shrinking instead of growing,'' said analyst Paul N. Nisbet of JSA
Research in Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   On a steadily downward trajectory since early last year,
Lockheed Martin's shares closed on Friday at $19, less than half
their 52-week high of $54.62 1/2 on Nov. 23, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, however, some analysts argue that defense
spending is expected to rise significantly for the first time since
the end of the Cold War, with Pentagon purchases rising to as much
as $75 billion by 2005 from $44 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And with Lockheed Martin's shares having fallen so far, some
analysts make a case that it has become a value stock with nowhere
to go but up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lockheed Martin shares are definitely in bargain territory,''
said John Dorfman, president of Dorfman Investments in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In a Bloomberg News report, Dorfman noted the rise in defense
procurements during the fiscal year that ended in September, the
first in 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a bipartisan consensus that defense spending has been
cut too much,'' Dorfman said. ``This bodes well for Lockheed
Martin, the largest U.S. defense contractor.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, this is probably a matter for speculation. The
company has not confirmed published reports that it is considering
the sale, or closing, of some core operations.
</P>
<P>
   The company's problems are not new and, given the long-term
nature of aerospace and defense projects generally, the situation
isn't likely to change fundamentally any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Near term, the widely mixed opinions of 15 Wall Street analysts
who follow Lockheed Martin shares provides perhaps the best clue to
the company's investment landscape _ seven have ``hold'' ratings on
the stock, two have ``sells,'' but six have ``buy'' ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
