A8214 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-UPS-IPO-$ADV14-NY     11-12 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-UPS-IPO-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDFALL AT UPS? NOT FOR ALL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 14) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ga.)   (af)  
 By MICHAEL E. KANELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In Silicon Valley and the world of the Internet, an
initial public offering is an occasion for wild celebration, as
employees from chief marketers to mail-room assistants count their
riches.
</P>
<P>
   At UPS, that is not necessarily the case.
</P>
<P>
   The United Parcel Service offering, first traded on Wednesday,
may have been historic, but among some hourly workers, it seemed
like someone else's history.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the employees who move 12 million packages a day were
pleased with their gains from buying shares at about half the
offering price. But for others, the UPS stock sale became an
example of how a benefit for workers can become an aggravation when
their company has unsettled labor relations.
</P>
<P>
   For some of these workers, the offering, rather than creating a
shared sense of ownership and gain, may have increased tensions as
they saw how much more money was made by members of management. The
stock offering came only two years after a 15-day strike by
drivers, loaders and handlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't buy UPS stock; that's a conflict of interest with
me,'' said Willie Harris, a UPS driver for 12 years, as he waited
in line on Thursday morning at a Burger King near a dispatch center
just outside Atlanta. Not that he shuns hometown companies, he
added: ``I buy Delta stock. And Coca-Cola.''
</P>
<P>
   In the biggest initial stock offering ever, UPS sold 109.4
million shares at $50 each; the stock ended the week at $71.9375.
Many managers, who have long been able to buy stock, made hundreds
of thousands of dollars. Others, who have been eligible to buy
stock only since 1995, typically made less even if they did invest.
</P>
<P>
   Of the roughly 205,000 unionized workers at UPS, about 66,000
have bought stock. Their average holdings are about 300 shares,
yielding average gains of less than $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Many workers are still smarting over issues that were at the
heart of the 1997 strike, including wages and the company's
reliance on part-time drivers who would much rather be full-time.
</P>
<P>
   The company declined to comment. At a news conference on
Wednesday, James P. Kelly, the chairman, said, ``The relationship
with our hourly employees has definitely improved and will continue
to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   John A. Challenger, chief executive of the consulting and
outplacement company Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas, said bitterness
often lingers for years after a confrontation between labor and
management. A company should try to ease tensions by having
managers meet with workers in groups and one-on-one to build trust,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But overcoming the bitterness can be very difficult, Challenger
said, especially for workers. ``If the battle hasn't ended in your
mind, if you still feel you haven't gotten what you deserve, then
each new instance just opens the wound,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many workers who do hold stock assume that the biggest gainers
were executives. ``And that's fine,'' said Daniel Pinner, a driver
for six years. ``I think it's good for the company to have people
running it who have a big stake in it. That way, if things go
badly, they'd lose a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Without saying how much he owns, Pinner said he wasn't cashing
in just yet. ``I'm probably going to hold on,'' he said. ``It's a
good company and things seem to look good for the company's future.
I'll probably keep buying.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even Pinner is concerned about management's loyalties in the
face of ballooning stock values. ``The only danger I see,'' he
said, ``is that some of the more talented management people may see
it as a way to retire, and it wouldn't be good for any company to
lose its most talented people.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris, recalling the public support that UPS strikers received
two years ago, said he wondered whether public ownership of the
company's stock could mean greater support for management next
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they get all of you to buy stock and then if we go to
strike, we'll get booed, we'll get things thrown at us,'' he said.
In future talks, he added, the company would therefore be more
likely to take a hard line.
</P>
<P>
   Public stock ownership, however, does not appear to have reduced
popular support for, say, striking flight attendants at airlines.
Striking airline pilots, who are better paid, have attracted less
sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   At UPS, salaries for drivers, loaders and handlers start at less
than $10 an hour. While more experienced workers earn about $22 an
hour, that may not leave much leeway for investing.
</P>
<P>
   Workers like Jack Jordan, a driver for 18 years, have more
immediate concerns than shares and offerings. Steering his truck
into an office park, Jordan began pulling boxes from the shelves,
then paused to shrug. ``I don't buy stocks,'' he said. ``I just
don't mess around with it.''
</P>
<P>
   What about the chance to have made thousands of dollars on UPS
stock? Jordan nodded, acknowledging that the stock had done well.
He ventured a small smile. ``I'm not disappointed, really,'' he
said. ``It's just water under the bridge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
