<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG INCREASES IN PRODUCTIVITY BY WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most debated economics issue in America today is whether
workers are becoming ever more efficient, thanks to computers and
the Internet. And the Labor Department, in the most comprehensive
review of the data to date, says there has indeed been an
improvement in this decade, mainly in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   The review, stretching back to 1959, came attached to the
department's announcement Friday that productivity _ the key
measure of labor efficiency _ had shot up in the third quarter at
an annual rate of 4.2 percent. Workers manufactured that much more
on average for each hour on the job, or sold that much more or
increased a huge variety of services. It was the biggest quarterly
jump in nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   But quarterly productivity numbers bounce around. The third
quarter jump, for example, followed a rise of only 0.6 percent in
the second quarter. What counts are long-term trends, and the Labor
Department, using new information about the economy, revised its
productivity data back 40 years. The new set of figures showed the
1990s to be unmistakably better than the 1970s and 1980s _ pulled
up by four powerful years.
</P>
<P>
   Four-year spurts occur from time to time. There was one in the
1980s, but it was not strong enough to raise the average for the
whole decade as the last four years have done for the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one point where we can say that we are on a new
upward trend line,'' said Michael Harper, chief of the division of
productivity research at the Labor Department's Bureau of Labor
Statistics. ``But in each of the last four years we have seen a
little more evidence that we may be.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest productivity numbers seem likely to work against an
increase in interest rates when the Federal Reserve's policy makers
meet on Tuesday. More output per worker, at a moment of full
employment in the United States, reduces the odds of shortages and
rising prices, two big concerns of the Fed. What's more, retail
sales leveled off in October, remaining unchanged from September,
the Commerce Department said in a separate report Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Productivity enjoys much less public attention than inflation or
economic growth or employment. The concept is more arcane. But no
measure is more important. A nation's standard of living rises with
productivity. Given limited population growth, a nation can acquire
more goods and services only if the existing workers produce more
in a given work day.
</P>
<P>
   But the Labor Department's new numbers, for all the improvement
they display, were not enough to settle a national debate over
whether a ``new economy'' has really emerged.
</P>
<P>
   They fail to answer these questions: Does the recent jump in
productivity simply mean that companies and their workers are
stretching themselves for a while to satisfy the strong demand of a
booming economy, and when the economy cools so will their
productivity? Or is there a permanent change in which computers and
the Internet are generating the long-term efficiencies that in the
past came with the spread of railroads, the invention of
electricity and the proliferation of cars and trucks?
</P>
<P>
   Optimists like Bruce Steinberg, chief economist at Merrill Lynch
&AMP; Co., say the New Economy has indeed arrived, and if the revised
numbers fail to capture the arrival, then they are still
under-measuring productivity. ``We are on an accelerating
productivity trend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But for the skeptics, the revisions leave too much unsaid.
Productivity is calculated by adding up all the output of an
economy, expressed in dollars, and then dividing by the number of
labor hours spent to produce that output. The revisions increased
the output side of the calculation, but failed to correct a
mismeasurement of hours, says Stephen S. Roach, chief economist at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has done a terrible job in uncovering the labor
effort required to produce all the new output,'' he said, noting
that in his own case, Morgan Stanley tells the Labor Department
that he has a 40-hour-a-week schedule, which is true. But in fact
Roach works 70 or 80 hours, common practice on Wall Street and in
other industries, too.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With hours rising only slowly in the official data, unit labor
costs _ the amount spent on wages and benefits to produce each
piece of merchandise or each service _ rose a very mild 0.6 percent
in the third quarter. The increases remained similarly mild in the
revised data. Economists cite these numbers in trying to explain
the low inflation rate in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The productivity revisions announced Friday resulted in changes
only for the years after 1973. From 1959 until 1973, productivity
rose at an annual rate of 2.9 percent, the same as the old,
unrevised average. Between 1973 and 1995, however, the rate of
growth was a fairly steady 1.4 percent to 1.6 percent a year,
Harper said. That was slower, of course, than the pre-1973 number,
but a considerable improvement over the unrevised average of about
1 percent a year for the 1973 to 1995 period.
</P>
<P>
   And then in 1995 a boom kicked in. Economic growth soared and
productivity jumped to an annual growth rate of 2.6 percent from
the third quarter of 1995 through this year's third quarter, far
better than the 1.9 percent figure before the revision. For the
decade as a whole, the new productivity growth rate was 2 percent a
year, much better than the unrevised 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The productivity revisions reflect new ways of measuring the
nation's output announced recently by the Commerce Department. One
major change has been in the calculation of inflation, which has
been revised downward for the years since 1978. That raises the
dollar value of the nation's output of goods and services. The
dollar total is adjusted for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Another big change involves computer software, a huge item,
particularly in recent years. For the first time, software is being
counted as a lasting investment that adds to the nation's total
output, and therefore must be listed separately in the national
accounts, adding greatly to total output. Under the old system, the
tens of billions of dollars spent on software were considered an
expense, lost in the value of other items.
</P>
<P>
   Software, in effect, has become a capital investment, and the
rise in the productivity growth rate in the late 1990s reflects a
sharp increase in capital spending, not only for software but for
new machinery and equipment, particularly computers.
</P>
<P>
   Capital spending has contributed in the past to temporary surges
in productivity. ``What is not clear,'' said Robert Gordon, a
Northwestern University economist, ``is what would happen if we
pulled out the accelerating contribution of capital investment. How
much would be left that reflects a fundamental change brought about
by new technology analogous to the invention of the electric
motor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
