<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8226 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-LOCKHEED13-COX     11-12 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Future of Ga. Lockheed Martin plant unclear as company mulls
consolidation
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Troubled Lockheed Martin Corp. acknowledged Friday it
is considering selling or closing some of its plants, raising new
questions about the future of its Marietta, Ga. facility.
</P>
<P>
   The aerospace giant has suffered a year of financial and
operational problems, and management is ruling out nothing as part
of a broad turnaround plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is not restricting its review of possible actions
in any way,'' said Hugh Burns, a spokesman at the company's
Bethesda, Md., headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``As to whether any specific plant might be closed or
consolidated, everything is under review and no decision has been
made,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   One scenario is for the company to pull out of the Air
Force-owned Marietta plant. It could move the plant's
underperforming C-130J and F-22 programs to a Lockheed Martin
aircraft plant in Fort Worth, Texas, that has capacity to spare.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say the company could cut overhead and better
manage programs that way.
</P>
<P>
   The Marietta plant, headquarters to Lockheed Martin Aeronautical
Systems and 8,000 workers, has outlived other shutdown predictions
over the years as aircraft programs waxed and waned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's just a lot of speculating going on,'' said
Wayne Myrick, president of the Machinists union Local 709. ``It's
got a lot of good people upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Myrick said, the union ``absolutely is taking this very
seriously. We're very concerned about members' jobs.'' A downsizing
of 2,000 jobs already is under way at the plant because of slow
orders and high costs.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and politicians were divided Friday over the likelihood
of a shutdown of the Marietta plant, built during World War II to
produce B-29 bombers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of unthinkable to close such a historic facility as
Marietta, but given the financial straits of the corporation, you'd
have to say anything's possible,'' said Richard Aboulafia, an
aircraft industry analyst at Teal Group, a Washington, D.C.,
consultancy.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Bob Barr, whose district includes the Marietta plant,
downplayed the potential closing. ``These are simply rumors that we
have to put out every year,'' said Barr. ``I don't know why
everyone is so churned up over this. We're hearing rumors again.
Big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.), through a spokeswoman, expressed
similar confidence that the plant's future is secure.
</P>
<P>
   The latest flurry of speculation follows a Wall Street Journal
report that the company is considering the sale or shutdown of
``core assets,'' including aircraft plants, to boost its sagging
profits. Previously, the company's turnaround plan has involved
milder moves.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing problems recently forced Lockheed Martin to halve its
profit forecasts for 2000 and to dismiss two top executives. One
was military aircraft chief James A. ``Mickey'' Blackwell, who
oversaw the Marietta division and once worked there. Blackwell
couldn't be reached for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin's new chief financial officer, Robert Stevens,
said the company can't afford to view any part of its business with
``pure emotional affection.''
</P>
<P>
   Company officials declined interview requests Friday, but Terry
Graham, the plant's No. 2 official, issued a memo to workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As everyone knows, the corporation is going through a very
difficult time, but no decisions have been made to close or
relocate any facilities, including Marietta,'' Graham wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analyst Paul Nisbet, of JSA Research in Newport, R.I.,
said Lockheed Martin may be floating a ``trial balloon'' to gauge
the reaction of the Pentagon and Congress to a plant consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's made sense for a long time, but the politics were too
daunting in the past,'' Nisbet said. He noted that Georgia's clout
on military issues _ chiefly through former Sen. Sam Nunn and
former House Speaker Newt Gingrich _ has waned since their
departures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now things have fallen apart and they need to take actions
they should have before,'' Nisbet said. ``Politicians from Georgia
are somewhat less influential, so it's a good time to try.''
</P>
<P>
   Myrick, the union chief, said he talked Friday with Marietta
plant President Tom Burbage and was reassured, to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said if nothing happened to the C-130J or F-22 programs
they would stay in Georgia,'' Myrick said. ``Of course, neither he
nor I can say what the corporation will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Myrick said he thinks it would cost Lockheed Martin $1 billion
or more to move the Marietta assembly lines to Texas. He noted the
company has spent millions retooling the C-130J line and building
specialized F-22 facilities. The plant has won industry and
Pentagon accolades for improving efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   But it has had trouble building and sustaining political support
for either the C-130J or F-22, contributing to broader corporate
woes.
</P>
<P>
   Nisbet estimates Lockheed Martin has lost upward of $1 billion
on the C-130J program because of slow sales and high development
costs. The company developed the updated model in the mid-'90s
without any advance Pentagon orders, which meant it accepted more
financial risk than usual with a new military plane.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin has sold 90 C-130Js to date but faces a sharp
slowdown in orders over the next few years, until the Air Force
begins replacing large numbers of older C-130s. Congress approved
only two C-130Js in the fiscal 2000 defense budget, with none
requested in the Pentagon's preliminary fiscal 2001 budget.
</P>
<P>
   The company is trying to persuade the Pentagon to fund 42 of the
planes over the next five years, enough to maintain production and,
it hopes, spur more foreign orders.
</P>
<P>
   The F-22 program is an Air Force darling but has been slowed by
political attacks. After heated debate this summer that threw the
entire program into doubt, Congress allotted money for six of the
new ``air superiority'' fighters in the fiscal 2000 budget, as the
Air Force had requested.
</P>
<P>
   It refused to move the program into the full production phase,
however, which analysts say would have made it less vulnerable to
future political attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin's corporate problems are far wider. Created by
the 1994 merger of Lockheed Corp. and Martin Marietta, the company
is the nation's No. 1 defense contractor.
</P>
<P>
   Nisbet and other analysts say the company has not smoothly
managed its far-flung operations. A particular trouble spot has
been its satellite and missile defense division, based in
Sunnyvale, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Aboulafia said any drastic moves in the aircraft
division may be premature. He said both the C-130J and F-22
programs are still likely to do well long-term, while Lockheed
Martin is also vying to win a lead contract for another new
warplane, the Joint Strike Fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all that pans out, they are going to need plant capacity,''
he said. ``But it's hard to look down the road very far when Wall
Street's baying for your blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
