<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8228 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-SECURITY13-COX     11-12 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SECURITY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas taxpayers footing bill for Bush's expanded security costs
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas taxpayers have spent nearly $1.8 million
so far this year to protect Gov. George W. Bush and Lt. Gov. Rick
Perry, more than nine times the average spent annually on security
before Bush became a Republican presidential hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   Figures disclosed late Friday by the Texas Department of Public
Safety show $1,790,384 had been spent on security through late
October, compared with $186,533 during 1995, Bush's first year as
governor.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 and 1997, the costs were $153,900 and $164,529,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1998, when Bush was considering a run at the
presidential nomination, the security costs had risen to $285,874,
according to the DPS figures.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign had previously said they had no plans to
reimburse taxpayers for the costs of presidential campaign security
and added that his Democratic predecessor, former Gov. Ann
Richards, traveled at taxpayer expense to help Bill Clinton win the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But state Democrats lashed out Friday at Bush, contending he
should reimburse Texans from his $57 million campaign warchest.
</P>
<P>
   Disclosure of the figures by DPS came as the result of requests
filed in July under the Texas Public Information Act by the Austin
American-Statesman, The Associated Press and Dallas-Fort Worth
television station KTVT _ after Bush launched his cross-country
campaign for the Republican presidential nomination with DPS
plainclothes security officers in tow.
</P>
<P>
   The DPS and Bush's office initially refused to make the
information public, claiming that allowing Texas taxpayers to know
how much was being spent would impair efforts to protect Bush. But
state Attorney General John Cornyn disagreed, ruling on Nov. 2 that
the information should be made public.
</P>
<P>
   Eight working days later, the DPS did so, just before closing
time Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, however, also ruled that other security information such
as the number of troopers assigned to protect Bush, the salaries
and overtime spent on his protection detail, phone records and
travel expense details could be kept secret.
</P>
<P>
   DPS spokesman Tom Vinger said late Friday he could not elaborate
on the figures, the first disclosure of security expenses since
Bush hit the presidential campaign trail in June. At the time, DPS
officials acknowledged that the size of his security detail had
increased.
</P>
<P>
   While DPS officials previously have acknowledged that the added
expenses for security were coming from the agency's $330.5 million
budget, Vinger said he could not discuss details.
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides Friday night defended the additional security costs.
Campaign spokesman Scott McClellan said there was no plan to
reimburse the state for security that historically has been
provided to a governor by the DPS.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the legal responsibility of the Texas Department of
Public Safety to protect the governor at all times, whether the
governor is in state or out of state,'' said gubernatorial press
secretary Linda Edwards. ``In the past, the Department of Public
Safety has protected other Texas governors when traveling out of
state, including Governor Ann Richards when she traveled to
campaign for Bill Clinton in 1992.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry and his top aides could not immediately be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democratic Party Chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm blasted
Bush for spending state taxpayers' money ``on his own personal
ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is forcing the taxpayers to pick up the tab for
a service he could easily afford to pay out of his huge pot of
campaign money,'' she said. ``The governor needs to be protected,
but it's a shame he's taking money that could be used for public
schools and children's health care . . . If Bush were the big
fiscal conservative he claims to be, he wouldn't be sticking the
taxpayers with a bill that big.''
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, U.S. Secret Service protection is offered to
``major presidential candidates'' _ usually about the time the
primaries are held. Federal taxpayers pay for Secret Service
security.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has not offered to reimburse Texas taxpayers for the
DPS' extra security expenses associated with his presidential
campaign, federal campaign filings show his campaign has repaid at
least one out-of-state law enforcement agency for campaign security
_ in New Hampshire, where a primary is scheduled Feb. 1, 2000. In
June, the Bush campaign reimbursed the Goffstown Police Department
a total of $324 for two campaign stops.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks since he launched his GOP presidential bid, Bush
has traveled extensively outside Texas. During the past week alone,
he has been in Florida, South Carolina, Hew Hampshire, Michigan and
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Bush announced he would forego his gubernatorial salary
of $316.01 a day for each day he campaigned outside Texas. On those
days, Perry is paid the gubernatorial rate.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
