<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8231 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SC-CONFEDERATE-FLAG-1     11-12 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-CONFEDERATE-FLAG-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH CAROLINA IN QUANDARY OVER CONFEDERATE FLAG CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 4th graf to change `is debating' to `has debated'; there is
currently no bill under consideration)   (bl)  
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Carrying the battle flag of the Confederacy
through this birthplace of the Civil War, the hundreds of men
parading in their gray uniforms and the women in their black
widow's weeds knew exactly what was at stake in their struggle over
the memory of an earlier era.
</P>
<P>
   Their immediate journey was to rebury the remains of 22
Confederate sailors and a 3-year-old boy whose first resting place
had mistakenly been covered by the football stadium at the Citadel,
the military college here.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the marchers and the 2,500 others who joined
them at Magnolia Cemetery on Friday were there to invest the
history and the symbols of the region with tangible meaning, which
at that moment were under attack by many who see them in far
less-glorious terms.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few hours earlier, Gov. Jim Hodges had spent the morning
asking business leaders to help him find an honorable way to remove
the battle flag from atop the State Capitol. It has flown there,
usually in the face of many offended people, since 1962. The
Legislature, which has debated bills to remove the flag, has
resisted efforts to take down the flag, even after South Carolina
became the last state flying it.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious of those efforts began this summer, when the
national and local branches of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People gave up trying to negotiate the
removal of the flag and announced an economic boycott of South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing the effects of the boycott and the growing damage to the
state's reputation, an increasing number of organizations have
called for the flag's removal, including the South Carolina Chamber
of Commerce, the state Baptist Convention and Bob Jones University,
a bastion of the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   But even some legislators who might be inclined to compromise
say they won't do so while an economic musket is pointed at their
heads, and much of that traditional, prideful stubbornness was on
display Friday at Magnolia Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, entirely white, was hardly representative of the
state, but many of those present said they had felt a twinge of
resentment when a national organization tried to tell them what
symbols their state was allowed to display.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of South Carolina have the right to choose what
flags they want to fly,'' said George Bragdon, a warehouse
supervisor from Lancaster, who was dressed in the gray flannel of
the 12th South Carolina Brigade, Company I, in which his
great-grandfather had served. ``No one from any other state can
tell us what to do. I would remind the NAACP that the South was
willing to go to war to protect its states' rights, and we are
still stubborn enough not to give in to this boycott.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodges, though he is eager to have the flag removed, essentially
had the same message in the speeches he has given all week,
including one Friday morning to the state Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NAACP boycott has drawn attention to the problem, which
has been helpful in trying to move it towards closure,'' Hodges
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is clear that in my discussions with legislators who
hold the cards in whether or not this bill will pass, that the
boycott now stands as an obstacle,'' he added. ``Clearly, the only
way to show progress on this issue, I believe, is for the NAACP to
suspend its boycott as the first step towards resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   If the NAACP agrees to do so, the governor said, he will not
only press the Legislature to move the flag elsewhere on the
statehouse grounds, but will work to enact a state holiday honoring
Martin Luther King Jr. and to build a museum in Columbia that would
reflect the heritage of both blacks and whites in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But the NAACP has rejected the proposal and intends to continue
its boycott.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight James, executive director of the South Carolina
Conference of Branches of the NAACP, said Friday that it was
ludicrous to try to appease blacks with the offer of a King holiday
and questioned whether an end to the boycott would lead to
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no discussions or negotiations before we called for
these sanctions, and there wouldn't be any if we withdrew,'' James
said. ``We are committed to standing firm to the end, and it is up
to the leadership of the state to change.''
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP's effort is the latest attempt to remove the flag
since it was put up in 1962 as a gesture of defiance to the civil
rights movement. Most recently, then-Gov. David Beasley led a vocal
campaign in 1997 but the Legislature rejected his proposal to take
down the flag.
</P>
<P>
   James and other proponents of removing the flag see it as a
symbol of slavery, and say the flag's presence over the seat of
government is indicative of the racial climate in the state. Many
Southerners, while acknowledging that the flag has been
appropriated by white hate groups, insist that it is not a racist
symbol, but rather a banner under which many of their relatives
fought and died.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a soldier's flag, and that's why it's wrapped around
those caskets right there,'' said Randy Burbage, president of the
Confederate Heritage Trust, the group that dug up the sailors'
remains from under the stadium and organized the reinterment.
``This is our heritage, and if the flag comes down, then next the
monuments will come down, and then the street names, and then we
will forget our history. We can't forget that this was America's
greatest tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Burbage wept as he helped lower the pine caskets into a long
trench grave at Magnolia Cemetery, which was full of 135-year-old
monuments to fallen rebels. The remains were discovered in June
after the Heritage Trust, working with a state archaeologist,
realized that a cemetery from the 1860s was beneath the stadium,
which was built in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   At Friday's ceremony, each of the flags over the coffins was
carefully folded by re-enactors in Confederate uniforms, and each
was handed to a woman dressed in the black hoop skirt and veil.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the crowd sang ``Dixie,'' the soldiers let loose a rebel
yell and there was a barrage of gunpowder salutes from rifles and
artillery pieces.
</P>
<P>
   One state official looking on let loose a barrage of his own,
his mocking voice a reminder of the deep trench that still divides
the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NAACP doesn't care about the flag, they're just doing this
to raise money,'' said state Sen. Arthur Ravenel, a Republican who
represents the Charleston area. ``I would say that not only will
the state not negotiate under threat of a boycott, but we'll never
vote to take down that flag at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
