People try to hail cabs on Friday in Midtown. Operation Refusal,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's plan to crack down on taxi drivers who
refuse to pick up blacks, was in full swing on Friday, with scores
of undercover officers and taxi inspectors hitting the streets.
(Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 14 --
NITEOUT-DOGMA-DIRECTOR, 11-12 -- Kevin Smith, the director of
``Dogma,'' at his New Jersey church. Going to Mass has lately
become exciting for Smith, thanks to the prospect of confrontation
arising from his film. ``If I listened to the nattering nabobs of
negativism, I wouldn't be here today,'' says Smith, 29. (Norman Y.
Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) QUINCY, Mass. -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- MUSIC-LETTER-BOS,
11-12 -- Kay Hanley and Michael Eisenstein - leaders of the Boston
rock band Letters To Cleo - play with their 4-month-old daughter
Zoe at home. ``A month and a half ago, I was nowheresville in my
feelings toward the band,'' says Ms. Hanley. ``Then all of sudden
there's the new batch of songs, and we're rehearsing, and we've got
a big rock show!'' (Janet Knott/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- KOREA-MASSACRE, 11-12 --
South Korean survivors of an alleged mass killing of civilian
refugees by U.S. troops at No Gun Ri during the Korean War are
accompanied by South Korean government officials, as they arrive to
the Pentagon on Friday. At left is Charles Cragin, deputy
undersecretary of Defense. Second from left is Chung Eun-yong, one
of four survivors of No Gun Ri who met with U.S. military
officials. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- BANKING-LAW, 11-12 --
President Clinton speaks with Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan, right, as Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, left, and
Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., look on after Clinton signed the
Financial Services Modernization Act of 1999 on Friday. The bill
repeals parts of the 1933 Glass-Steagall Act and the 1956 Bank
Holding Company Act to level the domestic playing field for U.S
financial firms and allow them to compete better in the evolving
global financial marketplace. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LINCOLN, Mass. -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- THOREAU-SCHOLAR-BOS,
11-12 --Bradley Dean has produced a ``new'' book by the great
Transcendentalist. By deciphering Henry David Thoreau's crimped
handwriting and reorganizing the jumbled manuscript, Dean has
resurrected ``Wild Fruits,'' the ambitious book Thoreau was working
on when he died of tuberculosis in 1862. (Janet Knott/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOSTON -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- DIGITAL-LIGHT-BOS, 11-12 --
George G. Mueller of Color Kinetics stands by a display of the
company's digital light bulbs. A tiny embedded chip lets users
generate one of 16.7 million hues at the touch of a switch. ``What
investors like about us is that we're a high-tech company that has
revenues, products, and patents,'' says Mueller. ``We're not an
Internet company that sells a hope and a prayer but has no revenues
and little long-term sustainability.'' (Janet Knott/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- INDONESIA-U.S., 11-12 --
President Clinton raeches out to Indonesian President Abdurrahman
Wahid just before their meeting in the Oval Office on Friday.
Clinton said Friday the U.S. would support Indonesia's fight
against corruption, but stopped short of embracing Wahid's plan to
pardon former President Suharto if he is convicted of stealing from
the government. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) TEHRAN, Iran -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 14
-- IRAN-JEWS-COX, 11-12 -- Benjamin Rankinkar, 18, looks over a
lesson in Talmud with two fellow students at the Abi Shami
Synagogue in the Iranian capital. Accustomed to cautious but
prosperous lives, Iranian Jews now wonder if the rules have
changed. Many consider joining relatives in North America, Europe
or Israel. (Larry Kaplow/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- OBIT-GALIMIR-B&AMP;W, 11-12 --
Felix Galimir performing in 1992. Galimir, a violinist who was one
of the last links to the vital musical world of prewar Vienna, and
a chamber music player who was revered by several generations of
instrumentalists as a demanding and inspiring coach, died on
Wednesday at his home in Manhattan. He was 89. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- ALBRIGHT-U.N.-DUES, 11-11
-- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright during testimony before
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee in October. Albright has
told the White House that she is willing to take the political heat
from abortion rights groups if the administration compromises in
its budget talks with Congress to free up a deal to pay off nearly
$1 billion the U.S. owes the U.N. (Shana Raab /New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) FRISCO, Texas -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SAT., NOV. 13
-- CARIBBEAN-ROCKET-2-COX, 11-12 -- Beal Aerospace manufactures
large-scale space vehicles at its facility in Frisco. Plans to
assemble huge rockets in the Caribbean island of St. Croix and
launch commercial satellites from a nearby island have set off
fireworks on the laid-back vacation paradise (Beal Aerospace
photo/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ST. CROIX, U.S. Virgin Islands -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- ADV.
FOR SAT., NOV. 13 -- CARIBBEAN-ROCKET-1-COX, 11-12 -- An artist's
rendering of a Beal Aerospaces BA-2 rocket during launch from a
Caribbean island. Plans by a Texas entrepreneur to assemble huge
rockets here and launch commercial satellites from a nearby island
have set off fireworks on this laid-back vacation paradise. (Beal
Aerospace photo/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LOS ANGELES -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- FASHION-KNITS-LADN, 11-12
-- Actress Lily Mariye, who plays a nurse on the show ``ER,'' joins
the latest knitting craze in her ruffled gray sweater by XOXO, with
snakeskin print jeans, by Paris Blues, both from Robinson's May.
(John Lazar/Los Angeles Daily News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LOS ANGELES -- Nov. 12, 1999 --
FASHION-KNITS-MAIN-2-LADN, 11-12 -- Actress Lily Mariye, who plays
a nurse on the show ``ER,'' and her husband Boney James who is a
jazz saxophonist, wear knits for the season. She's wearing an
alpine design by Liz Claiborne and he is in a turtle neck sweater
from Norstrom. Knit scarves are from Robinsons-May. (John Lazar/Los
Angeles Daily News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LOS ANGELES -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- FASHION-KNITS-MAIN-LADN,
11-12 --Actress Lily Mariye, who plays a nurse on the show ``ER,''
gets wrapped up in pashmina-mania with a lavender design by Bindya
over a Christian Lacroix two-Piece knit dress, all from Nordstrom.
John Lazar/Los Angeles Daily News Photo)
</P>
