<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 11/12/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) UNDATED -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- OBIT-KRAMER-B&AMP;W, 11-12 --
Robert Kramer, an American movie director whose portrayals of
militants caught up in the antiwar movement of the late 1960s and
early 1970s earned him a prominent place in modern political
cinema, died on Wednesday in a hospital in Rouen, France, at the
age of 60. Friends gave the cause of death as meningitis. (New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) CLAREMONT, Calif. -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
NOV. 14 -- BIZ-PROFILE-DRUCKER, 11-12 -- Peter F. Drucker, the
father of modern management who turns 90 on Friday, signing copies
of some of his 31 books after teaching a class last week at
Claremont Graduate School in California. ``The unique 20th-century
creation, the corporation, is not going to survive in the 21st
century,'' he says. (Lee Celano/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) FOUNTAIN VALLEY, Calif. -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR
SUN., NOV. 14 -- BIZ-CEO-BOARDS, 11-12 -- David Frosh was on the
board of directors before being chosen president of Camdata, a
software company in Fountain Valley. ``No one inside was ready yet
to be president,'' he says. After setting aside a couple of seats
for insiders, most companies fill out their boards with experienced
executives from other industries who can offer valuable advice and
look out for the interests of shareholders. (Lee Celano/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) UNDATED -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 14 --
BIZ-5-QUESTIONS-B&AMP;W, 11-12 -- Donald G. Ogilvie, executive vice
president of the American Bankers Association. ``The third-largest
provider of ATM machines in the country is EDS, which is not a
bank,'' he says. ``They put them all over the country and charge
you to use them.'' (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) SMITH POINT, New York -- Nov. 12, 1999 --
AIRCRASH-COUNSELING-3, 11-12 -- Relatives of the victims of TWA
Flight 800 on the beach at Smith Point during a memorial service in
July, 1996. Saying only they truly understand the intense grief,
numbness and denial that come when an airliner goes down, relatives
of plane crash victims are banding together to form ``grief
mentoring'' networks for those left behind in airline disasters.
(Steve Berman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- AIRCRASH-COUNSELING-2,
11-12 -- Lynn Ross with her dog in their Manhattan apartment
earlier this week. Ross, a Manhattan garment merchandiser, lost the
man she had lived with for eight years, Joseph LaMotta, 49, in the
Swissair crash last year off Nova Scotia, Canada. After having
difficulty recovering from her loss, Ms. Ross called Access, a
support group set up by relatives of victims from previous air
crashes. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- AIRCRASH-COUNSELING-1,
11-12 -- Heidi Snow, who lost her fiance, Michel Brieistroff, a
French hockey player, aboard the Paris-bound TWA Flight 800 in
1996, in her workspace at a friend's apartment in Manhattan. Ms.
Snow founded a nonprofit group and an Internet website to reachout
to mourners who lost friends or loved-ones in airplane crashes.
Saying only they truly understand the intense grief, numbness and
denial that come when an airliner goes down, relatives of plane
crash victims are banding together to form ``grief mentoring''
networks for those left behind in airline disasters. (Edward
Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) MOSCOW -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- KHRUSHSCHEV-POET-B&AMP;W, 11-12
-- Nikita S. Khrushchev, dressing down the poet Andrei Voznesensky
at a Kremlin meeting in 1963. Last month, Voznesensky, now 63,
obtained the tape of the meeting, which was unearthed by in a
closed government archive in Penza, Russia. Khrushchev's explosive
outburst was seen as a calculated attempt to silence artists and
writers like Voznesensky, whose poetry recitals were packing
stadiums. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 14 --
SUB-BUTLER-BOOK-2, 11-12 -- Paul Burrell, child of an English
mining town, followed his dream and found a princess at Buckingham
Palace. He has written a new book, ``In the Royal Manner: Expert
Advice on Etiquette and Entertaining From the Former Butler to
Diana, Princess of Wales.'' According to Burrell, ``style is not
the exclusive preserve of the rich and the famous.'' (Barbara
Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 14 --
SUB-BUTLER-BOOK-1, 11-12 -- Paul Burrell, butler to the late
Princess of Wales, at work in a castle without a dining hall.
``I've been offered a million pounds to tell my story, and I can't
do that,'' he says of his close relationship with Princess Diana.
``If I gave it away, who would I be? I wouldn't be the person she
called 'my rock,' would I?'' (Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 14 --
SKIN-DOCTORS-3, 11-12 -- At Ajune, a spa for cosmetic-surgery
patients which is part-owned by a dermatologist, a client is
treated with hydrotherapy. Today's skin doctors, repackaged as
beauty gurus, are marketing their own cosmetics, promising to
reverse the effects of aging and - the latest trend - opening their
own day spas. (Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 14 --
SKIN-DOCTORS-2, 11-12 -- Dr. Bruce Katz gives laser treatments and
sells ``cosmeceuticals'' in spalike offices at the Juva Skin and
Laser Center in Manahattan. Enter the age of the new dermatology,
the once humble medical specialty that is elbowing aside plastic
surgery as a glamour profession. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) MIAMI -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 14 --
SKIN-DOCTORS-1, 11-12 -- The face of 50? Dr. Frederic Brandt, a
Miami dermatologist, is a testimonial to Botox. His own products
will be sold at Bergdorf Goodman. (Cindy Karp/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- BANKING-LAW-2, 11-12 --
President Clinton reacts to applause by Congressional lawmakers
after signing the Financial Services Modernization Act of 1999 on
Friday . Also taking part in the ceremony was Chairman of the
Federal Reserve Alan Greenspan, far left. The bill repeals parts of
the 1933 Glass-Steagall Act and the 1956 Bank Holding Company Act
to level the domestic playing field for U.S financial firms and
allow them to compete better in the evolving global financial
marketplace. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 14 --
BIRTHDAY-BASHES, 11-12 -- Maggie, 13, left, had a dozen of her best
friends over for a slumber party at FAO Schwarz. Writers about
raising children may preach modesty in birthday parties or advise
inviting one guest for each year celebrated; but all over New York,
parents are ignoring them. (Rebecca Cooney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) OVERLAND PARK, Kan. -- Nov. 12, 199 --
TOY-COLLECTIBLE-KAN, 11-11 -- Hot Wheels toy car collector Chris
Marshall shows a one-of-a-kind, hot-pink die-cast prototype of a
1969 Volkswagen Beach Bomb van he has agreed to sell to Hot Wheels
for $72,000. The price, believed to be the largest ever offered for
a Hot Wheels car, seemed ``a little high'' to Jon Brecka, who
writes a monthly Hot Wheels column for Toy Cars and Vehicles. ``But
it's like an art piece,'' Brecka said. ``It's worth what anybody
will pay for it.'' (Talis Bergmanis/The Kansas City Star) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., NOV. 14 --
BODY-MIND-WORKOUTS, 11-12 -- Nathalie Levy-Koffler teaches krav
maga. Though Tae-Bo's 15 minutes seem to be up, it has produced
spinoffs that fuse American fitness with ethnic cultural
traditions, promising not only to strengthen the body but also to
integrate it with the mind. Both capoiera from Brazil and krav maga
from Israel claim to achieve this connection. (Nancy Siesel/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- POKEMON-FAD-2, 11-12 --
Julia Castro, 8, holds Pokemon cards she received after buying
tickets to see ``Pokemon: The First Movie'' on Thursday. The
recently opened movie is part of a carefully orchestrated effort to
prolong the life of a fad indefinitely. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Nov. 12, 1999 -- POKEMON-FAD-1, 11-12 -- Ben
Barasch, 13, and his friend Henry Haber, try to buy tickets for the
1:30 p.m. showing of ``Pokemon: The First Movie,'' on Thursday.
Haber and Barasch said they took advantage of being let out early
from school because of a faculty meeting to see the movie. However
the theater told them that children unaccompanied by an adult can
only purchase tickets after 2:30 p.m. The rule was instituted by
the theater to prevent truency. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BRAINTREE, Mass. -- Nov. 12, 1999 --
LIBRARY-OPENING-FLOATER -- Jack Bourikas, 3 months, naps in his
seat, while his mother, Janet, and brother, James, look through the
stacks in the children's section of Braintree's library. The
library reopened on Friday after an overhaul that included tearing
down the existing structure and rebuilding the new library on the
same site at a cost of more that $5 million dollars. (Janet
Knott/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
