<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8236 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-N     11-12 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHT FANS ARE SPLIT BETWEEN SENTIMENT AND SENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The heavyweight championship unification rematch
between Lennox Lewis and Evander Holyfield at the Thomas and Mack
Center on Saturday night is forcing boxing fans to choose between
their heads and their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   The bettors, who work these things out with their heads, are
picking Lewis, the World Boxing Council champion. But Holyfield,
the World Boxing Association and International Boxing Federation
champion, is the sentimental favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' perceived advantage in this rematch is based on his
performance against Holyfield in their first bout in March at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis fought a tactically sound fight, using his jab and reach
advantage to neutralize Holyfield. It seemed Lewis had done enough
to win the bout, but it was ruled a draw when the three judges
differed on what they saw. One judge had Holyfield winning, one
judge had Lewis winning and the third judge had the fight even.
</P>
<P>
   After having watched Holyfield dominate Mike Tyson in two
fights, Holyfield's fans could not have imagined that he would
perform in such lackluster way against Lewis in such a big fight.
It appeared that age was finally catching up on Holyfield, who is
37.
</P>
<P>
   One compelling aspect of the rematch is whether Lewis (34-1-1)
can top his first performance against Holyfield and whether
Holyfield (36-3-1) has enough left to sustain his warrior image.
The main event is expected to begin around midnight on the East
Coast and will be broadcast on pay-per-view by TVKO.
</P>
<P>
   If both boxers fight at their absolute best, many boxing people
believe that Lewis, who is 6 feet 5 inches tall and weighs 242
pounds, will defeat Holyfield, who is 6-2 and 217 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all things are equal, a good big man will always beat a
good small man,'' Emanuel Steward, Lewis' trainer, said.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield said he made several mistakes in the first fight that
he would correct in the rematch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't aggressive enough,'' he said. ``I didn't move my
head. I got hit too much. He controlled the range and I didn't
fight the fight I wanted to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield could not get inside Lewis' jab the last time and
seemed to have no strategy to get around it. Lewis is hard to hit,
because he leans back in his stance, Don Turner, Holyfield's
trainer, said. But that stance also makes it hard for Lewis to land
an effective right hand, Turner said. Holyfield and Turner have
worked on several tactics to get at Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working on attacking from angles and getting in
close,'' Turner said. ``You can tell him what to do. I can tell him
what to do. Everybody can tell him what to do. But in the final
analysis, he is the one to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the last fight, Lewis attacked Holyfield, calling him a
hypocrite, because Holyfield was espousing his Christian beliefs
while he had had a number of children out of wedlock. That prompted
Holyfield to predict a third-round knockout. After the knockout
failed to occur, Holyfield became frustrated and even thought about
quitting during the fight.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Holyfield has been toying with Lewis' head, because
he wants Lewis to fight in a manner that will be conducive to
Holyfield's style. Holyfield chided Lewis for taking a conservative
approach in the first fight and for not trying harder to knock him
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious that the winners in life that stand out are the
people who take chances,'' Holyfield said. ``Lennox had the perfect
opportunity of a lifetime to be the undisputed heavyweight
champion. He didn't because he didn't want to get caught. We all
might get caught. You have to take chances to be the very best you
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Those were fighting words for Lewis. ``When we go out in the
first round it's going to be fireworks,'' Lewis said. ``I'm going
to go after him in the first round to see what he's got.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis added: ``I think we're going to go after it a bit more.
I'll be right in his face. He's not going to have to look for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The cliche that the style of the fighter makes the fight
actually applies in this case. The styles of Holyfield and Lewis
clashed in the first bout and made for an ugly fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a fighter pressures me and comes forward, it's a lot
easier for me,'' Holyfield said. ``When a guy isn't aggressive, I
get lured into a lazy posture.''
</P>
<P>
   By nature, Lewis is not a foolhardy fighter, and few people
believe he will wade in against Holyfield with reckless abandon.
But even if Lewis does, he said he is not worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander doesn't knock anyone out with one punch,'' Lewis said.
``He knocks people out with 15 punches. I'm not afraid of his one
punch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
