<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8242 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-COUNCIL-OF-CHURCHES-N     11-12 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNCIL-OF-CHURCHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID FINANCIAL CRISIS, CHURCH COUNCIL ELECTS NEW LEADERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif, Pa.)   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ In the 49 years since its founding, the National
Council of Churches has distinguished itself by strongly supporting
civil rights legislation, helping resettle many thousands of
refugees in the United States and sponsoring two influential Bible
translations that have sold nearly 70 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, with the organization's leaders meeting here to
celebrate the upcoming golden anniversary, the council faced a
financial crisis and the question of what role it should play in an
ecumenical movement it once helped lead but which has moved far
beyond it.
</P>
<P>
   Signaling a desire to begin a new chapter, the council turned to
new leadership, under two men as well known in the secular world as
they are in religious life.
</P>
<P>
   In the final session of its conference Friday morning, the
council's governing General Assembly elected a new
general-secretary, or top officer, the Rev. Robert W. Edgar, 56, a
United Methodist minister who served in Congress from 1975 to '87
as a Democrat representative from Pennsylvania's historically
Republican 7th District. Edgar, who was named to a four-year term,
was selected by a search committee formed a year ago. Edgar, who
spent the past decade as president of Claremont School of Theology
in Claremont, Calif., will assume the job on Jan. 1, succeeding the
Rev. Joan B. Campbell, who stepped down after two terms.
</P>
<P>
   The previous evening, the council held a worship service to
install Andrew Young, the former U.S. representative to the United
Nations and an ordained United Church of Christ minister, as the
council's new president. The service took place in Cleveland's
Roman Catholic Cathedral of St. John the Evangelist, with the call
to worship led by Bishop Anthony M. Pilla, and it offered a
tantalizing vision of how broad the ecumenical movement might be in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The council represents only a partial vision of American
Christianity, with 35 member denominations _ mainline Protestant,
predominately African-American and Eastern Orthodox. It does not
include Roman Catholic, among other churches.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Edgar said the council had a ``fairly clear
vision'' of itself in its first three decades, especially in the
1960s when the struggle for civil rights for black Americans was at
its height. Since then, he said, the council has ``done good work,
but has been invisible at the local level.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgar said he would like to help the council offer greater
support and encouragement in cooperation to local councils of
churches. He also said he wanted to ask the member denominations
what they thought the ecumenical movement could be and ``then shape
the NCC to meet that need.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgar arrived at Claremont in 1990, when he said the school's
endowment had been reduced to less than $4 million, from more than
$7 million. He will leave the school, he said, with the endowment
at $22 million, several buildings renovated and the budget
balanced.
</P>
<P>
   Such experience would seem vital in taking charge of the
council. The organization is facing a deficit estimated at $3.5
million in an annual budget of nearly $70 million, a shortage
officials say that resulted largely from the expense of an
examination by outside consultants and a recommended overhaul of
the council's financial operations.
</P>
<P>
   Concern among denominations over the council's financial
management peaked this fall when the United Methodist Church, a
major contributor, said it would withhold a payment of more than
$300,000 until the council had its fiscal house in order. The money
is still being withheld.
</P>
<P>
   Council officials say the staff will be reduced through
elimination of vacant positions, attrition through retirements and
layoffs. It is a course that would echo cuts made earlier this
decade by several major Protestant churches at their national
headquarters, as they struggled with their own financial crises.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Campbell, general-secretary since 1991, said she thought
part of the council's problem, shared by many national
denominations, resulted from a trend within organized religion, as
Americans increasingly prefer to see their donations go to causes
at a local level or to a specific need, such as help for victims of
a natural disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our system, we have very modest _ and less and less _
unrestricted money'' for general operations, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Wes Granberg-Michelson, general-secretary of the
Reformed Church in America and a chairman of a committee formed to
help the council restructure itself financially, said that while no
one should underestimate ``the sense of crisis'' within the
organization, the council's leaders had nonetheless reached a
consensus this week on steps to turn this around. They should put
the council on a sound financial basis, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the council's difficulties might also lie in the very
success of promoting understanding and cooperation among the
different faiths. Rather than a single, centralized organization
like the council leading the movement, important ecumenical work is
now being carried on by churches at the local level, and by
denominations that forge formal ties with each other. There is also
a wider cast of potential partners for ecumenical efforts than
there was 50 years ago, particularly among Catholics, evangelical
Protestants and Pentecostals.
</P>
<P>
   Another ecumenical organization attempting a transition to a new
era, the World Council of Churches, is further along in the
process. It is also a half-century old and now represents nearly
340 denominations. Both the National and World Councils were
founded largely by Protestants in a bygone era when their churches
were dominant religious forces in their societies.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Konrad Raiser, the World Council's general-secretary,
said in an interview this week that that organization had been
trying to shift its center of gravity and adopt a broader vision,
so that its member churches _ not the organization's own agencies _
set the agenda, while it reaches out to other Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really matters is to look at the council as a fellowship
of churches,'' he said, referring to the World Council. ``Our
earlier understanding was very much focused around the council as
an advocate of issues, an initiator of programs that were in some
ways seen as a challenge to the churches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
