<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8246 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-KARMAZIN-CBS-ART-4TAK     11-12 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KARMAZIN-CBS-ART-4TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHIEF INTENT ON RAISING EYEBROWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of comparison of largest media companies;
Curriculum Vitae; Mel's investments is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 14)  
 (af)  
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One recent afternoon, Mel Karmazin, the chairman and
chief executive of CBS, stormed through the office of the network's
late founder, William S. Paley, on the 35th floor of Black Rock,
the CBS headquarters in Midtown Manhattan, and collapsed into a
chair in the adjoining conference room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a busy day,'' he said, fiddling with his silk tie in
a gesture of mock fatigue. ``First I worked on Letterman's
monologue. Then I wrote all of Howard Stern's jokes for tomorrow.
And then, I programmed all the radio stations.''
</P>
<P>
   No one present _ Karmazin's public relations envoy, a reporter
and a secretary standing at the door _ cracked a smile. It seemed
almost plausible.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Karmazin, a former radio advertising salesman
who next year will become the chief operating officer of
Viacom-CBS, one of the world's largest producers of news and
entertainment, was virtually unknown outside the tiny, tightknit
radio industry. Now he is the putative heir to Sumner M. Redstone,
76, Viacom's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Yet already Karmazin is talking about rising further. ``When
Jack Welch retires,'' he said, referring to John F. Welch Jr., the
chairman of General Electric, which owns the rival NBC, ``I plan to
buy NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not necessarily kidding. He said he believed that
Washington could be persuaded to further deregulate the media
industry, especially as television audiences continued to migrate
to cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   And this is not the first time since the Viacom-CBS merger was
announced in September that Karmazin has gone window-shopping:
according to several reports, he has his eye on America Online as
an acquisition candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But Karmazin's all-consuming aspirations raise several
questions. What exactly has he accomplished in his three years at
CBS? Is his background in advertising broad enough to run not only
a network, always considered a public trust, but also a
soon-to-be-merged company that will have an $80 billion market
capitalization and revenues of $19 billion from movies,
broadcasting, cable, publishing and music networks?
</P>
<P>
   Put bluntly, can Viacom-CBS be run successfully by a man who has
never seen a television pilot, has rarely made programming
decisions and has never supervised creative people on a daily
basis? Will his methods of bone-deep cost-cutting and micromanaging
work at a company the size of Viacom-CBS? And just what is he
thinking about the future of the lightning-paced media industry?
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin, who leads a quiet life for a media mogul, is a
reluctant celebrity, uncomfortable speaking about himself. He is,
for example, reputed to be a voracious reader, but when asked about
his choices, he snapped: ``I'm not going to tell you what books I
read. I'm not Oprah. Oprah, you should care about what books she
reads. If I were going to form a book club and make lots of money
off it, then I would tell you what books I read.''
</P>
<P>
   (His example shows that he is not a man to miss an opportunity
for free promotion. King World _ the distributor of ``The Oprah
Winfrey Show'' _ agreed to merge with CBS seven months ago in a
stock swap valued at $2.5 billion.)
</P>
<P>
   When Karmazin does talk about himself, he sometimes seems
awkward, more like a hyperactive 10-year-old boy than a 56-year-old
chief executive. He hates to sleep, saying: ``Why sleep? It's too
boring.'' So it's not surprising that he rises at 4:30 a.m.,
without an alarm clock, and rarely takes a vacation, despite owning
a beach house at the Jersey Shore.
</P>
<P>
   But his history gives some clues about what he will do at
Viacom-CBS, an entity that Karmazin fondly calls the ``largest
advertising platform in the world,'' where he will split duties
with Redstone. It is an advertising behemoth, he has said, that
guarantees ``unprecedented cross-promotional opportunities around
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   For Karmazin, stock price is an obsession, ``shareholder value''
a mantra he often drops into conversation, and advertising is king.
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin's roots in advertising go way back. He grew up in Long
Island City, Queens, and attended P.S. 1 there. His mother worked
in a factory while his father drove a taxi. During high school,
Karmazin was a typist at an ad agency in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Universally known as Mel (reporters who use his full name,
Melvin Alan, receive a phone call from a CBS spin doctor with this
reprimand: ``Ted Turner is not Theodore Turner. Walt Disney is not
Walter Disney. And Mel Karmazin is not Melvin.''), Karmazin
attended Pace University at night while he worked as an advertising
salesman by day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only day I stayed awake in college was the lecture about
Supply and Demand 101,'' he said. His first CBS job, at $17,500 a
year, was selling ads for the radio division. In the late 1960s,
when his commission exceeded $70,000, his boss balked at his cut;
Karmazin soon left to work for John W. Kluge at Metromedia, the
broadcasting company. He married, had two children _ his son owns a
small radio broadcasting company in Wisconsin _ and, a few years
ago, divorced.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast advertising sales creates a particularly aggressive,
jumpy kind of sales representative, said Norman Pattiz, an old
friend who is chairman of Westwood One, the largest radio network
in the country and the country's largest supplier of local traffic
and news to radio stations. (CBS owns 13 percent of the company's
stock and controls 10 percent of the voting power.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't sell yesterday's time,'' he explained. ``So it
creates a very intense kind of person. You need to know two things
to be a great salesperson. You need to know the business, which Mel
does. And you need to ingratiate yourself to the people you are
doing business with. And Mel does that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Karmazin was the chief executive of the Infinity
Broadcasting Co., which then owned 44 radio stations around the
country. He had taken Infinity public in 1992 for $17.50 a share,
then sold it to CBS in 1996 for $170 a share, securing his
reputation on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   That year, using a business strategy that has since become his
trademark, Karmazin approached CBS, which merged with Westinghouse
in 1995, and proposed that Infinity buy the company. Instead, CBS
acquired Infinity for $4.9 billion that June, and Karmazin came
aboard to run the combined radio operations of Infinity,
Westinghouse and CBS, along with its outdoor advertising business.
</P>
<P>
   Intent on making his stamp on the company, he was instrumental
in persuading Westinghouse to dump its industrial manufacturing
assets and to refashion the company under the CBS name.
</P>
<P>
   Michael H. Jordan, then chairman and chief executive of CBS,
appointed him to head CBS's station division. Karmazin rose quickly
_ so quickly that in October 1998 he forced Jordan's resignation,
assuming his titles in January. (A spokeswoman for Jordan, who runs
an Internet company in Pittsburgh, said he would not comment.)
</P>
<P>
   If Jordan did not sense it, others saw Karmazin's ambitions.
``He is always comfortable saying: `I don't have to control
everything. Just let me run it.' Once he runs it, his performance
allows him to control it,'' Pattiz said. ``I heard somebody
describe him one time by saying, `Mel is completely without guile.
He'll never stab you in the back. He'll stab you in the chest.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's true,'' Karmazin said, hearing the analysis. ``I
will be totally honest with you _ even if you might not like what I
have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   But Don Imus, the radio personality whom Karmazin installed more
than 10 years ago at WFAN, one of Infinity's 163 radio stations,
knows him well _ and said he believed that Karmazin, whom he
described as ``a cross between Lenny Bruce and Don Rickles,'' had
no strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think he goes from one point to the next with no
master plan,'' Imus said. ``I think his goal is to try to get CBS
stock to 100.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, since Karmazin's arrival, CBS stock has more than
tripled, from a low of $15.375 in July 1996 to a close of $51.8125
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Reif Cohen, a media analyst at Merrill Lynch who is one
of many loyal Mel Karmazin hagiographers on Wall Street, also said
he is single-minded. ``He is focused on one thing: bringing the
stock up,'' she said. ``Sumner can do the strategic visionary
thing, and Mel can be the behind-the-scenes operator, pushing the
stock, and that's what he will do.''
</P>
<P>
   When Karmazin arrived at CBS, his goals were few but clear: cut
costs and raise revenues so that the stock moves relentlessly
higher. To the dismay of many in the news division, he has cut
spending on the evening news _ as all three networks have done in
recent years _ even as he has invested $30 million to $50 million
in a potentially risky morning program, ``The Early Show;'' it made
its debut on Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The rationale is simple. The highest-rated morning program,
NBC's ``Today,'' generated $150 million in advertising revenue last
year. CBS's previous morning offering had only about one-fourth
that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder that at the ``CBS Evening News,'' Karmazin is
vilified as the man who has continued cuts that began under
Laurence A. Tisch, the chairman of CBS from 1986 to 1996, whom news
staff members felt had financially handcuffed the news division.
</P>
<P>
   According to CBS executives, the ``CBS Evening News,'' under a
reorganization instituted by Karmazin, has continued to reduce its
number of camera crews. CBS executives refer to it as surgery, not
an amputation, but will not say how many news crews the network
has, though they acknowledge that the total is far below the 125
crews fielded by NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin makes no apologies. ``We've been pretty good at
watching expenses,'' he said. ``And we're pretty good at generating
revenues. We've always been known to make huge investments in
properties that are worth it.'' For example, Howard Stern, the
shock jock Karmazin hired at WNEW, reportedly has a salary of $20
million a year; Imus makes at least $6 million, and Leslie Moonves,
the president and chief executive of CBS Television, got a raise to
$6 million, from $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin added: ``You know, I'm real comfortable getting my own
cup of coffee. I don't need a kitchen staff. I'd rather put that
money on the screen or in radio, not to behind-the-scenes stuff
that is about making my life more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   After slashing $180 million from the CBS budget last year,
Karmazin has raised revenue. Ad revenue climbed after he and
Moonves started preaching to advertisers that CBS's viewers, while
older than those of other networks, were a wealthier and thus
better demographic group. But it is unclear whether ad revenue rose
because of the demographic push or because of a healthy economy and
a big surge in Internet advertising, of which Karmazin said CBS has
managed to garner a majority.
</P>
<P>
   CBS's ad rates have increased: for the 1999-2000 season, NBC
remains the most expensive with an average unit rate _ the cost for
a 30-second prime-time spot _ of $171,114, a drop of around 9
percent from the previous year, according to a survey by
Advertising Age published each fall. ABC has an average rate of
$165,773, down 3.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But CBS, though still in third place, has managed a 27 percent
increase, to an average unit rate of $163,773.
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin's other trick at CBS was to put the sales force on
commission, without salary, a measure instituted two years ago and
noted throughout the industry.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That is not punitive, he said. ``The purpose of it is to have
them on your side, so the salespeople don't sit there and say,
`Hey, I did all this work and the big guys get all the money.''' He
recently told CBS radio advertising sales managers that he expected
to present a sales representative with a $1 million annual paycheck
_ a first _ someday soon.
</P>
<P>
   His advice to the sales staff is: ``Don't give me lame excuses
like, `Oh, Mel, but our ratings are down, wah, wah.' Or, `there's
no activity.' Your job is to create activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, Karmazin is not a man given to romantic notions
about network history. He has said he will sell the network, which
analysts say has lost money every year since the mid-1980s , if he
cannot make it profitable. (This year, he says it will be
profitable.) Asked if he ever senses the presence of Paley's spirit
in his office, he said: ``His ghost? Well, if it makes a better
story for you, sure I feel Paley's ghost.''Then he wiggled his
fingers, raised his eyebrows and said, playfully, ``Whoooo!''
</P>
<P>
   Befitting a man who thinks first of a network as a billboard,
not the home of ``60 Minutes'' _ once even betting Tom Wolzien, a
media analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein, Wolzien's salary that he
could sell the network for more than it was worth _ Karmazin spends
little time worrying about programming. ( Karmazin replies: ``Oh,
that was a chump-change bet anyway.'') He depends on the executives
in programming to report to him on an almost-daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mel once said, `The day that Leslie Moonves asks my opinion
about programming is the day I sell all my CBS stock,''' Moonves
said. ``That's flattering, but it says a lot about our
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Stringer, chairman of the Sony Corporation of America and
a former president of CBS, said that was Karmazin's style. ``He is
smart to know what he does not know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When he moves to the merged Viacom-CBS, Karmazin is expected to
approach his management duties with similar tactics, if Redstone
lets him run the show. By most accounts, the pair's engagement
joins two like-minded men from similar backgrounds in a mission to
generate more advertising revenue than any other company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are kindred spirits,'' Redstone said. ``Neither one of us
was born with a golden spoon in his mouth. We're both entrepreneurs
at heart and we're both driven by the same motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there has already been a tense moment. Last month, the
two appeared to differ over Blockbuster, Viacom's ailing video
rental chain. One day, Karmazin told analysts that it would be best
to spin it off, but later that week, in a conference call with
reporters, Redstone shot back that Blockbuster was ``not a sick
child.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a booming, thriving business,'' he said, quashing rumors
that he would sell it.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Karmazin said he had a few concrete plans for the
day the merger is approved by the Federal Communications
Commission. For one, he wants to integrate music units of Viacom _
MTV and VH1 _ with CBS's radio, advertising and Internet entities
in a Web site or series of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's assume that the American consumer likes music,'' he
said. ``And let's say that music might be something that might be
on the Internet. Take our radio stations. Take MTV and VH1, and
that's a pretty compelling site. You're able to drive traffic to it
because you've got all these billboards and forms of advertising,
and I think that's all pretty compelling.''
</P>
<P>
   He also intends to scrutinize the children's programming
business. ``There are interesting opportunities that are still
hypothetical,'' he said. ``But they have a lot of children's
programming. What if our networks wanted to run some children's
programming? That might not be a bad idea.'' He added that
Infinity's radio stations might be a great fit for MTV and VH1 in
terms of concert promotion.
</P>
<P>
   The merger also fulfills Karmazin's longtime desire to own cable
properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until now, CBS didn't have any cable, and that was a
problem,'' he said. ``And now we have cable. We didn't have a major
studio and now we have a studio.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this will quell the objections raised when the merger
was announced, especially from vocal critics in the advertising
industry. Because the merger will meld the CBS network, CBS
television stations, radio stations and billboards with Viacom's
MTV, VH1 and Nickelodeon and the company's stake in the UPN
network, some fear that the consolidation will allow Viacom-CBS to
charge excessive rates and unfairly corner some advertising
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think what Mel is doing is good for the country,''
said Jean Pool, executive vice president and director for North
American media services at J. Walter Thompson in New York. ``I
don't think monopolies are good for the country or the economy. Mel
is like the robber barons at the turn of the century. And you
remember what happened to the oil business and the railroad
business at the turn of the last century. They became terrible
monopolies that were eventually broken up.''
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin said the new company would ``not have, quote, unfair
leverage with any constituency at all.'' He added: ``Wherever
advertisers want to spend their money, we're going to be there.
We're indifferent to where they spend their money, as long as they
spend it with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pool said she did not expect the new company to increase any
ad rates before the Senate antitrust subcommittee and the FC C
approved the deal. ``I am sure Mel is half-joking when he says he
wants to buy NBC,'' Ms. Pool said, ``but if that is his dream, he
is going to have to be a good boy and at least look as if he is
behaving himself.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jon Mandel, co-managing director of Mediacom, the media services
arm of Grey Advertising, said the merger's so-called synergy _
extolled by Karmazin and Redstone _ was nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no natural fit between Viacom and CBS that makes
sense,'' Mandel said, noting that audiences watching ``60 Minutes''
were not also watching MTV. He had one exception: ``If you look at
music, however, there is a tremendous fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandel said the most fundamental issue with the Viacom-CBS deal
would be ``if Mel ever tries to change the programming.''
</P>
<P>
   At CBS, the closest Karmazin ever came to that occurred when Don
Hewitt, the producer of ``60 Minutes,'' and Mike Wallace, one of
the program's correspondents, appealed to him in 1998 to not go
forward with a plan put forward by Moonves and Andrew Heyward, the
president of CBS News, for ``60 Minutes II.''
</P>
<P>
   One CBS executive said that Hewitt and Wallace begged Karmazin
to quash the show, but that Karmazin listened and said, ``Sorry
guys, but I'm not going to override Andrew and Leslie.''
</P>
<P>
   According to another executive, the encounter had Karmazin
barking: ``We're putting on `60 Minutes II' whether you like it or
not. If I have to slap the title `60 Minutes II' across `The
Nanny,' I'll do it, but you're going to have `60 Minutes II.''' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In either case, it was a good move: ``60 Minutes II,'' despite
its low ratings with younger audiences, is ranked 24th in Nielsen
ratings, after ABC's ``Dharma and Greg'' and NBC's ``Law and Order:
Special Victims Unit.'' Karmazin smiled and said only this: `` `The
Nanny?' Does that sound like me? I think the team at ``60 Minutes''
was concerned. I was pleased that they cared so much about the
brand name.''
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin is notoriously tough with staff, and has become only
tougher.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he likes you, it would be great to work for him,'' Ms.
Cohen said. ``If he doesn't, it would be a nightmare.'' And his
style is famously brusque.
</P>
<P>
   One former CBS executive said he once attended a meeting with
Karmazin and Fred Drasner, then the co-publisher of The Daily News
of New York. After the meeting, according to this account, Karmazin
stood at the elevator, looked at the CBS executive, and said: ``The
day I fire you, the company's stock will go up $2.'' (Karmazin
fired him a few months later.)
</P>
<P>
   Some people who know Karmazin say an early career humiliation is
at the heart of his intensity. In the late 1960s, Karmazin, then at
WCBS Radio, tried to get a job at WCBS television. ``CBS was
dominated by a bunch of guys who were in the job because they
looked good and went to the right schools,'' another executive
said. ``The network business was great. O and O's were big. Cable
was still far over the horizon.'' (In TV jargon, ``O and O'' refers
to stations that are owned and operated by a network.)
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin, though, ``wore the wide lapels and the hair going out
in 18 different directions, his tie undone,'' this executive said.
``He came off as a street tough. And I believe that he was rejected
on a cultural basis.'' Karmazin still wants to prove them wrong,
the executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin's spokesman said he had no comment about the story.
</P>
<P>
   Ascending at Viacom-CBS would, of course, be the ultimate
payback. Karmazin said he had no intention of trying to oust
Redstone. But a provision of the merger was that if Redstone were
to step down, Karmazin would become chief executive of Viacom-CBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was to satisfy the board members,'' Karmazin said.
The two are paid identically, but Redstone also retains the right,
until 2003, to dismiss Karmazin, which doesn't seem to bother him
at all.
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner meeting with analysts last week, Karmazin said that
whether he and Redstone are friendly is ``immaterial,'' stressing
instead the assets of the combination. ``But,'' he added, ``I
expect to be here in 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Redstone said: ``And so do I!''
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin had little to say about Viacom's movie and book
business, but those who know him said he would keep his hands off
unless profits eroded.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it that I would want this job for?'' he asked. ``I
enjoy running my company. I like hands-on operations. I don't like
the visibility.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added: ``I'm very conscious of the fact that I wasn't
successful as a kid. I wasn't making a lot of money. I didn't come
from a rich family. I was comfortable in that lifestyle. But having
all this stuff _ people coming up to you, being in the public eye _
is more, well, unusual for me. I don't enjoy it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
