<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-U.S.-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFFERS TALKS ON RESUMING MILITARY TIES WITH INDONESIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton met Friday with Indonesia's new
president, Abdurrahman Wahid, and said that the United States was
willing to open talks aimed at resuming military ties between the
two nations, which were broken off by Washington several weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised Wahid, a respected Islamic cleric who was
elected last month in the most democratic balloting ever seen in
Indonesia, and said his election would lead to efforts ``to
strengthen our relationship, including the issue of
military-to-military ties.''
</P>
<P>
   While saying he was ``very encouraged'' by Wahid's election and
his efforts to promote democracy in the world's
fourth-most-populous nation, Clinton stopped short of endorsing the
Indonesian leader's call for a pardon for former President Suharto,
his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto, who ran Indonesia for more than three decades, is under
investigation over allegations that he and his family stole
billions of dollars from the Indonesian treasury and stashed the
money abroad.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving in Washington on Thursday, Wahid, who had been a
leading critic of Suharto during his presidency, told a group of
American business executives and diplomats that he had decided to
pardon Suharto if he is convicted of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid said Friday that one factor in his decision was that
Suharto's ``big followers'' might try to ``topple the cart'' _ an
apparent reference to the possibility that military officers loyal
to Suharto might seek to overthrow the new democratically elected
government.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said of the offer of a pardon: ``I think the decision,
first of all, is one for the Indonesian people and government to
make. I think every country has to decide how to resolve the
tension between the pursuit of a particular case and the desire for
the reconciliation of people, and to go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Washington would support Wahid and ``anything that he's
trying to do to build democracy to take Indonesia into the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States severed military ties with Indonesia after
that country's soldiers were accused of orchestrating the violence
that followed the independence referendum last August in East
Timor, a former Portuguese colony that was invaded by Indonesia in
1975 and annexed the following year. Voters in the referendum
overwhelmingly sought independence for East Timor, which is now
under the control of an international peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the American people know that a strong and stable and
prosperous and democratic Indonesia is very much in our interest,''
Clinton said at a news conference with Wahid before Friday's White
House meeting. ``I think we have to acknowledge that it's quite a
challenging task to preserve a democracy so widespread and so
diverse.''
</P>
<P>
   The nearly blind 78-year-old Indonesian leader, who appeared
full of energy and good humor despite reports of recent ill health,
said he had traveled to Washington ``to make sure that we are still
great friends of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by reporters about his promise of a pardon for Suharto, he
said, ``We will use law of course, and we would like to know
whether he is guilty or not, according to the law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But after that, we will pardon him because of two reasons,''
he said. ``First is that he was our president, and we have to be
careful about this for future generations. Second thing is that,
you know, that it's not easy, because Suharto still has big
followers. So we have to be careful not to, let's say, topple the
cart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
