<HEADER>
A8254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-VA-SWITCHED-BABY-NYT &LR;      11-12 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VA-SWITCHED-BABY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DENIES CUSTODY TO MOTHER OF SWITCHED BABY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A woman whose baby was switched at birth with
another infant was denied custody of her child Friday, but the
judge in the case granted the mother's request for visitation
rights.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling in a Virginia court means that Rebecca Chittum, 4,
will continue to be reared by Larry and Rosa Chittum of Buena
Vista, Va., and not by her biological mother, Paula Johnson of
Ruckersville, Va., about 75 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge John Curry II of Juvenile and Domestic Relations Court
said Ms. Johnson could visit Rebecca at least one weekend a month,
on holidays and for three weeks in the summer. ``This is all I ever
wanted, just to be part of her life,'' Ms. Johnson said. Her
lawyer, Ken Mergenthal, said the ruling was ``a great relief for
all of these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry and Rosa Chittum, who have been rearing Rebecca as their
granddaughter since the death of her presumed parents, were also
pleased, their lawyer said Friday night. ``Things couldn't have
worked out any better for my clients,'' said the lawyer, Michael
Groot.
</P>
<P>
   Curry ruled after a psychologist said Rebecca would be better
off if left with the Chittums.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Johnson, who is unmarried, gave birth at the University of
Virginia Medical Center on June 29, 1995. About a year later, she
sought child support from the man she believed had fathered the
child she had named Callie. Tests showed that the man was not
Callie's father and that Ms. Johnson was not her mother.
</P>
<P>
   The medical center then tested Rebecca, who had been born at
about the same time. She was being reared by the Chittums as their
granddaughter. Her presumed parents, Kevin Chittum and his
girlfriend, Tamara Rogers, were killed in a car crash in mid-1998
without knowing of the confusion over the babies.
</P>
<P>
   The tests soon established that Callie was the daughter of Kevin
Chittum and Tamara Rogers and Rebecca was Ms. Johnson's daughter.
Investigations have not determined how the babies were switched.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Johnson and the Chittums sued the hospital. The Chittums
settled their suit in April for just under $1 million, most of
which is invested for Rebecca's future, Groot said. Ms. Johnson's
suit is pending. She is continuing to rear Callie. The Chittums
have made no attempt to gain custody of Callie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 2153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
