<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0351 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8256 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-ART-97     11-12 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-ART-975(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET FIGHT PITS BUSINESS AGAINST ENVIRONMENTALISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By TIM WEINER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The most explosive issues remaining in the budget
battle are legislative land mines pitting business interests
against environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the White House and Congress try to strike a final deal,
new pro-business, anti-environmental measures are appearing,
including one that seeks to block the government from collecting
millions of dollars in fines from power companies it says are
defying clean-air laws.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have dug in so deeply on these fights over land, air,
water and money that some members of Congress fear the defeat of
the spending bills to which the measures have been attached, a step
that could cripple efforts to compromise on the budget and prevent
a government shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   The last days of any congressional session are a kind of
witching hour, when amendments like the power companies' proposed
measure can appear suddenly, sometimes seemingly out of nowhere.
Political deals cut in private materialize as fine print in a
thousand-page bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what phoenix will come up out of the ashes over
the weekend,'' Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The spending bills must eventually be passed to keep the
government going, but Congress could stiill continue to extend its
deadline, as it already has three times. As the last legislation
this year, they can carry politically sensitive material that would
not usually pass the normal checks.
</P>
<P>
   These include the measures known as riders, so called because
they are about unrelated, limited issues attached to the spending
bills.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has already put two dozen environmental riders on the
$15 billion Interior Department spending bill. President Clinton,
threatening a veto, called the riders ``a stealth attack on the
environment'' and said he would send the bill ``straight back to
the recycling bin'' unless they were removed.
</P>
<P>
   One of the new measures, which has not yet found a sponsor,
would stymie the Justice Department's efforts to fine power
companies for modernizing plants without modernizing pollution
controls, as required by clean-air laws.
</P>
<P>
   The power companies want to block the Environmental Protection
Agency from collecting millions of dollars in fines it wants to
impose on 32 coal-fired plants in the Midwest and the South. The
plants' emissions are blamed for acid rain in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   The Edison Electric Institute, the trade association of
investor-owned utilities that generate three-fourths of the
nation's electricity, is leading the charge to persuade Congress to
add a last-minute amendment written by the power companies.
</P>
<P>
   It appealed for ``legislative relief'' in a letter sent on
Wednesday to the most powerful members of Congress. A senior
official of the institute said Friday that he thought a senator
would sponsor the amendment in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Four Republicans _ Reps. Sherwood Boehlert and Rick Lazio of New
York, Michael Castle of Delaware and Wayne Gilchrest of Maryland _
said in a letter sent on Thursday to Hastert that the power
companies' bid was ``a blatant effort'' to protect plants that
``spew out pollutants that create ozone, haze and acid rain'' in
the towns and cities they represent.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Weiss, the political director of the Sierra Club, called the
power companies' move ``an unbelievable assault on efforts to
control smog and acid rain.''
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency sued the utilities on Nov.
3, accusing them of failing to make 17 plants abide by tough new
standards. The proposed amendment would block $27,500-per-day
penalties from piling up against the plants while the power
companies seek to settle the suit. At the same time, the agency
took administrative action against 15 other plants.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Bailey, the Edison Electric Institute's vice president of
environmental issues, said in an interview: ``Utilities are stuck
between a rock and a hard place. State law requires them to provide
reliable service. They're getting this message from the EPA saying
they're being fined for operating in violation of the clean-air
laws. If the government would give us the absolute assurance they
can continue operating, that would solve it.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Congress understands the problem we're facing, and
they're trying to help us find a solution to it right now. There
are efforts right now to craft the right legislative language.
There are some potential sponsors'' in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In the earlier riders attached to spending bills, Republican
senators took steps to allow more logging in national forests and
to let mining companies dump thousands of tons of waste on federal
land. Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., wants to allow coal miners to keep
dumping slag into streams.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, wants to delay new rules
requiring oil companies to pay royalties the government says they
owe. Another new measure cropped up on Thursday. It would delay
until the next administration takes power a new rule that Clinton
has proposed to block new roads in 40 million acres of national
forest.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and Congress continued to negotiate Friday over
the environmental riders by telephone and fax. Both sides have
proposed compromises, but neither side has agreed. A White House
official said Friday that he did not know if compromise was
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Any one of these riders could derail the five remaining spending
bills when they come to the floor in the House and the Senate next
week, both Republicans and Democrats in Congress said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environmental riders are still hanging out there,'' said
Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, the ranking Democrat on the House
Appropriations Committee. ``Some members will die over those.
Others will die if they're attached.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say they plan to lash all five bills into a single
$390 billion juggernaut. That means that every objection that every
member has to every issue within the bill will be concentrated into
one vote to support that omnibus measure or let it fall.
</P>
<P>
   Other problems also loom. There is a $6.5 billion gap between
what Congress has agreed to spend and the bottom line beyond which
the spending will dip into the Social Security surplus _ even with
the creative accounting that Republicans have used to disguise more
than $20 billion in the spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   Then both sides have to agree on whether the final accounting
for the spending by the Congressional Budget Office lets them argue
plausibly that the bills will not tap into the retirement funds.
</P>
<P>
   Other potential blockades remain as well. No deal has been
struck to allow the United States to pay the $926 million in back
dues it owes the United Nations. The White House wants a
quarter-billion dollars more for debt relief for the world's
poorest nations. Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wis., threatens to stop the
Senate cold next week in the name of protecting his state's 23,000
dairy farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Any one of these issues _ the riders, the U.N. dues, the debt
relief, the debate over the Social Security surplus _ could bring
the omnibus spending bill down to defeat, said the House minority
leader, Dick Gephardt of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned that it can't pass,'' Gephardt said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Obey, the Democrat who has the most authority over the spending
bills in the House, said, ``You run the risk of it blowing up,
because of the critical mass of people opposed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
