<HEADER>
A8258 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-U.N.-U.S.-DUES-N     11-12 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-U.N.-U.S.-DUES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DELICATE BARGAINING ON U.N. DUES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Nov. 13: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is right to try to negotiate a deal
with House Republicans that would allow payment of nearly $1
billion in back American dues to the United Nations. But it must
make clear that its willingness to compromise has limits. Even
though Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has offered to defend
any deal the administration makes from feminist criticism, Clinton
should not accept legislation that could be used to penalize family
planning organizations when they use their own money to advocate
more humane abortion laws. That is too consequential and lasting a
change in American policy to sign on to simply because Albright has
volunteered to serve as the administration's flak-catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation to pay the arrears has passed the Senate in recent
years, with the support of Sen. Jesse Helms, long one of the U.N.'s
fiercest critics. But it has been held up in the House. Senior
House Republicans have let the U.N. money become entangled with an
unrelated and unacceptable amendment that would terminate aid to
international family planning groups that lobby to change harsh
foreign abortion laws.
</P>
<P>
   The two issues are clearly separate. But for the past three
years, Rep. Christopher Smith of New Jersey, backed by the House
leadership, has tried to bully the administration into accepting
punishment of abortion advocacy abroad as the price for the House's
approving payment of U.N. arrears.
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, the administration has maintained its
pro-choice principles, even at the cost of the U.N. money. But now
there may be room for a pragmatic compromise, based on language
that has already won support from a majority of House members and
is conditionally acceptable to pro-choice and family planning
groups.
</P>
<P>
   That formulation would deny American aid only to those groups
that violate the abortion or lobbying laws of their host country.
Unlike the Smith amendment, that formula would not put Washington
in the position of gagging the free speech of family planning
groups abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Smith rejects this compromise, and to placate him, Republican
leaders are demanding more damaging concessions. Negotiators from
both sides are considering a plan that would enact the Smith
amendment into law but give Clinton authority to waive its
application in specific cases. The cost of such a waiver, however,
would be corresponding reductions in spending on family planning
aid. That proposal, which has tempted some administration
officials, should be resisted.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has some leverage in this bargaining. It should
not be afraid to use it. The House Republican position is not a
popular one among Republicans in the Senate or the broader American
public. The administration has offered a reasonable compromise and
should not rush to go further.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
