<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8259 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BOX-ADVANCE13-COX     11-12 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ADVANCE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The battle for legitimacy
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ For the combatants, tonight at the Thomas &AMP; Mack
Center means a chance to stand atop the boxing world as heavyweight
champion.
</P>
<P>
   For the sport, tonight means legitimacy. So, which one has the
most to lose? Evander Holyfield, Lennox Lewis or the fight game?
</P>
<P>
   In every circle, it's unanimous: Boxing wins if Holyfield and
Lewis put on a memorable display of pugilism. Memorable for solid,
exciting efforts, without punches after the bell, body slams or
suspect judging _ elements that have discredited a game that could
hardly use such transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   ``For better or for worse, this is now more important than just
a fight for the undisputed heavyweight title, and that is saying
something,'' said president of HBO Sports, Seth Abraham. ``That's
still one of the most important titles in sports, but because of
all the problems this year, this fight has taken on a larger
significance. It's not the Crusades. It's not the Christians vs.
the Muslims. But for the boxing industry, it's a very important
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Such significance is not lost on the participants. Both have
said they are going to do their part to make the unification bout a
thriller. ``My performance,'' Holyfield said, ``will be one that
may make everyone forget about all that has happened this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis (34-1-1) said, ``I think we'll go at it a little more.
I'll be right in front of him. He won't have to look for me. . . .
And I think everyone wants to see us mix it up.''
</P>
<P>
   There was little mixing it up in the first fight, March 13 in
New York. The bout was ruled a controversial draw, starting the
series of incidents that have threatened the viability of the
sport. Lewis was in control much of the fight, using his effective
left jab to keep Holyfield at a distance from which he could
inflict no damage.
</P>
<P>
   However, on the occasions when Lewis seemed to have a chance to
pound Holyfield (36-3-1), he did not. ``Lennox Lewis had a perfect
opportunity to be the undisputed heavyweight champion,'' Holyfield,
37, said of their first encounter. ``He didn't take the chance
because he said I might catch him with a shot. Some people don't
have the fortitude. Sometimes you have to take chances in life.
Winners in life take chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis promised that it would be the only change in his strategy
this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some say it's better to be cautious than sorry,'' he said.
``Some say I'm too cautious. I'm the one in there. Maybe I was a
bit too cautious in the first fight. I won't be in this one. ''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' size (6-foot-5, 242 pounds) and strength gave Holyfield
(6-2, 217) much trouble in March. But it might have been Lewis'
reluctance to brawl that hampered Holyfield the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a fighter presses me and comes straight ahead, it's a lot
easier for me,'' Holyfield said. ``When it's a defensive fighter, I
get lured into a lazy posture.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest corrections Holyfield said he will make will be in
lateral movement against Lewis' jab and head movement. Also, he
will concentrate on getting inside, where he's close enough to do
damage. ``It's not 'if' I can get inside, because I can,''
Holyfield said. ``It's what I do when I'm there. I prefer to be
inside, but I have to fight well on the outside, too.''
</P>
<P>
   His trainer, Don Turner, wants Holyfield to attack Lewis early
and see whether he has the heart to fight back. ``I'd like to see
that,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   But Holyfield has to be healthy to do so. He complained of
cramps and general lethargy in their first encounter, which he said
stunted his mobility. He since has been on a diet low in fats and
carbohydrates and high in protein and natural fibers. His attorney,
Jim Thomas, said Holyfield is in peak physical condition.
</P>
<P>
   And Turner said his fighter is more determined than ever. ``He's
better than ever,'' Turner said. ``I've been with him 5 1/2 years
and I've never seen him this good. And I've never seen Evander so
vicious and intense. He sent sparring partners out of camp almost
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, according to his trainer, Emanuel Steward, is just as
determined. ``There is not a heavyweight in the world who can go
past six rounds with Lennox right now,'' he said. ``He trained much
better, much harder this time. He wants a knockout. . . . Never has
anybody played and toyed with Evander the way Lennox did in the
first fight. When a big man fights a small man, he'll win easy.''
</P>
<P>
   If the fight matches the talk, many in the sport will be happy _
and relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing has had some very bad setbacks this year,'' Abraham
said. ``They've affected the fans' faith in the sport. That's why
in all our advertising we're not calling this a rematch or
Holyfield-Lewis II. I've spoken to all sides about that. We're not
selling this as a rematch. We don't want to remind people of March
13.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're selling it as the undisputed heavyweight championship of
the world, the biggest night in sports. If it's Holyfield-Lewis I,
the silence will be deafening. It's probably unfair, but these two
men are carrying more than their title belts into the ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
