A8262 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      11-12 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF: AFRICA, EUROPE, NORTH AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   IVORY COAST: PROTESTERS JAILED
</P>
<P>
   Henriette Diabate and 15 other leaders of the main opposition
party, Rally of the Republicans, were sentenced to up to two years
in prison by a government-controlled court for having led a protest
in Abidjan. The government of President Henri Konan Bedie said the
party's presidential candidate in next year's election, Alassane
Ouattara, is not Ivoirian and is ineligible to run, which prompted
the protest.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: COMMONWEALTH CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand Foreign Minister Don McKinnon was elected the
Commonwealth's new secretary general during the organization's
summit meeting in Durban. McKinnon, 60, who defeated former
Bangladesh Foreign Minister Farooq Sobhan, succeeds former Nigerian
Foreign Minister Chief Emeka Anyaoku, who steps down in April after
10 years as head of the 54-nation group.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO: REBEL TELLS OF FIGHTING
</P>
<P>
   A rebel leader accused President Laurent Kabila of launching a
``general offensive,'' in what he said was another violation of the
three-month-old cease-fire. The truce, part of a comprehensive
peace pact, appeared ever more shaky as the rebel, Jean-Pierre
Bemba, pledged to ``repulse the enemy'' from several towns. U.N.
officials in the region could not confirm the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   SWAZILAND: SUSPICIOUS BLAST
</P>
<P>
   A suspicious explosion destroyed a government building outside
Mbabane, the capital. No one was injured in the blast, which comes
almost a year after bombs destroyed a bridge near a military base
and killed a guard at a government office in the capital. Swaziland
is one of the world's last absolute monarchies, and pressure to
open up the political system has grown in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   BURUNDI: U.N. ALARMED
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed by outbreaks of violence and the flight of refugees in
Burundi, the United Nations Security Council met to urge Burundi's
neighbors to move quickly and pick a successor to Tanzanian
President Julius Nyerere, who died Oct. 14 while trying to mediate
a peace between Burundi's warring factions. The United States also
called the Burundian government's regrouping of 340,000 people in
camps near the capital ``a major human rights violation.''
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA: HAIDER APOLOGIZES
</P>
<P>
   The far-right leader Joerg Haider apologized for past remarks
about the Nazi period, saying he believed he had hurt people's
feelings. Haider also said he understood that Jews felt anxious
about his success in October's election, but said they had nothing
to fear from his Freedom Party. At a rally in Vienna scheduled
earlier, some 20,000 people protested racism and Haider's policies
on curbing immigration.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: JEWS TO BOYCOTT SLAVE TALKS
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish Claims Conference delegation negotiating with Germany
over a Holocaust restitution fund for former Nazi slaves said the
Jewish survivors on its team were displeased with the slow pace of
the talks and would boycott the next U.S.-German meeting Nov. 16-17
in Bonn. Though there are signs of progress, no breakthrough is
expected.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: UNESCO PICKS JAPANESE
</P>
<P>
   A Japanese diplomat, Koichiro Matsuura, was confirmed as the
next director-general of the Paris-based United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization. Matsuura, 62, is
expected to use his firm management style to reform Unesco's
bureaucracy and may try to woo back the United States, which left
in 1985, complaining of waste. He succeeds Federico Mayor of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: NEW RIGHTS AIDE
</P>
<P>
   The Senate named Jose Luis Soberanes, a prominent legal scholar,
to a five-year term as president of Mexico's National Human Rights
Commission. It was the first time the Senate had exercised its new
power to designate the highest rights ombudsman. Presidents Carlos
Salinas de Gortari and Ernesto Zedillo appointed the first three
presidents, a position created in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: KOSOVO PULLOUT
</P>
<P>
   Canada will remove almost all of its 1,450 troops from Kosovo by
next spring, said Prime Minister Jean Chretien. Stretched thin
after cutting its military budget by almost a third in five years,
Canada has 4,400 troops on 22 overseas missions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
