A8268 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      11-12 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASDAQ SETS ITS 10TH HIGH IN LAST 11 TRADING SESSIONS
</P>
<P>
   Led by banks and financial companies, the stock market rose
after a government report on productivity eased investors' worries
that the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates for a third time
this year when policy-makers meet on Tuesday. The NASDAQ composite
index closed at its 10th record high in the last 11 sessions,
rising 23.86 points, or 0.75 of a percent, to 3,221.15.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rallied 174.02 points, or 1.64
percent, to 10,769.32. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained
14.60 points, or 1.06 percent, to 1,396.06.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond decreased to 6.03 percent
from 6.09 percent on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE NEGOTIATORS EXTEND TALKS
</P>
<P>
   U.S. trade officials said they would extend their stay in
Beijing to a fourth day for at least one more meeting in a
last-ditch effort to salvage an agreement on China's entry into the
World Trade Organization. The Americans announced on Friday that
they were heading home after three days of fruitless talks. But
after an exchange of messages during the night, the two sides
agreed to meet again Saturday morning to make another try.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIE'S TO GO IT ALONE ON INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   Christie's decided against joining forces with an online
retailer like eBay or Walt Disney's Go.com to offer online
auctions. Five months after its archrival Sotheby's allied itself
with Amazon.com, Christie's said it had concluded that a link with
an online retailer risked diluting the Christie's brand name.
</P>
<P>
   `HISTORIC' BANKING MEASURE SIGNED
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton signed into law a sweeping financial
modernization bill that will allow banks, insurance companies and
brokerage firms to buy into each other's businesses without
restrictions. ``This legislation is truly historic,'' Clinton said
of the measure, which repeals parts of the 1933 Glass-Steagall Act
and the 1956 Bank Holding Company Act.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE BODY STALLS ON AGENDA
</P>
<P>
   Member countries of the World Trade Organization are mired in
gridlock over the agenda for negotiations. Trade ministers, who are
scheduled to gather in Seattle in two weeks, could be facing a huge
wish list from member countries that will be difficult to tackle in
the four-day meeting, which is designed to kick off new
market-opening negotiations. The trade body's director-general,
Mike Moore, has warned publicly that the impasse threatens to
torpedo the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRONMENT ISSUES IN BUDGET FIGHT
</P>
<P>
   The most explosive issues remaining in the budget battle are
legislative land mines pitting business interests against
environmentalists. Even as the White House and Congress try to
strike a final deal, new pro-business, anti-environmental measures
are suddenly appearing, including one that seeks to block the
government from collecting millions of dollars in fines from power
companies that it says are defying clean-air laws.
</P>
<P>
   BURNHAM PACIFIC EXPLORING OPTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Four months after rejecting a $1.2 billion buyout offer, Burnham
Pacific Properties said it was exploring ``a full range of
strategic alternatives.'' The San Diego-based real estate
investment trust, which is one of the largest developers of strip
shopping centers on the West Coast, owns about 80 properties, with
13 million square feet of space.
</P>
<P>
   4 BID FOR FAILED JAPANESE BANK
</P>
<P>
   Four major Japanese companies _ Ito-Yokado, Softbank, Orix and
Tokio Marine and Fire Insurance _ are jointly bidding for the
failed Nippon Credit Bank. But spokesmen declined to provide
details of the bid structure and declined to say if the group will
make a separate bid for the trust bank unit, Nippon Credit Trust
Bank, if the planned purchase of the parent fails.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
