<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8269 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-BCSRACE13-COX     11-12 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BCSRACE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Day's best: 'Bama vs. Miss. State
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUSCALOOSA, Ala. _ November is the best month in college
football because, for most teams, what happens in these 30 days
defines the season. A team that looked invincible in September and
October can become mortal in November. Ask Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   The November games are the ones you have to live with the entire
offseason, good or bad. Today's game between Alabama and
Mississippi State is such a game.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama (7-2) has had more than its share of problems this
season, on and off the field. But a win over No. 8 Mississippi
State (8-0) puts the Crimson Tide a giant step closer to the SEC
Championship Game in Atlanta on Dec. 4. Alabama needs the win for a
lot of different reasons. Coach Mike DuBose really needs it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State would like to return to the SEC Championship
Game, where they gave national champ Tennessee all it wanted a year
ago. The Mississippi State campus is just 90 minutes away, and
their fans have snatched up every ticket they could find. And by
the way, the Bulldogs think they can get into the national
championship race.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Alabama puts down that Mississippi State is going to be
one of its biggest games of the season, then you know you've come a
long way with your program,'' said Jackie Sherrill, whose team has
beaten Alabama three games in a row.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a college football player, coach, or fan, these are
the kind of games you live for.
</P>
<P>
   SEC
</P>
<P>
   Auburn (4-5) at Georgia (6-2), 6 p.m., ESPN2. Georgia has more
athletes but must exploit that advantage by putting maximum
pressure on Auburn quarterback Ben Leard and forcing some
turnovers. The Bulldogs need to get the lead early and not let the
Tigers hang around until the fourth quarter. Georgia, 24-17.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State (8-0) at Alabama (7-2), 3:30 p.m., CBS.
Mississippi State is probably the most-maligned 8-0 team in SEC
history. Alabama will have its two big guns, quarterback Andrew Zow
and running back Shaun Alexander, who will tackle the nation's No.
1 defense. Bama gets the slight edge at home. Alabama, 14-13.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee (7-1) at Arkansas (5-3), 12:30 p.m., NBC. The Arkansas
players have had this date circled on their calendar since losing a
heartbreaker to the Vols in Knoxville last season. The Hogs are
tough at home, but Tennessee might be the best team in the country
right now. Tennessee, 31-10.
</P>
<P>
   Florida (8-1) at South Carolina, 12:30 p.m. Coach Steve Spurrier
is not worried about winning this one. He's worried about getting
his offense ready for next week's visit by No. 1 Florida State.
Florida, 31-3.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky (5-4) at Vanderbilt (5-4), 9 p.m., ESPN 2. A huge game
for two teams that are trying to qualify for bowls. Both teams have
to play Tennessee in their final game, so this game is their best
chance to make the postseason. Kentucky, 24-20.
</P>
<P>
   Houston (5-4) at LSU (2-7), 8 p.m. After three one-point losses,
Tiger coach Gerry DiNardo is looking for anything positive. The
atmosphere in Baton Rouge will not be festive, but the Tigers have
enough talent to get the job done. LSU, 24-14.
</P>
<P>
   ACC
</P>
<P>
   Clemson (5-4) at Georgia Tech (6-2), noon, Fox Sports Net South.
Clemson coach Tommy Bowden knows how to find the weakness in a
defense and exploit it. That should be a serious concern to a
Georgia Tech team that gave up 42 points in a loss to Virginia.
Tech finds a way, but it won't be easy. Georgia Tech, 31-27.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland (5-4) at Florida State (9-0), 3:30 p.m. Florida State
will be doing a lot of experimenting today, getting ready for next
week's trip to Florida. Freshman QB Latrez Harrison of Atlanta gets
his first college start against one of the best defenses in the
country. Ouch. Florida State, 42-7.
</P>
<P>
   Wake Forest (5-4) at Duke (2-7), 1:30 p.m. Wake Forest has a
chance to become eligible for a bowl for the first time since 1992,
Bill Dooley's last year as coach. Wake Forest, 24-14.
</P>
<P>
   Top 25
</P>
<P>
   No. 19 Miami (5-3) at No. 2 Virginia Tech (8-0), 7:30 p.m.,
ESPN. Virginia Tech was fortunate last week to get a wakeup call
but still pulled out a 22-20 win over West Virginia. Miami is one
of the few teams on the Hokies schedule athletic enough to run with
them. Virginia Tech, 24-20.
</P>
<P>
   No. 16 Michigan (7-2) at No. 6 Penn State (9-1), noon, ABC. Penn
State saw the national championship slip through its fingers in
last week's loss to Minnesota. Can the Nittany Lions get back up
for a hard-to-figure Michigan team? Yes. Penn State, 17-14.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa (1-8) at No. 9 Wisconsin (8-2), 3:30 p.m. The Badgers need
a win to position themselves for a BCS bowl, and running back Ron
Dayne needs 99 yards to become the NCAA's all-time leading rusher.
Wisconsin 42, Iowa 3.
</P>
<P>
   The rest: Texas 24, Texas Tech 20; W. Michigan 21, Marshall 20;
BYU 31, Wyoming 21; Minnesota 28, Indiana 24; Washington 24, UCLA
17.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
