<HEADER>
A8277 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MRSCLINTON-GIULIANI-N     11-12 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SCOLDS MRS. CLINTON FOR WEST BANK EMBRACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MRSCLINTON-POLITICS, MRSCLINTON-MIDEAST) 
(lh) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani sharply criticized Hillary
Rodham Clinton Friday for ``embracing and kissing'' Suha Arafat,
the wife of the Palestinian Authority president, after listening to
Mrs. Arafat excoriate Israel for using what she said were
carcinogenic crowd-control gases in Gaza and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly wouldn't have embraced the person who said it,
hugged them and kissed them,'' the mayor said at a hastily called
City Hall news conference. ``I wouldn't embrace a person who said
that afterward, because I would understand that by embracing
someone, you approve.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton appeared uncomfortable during Mrs. Arafat's remarks
on Thursday in Ramallah on the West Bank. While Mrs. Clinton and
Mrs. Arafat kissed and warmly embraced before Mrs. Arafat's
remarks, afterward they exchanged a hastier kiss. ``They didn't hug
goodbye,'' said Marsha Berry, Mrs. Clinton's press secretary.
``There wasn't any big departure farewell.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the body language, Giuliani drew a sharp contrast
between himself and the first lady, whom he is expected to run
against for the U.S. Senate next year. ``Had I been in a situation
like that, I would have objected to it,'' Giuliani said. When asked
how he would have objected _ by leaving the dais, for example _
Giuliani responded: ``Well, look, you know, it's all hypothetical.
I mean, I can't imagine myself in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, the press secretary for Mrs. Clinton's Senate
exploratory committee, responded: ``Hillary Clinton isn't going to
put New York Senate politics in front of the Middle East peace
process. We will leave that to the mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson added that Mrs. Clinton was ``outraged and infuriated''
by Mrs. Arafat's comment, but went to Ramallah as first lady, to
announce that the United States would finance a health care program
there, because ``she believed it would help'' the peace process.
``Now some people are saying she should have walked out of the
room,'' Wolfson said. ``But that would have damaged the peace
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has long criticized Mrs. Clinton for her statement last
year that a Palestinian state is ``very important'' to Middle East
peace. Although polls show that Mrs. Clinton's views are shared by
increasing numbers of Jews in America and Israel, her position is
generally not supported by the conservative Jewish voters who are a
base of Giuliani's support.
</P>
<P>
   Friday during his weekly radio call-in show, in some of his most
extensive remarks to date on the Middle East peace process,
Giuliani criticized both the Palestinians and the Clinton
administration. ``A lot more pressure should be put on the
Palestinian Authority than the Clinton administration has been
willing to do,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there also has to be a recognition that there really is
not a moral equivalent between the state of Israel and the
Palestinian Authority. The state of Israel is a democratically
elected government of laws very, very similar to the United States.
The Palestinian Authority has not arrived at that yet. And
therefore you've got to demand something of them. You've got to be
strong enough to demand something of them. And not constantly be
demanding maybe what's easier _ more of Israel. So I think some
equity here would be valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Authority was set up under the Oslo agreements
of 1993 to govern Palestinian self-rule areas in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip until a permanent settlement is negotiated. The
president of the authority, Yasser Arafat, was elected in 1996. An
88-member legislative body, the Palestinian Legislative Council,
was also elected then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
