<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AIRCRASH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. AIRPLANE CRASHES IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  
(SUBS to make second sentence of last graf present tense.) (lh) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Kosovo _ A U.N. airplane with 24 people on board
crashed Friday in northern Kosovo during a flight headed here from
Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Wreckage of the plane was found on a steep mountainside about 12
miles northeast of Kosovska Mitrovica, late Friday night, about 12
hours after the plane went missing.
</P>
<P>
   A helicopter pilot who spotted the plane said that its front was
virtually disintegrated and that there were no immediate signs of
survivors, a spokesman for the NATO-led peacekeeping forces told
Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was a daily charter flight by the World Food Program,
a U.N. agency, and normally carries U.N. officials, aid workers and
sometimes journalists from Rome to the newly reopened Slatina
airport here. On Friday, the flight carried 21 passengers and three
crewmembers, but officials would not release the names or
nationalities of the people on board.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said there was no sign that the twin-engine, turbo
propeller aircraft, a French-Italian ATR-42, had been attacked. It
disappeared from radar at about noon near Vucitrn, some 12 miles
northwest of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   A statement from the manufacturer said that the plane, 13 years
old, had 25,000 hours of flying time in July, when it was delivered
to an Italian charter company, Si Fly.
</P>
<P>
   The World Food Program currently provides food aid to about
900,000 people a day in Kosovo _ more than half the current
population of the province. During the war in Kosovo from March
through June, some 800,000 ethnic Albanians were driven or fled
from Kosovo, and many of them returned to destroyed houses and
contaminated wells.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands more were forced from their homes inside Kosovo but
never left the province, living as best they could in the
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is feeding about 1.5 million people throughout the
Balkans, as well as some 500,000 people in Yugoslavia who were
affected by the war.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the agency fed some 75 million people, including most
of the world's refugees. It operates in 80 countries. According to
the agency, it has lost more employees than any other U.N. agency _
51 since 1988 _ in work-related accidents, illnesses or attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 2208EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
