<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8280 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-DUTIES-2TAKES-NY     11-12 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-DUTIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIFTING PRIORITIES, GORE CONTINUES DISTANCING HIMSELF FROM
CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After nearly eight years of touting himself as the
most influential vice president in history, Al Gore has apparently
had enough: He now thinks that his elected position as
second-in-command is secondary to his run for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running for president of this country is far more important
than being the best vice president I can possibly be,'' Gore told
reporters Thursday in response to a question about what accounted
for the dramatic overhaul of his campaign in the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of thinking like a vice president, which means, `How
am I going to advance the administration's goals and help the
current administration?', I started thinking like someone who was
asking the people for their ideas on how to make this a better
country and then responding spontaneously from the heart,'' Gore
said. ``And once that happened, then I said, `Hey, I gotta move my
campaign out of Washington.'''
</P>
<P>
   The comments seemed striking, given that Gore has always cast
his role as far more vital than mere standby equipment, and
reflects how difficult the job can be, trying to be his own man
while representing the Clinton administration. He is also attached
to the only modern president who has ever been impeached (in fact,
he is the only vice president ever to serve under an impeached
president). And so Gore seemed in his comments to go beyond
distancing himself to nearly severing himself, not just from Bill
Clinton but from his own job.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the job carries certain benefits, and Gore has not shied
from them. Just this week, during a three-day campaign swing, he
made two ``official'' appearances, including a Veterans Day speech
in Iowa, that gave him a platform to extol his views of America's
role in the world and allowed him to charge taxpayers for the trip.
Although the speech was deemed government business, Gore used the
occasion to chastise Republicans as isolationists. And the speech
took place at one of the sites where Iowans will caucus in little
more than two months to cast their votes for president.
</P>
<P>
   But even on overtly political occasions, he cannot always escape
the fact that he represents the administration. On Monday, he plans
to visit the Seattle headquarters of Microsoft, as a candidate who
is courting Washington state's largest employer, just as his rivals
have done.
</P>
<P>
   But at a time when the Justice Department is pursuing a
antitrust suit against the computer giant, Gore, who is the
administration's point man on technology, is likely to be seen as
an emissary whose visit might assuage some of the bitterness
between the government and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   (The visit was temporarily in doubt Friday night when Gore
learned belatedly that Microsoft intended to close the event to
reporters, as it had closed previous sessions with presidential
candidates. Both sides said they were negotiating the ground rules
and anticipated that Gore would still come.)
</P>
<P>
   Critics are pouncing on Gore's tough balancing act, which they
say is his attempt to have it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Pascoe, a spokesman for the Republican National Committee,
said: ``To say that I'm giving up my job but I'm certainly going to
take the benefits of the job to campaign _ it's nice having Air
Force II, taxpayer-funded advance people to help me against this
insurgent who has to spend twice as much as I do just to stay even
_ it's hypocrisy pure and simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just an elected official who is using the powers
of incumbency to aid his campaign,'' Pascoe added ``but he has now
said publicly he is not going to be vice president anymore. That's
what's outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what is different about two Republican officeholders,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush of and Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who
are seeking to become president. ``They are still doing their
jobs,'' Pascoe said.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, being vice president and running for president is no
longer a conflict; he says he has reset his priorities so that his
campaign for president comes first.
</P>
<P>
   He insists he is not shirking his duties, the primary one being
to serve as president pro tem of the Senate and break tie votes.
But his campaign schedule no longer allows for his weekly luncheons
with President Clinton or for him to be on hand every time a
foreign leader visits Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Officials who know both men say that the vice president believes
Clinton does not need Gore's tutelage on the ways of Washington as
much as he did early in the administration.
</P>
<P>
   But they also say the relationship between Clinton and Gore has
become much colder as the vice president seeks to assert his
independence. Clinton has yet to make a public campaign appearance
with Gore, but aides say he intends to do so and that the president
has raised money for him, most notably in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   As he searches for his footing, Gore has been undergoing a
painfully public coming-out process, with regular reports now about
everything from what is ``in his heart'' to his wardrobe to the
inner workings of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campaigns are intended to be transformational,'' Gore said,
saying that the process of connecting to an audience and listening
to people's concerns led him to overhaul his style, his message and
his operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started connecting in a new way, I started going
through some changes,'' he said. ``Six months ago if I told you I
was enjoying it, I'm not sure that I really was that much,'' he
said. ``When I tell you I'm enjoying it now, you believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that earlier, when he was asked a question, he would
think about whether he was advancing the administration's goals.
``The shift in priorities that I'm talking about in personal terms
has to do with eliminating that step,'' he said. ``And instead,
when you ask me a question, without hesitation, I tell you exactly
what's in my heart on it, spontaneously, here's what I feel about
it. And if that conflicts with what the administration's priorities
are _ I don't want it to, but if it does _ so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Gore has distanced himself very little on substantive
policy issues from the Clinton administration. But the political
bind he is in because of his position was evident when he was
talking about Microsoft. He was asked what kind of signal his visit
would send. ``None,'' he declared. ``I strongly support vigorous
enforcement of the antitrust law.'' But he added that Microsoft was
the largest employer in Washington and that his rivals had all
visited its campus outside Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I don't comment on individual cases,'' he added, ``I
want you to know that I think the trend toward concentration in
some areas _ and I have agriculture especially in mind _ has been
very troubling.''
</P>
<P>
   He also wears his administration hat when he is asked about his
``official'' Veterans Day speech in Iowa. Even though he lambasted
the Republicans for what he said were isolationist views and for
not paying America's dues to the United Nations, as well as for
cutting the foreign policy budget and failing to pass the nuclear
test-ban treaty, he insisted his was an official visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a speech on Veterans Day to veterans at a VA facility
ought to be official,'' he said, ``and in the process to talk about
how we can honor our veterans by helping to make future wars less
likely is not only appropriate but necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   He made another appearance this week that was cast as official,
this one in Memphis, Tenn., on Tuesday night to address the 92nd
annual convention of the Church of God in Christ. The setting was
the church where the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. delivered his
``Mountaintop'' speech just before his assassination. The audience
was extremely friendly to Gore, who spoke in a sermonlike manner
for nearly an hour about his views on family, health care,
education and included a few potshots at Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   His aides said this was an official visit because the invitation
was extended to him as vice president, not as a candidate. But the
audience had little doubt. ``I think this was very political,''
said Lee Shirley, 59, a worshiper from Los Angeles who found Gore
an ``excellent'' speaker. ``No. 1, he's interested in running for
office,'' she said, ``and naturally he wants to win as many votes
from our community as he can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 2213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
