<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, NOVEMBER 13
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-KOSOVO-DEATHS-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Nov. 10.)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Nov.
10, about the number of bodies found by war crimes investigators in
Kosovo referred incorrectly to a State Department briefing on April
19. The department did not say that up to 500,000 Kosovar Albanians
were missing and feared dead. Its spokesman, James P. Rubin, said
that 100,000 men were unaccounted for and that ``based on past
practice, it is chilling to think where those 100,000 men are.'' He
said, ``We know that civilian casualties are the objective of
President Milosevic's policy.''
</P>
<P>
   BC-AUSTRALIA-MONARCHY-NYT (moved on Saturday, Nov. 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, Nov. 6,
about a referendum on ending the symbolic role of the British
monarchy in Australia referred incorrectly to the results. Five of
Australia's six states, not five territories, voted against the
measure. Of the two Australian regions classified as territories,
one voted for it and one voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-OVARIES-NYT (moved on Friday, Sept. 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Sept. 24,
about the transplant of frozen ovarian tissue misstated the
occupation of an Arizona woman who underwent it. An annual report
newly received from New York Methodist Hospital, in Brooklyn, shows
her as a belly dancer, not a ballet dancer; the word was
misunderstood by telephone interviewers.
</P>
</TEXT>
