<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     11-12 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CHECKMATE IN A SQUARED CIRCLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ On the eve of a big fight, perhaps the last
significant heavyweight fight of the millennium, Emanuel Steward,
the trainer who put Thomas ``Hit Man'' Hearns on the map, is in a
clinch, simultaneously excited and frustrated. With a victory over
Evander Holyfield on Saturday night, his client, Lennox Lewis, the
World Boxing Council champion, will become the undisputed
heavyweight champion of the world.
</P>
<P>
   A riveting fight will be the first real step to re-establishing
professional boxing's popularity, more so than federal regulations
or moral hand-wringing over the fairness of the sport. Steward, who
has trained 11 champions, feels that Lewis, imposing at 6 feet 5
inches, 242 pounds, could be the most dominating fighter in boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Lennox opened up, he would knock Evander out in the first
round,'' Steward said. ``But I don't believe he's going to do it.
It's like he's got somebody with a chain holding him back, or like
a racehorse that's got a weight on its back. Lennox has put that
weight on himself, and I don't know if he's going to take it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Steward feels the weight on his fighter's back is a 64-square
menagerie of kings and queens, bishops, knights and pawns. Lewis is
an avid chess player, and throughout the week Steward has contended
that the boxer's fondness for the game has become an impediment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm against chess because in the ring he can't forget it,''
Steward said. ``This thinking and analyzing and looking two steps
ahead to how he could take advantage of Holyfield's mistakes
worries me.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's fight is a rematch of a battle last March at
New York's Madison Square Garden. Lewis controlled the fight but
didn't finish strongly, and the match ended in a draw. Saturday
night, Lewis is expected to come out more aggressively, take
chances and take charge. At least this is what Steward wants. Lewis
himself prefers finesse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am into the sweet science of the sport,'' he said. ``I'm
going in there to use all my talent: my height, my reach and my
boxing ability. It's not all about going in there and knocking
people out. So I think it really comes down to me: what I believe
and how I should go about it. I think this time I'll be as cautious
and take more chances as well.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the legitimate talk about having boxing's redemption
tied up in one fight, for Steward, Saturday night's bout is in
large measure about himself and Holyfield. Steward worked for
Holyfield six years ago, after Holyfield's loss to Riddick Bowe and
subsequent temporary retirement. When Holyfield returned to boxing,
he hired Steward, who then helped Holyfield in his rematch victory
over Bowe in 1993. After the victory, Steward asked for a raise.
Holyfield said no, and Steward said goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did for him was a total resurrection job,'' Steward
said at the time. ``All I asked for was what I thought I deserved.
I was used.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield then responded: ``It's all about ego with some
trainers. The trainer's only as good as the fighter. The trainer
don't make the fighter. It's all about money with Emanuel. He looks
at this as a lawyer does a client. Lawyers will try to get any
client in the world, just to keep their paydays flowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield bristles at suggestions that Steward helped him get
the title. ``Get the title?'' he said. ``Ain't nobody got me
nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Steward, Holyfield said: ``This man told me what to
do, and I paid him the money to tell me what to do. If that's all
it took, go find another fighter and make him champion.''
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to Steward and Lennox Lewis _ a fiery trainer and
a different sort of fighter who ``plays'' boxing the way athletes
play football or basketball or hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a boxer/puncher,'' he said this week. ``I'm not like Mike
Tyson.'' When someone asked about Holyfield's legacy of being a
warrior, Lewis said: ``I don't know if I want to be a warrior.
Warriors have to take punishment and come back. I think there's a
point where you can't come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Steward is predicting that he, his sport and his fighter will
storm back to prominence Saturday night with a crushing checkmate.
``The fight will end in a knockout,'' he said. ``I wanted a
knockout the first time, but Lennox wanted to show all his talents,
his boxing skills. This time, Lennox is more focused on a knockout.
And for his legacy, he needs it.''
</P>
<P>
   Evander Holyfield was boxing's Real Deal, Lennox Lewis could be
a sorely needed Paul Bunyan. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 2221EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8286 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-POKEMON-SUIT-NYT &LR;      11-12 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POKEMON-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 PARENTS SUE OVER DEATH OF CHILD WHO CHOKED ON POKEMON TOY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also POKEMON-FAD) 
(mk) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The parents of a Yonkers, N.Y., boy who choked to
death on a Pokemon ball filed a federal lawsuit against the toy's
maker and distributor on Friday, two days after the opening of a
movie about the popular game.
</P>
<P>
   The parents, Adrienne and Kevin Brazier, claim that the toy
manufacturer, Hasbro Inc., and the distributor, Toys ``R'' Us, were
negligent in making and selling the toy _ a 1.7-inch clear rubber
ball with a cartoon figure inside _ as safe for children over 3
years old.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 30, their autistic son, Robert, 7, was biting the ball
to remove the cartoon figure when he swallowed it, the Braziers
said Friday. Family members, neighbors, paramedics and emergency
room doctors were unable to dislodge the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit says the toy, a Pokemon Power Bouncer, violates
federal safety standards and presents a choking hazard because it
is smaller than 1.75 inches. ``If the ball was a little bit bigger,
it would never have gotten lodged,'' Mrs. Brazier said.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also said that the toy failed to pass a ``ring test''
established by a product safety company, ACTS Testing Labs Ltd.,
which measures the size of objects to determine choking hazards,
said Gary Certain, a lawyer for the family. The lawsuit seeks $100
million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro, the nation's second-largest toy maker, released a
statement Friday saying that it remained confident about the ball's
design and manufacture. ``Approximately 8 million of these balls
have been played with by children throughout the world without a
similar incident,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   A Toys ``R'' Us spokeswoman, Rebecca Caruso, said that she could
not comment because she had not seen the suit, but that all of the
company's toys meet federal safety standards. She added, ``We think
it was a very tragic incident and our deepest sympathies go out to
the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Brazier said she and her husband decided to sue when the
companies failed to redesign the ball or remove it from stores.
``It was the only way to get through to them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was timed to reach as many families as possible, she
said, with the movie opening and Christmas around the corner. ``We
could never live with ourselves if we saw that another child died
tragically the way ours did,'' Mrs. Brazier said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
