<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MISS-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MISSISSIPPI MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Nov. 13:
</P>
<P>
   For all its progress since those ugly days when only whites
could vote, Mississippi now faces an embarrassing reminder of its
worst old instincts. That embarrassment comes in the form of the
gubernatorial race that is still officially undecided 11 days after
the election. The Democratic candidate, Lt. Gov. Ronnie Musgrove,
received the most votes, 6,600 more than the Republican candidate,
former U.S. Rep. Mike Parker. If that would seem to settle matters
elsewhere in the union, it does not in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi's constitution includes a passage written more than
a century ago that was designed specifically to keep blacks from
gaining political power in the state. This provision requires that
if a candidate does not win a majority of the popular vote and a
majority of the 122 Mississippi House districts, the House members
choose the winner. Musgrove fell just short of a majority, with
49.5 percent of the vote, and Parker, who got 48.6 percent, is
stubbornly refusing to concede. Musgrove's Democratic colleagues
control the House, so his eventual victory seems assured. But that
vote will not come until Jan. 4. In practical terms, that means
Parker has invented a nearly two-month interregnum for reminding
the nation of his state's racist past.
</P>
<P>
   Parker may be holding out for reasons of shock. Pre-election
polls showed an easy Republican victory. But the continued efforts
to wheedle extra votes out of the legislature in hopes of
overruling the electorate can only make the Republicans look petty
and undemocratic.
</P>
<P>
   The delay in declaring a new governor should encourage
Mississippians to get rid of one of the last reminders of their
state's segregationist heritage. The Mississippi constitution no
longer requires literacy tests or poll taxes to keep blacks from
voting. It should also be rid of the 1890 provision designed to
give white legislators a chance to prevent any blacks who won at
the polls from ever taking office. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
