<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-BLAZERS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks reveal bench role was Rider's choice
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND _ Looking forward to ``a game I had circled on my
calendar,'' Isaiah Rider will be in the lineup tonight when the
Hawks play Portland and former teammate Steve Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Rider and coach Lenny Wilkens agreed on that Friday after
acknowledging it was Rider's decision not to start Wednesday
against Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think having J.R. in the lineup with Chris Crawford and the
other three (Dikembe Mutombo, Alan Henderson and Bimbo Coles) is
the way to go right now,'' Wilkens said, ``because they both add so
much to the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had also come to that conclusion before Wednesday
night's game, ``Although I was going another way during
shoot-around. I told J.R. before the game that I thought we'd be
better with him starting, but he thought we'd be better the way we
had practiced.''
</P>
<P>
   Rider said, ``It was no big deal to me then. My feeling was guys
went through shoot-around and went for their naps thinking it was
going to be one way, then it would be a disappointment to change. I
didn't want them to think that Lenny had me in the lineup just to
keep me happy because I already knew we were working up to having
me start by (Saturday's game). I already knew that.''
</P>
<P>
   This makes Rider's performance against the Grizzlies (2-for-7,
14 minutes) almost inexplicable. Wilkens removed him after a
five-minute stint in the second half because he showed obvious
disinterest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised,'' Wilkens said. ``I thought his head wasn't
there and I was surprised because we had talked before the game.
But we've had two talks since then and I'm going to put it behind
me and see where we go from here. I think he had to learn about me.
But I don't want to see it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Rider scored 65 points in three previous games, one a start in
Denver. It was his 28-point show in that game, Wilkens said, that
convinced him Rider should join the lineup for keeps ahead of
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready now,'' Rider said after a lengthy practice.
``Obviously, I want to play as many minutes as I can. On this team
I think I can play 35, 40, 42 minutes, but I didn't want it to seem
he was catering to me. I didn't want to be selfish that way. Now,
though, I think I'm ready to take my place.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his meetings with Wilkens and general manager Pete Babcock,
Rider said, ``Both sides aired some things out. ...I want to be in
there as much as I can and try to help the team win some games. I'm
ready to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I want the offense coming to me, trying to run some
plays in the post, drawing the double teams, finding my teammates.
I know if just stay out there on the wing I'm going to be too
predictable, and we can't let the defense have that advantage. No
one can work in today's rules in total (isolations), so if I get it
in the continuity of the offense that just helps my game,'' Rider
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Blazers know he will be coming at them. ``I talked
to Bonzi (Wells) and Rasheed (Wallace). Bonzi said, `I guess you'll
be coming at me,' and I said, `Of course I will in a situation like
this. Any player will.' But I'm not going to try and take the game
over single-handedly like I would when I was younger and didn't
know better.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
