<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; MICROSOFT  &LR; _  &LR;   &LR; Microsoft is in no mood to settle. Sure, Bill Gates
and his minions say Microsoft Corp. is ready to compromise with
antitrust authorities after a judge's ruling that the Godzilla of
software-makers has been stomping all over its rivals. But the
sentiment behind the scenes at the company's headquarters in
Redmond is of wounded pride and hurt feelings and a growing
determination to fight for what Microsoft employees believe to be
right _ that their company is a tough but fair competitor. By David
Lazarus
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; CONSUMERQ&AMP;A &LR;  _ The banking bill just signed by President Clinton
has been hyped as the biggest revolution in financial regulation in
more than half a century. It ends separations between banking,
insurance and securities brokerage dating from the Depression era
and rewrites rules in areas ranging from consumer privacy to
community lending. In fact, the bill merely recognizes what's
happening in the marketplace, where banks, insurance companies and
securities firms already have gotten deeply into each other's
businesses. Here are some questions and answers to help clarify
what the bill means for consumers. By Sam Zuckerman
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; TUXEDOS _  &LR;  Men's Wearhouse, the 800-pound gorilla of men's suits,
is trying to get the tuxedo rental business all sewn up. After a
successful test launch in 10 Seattle stores, the company has opened
tuxedo rental departments in its five Sacramento locations and is
rolling them out to all 27 of its Bay Area stores. If all goes
according to plan, every Men's Wearhouse across the country _
currently 437 _ will include a formal wear department in three to
five years, a plan that fundamentally will alter the fragmented
sector. By Carol Emert
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; KAISER _ &LR;  (Abate) Kaiser's vaunted labor partnership got a black
eye this week, when the National Labor Relations Board threw out
its choice for a pharmacist's union and replaced it with a
different union, thathasn't joined the HMO's labor-management love
fest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RITEAID13 _ &LR;  (Wires) Rite Aid Corp. may sell more of its 1,000
drugstores on the West Coast as the company seeks to raise cash,
slash $4.5 billion in debt and revive a stock that's dropped 86
percent this year. The third-largest U.S. drugstore chain already
sold 38 West Coast stores and last month said it may sell as many
as 350. Rite Aid is considering selling another 650 as it seeks to
raise about  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
