 &QL; 
 &LR; $2.5 billion from store sales, the Wall Street Journal reported,
citing a person familiar with the situation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ECONOMY13  &LR; _ (Wires) Americans spent more carefully in October,
while workers' productivity advanced strongly. That combination,
which can help keep inflation under control, increases the chances
the Federal Reserve will leave interest rates alone when it meets
next week, economists said. The Commerce Department reported Friday
that retail sales held steady in October, after falling 0.1 percent
in September, as Americans restricted their spending on cars and
furniture but shelled out more for hardware, building supplies and
clothing. In another report that Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan has
said he would be watching closely, the Labor Department said the
growth in American workers' productivity _ the amount of output for
each hour of work _ rose at a 4.2 percent annual rate in the
July-September quarter. Unit labor costs, considered a key measure
of wage pressure, rose just 0.6 percent, the slowest quarterly
increase this year. As long as workers are increasingly productive,
employers can afford to pay them without needing to raise prices.
But if productivity falters, pressures for higher wages can result
in inflation, a particular danger Greenspan is on the lookout for.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INDEX13  &LR; _ (Wires) U.S. stocks rose, led by financial shares
including American Express Co. and Citigroup Inc., after a
government report on productivity eased investors' concern the
Federal Reserve will raise interest rates for a third time this
year when policy-makers meet Tuesday. The Nasdaq Composite Index
rose to its 10th closing record in 11 sessions. The Nasdaq rose
23.57, or 0.7 percent, to a record 3220.86, rebounding from a
72-point loss as Qualcomm Inc. soared on a favorable report from a
J.P. Morgan Securities analyst. The Dow Jones Industrial average
rallied 173.71, or 1.6 percent, to 10,769.01, its biggest gain in
two weeks. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index gained 14.58, or 1.1
percent, to 1396.04. Seventeen stocks rose for every 13 that fell
on the New York Stock Exchange. Sunnyyvale's Finisar Corp., which
makes fiber optic systems that  &LR;  &QL; 
