<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAISER-KAISER </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Labor Board Shifts Union at Kaiser  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The National Labor Relations Board forced Kaiser Permanente this
week to replace one of its union partners with a different labor
group that hasn't joined the HMO's labor-management pact.
<P>
   Ironically, the move occurred the same day Kaiser was
publicizing a no-layoff deal with its AFL-CIO partners.
</P>
<P>
   The most immediate effect of the NLRB ruling is that 850 Kaiser
pharmacists in Northern California now will be represented by a
union that has won higher pay for 1,800 pharmacists in Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   The switch also sheds a little light on the closed-door
politicking between Kaiser and the region's health care unions.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser announced its no-layoff pact in a Tuesday press
conference with AFL-CIO President John Sweeney, touting the
agreement as proof that the 2-year-old peace pact between the two &LR; 
sides  &LR; was good for rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   That same night in Oakland, the NLRB finally tabulated the votes
in a union election that was held more than a year earlier. Kaiser
legal objections delayed the count.
</P>
<P>
   The year-old election had pitted Kaiser's AFL-CIO partner union,
Engineers and Scientists of California, against the independent
Guild for Professional Pharmacists. The Guild ended with 58 percent
of the vote, ESC had 37 percent, and 5 percent opted for no union.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser union negotiator Danycq &LR;  Valenzuela explained why Kaiser
contested the count. After ESC spent two years getting more than
half of Kaiser's Northern California pharmacists to sign cards
seeking union representation, the HMO agreed to recognize ESC as
that union.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as that happened, the Guild demanded an election.
Valenzuela said Kaiser felt obliged to stand behind its pledge to
ESC. Now that the NLRB vote has installed the Guild, she is ready
to bargain a new contract while the current pact, negotiated with
ESC, remains in effect.
</P>
<P>
   Wages are likely to be one item on the table. Guild President
Ralph Vogel said Kaiser pharmacists in Northern California get $37
to $38 an hour under the ESC contract. Kaiser's Southern California
pharmacists get an average of $40.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time, the north was ahead of us in the south, but they
slipped,'' Vogel said.
</P>
<P>
   The reversal in union representation, and Kaiser's role in
trying to prevent the vote count, has caused some bitterness among
pharmacists. Guild partisans wonder why, if Kaiser is so
buddy-buddy with the unions, did it slow the vote count with NLRB
maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   ESC officers, such as Santa Rosa pharmacist Jeff Wong, say their
union spent years trying to organize Kaiser pharmacists while the
Guild swooped in at the last minute and demanded an election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overriding factor was the Guild charged less in dues,''
Wong said, adding that the pro-Guild vote was not a rejection of
the AFL-CIO partnership.
</P>
<P>
   But Vogel believes the Guild won because pharmacists preferred a
union that represents only their profession rather than being
affiliated with AFL-CIO unions that represent many trades. He said
he has no plans to join Kaiser's partnership with the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
