<HEADER>
A8292 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE13-COX     11-12 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Qualifying dominated by Pontiac
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOMESTEAD, Fla. _ Pontiac's supremacy during first-round
qualifying on Friday for the Pennzoil 400 was so obvious that it
even evoked anger from mild-mannered Jeff Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get into that Pontiac thing,'' said Gordon,
who drives the No. 24 Chevy. ``It's more obvious than it's ever
been, so I don't need to say a whole lot.''
</P>
<P>
   David Green won his first career Winston Cup pole with a speed
of 155.759 mph at Homestead-Miami on Friday, but the accomplishment
was lost in the controversy over the domination of Pontiac, which
fielded the top five qualifying cars.
</P>
<P>
   John Andretti will share the front row with Green, followed by
Bobby Labonte, rookie Dave Blaney and Ward Burton. Rick Mast was
the top Ford qualifier at sixth, while Gordon drove the fastest
Chevy for the No. 10 position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good to be the first Chevrolet,'' Gordon said. ``That's
all we can do, be the best Chevrolet.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than relishing his first pole in 72 career starts, Green
found himself defending his manufacturer in the post-qualifying
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts a little bit at times because we (Pontiac) had our
best finish at Phoenix (won by Pontiac No. 20 driver Tony Stewart,
who qualified seventh Friday) and the first thing I read about in
the paper is the Chevrolet and the Ford people saying, `Well,
anybody can drive a Pontiac nowadays in Winston Cup and you are
going to win.' I don't feel like that is a fair statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a cycle. The Chevrolets are probably going to
come out with a better piece and Ford is going to do the same
thing. I don't care who you are in the garage area, from the top to
the bottom, you all have the same pieces. You all have the
capabilities of getting it through that inspection line and making
it the best you possibly can.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time a manufacturer showcased similar mastery was Ford
qualifying the top seven cars in last year's second Rockingham
race. Andretti said Pontiacs have no unfair advantage this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good news and bad news today,'' Andretti said. ``The good
news is that it was a good day for Pontiac. The bad news is, as in
any kind of motorsports, everybody that's not in a Pontiac is going
to tell you (there's an unfair advantage).
</P>
<P>
   ``Just throw a Chevy decklid (on our cars) and we'll go race
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, who is 38th in the Winston Cup points standings, switched
from the No. 41 Chevy of Larry Hendrick Motorsports to the No. 45
Pontiac of TylerJet Motorsports in September.
</P>
<P>
   The Owensboro, Ky. native's best finish of the season was 12th
last week in Phoenix. He has not won a race in five years of
Winston Cup racing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
