<SLUG> BC-NY-CABS-BIAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAB RADIOS BROADCAST WARNINGS, BUT DRIVERS ARE STILL CITED IN
STING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By the time Mohammed Faruque settled into his cab
just after dawn Friday, the radio of his yellow cab had already
started crackling with exchanges of advice: Take extra care _ pick
up anyone flagging down a cab, no matter the color of their skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course people are careful,'' said Faruque, 45, of Brooklyn,
as he chatted at lunchtime with a clutch of drivers over milky tea
and Marlboro Lights at New Kasturi Pavilion restaurant, a popular
pitstop for South Asian cabbies on Lexington Avenue in Manhattan.
``We are all being extra careful. Anyone who raises his hand, take
him.''
</P>
<P>
   On Day 1 of New York City's widely-publicized undercover sting
against cabdrivers who refuse to pick up minority passengers, this
was not an unexpected response. What was surprising were those who
apparently did not heed the warning.
</P>
<P>
   During the first nine hours of the program, called Operation
Refusal, teams of undercover police officers and taxi inspectors,
black and white, hailed 683 cabs throughout Manhattan. Of those,
five passed up customers on the basis of their race or gender,
police and taxi commission officials said. Among those cited was a
driver on the East Side of Manhattan who refused to pick up a white
woman with two children; instead, the driver picked up an
undercover inspector, a white male, nearby.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to those five, two drivers were cited for refusing
to go a particular destination. One of the would-be riders was a
Hispanic undercover police officer at 32nd Street and Park Avenue.
She asked the driver to go to Kings County Hospital Center in
Brooklyn and was told to get out of the cab, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
said. One of the most frequent complaints against cabdrivers is
that they refuse to go to primarily black and Latino neighborhoods
in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The cabs of the cited drivers were taken to local police
precincts until they could be reclaimed by their owners. The
authorities took away the hack licenses of the drivers who were
cited, pending a hearing at the city Taxi and Limousine Commission.
In addition to those who were cited for refusing customers, 10 were
issued summonses for a range of other violations.
</P>
<P>
   If found guilty of having bypassed a minority passenger, a
cabdriver can be fined and the driver's hack license suspended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the good news in all of this is that in the
overwhelming majority of cases, cabdrivers did what they were
supposed to do,'' Giuliani said Friday at a news briefing in City
Hall, just hours after the crackdown began. ``I think most
cabdrivers in this city attempt to obey the laws and are fair and
equitable in their treatment. Unfortunately, for too long, there
have been a few that haven't, and maybe the warning has reduced
that few to even a smaller number.''
</P>
<P>
   That praise notwithstanding, the mayor was not exactly popular
among drivers at the New Kasturi. Giuliani, they said out, had
already made their lives difficult last year with a series of new
stringent regulations. Friday's crackdown, they asserted, was part
of an effort to earn political points in his potential bid for the
U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an election, and Giuliani just wants to make black
people happy,'' said Rakib Hossain, 34, a driver for more than 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly added, ``But I don't refuse black people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
