<HEADER>
A8294 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-TUXEDOS-TUXEDOS_SFCHR     11-12 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUXEDOS-TUXEDOS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Small Shops Wary of Men's Wearhouse Entry Into Rental
Formal-Wear  Market 
 &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Men's Wearhouse, the 800-pound gorilla of men's suits, is trying to
get the tuxedo rental business all sewn up.
<P>
   After a successful test launch in 10 Seattle stores, the company
has opened tuxedo rental departments in its five Sacramento
locations and is rolling them out to all 27 of its Bay Area stores.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes according to plan, every Men's Wearhouse across the
country _ currently 437 _ will include a formal wear department in
three to five years, a plan that fundamentally will alter the
fragmented sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one national leader in the industry,'' said Kelly
Armstrong, an analyst with First Union Securities in San Francisco.
Men's Wearhouse's national footprint, brand awareness and sizable
advertising budget give it a leg up on the single-store bridal
boutiques and regional chains that populate the sector, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're (already) known for suits,'' Armstrong said. ``It's
not that big of a leap for a customer to go in and rent a tuxedo
from Men's Wearhouse versus some no-name store.''
</P>
<P>
   Men's Wearhouse is offering attractive prices: $50 to $70 a day
for a full ensemble. The average tux rental in 1996, the latest
year for which information is available, was $72, according to the
International Formalwear Association.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller merchants, not surprisingly, are wary. Men's Wearhouse,
which is regarded as aggressive and well-run, has blanketed the
country with moderate-priced stores known for good customer
service. The suit-seller also spends millions of dollars on TV
advertising _ an unaffordable luxury for most of its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the little guys aren't about to throw in the
handkerchief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody can create a monopoly,'' said Hal
Turner, president of Dick Bruhn Inc. of Hayward, which owns the
local Selix chain. ``We feel good about ourselves _ we've been in
business since 1906.''
</P>
<P>
   As a newcomer, Men's Wearhouse offers only 13 styles of tuxedos,
while Selix offers more than 40, Turner noted.
</P>
<P>
   Turner and other formal wear doyennes say they have the upper
hand because their reputations are established, they have marketing
expertise in the prom and bridal markets, and their staffs are
highly trained in the minutiae of cummerbunds and cuff links.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, the existing tux merchants also have mastered the
complex business of keeping track of thousands of multipart
ensembles as they are shuffled through orders and returns,
fittings, alterations and dry cleanings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like there's a general practitioner who can come in to do
your knees or there's a guy who does nothing but knees _ who would
you go to?'' said Jack Springer, executive director of the
International Formalwear Association.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for smaller players, a boom in the tuxedo business
should blunt any diversion of sales to Men's Wearhouse. The sector
has jumped to $1.2 billion in revenues last year from about $80
million in 1994, propelled by the prom-going members of the huge
Echo Boom generation, according to the formal-wear association.
Rentals represent about 80 percent of total revenues, with sales
accounting for the remainder.
</P>
<P>
   Rapid growth will continue for the foreseeable future because
there are many young Echo Boomers in the pipeline, Springer said.
``Our industry is having the best year we've ever had, and last
year was the second-best,'' he said. Millennium celebrations will
provide an added boost in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Men's Wearhouse, for its part, has high hopes for formal wear.
``There are all kinds of upsides for us,'' said Rich Goldman,
executive vice president of merchandising and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, a company co-founder, believes that his company's share
of the tux market eventually will match its suit share, which has
grown to more than 11 percent from 9 percent in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   One attractive bonus: The profit margin on tux rentals is much
higher than on suit sales. Goldman declined to discuss margins in
detail, but Turner provided this assessment: ``If Men's Wearhouse
can take a tux they were going to sell for $295 and rent it 80
times for $80 dollars (generating $6,400), there's a difference
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Men's Wearhouse has a big job ahead of it as it enters
this new business. While the company has always sold a few tuxedos,
Goldman acknowledges that the rental business is filled with a raft
of logistical obstacles that company planners are just starting to
tackle.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Men's Wearhouse must formulate a national
distribution system that quickly can move tuxes between tailoring,
cleaning, stores and warehouses. It must either set up a network of
reliable dry cleaners or learn to do the job itself, a big jump
into an entirely different business.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high. If a customer winds up with a 42-long
instead of a 42-short on his wedding day, Men's Wearhouse has lost
not only future tux rentals, but potential future sales for its
core tailored-clothing business.
</P>
<P>
   The company's competitors ``are people who have been in this
business a long time and they're formidable,'' said Goldman.
``That's why we're taking three to five years to roll it out
instead of doing it overnight. We want to make sure we're the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the tux business' fat margins, perhaps the biggest
draw for Men's Wearhouse is the opportunity to broaden its market
to a new group, teens and twentysomethings.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 percent of rented tuxes are worn to proms, and most of
the rest are for weddings. In contrast with that youthful
demographic, Men's Wearhouse shoppers generally range in age from
mid-30s to upper 40s, Goldman said.
</P>
<P>
   Although young men don't buy a lot of suits, Men's Wearhouse is
betting that a positive experience today will breed return visits
years down the pike.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing in new customers is particularly important for Men's
Wearhouse because it still is battling a negative image acquired
years ago from bad advertising, Goldman said. In the ads, which
left a lasting impression among American consumers, Men's Wearhouse
co-founder and chief executive George Zimmer came across as an
aggressive, fast-talking salesman.
</P>
<P>
   (Springer vividly remembers an ad in which Zimmer exhorted
viewers to buy tuxedos at Men's Wearhouse to avoid renting one
``that some high school kid had vomited on.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``People still think about that Zimmer guy sorta screaming at
them,'' Goldman said. ``People's perceptions tend to change when
they shop at the store.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuxes provide ample opportunity for both impulse buys and
image-building because renters must visit three times _ for the
fitting, the pickup and the return. ``Having three opportunities to
expose people to Men's Wearhouse is a wonderful thing,'' Goldman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Men's Wearhouse will be able to master the tux business
remains to be seen, but early returns are encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of the company's Seattle tux customers showed that 95
percent ``had no problems and were delighted with the experience,''
Goldman said. Two-thirds were first-time Men's Wearhouse customers.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether they would come back to shop, ``an
overwhelming majority said they would consider it, whereas they
might not have before,'' Goldman said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
