<HEADER>
A8295 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-CONSUMERQA-CONSUMERQA     11-12 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQA-CONSUMER </SLUG>
 QA _ SF CHRON  
 What Banking Reform Means for Consumers  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The banking bill just signed by President Clinton has been hyped as
the biggest revolution in financial regulation in more than half a
century.
<P>
   It ends separations between banking, insurance and securities
brokerage dating from the Depression era and rewrites rules in
areas ranging from consumer privacy to community lending.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the bill merely recognizes what's happening in the
marketplace, where banks, insurance companies and securities firms
already have gotten deeply into each other's businesses. Here are
some questions and answers to help clarify what the bill means for
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: Banks already are buying securities firms and selling insurance.
So what's new here?
</P>
<P>
   A: Federal regulators gradually loosened the separations between
banks, insurance companies and brokerages, but plenty of obstacles
remained. For example, banks generally couldn't sell insurance
directly, but only through independent affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   The new law sweeps aside those barriers, allowing different
types of financial services companies to merge freely and sell a
full range of products.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR;  Q: What changes will consumers see in the marketplace?
</P>
<P>
   &LR; a  &LR;  A: Bank watchers predict a wave of mergers until a handful
of giant, nationwide companies dominate an integrated financial
services market. A few regional companies and many small,
single-product firms also will remain. ``There are going to be some
big guys who try to do everything and some small guys who want to
do one thing,'' said Todd Conover, managing partner of San
Francisco's Starmont Asset Management and one of the nation's top
bank regulators during the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will prices for financial products and services rise?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's a matter of debate. Industry representatives say that
greater economies of scale of the emerging financial-services
giants will push prices down. Consumer groups insist that the
near-monopoly status of the new leviathans will give them more
power to raise fees and interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR;  Q: Banks were separated from insurers and brokerages to keep
deposits safe. Won't banks become riskier when the barriers come
down?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Regulators backed the bill, arguing that large,
diversified financial companies would be able to absorb problems in
one part of their business. And the law incorporates certain
protections, so-called firewalls, to keep financial problems in one
part of a company from spreading.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups counter that risk multiplies when a company
combines banking, insurance and brokerage. It's almost certain
though that the government wouldn't allow a giant financial
conglomerate to fail. As in the savings and loan crisis, depositers
would be bailed out. ``It's the taxpayers who would end up footing
the bill,'' said Frank Torres, a banking expert at Consumers Union
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR;  Q: How does the new law affect consumer privacy?
</P>
<P>
   A: The new law's privacy protections are weak. Consumers have a
limited right to require companies to keep their personal data
private. Loopholes allow financial companies to share personal
consumer data freely with affiliates and, in some cases, outside
marketing companies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR;  Q: Will banks still have to lend to low-income communities?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: The law chips away at Community Reinvestment Act
requirements to lend in all neighborhoods, including low- and
moderate-income communities. Instead of examinations every year or
two, regulators would review the lending records of small banks
once every four or five years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
