r f BC-MICROSOFT-MICROSOFT_S     11-12 1512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-MICROSOFT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 A Bunker Mentality at Microsoft Campus  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Microsoft is in no mood to settle.
<P>
   Sure, Bill Gates and his minions say Microsoft Corp. is ready to
compromise with antitrust authorities after a judge's ruling that
the Godzilla of software-makers has been stomping all over its
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   But the sentiment behind the scenes at the company's
headquarters in Redmond is of wounded pride and hurt feelings and a
growing determination to fight for what Microsoft employees believe
to be right _ that their company is a tough but fair competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to have your government make claims you don't
believe,'' said Steve Guggenheimer, director of marketing for
Microsoft's consumer commerce group. ``We know we haven't done
anything wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   He echoed the stand that Gates laid out at the company's annual
shareholder meeting Wednesday. Although Microsoft is willing to
seek common ground with federal regulators, Gates insisted that
this would not come at the expense of being able to freely add new
features to its products.
</P>
<P>
   This particularly applies to the Windows operating system, which
runs on about 90 percent of the world's personal computers. The
inclusion of Microsoft's Internet Explorer browser, and its
subsequent effect on Netscape Communications Corp., is at the heart
of the government's antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   But for Gates, as well as for most of Microsoft's 17,000 local
workers, the central issue is the right to ``innovate.'' They see
themselves as champions of good, old-fashioned American principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Principles are important,'' Guggenheimer said. ``If the
company can find a settlement that's fair to both sides, great. But
otherwise, we should fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, rank-and-file Microsofties are doing their best to
show a stiff upper lip. In conversations on the company's sprawling
``campus'' and at favorite haunts like the nearby Pro Sports Club,
they toe the official line that the antitrust case is no big deal
and that they just want to get on with their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think that we're here trying to beat down the
competition every day,'' said a worker in Microsoft's games
division who identified himself only as Humberto, sitting in the
cafeteria. ``The reality is that we're just doing our jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The lawsuit doesn't matter,'' said a worker in the Windows
group who gave his name only as Dan, while on his way into the gym.
``It's not a distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Microsoft employees have been avidly debating the
merits of the case around the office and in lunchroom confabs,
according to sources, and pay close attention to how recent
headlines have affected the company's stock (which isn't much).
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft workers have been instructed by the company not to
discuss the case with reporters without prior clearance, which is
why all those who agreed to be interviewed at length tended to
sound as if they were reading from the same script. Others refused
to comment.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who find themselves in situations where questions
are unavoidable, the in-house newsletter, MicroNews, provided
employees with ``answers that explain where Microsoft stands on
these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Microsoft's stance is that the company has done
nothing wrong, has not tried to eliminate Netscape as a competitor
and does not have a monopoly in the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft President Steve Ballmer reinforced the company's spin
last week in an internal memo e-mailed to employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This antitrust case will be a long process, and we are in it
for the long haul,'' he wrote. ``Bill and I would like nothing more
than to resolve this today, but we believe we must stand up for a
vitally important principle _ the freedom of every company to
innovate and improve its products for its customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Murray, the Microsoft spokesman who represented the company
through much of the antitrust trial in Washington, D.C., expanded
on this notion during a lengthy interview. He used the example of
speech-recognition software, which enables users to speak directly
to their computers, and other ``smart'' appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are stand-alone programs out there, but we're working on
a very robust speech-recognition application,'' Murray said. ``The
government lawsuit says that if we bundle it into the system,
they'll take us to court.''
</P>
<P>
   There's the rub. Microsoft says it must be able to add such
features as it pleases. But the reality is that if Windows were
equipped with an easy-to-use speech-recognition program, it would
certainly discourage would-be rivals from developing a similar
product that might be better.
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson mulls
potential remedies, Microsoft is trying to convince all who will
listen that free enterprise must take priority over intrusive
government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that is awkward but completely legally true
is that if your products are phenomenally popular or simply better
than other people's products, there is nothing wrong with that,''
Murray said. ``Microsoft's products are popular because people
choose them.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless a settlement is reached beforehand, the next step is for
the government to file its response early next month to Jackson's
``findings of fact,'' which stated that Microsoft enjoys a monopoly
in the computer business.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft would then file its response in January, followed in
short order by the government's reply and then the company's reply
to the reply.
</P>
<P>
   A final decision from the judge could come in March or April of
next year, and his remedy _ which could range from a slap on the
wrist to a breakup of the company _ could come several months
later.
</P>
<P>
   If either side were to appeal the judge's decision, the case
could drag on for three or four more years.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Cohen, who oversees Microsoft's dealings with Silicon
Valley startups, feels that the longer the case is drawn out, the
more other technology firms will come to see things Microsoft's
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the companies that have been fueling this case are
going to be in a world of hurt if the government starts regulating
products,'' he said. ``It almost seems like people are ignoring
that there's competition.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a constant refrain among Microsoft employees _ that the
software and computer industries are boiling with competition,
which is evidence of a free and fair marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   They tend to overlook other aspects of Judge Jackson's findings
of fact, such as Microsoft all but dictating terms to
computer-makers for use of Windows and its efforts to prevent
alternative software platforms, such as Java, from taking off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of people here agrees that Microsoft has done
nothing wrong and that the `facts' are a farce,'' said Dave Jacobs,
a former Microsoft employee who still works on campus testing
Windows products for a leading Japanese electronics firm. ``It's
like a direct insult.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that some Microsofties are embracing conspiracy
theories to explain the government's dogged pursuit of monopoly
charges. Such theories include resentment on the part of
politicians because Microsoft hadn't been throwing around enough
cash in Washington, as well as a personal vendetta against Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's hoping they'll fight,'' Jacobs said. ``Nobody wants
a settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes many investors at this week's shareholder meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they won't lie down,'' said Marlene Clark, a Los
Angeles restaurant manager whose stake in Microsoft has ``grown
enormously'' since 1986. ``They're a tough, fair competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gates is a smart guy,'' noted Gideon Parke, a Washington state
ferry worker. ``He earned his way to where he is. He should keep
doing what he's been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the community surrounding Microsoft's headquarters _ a
suburban wasteland of shopping centers, chain stores and strip
malls _ local merchants also are taking an active interest in the
outcome of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our customers are from Microsoft,'' said Steve Woody,
sales manager at BMW of Bellevue. ``What's good for Microsoft is
good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   And down the road at Savi, which offers free lattes with its
selection of upscale casual clothing, employees point out that
Microsoft's daily stock price is a regular feature of local radio
broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing isn't hurting them, so it isn't hurting local
businesses,'' said Lisa Halpern, a writer for the store's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   So where does it go from here? Murray, the Microsoft spokesman,
wishes he knew. But after spending nearly two hours detailing the
company's position on various points related to the antitrust case,
his earlier interest in reaching a settlement seemed to diminish.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are places where Microsoft has competed aggressively,
but we haven't done anything illegal,'' he said. ``At the end of
the legal day, the courts will find that we have acted fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
