<HEADER>
A8297 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-METS-GRIFFEY-NYT &LR;      11-12 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-GRIFFEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS PREPARE THEIR BEST PITCH FOR GRIFFEY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Md., Canada, Wash.)   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees have all but completed a new contract
with Jim Leyritz, while the Mets have made a small trade and
continue to explore the long-shot possibility of trading for
Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, who hit the final home run of 1999, has agreed in
principle to a deal for the 2000 season, a baseball official said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, who turns 36 next month, hit a home run in the eighth
inning of Game 4 of the Yankees' World Series sweep of Atlanta and
now has 8 home runs in 61 at-bats in the postseason. With the
Yankees, he will be a third-string catcher, a part-time designated
hitter and a backup at first base.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have been mostly concerned with fine-tuning their
roster, but the Mets are contemplating big changes. Pat Gillick,
the Seattle general manager, has indicated that he has received one
particularly interesting offer for Griffey, the All-Star center
fielder with 398 career home runs, and it appears the Mets
originated the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The offer may well include the Mets' closer, Armando Benitez,
because Seattle needs a closer. Benitez had 128 strikeouts in 78
innings, 22 saves and played an integral role as the Mets qualified
for the playoffs for the first time since 1988. But some members of
the organization have concerns about Benitez's approach to the
game. Translated: They don't like him.
</P>
<P>
   Mets officials surprised executives of other teams with their
willingness to discuss Benitez's availability at the general
managers' meetings, which ended on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets could also offer outfielder Roger Cedeno and perhaps
pitcher Octavio Dotel. Without identifying the team forwarding the
interesting offer, Gillick suggested that he planned to talk to
that team again last night.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Mets have the most attractive offer for Griffey for
the moment, they may be far from making a deal; most baseball
officials think the Cincinnati Reds eventually will be the most
competitive bidders for Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Mets will discuss trading Benitez, that does not
mean General Manager Steve Phillips, who made what turned out to be
a great deal to get Benitez, will ultimately be willing to deal the
hard-throwing right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were willing Friday to swap outfielder Jermaine
Allensworth, who batted .219 in 40 games for them, for Jon Nunnally
of the Boston Red Sox, a left-handed-hitting outfielder who mostly
played in Class AAA Pawtucket last season. Nunnally has a
reputation for playing hard and he has versatility. Because he is
out of options, it stands to reason that he will be part of the
team next year if he performs adequately in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets still want to re-sign first baseman John Olerud, but
Phillips said the team was prepared to pursue alternatives if
Olerud signed with Seattle. Friday was the first day free agents
could sign with different teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our plans in place,'' Phillips said, ``and we'll have
to see how this goes. Again, timing is an issue. What we don't want
to do is get caught holding the bag'' if Olerud leaves the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' options most likely include the pursuit of Toronto
first baseman Carlos Delgado or David Segui, the free-agent first
baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud, who is from suburban Seattle, played at Washington
State. Gillick was instrumental in coaxing him to sign his first
professional contract with Toronto a decade ago. Said Gillick:
``We're looking for a first baseman, that's for sure. I would think
he's an attractive-looking first baseman. We'll just see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have made contact with David Cone, a former Met who has
been with the Yankees since late in 1995. Baseball officials with
the Baltimore Orioles will meet Friday to discuss a possible offer
to the free-agent pitcher, among other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Executives who have dealt extensively with George Steinbrenner,
the Yankees' principal owner, say Cone's future with the Yankees
will be determined in the moments after Steinbrenner learns that
either the Mets or the Orioles are serious about signing the
veteran pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``If George can't stand the idea of Cone with the Mets or any
other team,'' said one baseball official, ``then he'll get a deal
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and the Mets will be involved next week with
Kazuhiro Sasaki, a 32-year-old right-handed reliever who is a free
agent after saving 229 games in Japan. Sasaki throws hard and
possesses a hard-breaking splitter, but he also is coming off arm
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips indicated Sasaki would throw for Mets officials at Shea
Stadium on Wednesday and would be working out later in the week in
Tampa, Fla., where the Yankees' player development offices are
situated.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball officials believe Sasaki's agent will try to negotiate
a deal for between $4 million and $6 million a season. Seattle and
the Los Angeles Dodgers may also be interested. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will eventually announce another deal that is all
but completed: the reliever Mike Stanton will sign a three-year
contract in the range of $2.5 million a season. ... The Mets
continue to try to deal Rickey Henderson. Tony La Russa, who
managed Henderson in Oakland, and the St. Louis Cardinals could be
a natural suitor for the outfielder, as they try to acquire a pure
leadoff hitter. ... Mets outfielder Darryl Hamilton has demanded a
trade. General Manager steve Phillips believes he did so primarily
to negotiate the right to a limited no-trade clause. The Mets have
until March 15 to trade Hamilton, but Phillips expects the player
to withdraw the demand before then, after some contract
discussions. ``Unless something else happens,'' Phillips said, ``I
expect him to be a Met'' in 2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 2230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
