<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8298 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-HAITI-OUTLOOK-ART-NYT     11-12 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-OUTLOOK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A HAITIAN CLIFFSIDE, LIFE ON THE EDGE OF EROSION AND
INDIFFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROS MORNE, Haiti _ The sound of raindrops heralds fear and
sleepless nights for Nicolas Tertilus and his neighbors. They live
atop a cliff overlooking the Mancelle River, which they watch swell
with torrents of water flowing down the treeless mountain slopes.
They hear the currents rush past the cliff, gouging chunks of dirt
from the base and making the earth tremble.
</P>
<P>
   The erosion below has also worn down the 31 families who live
above. Their backyards have been reduced to a sliver of soil.
Outhouses, kitchens and bedrooms have crashed to the riverbed. The
cliff is a sheer drop, smooth as glass, topped by a ragged edge of
broken soil and tangles of tree roots and pipes.
</P>
<P>
   Some people will not sleep in their homes when it rains, seeking
shelter with relatives. Women hang their laundry on the bushes
lining the cliff's edge but keep a safe distance, tossing the
clothes onto the branches and plucking them back with a broomstick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I built a wall two months ago to protect my children from the
edge,'' said Tertilus, a tailor whose house is now just a few yards
from the edge. ``Very soon, that will go too. In two or three years
all these houses could be lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The cliffside drama is both metaphor and microcosm of Haiti's
predicament. Decades of corrupt and dictatorial rule left the
country rotting while millions of dollars in aid were snatched up
by officials. The current government is saddled with debt from
those years, and the lingering paralysis makes it difficult to
improve roads, sanitation and other public works.
</P>
<P>
   Tertilus and his neighbors belong to a committee of residents
that has written to President Rene Preval and other officials
hoping to get a retaining wall to save the houses and protect the
national highway, town square and marketplace that lie in the path
of the encroaching erosion.
</P>
<P>
   But their pleas have gone unanswered. The government has been
paralyzed since 1997 from political infighting that has left the
nation with no legislature, no budget and no access to millions of
dollars in international aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day everybody sees they have a government with no
respect for the people,'' said Jean Gaston, a teacher active in the
committee. ``Regardless of the fact that there has been no budget,
the government buys new cars. They pay their ministers. They are
spending money. So they can spend money for this too.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior government officials said they were aware of the problems
in Gros Morne, a rural region about 125 miles north of the capital.
But they said the government could not do much until elections in
March. At best, it may take temporary measures to relocate the
families, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, there are so many urgent cases to take care
of,'' said Prime Minister Jacques Edouard Alexis. ``But until we
return to a normal political situation, we cannot have access to
the funds we need to take care of the major problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by their inability to budge the government, the
townspeople resorted to a desperate measure: they decided to move
river instead. Passing the hat for gas money, they got a bulldozer
from another town and sent it to the riverbed, where for two weeks
in June they dug a new channel and pushed mounds of dirt and stone
between the water and the cliff.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we did it, it was starting to break down, because we had a
rainy month,'' said Andre Altidor, a shopkeeper whose store is on
the cliff. ``It just started to wash away. It reminded me of a
saying in Creole: `You wash your hands and dry them in the dirt.'''
</P>
<P>
   The environmental calamities and administrative neglect that
have plagued much of the country are abundantly evident in Gros
Morne, a town of 20,000. For years, people cut down trees for
charcoal, deforesting 97 percent of the nation's land. The rainy
season brings mountainside erosion, rivers gorged with water and
more erosion along the water's path.
</P>
<P>
   Public services are unreliable. Running water is rare. There are
few phones. With the town's generator sputtering since February,
the nighttime streets are saturated in a darkness broken by
hundreds of flickering candles.
</P>
<P>
   People recall a time before the cliff, when a gentle slope led
to the river, which was lined with palm trees. The cliff began to
develop about 20 years ago, soon after a hurricane whose floods
eroded much of the hillside.
</P>
<P>
   But for most of the intervening years, the problems on the cliff
were seen as a personal tragedy affecting a handful of unlucky
homeowners. A government engineer visited the town and drew up a
plan for a protective wall. But without the $133,000 needed to
build it, the plan existed only on paper.
</P>
<P>
   About two years ago, heavy rains brought down large chunks of
the cliff. By then, Martin Floristil had abandoned his bedroom
inside his parents' home. One night, as he lay in his bed in an
adjoining room, he was jolted by a troubling noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around 10 o'clock I could start to hear soil falling piece by
piece,'' he said. ``Then there was a loud roar, and I got up and
ran out. The house trembled, and my old room fell off the cliff.''
</P>
<P>
   All that remains of his old bedroom is a cracked slab of
concrete floor, where a rusted mattress frame juts out over the
edge. The room where he once sought shelter is now used only to
take the occasional bath, its floor and walls lined with cracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can still feel the vibrations whenever the river swells,''
he said. ``You can feel the soil moving underneath.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, the residents formed their committee to
spur the government into action. They were joined by several Roman
Catholic nuns who brought with them skills from in decades of work
in the inner cities of Washington and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Patricia Dillon, who spent 25 years in the South Bronx
organizing tenants against indifferent landlords and violent drug
dealers, encountered the challenge of her life in Gros Morne. Some
people, accustomed to years of the government doing nothing, were
grimly and helplessly resigned to fate.
</P>
<P>
   She knew how to rally communities _ becoming a link between the
town and other religious and social justice groups that began to
help with reforestation projects and petitions to the Haitian
government. The committee found reports about the wall that was
never built and began translating the documents from the official
language of French into the popular idiom of Creole.
</P>
<P>
   ``For poor people to gain power, they need information,'' the
sister said in a telephone interview from New York, where she was
undergoing medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   One encouraging sign is that the townspeople have found a sense
of civic mission, much like many other grass-roots groups emerging
throughout the country to press for public efficiency and
accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people here are ready to do all we can,'' said the Rev.
Ronel Charelus, the pastor of the local Catholic church. ``We can
get to work. It's our situation. It's our lives. It's our town at
stake. But the money for this project, that is the one thing we
don't have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
