<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER `E-DODGERS' IN SCOREBOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ And the Dodgers were looking so good for _ how
long was it? _ two whole weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The front-office takeover by Bob Daly, trusted friend of Peter
O'Malley. The trade of bad boy Raul Mondesi for nice guy Shawn
Green. The rumors of an Eric Young trade. The rumors of key
free-agent signings.
</P>
<P>
   For Dodgers fans, down on the team since the Mike Piazza trade,
it has been a citywide sugar rush. Suddenly Los Angeles was looking
forward to opening day again (April 3, 2000, at Montreal; mark your
Christmas calendar). Amazing how quickly the metropolitan mood can
change.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes news the club might lose Adrian Beltre to free agency
as punishment for breaking major-league rules by signing the
Dominican third baseman to a contract before his 16th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Any number of things might happen as a result of the accusation
by Beltre's agent and the coming investigation by the baseball
commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   They range from insignificant (rulebreaking found to be careless
but inadvertent, Dodgers pay a slap-on-the-wrist fine) to highly
inconvenient (rulebreaking found to be willful, Dodgers forced to
outbid other teams to keep Beltre) to disastrous (rulebreaking
found to fit a pattern of deceit, Dodgers wave goodbye to young
infield cornerstone and are barred from signing foreign players for
a time).
</P>
<P>
   But whatever happens and whomever is to blame, it's another
embarrassment for the organization, more evidence things had spun
out of control before the Murdoch regime took over.
</P>
<P>
   The latest scandal is a reminder of the Dodgers' illegal
signings of Cuban players in 1996 and 1998, the punishment for
which cost the team two prospects and a $200,000 fine in June.
</P>
<P>
   It's a reminder of the $10,000 fine the club had to pay after
neglecting to tell the commissioner's office _ as the rules require
_ that it was absorbing part of Mel Rojas' contract after trading
the pitcher to the Detroit Tigers in April.
</P>
<P>
   It's a reminder of then-general manager Tom Lasorda's ignorance
of the free-agency rules that could have left the Dodgers with
nothing to show for trading Paul Konerko and Dennis Reyes to get
Jeff Shaw in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   It's a reminder of whatever other mess shook your confidence in
L.A.'s team.
</P>
<P>
   By trading a minor-leaguer Friday to get Florida Marlins third
baseman Kevin Orie (for ``corner infield depth,'' general manager
Kevin Malone said), the Dodgers seemed to admit guilt in the Beltre
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, a number of questions remain because Dodgers executives
aren't saying much beyond a written statement that rules and
integrity are good things, and Beltre is out of touch in the
Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Did a Dodgers scout or executive dream up the deceit when Beltre
was signed July 7, 1994, filing a phony birth certificate saying he
was born April 7, 1978, a year earlier than the truth? Or did
Beltre or his family lie about his birthdate because they wanted
the $23,000 signing bonus?
</P>
<P>
   Could his true age have stayed concealed for five years without
his participation in the lie?
</P>
<P>
   What went through his mind last season when he read newspaper
stories, media guides, yearbooks and trading cards that gave his
age as 21 when in fact he was 20? Did he think, ``Oh, an
unfortunate misprint, which I must call to the intention of the
proper individual''? Did he think, ``Still foolin' 'em''? Did he
even know about the rules?
</P>
<P>
   And how long has agent Scott Boras known that Beltre's Dominican
birth certificate says he was born April 7, 1979? Did Boras sit on
the information until October to enhance Beltre's value on the
free-agent market?
</P>
<P>
   If the player and agent participated in the deception, then is
it right that they stand to profit, since Boras thinks he could get
$6-8 million a year for Beltre, who made $220,000 in 1999?
</P>
<P>
   You can try to blame the scandal on Beltre or blame the absence
of an international draft, or point out that confusion about the
true birthdates of Latin American ballplayers _ usually they lie to
make themselves !ital!younger!off! _ is hardly news.
</P>
<P>
   But that's missing the point. However it happened, it's a
Dodgers screwup, another in a series. What next? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
