<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FIGHT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTERS VOW TO SLUG AND NOT BE SLUGGISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Both fighters, as well as those who run the sport,
say things will be different this time. Lennox Lewis and Evander
Holyfield meet again today at the Thomas &AMP; Mack Arena for one of
the biggest prizes in sports _ the undisputed heavyweight
championship _ and their place in history.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis says he'll be more aggressive than he was in their first
meeting, a controversial draw on March 13 in New York, when he
controlled the fight but fought too passively for his own good.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield says he'll be more like Holyfield, not the listless,
desperate fighter who looked all but shot.
</P>
<P>
   And Nevada officials have put everything in place to avoid the
disaster the first fight became _ read: terrible decision _ or
anything else that might sneak up and bite this reeling sport. The
state's best referee (Mitch Halpern) and most experienced judges
(Jerry Roth, Chuck Giampa and Bill Graham) will work the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of hope,'' said Marc Ratner, executive
director of the Nevada State Athletic Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Does Holyfield?
</P>
<P>
   Lewis (34-1-1, with 27 knockouts) dominated the fight in the
opinion of most. Using his immense height and reach advantages, he
kept Holyfield (36-3-1, 25 KOs) on the outside with his jab and
followed with what appeared to be more than enough power punches to
win easily.
</P>
<P>
   That judge Eugenia Williams stole the victory from him by
scoring it for his opponent couldn't mask reality: For the main
part, Holyfield was rendered helpless by a bigger, better fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget, Lewis (begin ital)did(end ital) outpunch Holyfield
348-130, according to computer statistics.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a flaw in Lewis' performance, it was his typical
lack of a killer instinct. It appeared he could've taken Holyfield
out had he pressed the issue but never took the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Steward, Lewis' trainer, has been pushing him to become
more aggressive _ Steward even predicted a knockout within six
rounds _ and Lewis acknowledged that he plans to pick up the pace.
At the same time, don't expect a brawl: He said he won't fight
recklessly even though he's extremely determined to right March's
injustice and stake his claim as baddest man on earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to go in there thinking I've got to knock him
out,'' Lewis said. ``I think I'll be (begin ital)able(end ital) to
knock him out if I pick up the pressure a little bit more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in there once and it's definitely do-able.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, who will be 37 on Friday, insists he was ill with
stomach and leg cramps going into the first fight.
</P>
<P>
   One of boxing's greatest warriors actually thought about
quitting after he failed to follow through on his prediction that
he'd knock out Lewis in the third round but, being the competitor
he is, persevered.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis dismissed such comments as excuses _ ``the cramps were due
to me punching him in the head,'' he said _ but Holyfield is
sticking with his story.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he's made some adjustments in training to cope with
Lewis' size advantage and tactics. He insists he'll find a way to
get inside the jab and, it appears, people are starting to believe
him. He remains about a 2-1 underdog but more and more experts are
predicting he'll win as fight time approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's his performances in rematches. He barely outpointed
Dwight Qawi but KO'd him in four rounds in their second
cruiserweight fight. He lost a close decision to Michael Moorer but
came back and knocked him out in eight rounds. He was outpointed by
Riddick Bowe but won a decision in a rematch few thought he could
take.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic thing is, you learn from your mistakes in life,'' he
said. ``I've made mistakes, but I've always been able to correct
them in another situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the opportunity to correct this and look forward to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, at what point does age become a factor?
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-seven is old for a fighter, especially one who has been
in as many wars as Holyfield. Some believe his performance against
Lewis was as much a result of age as anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (begin ital)has(end ital) to become a factor at some
point,'' said one knowledgeable observer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, after a series of debacles, boxing officials simply
hope Holyfield and Lewis earn the $15 million each will make and
that nothing goes wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Fans appear to be so disillusioned after the controversial first
fight, a boring Oscar De La Hoya-Felix Trinidad bout and a
no-contest when Mike Tyson met Orlin Norris, that they're staying
away from this one.
</P>
<P>
   The pay-per-view buy rate is not expected to exceed a measly
750,000, tickets remained available up to fight time and even
bettors aren't interested in putting down their money, according to
the casinos.
</P>
<P>
   An entertaining fight would certainly help ease the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just hope,'' Ratner said, ``they come out and (begin
ital)fight(end ital), not box.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
