<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARIDGE ABSOLVES USC COACHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PULLMAN, Wash. _ USC offensive lineman Travis Claridge knows he
will not play in a bowl game for the third time his four-year
career, but he isn't willing to blame the transition period between
coaches John Robinson and Paul Hackett as a reason for the Trojans'
woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough for us. We're kids trapped inside of men's
bodies. At 18, 19, we're not that mature yet,'' Claridge said.
``Someone was pulled away and someone was put in their place. But
there's coaching changes all the time. ``It has nothing to do with
what's on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches are not the ones dropping balls. Missing tackles.
Missing blocks. Making fumbles. Causing penalties. We're doing
that. Not them.''
</P>
<P>
   Claridge makes the 47th consecutive start of his career today
against Washington State and is on the verge of becoming the first
true freshman lineman to start every game of his career.
</P>
<P>
   That accomplishment means little to Claridge, however, compared
to stopping the Trojans' losing streak at five games. Other than
that, he's not looking at any other goals, including next week's
showdown with UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to end this five-game skid. Maybe we can beat UCLA,
but that game is not until next week,'' Claridge said. ``Before we
get to that game, we've got to win a game first. Just winning a
game. Not worrying about a streak. I never thought in a million
years I'd be sitting here with this many losses in my senior year
or that many losses in my USC career.''
</P>
<P>
   USC is 23-22 in Claridge's career.
</P>
<P>
   Who is this guy? Freshman tailback Deon Burnett of Claremont is
one of the few bright spots for the Cougars. His 761 yards rushing
is a school freshman record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Paul Hackett and Bob Toledo are looking at their
assistant coaches and wondering why they weren't recruiting this
guy,'' Washington State coach Mike Price said. ``He's from right
down the road. He probably wouldn't have the chance he has right
now had we not lost two backs in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got thrown into the starting position and he's done a great
job, he's improved every game. He can run inside, outside and he's
a good pass receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks commits: Fullback Jimmie Banks (6-foot-1, 240 pounds) of
Orange Coast College has orally committed to USC. He is the
Trojans' ninth commitment.
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of junior college players, Hackett has said he
would like to try to bring in at least two JC recruits to
participate in spring football, including a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   No interceptions: Is practice performance an accurate predictor
of a game? USC's quarterbacks did not throw an interception in
practice this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans have had an interception returned for a touchdown in
each of the past three games.
</P>
<P>
   Chasing Keyshawn: Wide receiver R. Jay Soward needs 17
receptions in his final three games to surpass Keyshawn Johnson as
the No.2 all-time receiver in school history. Soward enters today's
game with 152 receptions. Johnnie Morton is No.1 with 201.
</P>
<P>
   Two QBs: USC isn't the only school with a mini-quarterback
controversy. Washington State backup Paul Mencke led the Cougars to
its only touchdown against Oregon. Senior Steve Birnbaum remains
the starter, but Mencke could see action. Mencke threw six
interceptions last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
