<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-HUNGER-AGENCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGES FLY IN RACE AT U.N. HUNGER AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The Food and Agriculture Organization, a U.N. agency
headquartered in a marble and glass palace commissioned by
Mussolini, is not normally the subject of intense discussion
outside the building.
</P>
<P>
   That changed when an Argentine, Juan Carlos Vignaud, decided in
April to challenge the incumbent director general, Jacques Diouf of
Senegal, who had expected to run unopposed for a second six-year
term, following the custom at the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, marked by public charges of waste and anonymous
petitions against Diouf, has suddenly raised the agency's profile.
</P>
<P>
   The election, which will take place by secret ballot on Saturday
in Rome, is drawing 175 delegates from member states. Vignaud said
last week that he believes he has the support of more than 90
members, including Britain. But Diouf, who hopes for the backing of
the United States, Canada, France and much of Africa, is seen as
the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Established in 1945 to diagnose and alleviate the problems of
world hunger, the agency is a vast bureaucracy of 4,086 employees,
2,236 of whom are based in Rome _ whose renown has faded even as
its budget has grown. The World Food Program, a smaller and trimmer
U.N. agency which specializes in emergency work in places like
Kosovo, North Korea, and Eastern Timor, gets far more attention.
</P>
<P>
   To many, it was telling that when a tainted-food scandal
involving Coca-Cola erupted in Europe this summer, President
Jacques Chirac of France proposed the creation of a global food
safety agency, seemingly forgetting that food quality control is a
mandate of the FAO.
</P>
<P>
   Vignaud, Argentina's ambassador to Sweden, has traveled to 40
countries at his government's expense to lobby governments. In a
campaign manifesto, he complained that the agency's overhead budget
had increased to $754 million in 1999, from $652 million in 1993,
while spending on field operations tumbled to $444 million, from
$880 million. Diouf has not given interviews about the election,
but he disputed those figures and other charges in a 15-page
defense prepared by his office.
</P>
<P>
   Diouf disputed Vignaud's calculations on the main budget, saying
it had actually decreased to $650 million this year from $677
million in 1993. He conceded that spending in the field had
declined, but he blamed that on a cut in funding from the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Diouf also responded to anonymous letters sent to voting
delegates, which accuse the director general of arrogance,
excessive expense-account travel and misuse of perks. His life on
the road, Diouf said, ``is not a pleasure trip.'' He added, ``If I
were not to travel, those same people would criticize me for
staying in an air-conditioned office in an ivory tower in Rome.''
</P>
<P>
   Waste, high costs and abuse of privilege are perennial charges
lofted at many of its agencies, and that is why the United Nations
created the Office of Internal Oversight Services in 1994, to
monitor abuses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
