u a BC-NY-DEPORT-NYT &LR;      11-12 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DEPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE IMMIGRANTS ARE DEPORTED AS OFFICIALS' POWER INCREASES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Equipped with new powers to turn away immigrants at
the borders, and with more jail space available for those people
they arrest inside the country, immigration officials in New York
City have deported more than 4,000 people in the last year, an
increase of 12 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, nearly 177,000 people were deported or sent back to
their home countries for criminal or noncriminal offenses during
the 1999 fiscal year, an increase of 3 percent, according to a
report released yesterday by the Immigration and Naturalization
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, 62,000 people had committed, at some point during
their residence in the United States, one of the crimes that are
grounds for deportation. The agency said that about half of those
deported had been convicted on drug charges. Most of the others had
been convicted of assault, burglary, and violating immigration
laws. Almost 115,000 people were deported or turned away because
they were in the country illegally or had tried to enter with false
documents.
</P>
<P>
   The higher numbers were likely to please those in Congress who
have accused the agency of doing too little to find and deport
aliens with criminal records and false documents. The immigration
service estimates that 500,000 immigrants are in the country
illegally, although it has been using the same estimated number for
more than three years.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates for immigrants said the increase seemed to justify
their fears about a 1996 law that gave the INS an array of new
enforcement tools, including the right to deport people quickly
upon their arrival at an airport or land border without allowing
them a lawyer or a judicial hearing.
</P>
<P>
   That process is called expedited removal. It is used to turn
away not only people with false documents, but also those who
request asylum when they arrive. The agency did not provide figures
for the New York region airports alone, but it said that more than
89,000 people at all the nation's borders had been the subjects of
expedited removal in the last year, an increase of 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is really frightening,'' said Elisa Massimino, director
of the Washington office of the Lawyers Committee for Human Rights.
``This is an administration who opposed expedited removal and
unfortunately now embraced it to improve the deportation numbers.
We are afraid of what this portends for refugees seeking asylum
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials said that the increase in deportations was
the result in part of the success of their efforts to identify
criminals who are not citizens while they are serving their prison
sentences. Nearly 20,000 people were deported straight from state
and federal prisons in the last year, an increase of nearly 45
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In that same time period, the agency also received about $80
million in a special appropriation _ bringing its deportation
budget to $809 million _ to expand its detention beds to about
17,500 and bring its staff of enforcement officers up to 15,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greater our capacity to detain, the greater our capacity
to remove,'' said Russell A. Bergeron Jr., an agency spokesman.
``If you cannot detain, odds are you will not remove them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the field offices that look for undocumented immigrants
generally will not initiate a raid on a workplace, for example, if
there is not enough space to detain people awaiting deportation.
</P>
<P>
   The jump in deportations in the New York district paralleled
increases at other major gateway cities. San Francisco, for
example, deported 23 percent more people and Houston 29 percent in
the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, the agency has set annual targets for deporting
illegal and criminal aliens. Each year, it has surpassed its goal,
which for the 1999 fiscal year was 120,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 2344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8420 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-U.S.-TRADE-1STL     11-12 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-TRADE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. EXTENDS TRADE TALKS IN BEIJING 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS 6th graf to note Barshefsky-Zhu meeting.) 
(mk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In a last-ditch effort to reach an agreement on
China's entry into the World Trade Organization, American
negotiators decided overnight Friday to stay here a fourth day for
at least one more meeting.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, the Americans, practicing high-stakes
brinkmanship, had said that the talks so far had been fruitless and
announced that they were heading home.
</P>
<P>
   But after an exchange of messages during the night, the two
sides agreed to meet again Saturday to make another try.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Chinese have balked at demands for the thorough
opening of domestic industries to foreign ownership, which the
United States insists is a condition for China's entry into the
global trade body.
</P>
<P>
   Early Saturday, Tom Tripp, the spokesman for the American
negotiating team, said, ``Although progress has been slow in the
talks so far, because of the importance of the issues, both sides
thought it would be useful to have an additional day of meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   During the night, Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S. trade
representative, was for the first time this week asked to meet with
Prime Minister Zhu Rongji. They met Saturday morning inside the
government's leadership compound, Zhongnanhai.
</P>
<P>
   In private, American officials expressed pessimism and
disappointment that, up to now, the Chinese had been unable to
match the market-opening concessions Zhu made in Washington last
April.
</P>
<P>
   One American official here said Saturday morning, ``There's been
very little progress at all toward anything that could be
considered a commercially satisfactory agreement in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Clinton administration desperately wants to secure
China's entry into the trade body as a calming force in stormy
Chinese-American relations, it is under pressure from Congress and
American business interests to gain sweeping concessions.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese, while proceeding slowly toward a market economy,
fear the short-term social dislocations of opening industries to
outside competition and have pressed for more lenient terms of
entry.
</P>
<P>
   This week's talks, which follow more than a decade of fitful
negotiations and a near-agreement in April, have been widely seen
as make-or-break, and the administration is clearly anxious to
pursue all possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington on Friday, President Clinton said that differences
remained on a ``finite and limited number of issues'' and added,
``I have not given up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bringing China into the world organization soon has been a prime
goal of Clinton, and failure would be a setback for his strategy of
engagement with the world's most populous country.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese have been publicly silent about this week's
negotiations, and the Americans have not publicly described the
remaining areas of disagreement. One American diplomat said major
points of contention included the American demand that China allow
majority foreign ownership in the telecommunications and
financial-services industries.
</P>
<P>
   Other American officials said the negotiators had particularly
pressed China, without success, to open its securities industry to
outsiders. Garnering a foothold in China for Wall Street companies,
officials said, could broaden the political support for a deal even
if majority foreign ownership in telecommunications and certain
other sensitive sectors proved impossible.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a visit to Washington in April, Zhu agreed to open up most
industries to majority ownership by foreigners. But this week the
Chinese delegation, led by Foreign Trade Minister Shi Guangsheng,
has so far refused to match the April offer in important respects,
American officials said.
</P>
<P>
   China's backsliding may reflect not only Zhu's apparently
diminished power but a broader shift in the political atmosphere
here toward a more conservative and nationalistic stance. This
change gathered force during the Kosovo war last spring, when China
vehemently opposed the NATO bombing campaign, and it accelerated
after the bombing of China's Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, in
which three Chinese were killed.
</P>
<P>
   A failure to join the trade organization now would not mean that
China's gradual opening to outside competition, and its efforts to
overhaul hidebound state enterprises, would come to a stop,
economists here and abroad said.
</P>
<P>
   China and the United States had both hoped that an agreement
could be reached by Nov. 30, when discussions are to begin in
Seattle on a new round of global trade talks. China needs to
conclude bilateral accords with major partners before it can enter
the global body.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, administration officials privately said that an
agreement would be possible if China could match the terms it
offered in April.
</P>
<P>
   But in the intervening months, Chinese industrial and
bureaucratic interests began to lobby against such deep
concessions. Even military officers joined the fray, describing
control over the telecommunications sector, for example, as a
national security issue, said Joseph Fewsmith, a Chinese-politics
specialist at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu, an impatient, straight-talking reformer who is popular
abroad and with ordinary Chinese, came under attack from
conservative politicians and ministers who want to preserve
national control of key industries.
</P>
<P>
   According to many reports, he no longer has control over the
trade talks or the overhaul of state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced that Zhu Rongji remains prime minister in name
only,'' said Fewsmith, who recently visited China to examine trade
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu and his disciples hope that membership in the world
organization, and the resulting jolt of global competition, will
hasten the overhaul of a domestic economy still encrusted with
bloated state companies and monopolies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
