<HEADLINE>
DAVID GREEN WINS WINSTON CUP POLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOMESTEAD, Fla. _ David Green knows that ``the book'' on David
Green in NASCAR circles is pretty much the same old story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard it so many times: `He can qualify but he can't
race,''' Green said as the sun set on the Homestead-Miami Speedway
yesterday. ``So yeah, saying I'm `frustrated' is probably an
understatement.''
</P>
<P>
   A journeyman throughout his Winston Cup career, Green stole some
headlines for himself and team owner Tim Beverley of Texas by
winning the pole for tomorrow's inaugural Pennzoil 400. Green
toured the relatively flat 1.5-mile oval in 34.669 seconds at
155.759 mph to notch his first career Cup pole in his 72nd start.
</P>
<P>
   Green's timing could not have been better. In addition to
raising his stock in NASCAR's top series, Green also handed
Beverley some ammunition for his ongoing negotiations with primary
sponsor 10-10-345. The long-distance telephone carrier has not
decided if it will continue to sponsor Beverley's purple No. 45
Lucky Dog Pontiac Grand Prix after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our performance, I think, will keep those phone calls
coming,'' said Green, an unlikely candidate to lead a sweep of the
first five qualifying positions by Pontiac drivers. John Andretti,
championship runner-up Bobby Labonte, Dave Blaney and Ward Burton
all challenged for the pole before Green clicked off his rather
shocking hot lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts a little bit,'' said Green, referring to criticism
that has dogged him since his championship days in NASCAR's Busch
Grand National Series. ``We had our best \RCup\S finish at Phoenix
\R12th\S last week, and the first thing I read in the paper is some
of the Chevrolet and Ford people saying basically that `anybody
could drive a Pontiac nowadays in Winston Cup.' I don't feel like
that's a fair statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``So to beat Bobby and John Andretti is pretty special.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte's five poles trail only Jeff Gordon's seven this season
in a Chevrolet. And Andretti won his first pole of 1999 on the
similarly flat Phoenix International Raceway last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'll wake up \Rtoday\S,'' Green said, ``and I'll hear the
same old story: `Well, Green's a good qualifier. \RBut\S he only
won one race the year \R1994\S he won the Busch championship. And
he's not aggressive enough.' And all that. I won 19 poles in the
Busch series but didn't win 19 races. This is good; this is
special. But my goal is to show them on Sunday that we can race as
good as we qualify.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup points leader Dale Jarrett will start 12th after a
wind-whipped lap at 153.833 mph in the No. 88 Quality Care
Service/Ford Credit Taurus. Jarrett, who has a 231-point lead over
Labonte, can win his first Cup championship by finishing eighth or
better in a race scheduled for 267 laps.
</P>
<P>
   This will be Green's eighth start with Tyler Jet Motorsports and
Beverley, who fired Rich Bickle after the Pepsi Southern 500 at
Darlington (S.C.) Raceway in early September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we put David in the car at New Hampshire, he's just
gotten better and better and better,'' Beverley said. ``Somebody
said, `Do you think this will get the people you're talking to's
attention?' I said, `If it doesn't, then I'm going to quit.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But we'll figure out sponsorship. We've got some people that
want to work with us. And we'll make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Hut Stricklin scored his first career Busch GN pole
during qualifications for today's hotwheels.com 300. Stricklin,
driver of the No. 38 Barbasol Ford, toured the track in 36.131
seconds/149.456 mph.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
