<HEADLINE>
RANGERS LOSE FREE-AGENT WING TO BRUINS   SETTING OFF WEIRD CHAIN OF
EVENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JASON DIAMOS   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RYE, N.Y. _ Joe Murphy, the Rangers hardly knew you.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday morning, Murphy talked his way into a free-agent
tryout with the Rangers while the team was in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the 32-year-old right wing unexpectedly bolted to
Boston, agreeing to terms with the Bruins before allowing Neil
Smith, the Rangers' president, to even make a counteroffer.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a friendly parting of the ways. And judging by the
bizarre manner in which Murphy left the Rangers' practice complex
in Rye _ he argued with members of the front office and coaching
staff and accused Smith of throwing one of his skates into the
river (Murphy was not around long enough to know that the body of
water in Rye is the Long Island Sound) _ the Rangers felt a little
jilted.
</P>
<P>
   They also seemed to feel they would be better off without him.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Smith later said that he wished he had thought of
throwing Murphy's skate into the water. ``This should be in
Ripley's Believe It or Not,'' Smith said, referring to the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy took off for Boston as the Bruins were preparing to leave
for New York, where they will play the Rangers on Saturday night.
It should be even more interesting in Boston on Thursday, when the
Rangers and Bruins meet again.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest chapter of the feud between Smith and Harry
Sinden, the Bruins' president, the Bruins told the NHL that Sinden
had no idea that Murphy was working out with the Rangers. But news
of Murphy's tryout was reported last Monday, in both New York and
in Chicago, where Murphy lives.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, meanwhile, insisted Friday that Sinden had phoned
Murphy's father earlier this week to see if Murphy might be
interested in signing with Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy did, for a $900,000 base salary with incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the offer was a significant cut in salary from the
$3.8 million Murphy earned while collecting 25 goals and 23 assists
for the San Jose Sharks last season, he reached a deal with Sinden,
who often criticizes Smith and his free-spending ways.
</P>
<P>
   When Murphy left Chicago to train with the Rangers, he thought
he had a deal with Smith for an $800,000 base salary with
incentives.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith said Friday that he was going to offer Murphy only a
$500,000 base. In other words, the Bruins outbid the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy was incensed that he did not have an agreement with
Smith. He accused Smith on Friday of paying him only lip service
and he argued that he had to sign with Boston because he might have
got hurt skating with the Rangers and been out of luck with no
contract in place.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday afternoon, Murphy, who was an unrestricted free
agent, phoned John Muckler, the Rangers' coach and his former coach
in Edmonton, in Chicago to ask for a tryout. On Sunday, in two
meetings with Smith, Murphy, according to the Rangers, all but
begged for a chance to be on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beg?'' Smith said of Murphy, who had not fielded any contract
offers before the Rangers allowed him to accompany them to New York
on Sunday night. ``I was going to throw him a Milk Bone. Instead, I
gave him a tryout.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy skated with a handful of Rangers at Monday's optional
workout. He participated in Tuesday's full practice and Wednesday's
morning skate.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy did not make the trip to Washington on Thursday for the
Rangers' 5-4 overtime victory.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he phoned Smith in Washington twice on Smith's cell
phone during the game, then once more early Friday morning to
inform Smith of a noon deadline the Bruins had imposed on Murphy to
decide.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Murphy arranged an 11:15 a.m. meeting in Rye. But by
the time Smith arrived, Murphy had already informed the Rangers
that he had agreed to terms with the Bruins, his sixth NHL team.
</P>
<P>
   That did not go over well with the Ranger players, who were not
high on the idea of Murphy's signing with them in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   They also were not fond of Murphy's attitude when he arrived at
the Playland ice rink to retrieve his gear.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy complained to everyone within earshot of a missing skate
and a missing set of pads (he later found that his sticks had been
sawed halfway through).
</P>
<P>
   And then, with Smith and Muckler in an office 20 feet away,
Murphy tried to plead his case with the Rangers' assistant general
manager, Don Maloney, and the assistant coaches Charlie Huddy and
Keith Acton, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Tim Taylor, who scored the winning goal in overtime in
Washington, told Murphy to take a hike after Murphy had walked into
the trainer's room to question the trainer Jim Ramsay about his
missing gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the toughest I've ever seen him,'' Taylor later said,
referring to the perception that Murphy _ an excellent skater and
accomplished scorer _ is also a little bit soft.
</P>
<P>
   Capping the bizarre week were Murphy's parting words: he asked
Huddy to tell Muckler it was nothing personal, that he ``would go
to the wall'' for his old coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strange world,'' Muckler said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
