<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-MOLESTER-SENTENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN-AGER WHO KILLED BOY DEFENDS MOLESTER AS GOOD `ROLE MODEL' 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LAURA MANSNERUS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREEHOLD, N.J. _ Samuel Manzie, a teen-ager serving a 70-year
sentence for the murder of an 11-year-old boy, appeared in court
Friday to defend the pedophile who pleaded guilty to sexually
molesting him before he committed the crime.
</P>
<P>
   At the sentencing of Stephen P. Simmons, Manzie, now 17, said
Simmons had been a ``positive male role model.'' Manzie said he had
only cooperated in the investigation of his former lover because
the police hounded him and his psychiatrist told him he would be
arrested if he did not.
</P>
<P>
   Manzie's parents had traced their son's volatile and sometimes
violent behavior to his affair with Simmons. The relationship
between the two has been an integral part of a drama that has
played out in lurid detail since Sept. 27, 1997, when Manzie
sexually assaulted and strangled Eddie Werner, 11, who came to his
door selling candy and gift wrap for a school fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the appeal for leniency for Simmons, 45, charged with
criminal sexual contact and endangering the welfare of a child,
Judge Michael D. Farren of state Superior Court sentenced him to
the maximum term, five years. Simmons, who has served more than two
years, will be eligible for parole in four months.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons and Manzie saw each other Friday for the first time in
three years, though they had exchanged a few letters since Simmons'
trial in July. Farren dismissed sexual assault charges then, when
the teen-ager refused to testify against Simmons. As they were
brought into court, manacled and wearing prison khakis, the two
acknowledged each other with slight nods and sat impassively as
each gave his statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to shed some light on my relationship with Mr.
Simmons,'' Manzie said softly. ``It was a good one. Some say it
must have been a manipulative relationship, but how can they say so
if they weren't there?
</P>
<P>
   ``Please keep in mind,'' he told Farren, ``that he never forced
me to do more than I wanted to, and please keep in mind that I
never regretted the relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The case centered on several encounters in August and September
of 1996, when Simmons, who lived on Long Island, N.Y., met the boy
near his home in Jackson Township, N.J. The two had met on an
Internet chat room for gay men and teen-agers; Manzie was 14, and
Simmons, who had two convictions for sexual activities involving
minors, was 42.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, however, Manzie insisted that by the summer of 1997 the
relationship was ``a fond memory.'' He said investigators from the
Monmouth County Prosecutor's Office, who were notified by
supervisors in the psychiatric day program that Manzie had just
begun, bullied him and took him out of the clinic against his
wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Manzie rebelled shortly afterward, smashing recording equipment
that the prosecutor's office had attached to his telephone for
taping conversations with Simmons. He also alerted Simmons. Later
that week, Manzie killed Eddie Werner.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement Friday, Simmons said he shared the blame with
many others who had dealings with Manzie _ prosecutors, the police,
psychiatrists and the family court judge who refused to hospitalize
the teen-ager. Referring to the slaying of Eddie Werner, Simmons
said, ``I will go through the rest of my life _ it doesn't matter
whether you let me go today or a year down the line _ with this on
my conscience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not an evil person,'' Simmons said, insisting that he
never meant to harm Manzie. ``Is it so hard to believe I actually
care about him?''
</P>
<P>
   Manzie's parents, Nicholas and Dolores Manzie, dismissed
Simmons' statement as manipulative and insincere. ``He said he's
not an evil person,'' Nicholas Manzie said. ``He had sex with a
14-year-old boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Manzie, when asked whether she could forgive Simmons, said:
``When I look at Mr. Simmons I see a lonely and sad man who has to
have relationships with children to fulfill his needs. I just don't
understand why he wouldn't want to do something for himself and get
the right help. His life has led him down a lonely street.''
</P>
<P>
   The Manzies were accompanied in court by Edward G. Werner,
Eddie's father.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Marc Fliedner, said Manzie's defense of Simmons
was not unexpected, but Fliedner warned the judge that ``the young
person who's going to speak to you is still a teen-ager.'' Simmons,
he said, had ``sealed Sam Manzie into a dark world.''
</P>
<P>
   After the sentencing, Alton Kenney, the first assistant
prosecutor, acknowledged that in the investigation, ``what was not
clear was the emotional commitment that Manzie had, and still has,
to Simmons.'' When asked about Manzie's allegations of misconduct
by investigators, Kenney said: ``Sam Manzie is serving 70 years for
a horrible, horrible act. It's clear Sam Manzie is looking for
someone else to blame, some other contributor.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview from the Monmouth County Jail Friday afternoon,
Simmons said, ``I'm very proud of the way Sam handled himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
