<SLUG> BC-NY-CITY-RETALIATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE FINDS AIDS GROUP A VICTIM OF CITY RETALIATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In another First Amendment defeat for the Giuliani
administration, a federal judge in Manhattan ruled Friday that city
officials had improperly retaliated against an AIDS service
organization that had been critical of the mayor by moving to make
it ineligible for millions of dollars in federal money.
</P>
<P>
   The group, called Housing Works, has been a relentless opponent
of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's policies on AIDS, using guerrilla
protest tactics like blocking rush-hour traffic on bridges and
tunnels, interrupting the news conferences of city officials and
conducting sit-ins in city offices.
</P>
<P>
   The group operates two homes _ in Lower Manhattan and in the
East New York section of Brooklyn _ for homeless people with AIDS,
mental illness or drug addiction. The homes are supported through
federal grants, which are distributed by the U.S. Department of
Housing and Urban Development to nonprofit groups through a ranking
system developed by the city. The agency has allocated $54 million
this year for such programs in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Housing Works said in a lawsuit in August that the Giuliani
administration had initially given it a favorable rating, making it
likely to qualify for a share of the federal money. But the suit
says top city officials, upset with the group's antagonistic stance
toward the mayor, downgraded its score, effectively blocking it
from obtaining $2.4 million to cover three more years of operating
expenses for the two residences.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, U.S. District Judge Allen G. Schwartz ruled that Housing
Works had established a pattern of antagonism by city officials and
had shown that they had acted with ``retaliatory intent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The court acknowledges that any mayoral administration might
reasonably resent activities such as those engaged in,'' Schwartz
said, ``particularly the militant kind seemingly favored by
plaintiff.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Housing Works' ``right to continue to express that
criticism, however, is protected by the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision comes less than two weeks after a federal judge in
Brooklyn found that Mayor Giuliani had violated the First Amendment
by withholding payments to the Brooklyn Museum of Art over an
exhibition that the mayor deemed to be offensive.
</P>
<P>
   The city's corporation counsel, Michael D. Hess, said last night
that the city would appeal. ``We're disappointed in the outcome,''
Hess said, adding that the city denies all allegations of
retaliation in the suit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-12-99 2354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991112.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-12 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8437 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHRISTIE'S-INTERNET-N     11-12 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIE'S-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIE'S RULES OUT JOINING MASS-MARKET WEB VENTURES
</HEADLINE>
   (lh) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Christie's said Friday that it had decided against
joining forces with an online giant like eBay or Walt Disney Co.'s
Go.com to offer its auctions online and that it had merged its
six-month-old Internet unit into its marketing department.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's archrival, Sotheby's, announced an alliance with
Amazon.com five months ago, but after months of discussions,
Christie's officials said they had concluded that a link with a
giant online retailer risked diluting the Christie's brand name.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the officials said, Christie's will update
Christies.com, its Web site, so that over time it will be able to
offer its clients online bidding for all its auctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a decision to protect the integrity of our brand
name,'' said Edward Dolman, Christie's managing director in
America, when asked why the company chose not to link up with ebay
or Go.com. ``We made the decision not to go after high-volume,
low-value merchandise with a separate team of business-getters
because it didn't make commercial sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie's has decided to concentrate its energies on the high
end of the business rather than going after the mass market as the
Sotheby's-Amazon.com alliance has done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would potentially take us in the wrong direction,'' Dolman
said. ``We seek greater efficiency and market share at the top end
of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolman added that he believed that the company's change of focus
would better protect the core of Christie's business, selling
multimillion-dollar fine and decorative arts. ``It will make us
increasingly more competitive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's plans could not be more different from Sotheby's, an
unusual situation for two companies that for more than 100 years
have slavishly copied each other's strategies.
</P>
<P>
   While Christie's sees the online business as an extension of its
existing auction business, Sotheby's $25 million investment in the
online business is intended to broaden its client base by offering
millions of Internet users an enormous sampling of merchandise,
from low-end poster art to jewelry and eventually even fine art.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's has put together a team of more than 100 people to
work on its Internet business, which is scheduled to start sometime
before the end of the year. It has also signed up 4,600 dealers who
have agreed to sell exclusively through Sotheby's.com.
</P>
<P>
   Its link with Amazon means Sotheby's will be starting two Web
sites before the end of the year: Sothebys.Amazon.com for
lower-priced merchandise and Sothebys.com for more traditional
auction fare. Both will offer goods vetted either by the dealers
selling online or by experts at the auction house.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's will not have to worry about vetting merchandise for
the Internet since everything it auctions has already been
authenticated by its own experts.
</P>
<P>
   Dolman declined to say just how much money Christie's planned to
invest in upgrading its Web site. But over time, he said, the firm
will not only have the capability to hold online auctions, but it
will also be able to offer multimedia viewing capabilities for
every item offered for sale, e-mail chat rooms with specialists,
and virtual reality tours of its exhibitions. To do this, Dolman
said, Christie's expects to spend tens of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's has already begun to test online auctions. In June,
it used the Internet to sell 100 guitars that belonged to Eric
Clapton, and last month, it held a live Webcast of a sale of
Marilyn Monroe's property.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
